<SLUG> BC-BOEING-FAA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA ORDERS TIGHTER SAFETY CHECKS AT BOEING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Federal Aviation Administration has told The
Boeing Co. that it cannot deliver any airplanes to customers until
it does more to verify that it has complied with safety changes
mandated by the agency.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Boeing, the FAA said it was taking the action
after two planes _ one still in production and the other already in
service _ apparently did not have changes required by FAA
airworthiness directives.
</P>
<P>
   One of those directives was issued after a 20-foot section of
wing flaps tore off a Boeing 767 while it was landing at
Dallas-Forth Worth International Airport in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The other directive was issued after fasteners on 737 rudder
pedals worked lose, resulting in a loss of rudder control.
</P>
<P>
   A Boeing official on Tuesdsay questioned the FAA's findings and
said the order will not affect production or delivery of any
airplanes. Scott Peterson, director of quality assurance for
Boeing, told the Seattle Post-Intelligencer that the company
already verifies that applicable changes called for in
airworthiness directives are incorporated in the company's
passenger jets before they are delivered.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Boeing does not believe ``that we have delivered
any airplanes that have not had the airworthiness directive
requirements incorporated.''
</P>
<P>
   An airworthiness directive is an FAA order to aircraft operators
or the manufacturer to take some safety action.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Creedy, FAA spokeswoman in Washington, D.C., said
Tuesday that agency officials could not comment on the Boeing
letter because the matter is under investigation. But she did say
the FAA intends to make sure all Boeing jetliners include
airworthiness safety changes before they are delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not fail to verify full compliance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The letter notifying Boeing that it is under investigation was
sent to Peterson on April 8 by the FAA's James Robinson in the
aircraft certification office in Renton, Wash. Peterson said he did
not receive the letter until two days later, on Saturday, and that
he and others at Boeing are still trying to make sense of it.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said the letter is ``very confusing'' and contains
inaccuracies. He said Robinson was out of the office Tuesday and
could not be reached to clarify what he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there is some question whether the letter is
accurate enough to not be retracted and rewritten in an accurate
fashion,'' Peterson said. The Renton FAA office, he said, also has
concerns about the letter, and those concerns had been passed along
to the Washington, D.C., headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   According to the letter, the FAA on April 6 conducted an
airworthiness inspection of a Boeing 767 in production at the
Everett, Wash., plant to determine if it complied with an
airworthiness directive that was issued in 1998. It did not, the
letter said.
</P>
<P>
   That directive required airlines and Boeing to make a one-time
inspection of planes in service or in production to check fasteners
that connect pushrods to the rudder pedal assemblies.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing the airworthiness directive, the FAA said the captain
of a Boeing 737-400 had reported that after his plane landed, the
right rudder pedal moved to its full position when it was pushed,
but failed to return to its normal position when released. The
rudder, however, remained in its neutral position.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation revealed that the pushrod on the right rudder
pedal was not connected to the rudder pedal assembly. The bolt and
nut that holds the pushrod to the assembly had come lose.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA, in its directive, said another 737 operator reported
that a pilot felt a loose rudder pedal and a subsequent
investigation revealed that the fastener connecting the pushrod to
the rudder assembly was loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``These conditions, if not corrected, could result in potential
loss of rudder control, jamming of the rudder system, uncommanded
movement of the rudder system and consequent reduced
controllability of the airplane,'' the FAA said in its directive.
</P>
<P>
   Because the rudder assembly on some models of the 747, 757, 767
and 777 are similar in design to the 737, the FAA said its
directive would apply to all Boeing planes.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to Peterson, the FAA's Robinson said the 767
inspected on the Everett production line on April 6 did not have
the proper fasteners that connect the pushrod to the rudder pedal
assembly.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing inspectors had signed off on paperwork that showed
the directive had been met, Robinson wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said the FAA inspector was confused about the
requirements of the airworthiness directive.
</P>
<P>
   That directive only mandates that Boeing make a one time
inspection of planes in production to verify the nut and bolt are
tight, Peterson said. But after the directive was issued, he said,
Boeing engineers redesigned the nut and bolt to include a cotter
pin, which further ensures it will not come loose.
</P>
<P>
   The 767 plane inspected was line number 751. It was supposed to
have the redesigned fastener, Peterson said. All 767s starting with
number 750 on the production line are to have the new fastener, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   So why did the paperwork show the new fastener was installed,
when it was not?
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an oversight by the mechanic installing the bolt and
he went ahead and installed what he had always installed,''
Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing was never required as part of the airworthiness
directive to install the redesigned fastener, Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   He also also took issue with the second case cited in Robinson's
letter.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson wrote that on March 30 the FAA received correspondence
from a 767 operator that shims had not been installed in the flap
assembly as required by an airworthiness directive issued by the
FAA in 1997. The 767 in question was delivered by Boeing on March
2, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA issued the airworthiness directive after a 20-foot
section of wing flaps tore off a Delta 767 while the plane was
landing at Dallas-Forth Worth International Airport. The plane,
with 198 passengers and crew, managed to land safely.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation revealed that bolts holding the flaps to the
wing had failed. The airworthiness directive ordered 767 operators
to inspect the bolts for fatigue. Also, Boeing had to include
what's known as shims in its production 767s. And whenever the
bolts are replaced on planes in service, the shims have to be
added. Shims act like a washer on the flap bolts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that this airplane was delivered without the shims
installed as required...,'' Robinson wrote in his letter.
</P>
<P>
   But Peterson said Boeing has not been able to verify that the
shims were not installed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to track down information to see what actually
was installed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson wrote that as a result of the two cases cited in his
letter, ``Effective April 8, 1999, the FAA is requiring that all
aircraft deliveries be withheld pending verification'' that
airworthiness directives are incorporated on Boeing's planes.
</P>
<P>
   This new policy will continue until Boeing can demonstrate to
the FAA that it has improved its verfiication procedures, Robinson
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In a second letter to Boeing dated April 9, another FAA official
in the Renton office notified Boeing of the additional steps it
must take before the FAA will issue an airworthiness certificate
for Boeing airplanes. Such a certificate is required before a plane
can be delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``This added requirement in the delivery process is necessary
until Boeing provides corrective action ... that is acceptable to
the FAA,'' the sceond letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said the additional steps cited by the FAA involve
mostly paperwork and will not delay the delivery of any airplanes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
