<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE MCCAIN COMES OUT SWINGING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., formally declared
himself a presidential candidate Tuesday and immediately made a
campaign issue of the war in Kosovo by renewing his call to do
whatever it takes to win it.
</P>
<P>
   There were no balloons or pep bands as McCain made it official
that he is seeking the Republican nomination in 2000. Rather, the
announcement was made simply in a three-page news release that made
clear his intention to use the Balkans crisis to contrast his
leader ship in foreign policy with the Clinton administration's.
</P>
<P>
   ``As president, I hope to restore to the White House the kind of
leadership Americans expect in cri ses like this one and to reform
our institutions of government to make us proud again,'' McCain
said in the release.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in his first speech as a formal candidate, McCain seemed
to up the ante on Kosovo by accusing NATO and the Clinton
administration of ``critical tactical errors'' and by calling for
the immediate mobilization of infantry and armored divisions for a
possible ground war.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a former Vietnam pris oner of war and the son and
grandson of naval commanders, said the administration erred with
its ``excessively restricted'' air cam paign and its declaration
that NATO had no intention of summoning ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two mistakes were made in what almost seemed willful
ignorance of every lesson we learned in Vietnam,'' McCain told the
Center for Strategic and Interna tional Studies, a public policy
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton seems to have had neither a Plan A nor a
Plan B. If war against Serbia was necessary, then winning the war
is necessary as well. That is a trite remark, I know, but the
administration's policy is so mystifying to me that it begs such
obvious criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally, McCain had been scheduled to launch his presidential
bid formally with a three-day na tional tour, beginning with an
April 6 breakfast at the Naval Acad emy in Annapolis, Md. The tour
was to have included stops in New Hampshire, South Carolina, Ari
zona, California, Utah and Massa chusetts.
</P>
<P>
   While he has continued to raise funds _ he had $4.3 million
avail able as of March 31 _ McCain said Tuesday that, because of
Kosovo, ``now is not the time for the celebratory tour I had
planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Left unsaid was that his fre quently televised Kosovo appear
ances have earned McCain more media coverage than he could have
received on any campaign-kickoff tour, and that the crisis has
allowed him to demonstrate his strengths as a candidate: foreign
policy and national security issues.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's speech, a dozen television camera crews crowded
into the basement conference room where McCain gave his address. It
was the kind of media reception more familiar to the public appear
ance of heads of state rather than a candidate looking for an
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Kosovo erupted, Mc Cain had been a critic of
Clinton's responses to foreign conflicts. The senator also had
accused the admin istration of allowing the nation's defenses to
slip.
</P>
<P>
   A recent news release by Mc Cain's presidential exploratory com
mittee had noted McCain's past criticism of Clinton's ``feckless
photo-op foreign policy'' and the administration's ``empty threats
in crisis after crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   During a recent interview, Mc Cain was asked by The Arizona
Republic which issues he expected would most attract voters to his
White House bid. ``National de fense'' was the first one on the
list.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tuesday's address had obvious political overtones, it
was not billed as a political campaign speech, and there was no
mention by McCain of his White House candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   A news release about the speech was issued by McCain's Senate
staff, not by the campaign office that quietly changed its name
Tues day from the ``John McCain for President Exploratory
Committee'' to ``McCain 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's aides said his Kosovo thinking is driven by his
conscience and expertise, not by presidential politics. For that
reason, they said, the campaign will try to keep senatorial events
separate from cam paign appearances.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain acknowledged dur ing the address that his position
could hold political consequences because he will share in the
blame for American casualties. He has said that winning the war in
Kosovo must take precedence over avoiding the loss of lives, both
``theirs and ours.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather face that sad burden than hide from my con
science because I sought an advan tageous political position to
seek shelter behind,'' McCain said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
