<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-RIVALRY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS, COYOTES TEST EACH OTHER OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mike Modano walked away with a black eye, and the Stars
and Phoenix Coyotes walked away with another reason to hate each
other.
</P>
<P>
   It was March 23 in Phoenix when Modano received a shiner and
seven stitches in his eyelid, courtesy of a hit from Coyotes winger
Jeremy Roenick that caused Roenick to be ejected.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the facts.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the differing opinions of how Modano was injured that
form the basis for a great conspiracy novel ... or at least a
physical rivalry that will continue at 7:30 tonight at Reunion
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I don't know what to expect,'' Stars
captain Derian Hatcher said, shrugging. ``It could go either way.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way means that the Stars and Coyotes could play a
relatively clean game and respect each other professionally or they
could let subtle feelings of hate surface the first time one player
shoves another, and turn the game into a brawl.
</P>
<P>
   To compound matters, the teams are scheduled to turn around and
play again Saturday afternoon in Phoenix. That's not the kind of
scenario the Stars need to worry about as they try to get healthy
and hone their game for a first-round playoff series with Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have wrapped up the Presidents' Trophy and the top
seed through the playoffs. The Coyotes need one point in their
final three games to secure the fourth seed in the Western
Conference and home ice in the first round. So on that front,
there's little to play for. But here's a pertinent sidenote for the
Stars and their fans to consider: In a 3-0 loss to the Mighty Ducks
of Anaheim on Sunday, Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk wrestled down
Ducks winger Teemu Selanne after Selanne scored an empty-net goal.
That started a melee in which Tkachuk was ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lets people know when you play us, it's going to be a
physical game,'' Roenick said proudly. ``Even if you win, you're
going to take a bunch of licks.''
</P>
<P>
   Are the Stars prepared to ``take a bunch of licks'' even if they
get a victory?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go in worrying about bad stuff, bad stuff usually
happens,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We're looking at this
as a good game against a good team, and we're trying to get ready
for the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hitchcock and his players downplayed the rivalry
yesterday, their words three weeks ago were much stronger. A
sampling of the plot:
</P>
<P>
   Roenick, who had been getting knocked around by Hatcher and
Craig Ludwig in the first period, skated from 50 feet away to lay a
hit on Modano. The problem was that Modano was nowhere near the
puck. Roenick said he thought Modano, who had skated behind the net
and was obstructed from Roenick's view, had the puck on his stick.
So Roenick drove his shoulder, helmet or elbow into the side of the
head of the unsuspecting Modano, sending Modano sprawling across
the ice and forcing him to leave the game.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick was handed a five-minute major penalty for boarding
(although Modano didn't hit the boards) and was ejected from the
game. The Stars scored on the power play en route to a 3-2 victory
_ and both teams hurled barbs at one another.
</P>
<P>
   Stars players Darryl Sydor and Joe Nieuwendyk called Roenick's
hit ``cheap'' and ``gutless.'' Guy Carbonneau said: ``It was a
cheap hit, but that's just how Roenick plays.'' Brett Hull called
it unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars asked for a suspension. The league declined to suspend
Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick answered the charges in his soft-spoken way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carbonneau is a \Rexpletive\R,'' Roenick said. ``Joe
\RNieuwendyk\S is a class guy, but I'm a physical player and he's
not. Hull makes comments about everything, even Russian politics.
And he's not a physical player, either.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line to all this, however, might be a challenge to
the Stars' physical toughness. The Stars haven't been a fighting
team since tough guy Shane Churla was traded in 1996. In fact,
they're downright civilized, averaging the third fewest penalty
minutes per game in the NHL at 12.8. That's down from 15.9 minutes
per game last season and way down from the free-swinging 23.3 they
put up in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   So are the Stars tough enough to fight back against an
unpredictable bunch of Coyotes, or would it be folly to tempt the
injury gods one week before the playoffs start?
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock hinted that he will likely sit Modano in Phoenix,
where America West Arena is known to have some of the hardest glass
in the NHL and where Modano has been hurt in two of his past three
visits; he separated a shoulder there last season and missed 17
games. Hitchcock said he will play the line of Modano, Brett Hull
and Jere Lehtinen in ``two of the last three games.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the replacement line is probably Brent Severyn,
Brian Skrudland and Jon Sim _ a trio full of punch. That's just in
case anyone worries about the Stars lacking toughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good game against a good team,'' Hatcher said, trying
to throw meaning between the lines. ``I think it'll be good for
us.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
