<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMBIS REMOVES FATIGUED HARPER FROM LAKERS LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ From the Los Angeles Lakers' ever-busy
Something New Every Day Dept. came this zinger Tuesday evening:
starting point guard Derek Harper benched in favor of Derek Fisher,
at least for Tuesday night's game. But for how much longer, not
even coach Kurt Rambis knows.
</P>
<P>
   It was a move that acknowledged the overuse of the 37-year-old
Harper, and the diminishing results of his heavy minutes. His
shooting percentage was a meager 28.6 percent over the previous
nine games, and he had just six assists in his past four games.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than run him into the ground, Rambis decided to cut
Harper's minutes and responsibility, hoping he'll be fresh for the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that he's tired,'' Rambis said. ``Harp, when he came
here, he was supposed to be a 15-, 18-, 20-minute guy, max. But he
played so well in camp, played so well in the early part of the
year, he's getting 30 minutes. And I know how hard it is to
recover, especially when you're a guard, and playing the amount of
games we've played and in such a short period of time. It's just a
way to get his legs back fresh in time for the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Lakers trotted out their 12th starting lineup of the
season, and Fisher reclaimed the starting job he held for the first
nine games. Harper admitted fatigue was having an impact on his
game and said Rambis' decision made sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's looking down the road,'' said Harper, who played a
season-low seven minutes. ``I have confidence in Tyronn (Lue) and
Fish to get it done. I mean, at 37 (years old), 16 years in the
league, I'm gonna take the rest....
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a competitive person, and to say I welcome time off, I
won't go that far. I will support the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Rambis said he would keep Harper on the bench for the
rest of the regular season. But he wouldn't commit to that, or to
who would start in the playoffs, and didn't rule out giving rookie
Lue a start either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just gonna see how it goes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, who started the final 33 games last year, wants to stick
in the lineup this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so. It's been a crazy year, and so right now I'm just
geared to go out and do whatever the team needs me to do,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: The fever and sore throat that kept Glen Rice in
Los Angeles on Tuesday turned out to be a case of tonsillitis. With
the Lakers off for three days, the team hopes Rice will be ready to
play Saturday in Utah.
</P>
</TEXT>
