<SLUG> BC-EDIT-S&AMP;L-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: COSTS OF IGNORING A FINANCIAL MESS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, April 14:
</P>
<P>
   More than two decades ago, as the savings and loan crisis was
growing, the federal government tried to ignore it in the hope that
it would somehow go away. One part of that delaying strategy was to
sanction an accounting fiction allowing institutions that took over
sick thrifts to pretend they now had valuable assets. To do
otherwise would have meant closing down thrifts when Congress did
not want to appropriate the money needed to pay off depositors.
</P>
<P>
   By 1989 it was clear that the ostrich approach had been a
disaster, and Congress legislated away the accounting fictions.
Unfortunately, it did so in a way that left the government open to
damage claims from thrifts that had used the fictional accounting
in making acquisitions but now were required to conform their
accounting to reality.
</P>
<P>
   That bill is falling due. The Supreme Court ruled in 1996 that
the thrifts could collect damages, and now in the first decision on
damages, Loren Smith, the chief judge of the United States Court of
Claims, has awarded $909 million to Glendale Federal Bank. The
ruling is a balanced one, giving Glendale Federal less than half of
the damages it sought, and should provide a road map for settling
other cases, of which more than 120 are pending.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution of those cases is likely to boost the bill for
cleaning up the savings and loan mess, already at $480 billion,
above $500 billion. It would have been far less if the government
had acted earlier rather than played for time. If the financial
system ever gets into similar problems, that is the lesson that
should be remembered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
