<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-IBRAHIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA'S OUSTED DEPUTY PREMIER FOUND GUILTY OF CORRUPTION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Wednesday in lede cq.)  (nk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Anwar Ibrahim, the ousted deputy prime
minister of Malaysia, was found guilty Wednesday on four counts of
corruption in a trial that has set off the greatest political
unrest this country has seen in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Augustine Paul, sentenced Malaysia's most prominent
pro-reform leader to six years in prison on each of the four
charges. The sentences will run concurrently and begin immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Although the guilty verdict was widely expected, the severe
sentence was not. As the verdict was being handed down, several
hundred riot policemen ringed the Moorish-style court building here
and a line of officers wielding rattan canes pushed back a crowd of
several hundred protesters.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators, mainly students, were holding placards that
said, ``The people are the judge,'' and were chanting
``Reformasi!'' _ or reform _ a word that has become a rallying cry.
</P>
<P>
   In the moments before the verdict was announced, the crowd was
kept well away from the courthouse by the police, who were
reinforced by two water-canon trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's trial has galvanized Malaysia _ offering a daily drama
of lurid sexual charges that had never before been aired in this
predominantly Islamic country. From the start, Anwar treated the
trial less as a legal ritual than as a political spectacle.
Testifying in court, he aimed many of his comments at the galleries
in the back of the room, where the foreign news media sat.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's wife, Wan Azizah Wan Ismail, came to court every day
with one or two of their daughters. She, too, spoke regularly to
the media _ presenting evidence to exonerate her husband of the sex
charges or objecting to various court rulings. Ms. Wan Azizah, who
was trained in Ireland as an eye doctor, has since formed a
political party to challenge Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Anwar's trial has come to symbolize the personal
fallout of the regional economic crisis. Until last summer, when
Malaysia began feeling the effects of the downturn, Anwar and
Mahathir were close friends and steadfast political allies.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir, a 73-year-old physician, had groomed Anwar as his
successor. From Anwar's start as a fiery Muslim student activist,
he rose rapidly in the hierarchy of Mahathir's ruling party, the
United National Malay Organization. He eventually became deputy
party chairman and deputy prime minister _ and was entrusted with
the politically sensitive post of finance minister.
</P>
<P>
   It was as finance minister that Anwar finally came to grief with
his mentor. As the Asian financial crisis raged around Malaysia _
devastating the country's currency and reversing years of torrid
economic growth _ Anwar steadfastly kept Malaysia's markets open
and its interest rates high.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy made him popular with foreign leaders and the
International Monetary Fund who were advocating a similar remedy
for other crisis-torn Asian countries like Thailand and Indonesia.
But it angered Mahathir, who wanted to ease the pain on Malaysia's
14 million people by lowering interest rates and cordoning off the
country from the rest of the region.
</P>
<P>
   While the debate raged, the two men were fighting a backroom
political battle. Anwar began challenging Mahathir's leadership in
party meetings, saying the long-serving prime minister was not the
right leader for a time of crisis. At the same time, Malaysia's
police force had presented Mahathir with evidence of alleged
corruption and sex-related crimes by Anwar.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Mahathir dismissed the claims. But as the feud became
more bitter, he abruptly reversed course. On Sept. 1, Mahathir
announced that Malaysia would impose sweeping controls on its
currency and stock markets _ effectively scuttling Anwar's policy.
The following day, Mahathir ousted his deputy, saying he was unfit
to lead Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar responded by mobilizing a political movement against
Mahathir. Within two weeks, Anwar had drawn a crowd of 30,000 to
march through Kuala Lumpur, demanding the prime minister's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   But before Anwar's movement could really catch fire, he was
arrested and charged with corruption and sex-related crimes.
Although the protests have continued sporadically, the movement
against Mahathir has largely run out of steam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
