</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SIXERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS TOP 76ERS, 91-72 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They played padlock defense on Allen Iverson, never
trailed and resembled a playoff team. But with every sparkling
development for the Knicks, there is an expensive toll.
</P>
<P>
   The satisfaction of blowing the Philadelphia 76ers off the
Madison Square Garden floor, 91-72, on Tuesday night lasted as long
as it took Patrick Ewing to hobble from the court to the locker
room in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With his left Achilles' tendon nagging him again, Ewing is
questionable for Wednesday night's game against Washington. With 12
games left and the Knicks (21-17) in seventh place in the playoff
race, a familiar question enveloped the organization: will Ewing's
health be a factor in the post-season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I can play,'' Ewing said of the game against the
Wizards. ``If it's sore, I'm not going to play. If not, I'll play.
They tell me it's going to take eight weeks of not doing anything
to be 100 percent. But I don't have eight weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a big-man burden to be shouldered, Kurt Thomas and
Marcus Camby showed they will be up to the challenge. On Tuesday
night, the forwards combined for 33 points, 12 rebounds and 3
blocked shots. Larry Johnson added 17 points, 6 rebounds and 4
assists, and Latrell Sprewell contributed 16 points on 5-of-12
shooting in 31 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Camby, who scored 19 in Sunday's victory over the Nets, changed
shots on the defensive end and gathered himself well each time he
rose to shoot. Thomas had 9 of his 18 points in the third quarter,
when the Knicks effectively put the game away by pushing an
18-point halftime lead to 29 midway through the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, any time Ewing is hobbling, it's a bad sign. He missed
six straight games because of the tendinitis from March 11-18. The
Knicks were 4-2 without Ewing and are 7-7 since he returned from
the injury. He left the game with 3 minutes 10 seconds left in the
second quarter and did not return. Ewing was walking gingerly
upcourt for most of the second quarter and appeared to be in pain
soon after the opening minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Ewing disclosed the ailment had been bothering him
since Sunday. He said he planned to take anti-inflammatory
medication and described himself as ``day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   With Ewing out and the Knicks coasting, you knew chants of ``We
want Herb!'' would be heard. The Garden zealots got Herb Williams
with 2:10 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Unaccustomed to hearing his name called recently, it took the
40-year-old cult hero nearly a minute to finally discard his
warm-ups. With 11.1 seconds left, he garnered one of the loudest
ovations of the season by knocking down an 18-footer from the right
wing off a pretty pick-and-roll play with David Wingate.
</P>
<P>
   That shot climaxed a fairly impressive turnaround the past week.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Williams played in a game came with his team
behind by 26 points. Since the Knicks collapsed in Charlotte and
hit their nadir last Wednesday, they have won three straight.
Despite all their dysfunction after 38 games, they found themselves
one and a half games out of fourth place in the conference entering
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Knicks had returned to respectability, Coach Jeff
Van Gundy said: ``No, because every time you think like that you
get off track. Because once you believe you've arrived, it starts
the way. Larry said something that was in the paper today that I
always say to him, `It can get bad in a hurry; it can get good in a
hurry.' And that's the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the turnaround had to do with that old Knick staple of
defense. Iverson, who came into game leading the league in scoring
at 27.3 points a game, finished 4 of 16 from the field with 11
points and had 6 of 25 turnovers by the 76ers (19-18). Whether it
was Charlie Ward, Chris Childs or someone else doing the defending,
the Knicks made a concerted effort to keep Iverson in front of them
and contest nearly all of his shots. On Sunday, that same defense
throttled Stephon Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was one particular thing they did,'' Iverson
said. ``Don't get me wrong, they played good defense. But a lot of
it was me. I just made some turnovers, made some bad decisions and
I didn't make the shots I usually make.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks led, 48-30, at halftime, building on a 14-point lead
they had after one quarter. One sequence midway through the first
quarter illustrated New York's purpose. On one end, Ewing pinned a
shot by Iverson underneath the backboard. On the other end, four
Knicks touched the ball before Johnson knocked down a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   In a bustling and talky locker room afterward, Thomas said:
``We're not where we want to be yet, by any stretch of the
imagination. But we are a long way from where we were in
Charlotte.''
</P>
</TEXT>
