<SLUG> BC-BKW-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WNBA LABOR TALKS COULD REVEAL ICICLE AT THE CORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Women's professional basketball is still alive in the
United States, but this is what you might call a mixed blessing, at
least from a political point of view.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has the muscle and resources to will women's
professional basketball to succeed. The NBA, which runs the WNBA,
has the slick arenas and a mighty marketing arm and a standard for
success that has been the envy of every pro sports league in the
free world.
</P>
<P>
   But the opposing forces of darkness and light lurk there in the
same business suit, namely, the one worn by NBA commissioner David
Stern.
</P>
<P>
   He wants a women's league, but at what cost? The WNBA says it is
committed to the women's game, but how much, under what
circumstances and why?
</P>
<P>
   We may soon find out.
</P>
<P>
   Just months after an 11th-hour deal was brokered to end the
silly NBA lockout, the WNBA and its newly formed players union are
in heated discussions themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Since last Thursday, the two sides have run past at least two
deadlines, trying to agree on a collective bargaining agreement. No
progress was reported Tuesdayu. Meanwhile, a predraft camp is
supposed to take place Thursday in Chicago, the draft is April 27
and the league is due to open its third season June 10.
</P>
<P>
   While the two sides have agreed on year-round insurance, the
WNBA is offering players a raise in league minimum salary, from
$15,000 to $20,000 for the three-month season. The WNBA players
union is seeking $45,000, down from an original demand for $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   The players contend that $45,000 per player would amount to
about $2 million in total player payroll _ less than the average
salary of one player in the NBA and about $20 million less than
what Minnesota's Kevin Garnett makes.
</P>
<P>
   Also at issue is how many former ABL players will be allowed to
try out for the WNBA. The league would like for at least 52 of the
90 ABL players to get a shot. The union, showing extreme
shortsightedness for the future of the product, wants only two ABL
roster spots per WNBA team.
</P>
<P>
   The backdrop to these now prolonged negotiations is the fact
that the WNBA is the only game for women. With the demise of the
American Basketball League in December, the WNBA sits in the
glorious catbird seat.
</P>
<P>
   With no rival league, Stern (through his hand-picked WNBA
president Val Ackerman) can indeed hard-line his employees all the
way to a lockout. With no ABL, but with ABL players champing at the
bit to hook up with their next pro team, Stern can hold out longer
than the current crop of WNBA players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have to adhere to those demands. There's no other
competition. He's got that much more leverage,'' one former ABL
player said Tuesday as she waited for word about her fate.
</P>
<P>
   That is why this a moment of truth for women's hoops.
</P>
<P>
   To what end does the NBA's chief operating officer really want
his women's league to succeed? For what purpose does this
makeshift, summertime venture exist?
</P>
<P>
   Is it to fill NBA arenas?
</P>
<P>
   Is it to keep NBA employees such as trainers, ticket sellers,
promoters and marketing geniuses busy 12 months of the year?
</P>
<P>
   Is it to help further brand the NBA logo into the impressionable
psyches of yet another demographic category, such as young girls
and their parents?
</P>
<P>
   One thing is sure, the WNBA is not in business because it views
itself as the champion for female sports role models and equal
opportunity. That ground was staked out by the ABL, grass-roots
enterprise that billed itself as a players' league.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, for anyone who respected the ABL's business model
and social agenda, the nine-team league could not compete against
the monopolistic NBA.
</P>
<P>
   When the league shut down for good in December, ABL commissioner
Gary Calvelli said the ABL had ``offered millions of dollars to the
TV networks for air time but we couldn't obtain adequate coverage.
During the NBA lockout, the ABL (could not) buy air time.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvelli and ABL officials have discussed filing an antitrust
suit against the WNBA because the ABL found several national
sponsors and TV executives were unwilling to do business with the
ABL for fear of losing their tie-ins with the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just really convinced that the ABL would still be here if
we could have gotten some of the national sponsorship and
opportunities that the WNBA got because of their merchandizing and
TV tie-ins with the NBA,'' former Reign coach Tammy Holder said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Like many ABL employees, Holder is eager to see more positive
things happen for the women's game and questions the timing of this
standoff between players and management in the sole existing
women's league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally are having our dreams realized, being able to be
role models and have opportunities to play and coach. It just seems
like this might be a situation where you take one step forward and
three steps back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   All eyes are on Stern and his WNBA now. It's bad enough one
spunky little league already has been crushed. This is no time for
Stern to act like a miserly, monopolistic crusher of spirit and
ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 0054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
