<SLUG> BC-LA-SCHOOL-BOARD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SCHOOL BOARD CONTESTS UNDECIDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Editors: Story will be updated with later returns.) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The fate of Mayor Richard Riordan's bold $2
million campaign to elect a reform-minded Board of Education
majority remained undecided Tuesday evening, with most races too
close to call in early returns.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's slate -- Caprice Young, Genethia Hayes, Mike Lansing
and incumbent David Tokofsky -- hoped to turn around America's
second largest school district after years of poor student test
scores and administrative scandals. Riordan and his candidates
often framed the election as no less than an attempt to save an
entire generation of Los Angeles children.
</P>
<P>
   Young, Hayes and Lansing hoped to knock off incumbents Jeff
Horton, Barbara Boudreaux and George Kiriyama, respectively, while
Tokofsky faced a challenge from Yolie Flores Aguilar.
</P>
<P>
   Champions of local educational reform said even having one or
two new members elected to the board could help turn around the
district by demonstrating to other board members the public's
determination for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if only one new member comes in, there will have been
lessons learned,'' said Maria Casillas, director of the Los Angeles
Annenberg Metropolitan Project, which funds reform efforts in
schools. ``If you have a whole slate of new people come in, that
will send a really big message.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote capped a year of mounting calls for reform at the
700,000-student Los Angeles Unified School District. While
Riordan's attack on the school board was the most visible and
personal -- he has called the current board evil and inept -- other
groups weighed in with their own plans for change.
</P>
<P>
   Their presence shaped the race, as incumbents and challengers
alike rushed to declare themselves reformers. And the mayor's money
turned what used to be little-noticed, incumbent-friendly elections
dominated by cash from teacher and administrator unions into
bruising political fights.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking a set platform from the mayor, Riordan's hand-picked
candidates mostly adopted recommendations made by a committee of
prominent civic leaders led by Harold M. Williams, former head of
the Getty Trust.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, so great was the pressure for reform that all but one
of the incumbents targeted for removal also signed on to the
Williams plan, which calls for the school board to set overall
policies and hold Superintendent Ruben Zacarias and other
administrators accountable for implementing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say, first step, mission accomplished,'' Williams said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although his Committee on Effective School Governance was widely
viewed as being allied with Riordan, it did not endorse candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the committee would make sure those candidates who
pledged to implement the plan do not forget their promises after
the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either as friends or as watchdogs, we will be there,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While both incumbents and challengers vowed to work for reform,
they split sharply over other issues, including Riordan's
involvement in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a tough challenge in south-central Los Angeles, Boudreaux
said Riordan's choice of another African-American woman to unseat
her amounted to ``plantation politics.'' She fought back by lining
up endorsements from many of the city's African-American leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But challenger Hayes, head of the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference's Los Angeles chapter, defended her independence, saying
Riordan backed her only well after she had decided to run.
</P>
<P>
   In board district 5, which stretches from the northeast San
Fernando Valley to East Los Angeles, Tokofsky squared off against a
candidate backed by school board President Victoria Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Aguilar sought to neutralize Riordan's endorsement of Tokofsky
by saying her opponent was guilty of the same micromanaging of the
district staff that he had pledged to end. Tokofsky responded by
saying he and Riordan shared both an emphasis on the fundamentals
of education and a determination to root out bureaucratic
inefficiency and waste.
</P>
<P>
   Horton, whose district includes Hollywood and North Hollywood,
came under fire from challenger Young for his support of the
Belmont Learning Complex project, a half-finished downtown high
school already considered the state's most expensive.
</P>
<P>
   He fought back by pointing to his record of supporting reform
within the district -- specifically the drive to end the automatic
promotion of poorly performing students -- and emphasizing Young's
lack of education experience.
</P>
<P>
   And in a district connecting Watts and San Pedro, Riordan
candidate Lansing ran on a platform of focusing on poor academic
performance, while incumbent Kiriyama insisted that the district
already had turned the tide, as shown by a slight improvement in
test scores.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
