<HEADER>
A7197 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-1ST     04-14 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR COACHES, INDULGENCE IS A BAD RECIPE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The psychiatrist called the hotel room 10 minutes
after Larry Brown finished talking about Allen Iverson on sports
talk radio Tuesday afternoon. He was offering a personality quiz
for Brown so he might then determine the best approach to take with
his young star.
</P>
<P>
   Brown took his number, thanked him, hung up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept it,'' said Brown, never knowing when the next Iverson
crisis would come, where he might have to turn.
</P>
<P>
   He never knows what Iverson will do to astound, or confound.
Many nights, Iverson is truly The Answer. At any other moment, a
riddle. The spindly guard with the propulsion in his calves kept
trying to dribble behind his back last night, through double-teams,
when there was no place to go. He kept losing the ball, the
Philadelphia 76ers fell into a hole, never climbed out.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson, who averages 27 points a game, scored 11 and summed up
the experience with an air-ball free throw. The 76ers lost the
game, 91-72, at Madison Square Garden and more playoff ground to
the suddenly resurgent Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of riddles and answers, the Knicks won their third
straight, convincingly, with no help from a game but sore-footed
Patrick Ewing. Attention, defenders of Ewing: This is no knock at
the proud center, but there was more evidence from a multitude of
Knicks to suggest this team is better off when its guards and
forwards drive the ball, when Ewing gets most of his shots in the
flow, spotting up for jump shots, not from his longtime home in the
post. That's how they started this 180-degree turnaround in Atlanta
last Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   It's becoming so obvious, even William Goldman will figure it
out. As he goes on from here, as the games get bigger, Jeff Van
Gundy's brain twister will be balancing Ewing's in-and-out presence
with the rest of the cast. If Ewing gets healthy, Van Gundy will
have to say things his franchise player has never wished to hear.
Then we will find out how much Ewing really supports his coach, and
if he, at 36, is 13 years more mature than his distant Georgetown
cousin, who leads the league in scoring and swearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear him comment that people don't want to see him do well
_ the media, the league,'' Brown said of Iverson. ``That's baloney.
I think people in the league really want him to succeed.'' The
veteran coach is pushing 60, and he did not take the 76ers' job to
promote Iverson like some soulless shoe company. When he talks
about his shooting point guard, he sounds more like his
tough-talking guidance counselor than his coach.
</P>
<P>
   Brown tries not to forget that Iverson has already come a long
way, and dragged his team of role players with him, into playoff
contention, a mini-miracle based on Tuesday night. He remembers
that too many of the young and gifted come bounding into the pros,
onto bad teams, as Ewing did 14 years ago. The chances are greater
now than ever, Brown said, that they will remain rooted in the
cycle of self-importance until it becomes their personal prison and
there is no escape, and no chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson is a long way from there, but every time he curses his
coach for having the audacity to remove him from the game, or
whatever he interprets as an unproductive show of disrespect, he
most surely takes one step closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I've taken Allen out since I've been here, I've had
the same response,'' Brown said. ``Is it easy to take? No. I
understand he just wants to play, but he doesn't understand how it
affects his teammates or me.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in a season of dramatic improvement, the 76ers are
combustible at the core. Brown, the Dean Smith disciple, knows
Iverson has been indulged everywhere, even at Georgetown. ``I
watched him play there, and that wasn't the way John Thompson
coaches,'' Brown said. Thompson didn't handle Iverson the way he
did Ewing, but then, as Brown said, ``He only had Allen for two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ewing was Iverson's age, he rebelled against his coach,
Hubie Brown. When he was supposedly all grown up, he tuned out Don
Nelson, the only other coach who came along and tried to rearrange
the furniture in the Knicks' predictable offense.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing and Iverson are, of course, as different in style and
personality as they are in size. Ewing never moved with a posse,
never embarrassed the Knicks, on the court or off. But as he limps
toward the finish of his 14th season, he may have to admit what it
is that is so hard for one who has been the center of his universe
for so many years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 0118EDT &QL; 
