</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, April 14.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO (Moved in ``i'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Stankovic, Macedonia) _ In the week since
President Slobodan Milosevic announced that he had halted offensive
military operations in Kosovo, Serb paramilitary groups and
Yugoslav soldiers systematically expelled tens of thousands of
ethnic Albanians from a swath of southeastern Kosovo, according to
reports from refugees arriving here on Tuesday. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ The most liberal member
of the Yugoslav government has sharply attacked the use of Serbian
wartime patriotism for ideological and political ends, throwing
down an indirect challenge to President Slobodan Milosevic and his
nationalist and leftist allies, including Milosevic's wife. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-JEWS (Rome) _ A giant bronze menorah being put up at the
American seminary in Rome to commemorate the Holocaust. The
seminary is technically part of Vatican City, so it would be the
first permanent Holocaust memorial inside the Vatican. But the
sponsorship of the project, Jews from New Jersey and U.S. cardinals
who deal with interfaith issues, also underlines recent strains
between the Vatican and major Jewish organizations. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEALTH-HEARING (Washington) _ In the official government
record, the hearing that began on Tuesday in Room 2358 of the
Rayburn House Office Building will be listed as ``public witness
testimony.'' Unofficially, it was long ago dubbed ``Mother
Theresa's waiting room,'' a moniker that could not be more apt.
Here, for three days this week and two next, the sick and afflicted
and their lobbyists are gathering in an annual telethon of sorts:
the desperate competition for research funding to cure disease.
Hundreds of ailments are represented, from the most common cancer
to the rarest genetic disorder. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TECH-PRODUCTIVITY (Undated) _ For years, as the computer
revolutionized the workplace, productivity _ the output of goods
and services per worker _ stagnated, barely advancing 1 percent a
year. Yet today, skeptics on the subject of technology's
contribution to the economy are having second thoughts.
Productivity growth has picked up, starting in 1996, capped by a
surge in the second half of last year, after eight years of
economic expansion. That has drawn attention because past upward
swings in productivity typically occurred early in a recovery as
economic activity rebounded. Once companies increased hiring, it
slowed again. But something seems fundamentally different this
time, something apparently having a lot to do with the increased
speed and efficiency that the Internet and other pervasive
information-technology advances are bringing to the mundane
day-to-day tasks of millions of businesses. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   FARM-EQUIPMENT (Chicago) _ The biggest names in farm and
construction machinery _ Deere, Case and Caterpillar _ are moving
into new fields in an effort to buffer themselves from the
wrenching up-and-down cycle of their core businesses. By David
Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TRADERS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Having evolved from a nation of
savers to one of investors, America is rapidly becoming a country
of traders. As proof, several brokerage firms have just reported
record profits, fueled in large part by a surge in stock trading
among both individuals and institutions.
</P>
<P>
   VW-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ An unconventional commercial for the
Volkswagen Passat, with a twisty plot that curves more than a
rain-slicked highway in a traditional automotive spot, has people
talking _ and buying, too. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MET-TICKET (New York) _ Ever so quietly, the Metropolitan Museum
of Art has raised its suggested admission price to $10, from $8.
The price jump, which went into effect on Mar. 1, is necessary to
shore up the museum's finances, Met officials say. By Judith
Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   COLLECTOR (Undated) _ Before he died suddenly last year at 81 of
a heart attack, David Feigenbaum led the secret life of a collector
of Citizen Kane-like obsessiveness. He filled almost every inch of
his two-story house in Marblehead, Mass., with things, including
books, guns, model boats, Civil War and World War II paraphernalia
and an old Scottish Bible collection. And in the basement, amid
jewels, old manuscripts and historic letters, was an extraordinary
cache of mid-19th-century daguerreotypes. By Margaret Loke.
</P>
<P>
   TRUE-HEMINGWAY (Boston) _ Authors, scholars and fans gathered
here for the Hemingway Centennial conference at the Kennedy Library
and debated the wisdom and taste of producing a work like ``True at
First Light'' _ the posthumous Ernest Hemingway novel about an
African safari, edited by his son Patrick from a longer manuscript.
The book is to be published by Scribners this summer and is
expected to be the last of his leftover works to see the light of
day. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-JEWS (Hong Kong) _ Arts Abroad: The French photographer
Fred Brenner continues his documentation of the Jewish Diaspora, in
this case the Jewish community in Hong Kong. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   FASCIST-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Fascist Revolution,'' by
George Mosse (Howard Fertig, Inc). Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   TV-OLD-MOVIES (Undated) _ A critic's notebook on old movies on
television. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Maureen Dowd writes about Bill Clinton
and Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-NFL (Los Angeles) _ Last month, the National Football
League announced that Los Angeles was its first choice to receive
the league's as yet un-named 32nd franchise, bypassing a firm bid
of $200 million in public financing from Houston in favor of Los
Angeles' lucrative television market, which is bigger than many
states. But there's a catch: Los Angeles, the town that couldn't
keep a team, now has not one but two competing proposed stadiums
and owner groups, each of them featuring ``guys with egos the size
of Montana,'' in the words of one City Hall aide. By Todd S.
Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ARATON-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column on the
Knicks, who play the 76ers tonight. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-FUSION (Paris) _ Please don't tell Escoffier, but there
is a dessert in Paris called the wonton kumquat Nutella. Served at
a new Right-Bank restaurant called Cafe Mosaic, it comes in a
bamboo steamer. Its central feature is a very undessert-like
display of three soft wonton envelopes, each containing a whole
kumquat and a small puddle of molten Nutella. The thing is awful.
But in Paris, it may also be the wave of the future. Fusion has
come to France, and it feels funny. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-BISTROS (Paris) _ For generations bistros have been the
soul of Paris, casual neighborhood restaurants where regulars drop
in for local gossip and a reassuringly familiar meal. Almost as
important as the food is the setting, usually small, intimate and
aglow with stained or painted wood, etched glass and mirrors,
bric-a-brac, prints and posters. Lately there is a boom in bistros
that serve traditionally lusty cuisine at prices ranging from $20
to $100 for a complete meal for one, wine included. The concept is
so popular that some now require reservations as long as three
weeks ahead, which really compromises the spontaneous bistro
spirit. By Mimi Sheraton.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RAW-EGGS (New York) _ Nothing unusual about the egg yolk staring
up at me from a plate of tagliatelle at Babbo one night last week.
Except that the egg was raw. Totally uncooked. Cold. This was a
little disconcerting at first, but, once mixed in with the buttery
pasta and chunks of cured pork, the egg and the dish warmed up into
an irresistible indulgence, with an aftertaste of danger. Because
raw eggs can kill you. Or so we have been told. By Rick Marin.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
