r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-LA     04-14 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS BEAT LISTLESS LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Unpack the defibrillator, prepare the
artificial respirator. The patient is slipping into a coma.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers' as NBA championship favorites? Toss that
notion on a gurney and wheel it into the ER. Just don't expect a
medical miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Their ace shooter ill, their rebounding specialist bowing out
claiming elbow pain, the team's pulse now just a faint thudding
sound, the Lakers are crawling toward the finish line of this
regular season with barely a wheezing breath left in them.
</P>
<P>
   And with Kevorkian behind bars, no one's left to pull the plug
and end suffering like the Lakers endured Tuesday night in a 113-86
drubbing by the Portland Trail Blazers at the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers on life support? Even Shaquille O'Neal seemed to
indicate as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get some heart,'' O'Neal said in the wake of the
Lakers' worst defeat of the season. ``I'm very disappointed. Guys
on this team have gotta step up to the challenge.... Forget the
plays and all that stuff. We need to bring heart to every game.''
</P>
<P>
   At the least, they need to bring players to every game,
increasingly a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   One starter, Glen Rice, has tonsillitis. Another, Dennis Rodman,
developed another case of elbow soreness and could not or would not
play the second half. Derek Harper, the 37-year-old starting point
guard, was benched to protect him from overuse and fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   What was left was a disjointed team that made 39 percent of its
shots, scored a season-low 15 points in the second quarter, was
outrebounded by seven and allowed 113 points _ a regulation-game
season-high _ for the second straight game.
</P>
<P>
   After O'Neal's 24 points, Kobe Bryant's 20 (on 7-of-19 shooting)
and 17 from Rick Fox off the bench, the Lakers had nothing. And
nothing resembling defense, as they allowed Portland to shoot 56.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come out with any fire or intensity,'' coach Kurt
Rambis said. ``They showed us how far we have to grow and how far
we have to develop as a ballclub _ how hard we have to play and how
intense we have to play in order to match up against the best team
in the league, or one of the best teams in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   At 29-8, the Trail Blazers certainly look like the best, their
recent loss to the Clippers notwithstanding. The Lakers (25-15)
looked utterly outclassed.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Blazers scored in double figures in a game Portland led
from wire to wire by as many as 28 points. So deep are the Blazers,
Portland's bench outscored the Lakers' starters 63-51. Damon
Stoudamire and Isaiah Rider scored a team-high 16 points apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not at full strength,'' Robert Horry said. ``Glen was
out and then Rodman was unavailable, and it really wasn't a true
Laker performance.''
</P>
<P>
   But championship teams are supposed to overcome such obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't, not us,'' Horry said. ``Our bench isn't as deep as
it needs to be. Look at Portland _ they've got a whole second five
they can put in.... We need everybody healthy and everybody on this
team to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Including Rodman, who grabbed four rebounds in 13 minutes. He
was benched toward the end of the first half, then told team
trainer Gary Vitti his left elbow was in pain. It's the fourth time
in five weeks that Rodman has refused to re-enter a game, citing
the elbow or muscle tightness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said his elbow was bothering him and I'll take it for
that,'' Rambis said. Or was Rodman simply upset over being benched
in the first half? ``That's a question you'd have to ask Dennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman didn't speak with reporters but told TNT he expected the
media to ``make me look bad'' over the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Horry said the injury is real and that Rodman has been
complaining about the elbow ``the last three or four games.''
</P>
<P>
   But considering Rodman's track record, few others seemed as
sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was hurt,'' O'Neal said. ``I hope he really was
hurt. Because if he really wasn't hurt, I need him out there with
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
