<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ATHLETICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' OFFENSE TAKES NIGHT OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ The Anaheim Angels arrived in Oakland late Monday
feeling good about themselves after beating the Texas Rangers in
three of four games. But their mood changed Tuesday night after
discovering they left their bats behind in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that there was a transit problem with their equipment
on the flight from Dallas. It only seemed that way.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring 34 runs on 57 hits in four games against the
Rangers, the Angels were reduced to mere mortals in a 3-2 loss to
the Oakland A's before 5,377 at the Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   A's starter Mike Oquist, called up from Triple-A Vancouver to
make Tuesday's start, made the Angels hitters look like
minor-leaguers. Oquist (1-0) allowed one run and four hits in six
innings, and got relief help from 41-year-old Doug Jones and Billy
Taylor, who made his first save.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had one last chance to tie in the ninth inning, but
pinch-runner Orlando Palmeiro was thrown out trying to steal second
when the A's called for a pitchout. It was the first out of the
inning, but it took the steam out of a potential rally.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Steve Sparks picked up where he left off from his
first start _ giving up runs. He gave up at least one run in each
of his four innings on April 8 against the Indians, and started
Tuesday by allowing three in the first inning. Matt Stairs had the
big hit, a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks made 40 pitches in the first inning alone, but settled
down after that, keeping the A's from scoring again before leaving
after six innings. He made 134 pitches, giving up the three runs
(two earned) and seven hits with seven strikeouts and three walks.
</P>
<P>
   He had to wiggle his way out of trouble in both the third and
fifth innings. In the third, the A's had runners on first and third
with one out when Eric Chavez popped to short and Mike Macfarlane
struck out.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, the A's had runners on first and second with one
out when Ben Grieve struck out into a double play, Stairs being
thrown out trying to steal third.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the only offense the Angels could muster against
Oquist came thanks to a fly ball lost in the lights. Todd Greene
led off the third inning with a high fly to left field, but Grieve
couldn't find it and in fell in for a double.
</P>
<P>
   Two groundouts later and Greene scored to cut the A's lead to
3-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had a good chance to tie the game in the fourth
inning when a hot Troy Glaus (hitting .481 going into the game)
came to the plate with runners on second and third with two out. On
a 3-2 pitch, Glaus grounded out to third.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus got another chance in the eighth inning with runners on
first and second and two out, and doubled in one run. However,
third base coach Larry Bowa held up Garret Anderson at third, and
the next batter _ Greene _ flied out to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels offense was a far cry from the 20-hit attack one day
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``When somebody tells me they can explain this game to me, I'll
listen,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``It's a strange
sport, it's why it's so great. Every game is different.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 0200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
