<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7215 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCKETBOY-AZR &LR;      04-14 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ROCKET BOY' GETS ANOTHER CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
 BOY-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glendale's ``Rocket Boy'' has landed safely back in school.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprising vote Tuesday night, the Deer Valley Unified
School District Governing Board, meeting in a closed session, voted
to allow David Silverstein to return to Desert Sky Middle School on
April 26.
</P>
<P>
   The incident began about six weeks ago when David, 13, was
suspended for bringing a homemade rocket to school. It ended with
hugs and tears for David, his father, Ed, and his mother, Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just looked at me and started to, well, he's kind of a
quiet kid, and he gave his little smile,'' Ed Silverstein said. ``I
walked over and hugged him and could feel the feeling of happy
tears forming in both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials can't discuss what transpires in closed
sessions. The vote count wasn't released.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a little bit satisfied that the board members who I
looked in the eye when I spoke, I felt, really did show human
quality, flexibility and compassion for what occurred,'' the father
said.
</P>
<P>
   David, a seventh-grader, was suspended Feb. 26, a day after a
routine locker inspection turned up his rocket, which consisted of
a potato-chip canister can, some air plane paint, paper and three
strips of adhesive bandage.
</P>
<P>
   Police called it an incendiary device, and the school district
clas sified it as a firearm, subject to the district's
zero-tolerance policy on guns.
</P>
<P>
   David built his rocket after listen ing to his dad talk about
October Sky, a movie based on a true story about four boys who
decide to become rocket scientists in the late '50s.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Silverstein said he did not want his son to be interviewed
Tuesday night, but did say that he celebrated the result with a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The episode is behind us in as much as our first concern is
for David and his education,'' he said. ``We feel that justice has
been served in this case, albeit a little slow for us at times.''
</P>
<P>
   The Silversteins had requested that their appeal hearing, which
lasted about 90 minutes, be closed.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of teachers from the middle school, many wearing simi lar
shirts, showed up at the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens to the boy affects the whole school,'' teacher
Mary Whitson said.
</P>
<P>
   There was a party atmosphere in the overcrowded room, and most
people there for the rocket case seemed to wonder why no decision
was made public. The Silversteins left the building through a rear
exit to avoid media and school officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what their motiva tion was for being there,'' Ed
Silverstein said of the teachers. ``I would hope that their
interests are in teaching and educating children, and that's their
first priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression was that the board treated us fairly, listened
and showed compassion. Maybe it's a new begining for them, on how .
. . hiding behind policy is very old-fashioned.''
</P>
<P>
   David, who likes rockets but also is interested in computers,
has been home-schooled by his mother since his suspension.
</P>
<P>
   His plight caught the attention of many around the country, most
of whom are critical of the school district for what they see as
stifling a youngster's scientific curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   His situation also has been a rallying cry for space enthusiasts
and others around the country. He has received phone calls and
e-mails from former astronauts, as well as from Homer Hickam, the
hero of October Sky, and others involved in the aerospace industry.
</P>
<P>
   One Valley businessman offered to pay for David's education from
the eighth grade through high school at a private school. His
father said they are considering that offer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 0204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
