<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-CLIPPERS-NYT     04-14 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-CLIPPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS DEFEAT NETS, 109-101 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The New Jersey Nets' blowout loss to the New York
Knicks on Sunday was no aberration. But apparently, their stretch
of five victories in six games that preceded it was.
</P>
<P>
   In an almost certain sign that the seemingly rejuvenated Nets
have degenerated back to their struggling selves, they fell hard on
Tuesday night to the Los Angeles Clippers, the team with the worst
record in the league. Destroying the Nets' deteriorating defense to
shoot 57 percent from the floor, the Clippers earned a 109-101
victory before a sparse but raucous crowd of 6,218 at the Sports
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps fittingly, Sherman Douglas, the Nets' backup point guard
last season, played a large part in assuring their demise on
Tuesday night. Displaying the craftiness and leadership that had
the Nets dreading his departure as a free agent before this season,
Douglas scored 8 of his 18 points in the Clippers' 31-point third
quarter that saw them go ahead by as much as 18 points and take an
89-74 lead into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after the Nets' made a feverish charge to pull within 5
points three times, Douglas, who also had six assists, helped hold
them down. His most critical play came when he picked Stephon
Marbury of his dribble, took the ball the length of the court and
drew a shooting foul. He sank the ensuing free throws with 2
minutes 20 seconds remaining to put the Clippers up 106-96.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury came back with a 3-pointer, and Keith Van Horn followed
with one free throw to pull the Nets within 5 points again, but
Lamond Murray ended the suspense by hitting a 3-pointer with less
than a minute left.
</P>
<P>
   Murray led the Clippers (6-31), who assured themselves of not
having the worst winning percentage in National Basketball
Association history, with 22 points. Van Horn, playing before 30 of
his fans from his hometown in Diamond Bar, Calif., led the Nets
with 33 points. Marbury added 23 points to go with 8 assists. Jamie
Feick grabbed a career-high 15 rebounds, and Kerry Kittles added 16
points.
</P>
<P>
   Despite displaying defensive futility that allowed the Clippers
to shoot 53 percent, the Nets trailed by only 5 points at
intermission, 58-53. Murray, Tyrone Nesby and Eric Piatkowski,
juking and driving by the lethargic Nets defenders, combined for 40
points on 16-of-24 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, a 6-foot-7-inch forward who came off the bench, looked
like the All-Star he was projected to be when the Clippers made him
the seventh pick in the 1994 draft. Murray, making a mockery of the
defensive efforts of the Nets' swingmen, made 5 of 7 shots and all
six of his free throws to score 16 first-half points in just 12
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In one stretch, he scored 6 points, 2 of which came on an
18-foot baseline jumper in which he faked Kittles out of his
sneakers, to lead a 12-1 run that put the Clippers ahead by 43-35
midway through the second quarter. Nesby, also a swingman, was
nearly as lethal, scoring 13 points before the break.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the first quarter, Piatkowski made Kittles look as if
his feet were stuck in cement by scoring 11 points in seven
minutes. Just a minute into the game, Piatkowski drove baseline on
the Nets' shooting guard and threw down a vicious two-handed slam.
And half a minute later, he sank a running 11-footer, then followed
a Maurice Taylor jump shot with a 3-pointer and 16-footer. Kittles,
his defense having vanished, tried to hang in by sinking two
3-pointers and a 12-footer in the first five minutes, but he still
lost that battle.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
