<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7240 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHMIDT-WALK-AZR &LR;      04-14 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHMIDT-WALK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER SURVIVOR WILL WALK WITH FRIENDS AT GRADUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LORI BAKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The national spotlight, the media pressure, the
onslaught of supporters made it all but inevitable: The Deer Valley
school board had to vote Tuesday to let cancer survivor Cameron
Schmidt walk with his class at commencement.
</P>
<P>
   But to thunderous applause at a packed meeting, the board took
it one step further and decided to award the 18-year-old instant
celebrity an honorary diploma.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the right decision,'' a stunned Schmidt, wearing his
ever-present baseball cap, said after the 8:30 p.m. 5-0 vote to let
him walk with his class. ``The media coverage and support from
friends has paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he's short three credits, even though school
officials originally told him no, Schmidt will join the Mountain
Ridge High School's Class of '99 when it graduates May 20.
</P>
<P>
   Now Schmidt can begin planning for a future that eventually will
include college and possibly a career in marine biology or as a
firefighter. He expects to complete his three high school credits
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt, of Phoenix, and his friend, Melissa Robbins, had rushed
to the board meeting from Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport
after flying in from New York City, where they appeared Tuesday
morning on NBC-TV's ``Today.'' The show was one of a flurry of
recent national media appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters had read about the foregone conclusion in the
newspapers, seen it on national TV and heard about it on all the
local radio talk shows. But dozens poured into the Deer Valley
Unified School District offices on Tuesday night to hear it from
the five people who could make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   Board member David Cantelme said the honorary diploma was ``in
recognition of Cameron Schmidt's heroic battle against cancer, his
determined efforts to complete the required 22 credits to graduate,
and the example he has set and the lessons he has taught us all in
how to deal with life's adversities.''
</P>
<P>
   No one from the audience addressed the board before the vote.
They didn't need to. Board members were aware of the public
sentiment from the news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Schmidt's request and the support he's received
from his classmates struck a chord with nearly everyone who heard
it _ from students and fellow cancer survivors to parents,
retirees, blue-collar workers and educators.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt was overwhelmed with requests for interviews. On Monday
afternoon, he was on ``Inside Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, Schmidt and Robbins clutched hands as Katie
Couric read Monday's statement from the school district saying that
board members individually told Superintendent Gerald Cuendet that
they would grant Schmidt an exception to district policy.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins said she hopes the decision will open the doors for
students in similar situations.
</P>
<P>
   Board members said Tuesday's vote did not set a precedent, but
the board plans to adopt a policy allowing honorary diplomas to
recognize students of extraordinary merit and allow them to be in
commencement exercises.
</P>
<P>
   Some Valley districts grant exceptions, but some educators are
concerned about where to draw the line.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt, who had battled Hodgkin's disease with a bone marrow
transplant, chemotherapy and radiation treatments, has been
cancer-free for 10 months and says he is getting stronger every
day. He has maintained a ``B'' average.
</P>
<P>
   He received homebound instruction during his junior year and
part of his senior year. He takes four classes at Mountain Ridge,
22800 N. 67th Ave. &UR; in Glendale, and two classes at home. He was
unable to keep pace with his classmates while he underwent
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   After Schmidt returned to Mountain Ridge in January, his parents
asked administrators to allow him to participate in graduation even
though he was short credits. They were repeatedly told no.
</P>
<P>
   On March 23, Schmidt's father, Bill, pleaded with board members
on his son's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Friday morning, when about 800 Mountain Ridge
students joined his fight, that Schmidt's plight captured national
attention. Later that day, Deer Valley officials said a committee
of administrators would study the commencement policy and leave it
to the board to grant an exception.
</P>
<P>
   Deer Valley administrators will meet today to discuss the
policy. As many as 80 students who are short credits for reasons
ranging from illness to pregnancy could be affected by a policy
change, Cuendet said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this will clarify our policy on the graduation
ceremony requirements and we can get back to the business of
education,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
