<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-SPURS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS SEE SOME LIGHT, STUN SPURS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The future might look bright for the Mavericks after
all.
</P>
<P>
   In a season filled with near misses and bad luck, the Mavericks
finally stood up to one of the big boys of the NBA Western
Conference for an entire game. And they can thank their ``kids''
for it.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the aggressive play of rookie Dirk Nowitzki and
second-year player Chris Anstey, the Mavericks crawled out of their
slumber and stunned the highly regarded San Antonio Spurs, 92-86,
last night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   For the 12-25 Mavericks, the victory was huge because of the
impressive credentials the Spurs brought to town. San Antonio came
in sporting the best record in the NBA since March 1 at 19-3, while
the Mavericks dragged themselves out of bed losers in 11 of their
previous 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   But ... the unexpected happened, as the Mavericks recorded their
first win of the season in 17 outings against any of the top eight
teams in the Western Conference. Indeed, the outcome left parties
on both sides dumbfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a business,'' Mavericks coach Don Nelson said. ``We go
from the worst loss of the year \R91-90 to Golden State on
Saturday\S to the best win of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy, but I just felt good about the way the young guys
played. We gave them the opportunity, they seized the moment ...
and it got us an unexpected win.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory came even though the Mavericks wrote the NBA book on
how to cave in down the stretch. But such was not the case last
night, as the Mavericks outrebounded the taller Spurs, 50-44, and
executed in crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   In his first start since Feb. 26, Nowitzki scored 12 points,
and, more important, he was attacking the glass and wound up with a
game-high 13 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was huge for me,'' Nowitzki said. ``All of the time you
hear you're not ready, so this was huge for my confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Anstey scored all eight of his points in the frantic fourth
period, and also contributed six rebounds and three blocked shots.
Anstey's block of a Sean Elliott shot led to a highlight dunk by
Michael Finley, who soared to the basket and jammed the ball in
David Robinson's face, putting the Mavericks within 81-80.
</P>
<P>
   Anstey's jumper put the Mavericks ahead for good, at 82-81.
Anstey later crammed home a rebound dunk for an 86-81 Mavericks
lead with less than two minutes left as the Spurs (25-12) departed
wondering how this could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to keep plugging until something good happens,''
said Finley, who scored a game-high 25 points. ``The last couple of
losses have been really hard on me personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing for me is my mom is in town, and she just told
me to keep my head up and that God will never put anything in front
of me that I couldn't handle, and I took that to heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory ties Nelson with predecessor Jim Cleamons for
Mavericks victories with 28. Cleamons reached it in 98 games, while
it took Nelson 103 games.
</P>
<P>
   How to explain it? ``Even a blind squirrel is going to find a
nut every now and then,'' said Mavericks forward Gary Trent, who
scored 18 points. ``We got on them and we didn't let up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks are 4-12 in games decided by eight points or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether to be excited for the victory or to be
disappointed,'' said point guard Steve Nash, who had 12 assists and
two steals. ``This just pronounced how many of those close games we
should have won.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's part of the pain and the torture of being a young
team that's new to each other. I'm just glad that we were able to
get one, and we have to count our blessings in this case and be
happy.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
