<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MARINERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ'S 9 RBI BURY MARINERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Forget Hack Wilson. Juan Gonzalez needs to worry about
Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who for a time last season threatened Wilson's
single-season runs batted in record, holds most of the Rangers'
significant RBI marks. But Rodriguez stole one away from him last
night in the Rangers' 15-5 victory over the Seattle Mariners at the
Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, with two home runs and a single, drove in nine runs
in the first three innings and set a team record for RBI in a game.
He broke the record of eight set by Gonzalez in 1993 against the
California Angels and tied by Jose Canseco in 1994 against the
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez fell three short of the major-league record set by St.
Louis Cardinals first baseman Jim Bottomley in 1924 and tied by
Cardinals outfielder Mark Whiten in 1993. The American League
record is 11, set by Yankees second baseman Tony Lazzeri in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   The news was not all good for the Rangers though. Their injury
situation took another twist.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had shortstop Royce Clayton back in their lineup,
but now they have to worry about designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro
missing time. Palmeiro, limited to DH duty because of his knee
problems, had to leave last night's game in the first inning
because of a tight right hamstring muscle.
</P>
<P>
   He is listed as day-to-day, but there's a good chance he'll miss
at least the next two games. Trainer Danny Wheat said the injury
was similar to the hamstring problem Mark McLemore had last week
when he missed an exhibition game and the first three
regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers don't think Palmeiro's injury is related to his
injured right knee. The hamstring injury occurred during the
Rangers five-run outburst in the first inning against Mariners
starter Ken Cloude. Palmeiro, with runners on second and first,
smacked a line drive high off the right-field wall and felt the
hamstring tighten as he rounded first base.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's offense helped the Rangers jump out to a 13-0 lead
after three innings, more than enough support for starter Mike
Morgan. Making his first start with the Rangers, Morgan allowed two
runs on three hits through six innings before fading in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan gave up three runs then, but still beat the Mariners for
the first time since 1979, his second season in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's spectacular display started in the first inning with
a three-run homer into the second deck in left field off Cloude.
Rodriguez is only the 12th player to reach that area since the
Kingdome opened in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez followed that with a two-run single in the second and
a grand slam in the third, his first in 112 major-league home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez had a shot at the major-league and American League
records when he batted with runners at first and second with one
out in the fifth. But Mariners reliever Mac Suzuki got him on a fly
ball to center.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez had a leadoff single in the seventh, giving him four
hits for the 14th time in his career.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
