<HEADER>
A7246 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-REWRITE-LA     04-14 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISTAKE HURTS AS ANGELS FALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Score lots of runs, mistakes don't hurt as much. Score
a little, mistakes are magnified. Such was the case Tuesday night
when a mistake cost the Anaheim Angels in a 3-2 loss to the Oakland
A's before 5,377 at the Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   A potential ninth-inning rally was thwarted when pinch-runner
Orlando Palmeiro was thrown out trying to steal second with nobody
out.
</P>
<P>
   Aggressive baserunning? Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   There was no steal sign put on, yet Palmeiro broke for second
and was thrown out easily because the A's called for a pitchout.
Catcher Mike Macfarlane's throw was on target.
</P>
<P>
   After the game there was some question as to whether the A's had
stolen a sign and called for the pitchout. But Angels third base
coach Larry Bowa made it clear the A's could not have stolen a
sign, because there wasn't a sign to steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know 'em, and we don't know 'em,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The only sign that was on was the bunt sign, but the pitch was
too far off the plate for the hitter, Andy Sheets, to get a bat on.
And Palmeiro surprised the Angels by running _ not the A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed a sign, that's all that matters,'' Palmeiro said.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels arrived in Oakland late Monday feeling good about
themselves after beating the Texas Rangers in three of four games.
But the offense they had in Texas _ 34 runs and 57 hits _ didn't
arrive with them.
</P>
<P>
   A's starter Mike Oquist, called up from Triple-A Vancouver to
make the start, made the Angels hitters look like minor-leaguers.
Oquist (1-0) allowed only one run and four hits in six innings, and
got relief help from 41-year-old Doug Jones and Billy Taylor, who
recorded his first save of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels did manage five hits in the seventh and eighth
innings, but had only one run to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had nine hits,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``We
hit the ball, we just didn't get hits with guys in scoring
position. When we had guys in scoring position, they made good
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels missed an opportunity in the eighth after Troy Glaus'
two-out double scored Tim Salmon to make it 3-2. With the potential
tying and go-ahead runs on second and third, Todd Greene swung at
the first pitch by Jones and flied out to left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had chances late in the game to win the game and we didn't
execute, including myself,'' Greene said. ``I need a better at-bat
than a one-pitch pop-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Steve Sparks (0-2) picked up where he left off
from his first start _ giving up runs. He gave up at least one run
in each of his four innings on April 8 against the Indians, and
started Tuesday by giving up three in the first inning. Matt Stairs
had the big hit, a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks made 40 pitches in the first inning alone but settled
down after that, keeping the A's from scoring again before leaving
after six innings. He made 134 pitches, giving up the three runs
(two earned) and seven hits with seven strikeouts and three walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me two or three innings to feel comfortable and get
locked in with my knuckleball,'' Sparks said. ``The ball seemed
hard and slick, so it was hard to get a feel for it. I tried to get
by with my other pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fateful first inning, five of the first six A's batters
reached base _ three with singles and two with walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Sparks) walked some guys, went deep in counts,'' Collins
noted. ``He's a knuckleball pitcher _ you get in fastball counts
guys are going to hit you.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had eight innings to score some runs and get back in the
game. We didn't score. It's pretty simple.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
