<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS WIN AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dealing a cheeky attitude as they roll along, the
Los Angeles Clippers have just greeted history with an obscene
gesture that requires both hands.
</P>
<P>
   Six fingers for six victories.
</P>
<P>
   Our opening testimony is given by co-starring forward Lamond
Murray, who provided a team-high 22 off the bench: ``We're trying
to ride that wave of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest bit of chest-thumping was achieved in Tuesday's
109-101 victory over the New Jersey Nets in front of 6,218 at the
Sports Arena. This result prevents the Clippers (6-31) from sinking
their sneakers in the permanent ink of history; they now can lose
their remaining 13 games and still have a higher winning percentage
than the 1972-'73 Philadelphia 76ers. Those swingin' Sixers expired
with a 9-73 mark, which translates to a batting average of .110.
The Clips - checking in with a gaudy .162 -- could whiff the rest
of the season and finish at .120.
</P>
<P>
   But there is considerable evidence to the contrary. The Clippers
now have won consecutive games for the first time in over 15
months, and three of their last four.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can walk with your head up a bit more,'' said guard Eric
Piatkowski, who has spent most of the season huddled in a foxhole
with his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Nets (10-27), their collection of rising talent and
pre-season hype have made them as bitterly disappointing as your
first beer.
</P>
<P>
   For the rising Clippers, it was almost nothing but net.
</P>
<P>
   When Piatkowski drilled a 3-pointer at the 2:35 mark in the
third quarter, the Clipper held an 84-67 lead and had made 60
percent of their field-goal attempts. That's almost nothing but
net.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, their baby-faced frontline of Tyrone Nesby
(20, five), Maurice Taylor (18, 12) and Michael Olowokandi (six,
11) had combined for 44 points and 28 rebounds. Taylor's howling,
multi-facial slam with 6:55 also drew a Jersey foul and gave the
Clippers - who were tripping toward skid row -- a 95-88 cushion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that dunk was a 10,'' said Taylor, who probably should add
some extra credit for modesty.
</P>
<P>
   Piatkowski, who gunned in 11 points in the opening quarter and
finished with 17, was a bit more reserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of got on a roll,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran point guard Sherman Douglas, whose previous NBA stop was
New Jersey, was the man who executed Coach Chris Ford's plan. ``The
Shermanator'' scored 18 points, handed out four assists and
received a flood of praise in a rare post-game, dressing-room visit
from team owner Donald T. Sterling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was him, I wouldn't come in here much, either,'' Douglas
said.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Clippers signed point guard Troy Hudson for the
remainder of the season, and also have the CBA escapee under
contract for next season's training camp. Hudson, who previously
had played under back-to-back, 10-day contracts, is averaging 4.7
points and 1.7 assists per game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 0245EDT &QL; 
