<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-RANGERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOUDE DISSIPATES IN RANGER ROUT; RODRIGUEZ COLLECTS NINE RBI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When the Mariners sent Ken Cloude to Class AAA Tacoma
to start the season, this was the thinking: He would work on his
mechanical problems, experience some success and return a more
confident pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude dominated in two minor league outings and corrected his
physical flaws. But Tuesday night against the Texas Rangers, he
experienced the same kind of result that ruined his spring. Cloude
lasted 12/3 innings, allowing seven runs on six hits and four walks
in a 15-6 loss.
</P>
<P>
   He might be headed back to Tacoma. Manager Lou Piniella would
not say whether Cloude would make another start in Seattle, saying
he needed to discuss the matter with the front office first. But
with Mac Suzuki and Brett Hinchliffe unavailable after long relief
stints Tuesday night, Piniella said, the M's need an extra reliever
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't stay with 10 pitchers, I can tell you that,''
Piniella said. ``We'll see what we do, but we need someone that can
give us some innings.''
</P>
<P>
   That extra pitcher will not be reliever Mark Leiter, who was
sidelined with shoulder tendinitis and will pitch the first two
innings Wednesday night for Tacoma in hopes that he can be
activated Friday. As for Cloude's future, the 24-year-old
right-hander said he is not concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to (another start),'' Cloude said. ``I
don't see it happening any other way. Those kinds of things don't
bother me anymore. I try to worry about what I can control _
throwing strikes and getting people out. I don't worry about
getting sent down or making another start.''
</P>
<P>
   The M's were counting on Cloude to build off his 1998 season,
when he went 8-10 and made 30 starts. But patience might be running
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep looking for Ken to get over the hump,'' said pitching
coach Stan Williams. ``He showed us at times last year what he was
capable of, but he hasn't been able to sustain it for any length of
time. It's really time for him to make up his mind that he's going
to go out there and pitch with his mind as well as his body and
stay positive out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you what's in his mind, because I don't know. But
it's time for him to kick in and get some consistency. Nobody's
pulling for him more than I am, but he's got to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella and Williams said they expected more after Cloude's
last Class AAA outing, in which he gave up a hit to the leadoff
batter, then threw six hitless, shutout innings. This game started
with two quick strikes to Texas' Tom Goodwin, but Cloude ended up
walking him, soon loaded the bases on a single and another walk _
with a wild pitch that missed the catcher's glove mixed in _ and
the rout was on.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez led the Rangers' charge with a club-record nine
runs batted in, just three away from the all-time record shared by
Jim Bottomley and Mark Whiten.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude said the leadoff walk did not unnerve him. He was sharp
in his pregame bullpen session, and Williams said Cloude's arm
angle, which had been a problem in spring training, was fine this
time.
</P>
<P>
   But sideline success didn't carry over to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I threw in the bullpen before the game, I didn't think
about anything, I just threw,'' Cloude said. `` ... I go out there
on the mound, and it's as if I don't relax. That's a big
distraction, not being able to relax. It takes away from my
concentration. If anything, it's being too focused, too into it,
and you try to do too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloude said he doesn't like nit-picking with his mechanics and
believes his problems have been more mental than physical. He found
himself trying to muscle the ball Tuesday night, causing him to
lose movement on his fastball and depth on his breaking ball.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he remains in Seattle, he said he's staying positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' he said, ``but I'm not down on myself
right now, I know that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
