<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 03:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7276 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-OVITZ-LADN     04-14 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OVITZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY OFFICIAL REACTS TO OVITZ REPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Michael Ovitz has decided to withdraw his proposal for a NFL
expansion franchise in Carson, he hasn't told anyone in Carson.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday afternoon, city officials had been in contact with
Ovitz representatives about details of their bid and next week's
visit by the NFL expansion and finance committees. Published
reports today say that Ovitz is withdrawing his bid and will
support the New Coliseum proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being told (by Ovitz people) that's (the report) not
true,'' said Carson City Manager Jerry Groomes Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spoke with his attorney (James Ellis) yesterday. We've been
trying to prepare for the NFL visit and coordinating things with
Mr. Ovitz. We haven't heard a thing about this.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Carson city officials have admittedly been wary of
Ovitz's direction since the NFL meetings in Phoenix last month. At
that meeting, league owners gave L.A. a conditional bid for a 32nd
franchise subject to NFL interests here providing a tight stadium
and financing plan within six months.
</P>
<P>
   That resolution, hammered home by NFL Commissioner Paul
Tagliabue, made it clear the league would select the site and the
ownership group and not necessarily choose between the Ovitz/Carson
proposal or the New Coliseum plan backed by L.A. businessmen Ed
Roski and Eli Broad.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue also said the league wanted a broader ownership group
and hinted at the possibility of the two groups coming together as
one.
</P>
<P>
   After those meetings, Ovitz, chairman of Artists Management
Group, said he would do whatever the league asked him to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues are not anyone's to decide but the league,'' he
said last month. ``It only matters what they think. I think
(Carson's) the best option ... But you can't force them to choose
your site. They'll make the decision, and if they tell me to play
in a sandlot, I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Ovitz representatives Tuesday were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Groomes and Carson City Councilman Daryl Sweeney both have
expressed their frustrations over the last few months, or since
Tagliabue and expansion committee chairman Jerry Richardson took a
helicopter tour of the stadium site and lauded the city's effort.
</P>
<P>
   They wondered why Ovitz didn't have the same presence at the
Phoenix meetings as the New Coliseum group. Sweeney said he has
asked Ovitz and his representatives for input on making their
proposal stronger and rallying public support for next week's
visit, but there has been little substantive discussion.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday afternoon, NFL spokesman Joe Browne said the
expansion committee was planning to visit both sites Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   This comes a day after the Los Angeles Times reported that the
NFL has broached a plan with Fox and L.A. city officials about a
combined project that would have the Dodgers moving to a new
stadium next to the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Fox officials acknowledged the contact but said it's just one of
many proposals that's been presented since the company purchased
the Dodgers from Peter O'Malley for $311 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the Dodgers say the idea was floated by NFL
officials who want to make the New Coliseum proposal look more
palatable.
</P>
<P>
   There are still several NFL owners wary of returning to the
Coliseum in any fashion. Plus, the league has a credibility issue
if it accepts the New Coliseum idea as it stands now. It lacks the
fresh public funding that has been driving the league's stadium
criteria the last ten years.
</P>
<P>
   The City of Carson is prepared to invest upwards of $180 million
in the stadium and mall proposal, $30 million in cash and a bond
issue worth $150 million. Ovitz's blueprint was for a combined mall
and stadium called ``The Hacienda'' built on a former landfill at
the intersection of the Harbor and San Diego freeways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
