<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 03:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7305 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-DIAMONDBA     04-14 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-DIAMONDBACKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS FALL IN 16TH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Three times the Los Angeles Dodgers appeared dead,
done, finished. Three times they came back from improbable odds to
breathe.
</P>
<P>
   The one time the Dodgers seemed in control was the time it got
away.
</P>
<P>
   After the Dodgers scored twice in the top of the 16th inning,
the Diamondbacks countered with three in the bottom of the inning
to post a 7-6 win Tuesday at Bank One Ballpark. Dante Powell's
double off Pedro Borbon scored Tony Batista with the winning run
with one out.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers took a 6-4 lead in the top of the 16th without aid
of a hit. Raul Mondesi walked and moved to second on Todd Hundley's
sacrifice bunt. Pitcher Bobby Chouinard threw wide to first and
Diamondbacks second baseman Tony Womack hurt his ankle on the play
and wandered off the bag. Noticing it, Mondesi sprinted for third
and slid in safely.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros then lined a ball to third, but Matt Williams
misplayed it and Mondesi scored. After a Dave Mlicki sacrifice
moved runners to second and third, Adrian Beltre was intentionally
walked and Tripp Cromer grounded to shortstop to score another run.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't over. Steve Finley led off the bottom of the
inning with a single and Kelly Stinnett hit his first career
pinch-hit homer to tie the game 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   Batista and Womack each singled before Powell's double.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki (0-1) picked up the loss despite pitching well in relief.
Chouinard (1-0) was the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I needed help for Mlicki, but I was hoping he could get
by,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``It just wasn't meant to
be. It was a great team effort. We were battling.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the longest game in Diamondbacks history, but through the
first eight innings there were no indications how long things would
drag on.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scored twice in the top of the ninth to tie the
game, but that was nothing compared to the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Diamondbacks had the bases loaded with none out
and couldn't score against Mlicki. The situation was set up on
Mondesi's throwing error. Williams led off the 11th with a bloop
single to right. He made a wide turn and Mondesi tried to throw
behind Williams at first. Eric Karros couldn't handle the bouncing
throw and Williams went to second.
</P>
<P>
   Finley attempted to sacrifice the runners over. His bunt attempt
was fielded by Karros, but the throw was high to first.
Mysteriously, Finley was credited with a base hit to load the bases
with none out.
</P>
<P>
   But Mlicki struck out pinch-hitter Bernard Gilkey, and third
baseman Adrian Beltre saved the game on a heads-up play on Damian
Miller's smash. Beltre had the ball bounce off his chest but into
his hand. He fired to Todd Hundley for the force at the plate.
Mlicki got Batista to pop to right and end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona couldn't break through in the 12th either. Jay Bell
singled with one out and Travis Lee followed with a perfectly
executed hit-and-run through the shortstop side to move Powell, the
pinch-runner, to third. But a brilliant double play between Eric
Young, Cromer and Karros kept the game going.
</P>
<P>
   Williams hit a grounder behind second. Young fielded it, slipped
to Cromer, who pirouetted on second (or in the neighborhood) and
threw to a stretching Karros to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in five games the teams have gone into
extra innings this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers tied it in the top of the ninth with two runs, and
they rallied after having none on and two outs. And they came
within a few inches of winning the game in nine innings when
pinch-hitter Dave Hansen's drive to right-center field hit the top
of the wall. But the ball bounced back into play.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' rally started harmlessly enough against
Diamondbacks closer du jour Darren Holmes. Mark Grudzielanek
singled to center with two outs. Beltre doubled to the left-center
field fence to pull the Dodgers within 4-3 and set the stage for
Hansen, pinch-hitter extraordinaire.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen, who is 5 for 6 as a pinch-hitter this season, smashed
the ball off the top of the wall to drive in Beltre with the tying
run.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth blown save in four opportunities for Arizona's
bullpen. It also spoiled a tremendous performance by starting
pitcher Armando Reynoso. He gave up one run on five hits. He struck
out four and walked a batter.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona second baseman Jay Bell became the ninth Diamondbacks
player to hit two homers in a game. He had solo home runs in the
fifth and sixth innings.
</P>
<P>
   Until the ninth, everything was going Arizona's way.
</P>
<P>
   Two things pitchers need to do to be successful is minimize the
damage in any one inning, and shut down clubs the inning after
their offense provides runs.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers starter Ismael Valdes failed to do the latter. An inning
after Gary Sheffield homered to cut Arizona's lead to 2-1, Valdes
was hit hard.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' Miller led off the sixth with a double off the
right field wall. He was sacrificed to third by Reynoso. Womack
flied to right to set up what should have been a close play to the
plate. But Mondesi, long regarded as one of the best defensive
outfielders in the game, had his throw sail off line, which allowed
Miller to score.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who has punished the Dodgers in the early part of the
season, continued his torrid stretch against L.A. pitching. This
time he smashed Valdes' full-count offering into the left-field
stands to give Arizona a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bell's fourth homer of the season, and third against the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes was promptly pulled by Johnson as a solid outing turned
sour. He was chased after 52/3 innings, giving up four runs on nine
hits, walking three and striking out three.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scraped for a run in the eighth off reliever Brian
Anderson when Young, who doubled, scored on Sheffield's two-out
single to center as L.A. crept with 4-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
