<HEADER>
A7486 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-SCHOLARSHIPS15     04-14 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-SCHOLARSHIPS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High-schoolers set their sights on scholarships via the Web
 &HT;    By Jennifer Peltz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ Frank Raucci made his first stab at
designing a World Wide Web page a few months ago. Now he hopes a
Web page will help pay his way through college.
</P>
<P>
   Raucci and his teammate, fellow Suncoast High School senior
Allison Cammerata, are competing for a $25,000 scholarship by
creating a Web site about medieval Europe.
</P>
<P>
   At Palm Beach Gardens High School, senior Justin Slone is also
trying to turn his on-line skills into a scholarship. He and
classmate Gilbert Morejohn are teaming up for an on-line research
contest, with a full scholarship to Florida State University as the
prize.
</P>
<P>
   Just four years after the World Wide Web became widely popular,
Web skills have made their way into the academic mainstream _ so
much so that scholarships are emerging nationwide to reward and
court students who have on-line expertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like any other talent, whether it be music or art or
science or athletics,'' said Timothy McDonough, a spokesman for the
American Council on Education, an organization of 1,800 colleges
and universities. ``Institutions are trying to find a mix of
students . . . (and the Web) is very much a part of the learning
environment now.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State made that point last year, when it started
offering an on-line research scholarship ``to show that FSU is
connected to learning, to offering students the best in information
services,'' said spokeswoman Fran Conaway.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors search Lexis-Nexis, a giant on-line database of
articles from newspapers and other sources, to answer complex
multiple-choice questions quickly, Conaway said. Thursday is the
deadline to register for this year's contest; the details are
available through the flashing ``Online Scholars Challenge'' icon
(www.fsu.edu).
</P>
<P>
   The contest doesn't sound like too tough a challenge to Slone,
who uses the World Wide Web ``as my main source of research.''
</P>
<P>
   While Slone has worked with computers for years, Raucci is
taking his first computer programming class. But Web design has
come easily enough that Raucci is taking a shot at the worldwide
ThinkQuest Internet Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ThinkQuest, sponsored by Advanced Network &AMP; Services, a New York
company that helped build the Internet, asks students to design
educational Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Company President Allan Weis started the contest in 1996 because
he'd found ``nothing that took advantage of all of the power that
the Internet could have'' to teach 11- to 19-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ThinkQuest has drawn thousands of entries on subjects from sound
to Shakespeare to the programming language C++, Weis said. This
year's registration deadline has passed, but more information is
available on line (www.thinkquest.org).
</P>
<P>
   ArsDigita, a Boston company, is ready to give $10,000, not for
Web sites but Web services. The company's new contest for students
18 and younger calls for on-line creations that serve a purpose,
such as automatically reminding people to move their cars for
street cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get the bar raised in terms of creating useful
and tasteful on-line services,'' ArsDigita programmer Rolf Hanson
explained. The application deadline is May 1 (information is
available at arsdigita.org).
</P>
<P>
   While only a handful of scholarships recognize on-line skills,
some have already specialized by interest and area.
</P>
<P>
   Accounting.net, an on-line information service for accountants,
reserves scholarship money for accounting students who write an
essay explaining how the Internet has changed the profession. A
Chicago Tribune scholarship contest requires Chicago-area students
to create Web sites for nonprofit organizations. In Atlanta, the
Technology Association of Georgia runs a scholarship contest for
Web sites by and about Georgia high school students.
</P>
<P>
   But these new-media scholarships are old news to the makers of
Vivarin, an over-the-counter caffeine pill.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers started giving $10,000 scholarships for
interesting Web pages on any subject in 1995, when the Web was just
becoming popular outside computer-science circles. The awards
stopped in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet hit so fast that what was new and unique one year
became just so terribly old-hat the next year,'' scholarship
spokesman Chris Clark explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, college students are starting Internet companies
with (initial) valuations in the billions of dollars, so we feel a
little silly saying, `Show us your cool home page,' '' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Peltz writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
