<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7487 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRANDED-SKATERS15-CO     04-14 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRANDED-SKATERS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Police urge manager to leave children
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Nearly every Friday after the rink's 11:30 p.m.
closing time, Skateworld general manager Rick Corson takes on a job
he doesn't want _ late-night babysitter.
</P>
<P>
   Corson finds himself stuck with one or two kids, some as young
as 8 years old, whose parents have dropped them off and, for
whatever reason, failed to pick them up. Often, well beyond
midnight, the children can't reach their parents by phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a terrible spot here,'' Corson said. ``Could someone
please direct me what to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Police used to retrieve the stranded kids and try to contact
their parents, but now they say they will no longer perform
babysitting duties. And Montgomery County Children Services said it
had no legal authority to take the children into custody.
</P>
<P>
   Kettering police have told Corson the children are no longer his
legal responsibility after the rink's posted hours have ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me I should turn out the lights, lock up and go
home,'' he said. ``But what about my moral obligation? It's a
different world out there these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Corson said he can't leave the kids on his doorstep for fear of
what happened to Erica Baker, the 9-year-old Kettering girl who
disappeared more than two months ago while walking her dog one
rainy afternoon near the Kettering Recreation Complex.
</P>
<P>
   And Corson said he can't drive the kids home for fear he'll be
held liable if there's a car accident or find himself accused of
child molesting.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, he ends up babysitting the kids in his lobby until
their parents can be reached _ sometimes as late as 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm lucky I haven't had to spend the night here,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, when a 13-year-old Beavercreek, Ohio girl couldn't
reach her parents after 1 a.m., she insisted on walking home.
Corson said no, and had his security guard drive her and a
13-year-old girlfriend to Kettering police headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The security guard and the girls waited 40 minutes for an
officer to come out to the lobby and speak to them. When he did,
Corson said, ``the officer told (the security guard), 'Don't bring
them here any more. They're not our responsibility'.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, just before 2 a.m., the guard reached the father of one
of the girls, who called the girl's mother to come and pick them
up, Corson said
</P>
<P>
   The problem became more prominent beginning last fall, when
Corson said he started drawing record crowds. The increased
business _ particularly on Friday nights _ had more kids staying
after the rink's closing time.
</P>
<P>
   It's never the same kids who are stranded, Corson said, or he
would bar the offenders from his rink and possibly report their
parents to Children Services.
</P>
<P>
   Corson said he doesn't have the same babysitting problem at
Skateworld's nearby Vandalia location. ``Parents up there don't
leave them and forget them like they do (at the Kettering
location),'' he said. ``I don't know why that is.''
</P>
<P>
   Skateworld in Kettering draws as many as 550 children on Friday
nights from Kettering and surrounding areas. The Vandalia location
draws a slightly smaller crowd _ about 400 children on Friday
nights. The average age of the skaters at both locations is between
10 and 12 years of age, Corson said.
</P>
<P>
   The few times when he has had a stranded child at the Vandalia
location, Corson said, the Vandalia police have never refused to
pick up the child.
</P>
<P>
   Vandalia Police Chief Doug Knight said his department's policy
is ``first, to make sure the child is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, Knight said, Vandalia police attempt to contact the
parents to come get their child. If the parents can't be reached,
he said, the police call the Montgomery County Family Court Center
to arrange for the child's care.
</P>
<P>
   Kettering police spokesman Officer Larry Warren said Kettering
doesn't have the manpower to pick up stranded kids. ``To tell you
the truth, I find it hard to believe that Vandalia would go,'' he
said. ``If nothing of a criminal nature is going on, there's no use
in our going out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor do Kettering police want Corson to drop off the kids at
their headquarters. ``We don't want to be used as a babysitting
facility,'' Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Erica Baker's disappearance might create a sense
of urgency for children stranded at night, Warren said, ``the sense
of urgency should be from the parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim DeBrosse writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
