<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plan works incrementally, scholar says
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As a former infantryman, James MacGregor Burns is
skeptical about the effectiveness of the air war in Yugoslavia. As
a scholar who had devoted his career to the subject of presidential
leadership, he's not surprised Bill Clinton has championed that
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't hear much about the perils of moderation,'' said
Burns, referring to his forthcoming book with Georgia Sorenson:
``Dead Center: Clinton-Gore Leadership and the Perils of
Moderation.''
</P>
<P>
   In his view, however, the centrist, incremental approach that
marks Clinton's strategy in the evolving conflict in Yugoslavia is
at the core of his most serious shortcomings as a president.
</P>
<P>
   Burns, who lectured at Morehouse College on Monday, has come to
some rather unconventional conclusions about this president as he
faces his most serious international crisis.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton's highest marks have generally been for his
domestic accomplishments, Burns believe the moderate approach
hatched within the Democratic Leadership Council and carried out in
this administration has failed to address the nation's most serious
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic peril is that it just doesn't achieve major changes.
It achieves incremental changes _ most in my view good little
policies, but not policies that deal with the fundamentals of the
problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Burns believes Clinton has been unfairly
judged with respect to his handling of foreign policy. While they
have not led to the kind of changes the 79-year-old historian would
like to see in this country, Clinton's skills as a conciliator and
mediator have been ``very effective on the world scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has devoted enormous energy to international affairs,
Burns noted, and often shown a greater willingness to take a
principled approach abroad than at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been more steadfast in what's going on now than in some
of his domestic policies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether steadfastness is rewarded with success in the Balkans
remains to be seen. Burns thinks the president blundered by
commiting himself so strongly to a limited bombing strategy, but he
believes Clinton will get out of that box the same way he got into
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may just sort of incrementalize us into ground forces,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Burns lectured Monday on the subject of ``public values vs.
private virtues,'' for which this president provides a rich field
of study.
</P>
<P>
   The two levels of morality can come into conflict, as they did
last year. Fundamental to the great unifying American value of
liberty, Burns argues, is the right to privacy, which is at greater
risk for presidents than most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It's for that reason, and not the way the president conducted
himself, that Burns remains a staunch critic of the impeachment.
Clinton ``could have taken a moral stand'' and refused to testify
before the Kenneth Starr grand jury, thus precipitating a
constitutional showdown over the privacy question.
</P>
<P>
   To do that would have been true to the style of
``transformational leadership'' espoused by Burns, who,
incidentally, declares himself an ``unabashed admirer'' of Hillary
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
