<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Things to do in Texas before you die
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ There are three things a man ought to see before
he croaks:
</P>
<P>
   The State Fair, the Terlingua Chili Cookoff and the tryouts of
the Dallas Cowboys Cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, I finally got a chance to attend the tryouts for
the legendary hot pants dance ensemble, held in the Stadium Club at
Texas Stadium. I am here to report that this spectacular event
beats a bowl of red and Big Tex.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my guy friends were groveling at my feet, begging me to
take them along to these tryouts. For those unfortunates who had to
stay behind, let me report the experience was like going to a
topless bar, with tops and no drinks.
</P>
<P>
   But there were a lot more dancers than you'd find at, say, The
Crazy Lady.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 mostly well-conditioned young ``audition candidates''
in sleeveless leotards and flesh-colored tights took turns, five at
a time, ``free-dancing'' on a disco floor.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one wave of bouncing fun after the other. They
bumped, swiveled, leaped, kicked, spun. They smiled as if their
lips were wired agape to songs with titles such as ``We Like to
Party,'' ``Get Ready to Bounce,'' and ``Where's the Party At.''
</P>
<P>
   A major difference between these tryouts and a topless bar? I
didn't run into anyone named Bambi, Destiny or Desiree who had more
tattoos than teeth. All of the candidates I spoke with said they
have jobs or are in college, majoring in everything from sociology
to higher education.
</P>
<P>
   To be eligible for the tryouts, you have to be 18, have a high
school diploma or a GED and have a job or be a student.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm learning to fly airplanes, so I figured why not the Dallas
Cowboys?'' said Francine Fivash, who is in the Naval Reserve. ``I
want to be a pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked what kind of airplanes she is learning to fly. ``The
ones with the little propellers on the side,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I wish Francine luck with her flight career. And when she gets a
job flying for an airline, I want to be the first to know which one
it is.
</P>
<P>
   You can't skate your way onto the Dallas Cowboys Cheerleader
squad without demonstrating some smarts. Those who were fortunate
enough to make it through Saturday's preliminaries had to take an
85-question written exam during the semifinals on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On the test, the audition candidates were asked about the
history of the Cowboys and the Cheerleaders, as well as football
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's football questions like, 'How many points do you get
for a touchdown?' `` said Rachel Durbin, administrative assistant
for the Dallas Cowboys Cheerleaders. ``We don't want them cheering
when they (the Cowboys) just fumbled the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   And, no, one of the current events questions did not begin,
``When the big hand is on the four . . . . `` They were more
difficult than that. ``Name one of the Supreme Court justices,''
Durbin said, telling me one of the questions.
</P>
<P>
   I thought it would have been, ``Name one of the Supremes.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's written test was a little different than last
year's. This year, contestants had to write out the words to The
Star Spangled Banner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year it was the National Anthem,'' Durbin explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I knew the words until I started to write them,
'cause I used to sing them at football games, `` said cheerleader
candidate and school teacher Jennifer Nobra, speaking of The Star
Spangled Banner.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not all stuffy and intellectual at the Cowboys
Cheerleaders tryouts. During the finals on May 2, finalists will
perform two-minute talent presentations.
</P>
<P>
   It makes you wonder how many versions of ``My Heart Will Go On''
the judges will have to sit through.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
