<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pregnancy changes even the best of us
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ My friend is pregnant for the first time, at 38,
and having a little trouble getting used to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   She is also, for some mysterious reason, feeling a tad
emotional. Her mother found that out when she suggested perhaps
they shouldn't take that planned trip to Italy this summer, after
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean, we can't go to Italy?'' she said, sobbing.
``That makes me feel terrible, like I'm never going to have my life
back after I have a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   She immediately got on the phone with me, as close friends do,
by contractual agreement, after tiffs with their mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because I'm pregnant doesn't mean this isn't my life
anymore!'' she said. ``Does it?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a complicated question, but I knew the answer she needed to
hear: ``Of course not. I still have my life, don't I? I still go
out all the time, and get together with my friends. Being a mother
doesn't mean you're no longer a person.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which is true, but not the whole truth. No need to tell
her, just yet, about the contortionist tricks you perform to keep a
semblance of the life you have known. No need to tell her it's
tough for us older first-time mothers, accustomed to doing what we
want to do when we want to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs the whole truth when she's pregnant, anyway? Plenty of
time for her to figure that out later.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the whole truth is all that bad, at that. For all the
parts of your life you give up, there are parts you reclaim: Story
hour. Halloween. Disney movies.
</P>
<P>
   And there are avenues you would never have explored, in your
wildest dreams. It's a safe bet that, without my son, Alec, I would
not have my current profound understanding of the moral,
sociological and metaphysical implications of The Simpsons. Nor
would I have found myself at a Dayton Bombers playoff game Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   I would not have seen my daughter make friends with Bucky the
Flying Squirrel, reaching out to hug him, kissing him on the cheek,
dancing with him, with a toddler's uncomplicated affection and
magical belief in anthropomorphism.
</P>
<P>
   I would not have been able to read 60 pages in my latest novel,
in spite of the PA system blasting Bad to the Bone and We Will Rock
You . An acquaintance walked by and picked up my book. ``You must
have extraordinary powers of concentration,'' he said. I nodded
absently, only thinking of the snappy comeback later.
</P>
<P>
   I should have said, ``Of course I do. I grew up in a family of
six kids.'' No, no, I should have said, ``I work in a newsroom,
after all.''
</P>
<P>
   No, no, this is what I should have said: ``Of course I do, I'm a
parent, and do you have any idea how much I'd pay for three hours'
reading time?''
</P>
<P>
   My pregnant friend heard her baby's heartbeat for the first time
only a few days after our going-to-Italy conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most amazing thing,'' she said. ``I had to turn my
head, so the doctor wouldn't see my tears.''
</P>
<P>
   The seashell rhythms of the heartbeat answered her question _
``Will it still be my life?'' _ far better than I ever could.
</P>
<P>
   It's your life, only more complicated, with not a second in the
day your child isn't lurking in your consciousness, not a plan you
can make without taking him into account.
</P>
<P>
   It's your life, only richer.
</P>
<P>
   It's your life _ and someone else's.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
