</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton's continued lack of character bad for U.S.
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ If President Clinton felt ``honored'' to be
impeached, he should feel absolutely ennobled to be found in
contempt for lying under oath and subverting the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing surprises me when it comes to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   I fully expect Clinton's public approval ratings to once again
jump skyward following U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright's
withering 32-page ruling that found Clinton had lied and misled the
court in his successful attempt to violate a plaintiff's right to
important information that could have supported her claim of sexual
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton recently told CBS news anchor Dan Rather that he felt no
shame for being only the second president in U.S. history to be
impeached. He felt ``honored'' to defend the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was revealed in 1992 that he avoided military service
by dodging the draft, I have not associated Clinton with the
concept of honor.
</P>
<P>
   The incontrovertible proof that Clinton was a draft dodger
didn't bother me as much as the fact that he was a dishonorable
draft dodger.
</P>
<P>
   Honor is the adherence to principles considered right despite
personal risks. Clinton didn't like the military. He opposed the
war in Vietnam. He didn't want to be drafted. But rather than
adhere to his principles, he gave false, misleading and evasive
information to avoid the draft. It worked.
</P>
<P>
   That was my big break with Clinton. David S. Broder, the
Washington Post's respected political columnist, has said that
early revelation of Clinton's lack of character should have been a
tip-off of problems to come.
</P>
<P>
   Other tip-offs during Clinton's first presidential campaign
included the Gennifer Flowers revelations. Clinton not only lied to
the American people about their affair, he was heard on tapes
telling Flowers how to get away with lying.
</P>
<P>
   Still eight months away from election day, Clinton and his spin
experts honed the art of changing the subject to deflect
allegations of misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   Women who made allegations against Clinton had their reputations
trashed. The people behind the allegations were accused of being
involved in a radical-right conspiracy to ruin an honorable man who
just wanted to help America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honor'' puts principle first. Clinton can be trusted to put
Clinton first.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder it became necessary to order all men and women in the
U.S. military to not make denigrating remarks about Clinton, who
now orders these men and women to risk their lives in foreign
military actions.
</P>
<P>
   The same day that Judge Wright held Clinton in contempt of court
for ``clear and convincing evidence'' that he gave ``false,
misleading and evasive answers that were designed to obstruct the
judicial process,'' other news reports told how there appears to be
no firm evidence that Osama bin Laden commanded the bombing of two
American embassies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered dramatic airstrikes in Sudan and Afghanistan to
punish bin Laden for ordering the bombing of the two embassies.
That order, and another directed at Saddam Hussein's forces in
Iraq, deflected attention from Clinton's rapidly escalating
Whitewater problems.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton not only lied under oath to Judge Wright, he also
disobeyed her order by discussing his testimony with his private
secretary, Betty Currie.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's contempt citation will be forwarded to the bar
association. Clinton should be disbarred for violating the canon
prohibiting ``dishonesty, fraud, deceit or misrepresentation.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, it wouldn't surprise me if Clinton felt
``honored'' by the disbarment and that his approval ratings go up
again.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
