<HEADER>
A7495 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROSERB-COLUMN15-COX     04-14 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSERB-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The pro-Serb view
 &HT;    By Danielle S. Sremac
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Clinton and Slobodan Milosevic have much more in common
than one might think. Both are conducting military activities that
are resulting in the injury and death of innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's attempt to disarm and disband the terrorist KLA has
resulted in Albanian civilian casualties. Clinton, in his attacks
against the sovereign nation of Yugoslavia is killing innocent
Serbian and Albanian civilians alike.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are strong-willed, are not known for backing down, and
are generally mistrusted by the people they lead. Both leaders'
military pursuits are resulting in a staggering number of refugees.
Fighting by Yugoslav forces against the KLA has sent people fleeing
from Kosovo, while NATO bombings have compelled an even greater
number to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The major difference between the two is that Milosevic is
seeking a political settlement for Kosovo, while Clinton wants to
continue bombing _ with no exit strategy in sight.
</P>
<P>
   From the start of the Kosovo crisis, Clinton decided the proper
role for the United States would be that of police, judge, jury and
executioner. He dispatched his officials to Rambouillet, France, to
force a NATO ``police plan`` on the Serbs that would eventually
lead to the loss of sovereignty over the Serbian homeland of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing full well that Serbs would not accept this, Clinton, in
terms reminiscent of 1939 Germany, gave an ultimatum that
essentially said: ``Give up your land, let us occupy it, or we will
bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   While couched in terms of ``preventing a humanitarian crisis''
or ``stopping ethnic cleansing`` or fighting genocide, this war is
really nothing more than naked aggression by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of World War II, development of more democratic
international institutions, such as the United Nations, have proven
to be a preferable and effective means of resolving disputes
between nations, instead of fighting wars. It is striking that
Clinton has chosen to ignore the very body that was created to
handle such international disputes.
</P>
<P>
   By spearheading the bombing of Yugoslavia, Clinton has
jeopardized the very existence of the U.N. and undermined the core
values of the American people.
</P>
<P>
   While the Serbian people are inundated by a constant barrage of
rationalizations for Clinton's war of aggression through CNN, BBC
and other Western media sources, Clinton has not, and will not
convince the Serbian people that his actions are justified. What
they see in the Western media is unconvincing, one-sided and so
simplistic that if not for the bombs falling, it would be laughed
off as extreme naivete, sound bite policy, or feel-good liberalism.
</P>
<P>
   Bombs are the ultimate message to the Serbian people: Give up
Kosovo, or we will destroy you. That is a painful and difficult
message to a people that view Kosovo as their Jerusalem. For
centuries, empires and despots have conquered this land, and
subjugated the Serbs to harsh tyrannical rule. The 20th century saw
a degree of independence, but life in the Balkans was never as free
as hoped for. Serbs looked forward to the end of the Cold War as a
time when the nation would grow and prosper.
</P>
<P>
   The harsh reality has been quite the opposite. War, seven years
of sanctions, and now attacks by a former World War II ally have
shaken their faith in the new world order. It looks and feels too
much like the old world order.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs will continue to resist as they have become accustomed to
doing over the last millennium. They too have the strong desire for
freedom and independence that Americans had over 200 years ago.
They do not want to fight America for that freedom, but have no
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, throughout this crisis, it has been the Russians
leading the way, by taking the moral high ground; seeking
negotiations, and speaking out against aggression. Russia is
holding up a mirror so that America can better see what it has
become.
</P>
<P>
   Renowned Russian writer Alexander Solzhenitsyn said of the
Kosovo conflict, ``Casting off the United Nations and its charter,
NATO is imposing on the whole world and the next century, an
ancient law ... whoever's strongest is right. In the eyes of
humanity, a wonderful European country is being destroyed, and
civilized governments are applauding.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be wise for Clinton to look into that mirror, and see
himself as others do.
</P>
<P>
   It is not too late for peace in Yugoslavia. It is not too late
to end the carnage and human suffering on all sides. And it is time
to re-examine what America stands for and what made this nation
great. It is a true statesman who is able to resist the urge to use
the tools of destruction in favor of negotiation. Let us see what
Clinton's legacy will be.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle S. Sremac is director of the Institute for Balkan
Affairs in Washington and author of ``War of Words: Washington
Tackles the Yugoslav Conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
