</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316, rickd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334, andya(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   PROSERB-COLUMN _ Bill Clinton and Slobodan Milosevic have much
more in common than one might think. Both are conducting military
activities that are resulting in the injury and death of innocent
civilians. (Sremac, Institute for Balkan Affairs) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ As a former infantryman, James
MacGregor Burns is skeptical about the effectiveness of the air war
in Yugoslavia. As a scholar who had devoted his career to the
subject of presidential leadership, he's not surprised Bill Clinton
has championed that strategy. ``You don't hear much about the
perils of moderation,'' said Burns, referring to his forthcoming
book with Georgia Sorenson: ``Dead Center: Clinton-Gore Leadership
and the Perils of Moderation.'' (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ If everything had
gone according to plan, I'd be writing to you from somewhere deep
in Dixie. Instead, here I am still stuck at home. Oh, but it was a
fine plan. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Tony Bennett left his
heart in San Francisco. I left my luggage in Orlando. And Atlanta.
And points in between. I've been on the road most of the past two
weeks, attending company meetings twice in Florida. Tough duty, I
know. It's hard to come back with a Florida tan and say with a
straight face what a long half-month it's been out of town. But God
is a practical joker, and getting there and back, then there and
back again, was no picnic. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel)
MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ My friend is pregnant for the
first time, at 38, and having a little trouble getting used to the
idea. She is also, for some mysterious reason, feeling a tad
emotional. Her mother found that out when she suggested perhaps
they shouldn't take that planned trip to Italy this summer, after
all. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ WACO, Texas _ If President
Clinton felt ``honored'' to be impeached, he should feel absolutely
ennobled to be found in contempt for lying under oath and
subverting the rule of law. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ IRVING, Texas _ There are three things a man
ought to see before he croaks: The State Fair, the Terlingua Chili
Cookoff and the tryouts of the Dallas Cowboys Cheerleaders. On
Saturday, I finally got a chance to attend the tryouts for the
legendary hot pants dance ensemble, held in the Stadium Club at
Texas Stadium. I am here to report that this spectacular event
beats a bowl of red and Big Tex. (Kelso, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ will not move today. (Jefferson, Palm Beach
Post)
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ In lots of cities like Waco, school districts
raised taxes. Locally, what I did with my tax cut was pay for
school construction. I have no regrets. I voted yes for Waco school
bonds. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald).
</P>
