<HEADER>
A7499 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-INTERNET15-COX     04-14 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-INTERNET15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net site's message: Don't panic
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Companies and universities are increasingly turning to
the Internet in their crusade to rout the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
   They are using the Web to post status reports and inform
employees about how to make their computers recognize the Year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple good examples in metro Atlanta of how
organizations are using the Web, one of which is Emory Unversity's
Rollins School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   This school, which specializes in disease prevention research,
is ahead of the pack. It began correcting its computer systems
about five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's taking the campaign to its administrators, faculty and
students through the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of our Web page is to get information out there,''
says William Morse, the school's director of information services.
``There were a lot of people panicking about Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to put a human face on the problem and take away the
fear,'' Morse said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the school's site states up front that it will be
Y2K-ready at the end of the year. ``Our message is: Don't panic,''
says Morse.
</P>
<P>
   While the school has fixed its networks and servers, there is
still a lot of work to be done. Next, Morse is focusing on the
desktop and portable computers at the school.
</P>
<P>
   In fixing these computers, Morse must first combat the fear of
the unknown. He does that through his school's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Morse has on the site a complete and easy-to-understand
explanation of the Y2K bug and its origin. It says, for example,
that programmers in the 1950s and 1960s conserved the limited
memory available at the time by programming ``dates without the
first two digits. They knew about 2000, but expected that the
software they wrote then would be long gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Rollins' site gives a blow-by-blow account of what the school is
doing to fix the Y2K bug. That includes what has been done so far
and what is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   Morse and his team are moving onto desktop and portable
computers. ``A lot of people don't realize how complicated the
issue with desktops can be,'' says Morse.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the school has gotten rid of every computer with a
80486 or older microprocessor. Most of these machines cannot be
upgraded to handle the Year 2000, in his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The desktop computers that remain, says the Web site, will be
given a thorough inspection, making sure all software is
Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will give you a complete report of what was found so that
if you have some problems with your data or programs, you will be
able to fix it well before January 1, 2000,'' says Morse on the
school's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins' site is at
www.sph.emory.edu/is/computing/y2k/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
