A7500 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN15-COX     04-14 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    That bonanza, or better teachers: You choose, Texas
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The last time Texas cut property taxes you took
the difference, bought a yacht, sailed the world and then started
your own business with the change left in your pocket. Didn't you?
</P>
<P>
   All right, well, what did you do with your tax cut?
</P>
<P>
   Didn't get one? But you did _ the biggest tax cut in Texas'
history. If I heard it said once during the campaign I heard it 300
times.
</P>
<P>
   Where did that $1 billion tax cut go? In lots of cities like
Waco, school districts raised taxes. Locally, what I did with my
tax cut was pay for school construction. I have no regrets. I voted
yes for Waco school bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature is talking about another, bigger tax cut, but
not as big as a campaigning George Bush was talking about. He
wanted $2 billion. A bill by Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo, backed
by Senate leadership would cut property taxes $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   I know, you can't wait to get your hands on your share of that.
How much? Well, use the handy calculation used on the Senate floor
by Sen. David Cain, D-Dallas. The Bivins tax cut amounts to about
$5 a month for the owner of a $60,000 home. Enough, pointed out
Cain, to buy a Big Mac, fries and a Coke.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a $40,000 house, deduct the fries. And that may
satisfy you.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, let's say we directed that money to teacher
salaries. We would be making a huge statement about the value of
teachers _ versus, say, the value of grilled beef patties.
</P>
<P>
   The Bivins bill also includes a pay increase for teachers. The
state would pick up 100 percent of teachers' contribution to the
Teacher Retirement System (TRS) instead of about half of it as it
does now. That equates roughly to a raise of $2,000 a year on
average, based on income.
</P>
<P>
   Just passing the Bivins bill would not make this so. Texas
voters would have to amend the Constitution, which caps the state's
TRS contribution.
</P>
<P>
   A raise of this nature is welcome, but still would leave Texas
roughly $4,000 below the national average for teacher pay.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sen. Cain wants to make a major leap,
compensation-wise. He wants to exchange Bivins' $2,000-and-a-Big
Mac compensation package for a $4,000-a-year average raise by
forgoing the tax cut. Cain's bill still wouldn't elevate Texas to
the nation's average. But what an elevation it would be.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually everyone agrees that we don't pay teachers enough.
Unfortunately, the teacher pay issue continually, conveniently gets
hung up on rhetorical dodges.
</P>
<P>
   One dodge is the concern that we have some bad teachers in the
bunch, and we shouldn't reward them. We should fire them.
</P>
<P>
   No argument, there. But no one seems to acknowledge that one
reason why we have some bad teachers, or conversely, why we don't
draw or retain more good ones, is that we offer so little _ an
average starting salary of $21,240.
</P>
<P>
   If a $4,000 raise means we're rewarding bad teachers, at least
we'd be inviting better ones to come compete for their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Never considered, on the subject of teacher pay, is the amount
to which teachers subsidize the state _ buying supplies, display
material, classroom furniture, name it. One focus group of teachers
estimated convincingly that they spend the equivalent of a week's
salary making their classrooms special places where learning takes
place.
</P>
<P>
   So those of you who complain about teachers having it easy _ you
know, long summer break and all _ don't know how easy you have it
as taxpayers because of teachers' professional devotion.
</P>
<P>
   With what teachers get in return, we can't be surprised at
alarming attrition rates, at the number of teachers hanging on
lawmakers' every word and of a mind to say, ``Take your Big Mac
and. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: jyoung(AT)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
