r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CHIVES15-COX     04-14 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHIVES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In praise of chives
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In the beginning, there were chives.
</P>
<P>
   Long before basil can be planted, before the bitter leaves of
thyme have given way to fresh new growth, even before the newly
sown lettuces come close to harvest, chives burst from the earth
and soar.
</P>
<P>
   For those who love eating from the garden, chives are a tonic,
and snipping them for an evening meal is the first ritual harvest.
</P>
<P>
   So much reward for so little work. Chives, and their cousin
garlic chives, are the ultimate perennial herb. You can't kill
them. In fact, you can barely keep garlic chives in check, for
their fall seed heads scatter plants across the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   But ordinary chives just keep growing, the clump a little bigger
each year, but still not multiplying too fast. Division may be
necessary every eight to 10 years. Well, you can do it after five,
but if you forget to count the plant is forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Chives are the place any wannabe herb gardener _ or cook _
should start. The herb is accessible to even a novice cook who so
far has nothing beyond dried parsley on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the plant nearly indestructible, the season when it
is fresh lasts longer than virtually any other, from the earliest
of spring to late fall. That's a good reason never to resort to
dried chives, which bear no resemblance to the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Chives add not only a mild onion flavor but a touch of
presentation. Minced leaves _ and those long, hollow stems are
indeed leaves _ add a shower of green. The mauve flowers _ or the
cluster of white, star-shaped blossoms on garlic chives _ can be
separated with a pinch of the fingers and scattered over salads,
soups and even pasta.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of snipped chives is the quintessential pairing with
new potatoes that are equally symbolic of spring. Some cooks never
get beyond this use, or limit chives to creamy dips and toppings
for baked potatoes. But there are other natural pairings: with eggs
in all manner of dishes from scrambled to deviled, with creamy,
mild cheeses, and grains such as rice, couscous and pasta.
</P>
<P>
   While this gentle herb is never the star of the show, chives add
to the performance when the main course is salmon, grilled, poached
and especially smoked.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best, and most overlooked, combinations pairs chives
with citrus such as lemon or orange in sauces for grilled meats,
poultry, seafood and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7506 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS15-TAKE     04-14 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS15-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the hundreds of opinion polls reported by all the news
media in the last few years of crises, I have never been polled. In
fact, I personally don't know anyone who has ever been contacted.
How can I have my opinion counted?
</P>
<P>
   A: You don't volunteer. The Gallup Organization says its polls
are conducted by telephone using the process of probability
sampling. A computer uses random digit dialing to create phone
numbers from a list of all telephone exchanges, which allows
unlisted numbers to be called as well as listed numbers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gallup, the typical sample size for a poll deemed
to represent an adequate cross-section of the U.S. population is
1,000 adults. Your chance of being among them presumably is the
same as anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I haven't seen any pictures of the pilot of the Stealth
fighter that was downed in Yugoslavia. What happened to him?
</P>
<P>
   A: The pilot of the F-117 fighter-bomber, brought down March 27
by as-yet unspecified causes, has not been identified by the
military. That's why you haven't seen a photo. As previously
reported, the pilot bailed out of his Nighthawk, parachuted to
earth, and was rescued within six hours by U.S. helicopter-borne
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the total length of the U.S. coastline, plus its
borders with Canada and Mexico? We're wondering how long a fence
would have to be to completely surround the contiguous states.
</P>
<P>
   A: Excluding Alaska and Hawaii, the coastline is 4,993 miles
long. The U.S.-Canadian border is 3,987 miles and the U.S.-Mexico
border is about 1,933 miles (1993 boundary agreement). That adds up
to 10,913 miles. Your hypothetical fence would have to be much
longer to follow shoreline, as opposed to coastline. But that's a
different issue, involving harbors, bays, even islands, so we won't
get into that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read that five pages were taken out of Anne Frank's
diary by her father before it was published. Were those pages ever
printed?
</P>
<P>
   A: An Amsterdam newspaper, Het Parool, published extracts of the
newly discovered pages last August, immediately running afoul of
the powerful Anne Frank Fund in Basel, Switzerland. In taking legal
action, the fund, which owns the copyright for the diary, argued
that the newspaper had violated its copyright by publishing the
material. But the newspaper said it had received permission from
Cor Suijk, international director of the Anne Frank Center, USA,
after he authorized the inclusion of the pages in the book ``Anne
Frank _ The Biography,'' by Melissa Muller. In November, a Dutch
court ruled in favor of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   It's expected that the missing diary entry _ written on Feb. 8,
1944, on five sides of three looseleaf pages _ will be published in
an updated version of ``The Diary of a Young Girl'' when the issue
of ownership has been resolved. It's hoped that this could happen
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The missing pages contain Anne Frank's observations of the
marriage of her parents, according to Suijk. Otto Frank, Anne's
father, ``got letters from many women, married and single, and he
didn't want people to think he was not such a wonderful husband,''
Suijk said. Otto Frank, who died in 1980, didn't want the missing
pages published in his lifetime. Suijk said another reason for the
father's keeping the pages out of the public eye was his fear that
as long as he or his second wife were alive, they could be
confronted with questions on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who were the two guys who ran onto the field to congratulate
Hank Aaron after he hit his 715th home run? Where are they now?
</P>
<P>
   A: On April 8, 1974, two 17-year-olds from Waycross ran onto the
field at Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium and into seemingly every
Hank Aaron highlight collection since. They were detained briefly
by Atlanta police after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Courtnay, now 42, has two children and works as an
optometrist in Valdosta. Britt Gaston, also 42, has two children of
his own and owns a graphic supply business in Isle of Palms, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Neither had plans to attend Thursday's anniversary celebration.
Courtnay, after a long day at the clinic, managed to catch a few
minutes of the game when he returned home. Gaston was busy coaching
his son's baseball team at the time. His wife, however, taped the
ceremony for him so he could watch it later.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where did the expression ``coin a phrase'' come from?
</P>
<P>
   A: To ``coin a phrase'' means to frame or invent a new phrase,
much like the minting of new currency. According to the Oxford
English Dictionary, the sentiment appeared as early as 1589. George
Puttenham, a contemporary of Shakespeare, talked in ``The Arte of
English Poesie'' of young scholars who would ``coigne fine wordes''
to impress their friends. In this context, the phrase was used
disdainfully, liking the action to the work of a counterfeiter.
</P>
<P>
   In modern usage, the Oxford dictionary's earliest citation of
the phrase, itself, being coined was an appearance in modern
British writer Francis Brett Young's ``Mr. Lucton's Freedom.'' ``It
takes all sorts to make a world,'' Young wrote in 1940, ``to coin a
phrase.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the payout to the retailer who sells a single winning
Big Game jackpot ticket? Is it a flat fee or a percentage?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Star Market, in Boston, where the winning Big Game ticket
was sold, earned a $50,000 bonus from the Massachusetts State
Lottery Commission. Had the winning ticket been sold in Georgia,
the retailer would have received $25,000. These incentive bonuses
remain fixed regardless of the jackpot size.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can you tell us about Jamie Shea, the spokesman who
handles the daily Kosovo press briefings for NATO? What is his
background?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to a NATO biographical sketch, Shea was born in
1953 and is of British nationality. Since 1980 he has been a member
of the NATO international staff where he served in a variety of
functions, including senior planning officer and speechwriter to
the secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
   Shea obtained a doctorate in modern history from Oxford
University, and has been an associate professor at Michigan State
University, where he taught courses on security policy and European
politics. Shea assumed his current role of NATO spokesman and
deputy director of the office of information and press on July 1,
1993.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on NATO policies, personnel or transcripts
of the daily press briefings, visit its Web site:
http://www.nato.int
</P>
<P>
   Q: How are the residents of Washington, D.C., represented in
Congress?
</P>
<P>
   A: The District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, Virgin Islands, Guam
and American Samoa each are represented by a delegate in the U.S.
House of Representatives. Elected by their constituents, delegates
may introduce legislation, make speeches and hold chairmanships if
their party is in the majority. Although they have voting rights in
committee, they cannot vote on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Del. Eleanor Holmes Norton, a Democrat, has represented the
District of Columbia residents since her election in 1990. Her
spokeswoman, Donna Brazile, was quick to point out that D.C.
residents are the only American citizens who pay federal taxes but
do not have full voting representation in Congress. To this end,
Norton has consistently raised the debate over the delegate vote.
In 1993, she won the right to limited votes on the full House
floor. This decision was reversed in 1995 after the Republican
Party regained control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Norton serves on the Government Reform and Oversight Committee,
where she is ranking Democrat on the District of Columbia
subcommittee, and the Transportation and Infrastructure Committee.
She also is co-chair of the Congressional Women's Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
