Western Illinois University, the remaining Illyrians fled to the
remote mountainous areas of Albania. They fortressed into small
feudal states, which enabled them to preserve their language and
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Though Albanian is spoken by relatively few people, it is
considered its own distinct branch of the Indo-European language
family. It is one of the few unique languages of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On Saturday mornings, TNT shows reruns of the ``Hondo''
series, starring Ralph Taeger. I've never seen him in any other
shows or films. What else has he starred in? And where is he today?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Hondo''was a spinoff of the 1953 John Wayne movie, adapted
from the best-selling Louis L'Amour novel of the same name. The
television series originally ran for 17 episodes in late 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Before ``Hondo,'' Taeger co-starred with James Coburn in another
short-lived adventure series, ``Klondike,'' later renamed
``Acapulco.''
</P>
<P>
   Taeger also made notable guest appearances in episodes of ``The
Twilight Zone'' and ``The Six Million Dollar Man.'' He appeared in
six films between 1960 and 1971, including ``The Carpetbaggers''in
1964, and his last one, ``The Delta Factor,'' in1971.
</P>
<P>
   Now 63, Taeger lives a relatively quiet life in Northern
California, reportedly running a firewood business and acting in
the local theater.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read a report about a Cold War Recognition Certificate
available to Cold War veterans. Could you tell me where to send the
application to receive this certificate?
</P>
<P>
   A: Any member of the armed forces or any federal civilian
employee who served honorably during the Cold War era (Sept. 2,
1945, to Dec. 26, 1991) is eligible to receive the Cold War
Recognition Certificate.
</P>
<P>
   Applications must consist of two parts: a request letter, plus
documentation verifying one's service. This documentation should be
a government form that includes name, Social Security number or
military serial number or Foreign Sservice number, and the dates of
service. Do not send original documents, as they will not be
returned.
</P>
<P>
   There are three ways to submit requests: mail to Cold War
Recognition, 4035 Ridge Top Road, Suite 400, Fairfax, VA 22030; or
fax to 703-275-6749; or e-mail to coldwar(at)fairfax-emh1.army.mil
</P>
<P>
   Additional information and assistance can be accessed on-line at
the program's Web site: http://coldwar.army.mil. Available help
there includes a detailed list of eligibility requirements, a
sample request letter, and an on-line request form. Another
informative link is the official web site of the Department of
Defense: http://www.defenselink.mil
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the difference between a hurricane and a tornado?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hurricanes and tornados are both cyclones, the word used by
scientists to refer to all spiral-shaped windstorms that circulate
in a counterclockwise direction in the Northern Hemisphere or in a
clockwise direction in the Southern Hemisphere. Otherwise, except
for both being highly destructive and potentially deadly storms,
hurricanes and tornadoes are quite dissimilar.
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane begins over a warm, tropical sea, with its winds
swirling around a calm central area, between 10 and 20 miles wide,
that's called the eye. The eye is encircled by storm clouds that
rise thousands of feet high. Large changes in atmospheric pressure
in the clouds create the hurricane's strong winds, which can reach
approximately 200 miles an hour although they usually are less
powerful.
</P>
<P>
   A large hurricane may extend over hundreds of square miles, and
when it hits land can cause billions of dollars in damage and
thousands of fatalities through fierce winds, torrential rain,
flooding and huge waves crashing ashore.
</P>
<P>
   A tornado, although far smaller in size than a hurricane, has
stronger, rapidly rotating winds that reach speeds as high as 300
mph. A tornado with such powerful winds can lift cattle, automobles
and mobile homes and destroy almost everything in its path.
Fortunately, most tornadoes are less severe.
</P>
<P>
   Tornadoes form underneath severe thunderclouds in which warm and
cold air masses are colliding. Most tornadoes, once they reach
ground, have damage paths less than 1,600 feet wide, move at about
35 mph, and last only a few minutes. Extremely destructive
tornadoes, however, may reach 1 mile in diameter, travel at 60 mph,
and last for an hour or more. Tornadoes that form over water are
called watersprouts.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do members of the U.S. Senate and House of Representatives
pay federal income taxes? If so, at what rate?
</P>
<P>
   A: U.S. senators and representatives enjoy numerous privileges
that go with their office, but not having to pay federal income
taxes is not one of them. They, too, have to contend with the
Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   IRS Publication 17 states, ``You must file a federal income tax
return if you are a citizen or resident of the United States or a
resident of Puerto Rico and you meet the filing requirements for
any of the categories that apply to you.'' U.S. senators and
representatives are, of course, U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The main filing requirements that determine your tax-paying
category are age, income and filing status (single, married, head
of household). These requirements determine the tax rates paid by
all taxpayers, including members of Congress. The rates range from
a low of 15 percent for low-income workers to a high of 39.6
percent for wealthier persons.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard that Hillary Clinton offered $50 million to some
foreign country to improve its water supply. Where does she get the
authority to pledge this money?
</P>
<P>
   A: She didn't actually pledge the money; she just made the
announcement _ a timely one during her recent trip to North Africa
_ of a grant already in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   While visiting a family planning clinic in Luxor, Egypt, she
said the U.S. Agency for International Development will provide $45
million to upgrade the Luxor wastewater treatment system. Over the
past 20 years, AID, which administers the U.S. foreign aid program,
has provided $2.7 billion for water treatment in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   While in Egypt, the first lady also announced AID funding of $20
million for family planning activities and $14.5 million for
mother-child health programs there.
</P>
<P>
   Publicizing federal grants is a common political activity.
Members of Congress are quick to make the announcement when federal
funds are released for projects in their home districts.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it feasible to prepay one's funeral expenses?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is largely a question of personal choice. It is possible
to prepay funeral expenses in full, or you can buy certain items in
advance that will be needed, such as headstones. Prepaying may
bring a certain peace of mind to you, but be sure you know what you
are buying. And remember that you might move to another part of the
nation before your death.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you prepay or not, preplanning your funeral usually is
wise thing to do. Discuss your wishes with your family to ensure
your final rites will be conducted as you want. Also, preplanning
helps your survivors avoid making quick decisions and costly
mistakes by paying for a far more expensive funeral than you would
have chosen.
</P>
<P>
   END TWO TAKES
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
