<HEADER>
A7515 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-TRAINERS15-     04-14 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-TRAINERS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shaping up for the draft
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With NFL scouts eager for him to shed the 20 extra
pounds he carried to this year's combine workouts, Heisman Trophy
winner Ricky Williams undertook a formidable training regimen.
</P>
<P>
   Under the watchful eye of a personal trainer, the Texas tailback
worked the weights, hit the sauna and ran wind sprints. He also
pushed a Mercedes Benz through the streets of New Orleans and
logged several miles a day on a treadmill submerged in a swimming
pool.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he auditioned for scouts last week, Williams checked
in at 224 pounds _ 20 pounds less than he did in February. Williams
probably made himself a few million dollars on his first NFL
contract just by getting his weight under control, even though his
40-yard times were average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoa, I might owe my man a bonus,'' Williams said as he
stepped off a scale at the University of California-San Diego. His
man is Tom Shaw, former Florida State sprint coach. Shaw and Chip
Smith of the Atlanta Athletic Club are two of the gurus in the
nation's hottest NFL-related business.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for the annual combine workouts used to be a personal
endeavor, with college prospects laboring in solitude attempting to
shave one-tenth of a second from their 40-yard times. In the past
eight years, however, that preparation has become a burgeoning
cottage industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important part of the whole process now,'' agent Gary
Wichard said. ``A player wants to know how you're going to help him
(be selected) higher.''
</P>
<P>
   When Shaw began his business 10 years ago, he was one of only
three trainers nationally who specialized in preparing players for
the NFL. Shaw does not advertise but still had 70 clients this year
in a program with a two-week minimum stay. ``Once you gain
credibility, they find you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's group of 40 this year was his largest. He added several
members to a staff that includes strength coaches Robbie Stewart
and Dave Allen, formerly of Georgia and Georgia Tech, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   IMG, the sports and entertainment giant, also operates a
facility, the $18 million International Performance Institute, in
Bradenton, Fla. It is strongly recommended that all clients signed
by IMG football agents Tom Condon and Ken Kremer train there under
Mark Verstagen. The facility includes on-site condominiums, large
dining areas and dietary consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time a player's season ends, up to the draft, he can
get appreciably better in all the measurable areas,'' Condon said.
``While other agents are wondering where their players are off to,
we know.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, perhaps not as qualified, are getting into the business.
In Houston, for example, a trainer who did not return several
telephone calls, advertises ``guaranteed results'' for NFL draft
prospects. In Southern California, several gymnasiums represent
themselves as ``NFL training approved'' facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has gotten tremendously competitive, and that means you
get the good and some bad,'' said Smith, whose clientele this
spring included cornerback Champ Bailey and offensive tackle Matt
Stinchcomb of Georgia. ``But we don't promote; it's strictly about
word of mouth with us. If we do our jobs, the proof is out there
for everyone to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's program of at least four weeks has attracted prospects
from all over the country. Among this year's participants were
tailback Mike Cloud and guard Doug Brzezinski of Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   One of his favorite players this year was defensive end Nate
Stimson of Georgia Tech. Too small to play his college position in
the pros, Stimson projects to linebacker. By clocking a blazing 40
time in the low 4.4s at 260 pounds, Stimson has gone from an
undrafted free agent to possible middle-round selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as proud of a guy like Nate as any first-rounder we
have,'' Smith said. ``Last year, I got three phone calls from
parents who said their sons would not have been drafted without us.
That's gratifying. It's not about my resume _ it's about the
players. What we do is take their skills and refine them.''
</P>
<P>
   The players work six days a week, about three hours a day. Smith
brought many of his techniques from a 1986 stint at the Soviet
Sports Institute. Some trainers concentrate on speed; Smith prefers
to stress movements more pertinent to football that still reduce a
player's 40 time and increase the repetitions of his bench press.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like his philosophy, in that Chip treats every kid the same
and doesn't play favorites with the agents,'' said agent Pat Dye
Jr., who placed six players with Smith this year. ``It's not some
campout for the players, and it isn't supposed to be. It's all
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The top trainers will not disclose prices, but agents indicate
that the fees can range from $500 to $1,200 weekly per player. Most
of the agents viewed it as a good investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 goal in this business is helping your clients get as
much money as they can,'' Shaw said. ``The faster a guy runs, the
bigger that signing bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
