   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   GWTW-SEQUEL _ Now that Pat Conroy has rejected an offer to write
a sequel to Gone with the Wind, St. Martin's Press is scrambling to
find another author of his calibre to resume the lives of Scarlett
and Rhett. We give them a little tongue-in-cheek help by talking to
Southern writers from Anne Rivers SIddons to Kaye Gibbons about how
they would approach such a sequel. Siddons would kill off Scarlett
in her prime; Gibbons would enroll her in a writing school founded
by the love child of Rhett and Prissy. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). (EDS: With illustration.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN-SOUP _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Peter Vegso was sitting
in an airport when his life changed. It was just another manuscript
submitted to his publishing company, but this one provoked an
unusual response _ it made Vegso cry. Vegso did not know that
Chicken Soup for the Soul by Jack Canfield and Mark Victor Hansen
had been turned down by 33 publishers, i.e. everybody in New York.
He did not know that his Health Communications, Inc. of Deerfield
Beach was the the 34th firm to peruse the manuscript, nor would he
have cared. The book worked for him, therefore he would publish it.
(Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-HISPANOLA _ DAYTONA, Fla. _ Americans may not know very
much about Hispaniola, but they're starting to, says Michele
Wucker, author of a new book about the island, ``Why the Cocks
Fight: Dominicans, Haitians and the Struggle for Hispaniola'' (Hill
&AMP; Wang, $27.50, 281 pages). (Shashoua, Daytona Beach News-Journal)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SALMA-HAYEK _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Salma Hayek, the
bewitching Mexican bombshell who has boys doing backflips, was in
town recently for the Palm Beach International Film Festival. She
came for a screening of her new flick The Velocity of Gary, but is
best known for steaming, er, starring with Antonio Banderas in
1995's Desperado. She's also a Revlon model. And also a tad somber.
Today, anyway. (Grantham, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-APTPUPIL _ ``Apt Pupil.'' Bryan Singer's follow-up to
``The Usual Suspects'' is the morally creepy tale of a fresh-faced
teenage boy (Brad Renfro) who wants to grow up to be a Nazi. Grade:
B-. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
