<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON SUES 21 OVER NET CHAT POSTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ROSS KERBER   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a controversial case that has attracted national attention,
Raytheon Co. has sued 21 anonymous authors for allegedly revealing
company secrets on an Internet chat board and causing ``harm to its
business reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a matter involving at least two of the chatters the
Lexington, Mass. defense contractor had already reported in public
filings to the Securities and Exchange Commission some of the
information that it now alleges was improperly revealed on the Web,
a Boston Globe review shows.
</P>
<P>
   The material concerns problems at a Raytheon project to make
electronic devices in South Korea. Raytheon recorded a $54 million
charge after taxes last year because of losses on the project,
according to a company filing dated Aug. 12. Two people _ using the
screen names ``Winstoncar'' and ``bobchand'' _ made references to
the Korean project on a Yahoo message board a month later. Raytheon
now alleges their posts constituted ``disclosure of inside
financial issues.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Raytheon's suit, filed in February, Winstoncar
has been dismissed, a person familiar with the matter now says.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Winstoncar nor bobchand could be reached to comment
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon won't discuss why it considers the Korean matter
proprietary given its earlier SEC filing. Postings by the other 19
anonymous writers named in the suit covered other matters, ranging
from details of union contract talks to general gripes about
Raytheon management.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say that in light of Raytheon's filings, its chief
aim in pursuing the suit is to silence debate rather than to
protect company secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no grounds to say it's private, so they're just
going after people who repeat it,'' said James George, a private
investigator who has set up an Internet site devoted to the case.
</P>
<P>
   After its lawsuit caused a stir, Raytheon issued a policy
stating that employees can talk about public matters on the
Internet, but should keep quiet about proprietary information. Now,
``it makes you wonder what Raytheon means'' with its new policy,
said William Arabolos, chief executive of Akom Technologies Inc. of
Bethel, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Akom, a former supplier to Raytheon has sued the company over
the Korean project, and Arabolos says the details from the SEC
filing and the Yahoo chat relate to the same matter.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon filed suit in Middlesex (Mass.) Superior Court against
21 people it describes as ``John Does,'' who the company charges
posted improper information on the World Wide Web. Raytheon seeks
damages of more than $25,000 from the group, which it believes
includes current and former employees who signed agreements
pledging not to reveal proprietary information. Raytheon also wants
the group banned from further improper chat.
</P>
<P>
   Because the messages weren't posted under users' real names,
Raytheon obtained court motions against Yahoo to gain information
about what the California Internet portal service knew about their
identities. Based on that information, Raytheon in March obtained
similar motions against America Online, Microsoft Corp. and other
service providers in the hopes of tracing the identities of the
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't clear what the Internet service providers have told
Raytheon so far, and critics have seized on the case to argue
Internet users deserve more protection of their identity in civil
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Now the latest details about Raytheon's own previous disclosures
would seem to weaken its case against the John Does, said John
Reinstein, legal director of the ACLU of Massachusetts. ``Certainly
it's not likely they'll get an injunction against discussion of
material that's already in the public domain,'' he said. ``Nor is
it clear there's any basis for damages.''
</P>
<P>
   Attention to the suit comes at a sensitive time for Raytheon,
whose new chief executive, Daniel Burnham, has pledged to
decentralize decision making at the company. Yet Raytheon's pending
suit is also one of the most aggressive to date by a company
seeking to crack down on talk about it on line.
</P>
<P>
   The company has declined to discuss actions taken against
employees, citing their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The issues stemming from the Korean contract seem to be among
the most sensitive in the lawsuit. In all, the company objected to
29 e-mails that allegedly violated its rules against disclosing
proprietary information.
</P>
<P>
   In a message on the Yahoo chat board dated Sept. 4 Winstoncar
typed: ``I heard there was a bit of a scandal in Advanced Device
Center in Andover. Someone wasn't watching the `store' . . .
closely regarding $100 million in Korean contracts. Knowing their
economy wasn't that great, they decided to look into the books,
shortly after that the comptroller was walked out the door (fired),
and the head of ADC, I won't mention names, was demoted.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven days later, bobchand referred on the message board to
``the loss of 100 million on the Korea deal'' as part of a general
posting about the company's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Both Winstoncar and bobchand said in later postings on the chat
board that they didn't believe they were revealing inside
information.
</P>
<P>
   In a routine quarterly filing to the SEC dated Aug. 12, 1998,
Raytheon said it recorded a special charge of $54 million after
taxes. ``The special charge consisted of $27 million to writedown
to estimated realizable value certain assets the company has
decided to sell and $27 million as the current estimated asset
impairment for commercial electronics manufacturing operations
located in Korea,'' the document states.
</P>
<P>
   Arabolos said the work related to plans to manufacture office
networking products in Korea by a joint venture called RayCom.
Partners were Raytheon and a Seoul-based company.
</P>
<P>
   Akom was formed in 1996 to act as a purchasing arm of the joint
venture, according to Akom's suit against Raytheon and others,
filed in US District Court in Connecticut in February. Akom later
placed $22 million worth of orders on Raytheon's behalf, according
to the suit. However, Raytheon and the joint failed to pay for the
parts, Akom charges.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-08-99 2116EDT &QL;
</P>
