<HEADER>
A7587 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-TECH-CENTERPIECE-     04-14 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-CENTERPIECE-POKEMON13-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Pokemon portable video game popping up everywhere 
By Jennifer Hill  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Move over, Beanie Babies. Pokemon have seized the day.
And like those cuddly, stuffed, fabled toys of yesterday's trend,
there's seemingly a million of 'em.
</P>
<P>
   If you've heard your children talking about Squirtles and
Charizards, your household has been hit by the Pokemon bug. Since
hitting the U.S. market in September 1998, Nintendo has sold 1.5
million units, making it the fastest-selling Gameboy game ever.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Gameboy's portability, the game is played everywhere
from morning school carpools to playgrounds or any other place a
spare moment opens up. Where only a few months ago clusters of boys
put wildly colored plastic yo-yos through their paces, now many of
those same boys are huddled playing Pokemon.
</P>
<P>
   In the peculiar culture of video games, proximity can serve as
interaction. That is to say, two, three or four boys can all be
playing individual Gameboys but be communing with one another. But
with Pokemon, you advance your game by linking with another
player's Gameboy to trade Pokemon. Plus, you can also use the game
link cable to battle other players. (Of course, to do this you need
a game link cable, which costs about $10.)
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the parental purse, Nintendo makes two
versions of the game _ Red and Blue. Each game, which sells for
about $29, has a slightly different subset of the 150 different
Pokemon. So to collect all 150, you have to trade by linking up
with another player who has the other version of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The object of the game is to find, train, collect and use the
Pokemon in battle with other Pokemon trainers. When your Pokemon
defeats another in battle, you capture it and add it to your
collection.
</P>
<P>
   When you train your Pokemon, they evolve from lovable little
critters to larger and mostly still lovable creatures with a
variety of powers. For example, Squirtle evolves into Wartortle and
ultimately Blastoise. (Certainly makes your wonder if the author of
the American version names grew up in the Bronx, doesn't it?)
Depending on how they are trained, two Pokemon of the same type
could end up having different abilities in their full-grown state.
</P>
<P>
   The Pokemon onslaught shows no sign of slowing down. Episodes of
a cartoon show feature two-dimensional characters that only game
fanatics would know and love. According to Nintendo, the Pokemon
animated cartoon series is the top syndicated kids show in all
major U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   And as if 150 Pokemon weren't enough, there are more video
versions to come featuring new critters. Nintendo plans to release
``Pokemon Pinball'' for Gameboy and ``Pokemon Snap'' for N64 in
late June. Japanese versions are already available.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon trading cards, which appeared a few months ago, are
being snapped up with the same frenzy as Magic cards were in their
heyday. More than 50 million have been sold since December.
Currently, a yellow Volkswagen Beetle made up to like Pikachu, a
round yellow Pokemon that looks like a vertically challenged
relative of the Pillsbury Doughboy with tail, is making its way
across the country attending Pokemon trading card events.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro, the toymaker, has weighed in with collectible toys
featuring the Pokemon characters.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Internet is a part of the Pokemon craze.
In addition to official Nintendo sites www.pokemon.com/ and
www.nintendo.com/gb/pokemon/index.html, there are scores of sites
maintained by game devotees. One such site, Pikachu Centre at
www.nintendo.com/gb/pokemon/index.html, has a wealth of information
about the current as well upcoming and Japanese versions of the
games.
</P>
<P>
   Having a hard time capturing the Tauros Pokemon? Many of these
sites features tips sent in by other gamers on everything from
training Pokemon faster to help finding the rarest Pokemon.
</P>
<P>
   The expected June release of the new games will likely breath
new life into the game's popularity, ensuring its fans will take
the game's slogan to heart _ ``Got to catch 'em all.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
