 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Apple's OS 8.6 called `incredibly stable' 
By Charles Haddad  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Apple Computer is readying the latest version of its
operating system. Called 8.6, this version of the Mac's OS is
expected to be released _ probably for free _ later this month or
in early May.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing earth-shaking in 8.6, but this version
represents a steady improvement. Indeed, the release alone shows
Apple Computer's newfound stability. The company has systematically
released OS upgrades every six months for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer is not saying anything official yet about OS 8.6,
but the Internet is filled with news about it. Here are some of the
more important improvements, gleaned from credible sources such as
MacWeek and MacOS World.
</P>
<P>
   OS 8.6's new features include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Better multitasking. Multitasking is the ability to perform
several functions at once, such as emptying the trash and copying
files. The Mac already can handle some multitasking, but Apple
Computer will now let users launch applications while their Macs
empty the trash with 8.6.
</P>
<P>
   _ Better system stability. The current system, 8.5, has plagued
some users with random and inexplicable crashes. The bugs that
caused these crashes have been fixed. Beta testers have reported
that 8.6 is ``incredibly stable.''
</P>
<P>
   _ New Sherlock interface. Sherlock is Apple Computer's new
search technology, which scans not only within files but also
across the Internet. In OS 8.6, Sherlock's window listing plug-ins
is now resizable.
</P>
<P>
   _ New Start-Up Control Panel. Apple Computer has rewritten this
mini-program so that it easily lets you connect to a server and a
network.
</P>
<P>
   _ Improved internal codes. Apple Computer has updated many of
its internal parts with 8.6. Among the things improved are video
drivers, laserwriter software, DVD software, Open Transport,
AppleScript and FireWire video drivers.
</P>
<P>
   While no particular item is big, all these small improvements
will add up to a lot in 8.6.
</P>
<P>
   And 8.6 is a big step forward to Apple Computer's next major
release, called OS X. OS X is Apple's answer to Microsoft's
powerful Windows NT software.
</P>
<P>
   The company says OS X will run preemptive multitasking. It will
also offer protected memory, advanced virtual memory and
multithreading.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago no one would have believed Apple could pull off OS
X. After all, it had failed to pull off two previous major system
upgrades. But there's great confidence in Apple, given its return
to profitability and success in rolling out system maintenance
upgrades such as 8.6.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-12-99 1109EDT &QL;
</P>
