<SLUG> BC-CPT-FAN-WEBSITES-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTENTIAL PROFITS SEEN IN FAN-ORIENTED WEB SITES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wait a second. Wasn't entertainment supposed to be a flop on the
Internet?
</P>
<P>
   A lot of companies had high hopes that were dashed with such
entertainment concepts as online soap operas.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking that money may be the answer, Microsoft spent
television-style budgets to develop a series of elaborate online
``shows'' like ``Mungo Park,'' about adventure travel.
</P>
<P>
   The surfers were not amused. And Microsoft, and many others
retreated to focus on more practical Internet services, like e-mail
and shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is now a quiet resurgence of entertainment-based
material on the Internet, and companies that think they can profit
by offering it. Rather than original online programming, though,
the biggest successes are the most derivative: online extensions of
music, television shows and movies that fans already know.
</P>
<P>
   Pursuing the same impulses that made People magazine and its
many imitators so popular, many people want to use the Internet to
get closer to the entertainers they love, reading interviews,
looking at photographs and listening to unreleased record tracks.
Even more powerfully, they want to share their enthusiasm with
other fans, through chat rooms, message boards and even building
home pages about their favorite performers and shows.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, building such content and community around their
recording artists is one of the principal goals of an Internet
venture announced last week by Seagram's Universal Music and
Bertelsmann's BMG, which will sell advertising in addition to
promoting the music companies' recordings. And other entertainment
companies, especially Time Warner's Warner Brothers, are building
fan-oriented sites as independent media profit centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to find ways to get more from our existing
customers,'' said Jim Moloshok, the head of Warner Brothers Online.
``It's no different from McDonald's saying, `Do you want fries with
that hamburger?' ''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This phenomenon has been building from many sides. Many of the
home pages that individuals create on free services like Geocities
are devoted to celebrating certain entertainers, movies or
programs. Existing entertainment providers, like Viacom's MTV, and
new Internet start-ups like Sonicnet, offer online fan forums.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always looked at a media business as a club house people
join, whether they're fans of rock music or the old television
shows of `Nick at Night,''' said Fred Siebert, the president of MTV
Networks Online, which is building a big new site for fans of all
types of music. ``When kids watch television, they're on the phone
talking about it to their friends at the same time. The Internet
just provides an opportunity to make that sense of community all
the closer.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the increasingly interactive Web, big entertainment
producers are looking to build direct relationships with their
customers, cut out intermediaries like MTV, and, perhaps most
important, turn the fan-oriented sites into potentially profitable
services in their own right.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney, for example, has built an elaborate site at ABC.com
(www.abc.go.com) with advertising-supported material pegged to its
television shows. The most popular areas relate to its daytime soap
operas, where viewers go for plot updates, backstage interviews and
to express their own opinions about whether any given love affair
is destined for the altar or the trash heap.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, like others, is also moving to profit from selling goods
to fans online. In a Valentine's Day test, Barbara Walters listed
her choices for the most romantic movie, book and compact disk on
her daytime television show ``The View.'' ABC.com then presented
links so viewers could buy her picks on video, including
``Casablanca'' and a Frank Sinatra compilation, from merchants
paying a commission to Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Warner has had similar sites, supported by advertising and
commerce, devoted to its many television and movie properties. Now
it is going a step further with an elaborate offering called Acme
City (www.acmecity.com) that lets fans build their own home pages
devoted to Warner properties.
</P>
<P>
   Warner is even willing to let users incorporate sounds and
images of its characters into their own home pages, something many
other media companies officially ban because of copyright concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who create home pages devoted to your products are
the ones who will buy your albums the day they are released and see
your movies five times,'' Moloshok said. In Acme City's first 10
weeks, some 200,000 people have registered to build home pages. The
most popular topic: Loony Toons.
</P>
<P>
   But the business is hardly loony. Unlike the all-purpose
home-page sites, which Moloshok said typically charged less than
$10 for every 1,000 viewers of an ad, Warner has been able to
charge $15 to $22.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you place your ad over our site devoted to Loony Toons
you know what the content is,'' he said. ``If you are in a generic
community, the ad could be over a page on animation, knitting or
some alternate lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-11-99 2255EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
