</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-Y2K-INDUSTRY-TESTS-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 INDUSTRIES PASS TESTS FOR YEAR 2000 COMPUTER GLITCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three major industries racing to prepare their computers for the
Year 2000 _ securities, electric utilities and the airlines _ all
passed important testing milestones in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   The securities industry's test, which has been conducted on
weekends since early March, went through its single most important
phase on Saturday, when it simulated Monday, Jan. 3, 2000, the
first trading day next Year and the first day in the test to handle
both new trading and settlement of previous trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went extremely well,'' said John Panchery, the Year 2000
project manager for the Securities Industry Association. All of the
participating exchanges and the organizations that provide them
with clearing and other back-office services _ the backbone of the
$270 billion industry _ came through without any Year 2000
glitches, Panchery said. Results for individual brokers were not
available yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street tests are the most thorough performed by any
industry to deal with the inability of some computers to recognize
that ``00'' as a two-digit date means 2000. The tests involve
several hundred firms, virtually every type of equity they trade,
and, in most cases, the same equipment and software they use to do
business during the week.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Federal Aviation Agency focused on just one
airport _ Denver International _ and one flight in its test
Saturday night of air traffic control, but the test was hailed as a
reassuring success for an industry that many had seen as lagging
far behind the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
   The electric utility industry's simulation was not so much a
Year 2000 test as a drill of how it would deal with a Year 2000
disaster. More than 200 utilities in Canada and the United States
conducted exercises on Friday to see how they would respond to the
loss of voice and data communications that they normally rely on to
monitor power production and distribution. Without such
information, local utilities and then the power grids over which
electricity flows between states could become unbalanced, leading
to widespread blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   During the exercises, utilities switched to radio and satellite
communication systems and focused on making sure that the minimum
amount of information to keep electricity flowing was being passed
from substations and power plants to utility control rooms, from
the utilities to regional control centers such as the PJM
Interconnection (for Pennsylvania, New Jersey and Maryland) in
Norristown, Pa., and among the regional centers.
</P>
<P>
   It will take several weeks to gather all of the data. The drill
was described as successful, but it clearly pointed to a number of
minor problems that need further attention, according to Eugene
Gorzelnik, a spokesman for the North American Reliability Council.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Among the concerns utilities reported: field staff with
out-of-date phone numbers; radio antennae in locations that provide
poor coverage, and employees unable to operate recently purchased
satellite systems.
</P>
<P>
   The drill was conducted alongside normal operations and did not
involve changes to actual generating and transmission equipment.
Many utilities have previously moved power plant computers into the
Year 2000 to make sure that they would not be tripped by the
transition and some have left them there. Some utilities, like
Public Service Electric and Gas in New Jersey, plan to move the
computers on much of their equipment forward to the Year 2000 in
stages this year so that only a small percentage will make the date
transition on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most revealing problem reported in the three
industry tests was a telephone problem affecting the securities
traders that had nothing to do with whether computers will
correctly handle Year 2000 dates. A breakdown in a device that
controls phone traffic into computers at the National Securities
Clearing Corporation on Friday was not repaired before the industry
test began on Saturday. It delayed entries of trading and
bookkeeping information for an undetermined number of firms for
several hours, according to Panchery.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of equipment problems are common, and although we
hadn't planned on it during the test, we got to work on our
contingency plans,'' said Panchery. In a sign of the times,
Clearing Corp. was unable to immediately get all of the incoming
traffic transferred to its backup phone lines because Bell Atlantic
had them tied up in some independent Year 2000 testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not much time left and everyone is rushing to get
their testing done,'' Panchery said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-11-99 2007EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
