<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF WASHINGTON ENTICING YOUNG COMPUTER MAJORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By RUTH SCHUBERT   
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Most University of Washington undergrads toil for two
nail-biting years before they can even apply for admission to the
highly competitive Computer Science and Engineering Department.
</P>
<P>
   But in a bid to lure superstar high school seniors to the
University of Washington instead of losing them to places such as
MIT or Stanford, the university will now let a few outstanding
freshmen directly into the major.
</P>
<P>
   The new early admissions program is crucial to getting the best
and the brightest computer scientists of the future, say UW
administrators who pushed for the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The University of Washington is unusual in that students
choose their majors relatively late, so if you have your heart set
on a competitive major, that can be a drawback when you're choosing
schools,'' said Ed Lazowska, chairman of the Computer Science and
Engineering Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want great Washington state students to feel like they
ought to choose an institution other than the UW.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a major as competitive as computer science, which
regularly turns away a good two-thirds of those who apply, some
students have reservations about giving freshmen coveted slots in
the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me goes, `Well, that's not fair because I didn't have
that opportunity,''' said Erin Moore, a senior in computer science
who was admitted to the major a year after transferring from
Bellevue (Wash.) Community College. ``But I think it would be OK as
long as it doesn't push out other people.''
</P>
<P>
   This academic year, the computer science and computer
engineering department admitted a combined 148 students out of 355
who applied and enrolled 135.
</P>
<P>
   To students on the traditional route who may cry ``unfair,''
Lazowska and others say freshmen are limited to no more than 10
percent of those admitted. The freshmen also will have to meet
yet-to-be-determined ``satisfactory progress'' requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a trap door,'' said Denice Denton, dean of the UW
College of Engineering. ``What I would say to that other student
is, `Look, this student got this early admission and now they're
going to have to prove that they merit that.' ....It's not really a
special benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   The UW's Computer Science and Engineering Department ranks in
the top 10 in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of student computer science is hoping to lure to the UW
is someone like Steve Zhang. Under different circumstances, he
might have gone to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang is a UW freshman who, as luck and hard work would have it,
had enough advanced placement and community college course credits
to apply to the computer science major his first year. With nearly
all of the prerequisites under his belt, he was accepted into the
department during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came to the University of Washington because of their
Computer Science and Engineering Department and how good it was,''
Zhang said. ``I really wouldn't have a second choice at the UW, so
if I hadn't gotten into the computer science department, I would
have considered transferring.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that Zhang would have been rejected. He graduated
from high school in Beaverton, Ore., with a 4.0 GPA, scored a
perfect 1600 on the SAT and had a couple of summers at Intel under
his belt _ all by age 16. Zhang also had offers from MIT, Cal Tech
and the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Lazowska said that, like Zhang, virtually all students admitted
under the new program wouldn't have reason to worry about getting
into the major prior to their junior year. But the early admission
gives a higher degree of certainty.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly all of the application decisions complete, the UW
this year admitted 145 freshmen who declared ``computer science''
or ``computer engineering'' as their intended majors.
</P>
<P>
   Other departments are watching computer science to see how the
early admissions program works. It might be extended to other
engineering departments, Denton said. She cites national data
showing that 40 percent of college students who intend to major in
engineering do not do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just feel isolated,'' Denton said. ``There's a lot of
reasons to believe that bringing them into the loop earlier and
bringing them into the engineering community earlier would be
beneficial from an academic sense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-12-99 0056EDT &QL;
</P>
