</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SOFTWARE-FUTURE-04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINDER, GENTLER COMPUTERS OF THE FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By ANDREW J. GLASS  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- ``When it comes to computers,'' said Michael
Dertouzos, ``people should be able to do more with less.''
</P>
<P>
   As David Clark, Dertouzos' colleague at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, sees it: ``Everything is going to have a
computer in it. Everything will be connected to the network.
Tomorrow's networks must be consumer friendly and cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Still another MIT computer scientist, Victor Zue, believes the
machines of the future will be addressed and reply with the spoken
word, when, for example, a user says: ``Let me know when Microsoft
stock is over $160 a share'' or ``call me a half-hour before I must
leave for the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Also contributing on Tuesday to these 21st century cyber-visions
was Microsoft founder Bill Gates, who told scientists on the MIT
campus: ``In the future, all your personal and professional
information will be stored in a 'cloud' on the Internet. But
retrieval and privacy still pose a challenge. These are tough
questions that we have not yet answered.''
</P>
<P>
   The occasion that brought Gates to Cambridge was the 35th
anniversary of MIT's Laboratory for Computer Science, a
cutting-edge facility Dertouzos has directed since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   MIT marked the event by announcing a new home for the lab, to be
built after Gates sent a check to the university from his family
foundation for $20 million to underwrite construction.
</P>
<P>
   The new home should be ready in 2003, well into a fresh
five-year research project, also announced on Tuesday, aimed at
decoupling personal computers from their traditional desktop
setting.
</P>
<P>
   Dertouzos has dubbed that effort Oxygen. He and his MIT staff at
the lab spent much of the day explaining is goals, which are to be
met through a tax-payer funded $38 million grant from the Defense
Advanced Research Projects Agency, or DARPA, an arm of the Pentagon
that brought the Internet into being in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to liberate ourselves from the tyranny of 'going to
the computer,' Dertouzos said.
</P>
<P>
   In an Oxygenated future, users will carry a universal portable
device that looks something like a cell phone but also has a small
display screen. Dubbed ``Handy 21,'' it will include a digital
video camera, a global positioning system receiver and an infrared
detector, all under the control of a tiny but powerful computer,
which will also be designed at the MIT lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a chameleon,'' Dertouzos said, ``the unit can change at
the flip of a (software command) from a cell phone to a two-way
radio a TV, a beeper, a handheld computer, a pointing device and
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Complementing the Handy 21 will be the Enviro 21, a sensory
network to be placed in office walls, homes and cars. These units
would bear the same relationship to the portable devices as do
power sockets to batteries, offering much greater storage capacity,
communication speed and processing power.
</P>
<P>
   Other technology will link all Oxygen devices to each other and
offer speech-recognition, making the system easy to use as a
natural part of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   The lab plans to build on the Oxygen project by providing four
user services:
</P>
<P>
   -- A friendly, knowledge-access system that helps you find data
you need while you work in your own familiar way and that remembers
all prior forays onto the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   -- An automation technology that lets you tell the machine what
routine work it should off-load from human shoulders -- for
instance, how and when to interrupt you.
</P>
<P>
   -- A collaborative scheme that helps groups work together by
tracing discussions and keeping track of issues, documents and even
snippets of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   -- A customization approach that adapts Oxygen to the needs of
individual users.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no more shrink-wrapped software,'' Dertouzos
said. ``Everything will be downloadable.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
