<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7673 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEY-DAY-HNS &LR;      04-14 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-DAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW WALL STREET CAN HELP YOUR CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Since April 15 is already National Weep About
Money Day, devote a few minutes this week to pure capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   If you can understand the stock market _ one of the few places
where middle-class people are earning real money these days _ it
could help your career in all sorts of ways, financial and
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Money isn't a fashionable thing for a lot of career counselors
to talk about. You should have a career you love, they say, and
then the money will take care of itself. What they overlook,
though, is that having money gives you more career options, such as
starting your own business, working part time, or doing something
you love that doesn't pay much.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some things you should understand about the stock
market, and how they can help your career:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Internet has changed everything.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be hard for small investors to keep up with the news
about individual stocks; the daily newspaper and the Wall Street
Journal could give you only so much. Now there are tons of Internet
sites with news and statistics.
</P>
<P>
   At work, it's the same thing. Job hunters need to realize that
if they don't know much about a company or what their salary should
be, they haven't done their homework. Internet sites like
jobsmart.org have salary comparisons, and most companies have Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   This cannot be said loudly enough: If you're an investor or a
job hunter and you don't use the Internet, you're operating under a
severe handicap. And if your prospective company doesn't have a Web
site, think twice about how long it's going to stay in business.
</P>
<P>
   _ Understand all the risks.
</P>
<P>
   People are intimidated because stocks have bad days or months or
even years, and that sounds too risky for them. What they overlook
is that having plain old savings accounts also carries a risk:
Inflation and taxes can wipe out any interest they receive.
</P>
<P>
   Changing jobs or careers or even quitting a job outright all are
risky. But staying in the same job for 20 or 30 years also carries
a risk: If you're laid off, finding another job can be almost
impossible because you don't have the variety of experience that
employers are looking for.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dividends can be deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors think that a stock that pays a dividend is better
than one that doesn't. Not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   If a stock has a dividend, it usually means that the company
can't come up with anything more attractive than giving the money
back to shareholders. Many fast-growing companies don't pay
dividends because they can put the money to better use expanding
the business.
</P>
<P>
   Each time you get a raise or a bonus, think about whether you
really need the extra money immediately. If you don't, buy yourself
some future career options by investing it.
</P>
<P>
   _ The more established you get, the more important
diversification becomes.
</P>
<P>
   People who run mutual funds preach the virtues of
diversification. Their funds own lots of stocks and sometimes
bonds, so you won't be hurt much if one or two stocks crumble. You
can take advantage of the stock market's long-term growth without
putting too much emphasis on any one company.
</P>
<P>
   But diversification limits rewards as well as risks. If you put
a lot of your money in one stock and it skyrockets, no mutual fund
will be able to match that.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest career risks _ trying to be an actor or professional
athlete, starting your own business _ also offer the biggest
rewards. If you try to hedge instead of diving into them
passionately, you almost certainly will fail. But just as with that
risky stock, you have to know when to cut your losses.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you've gotten to where you want to be,
diversification helps you protect it _ and maybe even improve it.
</P>
<P>
   People who build strong networks and continually add skills are
not only more likely to find a job if they get laid off, they're
less likely to get laid off in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   _ Think long term.
</P>
<P>
   Nervous investors run into trouble because they buy or sell out
of panic, not logic. Try this: Don't think about buying a great
stock; think about buying part of a great company. If it's a great
company, it will succeed. And if it succeeds, its stock will go up
eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Your career might have as many ups and downs as the stock
market, but good workers generally end up with good jobs. Those who
succeed keep both their triumphs and disasters in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   _ Watch your assets.
</P>
<P>
   Even great companies don't necessarily stay great forever.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they get tripped up by the competition; other times by
their own arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   Think about how many athletes or actors fade away because they
either take success for granted or they just can't keep performing
at their peak.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to the top is hard. Staying there is even harder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
