A7676 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAXES-REFORM-TEX     04-14 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXES-REFORM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT HAPPENED TO TAX REFORM: SMALLER TAX CUTS, IRS BILL QUIET
RALLYING CRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARIA RECIO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Bill Archer of Houston might be expressing the
frustrations of millions of Americans when he says: ``I want to
tear the income tax out by its roots so it never grows back
again.''
</P>
<P>
   That anti-tax sound bite often uttered by the Republican
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee might seem
particularly appropriate on Thursday as procrastinators scramble to
get their tax returns postmarked by midnight.
</P>
<P>
   And many of them might wonder: Whatever happened to those
much-ballyhooed GOP plans to overhaul the tax system?
</P>
<P>
   Elimination of the graduated income tax was a rallying cry for
the new Republican majority when the GOP took control of the House
in 1994 for the first time in four decades.
</P>
<P>
   But ``tax reform'' is now little more than a wistful memory _ or
a campaign slogan _ for most lawmakers. It has become a casualty of
a robust economy and political reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``A funny thing happened on the way to tax reform, and that's a
booming economy,'' said Marshall Wittman, director of congressional
relations at the Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of good economic times, new legislation to curb
abuses by the Internal Revenue Service, and a weakened Republican
majority in the House have blunted efforts for a tax overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Except for such true believers as Archer, who champions a
national sales tax, and House Majority Leader Dick Armey, the
Irving Republican who wants a flat tax, few lawmakers on Capitol
Hill even talk much about overhauling taxes anymore. They prefer
instead to focus on tax cuts in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tax season,'' Armey said. ``We always find the affection
the American people have for the flat tax grows between January and
April.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the flat tax would do away with the current
graduated income tax, with its five rates, from 15 percent to 39.6
percent, and impose a single rate for all taxpayers. Armey, for
example, proposes a rate of 17 percent and says the tax returns
could be done on a form the size of a postcard.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I always knew that was a long-run project,'' said Armey,
who began touting the flat tax in 1994. ``I knew that it would take
me at least 10 years to pass it into law. I believe I'll pass it
into law by the end of the year 2002. But between now and then,
we've got to get that tax relief which is available to the
overtaxed American taxpayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer, who will retire at the end of this Congress, will be
turning from overhauling taxes to the equally formidable task of
saving Social Security from insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chairman hasn't lost any interest in reforming the tax
code,'' said Trent Duffy, spokesman for the Ways and Means
Committee. ``Having said that, with the president's interest in
Social Security reform, we're going to be seizing on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer and Armey have cultivated a friendly rivalry as each
promoted his respective version of tax code change, but lack of a
Republican consensus on a single approach was only one problem. As
the GOP majority diminished in the 1996 and 1998 congressional
elections, the Republicans are left with a six-vote majority and a
dim outlook for a tax overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, lawmakers' success in getting a
taxpayer-friendly IRS bill passed last year and making some tax
cuts, such as a reduction in the capital gains tax rate, helped
reduce the urgency for radical changes in the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   In the 106th Congress, which convened in January and runs for
two years, there are no hearings planned, no bills in motion _ in
short, no momentum whatsoever to a tax overhaul effort that once
appeared an unstoppable juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   Not that everyone is giving up on it _ especially those ordinary
folks out in the hinterland who have been listening to the
pronouncements of presidential hopefuls on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's fallen out of fashion in Washington,'' said Ken
Johnson, press secretary to Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La. ``But it
hasn't fallen out of favor with the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin, who advocates a tax on consumption, plans to introduce a
bill Thursday calling for a 15 percent national sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   Americans for Fair Taxation, a national sales tax group based in
Houston, takes a slightly different approach. It wants a 23 percent
national sales tax rate, which would also eliminate payroll taxes
that now fund Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only pure consumption tax,'' said Laura Dale, a
consultant to the nonprofit group.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Linbeck Jr., chairman of Americans for Fair Taxation, said
the plan was ``developed like a product _ by asking focus groups
and polling what people value and what their interest was in seeing
reform of taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization has spent $15 million over the past 31/2 years
developing and promoting its plan through an extensive grassroots
campaign. It expects to spend $90 million on the entire effort.
</P>
<P>
   Linbeck said he expects the plan to be introduced in Congress
before the summer break. He would not say who the sponsors might
be.
</P>
<P>
   Political forecasters are looking to the 2000 presidential
campaign, however, to breathe new life into the concept. ``It'll
probably take presidential leadership,'' Wittman said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a favorite for the Republican
presidential nomination, has not taken a position on a specific
plan. But others, such as magazine publisher Steve Forbes and
social conservative Gary Bauer, are pressing for a flat tax.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes helped make ``flat tax'' a household term, at least in
political circles, in the 1996 presidential race and is ready to
take up the flat tax banner again, advocating a 17 percent rate. On
Thursday, he will stage an event in Portsmouth, N.H., to call for
``tax code termination day.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey said he has spoken to Bush about the concept of reducing
taxes and overhauling taxes. ``I think he's pretty much in tune
with the rest of the party,'' Armey said of the governor.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
