<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS IGNORE IMPROVEMENTS IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Kosovo is the current international crisis
that engages the attention of American policymakers and military
forces, but I wonder whether another is brewing.
</P>
<P>
   I refer to China, the world's most populous nation, whose prime
minister just visited the United States, the world's most powerful
nation. Premier Zhu Rongji's American sojourn has prompted the
usual suspects, including Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., to demonize
China over its human rights record, its illegal donations to U.S.
political campaigns and suspicions that it has stolen U.S. nuclear
secrets.
</P>
<P>
   I admit to a degree of identity crisis. As an American-born
ethnic Chinese, I embrace the freedoms of our society yet honor the
cultural heritage of my immigrant parents.
</P>
<P>
   In my lifetime, their homeland has undergone monumental changes
_ from civil war to totalitarian Communist rule to significant
stability under capitalist-inspired economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   We are talking here of improving the lives of more than 1
billion people. Why are some American leaders so venomous toward
China? It could not be because China poses an immediate strategic
or economic threat.
</P>
<P>
   While in this country, Zhu asked why some Americans apparently
fear China when the United States has more than 6,000 nuclear
weapons compared to China's two dozen. And the U.S. economy is 10
times bigger than China's. Why exactly is the King of the World so
paranoid about China?
</P>
<P>
   I can't help thinking back on a trip I took to China four months
ago. (Most of my two-week visit, except for the plane fare, was
paid for by the Chinese government.) I visited high-tech
industries, historical sites and cultural institutions in four
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Discussions about politics were not on our agenda, but I managed
to talk with several young Chinese who were not part of the
official itinerary. I asked them whether the lives of ordinary
Chinese people have improved. All gave an unqualified yes.
</P>
<P>
   I did not see large areas of abject poverty when touring
Guangzhou, Xian, Hangzhou and Shanghai. What I saw were throngs of
people in modern department stores that sell a rich variety of
consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
   Do ordinary Chinese think about acquiring greater individual
freedoms, including political rights?
</P>
<P>
   A young teacher said ordinary Chinese today have more freedoms
than they had a decade ago, such as greater access to information
and more freedom to travel.
</P>
<P>
   Another _ a tall, slender young man who works at a
pharmaceutical company _ said he believes the Chinese people will
become freer with continuing economic modernization.
</P>
<P>
   I asked a 23-year-old journalist whether Chinese people think
much about having more individual freedom and political power.
</P>
<P>
   She said such thoughts were remote or nonexistent among ordinary
Chinese, who are too busy trying to survive.
</P>
<P>
   One of my traveling companions, a Chinese-American radio
journalist from New York who grew up in China, said that,
historically, the Chinese people have believed in honoring the
father in a family relationship. The emperor became the nation's
father and the people obeyed him without question.
</P>
<P>
   The father authority figure remains an animating force in how
ordinary Chinese people view their leaders, he said. But he quickly
added that modernization is slowly changing how the Chinese feel
about this.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the complexities of transforming a once-feudal
society, China has made big strides in economic reforms and some
advances in political freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Why aren't the China-bashers at least willing to concede that?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
