<HEADLINE>
A YEAR OF LOOKING FOR THE RIGHT CARDS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Roy Sorrels  &LR; was watching a game of three-card monte in
Manhattan when a voice yelled, ``Cop!'' The dealer disappeared and
three cards fluttered to the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Picking them up ``was the beginning of my yearlong hunt for one
full deck of found playing cards,'' he writes in the latest issue
of Smithsonian.
</P>
<P>
   At home, he created a display on which to glue the found cards,
no more than three at a time by his own rules. When friends accused
him of eccentricity, he created his own rationale. ``I want to
spend at least part of my time doing things that don't necessary
make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months later, he was short only one card, the three of
clubs. Then he came upon the same three-card monte man, shuffling
the cards at the site at which the collecting had begun. ``I
stopped 20 feet away from him and yelled, `Cop!' He kicked over the
boxes and ran.''
</P>
<P>
   There on the sidewalk, Sorrels found his card. ``Everyone
ignored me,'' he writes, ``just another guy kneeling on a New York
sidewalk, crying and kissing, for his own sweet reasons, the three
of clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOOD WORKS OF ASHLEY JUDD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ashley Judd &LR;  wanted to be a Peace Corps volunteer after
college, reports Marie Claire magazine. But she became an actress
instead. In meaningful celebration of ``the life I might have
lived,'' Marie Claire sent Judd to spend a week in Suriname, South
America, as a pretend Peace Corps volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give me a sense of the country and the people,'' writes
Judd in a first-person account of her altruistic week, ``they took
me to the central market, or marron. The women were dressed in all
styles. ... My favorite was the Pangi, or bright plaids worn on top
of each other and secured with twists of the fabric. ... A
wonderful saleslady guided me to the brightest of the brights. We
selected three eye-popping plaids (think Lilly Pulitzer amplified)
and she advised me on how to choose clashing threads for sewing the
hems. When next you see me looking very good in Nantucket, think
Suriname.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she concludes after a piece illustrated with a photo of her
``answering the call of nature ... in nature,'' ``I could have done
it when I was 22, joined the PC and flourished, but maybe by
telling you about my experience, I have done even greater good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOM JONES TAKES ON SEAN CONNERY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sean Connery &LR; , a Scot who plans to campaign for the separatist
Scottish National Party in parliamentary elections, is
``divisive,'' says  &UR; Tom Jones &LR; , a Welshman. Jones was recently
honored with an OBE; Connery is said to have been denied a
knighthood because of his politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British Isles is small enough as it is,'' Jones told the
Times of London. ``We don't want to make it any smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Sally Lilienthal &LR; , founder of the peace and disarmament
foundation Ploughshares, was honored with an 80th birthday
celebration in Washington on Monday night, co-chaired by
Representative  &UR; Nancy Pelosi &LR; , D-San Francisco, and attended by
 &UR; George Miller &LR; , D-Martinez,  &UR; Anna Eshoo &LR; , D-Atherton, and  &UR; Jim &LR; 
 &UR; Hormel &LR; , who brought his granddaughter so she could meet ``a great
lady.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Browsing at Benjamin Books at the Denver airport,  &UR; Brenda &LR; 
 &UR; Kahn  &LR; found ``Monica's Story'' in the humor section.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMONG THE LIVING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Atheist  &UR; Madalyn Murray O'Hair  &LR; disappeared in 1995. News
stories indicated last week that law enforcement authorities,
believing that she was murdered, may be closing in on suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, &UR; Sally Mack  &LR; recently received an e-mail, forwarded
through the Net by fundamentalist Christians, warning of O'Hair's
current attempts to remove prayer from radio and television and her
campaign to ban the singing of Christmas carols in schools. ``Do
not let this woman win again!'' says the e-mail, urging electronic
signatures on a petition that would ``defeat Ms. O'Hare'' (sic).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The massage is a health thing, not a pleasure thing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dale Van Pamelen, co-owner of the New York Dog Spa and Hotel,
which offers a complete day of dog revitalization, including
pedicure and polish, hot oil treatment and full body massage, for
$150. Van Pamelen was quoted in Jump magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
