</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-ARCHIVES-$ADV18-     04-14 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ARCHIVES-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARCHIVISTS, CURATORS GAINING HIGH-TECH TOOLS
 &HT;    570&AMP;add. With DECLARATION-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (e)
entertainment categories for release Sunday, April 18.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America's treasured national documents, including
the Declaration of Independence and the Constitution, are being
bathed in a greenhouse gas.
</P>
<P>
   And that's good.
</P>
<P>
   National Aeronautics and Space Administration chemists recently
used a laser-based instrument to determine that airtight cases
containing the two documents and the Bill of Rights have not
leaked.
</P>
<P>
   That means the documents, which are viewed by more than 1
million people a year at the National Archives here, are still
being protected by the mixture of helium and water vapor in which
they were hermetically sealed nearly 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The laser-based instrument _ built to allow NASA chemists to
measure atmospheric levels of water vapor, a greenhouse gas _ was
used to assay the thin film of gas surrounding the three ``Charters
of Freedom'' without opening their sealed cases.
</P>
<P>
   The laser beam was shot through the cases near the edges, where
it did not strike the documents inside. By analyzing the way the
film of gas changed the properties of the beam as it passed
through, the chemists were able to identify the gas mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the laser was back in its customary place, attached
to the underside of the wing of a NASA research plane flying over
the southern Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Its brief trip to the world of priceless historical documents
was an example of a growing trend among museum curators and
archivists to use Space Age technologies to deal with age-old
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Tools that sound like they belong in a laboratory or aboard a
man-made Earth satellite are enabling the keepers of treasured
objects of art and history to detect forgeries, plan restorations,
even study the careers of long-dead painters and sculptors.
</P>
<P>
   Technologies such as scanning electron microscopy, X-ray
fluorescence and xeroradiography can peer into areas that otherwise
are beyond the reach of art historians and museum curators:
</P>
<P>
   _ Before the Air and Space Museum restored the Wright Brothers'
1903 Flyer, the first plane successfully flown by the aviation
pioneers, irreplaceable bolts were X-rayed so curators would know
which way to turn them when the plane was disassembled.
</P>
<P>
   _ A treasured object thought to have been created by a master
painter or sculptor can be shown to be the skillful work of a
forger. At the Winterthur Museum in Wilmington, Del., an instrument
known as a Fourier transform infrared spectroscope was used a few
years ago to bombard a sample of paint from a ``rare 18th-century
chest'' and expose an ingredient that did not exist in the 18th
century.
</P>
<P>
   _ A famous painting can be shown to have gradually faded so that
it looks dramatically different from how it looked the day it was
finished.
</P>
<P>
   _ By analyzing brush strokes and other techniques throughout the
lifetime of an artist, scholars can learn how various traits
evolved during the artist's life.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian Institution Center for Materials Research not
only maintains a tool box filled with sophisticated instruments for
studying antiquities, fossils, and art treasures, but it also
supports research in such areas as the actual chemical and
biological processes in the deterioration of materials.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to working with individual Smithsonian institutions,
the center has provided assistance to the FBI and the Army.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the documents at the National Archives, the need
to find out what kind of gas occupies the space less than an eighth
of an inch thick in their glass cases developed after curators
noticed what appear to be small areas of deterioration in the
glass.
</P>
<P>
   The four-page Constitution, its letter of transmittal, the
Declaration of Independence and the Bill of Rights were encased in
the helium-water vapor mixture in 1951 and 1952 by the National
Institute of Science and Technology, then known as the National
Bureau of Standards.
</P>
<P>
   Joel S. Levine, the NASA scientist who performed the test
confirming that the same encased atmosphere still surrounds the
documents, said the mixture is approximately 99 percent helium, an
inert gas that will not corrode the sheepskin parchment on which
the documents were written.
</P>
<P>
   The 1 percent water vapor is intended to prevent flaking of the
parchment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   The test was possible, he said, because all gases, including
water vapor and helium, absorb light at specific and unique wave
lengths.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this is how the greenhouse effect works. Visible light
from the sun passes through the atmosphere at wave lengths that are
not affected by gases such as carbon dioxide, methane and water
vapor.
</P>
<P>
   But infrared radiation, given off by the Earth's surface after
it is heated up by the sunlight, does interact with those gases.
They absorb the infrared heat and keep it from escaping into space
while more heat comes in from the sun.
</P>
<P>
   To measure water vapor over various parts of the Earth, NASA had
a laser already tuned to the wavelength with which the water
molecule interacts.
</P>
<P>
   When it is attached to the underside of NASA's Douglas DC-8
research plane and directed at a receiver in the cabin, the laser
beam is weakened slightly by the water vapor molecules it
encounters along the way. By measuring the degree of change in the
beam, scientists can record an extremely precise inventory of water
vapor in the air the plane flies through.
</P>
<P>
   The same process, Levine said, allowed him and his NASA
colleagues to assay the air inside the Charters cases.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an Archives spokeswoman said there are plans to build
a new generation of cases for the Charters of Freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
