<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7697 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-ARCHIVES-DATA-$A     04-14 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ARCHIVES-DATA-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRAVELS OF THE ARCHIVES; MORE INFORMATION ON THE INTERNET
 &HT;    With DECLARATION. Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment
categories for release Sunday, April 18.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRAVELS OF THE CHARTERS
</P>
<P>
   Between 1776 and 1814, the Declaration of Independence traveled
with the Continental Congress, rolled and unrolled whenever it was
used.
</P>
<P>
   It remained in Philadelphia until late 1777, when it was taken
to Baltimore along with the Congress, which had moved out of
Philadelphia because of invading British.
</P>
<P>
   In 1789, Congress passed a law giving the Department of Foreign
Affairs, later to become the State Department, ``the custody and
charge'' of all national papers and documents.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, Thomas Jefferson, author of the Declaration
of Independence, became secretary of state and custodian of the
document, along with the new Constitution, the Bill of Rights and
the letter of transmittal of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In 1814, during the War of 1812, the documents were removed from
the State Department under orders from President James Monroe, to
keep them from falling into British hands. Packed in coarse linen
and bags, they were hauled to a grist mill in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   In 1841, Secretary of State Daniel Webster suggested the
documents be moved to a new building built for the U.S. Patent
Office. The Declaration was hung _ in a single frame along with
George Washington's commission as commander in chief _ on a white
wall opposite a window, resulting in prolonged exposure to
sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   In 1876 the Declaration was moved to Independence Hall in
Philadelphia, where it was originally signed, for exhibition in a
special safe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1877 it was placed in a cabinet in the State Department
Library, a room that had an open fireplace and in which smoking was
permitted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1894, the State Department announced the document was too
badly deteriorated to be displayed any longer, so it was wrapped
and placed in a steel case.
</P>
<P>
   In 1903, the Declaration and the Constitution were turned over
to the Library of Congress, where the Constitution was to be placed
on exhibition to the ``patriotic public.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 30, 1941, the librarian of Congress, worried about the
possibility of World War II leading to some incident that would
damage or destroy the documents, asked that they be locked up at
Fort Knox in Kentucky. They were.
</P>
<P>
   In 1944, Congress appropriated money to have the documents
turned over to the National Archives and preserved for the public
to see.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, following studies by representatives of a gas
manufacturers and officials of the Archives and the National Bureau
of Standards, the glass cases that currently hold the objects were
built.
</P>
<P>
   Source: National Archives.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET SITES ON HIGH-TECH ARCHIVES
</P>
<P>
   University of Delaware art conservation program:
</P>
<P>
   http://Seurat.art.udel.edu/ArtCon/ACDegree/PHD.html
</P>
<P>
   Smithsonian Center for Materials Research and Education
</P>
<P>
   http://www.si.edu/scmre
</P>
<P>
   National Archives
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nara.gov
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
