<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7702 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CERTAIN-JUSTICE-LADN     04-14 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CERTAIN-JUSTICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KCET VIEWERS TREATED TO CEREBRAL MURDER MYSTERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(``Tonight'' refers to Thursday, April 15)  
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ P.D. James is sort of the thinking person's Agatha
Christie. Like Christie's, her mysteries are intricately plotted,
but unlike Dame Agatha's tidy endings, James' are usually knotty
affairs. ``Mystery's'' dramatization of James' 1998 best seller ``A
Certain Justice'' is a perfect example.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Certain Justice &UR; , &LR; '' airing in three parts starting tonight
on KCET, marks actor Roy Marsden's 10th time as James'
introspective poet/detective Adam Dalgliesh. This time he is called
on to investigate the murder of high-powered barrister Venetia
Aldridge (Penny Downie).
</P>
<P>
   The ambitious and abrasive Venetia had recently successfully
defended Gary Ashe (Ricci Harnett), accused of brutally murdering
his aunt, a prostitute, in their London home. Venetia was fairly
sure that Ashe was guilty, but that hadn't deterred her from doing
her job.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, however, it's another matter when her
18-year-old daughter Octavia (Flora Montgomery) _ recently home
from boarding school and alienated from mother _ announces that
she's fallen in love with Ashe.
</P>
<P>
   Though voicing her opposition, Venetia doesn't have a chance to
break up the relationship. The barrister is found in her law-firm
office stabbed to death with a letter opener that replicates the
sword of justice, a barrister's wig _ a classic heirloom long in
storage _ on her head, and covered in blood that is not her own.
</P>
<P>
   Dalgliesh and his assistant, Detective Inspector Kate Miskin
(Sarah Winman), are faced with a multitude of suspects besides
Ashe. The investigation centers on a number of Venetia's co-workers
whom she has offended or who felt their positions were in jeopardy
were she to become head of the firm.
</P>
<P>
   It is, like other James' works, a complex web that involves the
past. The unsettling conclusion leaves as many questions as it
raises. Not about the whodunit, which is wrapped up quite nicely,
but about the nature of justice, and if we somehow determine our
own.
</P>
<P>
   While ``A Certain Justice'' is a smooth adaption of James'
novel, it is Marsden's quiet, thoughtful presence as Dalgliesh that
gives these productions an added edge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1304EDT &QL; 
