<SLUG> BC-OVERTIME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR BACKS BILL TO OVERHAUL CALIFORNIA OVERTIME LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A labor-backed bill in the California Assembly
would restore daily overtime and affect millions of primarily
nonunion, hourly employees.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, written by Assemblyman Wally Knox, D-Los Angeles, pits
organized labor against businesses and some wage earners who like
the flexibility allowed under the state's current law.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 16-month-old overtime law, workers can work longer
hours on certain days in exchange for working fewer hours another
day, in effect jamming a 40-hour work week into less than five full
days.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco restaurant worker Nancy Hahn said the flexibility
permitted under this system made both her and her boss happy. She
gets time during the week for personal business or leisure, while
her boss doesn't have to pay any overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is a lot happier this way,'' Hahn said, referring to
her fellow workers at the Fog City Diner. ``A lot of people are
working double shifts now because they want to, not because they
have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor organizers counter that that argument is just an excuse to
take advantage of employees. The Knox bill would restore a system
in which workers begin to earn overtime if they work more than
eight hours in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flexibility at a cost isn't what we need,'' said Walter
Johnson, secretary-treasurer of the San Francisco Labor Council.
``This situation without any control is really a form of slavery to
the people who have no control.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the 40-hour rule, which was approved by the
Industrial Welfare Commission under former Gov. Pete Wilson, has
saved businesses $1 billion in overtime since it went into effect
Jan. 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 study by the University of California and the AFL-CIO
criticized the 40-hour-week overtime law, making the case that
women would be disproportionately affected by the lack of daily
overtime because many work in hourly positions such as clerical,
service and sales jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Knox bill, at least in concept, is expected to be received
favorably by Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat who pledged during his
campaign to return to the eight-hour work day.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, as currently written, addresses some of businesses'
flexibility concerns by including a clause that lets workers take
up to four hours off a week and make up those hours during the
week, provided they have their employer's consent. In addition,
Knox's bill would give workers the right to vote on exceptions,
such as alternate shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Small businesses in particular balk at the proposed changes to
the overtime law since a higher percentage of them are nonunion
employers.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hauge, head of the Small Business Network in San
Francisco, described the process of voting on exceptions as
cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at his company, Cal Insurance &AMP; Associates, get every
other Friday off by working shifts longer than eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you vote on every issue? How do you vote on child care?
How do you vote on parent-teacher conferences? There are so many
things that can come up,'' Hauge said.
</P>
<P>
   When California changed its overtime laws, it joined the federal
government and 47 other states _ all of which count overtime as
work beyond 40 hours per week, rather than eight hours per day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
