<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, April 15, 1999. If you have any questions, please call
The Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   COAL (Parkville, Mo.) _ Twenty-six cars of a Burlington Northern
train headed from Lincoln, Neb., to Kansas City, Kan., derails in
downtown Parkville shortly before midnight, dumping 135,000 tons of
coal, wiping out two buildings, cutting power, gas and water lines
and forcing Park College to close. Five residences also were
evacuated. But no one was hurt. A miracle?? The cause is believed
to be a wheel bearing that caused an axle to drag and catch on the
train switch. Photos, graphic depicting the derailment sequence and
detail of wheel showing how accident happened. with SAFE: Who's
responsible for freight train safety? And what would have happened
if the train was carrying nuclear waste or chlorine gas? (Both will
move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   STAY (Tentative) Do Americans have the staying power it might
take to win a war in Yugoslavia? 25-30 inches. By Scott Canon.
(Will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MICRO (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Microsoft files software piracy
lawsuits against four Kansas City area firms. (Will move in the
``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   KTAX (Kansas City, Kan.) _ Thanks to the swell economy and all
those new jobs, Kansas will have 175,000 more individual tax
returns this year, up 15 percent from last year. And thanks to the
swell economy and all those new jobs, the state Department of
Revenue has had trouble hiring processors and has 40 positions
unfilled. The bottom line: Taxpayers should expect a longer wait
for refunds. Tom Perrin. (Holdover) 25 inches. With graphic. (Will
move in the ``a'' category.)
.MDNM/ WAGON (Kansas City, Mo.) _ A wagon train, mimicking those
that headed west during the California Gold Rush, approaches the
Kansas City area from St. Charles. It's hitting Fort Osage on the
14th, Independence on the 15th and Raytown on the 16th. With box on
where train's going to be. Trisha L. Howard. 15 inches. (Will move
in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
