<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HANDS-ON' DRIVING OUGHT TO MEAN WHEEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've heard a lot about aggressive driving, speeding, tailgating
and myriad other motoring transgressions that can lead to car
wrecks, traffic tickets and even to that most dreaded of
contemporary highway hazards: road rage.
</P>
<P>
   But all that pales in comparison to a modern menace that may
pose the greatest threat to driving safety since the advent of
drive-through liquor stores: the cellular telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Exaggeration, you say?
</P>
<P>
   Not really. At least one reputable study has suggested that
talking on the phone while driving can be as potentially dangerous
as driving drunk.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't believe it, start paying attention to those nitwits
who swerve in front of you in traffic, who meander mindlessly from
lane to lane, who suddenly speed up or slow down for no apparent
reason. Note how often that a driver who does such things is
talking on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you've noticed already. If you haven't noticed, maybe it's
because you're one of the people who insists on driving and talking
on the phone at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you are driving and talking it's because you are
capable of doing both without being distracted. You wouldn't make a
nuisance of yourself on the highways and byways.
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers can drive and talk, and some can't. Like the one
who was quoted in a Fort Worth Star-Telegram story on the subject:
``Most people know if they can do two things at once. I know I
personally can drive with one hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing to it. You just gotta know your capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   There must be untold numbers of people who can drive and (choose
one): eat breakfast, shave, apply mascara, read the newspaper, feed
the baby, play with the dog, program the buttons on the car radio,
count the loose change in the ashtray, search for a pack of
cigarettes in the glove compartment, take a nap ...
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe just a catnap.
</P>
<P>
   We know that people can do this stuff because they are out there
doing it, morning, noon and night, on every street and highway and
freeway in America.
</P>
<P>
   Most states have any number of laws that make it illegal to
drive like an idiot, so you'd think that drivers who don't pay
attention to their prime responsibility _ which happens to be
driving the car, in case anyone forgot _ would be racking up
traffic tickets as fast as the cops could write them. As we know,
however, the police almost never pull someone over for erratic
driving caused by eating a Big Mac with one hand and finishing up a
tax return with the other.
</P>
<P>
   The sad truth is, an all-out crackdown on disengaged drivers
would leave law enforcement officials little time to pursue serious
lawbreakers.
</P>
<P>
   But that isn't stopping state and local lawmakers around the
country from stepping up to the plate to take on the growing peril
of car phones.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Texas, where not so long ago a person could drive and
guzzle a six-pack of beer without fear of arrest, the Legislature
is pondering a bill that would outlaw the practice of driving and
talking on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   The Star-Telegram quoted the bill's sponsor, Democratic Rep.
Paul Moreno of El Paso: ``I think that if we make it specific that
perhaps we can save a life. It's a dangerous thing _ we all know
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreno's bill would prohibit motorists from using hand-held
phones while driving _ which wouldn't necessarily solve the
problem, because the same study that equated the use of car phones
with drunken driving suggested that using a hands-free phone is
just as dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the problem is one of concentration. Maybe some
people can drive with one hand and hold a telephone with the other,
but they still have only one brain to think with.
</P>
<P>
   Is it the state Legislature's job to force people to use their
brains for driving instead of talking?
</P>
<P>
   An Arlington cop told the Star-Telegram that it would be better
if drivers policed themselves in their use of car phones. He's
absolutely right.
</P>
<P>
   And the odds of that happening are about the same as those of
winning tonight's Lotto drawing.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
