<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUCLEAR WEAPONS LABS WILL UNDERGO SECURITY UPGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Federal authorities have announced that they are
tightening security at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory after
reports of spying at its sister nuclear weapons lab in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials said they also are trying to prevent tightened
security from impeding research by burdening staffers, including
foreign visitors _ a seemingly contradictory goal.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. citizens will receive uniform treatment regardless of their
national origin, the officials said at a news conference Tuesday at
the lab, to assuage any concerns that any Americans' security
clearances might be dependent on their ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   The concerns arose because an American citizen of Chinese
ancestry has been accused of spying for China at Los Alamos
National Laboratory in New Mexico. Both nuclear weapons labs are
run by the University of California under contract to the U.S.
Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, non-Americans from politically ``sensitive'' countries
might be subject to more intensive scrutiny if they seek to work at
Livermore, located in the East San Francisco Bay area, at Los
Alamos or the other main nuclear weapons facility, Sandia National
Laboratories in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Energy Department officials stressed the
importance of tightened security.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real issue,'' said Ernie Moniz, undersecretary for
the Energy Department. Even if the fuss over the alleged Los Alamos
spy hadn't erupted, the security upgrade would have been needed
sooner or later because ``the threat environment of today is very
different from the environment of 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Moniz explained, the Cold War of 10 years ago _
when the United States faced off with the Soviet Union _ has been
replaced by threats such as terrorist groups and Internet hackers.
</P>
<P>
   About a week ago, Livermore officials shut down all
security-related computers to update them with new protective
``firewalls'' to make them less vulnerable to espionage and
hackers.
</P>
<P>
   The computer system remains down pending further modification,
Moniz said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington Tuesday, Energy Department secretary Bill
Richardson announced new initiatives to guard the weapons labs
against espionage.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would:
</P>
<P>
   _Ask Congress to boost the department's counterintelligence
budget next year by $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   _Impose ``stricter document controls'' for all secret and top
secret documents concerning weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   _Review the security of the department's program that brings
foreign scientists to work in U.S. labs. The review will be led by
former CIA chief John Deutch.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Newsweek magazine reported this week that CIA
technicians found 31 secret files in Deutch's home computer soon
after he left the CIA post in December 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
