A7770 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSPAPERS-DIVERSITY-     04-14 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPERS-DIVERSITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPERS SEE LITTLE PROGRESS IN MINORITY HIRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A new survey of daily newspapers found the
proportion of minority and women journalists falls well short of
their representation in the population, causing concern among
industry executives who have struggled for years to diversify
newsrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of journalists who are Asian, black, Hispanic and
Native American was 11.55 in 1998, up from 11.46 percent the
previous year, according to a survey released Tuesday by the
American Society of Newspaper Editors (ASNE).
</P>
<P>
   It also found that women accounted for 36.88 percent of newsroom
staff and 34 percent of newsroom supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't sell newspapers to people if you don't reflect their
communities,'' said N. Christian Anderson, publisher of the Orange
County (Calif.) Register and incoming ASNE president. ``It's a
simple business equation as well as the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the sluggishness in diversifying newsrooms are
varied, news executives said. Many journalism students are more
drawn to television than newspapers and magazines; some leave the
industry because of lack of advancement opportunities; others avoid
journalism altogether, opting for careers in more-lucrative fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to rekindle enthusiasm for print journalism,'' said Ed
Seaton, president of the ASNE and editor-in-chief of the Manhattan
(Kan.) Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   A Newspaper Association of America (NAA) study indicated that
ignoring minority markets opens the door to competitive media, even
though researchers heard ``advertising directors saying advertisers
don't want `those people,''' said Chris Manai of the NAA.
</P>
<P>
   The ASNE newsroom census, which has been conducted annually
since 1978, surveyed 958 of the country's 1,456 daily newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time the survey included a count of women.
</P>
<P>
   The proportion of minority reporters, photographers and editors
has remained around 11 percent for several years, while the
minority population in the United States is now 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the disparities continue, newspapers will pay the price,''
said Pam Johnson, executive editor of the Arizona Republic and
president of Associated Press Managing Editors. ``If we have
coverage that is not relevant to large parts of our community, we
will continue to see the erosion (of readership) we have seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaton noted a couple bright spots. He said minority journalists
make up 25 percent of all new hires and one-third of interns.
</P>
<P>
   However, one of the biggest problems is retaining minority
journalists, Seaton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have as many going out as coming in,'' he said. ``We're
sort of on a treadmill here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich Oppel, ASNE board member and editor of the Austin (Texas)
American-Statesman, said his newspaper tries to retain minorities
through promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have that kind of mix, there's a greater comfort
level for minorities to come and stay and see they're rewarded for
good work,'' he said. ``What I've seen at some very good papers is
the top (levels of management) is not changing. Sooner or later,
frustration sets in.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that 91 percent of newsroom supervisors were
white.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Montiel, president of the Robert C. Maynard Institute for
Journalism Education in Oakland, Calif., said what is needed is a
cultural change at newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an industry that until 30 years ago was nearly all
white and within this century was nearly all male,'' he said. ``We
really need revolutionary change. What we're getting is incremental
change that is glacial.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Maynard, the late publisher of the Oakland Tribune and
founder of the Maynard Institute, Montiel and a group of other
journalists helped push ASNE in 1977 to set a goal of racial parity
in hiring by 2000. Controversy erupted last year when the ASNE
board decided that goal was unattainable and proposed scaling it
back.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it decided to aim for achieving parity by 2025.
</P>
<P>
   The ASNE is holding its annual convention in San Francisco this
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
