<HEADER>
A7771 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ETHIOPIAN-CHURCH-2TAK     04-14 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIAN-CHURCH-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW LAND, ETHIOPIANS STRUGGLE FOR UNITY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ They call themselves the first Christians _
heirs to an ancient covenant, builders of the world's earliest
churches.
</P>
<P>
   But here the congregation of St. Michael's Ethiopian Orthodox
Church carries out ancient traditions in a way their ancestors
could never have foreseen.
</P>
<P>
   They still remove their shoes, as Moses did when the angel
appeared to him in the burning bush. They guard against temptation,
with gauzy veils and separate pews for women. But under the gothic
arches of St. Peter's Episcopal Church, thousands of miles from
home, these Ethiopians are only visitors in another's temple.
</P>
<P>
   Since they spoke their first prayer in a Boston Lutheran church
10 years ago, the 200 members of St. Michael's have dreamed of
their own house of worship. Last year, after a decade of prayer at
a half-dozen altars, they resolved to buy or build their own.
Though church members have raised $100,000 so far, leaders say
soaring real estate prices have stalled the effort.
</P>
<P>
   But as St. Michael's celebrated its high holiday, Orthodox
Easter this month, the search for a building revealed a deeper
struggle, one that strikes at the heart of fledgling immigrant
groups: how to preserve ties to a distant past, while letting go of
the divisions and old arguments carried over from the homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctant refugees who never thought they would leave their
homeland, many Ethiopians say their American community is at a
crossroads. As it tilts further from the conflicts engulfing
Ethiopia and toward a long-term future in the United States, the
need for foundations here has become more important than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the foundations have been established: newsletters,
restaurants, Sunday school classes, an economic niche in the
parking garage industry, a partnership that aids families in
mourning _ all signs of growing cohesion. But a home for their
ancient faith is a critical missing element.
</P>
<P>
   As a community of some 10,000 Boston-area immigrants pools
scarce resources and searches for unity, it remains divided by old
alliances and new mistrust. The conflicts erupted in two lawsuits.
The first, in 1992, splintered the congregation of St. Michael's.
The second, filed in 1997 and still unresolved, has locked two
groups in a struggle for control of a community center.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the pangs of a community trying to find itself and
its leaders,'' said Antene Tamiru, a parking lot manager who lives
in Boston. ``It is a problem for all countries that don't have a
history of democracy. We don't always know how to understand our
differences and live with them.''
</P>
<P>
   As the conflicts simmer, the passing on of a national culture
and an unbroken Christian legacy hangs in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being an Ethiopian Christian is not just an ethnicity. It's a
covenant with God,'' said Getachew Selassie, a member of St.
Michael's who left Ethiopia in 1970. ``Our forefathers handed down
to us a tradition that was uninterrupted for centuries. And we are
throwing it down the drain.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Huge, hollow abdomens and bony limbs: To most Americans, the
dominant image of Ethiopia remains one of famine, which swept the
East African country in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   That was the country Genet Bekele fled in 1982, when she walked
for seven days to reach Sudan. But the Ethiopia she recalls is one
of proud legacies, not human tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   From the International Institute in Boston, where she counsels
refugees, Bekele, 39, invokes a history of scholars and diplomats;
a people who guarded their nation against Islam and the waves of
European colonization that swept the continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Ethiopia I knew, moving from one city to another was a
big deal, not to mention mass exodus,'' said Bekele, who left 17
years ago but can barely bring herself to speak about her flight.
``We had no history of leaving the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But beginning in 1974, a 20-year chapter of Marxist rule scarred
that history, toppling the country's Emporer Haile Selassie. Under
a regime many call ``The Red Terror,'' thousands were persecuted,
imprisoned, or killed, letting loose a tide of 2.5 million refugees
who fanned out from Africa, through Europe, and into the United
States. Chronic instability and civil war triggered smaller waves
of refugees in the '80s and '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The largest numbers of Ethiopians settled in Washington, D.C.,
Los Angeles, and Atlanta. But a small group trickled into Boston,
drawn by its colleges or by family members. Some were students who
had come before 1974. As revolution gripped the country, they
sought political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Tamiru, who manages the Pilgrim Parking garage in Boston, was
attending Boston College at the time. The son of a developer, the
17-year-old who had planned to continue the family business
suddenly found he had no tuition money, no work experience, and no
connection to his new home. He worked as a day laborer for weeks
before finding a job in a restaurant. And he waited patiently, as
many did, for the communists to fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This idea of being a refugee, we just didn't know what hit
us,'' said Tamiru, now 45. ``We all assumed we would study and go
back. It took us years just to accept that we were here.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, they planted roots, spreading out from Boston to
surrounding surburbs. Most who stayed without proper immigration
papers were granted amnesty in 1986. In the past five years,
newcomers have come through a federal lottery program that grants
thousands of visas to different countries each year.
</P>
<P>
   But as they climbed to higher positions and professions, most
Ethiopians told themselves their stay was temporary, and lived on
the wish that return was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
