<SLUG> BC-ELEPHANT-WOMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OUTSIZED LIFE AMONG THE ELEPHANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tallulah walked the well-used paths, trying to track her family
down, snaking her trunk along the ground to sniff as she went.
Occasionally, she would call out and then pause to listen. At the
first response, she dashed through tall grass and was soon in the
thick of her family group. They entwined trunks, trumpeted, and
rumbled in greeting. Tallulah let out ``a resounding rumble of
reunion.''
</P>
<P>
   From her base camp in Kenya's famed Amboseli National Park,
Cynthia Moss has been describing scenes like this for more than a
quarter century. Here, in the shadow of Mount Kilimanjaro, she has
set about recording the daily lives of about 1,600 wild African
elephants.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1972, Moss has perched in a vehicle _ first a Renault,
later a Land Rover _ hour after hour, quietly observing the complex
lives of elephants unfold in what she likens to a tautly plotted
page turner.
</P>
<P>
   She has observed birth and death, power struggles, social
relationships, kidnapping, sex, tragedy, and joy (``It may not be
similar to human joy or even comparable, but it is elephantine joy
and it plays a very important part in their whole social system'').
She has outlined family structure, attachments, gender differences,
and behavioral complexity. Through books such as ``Elephant
Memories'' and ``Echo of the Elephants,'' she has taught readers
about ``greeting ceremonies,'' ``mating pandemonium,'' ``sneaky
copulators,'' and the loose-limbed, carefree movement called
``floppy running.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the breadth of her scientific inquiry, Moss, 58, does
not possess a piece of parchment declaring her a scientist.
According to the book ``Elephant Woman,'' by Laurence Pringle, her
lack of scientific degrees renders her ineligible for some grants,
though much of her work is funded by the African Wildlife
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Ossining, N.Y., Moss was always surrounded by cats
and dogs and horses. Yet, after graduating from Smith College, she
started her professional life as a journalist for Newsweek magazine
in Manhattan. Within a few years, however, she reports, her
feelings for nature were reawakened, and a trip to Africa forever
changed her life. There, among elephants, lions, zebra, and
giraffe, she had an overwhelming sense that she was home.
</P>
<P>
   Degree or no degree, Moss has harnessed her unwavering
fascination to produce the longest, most detailed study of wild
elephants ever _ a feat that she downplays. ``I've only watched
those elephants for 27 years _ half a lifetime of one of these
animals,'' she says by phone from New York during a US lecture
tour. ``I'm really just beginning to scratch the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's a pretty ample surface. Research from her camp has
yielded a number of discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   With other colleagues, Moss has begun to crack the code of
elephant communication.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants have a vast repertoire of vocalizations, some too low
for the human ear to detect. Using sensitive recording equipment,
Moss and Katy Payne, an acoustic biologist, have begun to eavesdrop
on these ``rumble'' communiques. In the wild, elephants amble over
vast ranges but stay in touch with infrasound, which can roll
around trees and rocks and travel as far as 6 miles. This explains
the coordinated movements of elephants, which had puzzled
researchers for years.
</P>
<P>
   Another great mystery was something called ``musth.'' So little
was known of this strange and powerful hormonal cycle, scientists
weren't even sure African bull elephants experienced it. The
Amboseli camp not only proved that they do, but its observations
are also providing intriguing details. When these bulls get tanked
up on testosterone, Moss has observed, they are feared by other
males yet welcomed by receptive females and their cheerleading
families.
</P>
<P>
   When in musth, these big bulls, who can weigh in at 12,000
pounds, carry themselves differently. Their silhouettes change.
They leak fluids from temporal glands, and they dribble urine
constantly. They reek of virility. ``When he arrived upwind of us,
his smell almost knocked us sideways. It was a pungent, sharp,
somewhat musky scent which I had grown rather partial to,'' Moss
wrote of one in ``Echo of the Elephants.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss's long-term study has injected color and texture into a
previously sketchy portrait of the world's largest land animals. In
addition, her books and contribution to TV films, such as PBS's
``Echo of the Elephants,'' provide an intimate glimpse of the lives
of elephants. We now know how they live on a day-to-day basis.
</P>
<P>
   And so much of that life depends on the wise old matriarch _ the
eldest females of a species that can live to 70. All the elephants
in her group depend on her to negotiate two kinds of terrain: the
land, with its ever-shifting resources; and a complicated social
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Basic social units _ families _ consist of adult females and
their offspring of both genders. And those families are small parts
of a larger mosaic of clans and other communities. Males go off
sometime after the age of 10, spending time alone or joining loose
(and we mean this in all senses) bachelor groups.
</P>
<P>
   Moss's study site in Amboseli has allowed her to observe
elephants whose lives are more secure and stable than those of many
other populations. Tourists, scientists, and the Masai, who seldom
hunt wildlife, have warded off the heavy poaching other areas
experienced _ between 1973 and 1989, 85 percent of Kenya's
elephants were slaughtered for their ivory.
</P>
<P>
   A year-round water supply _ provided by the runoff from the
snows of Kilimanjaro _ enlivens the dusty alkali park with veins of
greenery and salad bowl swamps, keeping the elephants close.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is this fantastic body of knowledge that I'm most proud
of,'' Moss says, as she credits colleagues and field assistants.
``Elephants have the most extensive network of relationships of any
land mammal, and maybe any mammal, but we just don't know enough
about the whales and dolphins yet to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss could return to school for that piece of paper that
declares her a scientist. Although Cambridge University has invited
her to do just that, she has never wanted to take time out from
watching elephants. And while she has spent so much of her life
studying these family-oriented animals, she has never found time to
start her own family.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Moss has felt compelled to leave camp to bring a
message of elephant conservation to the world. She is attempting to
establish an endowment to secure the future for the Amboseli
elephants.
</P>
<P>
   In this time of shrinking habitats, is she optimistic? ``I am
hopeful for certain populations, especially those in areas not
suitable for humans. I'm hopeful that they can survive well into
the 22d century.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss is also battling to save the elephant's ancient way of
life. In Amboseli today, elephants are still able to follow
migration routes that their ancestors did 500 years ago. Here they
can be at their complex best. And that's what intrigues this
graduate of the wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elephants are always mysterious,'' Moss says. ``They are
always revealing new things. And they will always puzzle me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
