   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans four pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE (Brussels) _ Germany offers a peace plan as the
European Union holds a summit on Kosovo. The plan has key role for
the United Nations and Kofi Annan, its secretary-general, who is
attending the meeting. The plan calls for a halt in air strikes if
Yugoslavia withdraws its forces from Kosovo. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ A military analysis: NATO commanders
fear that even if the Yugoslav troops pull out, Arkan, the
notorious Serbian paramilitary leader, and others will keep
terrorizing Albanians. This, in turn, raises the question of using
ground forces to counter that threat. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Military developments on Kosovo
from Washington. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ A news-feature on the
mood of the Serb capital and the funeral of slain journalist. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BALKANS (Sarajevo, Bosnia) _ A larger look at the role of
NATO bombing and whether it undermines the effort of the U.S. and
its European allies to achieve peace and stability in the Balkans.
By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje, Macedonia) _ An interview with the
macedonian prime minister, Ljupco Georgievski.
