<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7778 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DATA-COMPANIES-ART-BO     04-14 1478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATA-COMPANIES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDLESS STREAM OF DATA SPAWNS COMPUTER-STORAGE FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   American industry is awash in computer data.
</P>
<P>
   From the burgeoning electronic commerce industry to today's
complex software to the millions of e-mail messages exchanged
daily, corporations say the volume of data is growing 50 to 100
percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are bursting at the seams with trillions of bits of
critical data that must be stored _ some in duplicate and
triplicate _ and managed, in branch offices, data centers, and
corporate headquarters around the world.
</P>
<P>
   This struggle to keep track of the seemingly endless flow of
data has created a booming business for EMC Corp. of Hopkinton,
Mass., the nation's largest independent disk storage company, as
well as for other leading hardware suppliers such as IBM Corp., the
Clariion division of Data General Corp. in Southborough, Mass.,
Seagate Technology, and Storage Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Now it has spawned a new generation of software and services
companies providing ways for corporations to monitor and manage
their data, back up and protect it, find and fix disk-storage
bottlenecks, and warn desktop computer users to clean out their
hard drives before they run out of space.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is home to a number of these new storage
start-ups, some launched by former employees of EMC and Data
General and some with initial investments coming from former EMC
top management.
</P>
<P>
   For investors, the attraction is the huge market potential. For
every dollar a company spends storing one megabyte of data on a
computer hard drive, it spends more than $4 on software, services,
and personnel to manage the information.
</P>
<P>
   According to research firm Dataquest, storage resource
management _ the monitoring and tracking of the physical location
of a company's data _ is expected to be a $1.2 billion market by
2002, up from just $210 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette Corp., for example, spends nearly one-third of its
computer systems hardware budget on new disk storage systems,
according to Patrick Zilvitis, chief information officer of the
Boston-based consumer products company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest growth in information comes from our transactions
systems where, for example, our Mach3 product is tracked from
manufacturing to customer order and collection of cash and
everything in between,'' said Zilvitis. ``All the pieces are bits
of data that have to be turned into information and then into
knowledge to run the business better. Data is a company's jewels.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a page from the telephone industry, Peter Bell is
offering corporate America an alternative to the hefty purchases of
data storage and related services. He wants to rent or lease data
storage services to corporations for a monthly fee by creating a
nationwide network of regional storage farms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as businesses don't own the telephone switches or the
electric power generators to keep the lights on because it is
easier and cheaper to buy these services from utility suppliers,
why not do the same for data storage?'' said Bell, president of
StorageNetworks Inc. of Wellesley Hills.
</P>
<P>
   StorageNetworks, which expects to raise $50 million in venture
capital this fall, is perhaps the most ambitious of the growing
group of small companies addressing data-storage issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bell and chief technology officer William Miller cofounded
StorageNetworks last summer with $10 million: $8 million in venture
capital from Greylock Management and Sigma Partners, and $2 million
from Roger Marino, a cofounder of EMC Corp., where Bell spent 10
years in marketing, operations, and sales.
</P>
<P>
   So far StorageNetworks has built its first disk storage farm,
known as a point of presence (POP), in Houston, catering to four
companies in the oil and gas industry. To ensure the data arrives
quickly, StorageNetworks builds a high-speed fiber-optic link _
called a Fibre Channel _ between its POP and each customer's data
center.
</P>
<P>
   By this summer the company plans to open similar data storage
farms in Somerville, to serve the Boston market, and in Weehauken,
N.J. and Brooklyn, N.Y., to handle the New York financial services
market.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said StorageNetworks revenues should reach close to $5
million this year, quadrupling to around $20 million in 2000.
Forrester Research of Cambridge, Mass. estimated that storage
outsourcing will become a $500 million-a-year business by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Astrum Software Corp. of Charlestown, Mass. has created a
program it says helps Ford Motor Co. and others monitor the
disk-storage usage at each PC and computer server within a
department. The software keeps track of PC and server storage
systems rapidly filling up with data and sends out messages to
prevent a system crash. It can also automatically purge old data
from networked PCs and servers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies with many personal computers know their users have
stored lots of electronic mail messages, Internet downloads, and
other information that is simply old data,'' said Robert Infantino,
who formed the five-person company with $250,000 of his own money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting employees to clean out their computer's hard disks is
a big problem, as some companies don't have formal policies. And
some users don't know how to save data to a floppy disk.''
</P>
<P>
   At Boston University, Astrum's software is used in the
biochemistry department to manage storage and monitor potential
e-mail problems, such as a user storing too many messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have 150 users who, on occasion, get carried away storing
huge files,'' said Anthony Abruzzese, the department's network
administrator. ``Sometimes I have to say, `Get your files off, or
I'm going to get them off for you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   HighGround Systems of Marlborough, Mass. provides storage
research management software and services at the corporate level,
with customers from the Walt Disney Co. to Kmart Corp. The nearly
four-year-old company has raised more than $20 million and has
licensed part of its technology to Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming months disk storage systems will be further
stressed, said HighGround marketing vice president Thomas. H. Rose,
as companies launch year 2000 compliance testing to ensure that all
programs work properly when the clock strikes midnight on Jan. 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   And while many large corporations routinely back up their data
each night, several new companies such as Connected Corp. of
Framingham, Mass. are developing products that will do it more
efficiently, particularly for people who travel and use laptop
computers.
</P>
<P>
   David Cane launched the company after his wife lost more than 60
pages of her doctoral thesis when her computer's hard drive
malfunctioned. She failed to routinely back up the data on floppy
disks. So Cane created an automated backup service that allows
laptop computer users with a PC modem and a standard telephone
connection to back up their internal hard drive each evening.
Several corporations, including Cisco Systems Inc. of San Jose,
Calif., have signed up their traveling employees to use the
service, which costs from $19.95 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The backup process takes less than a couple of minutes, and it
allows the road warrior to also check e-mail,'' said Glenn Gaudet,
Connected's director of product marketing.
</P>
<P>
   On a much larger scale, Network Integrity Inc. of Marlborough is
offering software that enables companies to more easily back up
their software during the day rather than at night. The software,
after initially copying an entire data base, records only the
changes made during the day. This approach, the company says,
reduces labor and equipment costs.
</P>
<P>
   As promising as the storage management and backup business is,
some older storage companies have run into problems after soaring
to an early success. Storage Computer Corp. of Nashua, N.H., which
enjoyed spectacular growth from 1993 to 1997, is now trying to
rebuld after some of its disk subsystems and software ran into
major quality control problems in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last year sales dropped to $17 million _ less than half the $37
million it reported in 1997 _ as the company lost $10.9 million, or
97 cents a share. In 1997, Storage Computer earned nearly $3.6
million, or 33 cents a share. And the company's stock, which had
traded at nearly 20 a share two years ago, now trades at under 2 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disks we bought from a company failed and some customers
lost their data,'' said Ted Goodlander, president of Storage
Computer, stressing the company has switched suppliers and should
become profitable again this quarter. ``The market is still very
strong and I believe we will recover.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
