<HEADLINE>
SHOOTOUT SHOULD BE SHOT DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shootout to decide drawn matches was initiated in the North
American Soccer League in 1977. Similar to hockey's penalty shot,
the shootout was among the gimmicks, such as a 35-yard offside line
and pyrotechnic goal celebrations, designed to glamorize soccer.
</P>
<P>
   FIFA did not approve of the shootout, in which the attacker has
five seconds to shoot from 35 yards and the goalkeeper can move off
his line, and no top level league seriously considered adopting it
until Major League Soccer revived it in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, FIFA made two subtle changes. The value of a victory
was increased to 3 points and goalkeepers were prevented from
handling backpasses. The adjustments were made late in the day, but
now soccer has regained its fashionable world image and games have
become fast-paced spectacles. Even in Italy, Serie A games are wide
open, caution thrown to the wind.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the shootout, then, is its superfluousness. As
a gimmick to attract attention, it has been made obsolete by the
awarding of 3 points for victories. And this is the main objection
to the shootout during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Since no other country uses the shootout, it is considered a
novelty. But the shootout is losing its charm because of
overexposure. MLS officials should seriously consider either
abolishing the shootout or relegating it to a lower division. Or,
they could limit its use to the playoffs, when the stakes are
greater and a winner is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Wynalda was injured in a shootout last season and never
fully recovered for the World Cup. Cobi Jones had a close call for
Los Angeles last week. Players are soon going to realize the
shootout is not worth risking injury for a single point. And MLS
should not place its assets at risk for the sake of novelty,
especially when the pace of the game is accelerating at a rate that
should satisfy even the most obtuse observers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ajax down the drain?
</P>
<P>
   Ajax's disappointing results continued with a 4-1 loss to
Cambuur Leeuwaarden, a team that includes US national team defender
Gregg Berhalter. Ajax, which has won four of the last five
Eredivisie championships, is on the verge of failing to qualify for
European Cup competition and is facing a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Several players have accompanied Louis Van Gaal, who coached
Ajax to the 1995 European Champions Cup title, to Barcelona and the
famed development program is not producing as in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gaal received derisive whistles during a recent tribute
match to honor past greats such as Johan Cruyff and Marco Van
Basten. Ajax supporters are understandably upset that Van Gaal
continues to take away their players. Barcelona's Ajax colony will
increase to seven when Jari Litmanen joins next year.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Ajax is breaking with the past, partially in
reaction to the Jean-Marc Bosman Ruling, the European Court of
Justice decision that opened the way to free agency. The club built
the Amsterdam Arena to replace the 19,000-seat De Meer Stadium, and
now is branching out by investing in satellite clubs, including one
in Capetown, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The club's plans might be overly ambitious and the directors
could have underestimated supporters' resistance to the
predominantly foreign composition of the team. But Ajax is forging
ahead, and the next step is a tour that will include a July 21
exhibition against the Revolution at Foxboro Stadium. Mixed in
among the Brazilian, Danish, Georgian, Nigerian, Russian, and Dutch
players will be an American _ John O'Brien, a midfielder whose
family roots extend to Boston. O'Brien is currently on loan to
Utrecht but is expected to rejoin Ajax next season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barcelona reigning
</P>
<P>
   Real Madrid coach John Benjamin Toshack could only feel
``humiliated'' after his team was routed by Celta, 5-1, in Vigo.
Real Madrid fell 10 points behind first-place Barcelona and
relinquished its title hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Celta moved into second place, 7 points behind. The
result indicated the wide-open play of the Spanish Liga. Celta is
the country's westernmost club, named for the Galician region's
Celtic tradition, and ``Gallegos'' are often considered outcasts by
Barcelona and Madrid. But Celta has restored pride to the area with
an effective mixture of players. Mazinho, who played for Brazil in
the 1990 World Cup and struck out in Italy, has been a driving
force in midfield. Russians Valeri Karpin and Alexandre Mostovoi
and the Israeli Haim Revivo were especially effective against Real
Madrid, and Bulgarian Luboslav Penev scored three goals.
</P>
<P>
   Predrag Mijatovic returned as a reserve for Real Madrid after a
one-game protest against NATO bombing in Yugoslavia that cost him 5
million pesetas.
</P>
<P>
   Other Serbian players made anti-war statements in Italy's Serie
A. Most players displayed shirts promoting aid to refugees from
Kosovo, but Lazio's Sinisa Mihailjovic's shirt read, ``Peace, no
war.'' Mihailjovic was red-carded late in the game after clashing
with Roma's Brazilian striker, Paulo Sergio, in a 3-1 loss. Lazio
holds a 4-point lead over Milan in Serie A.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Home-grown talent
</P>
<P>
   The American Soccer League, which existed from 1921-31 before
falling victim to internal strife and the Depression, was dominated
by foreign players, but eventually produced top American players
also.
</P>
<P>
   Barney Battles, who developed with the Boston Celtics (a soccer
team long before the basketball team), set a still-standing club
record of 44 goals in a season for Hearts of Midlothian in
Scotland. Billy Gonsalves, who made his reputation with Lusitania
Recreation in East Cambridge, started in the 1930 World Cup at age
21 and refused offers from Brazilian and Italian clubs to stay in
the US. In recently-released ratings by the International Football
Historians and Statisticians, Gonsalves was ranked the sixth-best
player in the history of the CONCACAF region, the only US-born
player in the top 11.
</P>
<P>
   The ASL also had the first African athlete to compete for a New
England pro team, Tewfik Abdallah, an Egyptian who played 80 games
at inside forward for Providence, Fall River, and Hartford.
Abdallah, nicknamed ``Toothpick,'' played for Derby County and
Hartlepool (England), Cowdenbeath (Scotland), and Brigend (Wales).
The next prominent African athlete in the area would be Eusebio,
the Mozambican-Portuguese striker who joined the Boston Minutemen
in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rocha ready to run
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Rocha, who was released after a dispute with Revolution
player-coach Walter Zenga, joined the Boston Bulldogs of the
second-division A League. Rocha will be available for the Bulldogs'
season opener Friday at Jacksonville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to get my fitness and play,'' Rocha said. ``What's
behind me is behind me and I don't want to say anything about it.
I'm still a young player and my goal is to play and learn and get
better as a player, and continue to follow my dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocha scored four goals in six games for the Worcester Wildfire
last year and was scoreless as a Revolution reserve.
</P>
</TEXT>
