<HEADER>
A7782 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ETHIOPIAN-CHURCH-2ND &LR;      04-14 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIAN-CHURCH-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 CAMBRIDGE, Mass.: ... was imminent.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Then came children. Investments. Businesses. Slow success. By
1991, when the Marxist government fell, many found their US ties
outweighed memories of a land now plagued by civil war and a new,
equally volatile ethnic-based government.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, they found themselves ill-equipped for life here.
Fixated on each political ripple back home, they had paid little
attention to community-building. Independent by nature, they had
not plugged into networks with other immigrant groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``People thought it would be as it was 20 years ago, but we have
all changed,'' said Binyam Tamene, who runs the Ethiopian Community
Mutual Assistance Association. ``If we are not going back, then who
are we? What kind of community do we want? We are just now
exploring how to know ourselves in this society.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet as he advocates unity from a tiny, gray office in Central
Square, Tamene himself has become one of the community's most
divisive figures. While he says the center and radio program he
runs remain apolitical, others _ including St. Michael's church
leaders _ say Tamene has polarized Ethiopians, hand-picking his own
board and ignoring community input into the center.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a community of exiles thirsty for democracy's freedoms
and deeply suspicious of any who would call themselves leader,
quiet conflicts continue to play out in the mirror image of
Ethiopia's own turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One Sunday, in the fall of 1992, the congregation of St.
Michael's nearly came to blows.
</P>
<P>
   Half a world away, Ethiopian rebel forces had come to power,
toppling the Marxist regime and replacing the church's highest
office, its patriarch, with a new, state-appointed figure.
</P>
<P>
   Divided over his legitimacy, a tense, shoving congregation
crowded outside the doors of St. Peter's, each side demanding the
other be thrown out. When the doors opened, they prayed under the
watch of police.
</P>
<P>
   The fight split one flock into two _ St. Michael's and St.
Mary's, which now worships in the South End. It was a painful
reminder that the church, long a refuge from political strife,
could also be engulfed by it. And it underscored a contradiction
facing many immigrants from developing nations: Even as they
embrace democracy, they find themselves reverting to the only
political models they have ever known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the experience of revolution and socialism has
affected many Ethiopians,'' said Ephraim Isaac, who heads the
Institute for Semitic Studies at Princeton University and lived in
Boston for 15 years. ``Those ideas of revolution have sown seeds of
dissension among the people.''
</P>
<P>
   The dissension sapped energy, members, and resources from a
community already dreaming of its own church. But over time, St.
Michael's grew to one of the largest Orthodox congregations in the
Northeast. In 1997, a visit from a bishop jump-started the search,
drawing $40,000 in pledges.
</P>
<P>
   But money was only the first of many obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   A building in Harvard Square won strong congregation approval,
but its price tag was too high, and leaders dismissed it.
Properties in suburban Boston were considered. But the community
resisted, saying transportation for many would be difficult, if not
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   For a people raised in a land where the state has always funded
churches, the slow progress has frustrated many.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who say, `You have $100,000. Why don't you
have a church?' '' said Solomon Lemma, a church committee member.
``But they don't know about zoning, about parking. They don't
completely understand what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   As church leaders tried to reassure their members, and the
wounds of a broken church began to close, dissension resurfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Groups of Ethiopians began to challenge Tamene's authority over
the community center. This time, with state and federal funding for
the nonprofit center at stake, suspicions of abuse grew, and
mounting criticism began to echo Ethiopia's upheavals _ charging
Tamene with abusing his power and stifling opposition. Tamene
maintained he was fulfilling his vow to keep the center apolitical.
</P>
<P>
   The rebellion came to a head at a community meeting in April,
1997: In a sweeping vote, more than 150 Ethiopians elected a new
board, ousting Tamene and the board. Tamene ruled the elections
illegal, triggering the community's second round of litigation in
five years. After two years, the conflict remains unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   For Tamene, the charges of exploitation only underscore the
lessons Ethiopians still must learn about their place here.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't always have the experience of nonprofit
institutions and how they work,'' he said. ``These are things the
community has to open itself up to and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   As the dispute festers, those on both sides hang their prayers
for resolution and new unity on a church _ legacy of every
Ethiopian, and healer of past divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sad what is happening now, but I believe the community,
and the church, will unfold no matter what,'' said Mehretu
HaileGiorgis, church committee chairman. ``The church is the place
where the markers in our lives are performed, from baptism to
remembrances of those who have passed. And in times of crisis, it
is the place where we go to seek salvation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
