<HEADLINE>
ALL SYSTEMS GO FOR GODOLPHIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes 6 top derby contenders text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It appears that Godolphin, the international stable owned by
Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum of Dubai, will send a powerful two-horse
entry of Aljabr and Worldly Manner to Churchill Downs in the
outfit's first attempt to capture the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Aljabr, a son of Storm Cat, assured himself a trip when he won
the second trial race that Godolphin held among its own horses last
Thursday at Nad Al Sheba Racecourse. Worldly Manner, a son of
Riverman, won the first trial March 21 with Aljabr second, and did
so well that Godolphin did not find it necessary to race him in the
second trial.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Aljabr took the trial by a neck over Mitchigan,
with five second-stringers trailing far behind. Aljabr, who was
ridden by Frankie Dettori, was timed in 1:48 1/5 over the distance,
which was just short of a mile and one-eighth. A winner of three
races in Europe as a 2-year-old, Aljabr is obviously talented.
Mitchigan, who was bred in Ireland, had won both of his races in
Europe and was considered s worthy opponent for Aljabr, although
Mitchigan is not nominated to the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very pleased with Aljabr and the way he went about his
business,'' said Simon Crisford, Godolphin racing manager. ``He
will have benefited a lot from this second trial as he needed more
experience racing on sand. We were very happy with the way he
finished, and the next steppingstone will be the Kentucky Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Worldly Manner, ridden by Jerry Bailey (in Dubai for the World
Cup), defeated Aljabr by a length in the first trial at the same
distance. Worldly Manner, who won the Del Mar Futurity when trained
by Bob Baffert, was purchased by the Sheikh for $5 million from
John and Betty Mabee. ``Worldly Manner doesn't need another race,''
said Crisford. ``He's on the top of his game at the moment and in
tremendous condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Godolphin also spent $3 million to purchase Comeonmom after he
won the Remsen at Aqueduct last year. But the son of Jolie's Halo
never caught up to his fellow 3-year-olds. ``We were a little bit
diappointed with him,'' said Crisford. ``He's not working as well
as we hoped he would. We've decided not to push him; so,
effectively, we're ruling him out of the Triple Crown.''
</P>
<P>
   The 125th Kentucky Derby will be run May 1. Godolphin plans to
fly a dozen horses, the other 10 to run in various races at
Churchill Downs, from Dubai to the United States in a private
charter, with a stopover in Shannon, Ireland, next Monday. The
horses will spend 48 hours in quarantine at Keeneland and then be
vanned to Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela cleared
</P>
<P>
   An armed robbery charge against Pat Valenzuela, who rode Sunday
Silence to victory in the 1989 Kentucky Derby, was dismissed in Los
Angeles County Superior Court last Friday. Valenzuela had been
charged with robbing a cab driver of $150 at gunpoint near Santa
Anita in February. ``There was no evidence,'' said attorney Donald
Calabria, who represented Valenzuela. ``Pat could not be identified
in court as the one involved. Pat has had trouble in the past, but
this wasn't part of that pattern. It was an out-and-out case of
mistaken identity.'' Valenzuela, 36, has been troubled by substance
abuse and has not ridden since 1997. He hopes to mount a comeback
but must complete rehabilitation for a knee injury before he
attempts to ride again . . . Julie Krone, 35, the winningest female
jockey with 3,541 victories, announced her retirement last
Thursday. She will ride Desert Demon Sunday in the Lone Star Derby
and will continue on only if Desert Demon goes to the Kentucky
Derby. Krone, who was hospitalized several times after taking
spills on the track, recently came back from a knee fracture to
enjoy a fine meeting at Fair Grounds, winning 76 races to finish
third. ``I'd rather go out on top both emotionally and
physically,'' she said. ``I enjoy riding full time, but it has
become a little too much for my ankles and knees. There is no
chance of me riding again after the 18th (other than the Derby).''
Krone, who hopes to work as a television commentator, is the only
woman to have won a Triple Crown race, tallying with Colonial
Affair in the 1993 Belmont Stakes, and she rode five winners on one
card at Saratoga Aug. 23 of the same year, when she was at the top
of her game . . . Suffolk Downs will give away a $1,000 wager on
the $25,000 Helena Stakes, the feature race of the Patriots Day
card. The bet will be awarded by random drawing and you must be
present to win.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Polishing up `Silver'
</P>
<P>
   Baffert is hard at work trying to return 1997 Derby winner
Silver Charm to peak form. After the big gray bled and finished up
the track in the Dubai World Cup, Baffert went back to the drawing
board and put blinkers on Silver Charm for a workout at Santa Anita
last Friday. Silver Charm, a 5-year-old, has not worn blinkers
since finishing second in his first race in August 1996. Blinkers
help a horse keep his mind on business, and that's what Silver
Charm, who has lost his last three starts, might need to do to
improve . . . Straight Man, a promising 3-year-old for Baffert, ran
poorly in the Gallery Furniture.com Stakes at Turfway. But he'll
get another chance in the Lexington at Keeneland Sunday after
working five furlongs in 1:00 at Churchill Wednesday. He'll be
joined by Doneraile Court, a $1 million yearling trained by Nick
Zito, who worked five panels in 1:02 at Keeneland last week . . .
Reraise, last year's Eclipse Award winning sprinter, made a
triumphant return with an easy score in the Count Fleet Sprint at
Oaklawn Thursday. Reraise, who had not raced since winning the $1
million Breeders' Cup Sprint at Churchill in November, zipped six
furlongs in 1:08 2/5 under Corey Nakatani, winning by nearly three
lengths. ``We came here because that timing and the money was
right, and he's a good shipper,'' said trainer Craig Dollase, who
is based in California.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
