<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNNY ADVICE FOR SENIORS, OR JUST MOONSHINE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)``Now a promise made is a debt unpaid, and the trail has
its own stern code.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Service
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cremation of Sam McGhee'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just one week ago I wrote: ``Some Harvard quack is pushing a
book called `Living to 100,' which I plan to ridicule under
separate cover.'' Quicker than you can say anti-aging miracle
compound dehydroepiandrosterone, I received a letter from Margaret
Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Careful who you call `quack'!'' Mrs. Simmons warned me. A
longtime friend of the quack's coauthor, Margery Silver, Simmons
wrote: ``Read the book and then swallow your smart-mouth remark!''
</P>
<P>
   Hot on the heels of Simmons's snail-mailed remark came this
e-missive from Dr. Thomas Perls: ``Dear Alex, I guess I am the
quack you referred to today. Please let me set you straight. . .
.'' Perls is indeed the principal author of ``Living to 100,'' and
a professor at the Harvard Medical School. To paraphrase, Perls
said I unfairly conflated his views with the ``seductive claims and
promises of hucksters seeking to capitalize on the age explosion.''
(The quote is from his book.) ``I have actually taken a very strong
stand in being a voice of moderation in this world of anti-aging
fads and promises of getting people to 200 or to 100 for that
matter,'' he wrote me.
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``I am pro-aging not anti-aging. I believe the
trick is not staying young, but rather, aging well. Please don't
trash me and my book. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   After promising to buy Perls's book, I fired back this salvo:
``You seem to indulge a rather epigrammatic approach to a very
serious, indeed a mortal issue, e.g. `Aging is an opportunity';
`the older you get, the healthier you've been.' Not to mention the
title of your book, and the Life Expectancy Calculator you include
with it. Who are you trying to kid? This is `medicine' in the grand
style of TV sports doc Bob Arnot (author of `The Breast Cancer
Prevention Diet'), who's willing to coin money selling women on the
idiotic notion that, by consuming more flax seed, they will avoid
breast cancer. How cynical.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynical? The trademarked Life Expectancy Calculator _ cynical?
More like inane. Try it yourself at www.livingto100.com. As I
pointed out to Perls, once you put your foot in this stream, the
water has moved on. For instance, as a former smoker, I had always
been interested in the state of my lungs. For many years, doctors
believed that the body recovers from the effects of smoking after
seven years without cigarettes. But a study released just last week
on the perils of youth smoking demolishes that conventional wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little ungracious of me to try to come between Dr. Perls
and his payday. Deep down, I wish that he and his coauthors might
have asked: Should you want to live to 100? Why? In Perls's
delightful centenarian fantasyland, interview subjects like
102-year-old Tom Spear play 18 holes of golf three times a week; he
consistently shoots ``15 strokes under his age.'' Lucy Boring,
``despite some memory loss,'' plays winning bridge at age 109.
</P>
<P>
   This is all very nice. But the cruel fact is that most men and
women over 65 are burdened with the maladies and concerns of old
age. Dr. Perls wishes it were not so, and his book purports to
contain useful tips on aging healthily: Floss after meals! Keep a
positive attitude! etc. etc.
</P>
<P>
   I yield the last word to Dr. Perls:
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to show people, using centenarians as an example, that
life after 65 can be tremendously fruitful, with years of
opportunities and possibilities. I can see why you might feel
differently, but that is the attitude we are trying to change.
People don't have to look at aging as a terrible thing. With a more
proactive approach it really can be an opportunity. . . . We just
can't be lazy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't say (make lifestyle changes) and you will live to
100. . . . We say, do these things because you will add healthy
years to your life and it is worth the effort. . . . There is
nothing free-lunch about our book. Just an optimistic and
empowering point of view about aging.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
