<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW MOVIE MAKES A CASE THAT SATIRE ISN'T DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- Before the debut of his satire series on the
Bravo cable network, Michael Moore complained to Scott Simon on
National Public Radio. ``Satire has been forgotten and millions of
Americans are ironically illiterate,'' he said. ``The Brits, the
French, the Canadians get satire, but Americans don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Satire depends on wit. Moore's latest ambush-interview saga
relies on stunts. Because Washington, D.C., is the capital of
self-parody, satirizing politics is too easy. Moore's Puritan
pecksniffs can not compete with the pack of pharisees assembled by
Kenneth W. Starr.
</P>
<P>
   If Moore's ``The Awful Truth'' were a play, it would follow what
George S. Kaufman, the sardonic playwright, predicted in the 1930s:
``Satire is what closes on Saturday night.''
</P>
<P>
   What about satirizing television itself? Nobody did it better
than Mary Tyler Moore in the 1970s. The movie ``EDtv'' succeeds on
the model enunciated by the eminent writer of the American
Southwest, Paul Horgan: ``The object of our satire is the other
face of our love.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Moore is one of the familiar cameos in ``EDtv,'' a
comedy which some film critics have unflatteringly compared to last
year's fable of television, ``The Truman Show,'' which took itself
as seriously as the critics did.
</P>
<P>
   Director Ron Howard's cast is so television-rooted that viewers
can only chuckle, not seethe. Ellen DeGeneres as a cynical network
executive? Not our winsome Ellen. Her boss, Rob Reiner, is both
vapid and villainous, having reached the top after starting ``as an
associate producer on `Good Morning Fresno.' '' He is still as
cuddly as Meathead was in ``All in the Family.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody Harrelson's character may have lingered at too many last
calls at ``Cheers,'' but he is as beguiling as Martin Landau,
operating gear slightly updated from his days on ``Mission:
Impossible.'' Swiping several scenes is a subdued Dharma of
``Dharma and Greg,'' Jenna Elfman, the Lucille Ball of the 21st
century if the network suits get out of her way.
</P>
<P>
   Ed of ``EDtv'' is Matthew McConaughey, not a television actor,
but suited to the role of Everyman as star of sitcom and soap
opera, a human life lived under a 24-hour television stakeout. The
characterizations are winning, even if the plot is predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Sudden celebrity was a staple of screwball comedy. ``EDtv''
balances Frank Capra's gee-whiz earnestness in ``Meet John Doe''
with the mordant mockery of Ben Hecht in ``Nothing Sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   ``EDtv'' is filmed in San Francisco, where a sign of its appeal
can be found on Grant Avenue. The video store where the McConaughey
character works is now busier, attracting the kind of crowds that
chug-a-lugged at ``Cheers'' in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's heart is in Mayberry, the North Carolina town where
Howard, the director, grew up as ``Opie,'' the sheriff's son in
``The Andy Griffith Show.'' In 1957, before his television career,
Andy Griffith starred in one of the first movie satires about
television, ``A Face in the Crowd,'' written by Budd Schulberg and
directed by Elia Kazan. As Lonesome Rhodes, a sudden celebrity
turned influential lout, he utters the fearful mantra of television
that echoed in Paddy Chayefsky's ``Network'' 20 years later: ``All
them millions of people believing in me. Doing what I tell them to.
It scares me.''
</P>
<P>
   Television does not scare Howard, or his audience. His
director's path has traveled widely in a Capraesque village of hope
and fantasy. ``Splash'' and ``Cocoon'' gurgle with the warm milk of
coziness, not the vinegar of satire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Satire flourishes in a stable society and presupposes
homogenous moral standards,'' Evelyn Waugh once wrote. Remote
controls and multiple channels explain why defiantly stiff animated
features lose their fizz. As George Frazier might have said,
whatever happened to Beavis and Butthead? But don't disturb them on
my account. South me no Parks and Bart me no Simpsons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
