<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7796 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLEGE-SAVINGS15-COX     04-14 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-SAVINGS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PARENTS STILL BEHIND IN RACE FOR COLLEGE SAVINGS
 &HT;    480&AMP;add. With COLLEGE-DATA.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most parents are saving too little, and too
inefficiently, for their children's college education, the College
Savings Plans Network warned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 1,000 parents of school-age children in 34 states
found that about 49 percent of the parents said they were trying to
save more than $10,000 for college costs, but 24 percent had lower
goals and 27 percent weren't saving anything at all.
</P>
<P>
   Savings of less than $10,000 could be gobbled up very early in a
student's college career. The College Board estimates that the
average budget for an undergraduate runs $6,445 a year for a
commuter at a public two-year college, $10,458 for a residential
student at a public four-year college, and $22,533 a year for a
resident at a private four-year college. Those sums include
tuition, fees, room and board, transportation, books and other
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Of parents who told the survey they were saving something,
nearly half put all or some of the money in passbook savings
accounts, which pay interest at rates lower than recent annual
increases in college costs of 4 to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passbook savings plans are terrific products for certain
savings objectives, but they're the wrong instrument for long-term
savings for future college costs,'' said Mississippi's Treasurer
Marshall Bennett, chairman of the network, which is sponsored by
the National Association of State Treasurers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do traditional savings accounts lose market value as
they fail to keep up with college inflation, they are so easily
accessible that families are tempted to reach in and take them out
for other expenses,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Other common choices were mutual funds (37 percent), U.S.
savings bonds (16 percent) and life insurance (7 percent). Only 4
percent said they obtained the tax advantages of state-sponsored
plans.
</P>
<P>
   In those plans, earnings on deposits are not subject to state
taxes until they are withdrawn, and some states offer state tax
deductions on deposits as well.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1995, only nine states offered some kind of
college savings program. The number ballooned to 34 last year,
after a federal law also exempted the earnings of all such accounts
from federal taxation until they are withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   The network reported that this year:
</P>
<P>
   _ 19 states offer a prepaid college tuition plan, which
guarantees that the earnings on deposits will at least match the
inflation rate for tuition.
</P>
<P>
   _ 17 states offer a savings plan, sometimes with a guaranteed
rate of return, which will accept deposits large enough to cover
college costs other than tuition.
</P>
<P>
   _ 10 states have enacted savings plans that will be operational
before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The 46 plans are in 44 states, because Massachusetts and
Virginia offer both types.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Bob Graham, D-Fla., and Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who
sponsored the law protecting the accounts from federal taxes until
withdrawal, are pushing this year to exempt the withdrawals as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great majority of states have concluded that prepaid
tuition and college savings plans work,'' Graham said. ``Congress
should defer to their judgment and put the tax code on the side of
educational security.''
</P>
<P>
   With 19 other co-sponsors, Graham and McConnell hope they will
be able to add their provision to a tax bill considered this year
or next year.
</P>
<P>
   Details of each state's plan (including some that don't require
the beneficiary or saver to live in that state) can be obtained
with a toll-free phone call to 1-877-CSPN-4-YOU (1-877-277-6496) or
on the Internet (http://www.collegesavings.org).
</P>
<P>
   The network consists of officials who run state-sponsored
education savings programs with more than $4 billion in deposits in
the accounts of more than 800,000 children.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
