A7803 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      04-14 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING FAST AND LUCE WITH AMERICAN CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, New York University's journalism department
announced the results of a survey ranking the century's 100
greatest works of American journalism. The results were the sort of
grab bag you might expect: a lot of usual suspects (Woodward and
Bernstein's Watergate coverage, No. 3), a healthy dose of
Volvo-left cant (Jonathan Schell's ``The Fate of the Earth,'' No.
59), and, yes, the occasional welcome surprise (Nick Lemann's ``The
Promised Land,'' No. 67; Jane Kramer's ``Europeans,'' No. 91).
</P>
<P>
   Now think of all the J-school students who can sleep soundly at
night, knowing that so many city-room dust-ups have at last been
definitively decided: Herbert Bayard Swope on the Klan (81) vs.
Hunter S. Thompson fearing and loathing on the campaign trail
(100)? ``In Cold Blood'' (22) vs. ``The Executioner's Song'' (72)?
``The Making of the President'' (26) vs. ``The Selling of the
President'' (99)? Casey Kasem, that avatar of connoisseurship
quantified, couldn't have done it any better.
</P>
<P>
   This is a list so uplifting and high-minded it makes you want to
run out and watch ``MacNeill/Lehrer'' reruns (first place went to
John Hersey's ``Hiroshima,'' second place to Rachel Carson's
``Silent Spring''). It's also so self-congratulatory and
muddle-headed it makes you want to raise a glass to the memory of
Spiro Agnew and tell Tina Brown all is forgiven. Certainly, it
would never deign to include something written by a publisher, let
alone a news-slanting, Republican-moneybags one. And therein lies a
problem. For if _ and it's a mighty big if _ one were so misguided
as actually to want to single out the most influential piece of
American journalism to appear since 1900, a very obvious candidate
(which, needless to say, failed to show up on the NYU list) would
be Henry Luce's ``American Century'' editorial from the February
1941 issue of Life. A couple of million people, tops, read it then.
But several billion have had to live with its fallout since.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that it was this nation's destiny to control the
remainder of the century, and by so doing benefit the rest of the
world, to boot, Luce (the man who founded Time, Life, Fortune, and
Sports Illustrated) not only contributed a highly useful phrase to
our cultural vocabulary. He presented a vision of America and its
place on the planet that _ however overblown, however jingoistic _
has stayed central to any understanding of international relations
since. Mock Luce's idea or embrace it, his conception remains as
relevant to our concerns today _ tomorrow, too _ as it did in the
months before Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound exaggerated, but Luce's basic premise is what
writers as eminent, and divergent in outlook, as Paul Kennedy,
Samuel Huntington, and Garry Wills grapple with in World Policy
Journal (spring) and Foreign Affairs (March/April). Kennedy, in the
former publication, is the most explicit, calling his essay ``The
Next American Century?'' As recently as 10 years ago, such a title
would have sounded insane _ as Kennedy's best-known book, ``The
Rise and Fall of the Great Powers,'' would have been the first to
point out. But the collapse of the Soviet Union, along with the
restructuring of the US economy and the Japanese slump, has changed
all that. Once again, the century is looking red, white, and blue _
and maybe the next one, too. Both Huntington and Wills fret about
this (Kennedy, still comfortable with the conclusions of ``Rise and
Fall,'' simply points in the direction of Carthage and Rome).
Huntington fears that we are mistaking what he calls a
uni-multipolar world for a unipolar world _ the United States is
strong, but not that strong _ and that misunderstanding is a
prescription for trouble. Wills's title, ``Bully of the Free
World,'' is pretty much self-explanatory: Red, white and black and
blue would be his Pax americana color scheme. Either way, it's only
fitting both articles should appear in Foreign Affairs, since for
more than 50 years now it's been de facto recording secretary at
American Century board meetings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The last few years have been difficult ones for The New
Republic. It enjoyed the best of times during the '80s and early
'90s with a run of spectacularly opposable presidents (Reagan,
Bush) and spectacularly good editors (Michael Kinsley, Rick
Hertzberg, Andrew Sullivan). But that was then, and not only is
Bill Clinton now, he has been for almost six years. Kinsley's at
Slate, Hertzberg's at The New Yorker, and Sullivan writes a column
for The Sunday Times of London. TNR has had trouble with plagiarism
(Ruth Shalit's), editorial fabrication (Stephen Glass's), and a
very messy firing (of Sullivan's successor, Michael Kelly). Worst
of all, the magazine has simply seemed tired for a long time. Well,
now at least it doesn't look tired. A special double issue (April
26 &AMP; May 3) introduces a complete redesign. It's still recognizably
TNR, but where the overall feel of the old design was an airy
elegance that verged on the finicky, the new TNR has a strong,
assertive look that verges on the overbearing. Body and headline
type have been beefed up. There's now color inside, and a lot more
photos. With its heavy reliance on bold blacks and reds, the
redesign makes TNR look a little bit like Time, of all things
(there's that Henry Luce again).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Okay, you want to see the new ``Star Wars'' movie,``The Phantom
Menace.'' I want to see it. My 82-year-old Uncle Bill who hasn't
gone to a movie in 13 years wants to see it. But the overkill
really has started to enter hyperspace. Vanity Fair (May) puts
Natalie Portman on the cover. She plays Queen Amidala, the
prequel's Princess Leia equivalent (minus the cinnamon-bun braids,
of course). So what if this is VF's third ``Star Wars'' cover since
December. Wired (May) has Mr. Star Wars himself, on the cover,
George Lucas, and that publication at least has the wit to
acknowledge the PR blitz (``Believe the Hype'' is the cover line).
But Vogue (April), of all magazines, Vogue, gets into the act, with
a feature on ``Star Wars Couture,'' photographed by Irving Penn, no
less. How about Cosmopolitan and ``Star Wars Sex Tips''? Cooking
Light and ``Star Wars Calorie Counters''? Commentary and ``Star
Wars Judaism''? And that's just magazines whose name begins with C.
Hey, now that they've told us what the century's top 100
journalistic works are, the NYU J-types might want to tackle the
question of where ``The Phantom Menace'' ranks on the 100
most-hyped events of the century. May the Force be with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
