<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER VICTIM OF DRIVE-BY FISHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a Georges Bank that was treated like a cornfield, dredged
and trawled as if by a farmer's combine, it must be some divine
intervention that the animal that might keep the boats idle at the
barn door is the barndoor skate.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, an international gathering of biologists warned that
this fish is on the verge of extinction in the northwest Atlantic.
It was a critical discovery precisely because the fish, despite
being one of the world's largest marine rays, was not a food fish
(unlike some other species of skate). A flat, winged bottom glider
that can grow up to 3 feet across and 5 feet long with no previous
commercial value, the barndoor skate is a victim of drive-by
fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1950s, the skate's population, as it was caught by cod
fishermen and scallopers, has dropped by 90 percent. ``Clearly
we're not keeping our finger on the sea's pulse,'' said Elliott
Norse, president of the Marine Conservation Biology Institute.
``The drastic decline of the barndoor skate says we need refuges in
the sea where wildlife can live, grow, and reproduce . . . without
being killed off.''
</P>
<P>
   The warning comes just as scallopers are fine-tuning their
dredges in hopes of returning to Georges Bank. Scallops have
recovered abundantly in a part of the bank called Area 2 after five
years of fishing closures. Scallopers have leaned heavily on
Senator Ted Kennedy and US Commerce Secretary William Daley.
</P>
<P>
   Daley has responded by pressuring the New England Fishery
Management Council to open Area 2 to scallopers by June 15. The
problem is that June 15 is far too soon for scientists to know
whether the return of the scallops is a symbol of a general renewal
or merely an opportunistic outbreak in a more lifeless sea.
</P>
<P>
   The plight of the barndoor skate is evidence that we should be
concerned about the latter. In the midst of growing fears that we
are fishing swordfish, wild salmon, and sharks into commercial
extinction, the barndoor skate is on the verge of becoming the
first extensively documented full extinction of a marine fish.
</P>
<P>
   Its crash has occurred from the waters off New England all the
way up to Newfoundland _ wherever fishermen have been. In a study
published last year in the journal Science, university researchers
from Newfoundland and Nova Scotia estimated that the population on
St. Pierre Bank off southern Newfoundland had decreased in the last
half-century from 600,000 to 500 by the 1970s. Barndoor skates were
a common bycatch in the 1950s, being caught in 10 percent of
trawls. There has been no recording of a barndoor skate bycatch in
the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The authors, Jill Casey and Ransom Myers, wrote that the skate
was ``driven to near extinction without anyone noticing. If such a
large, easily identified species has been allowed to disappear in
an area that is well surveyed, the fate of little-known species is
likely to be worse.''
</P>
<P>
   On Georges Bank, the barndoor skate appears to be making a
comeback, possibly in response to current fishing restrictions and
closures. But a reopening of the bank raises serious questions
about the creature's ability to survive.
</P>
<P>
   When born, it is already big enough, at nearly a foot in width,
to be caught by fishermen. There is a high chance of being caught
long before it reaches sexual maturity, which takes at least a
decade. Even when it lays eggs, it produces only about 47 a year,
hardly enough to compensate for the dredges.
</P>
<P>
   These are more reasons why Georges Bank should not be reopened
in knee-jerk fashion, as if it were just another government farm
program. Fishermen habitually refer to their catch as a
``harvest.'' It is highly misleading. You can reseed corn. Fish are
not so easy. ``Scientists know so little about the habitat of many
fish species that they are starting virtually from scratch,'' said
another article last year in Science.
</P>
<P>
   As well, scientists have only scratched the surface of knowing
how high-tech fishing combines ``harvest'' the sea. ``How many
passes of a trawl is equal to a single sea scallop dredge?'' asked
Peter Auster, science director of the National Undersea Research
Center at the University of Connecticut at Avery Point. ``That kind
of exercise has not been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Until those experiments are done, any return to the banks is a
high-risk exercise in extinction. Casey and Myers wrote: ``Perhaps
the only hope for the long-term survival of this species is to
designate an area protected from trawling on all the banks that is
sufficiently large to allow for a self-sustaining population.''
</P>
<P>
   Taken to its logical conclusion, any decisions on Georges Bank
cannot be made as if this were just a field left fallow to sow one
crop. While fishermen compare themselves to farmers, in too many
cases they are more like lumbermen carelessly slashing a clear cut.
</P>
<P>
   Until scientists learn a lot more about the impact of fishing,
the boats should remain at the barn door. Skating on thin knowledge
is no way to manage the oceans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
