<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOR-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD PACKAGING: NO LONGER AS EASY AS BLACK AND WHITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATE GURNETT  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ You're at the grocery store. You see the candy
bar. You grab the candy bar. You have a good excuse: It's low fat!
You know that because ... the package is green?
</P>
<P>
   Or so you think. Color plays a big role in what food products
people buy, experts say. It's the top consumer clue.
</P>
<P>
   Take Campbell's soup, Marlboro cigarettes and Coca Cola packaged
in red and white. Red is the most stimulating color; white gives
the best contrast, said Mona Doyle, author of ``Packing Strategy:
Winning the Consumer'' (Technomic Press, 1996). Yellow means happy
(think Cheerios and Domino Sugar). As diets change over time, so do
our color preferences, said Doyle, president of the Consumer
Network of Philadelphia and a packaging and consumer preference
researcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are popular colors. There are fad colors,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Black, once a symbol of no-frills, now emits elegance or
gourmet.
</P>
<P>
   Now back to green.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy being green back when Kermit the Frog was a young
croaker. Then, green was a ``barf'' color with monstrous
associations, Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, green is as hot as pink. Green says environmentally
responsible. It says decaffeinated. It says low fat. Manufacturers
of products from Healthy Choice to Hershey's Sweet Escapes have
wrapped their products in green.
</P>
<P>
   But don't snatch up those sweets just yet. First hear this
O'Henry tale.
</P>
<P>
   There once was an O'Henry candy bar, wrapped in a yellow
wrapper. Along came Brian Wansink, director of the Food &AMP; Brand Lab
at the University of Illinois, who wrapped it in green.
</P>
<P>
   He distributed it to consumers, then asked them what they had
eaten.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, they reported, this candy bar, the same old
O'Henry, now in new clothes, had fewer calories and more protein!
</P>
<P>
   ``People tended to see it as having 20 percent less of all the
bad stuff,'' Wansink said. ``Less fatty and caloric. They said,
`It's got a lot less cholesterol.' They also thought it had a lot
more vitamins.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrote one consumer: ``I like this even better than those Snack
Wells!''
</P>
<P>
   That's some color!
</P>
<P>
   People generally make subconscious judgments about places,
people and things within 60 to 90 seconds, said Eric Johnson, head
of Research Studies for the Institute for Color Research in
Chicago. ``Up to 92 percent of that decision is based on color
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Packaging is the front line in grocery sales, he said. ``When
you're walking down a grocery store aisle, two things are
happening. First, people seek product identity. I want a Tide box.
And we all know what Tide boxes look like.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Pepsi lost a chunk of its market when it came up with
new blue cans, said Johnson, who is writing a textbook on color
response.
</P>
<P>
   Second, if it's a new item, they notice the color. ``Colors for
food must be fairly congruent with what the food is inside. Except
for children's cereals or children's foods, then marketers can get
away with the really strong colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue is uncommon in food packaging, unless it's for seafood,
which has an association with water and fish, Johnson said. Purple
is less common, unless it means grape or children's products.
</P>
<P>
   Orange means cheap. ``Yellow and orange combined means this is
highly affordable, pick me up fast! Like Burger King.''
</P>
<P>
   However, as diets change from the 1950s meat-and-potatoes staple
to tofu and power bars, such variety is reflected in packaging,
Doyle said. ``It's like sneakers and kids' clothes. Anything goes.
Bright colors are more acceptable. Flamboyant colors, shining
colors, holography. You have dimensionality and translucent labels.
People are printing directly on packaging.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, people are so free these days they'll even buy green
oranges, Doyle said. That consumer move was unheard of two decades
ago. And those old black-and-white store labels are now dressed up
in four-color, shiny packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says to people, `This is all dressed up. The outside is
fancy so the inside must be fancy, too,' Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that new shapes, bottles with waistlines and silhouettes
and ovals and rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Such packaging beseeches: ``Come like me. Love me. Take me home
because you want me on your table. Feel me. Caress me. Enjoy me,''
Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a mistake to assume that all manufacturers know all
this stuff, Wansink said. ``They sit around and say, `My wife likes
blue. Maybe we should put it in blue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1405EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
