<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IS BETTER ON THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who knew banking could be this interesting?
</P>
<P>
   Like almost anything these days, banking becomes more compelling
to investors when you do it on the Internet. Our latest company
pulled from obscruity to the spotlight via the Web: Atlantic Bank &AMP;
Trust Co.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the tiny Boston institution traded at 11 1/8 on April
5, the day before the first of two on-line banking announcements.
As usual, the Internet news sent normal stock activity into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic stock traded as high as 52 1/4 Tuesday, before settling
down to finish the session at 41 1/8. The 4.1 million Atlantic
shares that changed hands Tuesday by far exceeded the stock's
trading volume for a full year before the April 5 announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Crazy? Atlantic president Richard Wayne isn't going to be the
person to tell you so. ``I'm not in the business of predicting
stock prices,'' he said. ``It is where it is. All I can say is that
I'm happy where it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are you've never heard of Atlantic Bank &AMP; Trust. Fleet
Financial Group makes more money in two days than Atlantic earns in
an entire year. It maintains a headquarters office in downtown
Boston and one branch. Even after the spectacular recent run,
Atlantic's stock market value is still just $170 million.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic specializes in wholesale banking, buying packages of
loans or pieces of big loans another institution originates. This
keeps overhead to a minimum so it can offer modestly higher
interest rates to depositors. It is a small but profitable and
growing business.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Atlantic shareholders, their bank announced its
Internet expansion at about the same time bullish sentiment was
building for two banks that conduct their business exclusively on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   If a strong wind was pushing Atlantic stock higher, a hurricane
sent shares soaring at Net.B(at)nk Inc. of Atlanta and Telebanc
Financial Corp. of Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Net.B(at)nk stock has zoomed from 68 to 235 1/64 this month
alone. The shares were up 76 33/64, in part on news of a 3-for-1
stock split.
</P>
<P>
   Telebanc shares, which traded at 47 3/8 three weeks ago,
finished Tuesday at 140 1/2. The stock was up 33 1/8 in Tuesday's
session alone.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the enthusiasm seems to have been sparked by recent
comments by Net.B(at)nk executives, who say deposit account growth
is exceeding their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other Internet stock explosions, news and hype bounces
around the Web itself as individual investors drive huge trading
volumes in lots of 100 or 200 shares at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Publicity and investor relations companies that conduct
``interviews'' with executives and then make the audio available on
Internet sites become part of the action.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic executives were involved in an interview conducted and
posted by one such service, Vcall Corp., last week. Another
service, talk-stock.com, was scheduled to arrange a similar
conversation with officials at Virtuallender.com today.
</P>
<P>
   Though Atlantic has enjoyed a bit of Web stock euphoria, it's
valuation can't compare with those of the pure Internet
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Ba(at)nk, which has a smaller business than Atlantic at the
moment, carries a stock market valution of $2 billion, more than 10
times larger than that of Atlantic. Telebanc, the larger Internet
bank, is valued at $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic announced on April 6 that it had signed an Internet
banking services agreement with a contractor to build a banking Web
site with hopes of getting it up and running by late summer.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, an Atlantic subsidiary touted a new on-line
system to generate small-ticket office equipment leases that could
be originated on the spot at stores just as car loans are arranged
at dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   Bank customers who were too expensive to service can become good
business over the Internet. The Web's lower overall expenses can
make it possible for banks like Atlantic to offer better interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne won't say how much Atlantic expects the Internet to impact
it's business. ``The technology is here, we all know that,'' he
said. ``I expect we'll participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic stock was in the dulldrums before its Internet
announcements and may have been undervalued at the time. Analyst
Robert Schwartzberg of Friedman, Billings, Ramsey raised his rating
on Atlantic to a ``strong buy'' on Feb. 17, when it traded at 12
1/2, and cited 18 per share as a price target.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzberg said Tuesday he didn't know how much value
Atlantic's Internet business could create, but has maintained the
same strong buy recommendation. He hasn't issued any new price
targets.
</P>
<P>
   Neither would we.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CAPITAL HONOR &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Venture Capital Association will honor famed
investor Peter Brooke with a lifetime achievement award at a dinner
Thursday in Boston. Brooke, founder and chairman of the global
venture firm Advent International, also was a founder of TA
Associates in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can also be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
