<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIBLE-EXPLOSION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM DADS TO STUDENTS, THERE'S A BIBLE FOR YOU 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First there was The Word. Today, there are Words, and Words and
Words.
</P>
<P>
   While the Bible has always been the world's best-selling book,
the number of different Bibles jamming bookstores has exploded in
recent years, driven by a phenomenal boom in Bibles catering to
special interest groups ranging from mothers to recovering
alcoholics.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 3,000 different Bibles on the market today,
with more coming. For instance, Whittemore's, New England's largest
Christian bookstore, stocks 1,000 different Bibles.
</P>
<P>
   From harried fathers to struggling high school students to
stressed-out businesss people, millions of Christians are buying
these specialty or ``niche'' Bibles, whose packaging and marketing
promise words of wisdom to meet their specific needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These specialized Bibles have become enormously popular,''
said Phyllis Tickle, contributing editor for religion at Publishers
Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Stroll down the Bible aisle at your local bookstore and you
might find: ``The New Adventure Bible,'' geared toward children,
with recommended activities related to Scripture passages; ``Holy
Bible: Woman Thou Art Loosed,'' featuring prayers and essays by
evangelical personality T.D. Jakes; and ``The End Times Bible,''
containing references to millennial prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   Some stores stock Bible-buying charts to help customers wade
through a sometimes overwhelming selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone walks into a store saying, `I'm looking for a
Bible,' it might be a scary 20 or 30 minutes because there are so
many choices,'' said Craig Featherstone, vice president of
Nashville, Tenn.-based Thomas Nelson, one of the nation's largest
Bible publishers.
</P>
<P>
   These specialty Bibles do not alter any of the basic narrative
of Christian Scripture. If they did, they couldn't be considered
genuine Bibles.
</P>
<P>
   What makes specialty Bibles distinct is what surrounds the
sacred text _ commentaries targeted at specific audiences,
graphics, and inspirational words linked to certain important
verses.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Women's Devotional Bible,'' for instance, includes ``a new
collection of daily devotions from Godly women.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Adventure Bible'' has a colorful graphic translating
the 10 Commandments for children, including this as the Second
Commandment: ``You may not worship, or put more importance on any
person or thing, other than God. You must worship only the Lord,
not your parents, not a friend, not a movie star or sports hero,
not a car or boat or or skateboard. Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These Bibles provide an avenue for people who may otherwise
find it difficult to find a way into Scripture,'' said Laurel Book,
Bible buyer for Family Christian Stores, the country's largest
chain of Christian stores with about 320 retail outlets. Specialty
Bibles generally cost from $20 to $80.
</P>
<P>
   The specialty Bibles use different standard translations or
versions of Scripture. The King James Version, once the leader, has
been supplanted by the New International Version, which was
published 25 years ago and has become a mainstay of Protestant
Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Another version, the New Living Translation, has sold 3 million
copies since it was published three years ago. The official Roman
Catholic Bible sanctioned by the US Catholic bishops is the New
American Bible.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to determine just how popular Bibles have become
because no single group track sales and Bibles are sold as
fundraisers in stores and over the Internet. But the top five Bible
publishers, including Thomas Nelson, Zondervan Publishing House and
Tyndale, say Bible sales have increased 30 percent to 40 percent
throughout the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a Bible that's going to speak to you and where you
are in your relationship to God and where you are in your life,''
explained Nancy Langevin, who owns two Bibles but prefers to
regularly read a special devotional Bible for people in recovery.
</P>
<P>
   While declining to go into specifics, Langevin says she has
``struggled with some addictive behaviors'' and the devotional
Bible helps her ``recognize that when God is in control of my life
things are much better.''
</P>
<P>
   The growth in specialized Bibles also is fueled by an enormous
appetite for spiritual nourishment, an increase in church-based
Bible study groups and a greater availability of inexpensive
Bibles.
</P>
<P>
   Another key reason, say book industry analysts, is savvy
marketing. ``Let's face it, we're talking about slick packaging and
smart advertising,'' Tickle said. ``Nobody is changing the Bible.
They're just presenting it differently. But it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Christians worry that the flood of specialized Bibles is
becoming excessive.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many Bibles does any man, woman or child want or need to
have?'' says Ginny Van Meter, general manager at Whittemore's,
based in Needham, Mass. ``A woman who appreciates the `Women's
Devotional Bible' may not need a `Mom's Devotional Bible' or a
`Parenting Devotional Bible.'''
</P>
<P>
   Others question whether Bible publishers are more interested in
profits than in spreading the Good News.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure Jesus would smile at what's going on right now in
the Christian world,'' said Rob Wilson, who tracks Christian
businesses and is senior vice president at Bustin and Company, a
Dallas-based business development firm.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mockabee, senior vice president and publisher of Bibles for
Zondervan Publishing House, based in Grand Rapids, Mich.,
acnknowledged the fine line publishers of sacred texts straddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take seriously the idea of representing what God would have
us say to today's culture, and do it without too much hip hop,''
Mockabee said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Christian scholars and ministers also warn that specialized
Bibles filled with ancillary notes and commentary could lead to
confusion between what is sacred text, and what has been added by
the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``A reader could easily think that since this is the Bible that
everything, including all the extra notes, have similar weight,''
notes Mark Coppenger, president of Midwestern Baptist Theological
Seminary in Kansas City, Mo. ``An innocent reader walking into a
bookstore will find a familiar name or attractive packaging or
fetching title and take it as something trustworthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathie Whitesel, who has bought several different kinds of
Bibles for her family and as gifts, also said she prefers to draw
her own conclusions rather than subscribe to someone else's views.
Still, she notes, the quality and readability of Bibles has
improved in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Bible publishers insist that inhouse editors scrutinize every
word to ensure that specialized Bibles do not lead readers astray
and are in line with accepted biblical scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask why publish a women's bible?'' Featherstone said.
``And I say because I'm not convinced that 75-year-old gray haired
scholars have as much sensitivity to women's issues as women
scholars would. You can't have the same scholars speak equally well
to the needs of all people in all denominations at all stages of
their lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1409EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7814 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-HARRICK-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     04-14 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HARRICK-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 KINGSTON, R.I.: ... to him.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Harrick Jr. often refers to his father as ``coach'' and
``Jim Harrick.'' He played for his father at Pepperdine, and
understood then that their's must always be a relationship in which
both are mindful that the father-and-son role must take backstage
to professional issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I got into this business I quickly realized there is a
business side to Jim Harrick and there is a social side to Jim
Harrick,'' said Jim Jr. ``And I understood the business. I
understand who I am, that I am a direct reflection of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very difficult to be in this busineness. It's not
always played out to my favor or to my benefit, but I've taken the
good with the bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Harrick Jr. said his father enjoyed URI and wanted his son
at his side but was also interested in coaching at the major
college level again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole process happened way too quickly for him,'' said
Harrick. ``He's not one of those guys who makes emotional
decisions, and the pressures of the time frame Georgia was putting
him under and the pressures of having to make that decision quickly
without evaluating all the intangibles caused him to have a lot of
doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Harrick is a loyalty guy, first and foremost, and that's
why he was bothered, because the people at URI had been so good to
him. It's always, always difficult leaving a good situation. And he
didn't have a good situation here, he had a great stiuation.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick said his father told him about Georgia's offer as the
two prepared to go to the NCAA championship game March 29 in St.
Petersburg, Fla. Following the game, he said his father told the
other coaches he was leaving and invited them to come to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then he said, `I want to talk to Ron (Petro) and the
people in Rhode Island because I'm not sure I don't just want to
sit down and work it out,' '' said the younger Harrick.
</P>
<P>
   He said the next morning his father flew back to URI to meet
with school officials. The coaches flew back later in the day and
met with him that evening. Harrick said his father received a
counter offer that ``blew him away'' and had spelled out for him
all the reasons why he should stay.
</P>
<P>
   But to the son's surprise, Harrick said he was taking the
Georgia job. ``I was very shocked. At that point I felt very
disappointed, because there was a chance it might not happen for
me. But I was happy if that was what he wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick said his father left for Georgia and because both were
busy the following day they did not correspond. ``Then on Thursday
morning, I got two or three calls from both of my brothers saying
he was struggling with his decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them it's a hard decision and transition is emotional.
And they said, `No, he's struggling with you, because he got down
there and it doesn't look like he's going (to get past the nepotism
issue).' ''
</P>
<P>
   Then Harrick said he heard his father had changed his mind. At
about 6 p.m., he spoke with his father from the URI basketball
office where, unknown to him, a crowd of more than 300 people was
swelling outside, ready to give Jim Harrick Sr. a hero's welcome
for returning to the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brothers were on the other line, and (Harrick Sr.) asked me
if I was OK with his decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hindsight is 20-20. If I had my druthers now, I would have
said, `I really want you here. I enjoy us working together. I like
our program. I love Rhode Island. Let's stay.' What I said to him
was, `If you want to go down there, I'll support you there. If you
want to come back here, I'll really support you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he hung up and the next thing I heard was he was going
(to Georgia).''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick said he spoke with his father two hours later, and told
him about the people who were standing outside the coaches'
offices. He said he asked his father if he was certain he wanted to
leave, but by then Harrick's second commitment to Georgia was
final.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this business you learn what is done is done and it's hard
to undo things,'' said the younger Harrick. ``I'll always support
him professionally in any decision he decides to do. And obviously,
I'll support him as a son would always support his father.''
</P>
<P>
   The past few weeks have been eventful for URI players. The team
lost to North Carolina-Charlotte in the first round of the NCAA
tournament in Milwaukee, then returned home, believing their 20-13
season was capped with that defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we come back from spring break and heard that coach
Harrick was going to Georgia,'' said freshman guard Tip Vinson, who
played for DeGregorio at St. Thomas Aquinas. ``That hurt because
(Harrick's) such a great guy and all of us like to play for him. It
was kind of a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vinson said he didn't pay attention to reports Harrick was
having a change of heart, so when he heard the coach was heading to
Georgia again he said it did not faze him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect coach Harrick and wish the best for him, as he
would for us,'' he said. But he added, ``Around campus people are
always asking us why did it happen. They ask a lot of questions.
Sometimes, you avoid trying to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of days a new coach could be in place at URI and the
talk will likely subside. Undoubtedly most URI officials hope so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's unfortunate, because Jim Harrick had 600 great
days in Rhode Island,'' said DeGregorio. ``It would be unfortunate
if people would define or remember Jim Harrick for two bad days.
Time heals wounds. If the program moves forward, succeeds or stays
at the level it has been, I think people will forget those two
days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
