<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIVE-PREP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MEXICO SCHOOL PREPS NATIVE AMERICANS FOR COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROWE, N.M. _ The memories are so vivid, so painful, that many of
the high school seniors speak of them as if they were their own.
</P>
<P>
   The students recall the chopped-off braids of their ancestors
and the beatings they received for speaking their own languages.
The bitter taste of the English names assigned to new students.
Surviving until graduation was a feat, college all but an
impossibility.
</P>
<P>
   As Wizipan Garriott, a 19-year-old Lakota, explained, ``I
guess'' white people ``didn't want us to succeed, and I guess we
didn't expect to.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than a century after the first federal boarding
school for Indians was founded, success is being celebrated on a
campus tucked away in the piney hills 45 miles southeast of Santa
Fe. The Native American Preparatory School is about to graduate its
first class, and each of the 22 seniors is college bound. So far,
not a single rejection letter has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   As acceptances roll in at the only privately funded school for
Native Americans, the seniors must decide between Occidental and
Grinnell, Antioch and Amherst. Several are waiting to hear from
Stanford, Dartmouth, and Vassar. Wizipan, who felt unprepared for
the Ivy League after graduating from a reservation school in South
Dakota, spent a year readying himself in Rowe. In the fall, the
aspiring architect will head to Yale, where, he said, he will be
the first student there schooled on a reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My other school was a typical reservation school,'' Wizipan
said, as he showed off a model of the tool shed and greenhouse he
designed as part of his hands-on coursework. ``How can I be
diplomatic but honest without cutting it down? The expectations are
just higher here. The whole goal is completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   At Native American Prep, one central goal is to give students
the book learning and life experience necessary to succeed in
college, and the confidence to know that they can. Another is to
begin building a network of graduates to rival any East Coast prep
school, able to assist one another and their tribes for decades to
come. Many of the teenagers vow to use their educations to improve
reservation life and reduce massive Indian unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   As Sven Huseby, who formerly ran Vermont's Putney School and
came out of retirement to take over in Rowe, noted, many of the 71
students come to the school from the poverty of the nation's
reservations. Between them, they represent 33 tribes in 11 states.
About half of Native Americans do not graduate from high school; of
those who enroll in college, only a tiny percentage finish. Even at
Native American Prep, more than half of the freshmen enrolled in
1995 have since left the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids know that if they do well'' colleges will ``want more
of them,'' said Whitney Laughlin, the campus's college counselor.
``If they don't, they won't. They know they're ambassadors for the
school and for Native Americans. They're pioneers, and they're
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   For four years now, the students have prepared themselves in
small classrooms where about half of the faculty is also Native
American. Students study the academic core _ English, math, and
science, for example _ as well as extras that emphasize their own
tribal histories and traditions. Traditional prayers, songs, and
medicines are not only allowed, they are taught, along with Indian
authors and folklore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contrast between what I experienced and they experience is
huge,'' said John Anthony Reyna, who teaches world cultures to
sophomores part time. ``We never had classes in Native American
history, in Native American anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even with four applicants for every acceptance, the school
has not gained easy acceptance among some Native Americans. Despite
the newfound wealth of many tribal nations that have ventured into
casino gambling _ and launched schools of their own _ the vast
majority of the prep school's $2 million or so annual budget comes
from white sources such as foundations, corporations, or
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Actor Val Kilmer, who lives nearby, made a film about the school
that is used for fund-raising, and he recently dropped off bags and
boxes of used clothing for the youths.
</P>
<P>
   Only two students _ one a white teenager from Santa Fe who
applied and had to be accepted under the school's admission
guidelines _ pay the full, $24,000-a-year tuition. The others
typically pay about $900, with parents able to work off those
payments by helping out on the sprawling campus, where modest
dormitories and classrooms are designed to fit into their wooded
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, some parents have to be convinced that the school
their children want to attend is not the school of their own
childhoods. Even today, education specialists said, many of the 180
or so Indian schools run by the Bureau of Indian Affairs are dim,
crumbling places with no money for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many parents come into my office and revisit the nightmare of
their boarding school days because they're hoping we're
different,'' said Edison Eskeets, the associate head of the school
who ran 38 miles a day for six days to raise $90,000 for student
scholarships. ``They were asked not to speak native languages, not
to bring their native traditions with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nikke Nez, one of the seniors who regularly dash off opinion
pieces to a New Mexico newspaper, felt shut out in both the white
world and the Indian world until she arrived at Native American
Prep. Part white, part Navajo, she said she was ridiculed for her
heritage at both a public school she attended and a federally
funded Indian school.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I knew of my culture was what the media fed to me,'' said
Nez, who plans to be an ethnobotanist. ``Even at the Indian school,
I was like, `Why do I want to be an Indian if everyone rejects me?'
I've learned a lot about me here. . . . But as far as giving back
to `my people,' that's a cliche. They didn't give anything to me.
I'm giving back to this school.''
</P>
<P>
   Like teenagers everywhere, many of the students snicker at the
stories of hardship they hear from their parents and grandparents,
and from the Indians who are now their teachers: planting corn,
herding sheep, walking 10 miles to school. Like typical teenagers,
they also have trouble articulating exactly what their own school
has meant for them.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they point to specific experiences: group trips to
visit colleges around the country; attendance at summer workshops
emphasizing everything from sports to computers; the semester a
student studied in China; and the senior year two students are
spending in Spain, part of a program sponsored by Massachusetts'
Phillips Andover Academy. Every year several also attend the summer
program at Cushing Academy in Massachusetts. The girls' basketball
team also won the district championship, despite the lack of a gym
on campus.
</P>
<P>
   But the rigidity associated with many prep schools is absent at
Native American Prep. At a recent ``morning gathering,'' students
lined the wall to hear announcements, read poetry, and thank the
staff for the Indian fry bread they had feasted on that Friday
night. Then, urged on by the science teacher, a dozen of them
demonstrated the country line dancing they had learned over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the push I needed,'' said Jolene Abeita, 18, a senior
from the Santo Domingo Pueblo in New Mexico who has been accepted
by nine schools so far and plans to major in English. ``I never
even thought about college before I came here. I'm expecting it to
be hard, but now I'm used to hard. I'm ready, and I'm going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
