<SLUG> BC-MARA-DRISCOLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEAN DRISCOLL IS BACK AND READY TO ROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Jean Driscoll, the queen of the Boston Marathon
women's wheelchair division, has a fire in her belly.
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll won her event seven consecutive times from 1990 to
1996. She seemed on the way to No. 8 in 1997 until her wheel caught
a streetcar track and threw her at Cleveland Circle. Victory eluded
her again last year when Louise Sauvage caught her at the finish
line in the closest Boston finish ever. How close? So close that
they posted the same times (1:41:19).
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll, 32, is on a mission this year. She has relived her
past two setbacks and comes to Boston with a new mindset.
</P>
<P>
   Replaying last year, Driscoll said, ``I had thought about that
race many times, and there are two very interesting things.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, after we climbed Heartbreak Hill, I thought I was in
pretty good position. I felt comfortable. I had a good lead on
Louise. Then, approaching Cleveland Circle where I took that tumble
on the streetcar tracks two years ago, I started thinking about it.
It was like playing a mind game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit my brakes hard three times approaching the Circle. I
really didn't have to but I was afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Mind games. Driscoll seemingly gave up inches while Sauvage
gained yards. Still, at that instant, it didn't figure much in the
overall picture.
</P>
<P>
   Said Driscoll, ``I think maybe I lost the race right there when
I think about it. Who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll's second replay confirms what many watchers suspected
last year: She wasn't aware that Sauvage was so close to her at the
finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were approaching the finish line after I turned onto
Boylston Street,'' said Driscoll. ``I turned the corner and had
maybe a 50-meter lead on Louise. I felt very comfortable as I was
making my final pushes. Then I heard the announcement from the
finish line, `Jean Driscoll wins her eighth Boston Marathon.' When
I heard that, I figured I had at least 20-30 meters on Louise. I
was just raising my arms to cut the tape at the finish line when _
whoosh _ Louise passed me. I was in shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told that the people at the finish line thought Louise
was a male wheelchair entry. Well, it wasn't a he, it was a she. It
was Louise. She won. What can I say? She beat me in the sprint and
the sprint is the strong part of her races. My strong point is the
hills.''
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll wasn't making an alibi, she just told it as it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I tumbled two years ago at Cleveland Circle, Boston fans
cried for me,'' said Driscoll. ``It was the same last year. There
were more tears for me at the most quiet finish line I ever saw.
The Boston fans seem to love me, and I love the Boston fans. I
cried too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, you can't take anything away from Louise. She never
gave up. She never quit, and I admire her.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Smith, Driscoll's trainer at the University of Illinois,
said, ``Jean's in great shape. Her workouts have been great. I'll
tell you, she really wants to win at Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll didn't do much training late in 1998. She was making
appearances for her sponsor (Ocean Spray) and spent little time in
her racing chair. She worked out in a hand cycle most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while I even thought about not going back to Boston,''
said Driscoll. ``That feeling didn't last too long, though. I got
an itch, and in December I got that fire back, that fire in my
belly I had in Boston the first three times I won. Not that I
didn't have fire the past six years. I just don't think it was as
intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started serious training, bought a new racing chair and I've
been serious since then. I want Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I will not have a feeling that I'm guaranteed a
victory. I know I have to make an all-out effort and race smartly.
I do have that fire back. It's a fire that I think was lacking
maybe a bit the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll didn't come to Boston 10 days in advance of the race as
she did the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was that I had too much time to think about the
race in recent years,'' said Driscoll who will arrive Thursday.
``The anticipation gets to you. You know, all the interviews and
hoopla. I do like that. But the nights are long and tough to cope
with. Too much time to think. After my workouts I was in a friend's
home or a hotel with plenty of time to think. That's why I'll come
in Thursday. I'm doing exactly what I did my first three years in
Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll always sees a silver lining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have a support group with me,'' said Driscoll. ``Five
friends took off for Cape Cod in a van last week. They'll vacation
there and be at the race. Three more are flying out. That makes
eight, and they all belong to same church I do.
</P>
<P>
   `You know, I think I have a God-given fire in my belly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1414EDT &QL; 
