<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-KRONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JULIE KRONE'S LONG RIDE COMES TO AN END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The voice _ straight out of Munchkinland _ makes her seem like a
little girl.
</P>
<P>
   But that would be a mistaken impression. Julie Krone, 35, the
winningest female jockey of all time, is a complex personality _
one who had already left a lasting impression on her sport before
she announced her retirement last week.
</P>
<P>
   She belied her voice and her size _ 4-feet-10 1/2, 100 pounds _
with winning performances that could have her alternately playing
the role of gracious winner or female wrestler or motorcycle moll
before reverting to charming spokeswoman for her sport. Consider
two tales from her colorful career:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Image No. 1: Rough and tumble
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A journeyman jockey, Miguel Rujano, took exception to Krone's
riding tactics in an ordinary race on a weekday in 1986 at Monmouth
Park in New Jersey. They argued while on horseback and Rujano then
hit her on the head with his whip. After dismounting, Krone began
punching Rujano, who defended himself with his whip. The argument
ended in the locker room where Krone picked up a chair and hit him
with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of those girls who tries to act macho around the
boys,'' she told reporters later. `I'm competitive on the track and
feminine off it . . . but I'm not going to stand around and let
someone strike me like that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Image No. 2: Friend of the family
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The walking ring at Saratoga in August. With families having
picnic lunches on the grass behind the grandstand, the Saratoga
crowd is unlike most racetrack gatherings. Fathers hold up young
children to see the horses and jockeys before they head out onto
the track. The code for jockeys, of course, is to ignore the fans.
Not Krone, there's a smile for all the children, some waves, a few
hellos, and maybe even a few blown kisses.
</P>
<P>
   It was this combination of charisma and toughness that helped
make her a star in thoroughbred racing. But that couldn't have
happened had not the toughness combined with a great skill for
riding horses that made her a champion jockey at Gulfstream Park,
Monmouth Park, and the Meadowlands and made her one of the top five
jockeys in New York for a short period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughbred racing is a multi-tiered competition with horses,
trainers, and jockeys competing and thousands of fans betting. It
is also one of the few arenas where women can compete with men
under similar conditions. In some situations _ such as Krone's size
_ women have an advantage. So, for a time, was her ability to
communicate with the horses, to direct 1,200-pound animals to the
correct area of the track for clear running or extract extra energy
in the drive to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   She has won 3,542 races, including 277 stakes races, and in 1989
her 368 victories ranked third in the country. She was the first
female jockey to win a Triple Crown race when she rode Colonial
Affair to victory in the 1993 Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 20, 1993, she won five races in one day at Saratoga
competing against some of the best jockeys in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days later, however, she was injured in a horrific spill at
the top of the stretch on the Saratoga turf course. She was sent
flying in the air before smashing into the ground and having a
horse's hoof kick her in the chest. It would have killed her had
she not been wearing a protective vest.
</P>
<P>
   But the fall was bad enough. He broken leg required two plates
and 14 screws to reconstruct.
</P>
<P>
   She mended and returned, only to fall again on Jan. 13, 1995,
and break both hands. That seemed to take its toll. She mended and
returned again, but her victories dwindled and she was forced to
leave the high-powered New York racing circuit to again find
success. It did not come easily and only in small portions.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, she tried something entirely new, riding at the
Fairgrounds in New Orleans. She finished third in the rider
standings against a group of jockeys who would have a hard time
finding one mount on an August afternoon at Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   Successful race riding requires a combination of courage and
recklessness along with great timing. An absence of one means
mediocrity. And that's where Krone found herself in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on top, I'm 35 years old, and I don't want to do this
anymore,'' Krone said. ``I don't want to get hurt any more, and
I've got nothing left to prove. I'd go to sleep at night, and my
ankle hurt and my knee hurt and I'd think, `I just want to get this
over with.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And it will be over when she rides her final race Sunday at Lone
Star Park in Texas, but her place in race history is secure. It is
one thoroughbred racing fans can see in every program at nearly
every track in the country where the jockey standings are listed:
Women are among the leaders. It's almost a given. Before Julie
Krone, it wasn't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
