<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7822 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-HARRICK-2TAKES-BO     04-14 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HARRICK-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIM HARRICK JR. CAUGHT IN A TRYING TEST OF LOYALTIES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, R.I. _ Jim Harrick still coaches men's basketball at
the University of Rhode Island. He has not gone anywhere. He is
still committed to helping to make the Rams a major college power.
But he admits the past few days at the school have been some of the
most trying of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Before you think there has been another twist to one of the most
bizzare farewells in college basketball history, the Harrick
employed by URI is assistant coach Jim Jr., son of the former head
coach. Jim Harrick Sr. two weeks ago said he would take the vacant
post at Georgia, changed his mind and said he would stay at URI,
then changed again and left for Athens, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of Jim Harrick's three son's, Jim Jr., 34, joined
his father's staff last season after stints at San Diego State,
Marshall, and Valparaiso. He considers his current job the best
he's ever had and hopes to stay in Kingston for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Yet each working day he enters the coaches' office and takes his
position between a rock and a hard place.
</P>
<P>
   On one side, there is the loyalty to the father he loved working
with, the man he figured would not depart Kingston unless a
professional job opened. He was surprised and disappointed when his
father left for Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, there's his loyalty to URI, where he watched
his father go from one of the school's most popular persons to one
of its most vilified.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very difficult in the fact that they've had two
unbelievable years here, two years they've never had at this
school,'' said Jim Jr. ``They've gone to the Elite Eight and won
the Atlantic 10 championship. They've had a lot of good coaches in
this program, but they've never been places Jim Harrick took them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has their feelings hurt and their egos struck, but
people jump to conclusions and make snap reactions and they have
paralysis by analysis. They overanalyze a lot of things. To react
in a despondent way of rejecting Jim Harrick and making negative
comments about him, obviously that's personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's understandable (that people were hurt by Harrick's
departure). My feelings are hurt. But the bottom line is that Jim
Harrick took URI to places it has never been before, and I know URI
will do well without Jim Harrick.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, athletic director Ron Petro said the school's
selection committee for a new basketball coach submitted six
finalists to the school's affirmative action officer and added it
will likely name Harrick's successor this week.
</P>
<P>
   Petro declined to say whether the list includes former Celtics
great Dave Cowens, URI assistant Jerry DeGregorio (who is interim
head coach), or former assistant Larry Farmer. They have been
rumored to be among the candidates for the post.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how the situation plays out, it promises to be
another intriguing offseason for URI basketball, which just last
month enjoyed one of the most thrilling moments in program history
when sophomore sensation Lamar Odom sank a trey at the buzzer to
give the Rams a 62-59 triumph over Temple for the school's first
Atlantic 10 championship.
</P>
<P>
   Last offseason, questions about Odom's eligibility made national
headlines. Two years ago, it was the hiring of Harrick that drew
major attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Harrick's departure) was disappointing, not so much that he
left, but disappointing in the way it ended, with him changing his
mind in going back to Georgia,'' said Petro, referring to the fact
that before departing Harrick did not meet with players and failed
to attend a scheduled press conference to announce his return.
</P>
<P>
   Petro, who said he hasn't spoken to Harrick since the coach
departed the second time, said he understands much of the shock and
dismay associated with the decision. ``It was a very unusual
situation. Jim had never acted like that before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was expected to be there (for the press conference)
and he wasn't it was disappointing. We had made calls to boosters
and the players were excited, and after he didn't show it was
difficult as to why he didn't tell us sooner and why he didn't call
his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we really appreciated him being here for a good two
years, and as for the bad days we'll move on. We have a strong
program with good players. We just have to make a right decision on
a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   For DeGregorio, who has had head coaching stints at St. Thomas
Aquinas High School in New Britain, Conn., and Mattatuck Community
College, last week was, as he put it, surreal.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and the other URI coaches have offers from Harrick to
join his Georgia staff should URI choose to go in another
direction. Jim Harrick Jr. must wait and see if Georgia will relax
its nepotism laws to allow him to work with his father again.
</P>
<P>
   But he said as of now, DeGregorio is committed to holding the
program together. Many believe the top priority is Odom, one of the
members of the selection committee, who is said to be pushing for
DeGregorio to receive the job. Many have speculated Odom might
leave for the NBA if that doesn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Others want DeGregorio to get the job so the coaching staff can
remain in tact. Moreover, Odom is part of a close-knit New York
contingent on the team that some fear will dissolve if Odom leaves.
Then there are members of URI's exceptional recruiting class who
reportedly are also pushing for DeGregorio and inferring they might
go elsewhere if he does not get the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my responsibility is to hold it together as long as I
can,'' said DeGregorio, ``and I have confidence in the kids and
their parents that if the University of Rhode Island chooses to go
another way and hire another coach other than myself, I'm confident
these players and their parents will support the new coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for for Lamar, if he wants to play college basketball next
year, he has to play at the University of Rhode Island, whether I'm
here or not. His decision should not be based on what happens to
me, and I've stressed that to him.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
