<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-RECEIVERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECEIVING CLASS HAS DEPTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Patriots and many other NFL teams made a huge
mistake leaving Randy Moss off their draft boards a year ago. There
is no such dilemma this year. While there are good receivers
available, such as Torry Holt, David Boston, and Troy Edwards, the
Patriots may not regret a decision to bypass any of the three with
their two first-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet don't be surprised if the Patriots decide to buck their
anticipated center-running back mindset and take a receiver to give
Drew Bledsoe more weaponry and to guard against Terry Glenn
breaking their hearts again.
</P>
<P>
   Holt, from North Carolina State, appears to the prize. At 6
feet, 192 pounds, with 4.5 speed in the 40, Holt already is an
accomplished receiver who has excellent hands, can seperate from
defenders, and runs superb routes. He has a chance to be an impact
player in the right situation.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Holt's size, he not only can go deep, but can catch
the ball over the middle. It doesn't appear Holt will get out of
the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State's Boston also has good size (6-1, 215) and displays
tremendous athleticism. He caught 74 passes for 1,330 yards and 14
touchdowns last season and possesses superb punt return skills,
making him even more of a prize. Boston needs to refine his route
running, but like the Patriots' Tony Simmons, that part of his game
will likely improve with experience.
</P>
<P>
   Some draft experts have Edwards dropping to the Patriots with
the 20th pick. The Louisiana Tech star is a smaller receiver at a
shade under 5-10 and 190 but is also prolific, as evidenced by his
102 catches, 1,707 yards, and 13 TDs last season. A former running
back, Edwards is also a kick returner.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's Peerless Price could be around in Round 2. The 5-11,
180-pounder has 4.4 speed and can be a deep threat, but his hands
need work. Syracuse's Kevin Johnson, who lost the quarterback job
to Donovan McNabb three years ago, has developed into a fine
receiver. He's 5-11, 194 pounds and is an intriguing athlete who
can do a little of everything. Equally intriguing is Northwestern's
D'Wayne Bates, another tall receiver at 6-1 1/2, 215, who already
has had to overcome several injuries but still managed 83 catches
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Others to watch are Ohio State's Dee Miller, Arizona State's
Kenny Mitchell, Auburn's Karsten Bailey, North Carolina's Na Brown,
and Kentucky's Craig Yeast.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the best year for tight ends. North Dakota's Jim
Kleinsasser, a Division 2 All-American, is the highest-rated of the
bunch at 6-2 1/2, 272. Mississippi State's Reggie Kelly and
Nebraska's Sheldon Jackson are also highly regarded.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi's Rufus French is considered the best receiver in
the group. At 6-4, 253, French caught 45 balls last season. He may
be more of an H-back, but could get big enough to become an
effective blocker. Georgia's Larry Brown, a 6-4 1/2, 280-pounder
who also played on the basketball team, could be a sleeper. He has
proven pass-catching ability (31 receptions) and may develop into a
good blocker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1418EDT &QL; 
