<HEADER>
A7825 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-HENDERSON-HN     04-14 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-HENDERSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENDERSON GIVES THE METS REASON TO GLOAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Stands for HENDERSON)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM REYNOLDS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He's a lock for the Hall of Fame, most likely on the
first ballot. He knows his place in baseball history is secure,
that he is the standard against which great base stealers will
forever be measured.
</P>
<P>
   So it would be inaccurate to say that life is beginning at 40
for New York Mets left fielder Rickey Henderson. But if his start
to the 1999 season is an indication, Henderson's days as a
productive leadoff man are far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, in his 21st major-league season, was batting .375
with 10 runs scored through eight games, leading the Mets to the
top of the National League East with a 6-2 mark. He also led the
National League in runs, walks and extra-base hits, was second in
doubles and on-base percentage and fifth in slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for this team to get off to the start we
have, to set the tone,'' Henderson said. ``It was more important
for the team, not for Rickey, to get off to a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson struggled a year ago, hitting .189 in the first three
weeks of the season for Oakland. His on-base percentage through
eight games this year was .571.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way Rickey gets on base is unbelievable,'' Mets pitcher
Bobby Jones said. ``You watch him sometimes, wondering how he draws
so many walks. He gets it done, but everybody has to get it done,
not just a couple guys. That's been the key for us so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson signed a one-year contract with the Mets on Dec. 13,
12 days before his 40th birthday. General manager Steve Phillips,
second-guessed for the move by skeptics in the New York media, has
so far resisted the urge to gloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rickey sets the stage,'' Phillips said. ``But we've been
getting good things throughout the lineup. There's a lot of guys on
this team who can hit.''
</P>
<P>
   None, though, has anything close to Henderson's credentials. He
is sixth all-time in runs scored (2,025) and third in walks behind
Babe Ruth and Ted Williams. He needs one stolen base to reach 1,300
in his career, 362 more than any other player in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still a good player,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said.
``He plays the game with a lot of intensity and that's what we
need.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson channels that intensity into tremendous patience at
the plate. In 1998 with Oakland, he took the first pitch in nine of
every 10 plate appearances, and led the American League in both
walks (118) and stolen bases (66), the fourth time he has pulled
that double.
</P>
<P>
   ``That comes with experience,'' Valentine said. ``Most
experienced hitters know their strengths and weaknesses, and like
to wait for their pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson spent parts of five seasons in New York as a Yankee
from 1985-1989, so he's used to the high expectations of New York
fans. He clearly reveled in the warm greeting the fans gave him
during Monday's home opener at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know what Rickey's capable of doing and they know what he
isn't capable of either,'' Henderson said. ``I've just got to go
out and do what I've got to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
