<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7827 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARA-KRISTIANSEN-BOS &LR;      04-14 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARA-KRISTIANSEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INGRID KRISTIANSEN SAYS 2:20 IS LONG OVERDUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The highlights are numerous.
</P>
<P>
   There were the dominating Boston wins in 1986 and 1989. There
were the four wins in the London Marathon. There was the course
record in the Houston Marathon. There was the stretch when she
became the only person to simultaneously hold world records at
5,000 meters, 10,000 meters and the marathon.
</P>
<P>
   In those mid-1980s days, the magic time of 2:20 for the marathon
seemed well within the reach of Norway's Ingrid Kristiansen.
Besides Kristiansen, Grete Waitz, also of Norway, and Joan Benoit
Samuelson of Freeport, Maine, were doing their share to push the
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Kristiansen put up a 2 hour, 21 minutes and 6 seconds time in
the London Marathon in 1985, breaking Samuelson's two-year-old
record of 2:22:43. The race for 2:20 was on.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Kristiansen said, someone was going to break the
2:20 barrier _ probably running closer to 2:18 _ and it might as
well be her.
</P>
<P>
   That was then.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Kristiansen took a couple of runs at 2:20, but
never quite pulled it off.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has anyone else. Kristiansen's 2:21:06 in London is
still considered the women's record because most feel that the
2:20:47 that Kenyan Tegla Loroupe posted last year at Rotterdam was
not a valid record because she received too much assistance during
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kristiansen remains surprised that no one has cracked
2:20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very surprised,'' she said this week from her home in Oslo.
``And I'm not sure why it has not been broken. I felt I could have
done it twice. Once in London (1987) for sure. But I got cramps in
my legs wuth 10 kilometers to go. I finished the race and won in
2:22 something, but it was so, so disappointing. With eight
kilometers to go, I was on pace for a 2:18 or 2:19.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a marathon, you have to finish the whole race for your
pace,'' she said. ``Nothing helps if you say you were good enough
and did it half the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, takes not a thing away from what Kristiansen
has accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, she comes back to Boston to celebrate just one of those
many highlights. She is one of the guests invited back in what has
become a yearly ritual to honor former winners. She will be here
and plans to run Monday on the 10th anniversary of her second
Boston win.
</P>
<P>
   What a win it was. Little drama, lots of domination.
</P>
<P>
   At first, as usual, she thought of 2:20 mark or at least a shot
at her world record, but Boston that day was way too warm, pushing
70 degrees, and she settled for a win. She ran 2:24:33, 22 seconds
faster than her Boston winning time in 1986 and more than four
minutes faster than runnerup Marguerite Buist of New Zealand. Just
as impressive, only 25 men beat her that day. Samuelson, fighting
injuries, finished a gutsy ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't think Ingrid is the world's best athlete, you're
kidding yourselves,'' Samuelson said that day.
</P>
<P>
   Kristiansen has been back to Boston twice since. The 100th
running in 1996 was fun and she ran a 2:39 to finish second in the
Masters division. She ran in 1991 and that was not nearly as much
fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going real good for halfway and then almost broke
down,'' she said. ``I came in fifth place or something (actually
sixth in 2:29:51). The course was tough and everything was tough.
When you're used to winning the race, it's tough to come in fifth
or sixth.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, she had adjusted her approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been so many years now since I really did push
training,'' she said this week. ``Now I feel I'm turning 43 (which
she did last month) and my time is over and a whole new generation
of runners is coming. The first year or two was tough. I still felt
OK, but as a runner I wasn't good enough. I tried to compete, but I
didn't make it. That was tough. In 1996, that was nice. I went into
the race just for fun. I was looking around, speaking to everyone
and running because I like it. It's easy now. I put no pressure on
myself and nobody else has any pressure on me. Then it's easy to
compete.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, said her husband, Arve, their son Gaute, 15, is the
runner in the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faster than his mother and his father,'' Arve said. ``But
we're very, very conservative with exposing him to competition.
It's something about having been in this running monkey business,
we are very careful about doing too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaute is the oldest of the Kristiansens' three children. Ingrid
coaches with a local club and one of her runners is in the
Rotterdam Marathon this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she waits for someone to break 2:20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Elana Meyer from South Africa could do it, but now I
think maybe she is a better half marathoner,'' Kristiansen said.
``Of course, a lot of Japanese runners maybe could have done it but
they're pushing too hard. And the Kenyans maybe are running too
many races. To be a real good marathon runner you need some years
to prepare. Young girls need some years, but I don't think Kenyan
girls get all the years. They have too many races for a few years
and then they are breaking down.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she heads back to the site of a couple of her
greatest triumphs, little concerned about race times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a fun runner, and I mostly ski in the winter,'' she said.
``I hope to run good enough to be between 2:45 and three hours. I
have not been running too many long runs. I will try and I will
see, but the most important thing now for me is to have fun. I do
it for fun. I will be happy if I do a good race, of course, but
it's not so important anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
