<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-FARRIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRIS FARRIS'S FORTUNES HAVE TURNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kris Farris doesn't understand it. How did he go from being one
of the best offensive tackles in college football last season _ the
best, if you put stock in voting for the Outland Trophy _ to
someone who is ``soft, disinterested,'' and not worth a first-round
pick in Saturday's National Football League draft?
</P>
<P>
   ``To me the whole thing is absurd,'' Farris said Tuesday from
his Southern California home. ``I didn't stop being a good football
player because I did or didn't do a few things in the NFL combine.
There's no doubt in my mind that whomever drafts me is getting the
best offensive tackle in the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is open for debate. If you believe the
draftniks, Farris, the former UCLA standout, is no better than the
fifth- or sixth-best tackle in a draft that is deep in offensive
linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Patriots, who need to restock the offensive line,
should consider Farris, who opted to pass up his senior season
because of what former New York Giants general manager George Young
labeled the ``planet theory of football.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why he selected a huge lineman, Young once said,
``There are only so many people on the planet that size that can
play offensive tackle in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 7 inches, 310 pounds, Farris fits that mold. But where
he doesn't fit the NFL mold is in his outlook on life outside
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to tell people,'' said Farris. ``It's
frustrating. What am I supposed to do? If I don't drool or eat raw
meat, that makes me less than a football player? I tell people,
`Look at the whole body of my work.' ''
</P>
<P>
   What the NFL people are saying about Farris is that he is not
strong enough, not athletic enough. In the combine, he hurt himself
by failing to do the requisite mumber of lifts during a workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' said Farris. ``I go in there and do 20 lifts
of 225 pounds and I'm not strong enough. I work out the next week
for a team and do 23 reps, which is way above normal. People just
pigeonhole you.''
</P>
<P>
   Farris has done his best to convince people. He has worked out
for the Eagles, Falcons, and Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team that has worked me out has been impressed with what
I've done,'' said Farris.
</P>
<P>
   Farris does not apologize for his interests outside of football.
He grew up in a family where sports was not a passion. As a kid, he
would take part in plays or recitals with his three sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to California from Minnesota when he was 7, Farris didn't
become passionate about football until he started playing in high
school. Even then, it started out as a slight interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't even planning on playing fooball,'' said Farris.
``But the coaches just kind of told me this would be a great thing.
I didn't know what I was doing. They just pointed me in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, Farris did what a smart kid with athletic ability
generally does. He got better and better and better.
</P>
<P>
   ``From where he was when he came here and where he is now, is
unbelievable,'' said UCLA offensive line coach Mark Weber. ``You
could just see the improvement each day, each game.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the knocks against him, particularly by Mel Kiper,
who is now projecting him from low second to third round, are so
frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be wild and it might take a while,'' Farris said
about Saturday. ``I've already prepared my parents, telling them
that they could be watching the draft for a few hours before I get
picked. But I know that when I do, I'm going to give the team that
picks me the best offensive tackle in the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked where he would like to wind up, Farris gave the stock
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't matter,'' he said. ``But if the Patriots need
offensive lineman, I'd love to come there and get a chance to prove
that I can play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
