<SLUG> BC-TAXES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SALES TAX IS CALLED `IRRATIONAL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES M. ODATO  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Ever wonder why Kool-Aid is taxed and Tang isn't?
What about baby diapers bearing taxes while similar items for
adults are tax-free? And what's the reason that honey-roasted
peanuts are taxed but salted peanuts are not?
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't the slightest idea,'' said Sen. Roy Goodman, a
Manhattan Republican who conducted a 2 1/2-hour hearing in the
state Senate Tuesday on the sales tax. ``It's a purely irrational
section of the law that can be changed by regulation of the tax
department.''
</P>
<P>
   Acting Tax Commissioner Arthur Roth promised that a team from
his department will examine inconsistencies. He told a reporter
that his goal _ should he become tax commissioner _ is to be able
to tell his children that he was the one who ended such mysteries
as why consumers are taxed for ice cream cones but not for pints of
ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Roth said progress is being made, and pointed to the marshmallow
mess of last summer when small marshmallows _ previously considered
candy _ joined big marshmallows among the non-taxed groceries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marshmallow tax is symbolic of the ... insanity of the tax law
as it now exists,'' Roth said. Indeed, candies are taxed, as are
prepared foods, even if the same products can be found elsewhere
sans taxes.
</P>
<P>
   New York was among the last states to impose a sales tax, in
1965, and the statute it enacted is perhaps the most complicated in
the nation, Roth suggested. That is largely because of the number
of exemptions _ about 115 _ on such things as textbooks, clothing,
certain food products and medicines.
</P>
<P>
   The tax has grown to 4 percent from 2 percent and generates
about $7.3 billion in revenues to the state, 22 percent of the
total state tax receipts. Another $7.5 billion is collected by
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, several governors have studied and considered
reforms, Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   Holding up different bottles of juice, Michael Rosen, general
counsel for the Food Industry Alliance of New York State, said
someone in state government decided to tax Hawaiian Punch and
cranberry juice because the beverages are not 70 percent natural
juices. But frozen versions of these drinks are not taxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the tax policy?'' Rosen asked. ``Oranges and
pineapples are good but cranberries are bad? Frozen is good and
liquid is bad?''
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers are complaining regularly at the service windows of
supermarkets, said Janet Dow, a scan file coordinator at the
Saratoga Springs (N.Y.) Hannaford Supermarket. She said she got one
story from a state official about why Tang is the only powdered
drink not taxed: ``We were told (it was) because it was the first
food that went to the moon,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tax department spokesman Chris McKenna, however, said the Tang
exemption is a mystery. ``Nobody knows why,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
