<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ The latest developments in the
NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia. Developing. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ As rank and file Congress members
return Tuesday from recess, President Clinton briefs many of them
on Kosovo at the White House. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-KOSOVO _ JACINZE, Macedonia _ He sat atop a cot inside a
dusky army tent, clinging to his three small children as though he
would never let go, dragging on a cigarette as though it could have
been his last. A simple farmer who arrived on foot Tuesday from
Kosovo, he was safe from the Serbs. He was warm, dry and cared for
in a refugee camp run with precision and prosperity by NATO. But
Haziz Shaqiri(CQ) could not speak. He could only weep, for he and
his family were forced to make a tragic choice and pay a horrible
price to escape Kosovo's violent upheaval. (Holmes, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   STARR _ WASHINGTON _ Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr and the
three judges who appointed him testify Wednesday before a Senate
committee considering whether to extend to indpendent counsel law.
(Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SCANDAL _ WASHINGTON _ Congress Wednesday looks at the
International Olympic Committee with a scheduled House Commerce,
Science and Transportation Committee review of the IOC's Salt Lake
City 2002 Winter Olympics bribery scandal. If found wanting during
the hearings, the IOC's tax exempt status could be revoked.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   BEGINNING _ WASHINGTON _ British cosmologist Stephen Hawking and
other scientists, theologians and philosophers talk about the
history of time at a daylong AAAS conference
</P>
<P>
   on whether the universe had a ``beginning,'' such as the
postulated Big Bang, or is a ``beginningless'' place. (Nesmith, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BEGINNING-MOVIE _ WASHINGTON _ Fearing a political backlash, the
National Air and Space Museum for a time barred words such as
``evolution'' and ``Big Bang'' from the script for its latest
educational movie, ``Cosmic Voyage.'' (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-SAVINGS _ WASHINGTON _ A survey of 1,000 parents in the
34 states that offer college savings plans shows that 73 percent
say they are saving for their children's college, but only 4
percent are using their state-sponsored, tax-protected tuition
plans and many say their savings goal is under $10,000. State
treasurers and college-plan administrators, who commissioned the
survey, discuss its implications Wednesday morning. (Mollison, Cox
Nedws Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   WEB-FUTURE _ CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Internet pioneer Tim Berners-Lee
lectures on ``The Future of the Web'' as part of the MIT Laboratory
for Computer Science's 35th birthday celebration. (Glass, Cox Nedws
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-WILDFIRES _ Amid concerns about a new round of wildfires
in Florida comes a new wildfire threat from the north. Outdoor
burning has been banned in 32 North Carolina counties, including
the Nantahala and Pisgah National Forests. Over the weekend, 60
homes were evacuated in Wilkes County, N.C. Meanwhile, the Georgia
Forestry Commission fought 119 wildfires that damaged 1,221 acres
over the weekend. A status report on drought worries in the
Southern Appalachians. (Harmon, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ALA-LOTTERY _ MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ Waiting for the Alabama Senate
to vote to establish a state lottery. (MWilliams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FREAKNIK-CONVENTIONS _ Freaknik is just a day away. But visitors
to the city will include not only tens of thousands of students,
but educators, engineers and IT workers as well. Thousands of
conventioneers will also be in the city during part or all of
Freaknik weekend, but convention bureau officials and meeting
planners expect few problems. They cite smaller crowds and better
planning with many activities held within the hotels. (Poole,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   STRANDED-SKATERS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Nearly every Friday after the
rink's 11:30 p.m. closing time, Skateworld general manager Rick
Corson takes on a job he doesn't want _ late-night babysitter.
Corson finds himself stuck with one or two kids, some as young as 8
years old, whose parents have dropped them off and, for whatever
reason, failed to pick them up. Often, well beyond midnight, the
children can't reach their parents by phone. ``I'm in a terrible
spot here,'' Corson said. ``Could someone please direct me what to
do?'' Police used to retrieve the stranded kids and try to contact
their parents, but now they say they will no longer perform
babysitting duties. And Montgomery County Children Services said it
had no legal authority to take the children into custody. Kettering
police have told Corson the children are no longer his legal
responsibility after the rink's posted hours have ended. ``They
told me I should turn out the lights, lock up and go home,'' he
said. ``But what about my moral obligation? It's a different world
out there these days.'' (DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DROPOUT-SCANDAL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The Austin school
district, attempting to prevent its high schools from being rated
``low-performing,'' worked hard to purge students' names from
dropout lists sent to the state, documents subpoenaed by a Travis
County grand jury show. School district administrators in 1996 and
1997 calculated exactly how many students _ of each ethnic group at
each school _ could drop out before a school would receive the
state's lowest rating, internal school district memos show. Kay
Psencik, the deputy superintendent who last week was indicted along
with the district in the test-tampering investigation, wrote a 1996
memo to area superintendents directing them to coach principals
``in strategies to improve their dropout rates.'' (Kurtz, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-SCHOLARSHIPS _ RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ Just four years
after the World Wide Web became widely popular, Web skills have
made their way into the academic mainstream _ so much so that
scholarships are emerging nationwide to reward and court students
who have on-line expertise. ``It's like any other talent, whether
it be music or art or science or athletics,'' said Timothy
McDonough, a spokesman for the American Council on Education, an
organization of 1,800 colleges and universities. ``Institutions are
trying to find a mix of students . . . (and the Web) is very much a
part of the learning environment now.'' (Peltz, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-JASON _ LOCHIEL, South Africa _ Here, they call him
Musa. The word means ``kindness'' in Zulu, but Jason Carter says
that's not necessarily why the villagers of Lochiel, a village on
the eastern edge of South Africa, call him that. It just happens to
be a common name. What is clear, though, is that they love him.
(Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-TURNER _ LOCHIEL, South Africa _ Moses Turner has
traveled such a long road since his childhood in the Timothy Road
neighborhood of Athens, Ga., that he has almost come full circle.
The son of a carpenter and a maid, he couldn't go to the University
of Georgia, even though it was in his back yard, because UGA in
1958 accepted no black students. But he eventually became a dean at
Texas Tech and then spent 15 years at Michigan State, part of that
time as vice president. Now, at age of 60, Turner has turned his
career in a different direction: He's the new country director for
the Peace Corps in South Africa. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS
</P>
