<HEADLINE>
TENNIS-BALL CAR HAS 4 ON THE FLOOR AND 7,000 ON THE BODY 

</HEADLINE>
 CAR-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (with art) 
 
By SHERRY THOMAS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Michael Hewlett received an urgent, almost breathless
telephone call one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids called us from the neighbor's house and said, `There
is this really trashy car in the driveway,''' Hewlett said,
grinning.
</P>
<P>
   He likes to tell this story.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `I think the house is being robbed.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett and his wife, Paule Hewlett, looked at each other. It
could only mean one thing.
</P>
<P>
   It had arrived. The car their tennis partner had told them
about. The car they had discussed two days earlier over sushi. The
one they would (deep breath) enter in the Art Car Parade on April
17 in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we were committed,'' said Michael Hewlett, joined by his
wife and their co-conspirators: Bill Ludlam and his wife, Lynn
Jeffcoat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gauntlet had been passed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That was February, about eight weeks before the members of the
Westside Tennis Club set proceeded to hot-glue 7,000 tennis balls
to a 1986 Pontiac Firebird.
</P>
<P>
   They were rebels with a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I've always wanted to do,'' said Paule
Hewlett, telling how she instigated the whole thing one day at
lunch. ``We had talked about it a couple of years ago,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Michael Hewlett added. ``But that was tax time and all
the events were during the week.''
</P>
<P>
   But those facts didn't seem to matter this year.
</P>
<P>
   And so, Ludlam's Firebird, ``Brake Point,'' awash in a few
gallons of lime, industrial-strength enamel with tennis balls
covering every inch (except the windshield and headlights), will be
one of about 250 entries in this weekend's 12th annual Art Car
Parade Powered by Pennzoil, slated to kick off at 12:30 p.m. in
downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The four are the epitome of what Jennifer McKay, assistant
director of the Orange Show Foundation, which organizes the parade,
called the ``can too'' faction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about this event in terms of three groups: the `have
to's,' the `want to's' and the `can too's,' spelled t-o-o,'' McKay
explained. ``The first group is the fringe, people living on the
edge. ... The `want to's' are the trained artists, who understand
the history of art but want to defy the gallery system and respond
to art. And then there are these folks _ people who glue thousands
of tennis balls to their car _ because they `can too.'''
</P>
<P>
   Since the first Art Car Parade was held in Houston 12 years ago,
the ``have to's'' have given way to the ``can too's,'' with more
than 60 percent of parade entries coming from school groups and
people like the Hewletts, Ludlam and Jeffcoat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started going to the parade when the kids were really
little,'' said Paule Hewlett, a free-lance writer. ``It was just so
funky, and everybody seemed to be in the best mood.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Jeffcoat, who works as an art teacher at Memorial Middle
School, will be riding in the parade this weekend with no concept
of what she will be in for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you're going to now,'' Paule Hewlett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what's made this so easy is we didn't have anyone
ramrodding,'' said Ludlam.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no preconceived thing,'' his wife added.
</P>
<P>
   Ludlam said their attitude was ``let's just do the car.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say who came up with the tennis ball idea, but it
was a natural. They liked tennis. They played tennis. Getting
tennis balls would be cheap and easy (or so they thought), and
glueing them on would be a breeze (or so they thought).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first executive decision was to paint the car,'' Paule
Hewlett said. ``So Bill took a tennis ball to the paint store and
... ''
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy matched it perfectly,'' Ludlam said as he finished her
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real challenge was how to stick them on,'' Michael Hewlett
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can tell you, shoe goo doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   The foursome collected what they believed to be more tennis
balls than they'd ever need (including some scavenged from behind
the fence at a local tennis tournament) and set out one Saturday
afternoon to get sticking.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 45 minutes later we were done,'' Paule Hewlett said.
``It covered the spoiler.''
</P>
<P>
   They quickly put the word out: Need tennis balls. Need tennis
balls fast. Then one day, they got a call from a friend who said,
``The pro down at Lakeside has got a million tennis balls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' they said. ``We'll be right over.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, they took ``Brake Point'' out for a spin,
cruising down the neighborhood cul de sac (dropping a few tennis
balls along the way) and tossing the lime green beauties to
spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so much fun,'' said Ludlam. ``It felt like Mardi
Gras.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Brake Point'' is just one of several new art cars to be
unveiled this weekend. Others include Susan Poole's ``Bruiser
Mower,'' a hot rod riding lawn mower, and Theresa Keefe's
work-in-progress, ``Pray Wheel,'' a Honda painted with large
black-and-white spirals overlaid with text from a wide variety of
creation stories, philosophies and religions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1434EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
