<HEADER>
A7857 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICAFOOD-HNS &LR;      04-14 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FESTIVAL OFFERS A TASTE OF SOUTHERN AFRICAN FOOD 

</HEADLINE>
 FOOD-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANN CRISWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Houston International Festival will offer many
Houstonians their first tastes of biltong (jerkylike air-dried meat
strips), bobotie (South African-style meatloaf), boerewors
(farmer's sausage) and other authentic foods from southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   This year's downtown festival, the 28th, takes place April 17-18
and April 24-25, and will honor 12 southern African countries, said
Cynthia Shepard Perry, chairwoman of the Houston Festival
Foundation Inc. and former ambassador to two African nations _
Sierra Leone and Burundi. She lived in Africa 18 years and sampled
foods all over the continent, visiting 35-40 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The honor countries are Angola, Botswana, Lesotho, Madagascar,
Malawi, Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania,
Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Foods from Chinese, Mexican, Italian, Continental, Southwestern,
Creole, Cajun and Caribbean menus will be featured, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Africa is a ``continent of cuisines,'' Jessica B. Harris wrote
in ``The Africa Cookbook: Tastes of a Continent'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $25). Its many cuisines have been influenced by France
(French Huguenots), England, the Netherlands, India and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa, particularly Cape Town, offers some of the most
sophisticated cuisine in Africa, but the ethnic cuisines have
remained separate until recently because of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that people are talking to each other, they're becoming
more aware,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are four concurrent culinary trends in South Africa _
Black African, Indian, Cape Malay (in Cape Town) and Dutch _ with
`pockets' of French and British,'' she said. Mozambique is known
for spicy foods, although dishes of many areas are bland. Indian
food has been in South Africa for many years; remember that Mahatma
Gandhi was in South Africa before he went to India.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest impression was how wonderful the food is,'' Harris
said. ``Cape Malay food was becoming more popular when I was in
Cape Town in 1996. Cape Malay food is very complex and to the
American palate, particularly the sophisticated palate, is more
interesting (than many African cuisines).''
</P>
<P>
   Cape Malay is Muslim, so there are Islamic influences. Harris
defines Cape Malay cuisine as ``a harmonious mixture of Dutch food
and slave spicing.'' The Cape Malay are a ``creolized'' mixture of
peoples from Malaysia, Madagascar, and northern and western Africa,
as well as indigenous Khoi and San people, who were the original
inhabitants of South Africa, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Desserts come from varied traditions, and there are many fruit
desserts, depending on the region and time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every area has a ``mealie'' (cornmeal) dish, Perry said.
Africans don't use the word corn; they have mealie, which when
ground is called mealie meal. Dried corn is maize; hominy is called
samp. Mealie pap is a porridge made from cornmeal; it resembles
grits or polenta but is firmer. There are lots of plantains and
lots of nuts, especially cashews, and rice and other grains.
</P>
<P>
   Staples include yams (not sweet potatoes), fufu (dumplings of
pounded yams), cassava (yuca), beans, cabbage, and other fresh
vegetables and fruits.
</P>
<P>
   Meat is popular, too. Combinations of meat (pork, beef and
chicken) are favored over single varieties for stews, Perry said.
Africans eat a lot of exotic meats, such as ostrich. Ostrich eggs
and omelets hardly raise an eyebrow.
</P>
<P>
   Barbecuing and grilling are common. Braai (barbecue that is
cooked on a grill over coals, but not smoked) is as popular in
South Africa as Texas barbecue is here, said Ettienne Leibman,a
native of South Africa and co-owner of Leibman's Wine &AMP; Fine Foods.
The usual accompaniment to braai is mealie meal with a traditional
tomato-onion sauce, along with a chutney and Worcestershire sauce.
Mealie meal is stirred with a special tool until it is thicker than
mashed potatoes. The tool resembles a primitive whisk or a dowel
rod with looped wires on one end.
</P>
<P>
   Leibman makes her own boerewors sausage and usually stocks
biltong and other South African specialties at her shop. Bobotie is
a popular entree at catered parties and South African wine
tastings. Sausage rolls and meat pies _ chicken, steak, steak and
mushroom, or steak and kidney pie _ are traditional South African
dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Africans could no more do without meat pies than
Americans could do without McDonald's,'' Leibman said.
</P>
<P>
   Afrikaaners are members of the ``White Nation,'' which speaks
English and Afrikaans. The first white settlers in what became
South Africa were Dutch and were known as Afrikaaners.
</P>
<P>
   In the home of the Afrikaaner, hospitality means lots of food,
said Clive Berkman of Clive's, a Houston restaurant. Berkman is a
native of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The table would be set with a white cloth and centered with a
huge bowl of fruit, along with cruets of vinegar and Worcestershire
sauce. Silverware and china, probably from England, are used.
Dinner might start with a hearty soup or fish and appetizer of
biltong or rock lobster tails. The entree often is Tomato or Green
Bean Bredie, stew made with a thick rib of mutton or lamb cooked
with tomatoes, potatoes and string beans.
</P>
<P>
   A hostess would probably serve hot sosaties, the South African
version of brochettes, accompanied by crisp biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   When a South African really wants to treat friends, the host
serves his or her special version of chicken pie, made with
chicken, ham or bacon, and hard-cooked eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Desserts would be fruit and cookies, or perhaps a rich pudding
or cake, served with African coffee or English tea.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may be handed a tall glass of cool mechow, a drink made
from cornmeal, prepared as a thin gruel and allowed to ferment with
a little sugar. It stands for two or three days, then is stirred
until smooth,'' Berkman said.
</P>
<P>
   Should you be invited to visit the circular huts in the kraals
(native towns) of any of the Bantu tribes as an honored guest, you
would be accorded the same hospitality as in all of Africa, he
said. Large earthenware pots of food would be spread on mats on the
floor. The menu would probably consist of putu, the thick mealie
porridge topped with a hot spicy stew and served with homemade
beer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
