<HEADLINE>
RECIPES FROM SOUTHERN AFRICA 

</HEADLINE>
 RECIPES-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Clive Berkman of Clive's in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
__ GRILLED PRAWNS PERIPERI PORTUGUESE STYLE
</P>
<P>
   _ 24 prawns (large shrimp)
</P>
<P>
   _ 1{ teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   _ 4 to 5 periperi, North African chilies or any hot red chilies,
crushed
</P>
<P>
   _ 4 garlic cloves, crushed
</P>
<P>
   _ Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   _ 4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 teaspoon mixed fresh herbs
</P>
<P>
   _ pound butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 tablespoon finely chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   _ Herb Rice (recipe comes after one for Grilled Prawns)
</P>
<P>
   RECIPE: Butterfly each shrimp, taking care to remove the vein
but not the shell. Combine salt, chilies, crushed garlic, lemon
juice, oil and herbs in food processor. Rub shrimp with mixture;
marinate 2 to 3 hours, covered, in the refrigerator. Place shrimp,
flesh side down, on a foil-lined baking sheet and place under
broiler until shrimp are golden brown. Melt butter, add chopped
garlic, cover and cook 3 minutes over low heat. Turn shrimp over
and cook the other side a few more minutes, basting with garlic
butter. Serve with Herb Rice. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   __HERB RICE
</P>
<P>
   _ 6 tablespoons butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 cup basmati rice
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   _ { cup chopped seeded tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 tablespoon chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   _ Salt and ground white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   RECIPE: Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Melt butter in ovenproof
casserole over medium heat. Add onion and cook until soft. Add rice
and cook, stirring, 2 minutes. Add stock, tomatoes and parsley.
Season lightly with salt and pepper. Cover with buttered wax paper
and a lid. Bake 20 minutes; do not stir during baking. Let sit a
few minutes, then stir to fluff rice. Adjust seasonings. Makes 4 to
6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   __CLIVE'S POTATO CRISPS
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 pound jumbo baking potatoes
</P>
<P>
   _ Oil for deep-frying
</P>
<P>
   _ Kosher salt and vinegar to taste
</P>
<P>
   RECIPE: Cut unpeeled potatoes into very thin slices; soak in
cold water 1 hour. Rub potatoes with your hands in water to
separate slices, remove starch and to keep slices from sticking
together while cooking. Drain slices and dry thoroughly with paper
towels. Plunge into hot (400-degree) oil in deep-fryer (watch
carefully to avoid spattering oil) and cook quickly, keeping oil at
400 degrees. Stir with a slotted spoon. When slices are golden
brown, remove from fryer, drain on paper towels and sprinkle with
salt. Serve immediately. Sprinkle with a little vinegar, if
desired. Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   __ SHANDY GAFF
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Africa Cookbook'' by Jessica Harris (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $25). The popularity of this thirst-quenching drink has
spread throughout English-speaking Africa, Harris writes. ``I had
my first taste of shandy in Lusaka, Zambia, in the 1970s. ... It's
a perfect beverage when you want the taste but not the potency of a
cold beer. You can personalize the shandy with a dash of a liqueur
like Grand Marnier.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 quart each: pilsner beer and ginger beer (ginger ale)
</P>
<P>
   RECIPE: Mix beer and ginger beer in a large pitcher or crock.
Add several ice cubes and let mixture chill. Serve cold over ice in
stemmed water glasses.
</P>
<P>
   __BOBOTIE
</P>
<P>
   Bobotie, originally Malaysian, is one of the national dishes of
South Africa. This version is from Ettienne Leibman of Leibman's
Wine &AMP; Fine Foods. She prepares it occasionally for friends or when
featuring South African food at catered dinners.
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 slices whole-wheat bread
</P>
<P>
   _ { cup milk
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 pounds ground beef (such as ground round)
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 to 3 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 medium onions, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 garlic cloves, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 tablespoons curry powder
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 tablespoon each: brown sugar and turmeric
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   _ { teaspoon each: ground cloves and nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 tablespoon vinegar
</P>
<P>
   _ { cup seedless or golden raisins (optional)
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 tablespoons chutney (recipe tested with Mrs. Ball's chutney)
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/4 cup chopped blanched almonds
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 tablespoon dried (desiccated) coconut
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 Granny Smith apples, grated with the peel
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 tablespoon ketchup
</P>
<P>
   _ 4 fresh lemon leaves or bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   _ Topping (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   _ Sliced bananas
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 limes, halved
</P>
<P>
   _ Chutney
</P>
<P>
   _ Chopped onion and tomato salad with cilantro (pico de gallo)
</P>
<P>
   RECIPE: Soak bread in milk until liquid is absorbed; squeeze out
excess and add bread to ground beef. Heat oil; add onions and saute
until lightly browned. Add garlic; saute 1 minute. Add curry
powder, brown sugar, turmeric, salt, cloves, nutmeg and pepper to
onions; cook 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add ground beef mixture; cook 3 to 5 minutes, stirring
frequently (do not brown meat). Remove from heat. Add vinegar,
raisins, chutney, almonds, coconut, apples and ketchup. Mix well
and place in lightly greased 13-by-9-by-2-inch glass baking dish.
Push lemon leaves into top of meat mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Make Topping, pour over meat and
bake 45 minutes, until custard topping is set and lightly browned.
Serve with bananas, a squeeze of lime, chutney, and chopped onion
and tomato salad. Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   __TOPPING
</P>
<P>
   _ 1{ cups milk
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 extra-large eggs
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 teaspoons lemon extract
</P>
<P>
   RECIPE: Beat milk and eggs lightly. Add lemon extract.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
