<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7867 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSPAPERS-HNS &LR;      04-14 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER EDITORS ARE TOLD THEY ARE DINOSAURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You're dinosaurs. But it's not all your fault.
</P>
<P>
   That was the message Intel Chairman Andy Grove delivered to a
crowd of newspapers editors gathered here for the American Society
of Newspaper Editors convention.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers, said the co-founder of the sixth most profitable
company in the nation, are waging a nearly unwinnable contest for
readers who can slake their thirst for breaking news in other
media, including the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   But newspapers may be able to recapture readers by concentrating
on ``interpretative'' reporting that portrays the context in which
a news story occurs, Grove added.
</P>
<P>
   Providing context, he said, is the job of those gathered to hear
him speak. ``That's what editors are supposed to be doing,'' Grove
said. ``I don't think you are doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Grove was quick to add that newspaper publishers, who are
cutting newsroom costs to save a dwindling bottom line, shoulder
the blame for readership decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't save yourself out of it,'' Grove said, describing
his prescription for the newspaper industry malaise. ``You (have
to) invest out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The current newspaper industry has ``run its course,'' a process
fueled by competition from the World Wide Web, he said, adding that
the demise has been a process of stealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will know (about a business crisis) when it's almost too
late,'' Grove told the editors. He compared the newspaper
industry's continuing readership and advertiser decline to Intel's
near ruination in the '80s when intense competition gutted the
company's memory chip business.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Intel's losses in that market equaled the cumulative
profits the company had made in its previous 15 years of operation.
Intel, under Grove's hand, cleaved off that business, redirecting
all its efforts into the computer processing chip business.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe a look into the abyss will encourage newspaper
publishers to beef up newsrooms and give the readers a depth of
coverage needed to compete with electronic media, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sight of gallows sharpens the mind,'' Grove observed.
</P>
<P>
   The Intel chairman had some encouraging words for modern-day
business journalists, saying they are much more knowledgeable about
complex high-tech issues than their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be bad in the '80s,'' he said, but today's
high-tech reporter is a ``journalist who knows stuff about your
business that you don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech was met with praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always good to hear worse-case scenarios,'' said Sidney
Goldberg, senior vice president and general manager of the New York
newspaper syndication company United Media. ``It's like a shot in
the arm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quality, depth. Those are the things that matter,'' said
Everett Mitchell II, executive editor of the Salem, Ore., Statesman
Journal. ``Mr. Grove is in touch with what readers want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1441EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
