<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7868 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-CHINA-BOS &LR;      04-14 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING CHINA A PARTNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No single country will be more crucial to US interests in the
coming century than China, so it is folly to pretend that there is
any realistic alternative to a policy of engagement with Beijing.
Indeed, both the government on Taiwan and His Holiness the Dalai
Lama support some form of American engagement with China.
</P>
<P>
   The central question concerning Beijing has nothing to do with
the protectionist fantasy of banning Chinese goods or the Cold War
fantasy of containing a Chinese Communist threat. In the real world
US leaders have little choice but to mold US-Chinese relations in
ways that are best suited to promote Asian security, nuclear
nonproliferation, and the vitality of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   China's Prime Minister Zhu Rongji &UR;  &LR; has made it clear that his
portfolio is largely confined to economic matters, but within that
sphere he represents a type of Chinese leader who would have been
unimaginable during the Maoist era. He eschews the rhetoric of the
commissars in favor of the free-market pragmatism of his favorite
American interlocutors, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and the
Federal Reserve chairman, Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu may not be able to satisfy American calls for democracy and
human rights in China _ the ultimate modernization _ but his
determination to phase out subsidized state-owned enterprises is
consonant with Greenspanian precepts, as is his ardor to clean up
China's debt-laden state banks.
</P>
<P>
   The more successful Zhu is in managing the perilous transition
of the Chinese economy, the brighter prospects will be for the rest
of Asia and the global economy. The Clinton administration and its
Republican critics should transcend partisan politics and support
China's accession to the World Trade Organization, a development
sure to benefit America's own economic interests.
</P>
<P>
   The path to a strategic partnership with China is open. If it is
bungled, Washington could transform an aspiring partner into a
dangerous rival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1441EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7873 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-KOSOVO-0415-C     04-14 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-KOSOVO-0415-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM MACEDONIA: FOR ONE KOSOVAR FAMILY, FREEDOM AT A
HORRIBLE PRICE
 &HT;    With Photo; Photo mug of Holmes.
 &HT;    Moving in both International and Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEPROSTINO, Macedonia _ He sat atop a cot inside a dusky army
tent, clinging to his three small children as though he would never
let go, dragging on a cigarette as though it could have been his
last.
</P>
<P>
   A simple farmer who arrived on foot Tuesday from Kosovo, he was
safe from the Serbs. He was warm, dry and cared for in a refugee
camp run with precision and prosperity by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   But Haziz Shaqiri(CQ) could not speak. He could only weep, for
he and his family were forced to make a tragic choice and pay a
horrible price to escape Kosovo's violent upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   Shaqiri, 41, left Kosovo as a husband and father of seven; he
arrived in Macedonia a widower and father of five. Two of his
children are dead; the rest are now motherless.
</P>
<P>
   His 33-year-old wife Sevdije, a son named Ferid, 17, and a tiny
daughter, Vlora, 5, did not perish in a hail of Serb bullets or
burn when their house was pulverized. They had successfully evaded
Serb forces for two weeks when they succumbed to nature. They froze
to death in a snowstorm Saturday night while trying to follow a
mountain pass to safety in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   This part of the world has had a monopoly on mass misery and
suffering in the last few weeks, with nearly 1 million ethnic
Albanians of Kosovo on the move because of a grinding campaign of
ethnic cleansing by Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   The massive scale of the tragedy is embedded with heartbreaking
personal stories like the one played out by Shaqiri and his family
over the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   The family ran from ``one risk into another risk, away from
bullets into a natural disaster,'' said refugee Zebibe Imeri, 25,
who days earlier had taken the same mountain path to flee the
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Forced from their small village of Bitij in southern Kosovo two
weeks ago, the family managed to avoid Serb patrols by taking
shelter in nearby villages and hiding in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past weekend, they worked their way with about 25 other
villagers to a remote mountain path which crosses the snow-capped
peak of Ljuboten, at 2,499 meters one of the highest summits in the
Shar mountains that form the natural border between Yugoslavia to
the north, and Macedonia to the south.
</P>
<P>
   In the best of weather it is a 24-hour hike across the mountain.
Their timing could not have been worse. Clouds settled in Saturday
night and a snowstorm began to rage. Family members became
separated. The icy winds were so intense, some could not go on.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday morning, Shaqiri's wife and teenaged son were lifeless
in the snow on the Kosovo side of the border. Shaqiri managed to
drag their bodies down the mountain to the nearby village of Brod,
where he buried them Monday in unmarked graves.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Shaqiri set off over the mountain, only to reunite
Tuesday morning with the rest of his family at a refugee camp in
Macedonia. There, he discovered that his 5-year-old girl also was
dead.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the storm, a fellow refugee had offered to carry
the little girl, Vlora, on his shoulders. Only after they had
reached the Macedonian side of the border did the refugees realize
that Vlora had frozen to death atop his shoulders. The girl, and an
unrelated woman who also died in the cold, were buried Monday in
the Macedonian town of Tetovo.
</P>
<P>
   The events above were described by relatives, including
Shaqiri's older brother, Muharem, who made the fatal trek with the
group and wept uncontrollably as he told two reporters what had
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Overcome with shock and raw grief, Shaqiri could not speak, nor
did we ask him to.
</P>
<P>
   His now-oldest child, 14-year-old Vahid, sat on a separate cot
and sobbed, hiding his face from the crowd inside the tent. A
daughter, 9-year-old Shiqipe was being treated for frostbite by
German doctors in a hospital tent at the camp. The three other
children, including two-year-old Arlinda, were clinging to their
father and watching the adults around them cry.
</P>
<P>
   I asked our ethnic Albanian translator, tears streaming down her
face as she heard the story, to whisper to Shaqiri our condolences
for his losses. I asked her to add that we would tell his story to
Americans so that they could understand his personal tragedy and
the predicament of his people.
</P>
<P>
   He never broke his vacant stare, but slowly nodded in
acknowledgement. He wanted his story known, his brother told us,
but simply could not tell it.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1445EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7874 &Cx1f; tad-z
