<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7890 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSPAPERS-HNS &LR;      04-14 0334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY LEADER HAS ADVICE FOR AMERICA'S NEWSROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The chairman of one of America's most successful
technology companies told newspaper publishers and editors that
they must invest in their news operations if they are to survive
the crush of information available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers are waging a contest for readers who can quench their
thirst for breaking news in other media, Andy Grove, the chairman
of the Intel Corp., told the American Society of Newspaper Editors
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But newspapers may be able to recapture readers by concentrating
on ``interpretative'' reporting that portrays the context in which
a news story occurs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what editors are supposed to be doing,'' Grove said.
``I don't think you are doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Grove, whose company produces the microchips that run computers,
was quick to add that publishers, who have cut newsroom costs to
boost profits, shoulder the blame for readership decline. He
encouraged publishers to invest in their news operations and give
the readers a depth of coverage needed to compete with electronic
media.
</P>
<P>
   While newspaper circulations declined for years, readership has
stabilized and even grown in some markets. But most newspaper
companies also are investing in Internet sites to complement their
print editions and reach out to younger people.
</P>
<P>
   Grove's message drew support from some of the audience of
editors meeting this week in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quality, depth. Those are the things that matter,'' said
Everett Mitchell II, executive editor of the Salem (Ore.) Statesman
Journal. ``Mr. Grove is in touch with what readers want.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always good to hear worse-case scenarios,'' said Sidney
Goldberg, senior vice president and general manager of the New York
newspaper syndication company United Media. ``It's like a shot in
the arm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
