<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7926 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARADISE-AND-OIL-NYTS     04-14 1506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARADISE-AND-OIL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARADISE AND OIL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    FIVE COLOR SLIDES showing creatures in the rain forest are
available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of this article. The art can
be sent by mail or overnight delivery, using your FedEx or Airborne
delivery number. Please specify that you want the art when you
order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JARED DIAMOND  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   As the plane banked toward a dirt airstrip, I looked out on New
Guinea's tropical rain forest, biologically one of the richest
environments on Earth. Suddenly, this embodiment of beauty was
shattered by a column of burning gas flaring up from an oil field.
The heat withered nearby trees, a perfect metaphor for human
desecration of nature.
</P>
<P>
   Then something large moved near the oil field, and I was
astonished to see it was a cassowary. These big, shy, ostrichlike
flightless birds that depend on undamaged forest are rarely found
anywhere near the disturbances people create. How could such an
elusive bird survive 10 feet from that searing flare?
</P>
<P>
   I have been studying birds and exploring the biology of New
Guinea for 35 years. My most recent project took place along the
Kikori River within the nation of Papua New Guinea, which occupies
the eastern half of the island. A decade ago, the discovery of oil
threatened the remote paradise.
</P>
<P>
   A consortium of oil companies, called Joint Venture Partners,
runs New Guinea's largest operating oil and natural gas field along
the Kikori. It is managed by a subsidiary of Chevron. From wells
100 miles inland and as high up as 4,400 feet, a pipeline carries
oil to the Gulf of Papua, where it is pumped into tankers.
</P>
<P>
   Oil is not the only danger to this pristine rain forest. Much of
it is slated to be cut down for timber.
</P>
<P>
   I was wary before I left for this trip, but from the moment I
landed at the airstrip in Moro, the partnership's headquarters at
the inland end of the pipeline, we were in for constant surprises.
Private security guards working for the company began rummaging
through our luggage, checking for items forbidden in the
partnership's lease area _ drugs, alcohol, material deemed
pornographic and firearms and other weapons.
</P>
<P>
   After the search, we were welcomed to offices of Moro's World
Wildlife Fund _ a partner with Chevron to preserve the Kikori area.
Here we found comforts we were not used to in the outback:
air-conditioned rooms, e-mail and phone links, dinner in a
luxuriously stocked cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Before sunrise the next morning, I grabbed my binoculars for a
little bird-watching. I didn't expect much, but within hearing and
sight of the camp _ and its gas flare _ I watched some of New
Guinea's shiest and most heavily hunted bird species, including
harpy eagles, vulturine parrots and birds of paradise. What were
these retiring denizens of the rain forest doing near manmade
structures?
</P>
<P>
   For the next month, I birded every day through the rain forest
that led all the way down to the sea along the pipeline. Hundreds
of feet above the road and the nearby Kikori flowed another river _
of birds in the sky. Near the oil camps and gas flares ventured not
only cassowaries and harpy eagles but every single one of the other
large, threatened bird species of the New Guinea lowlands.
</P>
<P>
   The fauna throughout the oil lease zone remains pristine because
the partnership keeps a tight rein on employees' activities.
Prohibitions on hunting, exporting animals and plants, collecting
any living thing, making gardens and cutting down trees minimizes
forest disturbance. The partnership also rigorously controls the
number of people who can come here, requiring company authorization
to arrive by plane.
</P>
<P>
   Why was the partnership so strict _ how were these rules
connected to making money? A bird-watching Chevron executive
offered one answer: ``Bhopal, Exxon Valdez and the North Sea oil
rig'' _ notorious industrial disasters that cost Union Carbide,
Exxon and Shell Oil billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership has cause to worry about its activities in New
Guinea. Chevron learned its lesson the hard way when it cleared a
small summit on Mount Sisa for a helipad, intending to erect a
radio relay station there. As soon as Huli tribesmen living around
the base of the mountain saw helicopters hovering there, they began
climbing. On reaching the helipad, they introduced themselves and
announced their claim, demanding huge compensation for trespassing,
cutting trees and disturbing birds. Local Samberigi tribesmen later
hijacked chartered helicopters to enforce their demands. Faced with
lawsuits and bills for damages, Chevron abandoned the place.
</P>
<P>
   Similar considerations reinforced the partnership's desire to
keep environmental disturbances to a minimum. Local landowners also
get royalties on the oil pumped. The fees are a major source of
income for clans in the area. The partnership builds schools,
hospitals, roads and other public works at no cost.
</P>
<P>
   What I have witnessed along the Kikori has changed my mind about
the inevitability of environmental disaster when oil is pumped out
of the ground. But I worry about the other rivers I saw there,
rivers in the sky streaming constantly above me _ of birds, bats,
insects, spiders, seeds and pollen blown in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   As a bird-watcher, I was especially struck by the importance of
three components of the rivers. Most conspicuous were birds leaving
their roots daily to forage, or moving their roosts to track
seasonally shifting food supplies. Second were birds that hatch as
nestlings at one altitude, fly as juveniles to spend their early
years at some other altitude, then return as adults to build their
own nests and breed.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining bird movements were of individuals that disperse
only once in a lifetime, leaving their nest sites in search of new
breeding grounds. These movements are essential for maintaining
populations in habitats so small that they can support only one or
a few breeding pairs. For instance, I found a population of a high
altitude species otherwise missing in the conservation area _ the
superb bird of paradise. The population was just one adult male and
one female.
</P>
<P>
   All these movements of birds mean that a policy of landscape
management preserving only isolated pieces of natural habitat is
doomed to fail. The plant and animal populations in isolated
patches risk gradually going extinct unless a sea of natural
habitat surrounds and supports them. Instead, whole landscapes must
be preserved and managed.
</P>
<P>
   We have a model that may work: The oil partnership lease area
along the Kikori. It is the largest area of land rigidly controlled
and managed as an integrated entity in the country. Although the
reasons have to do with oil, not conservation, the requirements for
managing long subterranean oil pipelines have turned out to
coincide with the requirements for managing long aerial pipelines
of life.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; SIDEBAR: TIME TO STOP CUTTING DOWN TREES AS FAST AS THEY GROW &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's left of the world's forest is being logged at such a
breakneck pace that almost all the remaining tropical rain forests
in the world will be destroyed within 50 years. In some countries,
such as the Philippines and the Solomon Islands, they'll be gone
within a decade. Most logging operations are nonsustainable _ trees
are cut faster than they can regrow.
</P>
<P>
   What can be done to halt the juggernaut? One solution is a
benign cutting schedule, called eco-forestry, that attempts to
harvest trees no faster than new ones can grow to replace them.
</P>
<P>
   Because an increasing fraction of the buying public _ especially
in North America and Europe _ would prefer to buy responsibly
harvested timber products, logging companies increasingly label
their operations as sustainable.
</P>
<P>
   To certify such claims, a coalition of environmental groups,
indigenous peoples' groups and other interests have set up the
Forest Stewardship Council. Logging projects have now been
certified in 20 countries, and public response is so favorable that
the demand for certified timber products exceeds the supply.
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jared Diamond is a professor of physiology at UCLA Medical
School and a longtime contributing editor of Discover magazine. He
made his 17th visit to New Guinea last year under the auspices of
the World Wildlife Fund.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1507EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
