<HEADER>
A7928 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CROOKED-CHILD-NYTSF &LR;      04-14 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROOKED-CHILD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CROOKED CHILD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR ILLUSTRATION is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers
of this article. The art can be sent by mail or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number. Please specify that
you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By SHARRON SUSSMAN  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Little Gabrielle, 3 years old, sat mutely on the examining
table. Her legs dangled over the edge, revealing a right knee that
protruded about an inch farther than the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can fix her, can't you, Doctor?'' her mother asked
anxiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her pediatrician was very concerned,'' I said, evading the
question. In fact, her pediatrician had brought the X-rays straight
to my office door. Orthopedic surgery is rooted in a long tradition
of preventing deformity in children. (Orthopedics comes from two
Greek words meaning ``straight'' and ``child.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``When did you first notice something was wrong?'' I asked the
mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister noticed while watching a videotape we made at a
birthday party. Gaby was wearing shorts, and in one shot from the
back, I could see that her bottom was kind of tilted and that she
limped a little.''
</P>
<P>
   The X-ray suggested that the problem had developed gradually.
Gabrielle's right hip joint was perfectly normal, but the left hip
socket was enlarged and slightly shallow. Worse, the round head of
the femur wasn't centered in the socket but had slipped up toward
the outer edge.
</P>
<P>
   Gabrielle had a problem called developmental dysplasia, a
general term for a group of malformations in the hip joints of
children. Nobody knows what causes them. But early detection makes
dysplasia easier to treat.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, evaluation of the hips is an important part of
examining newborns. I had no way of knowing what Gabrielle's
examination had been like when she was a newborn. Most likely, she
had been born with slightly loose ligaments in her hips. As she
began to walk, and especially after she grew taller and heavier,
the increasing pressure on her hip joint would have caused the ball
of the femur to start slipping out of place. Eventually the ball
could work its way completely out of the socket. The hip would most
likely deteriorate, causing Gabrielle painful arthritis by the time
she was in her 30s.
</P>
<P>
   Gabrielle was easy to examine, but when she let me measure her
legs and move them through a range of motion, I noticed a slight
tightness in her left inner thigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not exactly an emergency,'' I told her mother, ``but I
want to bring Gabrielle into the hospital and get that hip back
where it belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Will she need surgery?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' I said. ``And there'll be some time in a cast too.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Gabrielle was back in my examining room with
her family. I put up the X-ray, which easily showed the difference
between her two hip joints. The hard part was explaining the
treatment: A simple manipulation could possibly relocate the ball
in the socket, or I might have to perform an invasive operation to
clear away any tissue obstructing the socket. Either way, Gabrielle
would have to spend time in a cast stretching from her waist to her
ankle. Then she would have to wear a brace for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of all this, the hip could migrate back out of the
socket, even years after surgery. That would mean another
operation, possibly cutting bone.
</P>
<P>
   After a moment, the father asked, ``Would all this have been
necessary if we had noticed it sooner?'' I told him we couldn't
know for certain.
</P>
<P>
   Gaby was admitted to the hospital a week later, and the cast
technician and I set up traction to draw her legs gently down and
apart, gradually stretching the soft tissue. In the operating room,
I could see that traction had helped. But with Gabrielle
anesthetized to allow her muscles to relax fully, the tendon in her
groin remained tight.
</P>
<P>
   So I made a tiny incision, and cut the tendon with a small
scalpel. That, I hoped, would free up movement in the joint. I
flexed and rotated her thigh until the ball appeared well seated in
the socket. I held Gabrielle's legs in position while the
technician applied the fiberglass cast that would stabilize her
hip.
</P>
<P>
   Gabrielle recovered easily from the anesthetic _ as children
usually do _ and was discharged. At her one-week post-op visit, her
X-rays looked fine. Five weeks later, a new set of X-rays showed
that the hip was still in good position, so we cut the cast down to
midthigh length.
</P>
<P>
   When the family came back for final cast removal, everyone's
spirits were high. Gaby held her mother's hand tightly as the loud,
buzzing cast saw cut away. She didn't cry or complain as the brace
was fitted. Then she headed home with her parents to celebrate _
and to take a bath.
</P>
<P>
   But when I saw the next X-ray three weeks later, my heart sank.
With the little extra motion allowed by the brace, and the stresses
of walking on the hip again, the ball had slipped right back to
where it had been before. I would have to go back to the operating
room.
</P>
<P>
   Gabrielle's parents read my face before I even started to speak.
``This is a setback,'' I said, ``not a disaster. We haven't lost
anything except a little time.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, I cut into the outer front of Gabrielle's left
hip. I separated layers of muscle and tendon down to the bag of
ligament and fibrous tissue that holds the joint together. I cut
away the thickened tissue and tightened the baggy upper part. When
I gently rotated Gaby's thigh inward, the ball fell into the socket
with no resistance. Then I held the hip where I wanted it while my
assistant put on the cast.
</P>
<P>
   Gaby was in her long cast for eight full weeks before she was
allowed to walk in a brace. She was as stiff as a board when I
finally let her spend a little time out of the brace, shortly after
her 4th birthday. Her X-rays continued to show a hip sitting
normally in the socket.
</P>
<P>
   Just before she started school, I examined Gaby again.
Everything looked great. ``Your daughter's not out of the woods
yet,'' I told her mother. ``She won't really be until her growth is
complete. I want to see her for new X-rays in three months, and
after that maybe we can go to every six months or a year between
visits.''
</P>
<P>
   I paused and took a deep breath. ``But I think she can stop
using the brace altogether now.''
</P>
<P>
   She smiled. I smiled. Gaby smiled, too, head down. ``Thank you,
Dr. Sussman,'' she said in a clear voice. I bent down and got a big
hug.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Dr. Sharron Sussman is an orthopedic surgeon in Berkeley,
Calif.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
