<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7930 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CLINTON-AZR &LR;      04-14 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON GETS PUNISHMENT DUE TO HIM  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE APRIL 14 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It is the perfect epilogue to a sorry burlesque. Just
as the cheating husband tries to sneak up the stairs to bed, the
long-suffering wife knocks him upside the head with a rolling pin.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody deserved a figurative clobbering at the hands of justice
more than Bill ``Tom Cat'' Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately, Lady Justice _ played by Judge Susan Webber
Wright _ delivered the well-placed blow with her contempt citation
against the president.
</P>
<P>
   The injured party in Bad Bill's naughty escapades was never
Hillary. She knew her knave, accepted his flaws and rode his fame
to power.
</P>
<P>
   The real cuckold was our sense of fairness _ not to mention the
office of the presidency and the confidence Americans naively place
in its occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Past presidents who conducted themselves with dignity and
contemporary Americans who demand integrity were deeply wounded by
Clinton's behavior. Only late-night comedians, columnists and
political cartoonists benefited from the spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Now we can all laugh with a little less cynicism as the errant
husband gets his comeuppance.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's action was the first formal finding of wrongdoing in
the Monica Lewinsky debacle. It may calm the spinning of long dead
American presidents who saw the office as something more than a
sexual playhouse. It should ease the minds of Americans who
wondered if there were any standards anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Wright called Clinton's lie, a lie. And she said even the
president of the United States is not allowed to do that under
oath.
</P>
<P>
   Some hoped that message would come through Kenneth Starr's
extremely long and expensive investigation. Some hoped it would
come in a Senate conviction of an impeached Clinton. But both those
procedures were tainted by charges that they were politically
motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's rolling pin wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wright deftly addressed the motives of both Clinton and
those who brought the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit in
which the president lied. She wrote: ``It simply is not acceptable
to employ deceptions and falsehoods in an attempt to obstruct the
judicial process, understandable as his aggravation with the
plaintiff's lawsuit may have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply not acceptable. That about says it.
</P>
<P>
   And it's about time. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1508EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
