<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7955 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      04-14 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO THE DEAD HAVE PCS IN HEAVEN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Some days you just never know what you'll find in the
old e-mail bag.
</P>
<P>
   Take last Friday, for example. There in my e-mail box was a
message from Harold Temmer asking, essentially, whether it was
possible for a dead man to use Temmer's computer to communicate
with the living.
</P>
<P>
   You read that right. I'm not making it up.
</P>
<P>
   Temmer, a long-time Sun City West, Ariz., resident, knows that
sounds crazy, but he's having trouble arriving at another
explanation for the funny thing that happened a couple weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   It all began when Temmer sat down at his PC and called up a
letter his wife had written to friends in Flagstaff. The letter was
written in January using an old DOS version of WordPerfect.
</P>
<P>
   Temmer printed the letter out and noticed that the name and
address of a Sun City man appeared at the end, as if this unknown
man had written the letter himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' Temmer said. ``At the close of the letter,
instead of my wife's name, there was neatly typed the name and
address of a complete stranger.''
</P>
<P>
   Temmer's wife doesn't remember seeing the name and address the
first time she printed the letter out, signed it and mailed it to
Flagstaff. (The Temmers are in the process of contacting the
recipients of the letter to see whether the strange name was at the
bottom.)
</P>
<P>
   It's not unheard of for people to find that their computers
contain personal information about strangers. Stores have been
known to resell used computers without first wiping hard drives
clean.
</P>
<P>
   But that explanation doesn't appear to apply in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Temmer swears that he bought his computer brand new about six
years ago, and that all the software he uses was purchased new.
</P>
<P>
   He also claims that nobody besides his wife uses the machine,
that his online use is limited to about an hour a week and that his
electronic address book contains only a handful of entries _ all
people or companies he communicates with.
</P>
<P>
   As if it wasn't weird enough that a stranger's name and address
appeared at the bottom of his wife's letter, Temmer soon learned
that the stranger has been dead for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up the Sun City address and called,'' Temmer said.
``I reached (the stranger's) wife. I explained why I called and
asked to speak to her husband. She told me that her husband had
died 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Temmer added, ``She said she doesn't own, and has never
owned, a computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. Anybody besides me starting to hear the Twilight Zone''
theme song?
</P>
<P>
   Temmer, a retired assistant vice chancellor with the University
of California-San Diego, is baffled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't accept that a hacker penetrated my DOS program to type
the name and address,'' he said. ``So is my computer haunted, or
what?''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I'm at a loss to explain this, too. My brain tells me
that there has to be a logical explanation, that, somehow, Temmer
is forgetting a crucial fact that would clear everything up.
</P>
<P>
   Right about now, you might be yelling, ``Hey! This guy might
have made the whole thing up!''
</P>
<P>
   I know that's possible. But even though Temmer admits he has no
way to prove all this really happened, I'm willing to take him at
his word _ if for no other reason than it's fun to try and figure
out how this might have happened.
</P>
<P>
   Temmer swears that he's never heard of the Sun City man, whose
identity I'm not publishing because the whole episode has upset his
widow. But, according to ``The Arizona Republic's'' obituaries, a
Sun City man with the same name did pass away in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   All this reminds me of a story I wrote for ``The Republic'' on
Oct. 30, 1995. The story dealt with ``instrumental
transcommunication,'' or ITC, in which people claim to have
communicated with the dead _ and vice versa _ using computers,
televisions, telephones, tape recorders and other gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds strange, I know. But the number of believers has
grown since 1995. As a matter of fact, the group now has its own
Web site at www.worlditc.org.
</P>
<P>
   If you check out that site, one of the things you can read is a
message a believer is said to have received in 1995 from author
Jules Verne.
</P>
<P>
   I told Temmer about all this, and we both had a good laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you buy into ITC, why would a dead guy pick on Temmer's
computer, and why would he write down his address? Why wouldn't he
write something like, ``Hello. How are you? I am fine. How are the
Yankees doing?''
</P>
<P>
   I thought it would be fun to share this story with everybody. If
anybody out there has any ideas, drop me an e-mail, and I'll pass
it on. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chat rooms, e-mail, Kosovo &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are some great Web sites and related services to check out:
</P>
<P>
   - Wouldn't it be great to have your very own chat room on your
very own Web site? One of the companies offering this deal is
Xoom.com (www.xoom.com). If you register with Xoom, the company
allows you to create your own Web page and host your own chats _
free. The catch is that Xoom reserves the right to display
advertising on your site.
</P>
<P>
   - Looking for a free, Web-based e-mail service? The March issue
of Internet magazine rates Yahoo! Mail (mail.yahoo.com) as the top
service. HotMail (www.hotmail.com) comes in a close second. ``The
range of services from Yahoo!, (its) crisp design and ease of use
make this an excellent choice,'' the reviewer said. sounds good to
me.
</P>
<P>
   - Hey Juno users! Wouldn't it be nice to see a Web page once in
a while? Now Juno users and anybody else with an e-mail-only
account can browse the Web via e-mail. At least that's what Tom
Dolan claims. His Web site (dolan.acu.edu/how &QL; 
to/howtogetwebpagesby &QL; 
email.htm) has the instructions. It sounds pretty easy. I tried it,
but as of this writing, the Web page I requested has not yet shown
up in my e-mail box.
</P>
<P>
   - As the crisis in Kosovo continues, you might want to turn to
the Web for a perspective that's different from the daily newspaper
or what you might find on CNN. For example, the Yugoslavian
government maintains a site about Kosovo at www.gov.yu/kosovo. And
a decidedly different slant can be found at the U.S. Information
Agency's Kosovo page at www.usia.gov/kosovo. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye &LR; home.net via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
