<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA A MAGNET FOR IRS AUDITS, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Amid the depressing fact that Thursday is the
deadline for filing taxes comes a tidbit of even more disheartening
news: Northern California has the highest percentage of people
being audited by the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   Higher than big-bucks Los Angeles. Higher than the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS had no explanation. About the only good news is that
even in audit-prone areas, the number of people called before IRS
examiners is minuscule.
</P>
<P>
   An annual study conducted by researchers at Syracuse University
in New York found that Northern California, including the San
Francisco area, has jumped from third to second, and then to first,
in the past three years as the most popular target for IRS audits.
</P>
<P>
   The study by the university's Transactional Records Access
Clearinghouse, a research group that uses the Freedom of
Information Act to pry closely guarded figures from federal
agencies, showed that 1.08 percent of returns filed by taxpayers in
the San Francisco area were audited in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, with 0.98 percent of returns audited, was in
second. Southern California, excluding Los Angeles, was third and
Central California was fourth. The North Central region (Minnesota
and South Dakota) was fifth. And Manhattan was sixth, with 0.61
percent of returns audited.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles for years has been the most or second-most audited
part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Accountants speculated that the relative new wealth of Silicon
Valley may be the reason for Northern California's dubious
distinction.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Weinstein, a certified public accountant in San
Francisco, noted that high incomes are being generated from
incentive compensation and stock options at Silicon Valley
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In states where the auditing rate is low, in Ohio, for example,
returns come from taxpayers who often work for big, established
companies, Weinstein said. Their tax returns are much more
straightforward and simple than those from burgeoning start-ups in
the Silicon Valley, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Northern California, there are very independent people who
have generated small businesses, and because of that the IRS may
see an opportunity to make aggressive use of expenses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein and other accountants said their anecdotal experience
tells them there are many self-employed people or independent
contractors whose Schedule C forms are more complicated to file
and, therefore, more subject to mistakes, abuse and, ultimately,
extra scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Across the nation, auditing dropped dramatically from 1992
through 1998, the Syracuse study showed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the IRS received 118 million individual income tax
returns. On a national average, about 1 in every 100 will be
audited.
</P>
<P>
   In the 33 regions studied by Syracuse University, the percentage
of scrutinized returns during the 1992-1998 period increased in
Northern California. The highest year ever for Northern California
audits was in 1997, when 1.34 percent of returns were held under
the IRS microscope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
