<HEADLINE>
A BERRY NICE DESSERT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A reader writes looking for a recipe for strawberries Romanoff.
This recipe for the classic is from ``Breakfast at Brennan's and
Dinner, Too'' by Pip, Jimmy and Ted Brennan (self-published,
$27.50).
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRIES ROMANOFF
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   3 cups sliced strawberries
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Grand Marnier
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Drambuie
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated orange peel
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 pints French vanilla ice cream
</P>
<P>
   In large bowl, combine strawberries, Grand Marnier, Drambuie,
sugar, orange peel and lemon peel. Cover the bowl and marinate
strawberries for 6 hours in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl, beat cream until stiff, then fold in the
powdered sugar and vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Drain strawberries and place in nonmetallic bowl; reserve
liquid. Mash strawberries with a fork, then fold in ice cream.
Spoon strawberry and ice cream mixture into stemmed glasses and
spoon some of the marinade over the mixture. Top with whipped cream
and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 366 calories, 20 grams fat, 33
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 79 milligrams cholesterol, 86
milligrams sodium, 50 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   A Southern fave: Margaret Jordan of Weatherford, Texas, saw our
recipe for margarita pie and sends along her recipe. She likes this
recipe so much that she keeps one in the freezer at all times.
</P>
<P>
   JO ANN'S MARGARITA PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce container nondairy whipped topping
</P>
<P>
   2 dry packets margarita mix
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 chocolate or graham cracker crumb crust
</P>
<P>
   Combine first 4 ingredients and spoon into crust. Refrigerate or
freeze. Garnish with lime slices, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 415 calories, 25 grams fat, 47
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 31 milligrams cholesterol,
263 milligrams sodium, 53 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Carole Griggs of Stephenville, Texas, requests a recipe that
dates to before our computer database.
</P>
<P>
   ``In June or July of 1986, there was an article about
chicken-fried steak and cream gravy (it covered the whole cover of
the lifestyle page) and there were several different people who had
been canvassed. One of them was a lady that had fixed chicken-fried
steak and gravy for her husband and daughters every day for 35
years for lunch. I cannot find this anywhere, and it was the best
gravy I have ever fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane Bowles of Arlington, Texas, used to make a cookie in the
1970s that had an oatmeal-type base and top, and a fudgy center. I
lost the recipe when a similar mix became available, marketed under
the name Fudge Jumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne McKnight would like the recipe for the marvelous spinach
salad that the now-defunct Highland Park Cafeteria used to serve.
``I know it had hard-boiled eggs cut up in it, and, I'm sure, some
horseradish. I'd love to taste it again, and again, and again.''
</P>
<P>
   Daphne Myles writes looking for a muffin recipe that uses grated
carrots, pineapple pieces and, she believes, nuts. She lost the
recipe and thinks it was printed in this column in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
