<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIXING DAMAGE TO CARPETS AND FLOORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A how-to drawing is being sent to NYT photo and NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The floors in homes, whether they be wood or covered with vinyl
or carpeting, take a lot of abuse. Floors exposed to heavy traffic
suffer occasional damage and require spot repairs. The most common
repairs for vinyl flooring include flattening blisters and patching
tears or scratches. Common carpet repairs include removing burns
and stains and regluing loose seams.
</P>
<P>
   Blisters form in vinyl flooring when a small section pulls away
from the adhesive on the subfloor. Use a utility knife to cut a
slit through the blister. Cover the area with aluminum foil and
heat it with a warm iron. This will soften the vinyl and the
adhesive beneath. Use a putty knife to insert new adhesive through
the slit, then press the blister flat. Clean away any excess
adhesive that seeps through the slit with mineral spirits. Place a
weight over the area and allow at least 24 hours for the adhesive
to set.
</P>
<P>
   It is not difficult to repair deep scratches or tears in vinyl
floor covering provided you have a spare piece of the covering to
make a patch. You may have some scraps remaining from the original
installation. If not, you may also be able to buy a small piece of
material from a floor-covering supplier. If neither of these
options are viable, you can remove a small section of the floor
covering from the hidden areas under a large appliance or piece of
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Cut a patch larger than the damaged area. Place it directly over
the damaged section in the floor, and adjust it so the patterns of
the two match. Tape the patch in place. Using a metal straight edge
as a guide, cut through the patch and floor covering underneath
with a utility knife. Remove the patch and lay it aside. Pry out
the damaged section with a putty knife.
</P>
<P>
   A stubborn piece of vinyl floor can usually be loosened by
softening the adhesive underneath with a warm iron (cover the area
with aluminum foil first). Clean the subfloor by dissolving the
adhesive with mineral spirits then scrape it with a putty knife or
a single-edged razor blade.
</P>
<P>
   Apply adhesive to the patch and press it in place. Use a roller
(you can use a kitchen rolling pin for this, but cover it with
plastic wrap to avoid possible contamination with adhesive.) to
flatten the patch and assure a good bond. Remove any excess glue
that seeps around the edges with mineral spirits. Place a weight
over the patch and allow the adhesive to set.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure for repairing damaged vinyl tiles is the same as
for patching a damaged section of vinyl sheet flooring, only there
is no need to cut a patch because tiles are precut. First, use a
warm iron to soften the adhesive, then pry up the damaged tile with
a putty knife. Coat the back of the replacement tile with adhesive,
then press it into place. Weight it down until the adhesive sets.
</P>
<P>
   When a carpet is stained, obviously the first course of action
is to try and remove the stain with a commercial carpet cleaner.
Follow the directions on the can and test the cleaner in an
inconspicuous spot to see how it affects your carpet.
</P>
<P>
   If the cleaner proves ineffective, you can remove the stained
section of carpet and replace it with a clean piece. For the patch
to be invisible, the cutout section and the patch must be the same
exact size and shape. One inexpensive tool that is useful for
cutting carpet patches is a ''cookie cutter.'' The cookie cutter,
available at most carpeting stores, cuts a round hole about four
inches in diameter. For larger patches, you will have to use a
utility knife.
</P>
<P>
   To use the cutter, press it down on the stained section and
rotate it. The cutter will make a neat circular hole. Use the same
technique to cut a replacement patch from a piece of scrap carpet.
Both the hole in the carpet and the patch will be the same size and
shape.
</P>
<P>
   Carpet is generally held in place with double-faced carpet tape,
not adhesive. Double-faced carpet tape is available at carpeting
stores. Cut a couple of pieces of tape and insert them into the
hole. The tape should extend past the perimeter of the hole to the
underside of the surrounding carpet. Press the patch into place,
making sure that the nap and pattern matches the existing carpet.
</P>
<P>
   Carpet comes loose at the seams when the double-face tape
beneath loses its adhesive grip. Make the repair by first pulling
out the old tape from under the seam, then replacing it with a
piece of heat-activated carpet tape (available at carpeting
stores). Heat the tape with a special seam iron (you can rent one
at carpet stores), then press the carpet down to seal the seams
together.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
