<HEADER>
A8005 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-TOO-MANY-CATS &LR;      04-14 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-TOO-MANY-CATS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMAL EXPERTS CALL CAT COLLECTORS 'SCOURGE' 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ALEX LANE  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stereotype of the neighborhood ``Cat Lady'' _ sweet albeit
eccentric widows or spinsters who fill their houses with cats,
opting for feline friends over human companionship _ is well known.
</P>
<P>
   But many animal professionals say that these cat lovers do more
harm than good to their pets and themselves. Harmless cat lovers
often turn into compulsive cat hoarders with filthy houses and an
unrestrained population of sick, inbred, feral felines.
</P>
<P>
   Now some shelter directors, psychologists and veterinarians are
mobilizing _ and calling for this behavior to be studied,
understood and stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cat collectors are one of the largest sources of animal
suffering in the nation,'' said Gini Barrett, director of the
American Humane Association office in Los Angeles. ``It's a huge
human problem, it's a huge animal-suffering problem, it's a
nightmare. It needs to be fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett is trying to develop a network through which Los
Angeles-area shelters can share information about collectors _
most, but not all, of whom are older single women. She is also
trying to educate judges and prosecutors about the danger presented
by these often sweet, sympathetic defendants.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Barrett and other experts said, only a minority of
cat lovers create problems. Many can handle large numbers of cats
and keep their houses clean and their animals healthy. Only those
who cross the line into compulsion are worrisome. Compulsion, in
this context, refers to collectors who accumulate large numbers of
animals far beyond the collectors' ability to provide proper care
for the animals.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said she, like most shelter workers, has encountered
several cases of extreme cat hoarding. The worst was that of a
woman who kept 589 cats in a flea-infested, feces-smeared house.
Thirty-nine were so sick they had to be killed immediately. Nine,
stuffed between couch cushions and into shopping bags in a closet,
were already dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This woman truly believed her cats were fine,'' Barrett said.
``You're not talking logic here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Lee has dealt with several off-the-deep-end collectors in
her job as director of an animal shelter in the small mountain town
of Durango, Colo. ``When I walk into these ladies' houses,
sometimes it scares me to death,'' Lee said. ``These cats can be
violent if they don't get their way.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the problem has gone unstudied. But recently Dr. Gary
Patronek, a veterinarian at Tufts University near Boston,
researched this behavior out of concern for the animals it hurts.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Patronek released the results of his study, in which
he estimated that animal shelters uncover 700 to 2,000 new cases of
animal hoarding every year. Because of the secretive nature of
hoarders, he said, the real total is much higher. Cats are the
collected animal in 65 percent of cases, with the rest spread out
among dogs, farm animals such as cows and chickens, and birds.
</P>
<P>
   Patronek's findings, combined with stories from shelter workers
and mental-health professionals, paint a portrait of a typical
collector: a reclusive, older woman who compulsively collects not
just animals but also household items such as bottlecaps or
newspapers. When confronted, collectors tend to be adept at
attracting sympathy. And if caught and punished, they are very
likely to build a new collection after the authorities stop paying
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said most collectors start out as helpful animal
rescuers, then slowly slip off the edge. ``It's the day you have
more than you can manage,'' Barrett said, ``the day you cannot see
the filth or the illness.'' That could be at five cats or at 50
cats, Barrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephanie Lafarge, a psychologist for the New York chapter
of the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals,
explained that people who compulsively collect cats are probably
trying to deal with bad family or romantic relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Cats are an attractive collectible since they are quieter and
more self-sufficient than dogs, for example, which need to be
walked and groomed. Also, the sometimes-aloof nature of the cat can
make emotional sense to people with low self-esteem, Lafarge said.
</P>
<P>
   A 53-year-old Manhattan cat lover who calls herself a ``cat
rescuer'' and wishes to be identified only by her first name,
Xiamara, is confident that she will never get to the point of
compulsive, harmful collecting. But she acknowledges that her cats
control her room and her routine.
</P>
<P>
   Xiamara lives in a one-room apartment in a Harlem tenement, with
21 cats. Stacked unlocked woven-wire cages line the faded orange
walls. Dusty clutter, like chairs and lamps, are piled high in
corners, stowed away to make more room for cat paraphernalia. She
has no room for furniture _ at night she rolls out blankets and
sleeps on the floor. She rises at 4:30 in the morning, and cleans
up after her cats for the next three hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see 21, do you?'' Xiamara said recently. Indeed,
only six or seven cats were visible. But with a shake of the food
bag, the cats materialized, darting out from makeshift dens in the
depths of cages and hidden corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in my blood, I can't stop,'' Xiamara said. ``I walk down
the street and my heart starts beating, because I'll see a paper
bag and I'll think it's a cat. I ask myself, 'What is this? Why do
I feel this way?' I just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the next breath, she tells the story of her childhood.
She was abandoned at birth, and by the time she was 15 she had
lived in eight different institutions and foster homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask, 'Are you happy?' '' Xiamara said. ``I'm happy for
the animals I've helped. For myself, I dreamed of being married in
a house with a husband and children and a car. I died and cried for
it many nights. Now I'm just accepting, this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Alex Lane is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
