<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL GREETINGS FLOURISH BUT PAPER CARDS RULE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By MANUELA BADAWY  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 10th most popular Web site in the world is an
electronic greeting card site where users can send and receive
cards for 104 different occasions in three different languages, all
at no cost.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Mountain Arts Inc., which is also the No. 1 Web site in the
greeting card industry, records the most visits, about one million
hits a day. Over the shopping season for Valentine's Day _ from
February 1 to 14 _ the company had ``tens of millions'' of hits,
said Erica Wilhelm, assistant to the vice president of business and
development at Blue Mountain. Christmas is equally busy. Almost as
hectic as those two holidays are the periods leading up to Father's
Day and Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's profit comes from its printed cards, sold
wholesale to retailers. The Web site is used to introduce consumers
to the cards. ``The site is only a complement for the paper
industry,'' Wilhelm said.
</P>
<P>
   While there are more than 150 greeting card Web sites with
original designs and messages, most people still send the
traditional cards, according to the Greeting Card Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still like to hold, touch and display their cards,''
said Mila Albertson, director of publications and promotions at the
trade association.
</P>
<P>
   The trade group estimated that more than 7 billion cards were
sold last year, 900 million of them for Valentine's Day. That adds
up to an estimated $7.5 billion in revenue in just the United
States. Christmas and Valentine's Day are the two busiest holidays
for the greeting card industry.
</P>
<P>
   E-cards, with animation and music, can be sent instantly, with
prices ranging from nothing to $10 each. But some recipients don't
want E-cards and others do not have the software to open such files
or the space to store them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they spam you with junk mail,'' said Jurgen Efeish,
technical solution engineer for a database company called
Prolifics, ``but it's lots of fun to receive these things.'' The
term ``spam'' is generally taken to mean junk e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 153 million people are online worldwide as of this
past January, according to Nua Internet Surveys, making electronic
greetings not yet a mainstream product.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of the people who send Web greeting cards are
women, according to a survey by NPD Group, an international
marketing information company. Eighty percent of the people who buy
paper greeting cards are women, most of them middle-aged, according
to the Greeting Card Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I am an Internet fan,'' said Karin Dauch, a native
of Brazil who is a graduate student in new media in New York City,
``I still think it is nice to see that a person went to the trouble
of licking a stamp.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper greeting card industry is not disappearing. To the
contrary, e-mail cards are helping the traditional business,
Albertson said. There are 1,800 publishing companies, and, she
said, they are not threatened by electronic greeting cards. ``Are
printed books going to disappear because of the Internet?'' she
asked. ``No. Well, it's the same with greeting cards.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many Web sites for different purposes, like C-ya.com,
for relationship closure issues; cyber-cards.com, which includes
images of landmarks and vehicles, and
electronicpostcards.com/pc/insults for clever insults. For
traditional greetings, try: www.hallmark.com.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic cards can help busy people show they are thinking of
someone. ``It follows the rule of the market,'' Efeish said.
``Before, it was telex; now it is e-cards.'' SIDE BAR
</P>
<P>
   The 10 most popular Internet sites:
</P>
<P>
   1. AOL
</P>
<P>
   2. Microsoft
</P>
<P>
   3. Yahoo!
</P>
<P>
   4. Lycos
</P>
<P>
   5. Geocities
</P>
<P>
   6. Netscape
</P>
<P>
   7. Excite
</P>
<P>
   8. Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   9. Infoseek
</P>
<P>
   10. Blue Mountain Arts
</P>
<P>
   --Source: Media Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Manuela Badawy is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
