<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-ELEPHANTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUMBOISM: ARTISTS DEVELOPING THEIR INNER ELEPHANT 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By DESIREE ADIB  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Deep in the lush jungles of Thailand, Nam Chong
stands in concentration, staring into the morning mist. Suddenly,
he picks up a paintbrush and with bold dramatic strokes begins his
latest masterpiece on the canvas propped up on the easel in front
of him. An artist, a landscape, an easel _ it all sounds perfectly
normal, except for one thing. The artist, Nam Chong, is an
elephant.
</P>
<P>
   When he paints, Nam Chong holds a specially designed brush on
the ``finger'' at the end of his trunk, and flexes nearly 50,000
muscles in his trunk to create vivid smears of reds, yellows and
greens across the canvas. After much ear flapping, tail swooshing,
and trunk waving, the result is an array of blotches and squiggles
that might be considered the ultimate in abstract art.
</P>
<P>
   Nam Chong is seen on a slide show in the studio of New
York-based artists Alexander Melamid and Vitaly Komar. He is one of
30 or so elephants who have the privilege of being enrolled in one
of the three exclusive Thai Elephant Art Academies. Komar and
Melamid recently returned from Thailand, where they helped start
the art schools, located in the village of Ayuthaya, the southern
resort island of Phuket and the northern city of Lampang.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of grants from the World Wildlife Fund, the
Russian emigre artists started the Thailand Elephant Art Project
after learning about the plight of starving Thai elephants who were
left unemployed after the government banned teak logging. Most of
the 3,800 domesticated elephants in Thailand were formerly employed
as hard laborers, hauling teak logs in the rugged jungles.
</P>
<P>
   Now, thanks to the Thailand Elephant Art Project, some of these
elephants are happily producing and selling canvases adorned with a
colorful array of blotches and squiggles that have been compared to
the works of the renowned 1950s abstract expressionists, like
Jackson Pollock and Willem De Kooning. Pollock was known for his
eclectic painting style of punching holes in cans of paint and
dragging the dripping colors over a canvas spread out beneath him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The abstract expressionists in the '50s were always trying to
discover the beast within and release their emotions and instincts
through the act of painting,'' said Mia Fineman, an art historian
at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City. ``The elephants
come by this vestal quality by naturally being animals themselves,
so in a way it's kind of an end-of-the-century comment on abstract
expressionism.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so serious about the elephants' artwork. Komar
and Melamid are known in the New York art community for making
parody statements on the art establishment and the contemporary art
world. They claim to have turned dogs into painters and monkeys
into photographers. Their future plans include turning termites and
beavers into architects. Komar and Melamid like to call their work
with animals and nature ``eco-collaboration.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Ronald Jones, chairman of Columbia University's
Graduate School of Visual Arts, the Elephant Art Project is just
another practical joke being played on the art world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Komar and Melamid for a number of years have been known for
doing a social demographics art and commentary of what popular
taste is,'' Jones said. ``It falls almost too neatly under the old
rhetoric about abstract art that we've heard before with regard to
Pollock _ 'My 4-year-old could do this.' With this it's 'My pet
could do this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But with a straight face and a serious attitude, Komar insists
that the elephants' art and their behavior while creating the art
can be compared directly to such painters as Pollock. Some
elephants even like to paint with the canvas spread out on the
ground beneath them in true Pollokesque style.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are elephants who like to paint only after a bottle of
rice whiskey,'' Komar said. ``Just like Pollock! Pollock also liked
to drink his whiskey before painting.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a practical joke or not, it is evident that these
elephants don't work for just peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, they raised $50,000 at a glitzy art exhibition
held in the Hilton Hotel in Bangkok. Princess Galyani Vadhana,
sister of the King of Thailand, attended the gala and purchased a
few select pieces of the elephants' art. The money goes to the
elephant art academy, which houses the elephants and their keepers.
Why not? Komar and Melamid are very serious about the creative
talents of the elephants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of them are individuals, stylistically and by
character,'' Komar said, fawning over the fierce blotches of a
yellow and green elephant creation. ``Look! The sense of
composition is really fantastic!''
</P>
<P>
   In between banana treats and swigs of rice whiskey, the
elephants wave their trunks in bold strokes on the canvas in front
of them, apparently getting their inspiration from the beautiful
lush landscape around them. But not all elephant art looks the
same. There are three distinct schools and regional styles that
have emerged in this new art movement, said Fineman, who is also an
art history professor at Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The northern style is more lyrical and looser, tending toward
clearer primary colors and broken brush work,'' Fineman said. ``The
central Thai style, centered in Ayuthaya, was more vigorous _ they
tended to use broader brushes and straight strokes that sort of
sweep across the canvas from edge to edge sometimes covering the
entire surface in a kind of color field. And the southern style was
more gentle, curvy, tending to use complex colors like plum and
magenta and mustard.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the cognoscenti believe the pachyderms' work is true art
or not, Komar and Melamid hope that the new art movement, which has
been referred to as Dumboism,'' will help sustain some of the
domesticated elephants in Thailand _ not to mention the flourishing
``inner elephant'' of the artists themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Desiree Adib is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
