</P>
<P>
   QUEEN NOOR _ Although there is no constitutional role for Queen
Noor within Jordan's monarchial system, King Hussein decreed before
his death that she would retain her title and live in the royal
palace, Bab Al Salam. She is expected to retain a public role.
``She will continue to be important and to play an important role
in the Jordanian Government,'' said Hassan Abu Nima, Jordan's
Ambassador to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   US-IRAN _ After two decades of silence, the delicate dance of
words between Washington and Tehran has yet to whirl into a full
negotiating waltz. Iran is celebrating the 20th anniversary of its
Islamic revolution this year, which led to the takeover of the
American embassy by the revolutionaries, and the taking of 52
American hostages, who were held for 444 days. But the animosity
that once existed between the two nations is being replaced by
respectful relations at the governmental level.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K PROBLEM _ In the 14th century, the Black Death ravaged
Europe and Asia. In the 1800s, a cholera pandemic rampaged from
India to Mississippi. What will be the disease of the new
millennium? Increasingly, prognosticators say the threat is the Y2K
glitch, which they say could sweep through computer systems
worldwide, downing planes and generally causing unprecedented
devastation.
</P>
<P>
   ELEPHANTS _ With the help of grants from the World Wildlife
Fund, two Russian emigre artists started the Thailand Elephant Art
Project after learning about the plight of starving Thai elephants
who were left unemployed after the government banned teak logging.
Most of the 3,800 domesticated elephants in Thailand were formerly
employed as hard laborers, hauling teak logs in the rugged jungles.
Now, thanks to the Thailand Elephant Art Project, some of these
elephants are happily painting works of art.
</P>
<P>
   TOO MANY CATS _ The stereotype of the neighborhood ``Cat Lady''
_ sweet albeit eccentric widows or spinsters who fill their houses
with cats, opting for feline friends over human companionship _ is
well known.
</P>
<P>
   But many animal professionals say that these cat lovers do more
harm than good to their pets and themselves. Harmless cat lovers
often turn into compulsive cat hoarders with filthy houses and an
unrestrained population of sick, inbred, feral felines.
</P>
<P>
   PITBULLS _Pit bulls' social nature, combined with their
strength, make them good pets and helpers for the disabled. But
they have a bad reputation as dangerous dogs.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL CARDS _ E-mail greeting cards are soaring in popularity.
But old-fashioned print cards are not threatened.
</P>
<P>
   WEB ADDICTS _ Some people say they are addicted to the Internet.
There is help available for them, but there is one catch: the
therapy is available online.
</P>
<P>
   TOILET ADS _ One of the last places where a person could truly
be alone _ the toilet stall _ has been invaded by advertising.
</P>
<P>
   WILD FOOD _ A man known as Wildman relishes showing tour groups
how to eat hearty on the plants in Central Park in New York.
</P>
