<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT COMES TO PIT BULLS, IS MAN BITING DOG UNFAIRLY? 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By AMY L. ANDERSON  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The door has barely swung shut, when the muscular,
reddish dog jumps down from its perch by the window and flings
itself at the intruder. Forty pounds of writhing, panting pit bull
scrabble across a cement floor on Manhattan's Lower East Side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop it!'' Glen Hettrick, the beast's owner, yells from the
back of the bar, but the dog ignores him.
</P>
<P>
   Hettrick shrugs and returns to his pool game. The pit bull,
named Ginger, tail wagging, jumps up again and again, trying to
lick the stranger's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll go home with you after a few drinks,'' said Hettrick's
wife, Rosemarie.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly the snarling, spike-collared beast with steel-trap jaws
that the name pit bull calls up. To many dog owners, pit bulls are
beloved family pets, guilty, if anything, of an insatiable craving
for affection and an over-eagerness to please.
</P>
<P>
   But many municipalities across the country are acting on the
dogs' reputation, singling out pit bulls and their cousins with
``dangerous dogs'' legislation. A bill before the New York City
Council, for example, would require owners of pit bulls _ defined
as Staffordshire bull terriers, American Staffordshire terriers,
American pit bull terriers or similar mixed breeds _ to carry
$100,000 in liability insurance in order to obtain a dog license.
Those who have worked with and lived with pit bulls maintain that
such legislation will serve only to punish responsible owners and
their dogs, while propagating a misleading stereotype of so-called
``bully breeds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll lick you to death,'' Paul Daly, a 37-year-old carpenter
who lives in the East Village, said of Eleanor, his pit-bull mix.
Daly scoffed at the idea his dog might be dangerous. ``The myth of
the evil pit bull is just a myth,'' he said. ``They're sweet
critters _ very loyal, happy, very calm. If you get the dog as a
pet, it's the best pet you can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Pit bulls' social nature, combined with their strength, make
them good helpers, said Dennis Owens, a 32-year-old Manhattan
resident who trains dogs to assist the disabled. Owens, who was
injured in an elevator accident a little more than 10 years ago,
uses his pit bull, Asha, to retrieve things for him, and the dogs
can also be trained to pull wheelchairs. ``She's the best thing
that ever happened to me,'' he said. The emotional support Asha
provides is as important to him as the physical support. ``They
enjoy life, no matter what else is going on,'' he said, explaining
why he chose a pit bull over other breeds. ``They're a lot of fun _
enjoyable to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many pit bulls do exhibit a nasty streak. According
to the New York Department of Health, which is responsible for
enforcing dog-control laws, pit bulls accounted for 294, or 33
percent, of the 892 dogs held by the department in 1997 for biting
or other menacing behavior. While other breeds, including German
shepherds and Rottweilers, also had significant reports of bites,
pit bulls tend to do more damage when they bite, the health
department commissioner, Neal Cohen, testified before the New York
City Council earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Robin Kovary, a Manhattan dog trainer, said that was no
reason to punish all pit-bull owners with an insurance requirement.
``If raised by good people, they're affectionate, intelligent,
devoted pets,'' said Kovary, a behavior consultant who has worked
extensively with pit bulls. Problems arise when owners encourage
aggressive behavior by roughhousing or egging a dog on when it
barks or growls. ``They're fantastic dogs in the right hands,'' she
said. ``Unfortunately, a lot of them end up in the wrong hands _
people who shouldn't own a hamster.''
</P>
<P>
   And the requirement will not affect the most dangerous slice of
the pit-bull population. A health department spokesman, John Gadd,
said that approximately 90 percent of the dogs seized last year
were unlicensed. Gadd maintains that the law will still help, by
giving the department more authority to fine such owners and, if
necessary, confiscate their dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Similar bills have been defeated in Toronto, Annapolis, Md., and
Youngstown, Ohio, largely on the strength of protest from dog
lovers who claim that breed-specific legislation fails to address
the real problem. Pit-bull owners in New York are rallying against
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Lettis, director of the Responsible Dog Owners Association
of New York, acknowledged that ``there are people who use dogs as
lethal weapons.'' But, she added, ``the criminal element will use
any breed.'' Officials would do better, she said, to enforce
existing rules, like leash laws, that apply to all breeds. ``When
you tell the public this breed is dangerous, you're telling the
public all other breeds are fine, and that's a misrepresentation,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   A 56-year-old legal secretary who owns two American
Staffordshire Terriers and two Staffordshire Bull Terriers, her
interest in bully breeds stems from pit bull-specific legislation
proposed in New York in the 1980s. Lettis, who at the time owned
two boxers (dogs unrelated to pit bulls), volunteered to help the
American Kennel Club fight the legislation and, in the process,
began to research the breed. ``Because of the research, I truly
fell in love with them,'' she said. ``I thought, I had to own
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Lettis, who regularly takes her dogs to schools to teach
children about responsible dog ownership, was delighted with her
first Stafford, Mikey. ``He was the easiest dog to train I've ever
owned in my life,'' she said. Mikey has also displayed an unusually
sensitive side. ``He has found wounded birds in the yard and come
to the back door to get me to do something about it. He's sort of
like the Albert Schweitzer of the canine world.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Amy L. Anderson is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
