<HEADER>
A8012 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-WILD-FOOD &LR;      04-14 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-WILD-FOOD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CALL OF THE WILD(MAN) 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ITAY HOD  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the spring of 1986, Steve Brill, also known as
``Wildman,'' was handcuffed and detained for three hours at police
headquarters in New York City. His crime? Eating dandelions in
Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Brill was giving one of his private tours in the Manhattan park,
his own version of how to survive in the urban jungle. He was
showing his followers which plants were edible. As soon as he
placed the dandelion in his mouth, two undercover cops with
walkie-talkies jumped from behind the bushes and made the arrest _
a real life sting operation. Wildman was caught yellow-handed.
</P>
<P>
   But he beat the rap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had eaten all the evidence,'' Brill said. The case got so
much publicity that the charges were dropped and Brill was hired by
the city's Parks and Recreations Department to conduct the same
tours. Although he is no longer affiliated with the department,
Brill is busier now than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of his tours, Brill insisted, is to help New Yorkers
become reacquainted with the natural world. For a small price _ $10
for an adult, $5 for a child _ urban sophisticates can find food
without dialing for delivery or ordering off a menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have very little contact with their environment in the
modern urban and suburban setting,'' said Brill, 49. ``I want them
to have a different perspective of their environment. You don't
have to go out of your way to get in touch with nature. It's right
out there, close by to where you live.''
</P>
<P>
   Brill conducts five tours a week, four hours at a time. This is
his full-time job. He works with schools and organizations around
the city leading group excursions in all five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   With his thin physique and dark-framed glasses, this tour guide
looks more a math teacher than a wild man. He has no academic
qualifications other than a psychology degree from Georgetown
University. But that has not stopped him from publishing on
nature-related topics. Brill has written a book called
``Identifying and Harvesting Edible and Medicinal Plants in Wild
(and Not So Wild) Places,'' and is working on a wildlife cookbook.
He is even planning his own Web site.
</P>
<P>
   So what can you eat in Central Park?
</P>
<P>
   Gingko nuts, which are now in season, can be harvested off the
ground and are great for circulation and memory. Gingko nuts also
serve as a low-fat substitute for cheese. Sorel, a lemon herb used
in soups, is free for the picking. Brill also shows how to find
greens of garlic and poor man's pepper, two ingredients that can
spice up a meal. Serviceberries, small berries that are a cross
between apples and blueberries, have an ``indescribable sweet
flavor'' and cannot be bought anywhere, Brill said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Vogel, 36, a Wildman follower, cannot get enough of the
nature walks, which Brill sprinkles with mythology, literature and
humor. Vogel has been touring with Brill for the past eight years,
sometimes as many as 16 times a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of exciting to be out there on a beautiful day and
meet some people who are real enthused about nature,'' said Vogel,
who works for the city comptroller's office. ``I'm always learning
new things. He's entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   But New York City's Department of Parks and Recreation is not so
enthusiastic. They want Brill to go wild somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``The park is for people to enjoy, not for people to consume,''
said Ed Skyler, spokesman from the department. Skyler is concerned
that Brill's tours are destroying plant life. He also worries about
health hazards; poisonous plants are not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   Brill insists he knows how to identify lethal greens and how to
teach others to avoid them.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics question Brill's claim that it is possible to live
for up to eight months eating off the land with the right
combination of herbs, roots, greens, fruits, nuts, berries,
mushrooms and weeds _ not that he has tried it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to know what kind of research he has done to make
such a statement,'' said Wahida Karmally, a spokeswoman for the
American Dietetic Association and a nutritionist. ``It can be very
damaging unless you have confirmed data.''
</P>
<P>
   Vitamin B-12, for example, can only be found in animal products,
she said, and ``unless there are cows in Central Park, I don't see
how the diet could be complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Brill conceded that he took B-12 supplements himself.
</P>
<P>
   While some nutritionists do not support an all-Central Park
diet, few of Brill's customers are concerned. ``He has no formal
education about this, but it doesn't mean he doesn't know what he's
talking about,'' said David Reich, a chiropractor from Queens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Itay Hod is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
