<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8013 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-Y2K-PROBLEM &LR;      04-14 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-Y2K-PROBLEM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR COUNTRIES FACE Y2K CHAOS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 F. BRINLEY BRUTON  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the 14th century, the Black Death ravaged Europe
and Asia. In the 1800s, a cholera pandemic rampaged from India to
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   What will be the disease of the new millennium?
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, prognosticators say the threat is the Y2K glitch,
which they say could sweep through computer systems worldwide,
downing planes and generally causing unprecedented devastation.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts warn that the world is not prepared for the Year
2000 problem, which stems from the inability of computers to
differentiate the year 2000 from the year 1900. A World Bank study
found that 85 percent of countries surveyed at the end of last year
were unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a pretty picture,'' said Joyce Amenta, who heads the
World Bank's Y2K task force. ``The issue is fundamental to the
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Sloan, the World Bank's Africa technology specialist, said:
``There are 30 billion chips in the world. There is no way to know
what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   A study released in March by the U.S. Senate emphasizes domestic
considerations like the threat to the American health care system,
but warns that the international picture is alarming because Y2K
foul-ups abroad could have serious repercussions at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides the interdependent nature of the U.S. and world
economy,'' the report says, ``the U.S. has a responsibility as a
world leader to encourage a politically stable environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the World Bank, the Senate found that many countries are
not gearing up for the expected computer failures. The Senate cited
a study by the Gartner Group showing that 54 of the 81 countries
surveyed will probably be unprepared for potential computer
malfunctions on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Fear has prodded some advanced nations' governments and private
companies into action. But many poor countries, potentially most at
risk of widespread havoc, have done the least to anticipate their
computer clocks going haywire at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank is worried that such countries as Indonesia,
Russia and Brazil are so preoccupied with their economic, political
and social problems that they are all but ignoring the Y2K threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate report said Venezuela and Saudi Arabia, two major
sources of U.S. oil imports, are more than a year behind in
preparing. Even important trade and financial partners like Germany
and Taiwan are lagging in dealing with the problem.
</P>
<P>
   So serious is the worldwide concern that the State Department
has ordered its personnel to refrain from travelling from Dec. 15,
1999, to Jan. 15, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is rooted in the two digits, instead of four, that
computer programmers traditionally have used to represent a year,
so that many computers will read 00 in 2000 to mean 1900. Resulting
calculations could scramble telephone lines, block credit cards,
confuse air traffic patterns and shut down hospital equipment,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   One big issue is that no one knows whether the problem is
overrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you lose power for a week in New York, it's complete
pandemonium,'' said Eugene Chang, an international Y2K consultant
based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, power outages in developing
countries may cause only a ripple, because those governments are
used to glitches.
</P>
<P>
   One of Chang's bank clients tried to tell Russian businessmen
about the chaos that could ensue on Jan. 1: power failures,
economic collapse and social unrest. Audience members listened
quietly, Chang said, until one spoke up: ``Yes, that is very
interesting, but those things have already happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   Many developing countries already struggle with imperfect
computer systems, and have perfected what Chang called ``manual
work-around'' tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the regional implications are vast. If Uganda's energy
grid goes down, African neighbors that rely on Uganda for energy
could be left without power.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank says that one of the least vigilant countries is
landlocked Zimbabwe. At Harare's embassy in Washington, however,
counselor Lloyd Zithoi said the question is ``not a thing a person
worries about; it's not a big issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The word computer isn't in most people's vocabulary,'' he
said. But Zimbabwe's government departments are computerized, he
conceded, and are now being adjusted by a U.S. computer consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Some countries, like Argentina and Tunisia, have pounced on the
problem. But the world's largest nation, China, has not bothered to
return the World Bank's Y2K preparedness form, and Beijing has
taken the bold stance of ordering all its airline executives to fly
on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank, undeterred, has established a program called
InfoDev that specializes in the Y2K problem, and has lent $159
million to Sri Lanka, Argentina and Malaysia to help them prepare.
Few other countries have even bothered to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Even with widespread warnings, the world is unlikely to be ready
for Y2K, many experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the new century will give the world's computers a
version of the bubonic plague or just a case of the sniffles is
impossible to know.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it may pay to take a few precautions, Amenta said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a good idea to buy a few extra groceries right
before New Year's,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: F. Brinley Bruton is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
