<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-TOILET-ADS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISERS TAKE THEIR MESSAGE TO THE TOILET 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By STEPHEN SIFF  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Corporate America wants you to read the writing on
the bathroom wall. No, not the profanity. Not the messages of love.
But the cheeky advertisements it has designed for the ultimate
captive audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enjoy every part of the city,'' read one poster recently
displayed above urinals and on toilet stall doors in 300 New York
City bars. ``And don't forget Flushing.''
</P>
<P>
   The framed advertisement for Time Out New York magazine was
distributed by Zoom Media, one of the two major companies engaged
in a nationwide bathroom brawl.
</P>
<P>
   People have always read in bathrooms, and accommodating
bartenders have long affixed sports pages to restroom walls. But
for the last two years, such blue-chip advertisers as Proctor and
Gamble and General Motors have also vied for the relaxed attention
of bar-goers.
</P>
<P>
   There are several good reasons for advertisers to take their
message to the john, say salesmen for the new medium. The ads can
almost unerringly be targeted to men or women; they reach the
coveted 18-to-34 age demographic; people in bars usually have
disposable income; and for one to three minutes, the target
audience has no place else, well, to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an unspoken urinal etiquette,'' said Clarence
Robertson, a 27-year-old bar patron on the Upper West Side of
Manhattan. ``You don't look left, you don't look right.'' That
leaves straight ahead, which is where the advertisements are
positioned.
</P>
<P>
   For around $200 per month, Marc Miller, the 23-year-old
co-founder of Insite Media, promises advertisers the undivided
attention of ``trendsetters'' who frequent one of the 9,000 toilets
he has rented in fashionable bars in nine major media markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the overseers of what is hot and what is going on,''
Miller said. ``Let them receive your message and the others will
follow. People who grew up in an ad-infested age thrive on it.''
</P>
<P>
   For bar owners, the advertisements have a simple appeal.
Depending on the number of toilets, a bar can reap $500 to $2,000 a
year by allowing Insite Advertising to install aluminum and glass
advertisement frames in its bathrooms. The posters are
interchangeable; Miller uses his desktop computer to keep track of
which bathrooms are displaying what ads. Representatives check on
the advertisements once per week to make sure they are still in
good condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the logical next step,'' said James Twitchell, author of
``Adcult USA: The Triumph of Advertising in America.'' Companies
already print advertising slogans on beach sand, supermarket
receipts, airport baggage carousels, phone booths, and even the
little stickers on fruit. Several Texas school districts have
approved a plan to sell advertising space on the side of school
buses.
</P>
<P>
   But the more advertisements people see, the less they pay
attention, Twitchell said. As advertisements begin to appear on
nearly every surface, the challenge for advertisers is to break
through the clutter. ``A place where people have to stand still is
advertising Valhalla,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Insite's primary competitor, Canadian-based Zoom Media, has
found the bathroom advertisements so popular with the public that
it routinely prints double or triple the number of posters so it
can give them away. For example, the ``And don't forget Flushing''
poster has sold out, presumably to the people of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   The poster has also been nominated for an Obie advertising
award, a first for bathroom media, said Sheila Hayes,
communications director at the Outdoor Advertising Association.
</P>
<P>
   Zoom Media opened its first U.S. office in New York City a year
and a half ago, and now has a presence in eight U.S. cities and
throughout Canada. Last year, total revenues hit $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company was founded by Gui Forten and Carl Grenier in 1991,
from a blueprint they developed in a senior-year business class at
the University of Montreal. Grenier, 32, said the idea was an
outgrowth of a public health campaign that used rest room
advertisements to urge students to perform self-examinations for
venereal disease. ``Everybody talked about them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the world was not quite ready for the bathroom advertising
back then. It took two years of sleeping in his car on business
trips and being teased by friends as a ``crazy washroom guy''
before Zoom Media landed major accounts from beer and condom
companies. Those ads brought results, Grenier said, and Zoom Media
now counts Volkswagen and General Motors among its clients. Now
they are spending $20,000 to see if the idea will fly in a Montreal
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Insite Advertising also began as a college fantasy. Miller was
inspired by the Jim Carrey movie, ``Opportunity Knocks,'' during
his college summer vacation in 1996. At one point in the film,
Carrey's character tells a company president that life's big
decisions are made in the bathroom, not the boardroom, Miller
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   When Miller returned for his senior year at the University of
Michigan, he developed the idea in a class on small business. ``The
professor thought I was crazy, but the students loved it,'' he
said. A month after graduating, he launched his business in New
York City with a partner, David Dorfman.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are dozens of regional companies that sell
bathroom advertisements locally, some for more than a decade,
Insite advertising narrowly beat out Zoom Media to be the first in
the United States to market itself to national advertisers. Local
advertising ``cheapens the medium'' with shoddy advertisements for
questionable establishments, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Its first year in business, Insite posted revenues of $300,000.
Miller said that he expects 1998 revenues to hit $4 million. The
company now has 20 employees and offers R.J. Reynolds, Rossignol
skis and Fox Searchlight Pictures exposure in stalls on both
coasts.
</P>
<P>
   But some companies have no interest in being seen in the john.
Food companies, high-end fashion designers, and the American
Association of Retired Persons are probably never going to be
convinced to advertise in rest rooms, Miller said. But he contended
that many companies already advertise in less pleasant locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some bars, the bathrooms are cleaner than the subway,''
said Miller, a New York City resident. ``I would rather see an ad
there than in the subway.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, most people don't mind a sales pitch in such an
intimate space. A study by Zoom Media found that 85 percent of bar
patrons in Montreal like the bathroom ads, and 12 percent are
indifferent. According to the study, only 2 percent of patrons
hated the ads.
</P>
<P>
   A spot survey of patrons in New York City bars found no
objections to the ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is a clean bathroom, I don't mind,'' said Erik Klein, a
25-year-old college psychology student. ``But I would prefer clever
graffiti.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Stephen Siff is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1607EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8015 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-WEB-ADDICT &LR;      04-14 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-WEB-ADDICT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADDICTED TO THE INTERNET OR JUST FASCINATED? 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By JEROME LUSSIER  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joanna Curtis should have seen it coming. In the six
months after getting her Internet connection, she ran up a phone
bill of about $400 a month, on a $16,000 annual salary. During the
busiest months, Curtis, who lives in Brighton, England, was living
by West Coast time, which is eight hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   She spent all night chatting online with her Los Angeles
friends. But it was only when a close friend decided to open an
e-mail account because he could not reach her any other way, that
she realized she had a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis is not alone, according to hundreds of articles published
in recent years. ``Internet addiction'' has received considerable
media attention, exposing a possible downside of the Internet at a
time when enthusiasm for the Web is high. The stories range from
college students dropping out of school to play online games to
mothers neglecting their children to chat, to employees getting
fired for spending too much time on Web sites unrelated to their
work.
</P>
<P>
   As in many psychological disorders, there are no objective
criteria for what constitutes an addiction. Internet use only
becomes a problem when it has severe repercussions, like the loss
of a job or relationship. The novelty effect must also be accounted
for, since real addictions do not just fade with time.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most quoted experts on the so-called addiction is Dr.
Kimberley Young, who has a doctorate in psychology. Calling herself
the first ``cyberpsychologist,'' she conducted one of the first
studies of Internet addiction and is president of the Center for
Online Addiction, an online counseling service for so-called
Internet addicts.
</P>
<P>
   The center's Web site proudly states that ``her research has
been featured in more than 510 newsprint publications,'' in which
she often mentions her book, ``Caught in the Net.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Young's online clinic offers clients two forms of
counseling: a $15 e-mail reply, or a 50-minute chat room session
that costs $55. Although many critics have likened her practice to
Alcoholics Anonymous convening a 12-step meeting at a tavern, she
finds no contradiction in treating Internet addicts online.
Instead, she emphasizes the difficulty some people have in finding
competent therapists and the ease with which she can be contacted
through the Web.
</P>
<P>
   James Chriss, a sociology professor at Newman University, said
that ``the whole idea of 'addiction' to such things as gambling,
the Internet, etc., is basically a myth perpetuated by a particular
discipline _ psychology and other 'helping' professions _ which
serves to expand the areas of 'expertise' claimed by proponents of
these disciplines.''
</P>
<P>
   In his forthcoming book, ``Counseling and the Therapeutic
State,'' Chriss discusses ``the ways in which the language of
disease and addiction has infiltrated understandings of everyday
life, and why it is in the best economic interests of psychologists
and others to have us believe that such things are really
'addictions.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Other psychologists have adopted a more cautious approach.
``There is healthy skepticism in the field about Internet
addiction,'' said Eric Zehr, a clinical psychologist and vice
president of Addiction and Behavioral Services at Proctor Hospital,
in Peoria, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The American Psychological Association has not recognized
Internet addiction as an established disorder. Neither has the
American Psychiatric Association. ``But if you go back 50 or 60
years ago, people had the same reaction toward alcoholism,'' Zehr
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he believes the addiction is real, Zehr says very
little research has been conducted on Internet addiction, and that
the number of cases remains very low. Proctor Hospital, one of the
country's most comprehensive treatment providers for addiction
disorders, has had fewer than 100 inquiries on the problem, with
fewer than 20 people ending up in treatment as outpatients. Zehr
said most cases turned out to be sexual, gambling or spending
addictions, for which the Internet is simply a new vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   As for Curtis, she got over her problem alone, over the course
of the year. ``As my personal life gradually got sorted out, and I
became happier, the addiction gradually left me,'' she wrote in an
e-mail message.
</P>
<P>
   Today, three years after her first Internet connection, she
works as Web master for the University of Sussex in Brighton. She
said she enjoyed every minute of her work but felt totally free to
leave it whenever she wanted. ``I guess that in a way you could say
my year of addiction taught me a new skill,'' she said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Young's Web site address is www.netaddiction.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Jerome Lussier is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
