<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERRUPTING AN IMAC NAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Sometimes when I put my iMac to sleep, it won't wake up when
I want it to. How can I fix that?
</P>
<P>
   A. With the Macintosh operating system, putting your computer to
sleep means putting it in a low-power state. The screen will go
dark, but any files and programs that are open will stay that way
until you wake up the machine by hitting any key. You can put the
Mac to sleep manually with the Sleep option under the Special menu
or set your Energy Saver control panel to put the machine to sleep
after a specified period of inactivity.
</P>
<P>
   If the computer refuses to wake up without rebooting, there are
a number of things that could be causing a problem. Run a
third-party utility software or the Disk First Aid program (found
on the system software CD-ROM) on your hard drive and repair any
disk corruption the program finds. Screen savers or security
software might also interfere with the Energy Saver control panel.
If you have these installed, try turning them off and see if the
computer wakes up normally after sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The Tech Info Library on Apple's Web site lists a number of
other troubleshooting steps at the
til.info.apple.com/techinfo.nsf/artnum/n30894 page. While on the
Apple site, you may want to go to the Software Updates
(www.info.apple.com/swupdates), click on Fast Search for iMac
updates and download the iMac Firmware Update. That patch is
supposed to help prevent iMac start-up problems.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
