<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8035 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELEBRITIES-CHILDRENS     04-14 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEBRITIES-CHILDRENSBOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRITY-AUTHORED TALES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies SHRIVER-CHILDRENS BOOK) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a random sampling of recently published ``celebrity''
books for children, ranked in approximate order of literary quality
and entertainment value.
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Dr. White,'' by Jane Goodall (North-South Books, $15.95):
The woman associated with studying chimpanzee behavior proves she
knows a lot about children's psyches. Dr. White, a furry little
dog, helps critically ill kids until a misguided health inspector
tries to chase the pooch/physician out of the building.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``The Meanest Thing to Say,'' by Bill Cosby (Scholastic Inc.,
$13.95): Cosby, who holds a doctorate in education from the
University of Massachusetts, has crafted a wonderful series of
stories about the ways kids can solve problems. ``Meanest Thing''
may be the best, when lead character ``Little Bill'' has to decide
whether to be nasty back to a new kid at school.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``What's Heaven?'' by Maria Shriver (Golden Books, $15):
Shriver's writing skills are impressive. If her personal religious
beliefs sometimes seem overstressed, at least there is no doubt
about her sincerity in helping children understand how deceased
loved ones can live on in their family members' hearts.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Count Me In,'' by Cal Ripken Jr. with Greg Brown (Taylor
Publishing, $14.95): Baseball's Iron Man reminds kids to work hard
for their dreams. Some baseball terms won't mean much to youngsters
who don't follow the sport, but then they probably wouldn't be
reading a Cal Ripken book anyway.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``The Jolly Mon,'' by Jimmy Buffett and Savannah Jane Buffett
(Harcourt Brace, $16): The story is pretty good, but the
illustrations by Lambert Davis are much, much better. Apparently
this is a tale told often over the Buffett family dinner table
(Savannah Jane is Jimmy's daughter). At least he's not sending kids
to ``Margaritaville.''
</P>
<P>
   6. ``Halley Came to Jackson,'' by Mary Chapin Carpenter
(HarperCollins, $15.95): The ``Halley'' in question is the comet.
The story is ``very'' basic, but the book comes with a cassette of
Chapin Carpenter singing a similar tale.
</P>
<P>
   7. ``Dr. Laura Schlessinger's Why Do You Love Me?'' by Laura
Schlessinger with Martha Lambert (HarperCollins, $15.95): The
Schlessinger ego is evident throughout, including putting the
author's name first in the title. Why would that mean anything to
children? Obviously, the talk-show host thinks Mommy and Daddy will
be doing the book-buying _ and it's hard to believe many kids would
enjoy this awkwardly written tale of a child wondering why Mom
loves him, no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   8. ``Today I Feel Silly &AMP; Other Moods That Make My Day,'' by
Jamie Lee Curtis (HarperCollins, $15.95): Run from this, just like
Jamie Lee ran from the killer in ``Halloween.'' The rhymes are
stilted, the humor is forced and the make-a-face cutout at book's
end rips way too easily.
</P>
<P>
   9. ``The Teddy Bears' Picnic,'' arranged and performed by Jerry
Garcia and David Grisman (HarperCollins, $14.95): This is another
singer's book with an accompanying song tape. It's nothing more
than the words to the venerable old ``Teddy Bear's Picnic'' tune
with some matching illustrations. It was bad enough that Garcia
spent some of his last days helping peddle ties. Unless your 3- or
4-year-old is a Deadhead, this one's a must to avoid, as another
old song suggests.
</P>
<P>
   10. ``Budgie Goes to Sea,'' by Her Royal Highness the Duchess of
York (Aladdin, $5.99): ``Budgie'' is a helicopter who saves people
from certain disaster. But he can't save this book. Simplistic,
pedantic, boring _ you come up with a negative adjective, any
negative adjective, and it will apply.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
