<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8041 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SCHOOLS-WEB-ART-2     04-14 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SCHOOLS-WEB-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIRING THE SCHOOLS FOR E-MAIL AND MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By SIMON RODBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At Stuyvesant High School on a Friday not long ago,
students in Nautica jackets and flared jeans lounged in the
hallways and played with a football on their way to class. In the
library, seniors finished last-minute revisions of their college
essays.
</P>
<P>
   Under a poster bearing the school's computer-use policy,
Beatrice Jason, a 14-year-old freshman, logged into her school
e-mail account. ``I never had e-mail before I got to Stuyvesant,''
she said. Now she corresponds with friends, sends homework to
teachers, and asks college professors for help with social studies
projects.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of schools now include Internet access in their
services to students, and the New York City Board of Education
hopes to provide a citywide e-mail system for its students by
September. But in a city of overcrowded classrooms and outdated
textbooks, schools' use of e-mail shows both the possibilities of
innovation and the persistence of old problems in a new era _ lack
of money, the schools' responsibility for sheltering children while
also teaching them, and basic questions about how children learn.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-two percent of New York City public school students live
in areas of concentrated poverty, and according to the most recent
state survey, the city school system has only 7.7 computers per 100
students, compared to an average of 12.2 per 100 students
statewide. Many students' only exposure to modern information
technology is through school-based computer access.
</P>
<P>
   Technology advocates can be so enthusiastic about the Internet's
ability to give students access to new sources of knowledge that
they make textbooks sound superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had the choice I wouldn't have the Internet or e-mail in
my school, I'd have a Concorde jet,'' said James Bosco, Chairman of
the Board of the Consortium for School Networking, a national
educational technology group. ``Well, I don't think that's in the
cards. The next best bet is for kids to encounter the world via
contact with other kids, and that's one of the best things that
e-mail can do.''
</P>
<P>
   But as anyone with an e-mail account and an over-enthusiastic
friend knows, e-mail has many uses. Students may spend less time
sending e-mail to far-off professors than reading the latest Monica
jokes. The possibility of such jokes also touches on problems like
child protection and online censorship that concern parents,
educators, and civil-liberties experts.
</P>
<P>
   The advantages and limitations of the Internet are clear at
Stuyvesant, an elite public school on the Hudson River. For
instance, a math teacher, Danny Jaye, uses a class Web page to post
homework problems, reviews, and even test grades using student
identification numbers.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail is also a one of his teaching tools. ``If students have a
problem with the homework, they're not hesitant to e-mail me and
ask for help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The correspondence goes both ways: ``Whenever they're absent or
if I want to get in touch with a student, I have their e-mail
address. It's less intrusive than calling them at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those e-mails do go home, however. Jaye estimated that
80 percent of his students ask him to send e-mail to accounts
outside Stuyvesant. Students are quick to disparage their school
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get a free e-mail address from Hotmail or Yahoo,''
said senior Adam Ostoasewski, 16, ``so what's the point?'' Tatiana
Schnurr, a 17-year-old senior in Jaye's calculus class, prefers her
home e-mail account, but she appreciates the class Web page. ``It's
useful and easy to use,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalton School, a high-tech, high-cost private school on the
Upper East Side, aspires to integrate e-mail directly into
students' education. But the school's motive is not
intercontinental correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Access to the outside world wasn't really the initial purpose
of our electronic mail, and it still isn't,'' said Wolfgang
Heidmann, Dalton's technology director.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the school used its e-mail program to set up an
internal conference system, with subjects ranging from sports to
ethical problems. All sixth-grade students receive e-mail accounts
to use throughout their high school years, and most of the
conferences have no limits on who can participate.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Sheridan, who teaches a senior course on Shakespeare and
monitors the class' e-mail conference, said that ``the conferences
are seen as an extension of the classroom,'' allowing shy students
to share their thoughts and inviting all students to continue
discussions. One 24-hour ``thread'' on the Shakespeare conference
comprised 15 postings from five students and Ms. Sheridan.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Fruchter, of New York University's Institute for Education
and Social Policy, agrees that computers can be helpful. but he
cautioned that ``the primary difference is still the quality of
teachers in the classroom, including what they do with
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers must also play a crucial role in insuring that online
behavior follows the rules of classroom behavior. ``The approach to
behavior that is not tolerated online should be the same as it is
for behavior that is not tolerated off-line,'' said Alex Fowler of
the Electronic Frontier Foundation, an Internet policy group.
</P>
<P>
   At the Dalton School, Ms. Sheridan said that part of her e-mail
duties is peace-keeping. ``Every conference is monitored by an
adult, so if there's an unfortunate remark the adult can remove
that remark and warn the student to pay attention to the protocols
of the conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Most school e-mail systems have policies detailing ``acceptable
use'' of their systems.
</P>
<P>
   Obscenity is a standard, if ill-defined, prohibition. Other
areas are more fuzzy. The Board of Education's current Internet
usage policy prohibits the use of e-mail accounts to send or
receive personal messages, while Stuyvesant's policy has no such
prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   Elspeth Taylor, who oversees the board of education's technology
program, says that as e-mail becomes more widespread, her policy
will have to change: ``I don't think anyone really believes that no
e-mail messages are going to be on the system for personal
purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Practices such as the removal of offensive material from
postings raises civil liberties issues. Bill Stamatis, who studies
the Internet for the United Federation of Teachers, said there will
be conflicts over management, free speech, and privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is e-mail the property of the Board of Ed?'' he asked. ``Who
has a right to it?'' School administrators may want to screen
messages teachers send to students or read e-mail newsletters
produced by children, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The board of education's experience with e-mail provides another
cautionary note. The Strategic Technology Plan of 1997 called for
$2.1 billion in improvements, including full networking of schools
and 130,000 new computers, or at least one computer for every eight
students, about the statewide average.
</P>
<P>
   The board of education says it will wire at least five
classrooms in every school building to the Internet by September,
with the help of $55 million in federal grants. But the board has
not yet found the money for many other parts of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   And school-based e-mail? At the beginning of this semester, Ms.
Taylor of the board of education said she planned to put into place
a citywide system by September, providing every student from the
4th through 12th grades with an account. Now, realizing the
difficulties of designing such an extensive system and the lack of
money for staff support, she is not as optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an interest in going to e-mail,'' she said, ``but
we're not sure how we're going to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
