<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV02-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., MAY 2, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have a water stain on the ceiling of my upstairs bedroom
which is apparently due to a roof leak. I cannot seem to locate the
source even though I inspected all roof flashing and shingles over
the area where the leak appears and patched every place that looked
even the least bit doubtful. The leak still shows up after every
heavy rain. My attic is unfinished, but it is insulated and I
cannot see any places where daylight shines through or where there
is any kind of crack or open seam. What can you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   A: Roof leaks are often very difficult to locate because water
does not necessary fall straight down through a hole or open seam.
In many cases water that seeps in can travel horizontally along
roof sheathing or even the underside of a rafter as shown here
until it runs down a stud or other structural member. Then it may
travel further along that joist or beam until it finally drips down
onto the ceiling below. Finding the source of the leak may require
crawling into the attic during a heavy rain storm (or while someone
is running a hose over that part of the roof) and shining a bright
light under the roof. Pull off insulation to expose the roof
sheathing and rafters if necessary, then start near the eaves and
move your light upwards to see where the water, or a damp spot,
first appears. Then follow the path of the water back up to see
where it originates.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My home is heated with radiant heat and the heating pipes are
embedded in the ceiling plaster. There is also a circulating fan
that moves the heated air throughout the rooms. My problem is that
cracks have formed in the ceiling due to the heating pipes and
although I cleaned these cracks out and resurfaced them with
conventional plaster the cracks have reappeared. Is there some
special kind of plaster or a porous tape I can place over the
cracks before I repaint again?
</P>
<P>
   A: Plaster, or patching plaster, is not the best material to use
for filling cracks. Normally a vinyl base spackling compound is
used for maximum bonding power, and for best insurance against
further cracking. However, if there is a continual problem with
cracking, due to expansion and contraction of the heating pipes,
then you would probably be better off applying a fiberglass tape
that is sold for this purpose in most hardware stores and home
centers. This bridges the cracks and is then covered with a special
type of patching compound that dries semi-flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There are dark stains in the corners of several rooms in my
house as well as in the middle of one wall. There is also a similar
dark stain in one corner of the basement near the back of the
house. What could be causing these stains?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sounds as though you have a mildew problem due to moisture
inside the walls. This could be caused by one or more leaks in your
outside walls, or in the caulking around the outside. You should go
over the outside carefully to look for cracks or open joints, as
well as possible missing or cracked caulking around window and door
frames.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The people that owned this house before we bought it added on
an extra room. This room had plain brick around the outside,
although the rest of the house was covered with yellow brick. They
painted the new brick yellow to match the original and now this
paint is all peeling and looks awful. One contractor suggested
using a gel remover and pressure washing to get the old paint off,
but this would be messy. Another suggested sandblasting and then
tuck pointing. This would cost $1,500. Is this reasonable?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you are asking if the cost is reasonable, then there is no
way I can answer since it would depend on the size of the areas and
many other variables that I know nothing about. If you are asking
does this seem a reasonable way to get the paint off, then I can
say it would work, but you must be sure the contractor knows what
he is doing. If sandblasting is not done carefully and by an
experienced professional who has done this work before, it can do
considerable damage to the brick and to the mortar joints.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``DRIP EMERGES THROUGH CEILING'' goes
with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Water seeping in can travel along beams and structural
members for a considerable distance before dripping down onto
ceilings below.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
