<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARTRAM-GARDEN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIC BARTRAM'S GARDEN: IN BLOOM, PRECARIOUSLY, FOR CENTURIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (bl) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easy to get lost trying to find America's oldest living
botanical garden. A few miles off Route I-95, just south of Center
City, Philadelphia, anonymous boulevards crisscross miles of
industrial parks, vast stretches of treeless tarmac and boxy
buildings. Plant hunters looking here would just find grass.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a sharp eye to follow the little signs for the Historic
Bartram's Garden, now a public park, cinched between the railroad
track and a river lined by oil tanks. But it must have been a
little paradise when John Bartram, a Quaker farmer with a lust in
his heart for wild plants, bought 102 acres along the Schuylkill
and proceeded to grow a lot more than corn.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Bartram put down his plow, he collected plants, from
the headwaters of the Schuylkill to the shores of Lake Ontario and
all through the South. (Fine, John _ let your wife and the nine
kids stay home and weed the dang garden.)
</P>
<P>
   Soon Bartram was sending boxes of seeds and plants wrapped in
moss to Europeans hungry for exotic species from America: sweet
gum, oak-leafed hydrangea, swamp azalea, mountain laurel and the
now-legendary Franklinia tree.
</P>
<P>
   By 1783, the Bartrams' first nursery broadsheet catalog, in
English and French, offered 220 species, from tulip poplars and a
wide variety of oaks to poison ivy, which was considered a
beautiful plant with medicinal possibilities. By the 1830's, the
Bartram clan was growing 4,000 different species of trees, shrubs
and herbaceous plants, supplying the great estates of Europe, as
well as Monticello and Mount Vernon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linnaeus called John Bartram the greatest natural botanist in
the world,'' said Martha Wolf, the director of the John Bartram
Association, which oversees the garden and which, in mid-May, will
celebrate the 300th anniversary of Bartram's birth with a series of
lectures, demonstrations, plant sales and musical events.
</P>
<P>
   Carolus Linnaeus, the Swedish botanist, had just created a
system of naming plants _ a sexual classification based on the
number of stamens and pistils in the flowers. Bartram taught
himself enough Latin to use the system, and even researched plants
for Linnaeus, but he saw the limitations of such a classification.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving things official names made it easier to do botany,''
said Joel T. Fry, the garden's curator of historic collections.
``But it ignored the family relationships between plants, which
naturalists like Bartram had observed for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartram's son William was a great explorer in his own right, and
his ``Travels Through North and South Carolina, Georgia, East and
West Florida,'' first published in 1791 filled with his exquisite
illustrations, appealed to the romantic sentiments of the day,
which saw God's spirit in all of nature.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1765, John and William were heading down to
Florida when they came upon a grove of graceful trees with striped
bark on the banks of the Altamaha River, in Georgia. They named the
species Franklinia altamaha, after their friend Benjamin Franklin.
They were too late to have seen the trees bloom in August, when
they cover themselves with flowers shaped like white camellias with
plush golden stamens, but William returned to collect seeds and
specimens, planting some in the nursery in 1777.
</P>
<P>
   John Bartram died that same year, so he was not to see the
Franklinia bloom in his garden four years later. Nor would he have
known that, after 1803, the tree would disappear from the wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those seeds the Bartrams first collected have helped save the
tree from extinction,'' said Ms. Wolf, who, with Fry, recounted the
rocky history of when the last Bartram gardeners got too old to
carry on.
</P>
<P>
   When John Bartram died, his sons William and John Jr., as well
as a granddaughter, Ann, expanded the nursery, which in its heyday
had enough greenhouses to grow 10,000 potted plants. But by 1850,
there were no more Bartrams interested in the business, and the
land was set to be sold at a sheriff's sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``And nobody was interested any longer in American plants,'' Fry
said. ``The fad was bedding schemes with begonias and geraniums.''
A railroad baron, Andrew Eastwick, bought the place, vowing, ``Not
a bush of this beloved old garden shall be disturbed,'' and built a
mansion.
</P>
<P>
   The Bartram house, built of local Wissahickon schist and
lovingly expanded by the Bartrams over three generations, has a
wide porch and many doors opening to the gardens. The trees, both
exotic and native, were lined up in straight allees that marched
down to the river. Shrubs and herbaceous plants were tucked in
among the trees if they needed partial shade, or near the river if
they wanted wet feet: as plant explorers, the Bartrams respected
natural habitats. And John, who had longed to be a doctor, grew
medicinal herbs and treated his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bartram planted everything,'' Fry said. ``He wanted gorse and
firs from Scotland. Ben Franklin sent him soybeans from China and a
recipe for tofu.'' The Bartrams loved Native American foods, too,
like papaw, persimmon and hickory nuts. ``They would bring back
selected varieties from the Indians,'' Fry said, ``but no one
thought to save them when the land was sold.''
</P>
<P>
   After Eastwick died, in the 1870's, this vast repository of
cultural and genetic material fell into oblivion, and many of the
finer specimens were spirited off by those who knew their value. In
1891, the City of Philadelphia bought the property as a park. In
the 1950's, the John Bartram Association, founded in 1893 by the
descendants, found a whimsical drawing of the eight-acre botanic
garden, dated 1758 and sketched by either John or William, showing
the rough layout of trees and beds.
</P>
<P>
   But only a few of the trees planted by the Bartrams survive _
like the gingko, planted in 1785, and the Kentucky yellowwood,
planted in 1803. They stand among a hodgepodge of trees planted by
the city as a rough sort of arboretum. It took the Bicentennial to
inspire Philadelphia to see the historic importance of the Bartram
garden, and in 1980, the University of Pennsylvania started an
archeological dig that turned up everything from the placement of
paths and garden beds to evidence of prehistoric man.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
