<HEADER>
A8092 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARTRAM-GARDEN-NYT &LR;      04-14 0232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARTRAM-GARDEN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: prehistoric man.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, the garden operates on a shoestring, with not even a
full-time gardener to tend the 45-acre site. But the old barn is
being turned into an education center, and there are plans to
restore the gardens as a living laboratory for the native plants
the Bartrams collected and propagated.
</P>
<P>
   The association also managed to buy the polluted site of an old
cement factory and turn it into a wildflower meadow, and when Sun
Oil Co. was cited by the Environmental Protection Agency for
violations on the south side of the garden, the company agreed to
mitigate its penalties by planting native plants in the marshland.
And as part of Bartram's 300th anniversary, the association has
sponsored a worldwide census of the Franklinia altamaha.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had more than 2,000 responses, a handful of them from
other countries,'' Ms. Wolf said. ``What touches me is how
emotionally involved people are with this tree. They'll tell how it
was mowed down or the pig ate it, and it came back. They remember
the year they got it, and when it first bloomed.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because it's a story _ a beautiful living thing snatched
from extinction. Just like the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Historic Bartram's Garden is at 54th Street and Lindbergh
Boulevard, in Philadelphia. Information on the 300th anniversary
events is available from (215) 729-5281).
</P>
</TEXT>
