<P>
   AIRTRAN-PROFIT _ AirTran Holdings turned a profit in the first
quarter, beating analysts' expectations. The company turned around
a $7.9 million loss a year ago for a gain of $3 million. It said
the improved results reflect better economic conditions and the
effects of some recent initiatives. It said traffic was up 14.8
percent while capacity grew by 9 percent. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ROB-HUMPHREY-CONFERENCE _ Charles Brewer and new CFO address
analysts and Robinson Humphrey conference. Hopefully, he'll
elaborate on the broadband comments he made Tuesday about setting
up an AOL-like arrangement with telecomm and cable carriers. (Katz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-PERU _ BellSouth Corp. (BLS) launched a bid to
purchase an additional 15% in Peruvian communications company Tele
2000. In a press release Wednesday, BellSouth said it will offer 50
cents a share to purchase a minimum of 31.5 million shares of Tele
2000. BellSouth already owns more than 124 million shares, or 59%,
of Tele 2000, which has about 210 million shares outstanding.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FREAKNIK-CONVENTIONS _ Freaknik is just a day away. But visitors
to the city will include not only tens of thousands of students,
but educators, engineers and IT workers as well. Thousands of
conventioneers will also be in the city during part or all of
Freaknik weekend, but convention bureau officials and meeting
planners expect few problems. They cite smaller crowds and better
planning with many activities held within the hotels. (Poole,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (f) Financial and (a) General News categories.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-INTERNET _ Companies and universities are increasingly
turning to the Internet in their crusade to rout the millennium
bug. They are using the Web to post status reports and inform
employees about how to make their computers recognize the year
2000. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
