<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8161 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POSTMODERN-CHURCH-NYT     04-14 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSTMODERN-CHURCH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAINLINE CHURCH SEEKS TO CATCH THE WAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``This place is like a tree,'' a woman recently told me about
her Episcopal parish, ``We're growing deep roots and branching out
into the world at the same time. This church is a good place. The
Spirit is here.''
 &HT;    In recent years, few religious groups have taken as much media
battering as historic mainline Protestant denominations -- the
Episcopalians, Presbyterians, Lutherans, Methodists, and
Congregationalists included.
 &HT;    Depicted as declining institutions mired in moldy liberalism and
embattled by culture wars, critics have long awaited the final
extinction of these religious dinosaurs.
 &HT;    Mainline Protestants, imbued with a spiritual inferiority
complex, appeared to be quietly accepting their imminent demise.
Unlike evangelicals who kick up a fuss when criticized in the
media, mainliners took their punches with grace.
 &HT;    With the exception of a few stories on gay ordination, the media
lost interest in them and turned its gaze toward evangelicals,
Eastern faiths, new religious groups and Catholicism. After all,
what could possibly be interesting about the local Episcopal
Church?
 &HT;    As it turns out, plenty.
 &HT;    Over the last year, the Episcopal Church has embarked on a
self-study called the Zacchaeus Project. Named after a biblical
character who climbed a tree to see Jesus, the Zacchaeus Project
hoped to get a clear view of their church. The project has revealed
a denomination of surprising growth and spiritual vitality.
 &HT;    Like other mainline churches, the Episcopal Church suffered
membership hemorrhage in the 1970s and 1980s. That, however, has
stopped. In the last decade membership has remained steady while
attendance climbed -- and is still climbing. Although unwilling to
sign-up as full-fledged members, thousands of new people are coming
to Episcopal churches. Decline is no longer the story.
 &HT;    An increasing birth rate, lower death rate, and baby-boomers
returning to church contributed to the turnaround. However, the
Zacchaeus Project reveals that people are going to Episcopal
churches for distinctly theological and spiritual reasons -- not
just as a result of demographic quirks.
 &HT;    Episcopalians praise their church as ``diverse,'' ``inclusive,''
``comprehensive,'' ``tolerant'' and ``pluralistic.'' Even at the
most conservative Episcopal parishes, these words appear as
positives. ``I was about to leave the church altogether,'' said one
man at a growing urban church, ``because the church I grew up in
was so exclusionary. Then I found this place.''
 &HT;    In the 1970s and 1980s, churches with ``tight boundaries'' grew.
Thus, conservative groups with strict morality and doctrine
exploded numerically. The principle held for new religious
movements and traditionalist Roman Catholicism: the more
restrictive, the more successful. Millions of people embraced
exclusive religions -- ``we are saved and you are not.''
 &HT;    Strict religion appears to have created a spiritual backlash.
Those constricted by dogmatism -- who migrated to such groups as
teen-agers or at a moment of personal crisis -- began to question
the limits placed upon them. Indeed, that most new Episcopalians
are ex-evangelicals and former Roman Catholics points to the
inadequacy of tightly boundaried faith.
 &HT;    Rather than certainty, the Episcopal Church -- in line with
other mainline denominations -- emphasizes ambiguity and mystery as
paths to God. Its theology, sometimes decried as ``mushy
liberalism,'' is actually a pluralistic theology that affirms
questions and intellectual exploration.
 &HT;    Thus, the old mainline churches were perfectly poised to welcome
those questioning fundamentalism. As newer statistics show, a
significant minority of Americans are migrating toward more open
faiths than in previous decades.
 &HT;    American religion is often divided politically between
``conservative'' and ``liberal.'' It is better understood in terms
of its spirituality -- a continuum between styles of certainty and
mystery, between clarity and ambiguity. Some people like answers;
other prefer the quest.
 &HT;    Contemporary mainline religion leans toward quest-spirituality
and resists all polarization -- even between itself and other
spiritual styles.
 &HT;    Thus, the new Episcopalians believe that the answer is the
journey; that certainty arises in mystery. They value inclusivity
so much that they extol such paradoxes as signs of spiritual
wisdom. They see their hearts and minds engaged in a holistic
journey toward God. They envision spirituality as a circle (or
spiral) rather than a line. They seek to enfold all persons --
indeed all faiths -- into a community striving to touch the divine.
 &HT;    The Zacchaeus Project points to good news for the Episcopal
Church and other mainline churches. The cultural ethos seems to be
shifting their direction: culture-wars weary Americans are more in
a mood for questions than answers, consensus rather than exclusion.
And the up-coming Generation-Xers resonate more with mystery than
with dogmatism.
 &HT;    In short, the old mainline has reinvented itself into a
postmodern church and the message is seems to be reaching many
Americans.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
