<SLUG> BC-MURDER-EXECUTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITIAN EXECUTED FOR 1988 MURDER OF COUPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Roy Ramsey Jr., convicted of killing a
retired Grandview, Mo., couple in 1988, was executed early
Wednesday at the Potosi Correctional Center.
</P>
<P>
   He was the fourth person to die by lethal injection in Missouri
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before his execution, Ramsey came as close as he ever
would to an apology for his brutal slaying of Garnett and Betty
Ledford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't mad at nobody,'' Ramsey said from his holding cell
next to the death chamber. ``Matter of fact, tell the Ledford
family for me that I feel bad about their tragedy. And if I cross
over to the other world, I'll tell (the Ledfords) that their family
back here loves them and misses them. I do feel bad for them.''
</P>
<P>
   And as he waited Tuesday night with his attorney, J.R. Hobbs,
and two preachers, the Rev. Larry Rice of St. Louis and the Rev.
Paul Jones of Kansas City, he maintained his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly say I didn't kill them,'' Ramsey said. ``I
guess I'm going to pay for it though, and that's all right. I ain't
mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Others had little doubt of his guilt in the murder of the
retired south Kansas City couple.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey's fate was sealed at 9:15 p.m. Tuesday when Gov. Mel
Carnahan denied a request for clemency. The U.S. Supreme Court also
had rejected a final plea for a stay of execution.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon said Tuesday that he had no
doubt about Ramsey's guilt or whether he deserved to be executed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a brutal double murderer who has attempted to slow down
and manipulate the system for years,'' said Nixon. ``The killing of
senior citizens in their own homes _ execution style in their own
bedrooms _ is an example of the cruel and cold-blooded murders for
which the death penalty should clearly be an option.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8169 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSERVATIVES-CULTURE     04-14 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSERVATIVES-CULTURE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVES DEBATE THE FUTURE OF AMERICAN CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Is political involvement the way to change society?
Or has politics failed because of ``cultural decay,'' as one
conservative activist says?
</P>
<P>
   Those have been central questions within the
religious-conservative movement since President Clinton escaped
expulsion from office this winter. They were debated Tuesday before
a panel gathered by Sen. Sam Brownback of Kansas and Rep. Joseph
Pitts of Pennsylvania, both Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The two lawmakers said American culture needed healing, but in a
way that transcended the bitter political divisions that have
characterized the battles so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must aim to change hearts and minds as much as we seek to
change laws,'' Brownback said. ``We each have a role to play in
making our society more civil, more compassionate and more
connected.''
</P>
<P>
   But the divisions remain.
</P>
<P>
   They surfaced in February after the Senate's decision not to
remove Clinton from office after he had been impeached. Paul
Weyrich, head of the Free Congress Foundation and a veteran
conservative activist, wrote a letter that he posted on the group's
Web site in which he said, ``Politics has failed because of the
collapse of the culture. The culture we are living in becomes an
ever-wider sewer.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on Brownback's panel, Weyrich said he never meant to
suggest that religious conservatives abandon politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to remain in politics for defensive purposes,'' he
said. ``What I'm saying is don't depend on the political process to
advance the cultural agenda. We have to take back the culture by
ourselves. The question is how we do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Weyrich's ideas focus on conservative activities outside the
mainstream of society, such as home schooling.
</P>
<P>
   But Don Eberly, president of the Civil Society Project and an
aide in Reagan administration, called that an ``oasis strategy''
and a ``quarantine'' of conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Eberly said conservatives need to reach out more to the
``gatekeepers'' of culture, in the museums and media and other
institutions. He said conservative communities spend ``billions''
on radio and television but simply ``to talk to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The forum, which Brownback hopes to use to help in his writing
of a book, was called ``Next Steps Toward Cultural Renewal.'' No
clear path emerged, however, after two hours of polite discussion
that wandered over terrain ranging from Jesus and the Apostles to
the Victorians to Martin Luther King Jr. to Jerry Springer.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives have a familiar list of cultural touchstones that
they argue define the degradation of society, from the sex and
violence portrayed by Hollywood to the behavior of President
Clinton. But they are divided on the way to solve some of the more
general concerns, such as the rise in teen-age pregnancies, the
number of young black men in prison and the quality of schools.
Some demand adherence to a conservative agenda; others say they
must go beyond partisan politics.
</P>
<P>
   Some panel participants such as Adam Myerson of the Heritage
Foundation, which sponsored the forum, said this was
``conservatism's cultural moment'' to ``repair the fabric of
American life.'' Others said the cultural war was being won, albeit
slowly.
</P>
<P>
   The debate boiled down to two points of view:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in great danger of politicizing Jesus,'' said
the Rev. Ed Dobson, a Grand Rapids, Mich., pastor and former
official with the Moral Majority. ``Where I sit, I feel tremendous
pressure from national political organizations to be more
politically active in order to bring about cultural
transformation.''
</P>
<P>
   He said churches need to divorce themselves from politics
because the religious conservative movement appeared to be simply
``white, middle-class and Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ralph Reed, a Republican strategist and former executive
director of the Christian Coalition, said that while his own
political activism was not due to a ``desire to lead anyone to
Christ,'' Christians have a basic responsibility to be politically
aware.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can still go to evangelical churches all over America today
and ask people, `Who knows the names of their congressman?' and
two-thirds of them... (don't),'' Reed said. ``That means you're not
even knowledgeable enough to be an effective citizen. It's not
about whether you're white, middle-class and a Republican.''
 &LR; tag1:To reach David Goldstein, a Washington correspondent for The
Star, call (202) 383-6105 or send e-mail to
dgoldstein &LR; krwashington.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
