<SLUG> BC-TAX-TIME-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S DOWN TO THE WIRE FOR FILING INCOME TAX RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Tax-preparation offices really started humming this
week, but the pros still have one bit of advice for the
foot-draggers:
</P>
<P>
   Get moving.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline for filing federal and state income taxes in time
to avoid needless hassles, penalties and interest charges is less
than 48 hours away.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if you finish in time to file before the midnight
Thursday deadline, you'll have more time to snag free bagels, ice
cream, candy bars and other goodies that marketers of all sorts
provide at impromptu street parties around post offices each April
15.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers using the Internet might find even more exotic fare; a
group identifying itself as the Busty Bookkeepers offers live nude
tax advice at a Web site set up by a Los Angeles entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the Internal Revenue Service estimates that nationally
perhaps more than 30 million taxpayers haven't filed yet, an
unusually high number.
</P>
<P>
   Just remember that the lines aren't likely to get shorter if you
delay, tax preparers said. Nationally, about 45 percent of an
expected 126 million taxpayers still hadn't filed by April 2, when
the IRS last counted.
</P>
<P>
   Business ``has been building steadily all this week,'' said Mike
James, an executive in charge of several Kansas City H&AMP;R Block
offices.
</P>
<P>
   Tax officials said that by April 2 a record 1.8 million
taxpayers had filed returns from home computers and that more than
18 million had filed electronically through tax-preparation
offices.
</P>
<P>
   Don't wait until the last minute to try to file that way,
either, because telephone lines are likely to be very busy,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you aren't going to have your taxes done until 11:59, the
best place to be then will be in your car heading for a post
office, not at home in front of your computer,'' said Neil Allen of
CCH Inc., a suburban Chicago tax information and software
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers who want to file electronically late Thursday still
should be able to get their returns in on time, however, said Don
Roberts, a spokesman at IRS headquarters in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that a surge of refund seekers filed in early February,
so the agency's computers already have absorbed one electronic
avalanche larger than what is expected Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS also has built a safety valve of sorts into the system,
Roberts said. Taxpayers who try to file electronically late
Thursday and are rejected will have five more days to try again
after the problem is corrected.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we still need to be able to tell that you first tried to
file before the deadline,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Tax professionals said they had a pretty good idea of which tax
changes were the most likely to cause trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Sorting out HOPE and Lifetime Learning tax credits for college
students has been among the biggest challenges for families coming
to H&AMP;R Block, said Todd Ransom, a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Either credit can produce four-figure tax savings. But each goes
by different rules, and families can't use both for the same
student in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Families with younger children generally wrestle hardest with
the $400-per-child credit that's also new this tax year, Ransom
said. First, the credit isn't automatic; income and other credits
claimed affect the savings. Also, families with three or more
children generally need to calculate the credit differently than
families with just one or two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then you have the Roth,'' Ransom noted.
</P>
<P>
   The Roth IRA is new this tax season. It essentially allows
taxpayers to trade a potential $2,000 deduction on a traditional
individual retirement account now for tax-free income in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   It would take some pencil pushing to determine which might be
better deal for each taxpayer, of course, because key rules aren't
the same for both types of retirement accounts. Many who choose
Roths encounter extra tax work, too, especially if they've switched
money from either type of IRA to the other.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS estimates that a record 7.8 million taxpayers this year
will request automatic four-month extensions to buy time for
finishing their paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Those requests also must be filed, on Form 4868, either
electronically or on paper before midnight Thursday. And if you
expect to owe more money, you need to send that payment along with
your extension request. All tax liabilities are due April 15
whether you get an extension or not.
</P>
<P>
   Send the full amount, if you can, to avoid interest and
penalties, tax specialists advise. Otherwise, send at least as much
you paid last year to avoid potentially escalating late-payment
penalties. You still would pay interest, currently about 8 percent,
on any money not paid by April 15.
</P>
<P>
   Cash-strapped taxpayers can reduce, but not eliminate, potential
penalties and interest by requesting to make installment payments
when they file and paying a $43 fee. The IRS can say no but often
doesn't if the debt is less than $25,000 and you offer to pay
within five years.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, for the first time, taxpayers also can pay by
credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Tax experts disagree about how good an idea that is. Credit card
rates generally are higher than what the IRS charges, but taxpayers
suffer less financial damage if they miss a payment to the credit
card company. Taxpayers also must pay an additional fee, usually
around 2.5 percent to 2.8 percent of the balance, to use plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and how are federal refunds running this year? At last
check, they were averaging $1,575.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
