<HEADLINE>
BUT WHAT ABOUT TAX CUTS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the tax-filing season winds down, it's hard to resist the
notion that the tax-and-spend crowd has finally prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain the lack of grousing about taxes? There may
be scattered pockets of protest, but the quest to reduce Big
Government's oxygen supply has lost its sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   It's not an election year, of course, but this doesn't
adequately explain the demise of tax reduction and tax reform as
burning issues. One theory making the rounds is that good times are
making it harder for relief and reform advocates to connect with
taxpayers. People might say they're for tax relief when asked, but
translating that into political oomph is easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that the affluent's share of the tax load has
risen substantially in the '90s, which shrinks the potential for
grass-roots revolt. Another problem is public misperceptions of
federal finance and what's best for the economy.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by a Republican organization, for instance,
showed two-thirds of the respondents favoring a 10 percent
across-the-board cut in marginal tax rates. When those polled were
asked how budget surpluses should be used, though, 31 percent
wanted excess revenue devoted to helping Social Security and 26
percent wanted to pay down the debt. Only 18 percent opted for tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Social Security is overfunded to the extent that
it is the budget surplus. Never mind, too, that paying down the
debt won't improve individual economic fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   It's as simple as Big Government advocates having done a great
job of selling the idea that there's no economic downside to
government pre-empting an inordinate share of the resource pie.
Federal revenue is consuming more than one-fifth of economic
output, but few see this as a threat to sustaining what's already
the longest peacetime expansion ever.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope things turn out better this time than they did the
last two times prosperity cycled into decline. While government
benefits immensely from booms, it often realizes too late the
wisdom of practicing revenue restraint.
</P>
<P>
   The Roaring '20s, thanks to declining tax rates, was one of the
most prosperous eras in U.S. history. Then came the '30s. Tax
relief in the mid-1960s also helped make that decade one of the
best ever. Then the '70s saw inflation-induced bracket creep savage
after-tax income.
</P>
<P>
   Tax cuts are needed. So is reform to simplify the system.
Nothing, however, gets done without public clamor. What would
create enough public concern about the tax situation to ignite
public clamor?
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating withholding would do the job. Before the advent of
withholding in World War II, government didn't dare impose taxes
beyond the comfort zone of taxpayers accustomed to settling their
tax obligation to Uncle Sam once a year.
</P>
<P>
   Failing a government solution, companies could start paying full
wages in actual currency. Employees then would go down a line of
tables at which they would stop at each one and peel off enough
cash to settle federal, state, local and FICA obligations. Several
trips down such a line would no doubt create an appreciation for
what government demands from us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
