<HEADER>
A8173 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-FREE-PCS-2TAKES-N     04-14 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FREE-PCS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Attn: La., Calif., Va., N.J.)  
 WARY CONSUMERS TRY `FREE' PCs  
(Eds: A list of companies offering `free' computers is at end of
article.) 
(af) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Barbara D. Fontenot, last Friday was the big day. She
practically hugged the United Parcel Service man who lugged the big
box up the stairs to her sparsely appointed second-floor apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fontenot, 58, a sixth-grade teacher in Alexandria, La.,
plopped down on her hardwood living room floor and carefully
unpacked her first computer. It was something she could not have
afforded until a man named Joseph Calimari came along: rather than
paying for her computer outright, she pays $29.99 a month in a
rent-to-own plan offered by Calimari's startup company,
Intersquid.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one happy child when the UPS man showed up,'' Ms.
Fontenot said. She is participating in a new way of buying and
selling computers that has computer industry analysts intrigued and
wary. They say the new means of distributing PCs is poised to gain
wide appeal, but its eventual success is less certain.
</P>
<P>
   The computers are being offered to consumers much the way
cellular phones are provided by the companies that provide phone
service. Computer companies offer to give a ``free PC'' to
consumers, then charge them for monthly Internet access fees.
</P>
<P>
   The fees start at $20 a month _ depending on how powerful the
computer is _ a price that is not much higher than you might expect
to pay for Internet access alone.
</P>
<P>
   There's a catch, of course. In some cases, users must sign up
for a two- to three-year contract, locking them into a long-term
deal in a world full of unknowns and committing them to companies
that may be as new to the computer business as many of their
customers are to computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty good deal for consumers and pretty compelling
for first-time buyers,'' said David J. Stremba, principal analyst
for Dataquest, a San Jose, Calif., market research company. ``But
they just need to be aware of what they are making a commitment
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the questions Stremba recommends that consumers ask: Who
is operating the company? Will it survive to live up to its
commitments, like long-term technical support and Internet access?
Are the computers reliable? What, if any, upgrades can a buyer
expect?
</P>
<P>
   Stremba said that some consumers might sign up for three years
of Internet access, for example, provided over phone lines _
so-called dial-up access. But, he said, cable access, which is must
faster than dial-up access, may be widely available, before long.
``Three years is a long time to get locked into something,'' he
said. ``In three years, standard dial-up access is going to look as
appealing as a moldy sandwich.''
</P>
<P>
   Stremba also said these companies simply could not afford to
sell computers and Internet access for $20 a month. He recently
completed a study of the industry and concluded that 95 percent to
99 percent of the businesses offering that kind of deal ``won't
survive past six months to a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Calimari, 30, who founded his company four months ago and
started shipping computers two weeks ago, disagreed. ``We don't
lose money now,'' he said. ``We're offering this at a point where
we're just making a profit.'' But he conceded that the profit
margins were slim and that he was not sure how his competitors
could make money if they offered better deals. ``I don't know how
they're doing it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that the driving force behind the business
model _ and the reason the companies are getting involved _ is the
precipitously falling price of computers. It now is possible to buy
name-brand computers for less than $700, including a monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Putting a fine point on the story of falling prices, a San
Francisco company called Emachines suddenly propelled itself to
become the fourth-largest PC maker in the United States in the
month of February, according to PC Data, a market research company
in Reston, Va. The key to the company's success: it sells computers
for less than $600.
</P>
<P>
   As the trend toward cheaper computers became clear last year, a
light bulb went on in Calimari's head. ``I was at American Express
doing accounting,'' said Calimari, 30. ``I suddenly realized this
industry was going the way of the cellular phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, he wanted to name his company PC-for-Free but decided
it was similar to too many other companies' names. So he chose
something a little more offbeat _ Intersquid.com, based on his last
name, which means squid in Italian.
</P>
<P>
   For a $30 registration fee and $29.99 a month for 30 months,
plus shipping and handling, subscribers to Intersquid.com get
Internet access and a new computer.
</P>
<P>
   The computer includes a 333-megahertz Intel Celeron I processor
_ a stripped down Pentium _ 32 megabytes of memory, a 40x CD-ROM
drive, a 56-kilobits-per-second modem and a 15-inch monitor. It
also comes with 24-hour technical support and a limited warranty,
which Calimari said would cover problems with the computer not
caused by the user. After 30 months, users own the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Fledgling competitors are offering similar deals. In New York,
Ganesh Ramakrishnan, 26, a former anthropology and economics
student turned investment banker turned computer entrepreneur,
recently started Gobi Inc. For $25.99 a month for 36 months, plus a
one-time fee of $29.99 and shipping and handling, Gobi sells a
machine with a 300-megahertz Celeron processor, monitor and modem.
</P>
<P>
   Ramakrishnan said that the company plans to upgrade the computer
as technology changes but that he is still ironing out the details
of how the upgrades would take place and what technological
advances would qualify for upgrades. He said subscribers would be
able to purchase the computer at the end of their
three-year-contracts for about $50 each.
</P>
<P>
   In Mount Laurel, N.J., Dennis M. Cline and his colleagues have
begun Direct Web. The company plans to offer national service but
for now is taking orders only for the Philadelphia area for a
computer and Internet access ranging from $19.95 to $49.95
depending on the model of the computer.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Direct Web, the contract is month to month, not
long term. But there is still a catch: when subscribers log onto a
Direct Web computer, they will go immediately to a home portal page
sponsored by Direct Web. The page will feature advertisers who will
be allowed to store information like audio and video commercial
clips on the computer's hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cline said he had become convinced after spending months
conducting focus groups that consumers would buy into the
rent-to-own concept. He said consumers were looking for simplified
solutions when buying computers _ like bundling computers with
Internet access and tech support _ and that they hate the fact that
when they ought a computer, it would not be on the cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   In focus groups, he said, users said they felt stupid when
trying to buy a computer. ``Once I buy it and install it, I find
out it's obsolete,'' Cline said, parroting a focus group member.
``I went through all the gyrations to buy this, then my
brother-in-law shows up and says, `Why'd you get the old one?'''
</P>
<P>
   The early interest in his company and in his competitors seems
to bear Cline out. Since his company opened the phone lines for
orders two weeks ago, he said, it has received 1,000 orders or more
each day. Similarly, the owners of Gobi and Intersquid said the
phones have been ringing constantly at their companies.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Ms. Fontenot illustrates some of the appeal and
potential pitfalls of the experience. A public school teacher since
1962, Ms. Fontenot said her $30,000 salary did not permit luxuries
like computers. So several months ago, she started surfing the Net
in the school library looking for ``free PCs.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, she found a company called Free PC, which attracted a
lot of attention with its offer to give away 10,000 computers. In
exchange for the computers, users agreed to put up with a constant
stream of advertising and provide personal information to be used
by advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fontenot said she had filled out ``20 or 30'' applications
on the Web for a computer and had never received any responses.
</P>
<P>
   Then she found Intersquid.com. She said she had been skeptical
at first but finally decided to call the company, where she had
conversations on four days with a man named Joe, who she later
found out happened to be the company president. He told her about
the computer and the Internet access. She started to feel
reassured.
</P>
<P>
   She had to overcome her fear about giving her credit card number
to someone she had never met, ``finally, I just jumped,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her concern resurfaced several days later when the computer
failed to show up. She called Intersquid and found out that
shipping had been delayed by the Easter holiday. Several days
later, Calimari called again: he had sent the package but had
forgotten to include the CD-ROM necessary to hook the computer to
the Net.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Ms. Fontenot realized that there was a question
she had not yet asked. ``I said, `I've never asked you this, but
how old is your company?''' she recalled. ``He told me four
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Intersquid is not alone in experiencing growing pains. Gobi
Inc., for example, began getting national press coverage last week,
causing dozens of prospective clients to try to get in contact with
the company.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, the company had not yet set up an ordering line
and had had even had an internal debate about whether it should set
one up at all. Franklin Raff, a spokesman for Gobi, said the
company was worried about whether it could afford an 800 number
because ``its margins are so tight.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Ms. Fontenot maintains her faith through it all.
She said she has set up her new computer and was waiting for her
CD-ROM. And she said she admired the Calimaris of the world, whose
entrepreneurial spirit has enabled her to own a computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an old schoolteacher taking a risk _ a big one,'' Ms.
Fontenot said. ``I'm trusting a lot of people here. I don't know
much about computers. You could sell me anything _ except the
Brooklyn Bridge.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Free' Computers, and What They Cost &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several companies are offering deals for so-called free
computers, in which the user pays a fee for Internet service. The
computers and the terms of payment vary. Here are three of the
deals currently offered. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INTERSQUID.COM: www.intersquid.com For a payment of $29.99 a
month for 30 months, Inter-squid offers a computer with a
333-megahertz Intel Celeron chip, 32 megabytes of RAM, 4.3-gigabyte
hard drive, floppy disk drive, 40X CD-ROM drive, 56K modem and
15-inch monitor. The machine has a three-year limited warranty with
7-day, 24-hour technical support. Phone: (877) 724-3733. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GOBI: www.gobi.com For $25.99 a month for 36 months, and a
one-time fee of $29.99 and shipping and handling, Gobi offers a
computer with a 300-MHz Celeron chip, 32 MB RAM, a 3.2-GB hard
drive, a floppy drive, a 56 K modem, a 40X CD-ROM drive and a
15-inch monitor. 800-YESGOBI. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DIRECT WEB: www.directweb.com The company offers three programs,
all on a month-to-month basis.
</P>
<P>
   Basic, at $19.95 a month, provides a 333-MHz computer with a
Celeron chip, 64 MB of RAM, a 6.4-GB hard drive, 32x CD-ROM drive,
a 56 K modem and a 15-inch monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The Select plan, at $29.95 a month, gives you a 366-MHz Celeron
chip computer, 128 MB of RAM, an 8.6-GB hard drive, 32x CD-ROM
drive, 17-inch monitor and 56 K modem.
</P>
<P>
   Premium, at $49.95 a month, includes a computer with a 450-MHz
Pentium III chip, 128 MB of RAM, a 10.2-GB hard drive, 6x DVD-ROM
drive, 17-inch monitor and 56 K modem. Phone: (888) 468-2746.
</P>
</TEXT>
