<HEADLINE>
HOW TO FIND HELP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas)  (With CIR-ORGANIZE) 
(af) 
 By JULIA LAWLOR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are planning to hire someone to help you organize your
electronic tools, be sure to specify what you want to accomplish
(i.e. clean up computer files, organize e-mail, switch from paper
to an electronic calendar).
</P>
<P>
   Word of mouth _ from co-workers or friends you trust _ is often
the best way to find help. Another way is to contact the National
Association of Professional Organizers, in Austin, Texas, which has
more than 1,000 members nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   NAPO (www.napo.net) has a referral service (512-206-0151) that
will give you names of organizers in your region. You may find
professional organizers listed in your Yellow Pages under
``organizing consultants.''
</P>
<P>
   Expect to pay fees ranging from $50 to as much $200 an hour,
depending on experience, region of the country and other factors.
Some have one rate for corporations and a lower rate for
individuals or nonprofit organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have a candidate, ask for references and check them.
Professional organizing is unregulated, although NAPO is developing
a certification program. Ask how long the candidate has been in
business, what types of clients he or she has worked with
(corporate? small business? solo practitioners?) and whether he or
she is familiar with a range of electronic tools and software
programs.
</P>
<P>
   If you use a particular product, such as Microsoft's Outlook,
and do not want to change, make sure the consultant is familiar
with this product.
</P>
<P>
   Look out for those who can't give you references. Beware if you
get a gut feeling the candidate is not listening to you, and
remember that a good coach is a good listener. Finally, be willing
to do your part. Being coached, says Ken Diebold, a professional
organizer, ``is not getting into the back seat and watching someone
else drive.'' You must be willing to accept advice, share
information and test new things.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
