u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SURFBOARDS-2TAKES     04-14 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SURFBOARDS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GUIDE TO SURFING (THE OCEAN, NOT THE NET) 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BRIGID BUCKMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The surfing heroes of ``The Endless Summer,'' a 1966 documentary
directed by Bruce Brown, circled the globe, long boards in hand, in
search of the perfect wave. But in location after location, they
were plagued by the dispiriting greeting of ``you should have been
here yesterday'' as they grimaced at the flat waves that faced
them.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, Brown and his surfers would be able to take a
more educated guess at which beach would be hopping with
well-shaped tubes (waves) by using a computer and a modem. Surfers,
from professionals to groms, or novices, can use the Web to find
tidal charts, weather reports, tropical storm maps, local surf
reports, pollution watches and buoy readings before they make the
trek to search for the perfect wave.
</P>
<P>
   A global community of surfers from places like England, Israel,
Italy, Australia, Southern California and even Brooklyn has tamed
not only the surfers' local breaks but the Web, too. The surfers
are making their information and experiences accessible to all who
have an interest in the surfing life.
</P>
<P>
   Mikke Pierson, the owner of Z J Boarding House, a sporting gear
store in Santa Monica, Calif., said he looked at the Internet every
morning to find out about storm activity that might affect
California surf conditions as well as swell information for his
area. ``You can really tell where you should go surf,'' he said.
Pierson shares the information he finds with his patrons through a
telephone surf report his store provides. Apart from predicting
great waves, the Internet helps link surfers worldwide, Pierson
said. ``Totally _ that's what it's all about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though many of the Web's surf sites are bogged down with
superficial information and advertisements, or consist solely of
action photos of surfers looking for a little glory, a number of
sites offer quick-loading practical information, like the
conditions at local beaches and the nearest surf shop for having a
fin replaced. For the many armchair surfers, other sites act as
cultural tutorials through the often romanticized subculture of
surfing that, more than just being a sport, has become synonymous
with a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   An endless summer, like the one Brown chronicled more than 30
years ago, may be elusive today to the average surfer (especially
the average surfer with a job), but through the Web, the waves of
famous spots like the south shore of Australia or Hawaii's Pipeline
become a little more tangible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CITY SURFER: NYC
</P>
<P>
   www.users.interport.net/barney
</P>
<P>
   Created and maintained by Rob Cummings, a surfer living in
Brooklyn who is nicknamed Barney, City Surfer: NYC is a jumping-off
point for any New York City dweller with aspirations of trading in
concrete for a day on the swells of the nearby Atlantic Ocean or
Long Island Sound. Cummings plans to expand this site within the
next few months. He also intends to introduce advertisements and a
stronger emphasis on travel.
</P>
<P>
   The site includes things like the complete 1999 tide tables for
the Fire Island Inlet and journal entries that chronicle the
creator's surfing adventures (including advice on how to carry a
surfboard on a crowded subway car without making enemies). The
site's main attraction is a network of links that gives the visitor
quick access to specific surfing information for the tristate area.
Links to local weather reports, Atlantic wave models and nearby
surf video cameras are organized in groupings that are easy to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   If a trip to Montauk, N.Y., or to the Jersey Shore is out of the
question, a subway token can get anyone in New York City to
Rockaway Beach in Queens and, with luck, a nice set of waves. Nor
is summer the only season for New York surfing. Monster waves
created by autumn hurricanes and winter storms are favorites of
many hard-core Manhattan surfers, as was evident during last year's
Hurricane Bonnie. Dozens of surfers, exhilarated by the brawny
waves, ignored the closing of Rockaway Beach and took to the water.
</P>
<P>
   Cummings' site also features a travel section that offers
information and advice through excerpts from e-mail messages. The
firsthand accounts are colorful _ sometimes even profane _ and
laden with facts about surf conditions and hot spots around the
globe, along with grass-roots nuggets that may be otherwise hard to
find in travel guides. How many travel books, for instance, could
identify surfing beaches in County Mayo in Ireland that not only
have pubs within walking distance but have, the source says, pubs
that ``pull an excellent pint?''
</P>
<P>
   Another message warns of a 14-foot reptile that has laid claim
to a river mouth in Costa Rica. Despite the report of a man-eater,
this surfing spot is not to be missed, the writer says.
</P>
<P>
   The Enviro, Weather, Buoys and Surf Culture pages have numerous
links on each page. Succinct descriptions of the focus and
usefulness of each link (the Surfbook site is described as
``containing all you need to know from hanging 10 to shaping
blanks'') allow the site visitor to decide quickly about which way
to click. Also included is a Tips page, which appears to be a
seemingly endless block of text. The page has e-mail, most of it
didactic, from various people. Use the page index to avoid getting
stuck in this mire of information.
</P>
<P>
   As with a lot of writing about surfing, the Travel, Tips and
Journal pages are dominated by the surfers' lingua franca: ``kook
flails for the shoulder, pearls right in front of me, loses his
board, which cuts a four-inch gash in my rail.'' You can do your
own rough translation (an unskilled surfer falls off his board,
which then becomes a menace to other surfers) by using the
surfer-speak dictionary of the Surf Culture Orange County Web site
(reviewed below).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   SURFLINE
</P>
<P>
   www.surfline.com
</P>
<P>
   For surfers who don't live close to the ocean, every free day
poses a problem: where to surf? An uninformed decision may lead to
a day spent among Lilliputian waves, while a nearby beach has
lovely tubes just waiting to be tamed.
</P>
<P>
   One solution is to check Surfline before setting out. Scouts
employed by this site report conditions at their local beaches at
sunrise each day. An easy-to-read map of the United States lists
reports from more than 40 coastal locations, from the cold waters
of Hampton Beach, N.H., down the East Coast and across the southern
coast of Texas, then up the West Coast to Ocean Beach in Northern
California, with a detour to Hawaii. Popular Costa Rican and
Australian beaches are surveyed daily as well.
</P>
<P>
   The local surf reports include water temperatures, wind
conditions, high and low tides, and descriptions of the wave
quality. ``Poor shape and ridability'' or a ``fading south ground
swell with fair shape'' can make the difference between staying
home or pulling out the wet suit.
</P>
<P>
   Once a visitor chooses a specific surf report location, links
appear for local satellite images, buoy readings, marine forecasts,
tropical storm tracking, tide and current reports, and in some
locations, swell models. Though the surf report should provide
enough to help you decide whether to tie your surfboard to the top
of a car and sit in beach traffic, the additional information can
aid serious surfers in setting up a schedule for several days.
Local surf shop information is also accessible for each location in
case you forget your wax or, worse yet, waterproof sunblock.
</P>
<P>
   If calculating the buoy readings' relationship to an upcoming
swell seems too academic, this site also offers what a budding
Kelly Slater or Lisa Andersen (two recent world champions) could no
doubt use: surf alerts via e-mail. The Web site's surf forecasting
team offers free notification by e-mail whenever the surfing
conditions in the member's area become noteworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Surfline also has cameras set up at a handful of locations,
mainly on the California coast and at famous breaks like Hawaii's
Pipeline, to offer live streaming video feeds. Though the quality
of the video is crude, the load time is quick and provides a rough
look at what you are (or aren't) missing.
</P>
<P>
   Though this site is efficient for getting information about
conditions quickly, the surf reports are subject to the whims of
the surf scouts. Texans take note: there hasn't been a update from
Galveston since May 22, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   SURF CULTURE ORANGE COUNTY
</P>
<P>
   www.inorangecounty.com/orangemedia/sites/surfculture
</P>
<P>
   For armchair and devout surfers alike, this site is full of
information about the culture of surfing, showing how the legendary
surfers of the 20th century turned surfing into a professionally
competitive sport that draws crowds worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The material for the site is from the International Surfing
Museum in Huntington Beach, Calif., one of the nation's most
popular surfing towns. The rich atmosphere of nostalgia is created
through the use of archival photos and the ``Beach Blanket Bingo''
style of kitsch in the design.
</P>
<P>
   A Kings of the Wave page links the listed honorees with quick
biographies and photos of their glory days. The list includes Tom
Curren, Linda Benson, Rell Sunn and Duke Kahanamoku, the Hawaiian
Olympian whom many credit with the rise of modern surfing. But do
not expect vast insight into your favorite surfing legend: the
biographies really just provide lists of career highlights.
</P>
<P>
   The site has a landmarks and culture section that offers an
overview of the relationship between surfing and cars, a
relationship that has apparently weakened since the days of the
Volkswagen bus and the woodie station wagon, as well as a page on
surfing tunes that is helpful to those of us who need reminding
that Dick Dale and the Del-Tones were around before Pulp Fiction.
</P>
<P>
   There are also some odd pieces of surf lore, like the story of
the 15-foot-long, 100-pound redwood surfboard that Tom Blake built
for himself in California as a ``lightweight'' board after being
inspired by a trip to Hawaii in 1922. But while this site delivers
a clear historical perspective and an entertaining, easily
navigated layout, it leaves a visitor wanting more background
information, especially on the sport's pop-cultural role in
history. The Magic Surf Bus
(www.surfbus.freeserve.co.uk/index.htm), an elaborate surfing
museum full of offbeat information, is a nice detour for visitors
looking to pick up where the Orange County site leaves off.
</P>
<P>
   To help readers understand surfing culture better, the site
offers a surf language dictionary. Comical as well as practical,
the dictionary supplies definitions for terms like kook (an
unskilled surfer), green room (the space inside the curve of the
wave) and bone crusher (a big wave that breaks with extreme force).
</P>
<P>
   SURFERMAG.COM
</P>
<P>
   www.surfermag.com
</P>
<P>
   In the translation from page to screen, the online version of
Surfer magazine, one of the sport's best-read publications, gains
in inventiveness what it loses in photo quality. The site's images
pale with their lack of clarity and often grainy appearance. But
the Vintage Surfer section earns those lost points back with a
22-page unedited interview with the legendary surfer Duke
Kahanamoku from the mid-1960s (in its original type), as well as
excerpts from the first edition of Surfer, published in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   News of the latest professional competitions, like the Rip Curl
Pro, and the Surf Rider Foundation's link (www.surfrider.com) along
with breaking environmental news give this site more currency than
you would find in its stale paper-based version. The features
available, however, are a chop-shop version of the magazine. An
interview with the current world champion, Kelly Slater, and an
article on the Men Who Ride Mountains competition at Mavericks, in
Northern California, are among the most recent features posted.
Older issues of the magazine are also on line, but only a handful
of articles from each issue are available to the visitor at no
charge. Full back issues can be purchased.
</P>
<P>
   An informal bulletin board page is a spiraling source of
interactive advice _ the topics posted vary from surfing in France
to coping with crushes on the professional surfer Shane Dorian. A
search engine allows participants to save time by typing in a
keyword to pull up the relevant postings.
</P>
<P>
   On the site's interactive Ask the Surf Doc section, a doctor
handles questions regarding surfing-related medical hazards, like
one visitor's worrisome ``weird tan thing'' and another's ``funky
numb toes.'' A pragmatic brevity marks the surfing doctor's bedside
manner. When asked, ``Is there such a thing as shark repellent?''
he replied, ``If you're afraid of sharks, then don't surf.''
</P>
<P>
   MINING COMPANY SURFING HOME PAGE
</P>
<P>
   surfing.miningco.com
</P>
<P>
   The Mining Company provides a virtual library on surfing and
surfing-related sites, catalogued by Thomas James Rezeski. The
sheer volume of sites, however, is both a help and a hindrance. The
site is best visited with a specific topic in mind _ or if you have
enough spare time to browse the labyrinth of information.
</P>
<P>
   Rezeski sorts the sites he has chosen into more than 30
categories, like tandem surfing, surfing camps and schools, surfing
museums, windsurfing and surfing events. Once a specific category
is clicked, a list of all pertinent links appears. Each link is
accompanied by a brief description of its contents, which often
contain ``fabulous'' or ``must visit'' directives from the
enthusiastic Rezeski that tend to blur the line between the average
and the exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   A number of essays and stories are accessible without having to
go to other Web sites. Tips on how to prolong the life of your
surfboard and a quick history of the evolution of the surfboard are
among the essays Reznick provides.
</P>
<P>
   Boxed in by advertisements and links to the rest of the Mining
Company site that have nothing to do with the surfing page, the
page has a claustrophobic look. Once you are within the catalogued
links, however, an easy-to-read layout is available for a
well-mapped ride through the multitude of sites the surfing world
offers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
