<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8183 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS15-COX     04-14 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini CD reviews
 &HT;    By Eileen Drennen, Sonia Murray and Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Dusty in Memphis''
</P>
<P>
   (Deluxe edition)
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Springfield. Rhino. 25 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Though Dusty Springfield was honored with long-overdue awards
weeks before her March 2 death, none is as fitting an epitaph as
this seminal 1969 album. Made the old-fashioned way (live in the
studio) with Aretha Franklin's producers and the rhythm section
behind Elvis Presley and Wilson Pickett, the session gave her
R&AMP;B-based pop the soulful grounding it needed. Her husky voice
never sounded better, from the sweet strains of ``Just a Little
Lovin' '' and ``Breakfast in Bed'' to the darker notes of ``No Easy
Way Down'' and ``I Can't Make It Alone.'' Though the sweetly
lustful ``Son of a Preacher Man'' was the album's only Top 10 chart
hit, this Memphis collection (including 14 bonus tracks) is the
very best of the former Mary O'Brien, who would have been 60
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eileen M. Drennen
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Thug Mentality 1999''
</P>
<P>
   Krayzie Bone. Mo Thugs/Relativity.
</P>
<P>
   32 tracks. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Bone Thugs-N-Harmony has distinguished itself as the closest
thing hip-hop has to an R&AMP;B act. But it wasn't until the release of
Krayzie Bone's solo debut that we learned who clearly fashions the
Cleveland group's unique sing-song sound. Barely distinguishable
from Bone Thugs-N-Harmony's million-selling collective efforts _
and thankfully more cohesive than its other solo ventures _
Krayzie's offering makes street level topics such as selling drugs
(``Dummy Man'') and exacting bloody revenge (``Payback Iz a
Bitch'') soar where pop stars such as Mariah Carey (who appears on
this record) shimmer. And he does it by simply applying what works
in divadom: polished production, memorable choruses and even better
storytelling. Put those elements together and before you know it,
Krayzie's made melodies out of mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Foliage Volume One''
</P>
<P>
   Olivia Tremor Control. Flydaddy.
</P>
<P>
   27 tracks. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Listening to the new CD by Athens' (Ga.) Olivia Tremor Control
is much like an hourlong tour through the experimental outer limits
of rock. There are bits of the Beatles, the Beach Boys (in Brian
Wilson's late-'60s, sandbox-in-the-living room phase), German
boundary-pushers Can and Neu! and the tuneful art damage of Wire,
to name a few. ``The Sylvan Screen'' is a shining example of OTC's
method: two minutes of tape manipulation, then a beautiful and
startlingly Beatlesque tune, more tape weirdness and a wordless a
cappella outre that wouldn't sound out of place on a late-'60s
Beach Boys track. It's an imaginative concoction.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8184 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-PETTY15-COX     04-14 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-PETTY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Echo' sounds like Petty at his best
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Echo'' is vintage Heartbreakers _ Tom Petty's swamp cat yowl
backed by the pit crew precision of Benmont Tench's growling organ,
Howie Epstein's relentless bass line and Mike Campbell's lead
guitar. The 15 tunes here take us through all the tempos and
tactics we expect from this band, from driving rock anthems, to the
electric folk of Dylan and (of course) Byrds-influenced country
rock.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike contemporary offerings from other aging rockers, this
is no exercise in nostalgia. Petty and the gang sound as fresh as
when they shouted out ``Breakdown'' nearly 20 years ago, and one
wonders how they do it. It may be because the new songs sound
genuinely inspired, from the world-weary lyrics to the band's
seasoned playing style. Tench and Campbell know how to weave their
instruments around Petty like vines up an old oak tree, whether
it's pulling back with a simple acoustic piano or blowing it out
with an Eldorado roar on Hammond organ and soaring guitar.
</P>
<P>
   What keeps this out of ``Behind the Music'' territory, however,
are the experienced lyrics. Petty has always loved to sing about
women (``American Girl,'' ``Free Fallin'''), but his subject in
``Free Fallin''' is no longer a teenager living with her mama in
Reseda; she's a ``Free Girl Now,'' driving and smoking her way
across the landscape of middle age. On ``Lonesome Sundown,'' Petty
cries ``This is gonna be hard/Redemption comes to those who
wait/forgive-
</P>
<P>
   ness is the key,'' but it's about leaving a daughter, not a
lover.
</P>
<P>
   Petty and the Heartbreakers have not only become well-oiled in
their playing, but in their perspectives as well, learning through
their personal mistakes, misplaced choices and the inevitable
regrets that follow. In a sweet acoustic moment on a tune called
``This One's for Me,'' Petty reflects, ``You don't even know what
you got 'til you see it walking away.'' It's an experience his now
40-something fans will connect with immediately, which, after all,
is the secret to making music that remains vital and alive.
</P>
<P>
   ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Echo''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Petty &AMP; the Heartbreakers. Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
