A8185 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-APTPUPIL15-COX     04-14 0145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-APTPUPIL15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Opening the door to WWII-era evil
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Apt Pupil'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   Director Bryan Singer's follow-up to ``The Usual Suspects'' is
the morally creepy tale of a fresh-faced teenage boy (Brad Renfro)
who wants to grow up to be a Nazi. His dreams come true when he
figures out a man in his neighborhood (Ian McKellen) is really an
infamous war criminal, a German escapee masquerading as a seemingly
benign old chap. Though smoothly adapted from a Stephen King
novella, and commandingly acted by McKellen, the film sticks a foot
in the door of its subject, but can only seem trivial in comparison
to the true evil it tries to evoke. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
