<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      04-14 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: (AT) in the e-mail address in the last graph should be
replaced by the typographical symbol.) 
(jt) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blueberries in Shade
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to know if I can plant blueberries in a raised
bed in my garden on Long Island. The spot I have in mind is in the
shade of a mature oak tree, about 12 feet from the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   A: There are three common kinds of blueberry: the ``wild'' ones,
Vaccinium angustifolia, low-growing spreaders that are pretty, but
not suitable for home fruit production; rabbiteye blueberries, V.
ashei, which do best in the South, and highbush blueberries, V.
corymbosum. These last would be an excellent choice for a Long
Island garden, particularly one with the acidic soil for which the
area is famous. But it would be best if you could think up a
brighter spot for them. Though blueberries are often described as
able to tolerate some shade, there's likely to be more than
``some'' only 12 feet from a mature oak.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine problems aside, the location you have in mind won't be
ideal unless that raised bed is really king-size. Most of the
reliable, readily available highbush cultivars, including Blueray,
Patriot and Bluecrop, can eventually become shrubs 6 feet tall and
almost as wide, and you'll need at least two of them _ even
varieties advertised as ``self-fertile'' do much better with a
pollinator nearby. While there are some handsome dwarf types that
would fit nicely in a raised bed (Northblue, for instance, is about
two feet tall), they are not what you'd call fruit factories.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that won't matter if you're growing blueberries as
ornamentals. Their pretty spring flowers and bright yellow, orange
or red autumn foliage are reason enough to grow them even without
fruit _ which is what be unless you protect your crop from the
birds. It's a good idea to build an arbor around the bushes when
you first plant. This structure will add visual interest while the
shrubs are still small. Then, when it's time to foil the flying
freeloaders, you'll have a ready-made frame to hang the
bird-netting from.
</P>
<P>
   Catalogs offer a good selection of early, midseason and
late-ripening fruits, so you can have blueberries for almost two
months. You can also end up with bloom times too widespread for
cross-pollination, so if the catalog doesn't say when they flower,
don't forget to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Patriot, Blue Ray, and V. angustifolium are among the choices
available from Bear Creek Nursery, P.O. Box 411, Northport, Wash.
99157; (509) 732-6219. Patriot, Bluecrop and Northblue are sold by
Henry Fields Seed and Nursery Company, 415 North Burnett,
Shenandoah, Iowa 51602; (605) 665-9391. Catalogs from both are
free.
</P>
<P>
   Building Up a Bed
</P>
<P>
   Q: I plan to build up a perennial bed with an extra two to three
inches of soil and compost. Is it necessary to dig up and replant
the flowers and bulbs that are already there, or will they adapt to
being buried deeper?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are a few perennials that are fussy about being buried.
Peonies, for instance, will fail to bloom if the buds that will
form shoots are more than about two inches underground. And the
lumpy rhizomes of bearded iris are prone to rot if their tops don't
get light and air. Most bulbs, on the other hand, won't care a bit.
In fact, experts often suggest burying bulbs, especially tulips,
more deeply than normal to encourage them to come back in future
years.
</P>
<P>
   Special exceptions aside, the rest will depend on how much of
your mixture is compost and how much is soil. Compost is lighter
and fluffier than soil, and much less likely to smother plants.
Over the course of the season, compost will continue to break down,
blending into the old soil, adding nutrients, improving structure
and encouraging beneficial organisms. A three-inch layer of compost
is definitely good, but by fall the bed won't be any taller than it
was before.
</P>
<P>
   There are different kinds of soil, all of them heavier than
compost. If your plants are already up, it would probably be wise
to lift them _ or wait till next year to build up the bed _ rather
than heaping three inches of dirt on their tender little heads. But
if your established perennials have not yet shown above ground,
they should have no trouble pushing new growth up two or three
inches farther to reach the light.
</P>
<P>
   Skunks in the Suburbs
</P>
<P>
   Q: I live in a lovely suburb 15 minutes outside Boston, and we
have a large skunk community. How can I keep them out of my yard?
Is there some kind of plant or shrub or other organic matter they
will avoid? It wouldn't be a problem except that my dog cannot stay
away from them. Is there a way to get rid of them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Getting rid of them is not to be. Skunks have adapted very
well to the suburbs, where there are lots of good things to eat _
lawn grubs, earthworms, mice and rats _ and plenty of sheltered
places to build dens. When you remove a skunk from such habitat,
all you do is open territory for the next one.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to keep them out of your yard is with a low, tight
wire mesh fence. Skunks don't do much climbing, so two feet tall
should be adequate. They do dig, though, which means you'll want to
bury the fencing six to eight inches deep. Nothing repels them, but
they are easily attracted, especially by grub-infested lawns and
anything fishy, meaty or sweet. (They love moldy cake and stale
cookies almost as much as raccoons do.)
</P>
<P>
   Some authorities suggest drenching the lawn with pesticides to
get rid of the grubs, but even doing that is unlikely to solve the
skunk problem completely. It's important to keep the garbage
covered, and to be aware that such organic fertilizers as blood
meal and bone meal are powerful lures. Keep unused supplies in
tightly lidded containers, and be sure to work the fertilizers well
into the soil as soon as you use them.
</P>
<P>
   Since as you note, the problem is not so much with the skunks as
with your dog, the easiest solution is probably to control the
pooch rather than the polecats.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd
St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
