<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New on DVD
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Fish Called Wanda'' (R) _ A larcenous lark meant to be
swallowed hook, line and sinker, it's a head-spinning farce in
which John Cleese, Jamie Lee Curtis, Kevin Kline and Michael Palin
prove there's no honor among thieves by double- and triple-crossing
each other after a jewel heist (Kline won a supporting actor Oscar
for his efforts). The DVD edition is skimpy on special features,
but there is a booklet of production notes that reveals some
intriguing behind-the-scenes tidbits, some fishier than others. For
instance, Cleese recalls they had several fish they were
considering for more prominent roles. ``One morning we walked to
the tank and realized this particular fish had eaten 32 extras. She
must have wanted the part very badly to have disposed of the
competition in that way.'' Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Antz'' (PG) _ Animation freaks will be especially pleased.
When it was released in theaters last fall, more attention was paid
to the all-star cast of voices (led by Woody Allen and Sharon
Stone) than to the nitty-gritty of the animation process. Not so
here. Among the special features is an audio commentary by
directors Tim Johnson and Eric Darnell, a short feature on the
production and looks at everything from the basics of computer
animation to the character design for the movie. Plus, there's the
always-tempting ``never before seen footage.'' Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
