<HEADER>
A8190 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-RINGEL15-COX     04-14 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Humans outdo high-tech schemes in screen intrigue
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Movies such as ``The Matrix'' or David Cronenberg's upcoming
paranoid gamesmanship ``eXistenZ'' remind us how relative reality
really is. But both these pictures' manipulations are byproducts of
technology _ in the former, alien machinations mask the real world
from its inhabitants, while in the latter, an ultra-sophisticated
virtual reality game asks its players to willingly enter an
alternate world.
</P>
<P>
   Yet once upon a time, we didn't need high-tech intrusions on our
lives. Perceptions could be skewed by mere human beings with a good
scheme. Or, even better, a good scam.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some intriguing titles with a few tricks up their
sleeves. And the only gadget they need is the human mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sleuth'' (1972)
</P>
<P>
   Joseph L. Mankiewicz's film adaptation of Anthony Shaffer's hit
play pairs Laurence Olivier and Michael Caine in some very canny
cat-and-mouse games on the grounds of one of England's statelier
mansions. Olivier is a hugely successful mystery writer who's
hugely upset that his wife is having an affair with _ ouch _ her
lower-class hairdresser (Caine). Olivier invites Caine over to sort
things out. Or set things up?
</P>
<P>
   Impress your film buff friends: When it came to his work, the
great Olivier was as human as the rest of us. Caine recalls that he
came on set one day in a desperate state and holding a small
mustache. He told Mankiewicz that last night, he'd suddenly
realized what he was doing wrong. Producing the sliver of hair, he
almost cried, ``I can't act with my own face! I always need some
sort of disguise.'' The mustache apparently solved the problem.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``House of Games'' (1987)
</P>
<P>
   David Mamet made his debut as a bona fide double threat (writer
and director) with this devilishly clever comedy-melodrama. His
then-wife, Lindsay Crouse, plays a chilly, repressed analyst who
wouldn't know real life if it hit her in the face. Which is more or
less what happens when she falls in with some con men and falls for
their leader (Joe Mantegna) hook, line and sucker. Done as a sort
of Pinter-esque noir, the movie has a highly stylized look and a
seductive theatrical flair.
</P>
<P>
   Impress your film buff friends: Crouse later told an interviewer
she was so successful in the part that, for a while, ``I kept
getting cast as Nazi surgeons.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Sting'' (1973)
</P>
<P>
   Having guided Paul Newman and Robert Redford through ``Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid,'' director George Roy Hill decided to
see if the magic still worked if he switched their cowboy gear for
'30s gangster garb. Thus, ``The Sting,'' in which the erstwhile
outlaws are transformed into raffish con men who orchestrate a very
complicated betting scam to fleece a big-time racketeer (Robert
Shaw.)
</P>
<P>
   Impress your film buff friends: Talk about a sting. . . . Hill's
lightweight entertainment made off with seven Oscars, including
best picture. Among the heavyweight also-rans: fellow nominees
``Cries and Whispers'' and ``The Exorcist'' and non-nominees ``Mean
Streets,'' ``Serpico,'' ``The Last Detail,'' ``Paper Moon,'' ``The
Long Goodbye,'' ``The Way We Were'' and ``Last Tango in Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dirty Rotten Scoundrels'' (1988)
</P>
<P>
   Steve Martin and Michael Caine are rival con artists trying to
work the same Riviera turf. Caine is the resort's resident prince
of thieves who bilks rich women by posing as deposed royalty;
Martin is a two-bit hustler who's cramping his style. To settle who
rules, a bet is proposed: The first to extract a certain sum from
an innocent abroad (Glenne Headly), rumored to be a soap heiress,
wins; the loser leaves town.
</P>
<P>
   Impress your film buff friends: The movie is a loose remake of a
1964 flop called ``Bedtime Story,'' which starred Marlon Brando and
David Niven. And if your buff already knows that, stump him/
</P>
<P>
   her with this bit of trivia: Caine had been asked to read the
script a few years earlier, only then it was called ``The King of
the Mountain'' and his co-star would've been an up-and-comer named
Tom Cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
