<HEADER>
A8194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DESIGN-PRIZE-NYT &LR;      04-14 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGN-PRIZE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SUBVERSIVE ZIPPER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KARRIE JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In February, I spent a few days in the Netherlands with Peter
Noever, the director of the Austrian Museum of Applied Arts in
Vienna, and Sarah Lerfel, the owner of Colette, a shop in Paris
that mixes design, fashion and art, when we were all judging the
entries for the Rotterdam Design Prize. Our mission was to select
one winner from 47 examples of Dutch graphic, industrial and
architectural design.
</P>
<P>
   After much debate, we awarded nearly $20,000 in prize money to
Heat Transfer Station 8, a mysterious black building with soft
polyurethane-coated walls that sits in a farmer's field outside
Utrecht. Someday it will supply hot water to the future city of
Leidsche Rijn. For now, it is an enigma, like the black monolith in
``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' except friendlier: It has a basketball
hoop on the front, a climbing wall on one side, and swallows nests
along the roof line.
</P>
<P>
   We nearly gave the prize to a highway underpass connecting the
old city of Leidschendam with a new city, now under construction,
called Leidschenveen. Designed by Zwarts &AMP; Jansma, an architecture
firm from the town of Abcoude (outside Amsterdam), and Hans Muller,
an Amsterdam artist, the tunnel is supposed to provide an inviting
link between old and new towns, a place where pedestrians and
bicyclists can feel safe and comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   One wall of the tunnel is dotted with green light-emitting
diodes that display constantly changing abstract patterns. The
tunnel's centerpiece is what New Yorkers would call a zipper, an
electronic message board like the one that wraps around 1 Times
Square. The designers call it a ``light journal'' or
``lichtkrant.'' Instead of displaying news or advertising, it shows
messages that anybody can type in from a special Web page. The
tunnel's Web address (www.Leidschenveen.nl/tunnel) appears on an
otherwise conventional Dutch street sign by the tunnel entrance.
</P>
<P>
   While I was delighted by the twinkling green diodes, I was
unmoved by the lichtkrant. After all, the Joe Boxer billboard in
Times Square has been running e-mailed messages _ ``Brandi Adams
loves Ross Peters!'' _ since 1995. And zippers, in general, are too
commonplace to be exciting.
</P>
<P>
   By my count, there are at least eight working zippers in the
Times Square area, ranging from the magnificent triple-decker
display of financial data racing around the Morgan Stanley
headquarters to more modest devices that run texts promoting the
cable company RCN or the play ``Beauty and the Beast.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Times Square, Fox News Channel's building at Avenue of
the Americas and 48th Street sports what is supposedly the world's
third-longest zipper. It's also the only one in the city with a
serif typeface: Times New Roman.
</P>
<P>
   Or it was. There's now a miniature version of the Fox zipper in
a newsstand in Grand Central Terminal. ``We took over the Hudson
News stand as a marketing thing,'' Roger Ailes, the chairman of Fox
News, said. The zipper runs in a circle, like an electronic crown
molding, above the heads of the cashiers.
</P>
<P>
   As a jaded New Yorker, I just couldn't get worked up about yet
another zipper. After all, most zippers, despite a look that
screams ``Information Age,'' dispense nothing but blather.
</P>
<P>
   What I'd failed to realize during the Rotterdam judging is that
the lichtkrant is, in fact, unique: It's a free-speech zipper.
While the e-mail messages displayed on the Joe Boxer billboard have
been carefully screened and selected, in Leidschendam, messages
flow unimpeded from Web site to tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, said Rein Jansma, a partner in the firm that designed
the underpass, was to circumvent the problem of graffiti by
offering an electronic substitute. ``Even if people write abusive
language,'' Jansma said, ``it will disappear all by itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Leidschendam's city fathers, Jansma said, are not happy about
the uninhibited stream of text, which, inevitably, includes
obscenities and dirty jokes. When the city officials proposed
hiring a censor, Jansma countered with a ``dynamic filter.'' If
people are really hurt by the text on the wall, Jansma suggested,
they can put offensive words on a blacklist for a week.
</P>
<P>
   City officials would prefer a fixed list of forbidden words. But
Muller, the artist who is under contract to maintain the Web site
and tunnel link, refuses to cooperate. ``They want to sue me,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the messages continue to flow, uncensored.
</P>
<P>
   Had I fully grasped the subversive nature of the Leidschendam
zipper, I might have voted differently when I sat on the Rotterdam
Design Prize jury. On the other hand, a heat transfer station with
a basketball hoop is hard to resist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
