<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8195 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE15-COX     04-14 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Follow the food to some fascinating history
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   To explore the origins of the food we eat is never to look at a
salad bar quite the same way again.
</P>
<P>
   Tracing the history of everyday foods _ those we may take for
granted _ can lead to something as lofty as the unfolding of
civilization. Follow the food and learn of geography, history,
anthropology, science, culture, art and even religions of the
world. You'll learn of the people who first developed the food, how
it was dispersed to other areas and the monumental changes that
came about with the development of certain foods.
</P>
<P>
   Take the lowly carrot at that salad bar. When first cultivated
in Afghanistan around the seventh century, they were purple, and
they stayed that way until Dutch botanists got hold of them and
turned them orange during the Middle Ages. Sometime in the 1500s,
Spanish explorers brought the now orange cousin of parsley westward
and planted it on an island off Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   And what of celery? It was considered so powerful as a medicine,
an aphrodisiac, even an aid to help witches fly, that it became a
common design on the crowns and crests of royalty.
</P>
<P>
   Beets, too, have an interesting history. Lucius Junius Moderatus
Columella, the first century version of a food writer, waxed poetic
about the glories of beets, which were called beta because of their
shape, which is similar to that of the second letter of the Greek
alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   These are just snippets. While there are advanced university
college courses on food history, the Internet has some wonderful
and fun sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  From the development of the hearth and its impact on
civilization at ificinfo.health.org/insight
</P>
<P>
   /foodhist.htm to the history of space food at
liftoff.msfc.nasa.gov/academy/astronauts
</P>
<P>
   /food-history.html, this is fascinating stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Check in the next time you're looking for a recipe. It will not
only add to your knowledge, but add interest and excitement to your
table.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  One site you'll want to visit for a quick history of certain
foods is www.bpe.com/food/columns
</P>
<P>
   /ferrayfiszer/ferrayfiszermenu.htm at the award-winning
``Sally's Place.'' The Monthly Market Basket column includes some
history of seasonal foods along with information about growing,
storing and cooking. And there are recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Then there's the dangerously fascinating
www.gti.net/mocolib1/kid/food.html, ``Food Timeline,'' which traces
food from 10,000 B.C. to the present. It's so loaded with
interesting information and links that you may forget to eat.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Curl up with members.aol.com/TchrfromOz
</P>
<P>
   /fashion.html, ``The History of Fashion, Food and Fun,'' when
you have a few hours (or days) to spare. You'll find links to
History of Food Development, The Paleolithic Diet Page, Recipes by
Time Period, The Ancient Art of Roman Cooking, Aztec Medicine Diet,
Food and Drink in Anglo-Saxon England, Salt Made the World Go
Round, the official histories of the table fork, french fries,
barbecue, Southern food, candy, sushi, cola and potato chips ... to
name but a very few.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.gourmetspot.com/foodsatoz.htm _ Epicurious Food
Dictionary, Food from A-Z
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.sof.com/believeit/frame-encyclopedia
</P>
<P>
   .html _ The Encyclopedia of Food
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.richland2.k12.sc.us/svh/Media/foods
</P>
<P>
   .htm _ History of the Moon Pie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  soupsong.com/ibard.html _
</P>
<P>
   Food in Shakespeare
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And don't forget to visit www.foodmuseum
</P>
<P>
   .com/(tilde)hughes/ _ The Food Museum
</P>
<P>
   Asparagus is an exotic vegetable of the lily family, enjoyed for
its delicacy of flavor and nutritional values since ancient times.
As early as 200 B.C. the Romans were growing asparagus, enjoying it
in season and preserving it by freezing. Roman emperors maintained
special asparagus fleets to gather and carry the choicest spears to
the empire.
</P>
<P>
   Asparagus was probably a medicine long before it was a food; the
second-century Greek physician Galen described asparagus as
``cleansing and healing.'' It's an excellent source of vitamins A
and C and is a good source of minerals, potassium and phosphorus.
</P>
<P>
   Growing asparagus takes patience, as the seeds are planted in
the spring, then the plants are set out into permanent fields when
they're a year old or older.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Rotelle With Asparagus and Mushroom Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 servings Prep time: 8 minutes Cooking time: 15
minutes
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces fresh mushrooms, trimmed, halved if large, and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white wine or vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, crushed
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces fresh asparagus, trimmed and cut into 1/2-inch
diagonals
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces uncooked rotelle (spiral) pasta
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   In a medium skillet, combine mushrooms, wine and garlic. Cook,
covered, over low heat until mushrooms release their juices, 5 to 7
minutes. Add the asparagus; cook, covered, 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Uncover and cook over medium-high heat, stirring until most of
the liquid is evaporated, about 3 minutes. Add salt, pepper and
lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cook the pasta in plenty of boiling, salted water
until al dente, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon out 1/2 cup of the pasta cooking liquid and add to
mushroom mixture. Mix well and adjust seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Drain pasta. Toss the pasta with the mushroom mixture and red
pepper. Mix well and serve. _ From: Veggies Unite! www.vegweb.com/
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (based on 4): 244 calories, 10 grams protein, 1 gram
fat (percent calories from fat, 5), 49 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 8 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
