<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Special corn bread plea turns up two possibilities
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Susan Vaughn of Conyers (Ga.) requested a hot water
corn bread recipe after reading about it in a book that didn't
include a recipe.
</P>
<P>
   We're giving her a choice of two, both making patties _ the
first fried, the other baked.
</P>
<P>
   The first recipe was sent by Joanna McQuillan Weeks, food editor
at The Standard-Times in New Bedford, Mass., who read the request
when this column went out on the wire to other newspapers. She
remembered reading about this recipe from Earl's Southern Catering
in Milwaukee in another wire story.
</P>
<P>
   The second comes from Texas and was published here two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Fried Hot Water Corn Bread
</P>
<P>
   Makes 20 pieces
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 8 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups self-rising white cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons granulated sugar (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups hot water
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   In large bowl, combine cornmeal, flour, egg, sugar (if desired)
and hot water. Mix well. Pour enough vegetable oil into medium
skillet to cover bottom. Heat until hot. Place about 2 heaping
tablespoons of cornmeal mixture for each bread patty in skillet.
Fry in hot oil over medium heat until edges are light brown. Flip
and fry until bottom is light brown. Add more oil as needed to fry
patties in batches. Cool and drain on paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   Per 2-piece serving: 194 calories, 4 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 47), 22 grams carbohydrates, 32
milligrams cholesterol, 322 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Baked Hot Water Corn Bread
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 pieces
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Southerners call it hot water corn bread; in New England, it's
johnnycakes. This recipe comes from chef Alphonse Widmer of the
Balcony of Ridglea restaurant in Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup stone-ground yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Combine cornmeal, salt and sugar in
medium bowl. Pour boiling water into dry ingredients and stir well.
</P>
<P>
   Add butter or margarine and beat until well-mixed. On greased
baking sheet, spoon mixture to form 2 1/2-by-1 1/2-inch ovals. Bake
20 minutes or until edges are crispy and brown.
</P>
<P>
   Per piece: 56 calories, 1 gram protein, 2 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 37), 9 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 125
milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe request
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Diane White (e-mail) of Cumming (Ga.) is looking for Plum
Pound Cake. It's made with prunes and raisins, cinnamon, ginger
and, maybe, walnuts and baked in a bundt pan. While the cake is
hot, a glaze containing butter, sugar and Tawny Port is poured into
the pan. ``It tastes like Thanksgiving and Christmas all rolled
into one. It can be addictive. Please help,'' she pleads.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
