<HEADER>
A8197 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     04-14 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miller Lite's masquerade a pale imitation of pilsner
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A generation ago, people would breezily call any red
wine from California a burgundy. One of Ernest &AMP; Julio Gallo's
biggest sellers was a $2.99 wine it called Hearty Burgundy. A
parallel charade took place on the white side. Any sweetish wine
could call itself a chablis and no one thought twice. Not even the
straw jug raised a suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   In none of these cases was the appellation close to the truth,
and it's no closer with Miller Brewing Co.'s new ad campaign for
Miller Lite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enjoy the Great Taste of a True Pilsner Beer,'' the billboards
and full-page magazine ads say.
</P>
<P>
   You might as well call Velveeta an aged cheddar.
</P>
<P>
   P.T. Barnum pegged us right: You can sell some people anything.
That's why the federal government enacted truth-in-advertising
laws. We're suckers for advertising, and mass-market brewers know
it as well as anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Not to put too fine a point on it, but Miller Lite would be
deported without appeal if caught in the Czech Republic or in
Germany. The only thing it has in common with a real pilsner is its
pale gold color.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of beers, both lagers and ales, are gold without being
in the pilsner style.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver-based Institute of Brewing Studies, in a style guide
it publishes for beer sellers, is quite specific. Whether in the
German or the Czech style, a pilsner is characterized by high hop
bitterness and a medium hop flavor and aroma (medium to low, in the
German).
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a pilsner is an assertive beer, slightly maltier
in the Czech style, slightly drier in the German. Except for the
color, there is nothing light, or Lite, about it.
</P>
<P>
   The classic example is Pilsner Urquell, first brewed in the
Bohemian city of Pilsen in 1842. (In German, ``Urquell'' means
``original source of.'') Its pre-eminence is justified, as is its
reputation for traveling poorly. In my experience, the chances of
getting a bottle of Pilsner Urquell that's even tolerably fresh are
50-50 at best.
</P>
<P>
   But in both the German and the Czech styles, there are other
first-rate pilsners, this one a touch hoppier, that one a touch
maltier.
</P>
<P>
   Staropramen, from Prague, isn't as complex as Pilsner Urquell,
but it has a nice hoppiness and it certainly travels better. Easily
the best pilsner I drank in Germany was made by Jever, in the far
north. Unfortunately, it's not available in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Veltins and Bitburger, both from the Rhineland, each
distinguishable from the other, are available and worth a try.
</P>
<P>
   Among domestic interpretations of the style, none that I've
sampled matches Tuppers' Hop Pocket Pils. Indeed, few German or
Czech pilsners are as ``big'' as this beer.
</P>
<P>
   But what all of these have in common is a distinctive hop
presence _ always the flowery Saaz hop in the case of a Czech pils,
the Saaz in combination with other hops in the case of most German
pilsners.
</P>
<P>
   If the palate finds one different from another, it usually is a
difference of degrees. All are recognizably pilsners _ and none of
them tastes even remotely like Miller Lite.
</P>
<P>
   But here are these billboards and ads, selling a fake. The sad
truth is the ``pilsner'' is a term that Americans have bastardized,
just as they once bastardized ``burgundy'' and ``chablis.'' Most
American mass-market lagers are distant derivates of the pilsner
style _ but so distant that the lineage is no longer discernible.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked Dr. David Ryder, vice president for brewing and
research at Miller, in what sense Miller Lite was a pilsner, he
said (in a British accent), ``You're going to have to speak with
the public relations department.''
</P>
<P>
   A young man from the PR department confidently said, ``There are
certain characteristics common to all pilsners, and Miller Lite
falls into that category.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, no, it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   A true pilsner is lagered for up to 60 days, the time during
which the malt and hops slowly develop their complexity. It's
customary for mass-market American brewers to lager their beers for
only 21 days, and sometimes less. Production takes priority, and
then it's all marketing.
</P>
<P>
   A true pilsner will be made of entirely barley malt, with no
corn or rice. American mass-market beers make ample use of both.
</P>
<P>
   A true pilsner is hopped at a rate of 25 to 40 International
Bitterness Units. American mass-market beers, brewed with the
lowest common denominator in mind, have IBUs barely in double
digits _ 10 to 12 is typical. A ``pilsner'' with no more hop
character than that is masquerading as something it's not.
</P>
<P>
   Why not just call it Miller Lite and be honest about it.
</P>
<P>
   PICK OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   The Ralph Steadman art on the label catches the eye, dogs with
wings, dogs like you see only in dreams. But unless you're into
buying labels, sooner or later you ask what's inside. The Flying
Dog line of beers from Colorado has moved briskly since being
introduced to Atlanta last year. Not all of them are something
special, but the Classic Pale Ale and the Snake Dog India Pale are
exceptionally well-made beers that grow on you _ or have grown on
me, at any rate.
</P>
<P>
   The Classic Pale Ale is dry-hopped with Cascades but isn't as
hoppy as many Pacific Northwest pale ales. It has a firm malt
backbone, characteristic of the Colorado style, and complements
just about any food except the very light and the very spicy. I had
it recently with something as simple as a spinach salad dressed
with olive oil and accompanied by smoked Gouda and crackers. It was
wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   I could drink it easily with, say, the kids' pizza or with chili
that didn't reach a flash point of pepperiness. If you like your
chili hot, try the Snake Dog, hopped with domestic strains of the
classic East Kent Goldings of England, and with a maltier character
than many West Coast IPAs. ``We really tried to model it after a
British IPA in body and color,'' says brewer Eric Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Warner enjoys it merely as an aperitif, something to get the
digestive juices working. That, in fact, is how I enjoy it myself.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
