<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8198 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEN-SHOPPING15-COX     04-14 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-SHOPPING15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Men Who Shop: By necessity or by choice, more and more males are
becoming `primary' buyers
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's 10:12 p.m. at the Kroger in Tucker, and Lane
Teilhaber is on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Kris, has been working late, and Teilhaber is cruising
the aisles like a man possessed, picking up ``the essentials'':
soap, shampoo, mouthwash . . . Entenmann's chocolate chip cookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she has to work a 12-hour day, it's only fair if I do the
shopping,'' says Teilhaber, 39, a Atlanta shoe salesman. ``There
are things I'd much rather be doing, but we split up the grocery
shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone. Teilhaber has joined a generation of American
males who, by necessity or by choice, are shrugging off traditional
gender roles and undertaking a chore once considered the exclusive
domain of women. They are Men Who Shop.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers say that more men are pushing buggies down
grocery store checkout lines, elbowing their way toward discount
racks and shopping malls, and buying big-ticket status items that
are markers of modern masculinity.
</P>
<P>
   But these shoppers fit no neat stereotypes. They can be
fashion-conscious up-and-comers trying to impress with a Hugo Boss
suit, empty-nesters wanting to buy a Jet Ski or work-at-home dads
who don't mind clipping coupons.
</P>
<P>
   The bread-and-butter shopper
</P>
<P>
   Among the most studied of male shoppers are those forced into
the marketplace by the demographic and lifestyle changes of the
past two decades. Higher divorce rates, more men remaining single
for longer and more fathers winning joint-custody cases mean that
they're learning to shop both for themselves and their children,
for everything from disposable diapers to the latest styles in
jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, the trend is being driven by the growth of
two-income households, such as the Teilhabers' of Decatur, where a
more egalitarian attitude toward domestic duties has taken root. In
a 1978 survey of shopping patterns by Progressive Grocer, a New
York-based trade publication, men accounted for about 10 percent of
the primary shoppers in U.S. households. In 1998, a similar survey
by the magazine found that the number of male primary shoppers had
risen to 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a tidal wave, but some experts say the number is
steadily increasing _ and with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among men, grocery shopping is still a minority activity,''
says Ruby Roy Dholakia, a professor of marketing at the University
of Rhode Island, who has studied the trend. ``But in homes with two
wage earners where the labor is divided, men seem to have taken on
two chores: playing with the children and grocery shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   Dholakia believes that men generally find shopping ``more
gratifying'' than other domestic grunt work, because the activity
may help them bond with their families.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Kirton, director of strategic planning for Turner Sports,
says he generally does the family grocery shopping instead of his
wife, Wonya Lucas, vice president of marketing for TNT. Kirton, 38,
says he enjoys it and insists he's better at it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan it out. She just goes to the store and gets what she
thinks we need, so sometimes we wind up with three jars of peanut
butter,'' says Kirton, of Marietta, who has two young daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly, says Lucas. ``I don't know about better, but he is
more particular,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The power shopper
</P>
<P>
   Of course, men are shopping for more than just bread-and-butter
items at the grocery store. Although shopping typically ranks low
as a male recreational activity, retailers recognize that there's a
core group of men who are enthusiastic buyers of electronics,
stereo equipment, sporting gear, power tools and cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most powerful consumers in America are older, baby boomer
men,'' says J. Walker Smith, a managing partner of Yankelovich
Partners, a marketing research group with offices in Atlanta.
``They're between 45 to 55 and are in their peak earning years.
They have more disposable income because their kids are grown.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith describes these shoppers as thrill-seekers who are buying
``big toys'' such as personal watercraft and snowmobiles. And savvy
retailers are taking note, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some stores are incorporating adventure and excitement into
the retail setting,'' Smith says. ``Range Rover is a perfect
example. When you go to one of their car lots, they make it feel
like you're going on a safari.''
</P>
<P>
   The fashion-conscious shopper
</P>
<P>
   The men's magazine POV recently identified another group of male
shoppers: the fashion-conscious ``emerging affluents.'' Typically
men between ages 21 and 34, 70 percent of these upscale shoppers
said they shop for clothes at least once a month, with about 16
percent saying they do it once a week. More than 90 percent shop
for themselves, with 5 percent relying on the help of a girlfriend
or wife.
</P>
<P>
   This group may be fueling the increase in menswear sales, which
totaled $35 billion between January and September 1998, up from
$32.5 billion during the same period of 1997 _ a faster growth than
that of any other market segment, including women's and children's
apparel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a quiet revolution,'' says Ted Kruckel, a New
York-based fashion consultant who has written about male shoppers
for GQ magazine. ``I'm not talking about the stereotype of the
fussy homosexual who can tell the difference between Prada and Hugo
Boss. I'm talking about straight guys who don't mind wrestling over
a cashmere sweater at a grubby discount outlet.''
</P>
<P>
   Kruckel says the willingness of men to shop for their clothes is
an outgrowth of the 1980s fitness craze: ``Men are taking better
care of themselves and don't mind going shopping if it will help
them show it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bennett of Norcross is a musician and moving company owner
who says he's probably more picky about his wardrobe than most
guys, and he's not ashamed of it. On a recent day off, he was a
solitary but determined figure as he went through racks of casual
shirts at the Value City discount store on Buford Highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go clothes shopping about every other month,'' says Bennett,
37. ``I don't spend a lot at one time, but I like to keep up with
the style. I hate the crowds, so I come when I know the stores are
quiet and empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Although studies have shown that most men spend little time
browsing for clothes and will pay higher prices rather than
bargain-hunt, shoppers such as Bennett are the exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind searching for deals, and I know quality when I
see it,'' he says. ``I shop off-season and look for stuff on sale.
Only suckers pay full price.''
</P>
<P>
   Lance Robertson, a 35-year-old independent filmmaker, is also a
value-minded clothes shopper. He checks regularly at favorite
outlets such as Apparel Mart, K&AMP;G and Men's Wearhouse and goes into
department stores only if they're having a big sale.
</P>
<P>
   A self-avowed Man Who Shops, Robertson says he's just as
comfortable picking out bath oil for his girlfriend at Victoria's
Secret as buying fresh flowers for his grandmother or complimenting
another man on his outfit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know who I am,'' declares Robertson. ``I don't mind giving
someone their props if they're wearing a nice tie or something. I'm
secure enough in my masculinity, and I don't think being a man has
anything to do with whether you shop or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he considers shopping more than just an idle pastime.
It's a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a city like Atlanta, a man has to stay ahead of the curve
because it's so socially competitive. If you look a certain way,
you can parlay into any environment and people think you belong.
You don't want people to look at what you're wearing at a social
function and say, `Who invited that guy?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The three `P's' of male shopperdom
</P>
<P>
   Male shoppers _ whether in the market for milk, riding mowers or
Mossimo _ fall into three distinct categories, according to
Frequency Marketing. The Ohio-based marketing consultant has
separated them into the following groups:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Patricians tend to be more affluent, as well as single and
childless. They are more likely to shop in specialty stores, for
clothing, electronics and sporting goods.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Practicals also tend to be single but have lower incomes than
Patricians and are usually less free-spending. They prefer discount
stores and are more likely to pay with cash. Although not
particularly fashion-conscious, they plan purchases rather than
buying on impulse.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Patriarchs are older and less educated. They have lower
incomes and are likely to be retired or unemployed. They usually
shop out of necessity, but their purchases tend to be top-of-the
line items.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
