<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VOICE-WEB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE GARBLES OUT OF INTERNET PHONE CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By IAN AUSTEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the telecommunications industry, making a phone call over the
Internet using a PC and a modem is considered something for
``hobbyists,'' a nice way of saying it is frustrating and produces
dubious results. Anyone who has tried making a call over the
Internet will know what they mean.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the idea of talking over the Net holds great
appeal, at least from a financial standpoint. For that reason,
traditional telephone equipment companies like Nortel and Lucent
and Internet equipment makers like Cisco are working to make
Internet calling more than just a curiosity. Currently, the
International Telecommunications Union is developing design
standards for broad-band Internet-based telephone calling. The
standards are being tested at six sites; the only one in North
America is Nortel's subjective testing laboratory in the suburbs of
Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are about to do now is not just deliver quality equal
to today's traditional telephone network,'' said David Cuddy,
director of Network Edge Technology for Nortel. ``We will deliver
better quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Current telephone networks are not as efficient as they are
reliable. The single line the existing system holds open between
two callers is rarely used to capacity during conversation, let
alone during pauses.
</P>
<P>
   Internet calls, by contrast, convert conversation (but not
silences) into computer data which then is broken apart into small
pieces known as packets. Those packets are grouped with other bits
of information flowing through the Net until they arrive at their
destination, where they are, hopefully at least, reassembled into
sounds resembling human speech. It is complex but it lets networks
run at high-capacity levels. A study released last week by Analysys
Ltd., telecommunications consultants in Cambridge, England,
estimates that Internet calling could cut costs by half.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some considerable technical hurdles in the way
before Internet calling can be widely used. According to Cuddy and
his staff, current Internet calls suffer from three major problems:
excessive delay, mostly induced by converting the voice to data and
back again; echo, which comes from poor-quality audio equipment on
computers, and some network problems and garbles created when data
packets vanish or are excessively delayed in transit.
</P>
<P>
   Since perfection is not likely to be economically feasible, the
job of the Nortel testing lab is to figure out how much distortion
phone users will tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   The testing is carried out in a soundproof chamber which is
itself surrounded by a second soundproof chamber. With its light
beige perforated metal walls, the chamber resembles a sparsely
furnished meat locker. When the two steel doors are pulled shut,
the silence is slightly unnerving. ``Most people in here think they
have pressure in their ears,'' said Leigh Thorpe, an experimental
psychologist who regularly rounds up other Nortel employees and
puts them in the room. ``But what they really have is a brain
that's saying: `I'm in a room but there's so sound coming back off
the walls so my ears must be plugged.''
</P>
<P>
   Once locked inside, the employees spend about three hours
creating digital recordings of a word list carefully crafted to
reflect how phonetic sounds are used in English speech. The
deliberately spoken, recorded sentences sound like the ravings of a
troubled mind or some particularly bad beat poetry:
</P>
<P>
   What time of the year are parsnips planted?
</P>
<P>
   A tusk is used to make costly gifts.
</P>
<P>
   A zestful food is the hot cross bun.
</P>
<P>
   That fellow is just a dope of long standing.
</P>
<P>
   The Frenchman was gone when the sun rose.
</P>
<P>
   Once a batch of technically perfect recordings is finished, the
lab begins begins distorting it to reflect actual Internet calls,
either using computer manipulation or by running them through the
Nortel lab's own intranet.
</P>
<P>
   Then 60 people, mainly college students, will come to another
sound chamber in the lab. After donning studio-quality headphones,
they listen to the mangled recordings and rate them on a scale of
one to five with push buttons. Phonetic considerations aside, the
sentences are made deliberately unfamiliar and unrelated _ the
readers' voices intermixed _ in an attempt to force listeners to
concentrate on every word.
</P>
<P>
   Echo and delay are problems that have been overcome in
conventional telephone systems and are not likely to pose
unbeatable technical challenges with Internet calling. That aside,
Dr. Thorpe has found that delay often doesn't trouble listeners.
``They don't attribute it to the connection. They think, `It's that
guy at the other end, what's wrong with him?'''
</P>
<P>
   Fixing missing data, however, is another story. ``With packet
loss, the information is gone,'' said Andrew Patrick, manager of
the subjective assessment group. The only solution so far is to
blend the remaining sounds together; although this process doesn't
replace the missing sound, it can reduce the jarring staccato
quality. ``We just fill it in with some putty so it doesn't sound
so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Because closed corporate Intranets (some of which already use
Internet calling) can minimize packet loss and delay, Nortel is
concentrating most of its Internet calling efforts in that segment.
Across a hall from the sound chambers is a prototype of what the
lab's research has so far helped produce. It is a speaker phone
stuffed with computer memory and a powerful microprocessor that
plugs in directly to the Internet using the Ethernet outlets found
in many offices.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a regular phone, it offers two levels of calling. During
a demonstration using Nortel internal network, its low quality
setting sounded much like a conventional phone line. But when put
on its high quality, or high bandwidth setting, the unit's speaker
was able to reproduce music _ piped from a CD into a second unit in
another room _ with the fidelity of a reasonably good clock radio.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that the unit must have a relatively high-speed
link to the Net. Cuddy said the as-yet unnamed phone will be
introduced ``shortly'' and he expects some kind of consumer
variation will follow before the year's end.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for an Internet telephone is that the PC itself is
responsible for many of the current problems with Internet
telephony. Sound cards, which were created mainly for games, induce
delay. Inadequate microphones create echoes and distortions. PC
software severely compresses data so that it can squeeze through
slow connections.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, PCs just aren't as reliable as telephones yet.
``I still want to be able to make calls when my PC has crashed or
my hard drive died or during the three minutes it takes Windows to
boot,'' said Cuddy.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately solving the technical problems may prove to be
only half the battle for Internet voice calling. If the quality
issues are successfully conquered, its potentially cheap rates
could force a major shift towards Internet telephony, creating
regulatory chaos for both telephone companies and Internet service
providers. ``The dilemma is going to be finding the policy and
billing structure that will make this work,'' said Cuddy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
