</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAM SPADE, MBA: CHANGED DETECTIVES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A sun half-cut by the thick cloud blushed its glimmer
through trees sparkling with recent raindrops. It was about noon,
mid-April. I was wearing my blue pin-stripe suit, a bit shiny from
too many cleanings, with a dark blue shirt and tie and black Gucci
loafers, which had seen better days, but were highly polished. A
red pocket handkerchief splashed color on the jacket. It used to be
the way a private investigator dressed before he lay down for the
big sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Everything's changed now. Spade and Marlowe are gone. Sure,
there are a few tough pros left, like maybe Spenser sometimes, or
Easy Rawlins, a black guy, some hard cops in the 87th Precinct. But
now there are antique dealers and cooks and priests and teachers
and even a handyman has checked in, doing what private dicks used
to do, and they're all amateurs. As for the women, forget it. Quilt
makers, except for a medical examiner or two. And I used to think
Nero Wolfe was a bit freakish with his orchids.
</P>
<P>
   I went through the double glass doors to meet the new breed. I
would have been better off in an apron and a toque.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the antiques dealers and pathologists, the ranks of the
new-breed fictional detective include gay teachers, a lesbian
restaurant owner, a document examiner, psychologists, a forensic
anthropologist, a quadriplegic police criminologist, a sports
agent, an Egyptologist _ all he needs is a fistful of bones to
solve the mystery _ and a young woman who plays the saxophone on
the streets of New York. In short, all have professions. They don't
have to depend on a sexy woman slipping them a pair of greasy Ben
Franklins.
</P>
<P>
   There's also been an explosion in the ethnicity of the
detectives and the geography of the story. The detectives used to
be white. Now there are black, Hispanic, American Indian and even a
few Asian detectives. In this country the detectives roamed the
mean streets of Los Angeles or New York. Today they're all over the
place: New Orleans, the Florida Keys, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The tough-guy stuff, with its touch of masochism, started in
what was considered by book publishers to be the first golden age
of the private eye and the puzzle mysteries, a period lasting from
about the mid-1920s to the late 40s. Of course back then there were
female sleuths who used their brains not guns or fists to solve
murders, but they generally didn't have professions. Agatha
Christie's Miss Marple was typical of the popular English little
old lady school of sleuthing. She ran a household and solved crimes
by asking questions, and the books were grandly written. Ellery
Queen was one of the few exceptions to the hard-boiled school of
male detective.
</P>
<P>
   Marlowe and Spade, of course, were the models. Tough and
cynical, a bit down at the heels, almost always about to yield
their honor. But in the end, no matter how painful, they did what
was right and just.
</P>
<P>
   So why the change? Barbara D'Amato, author and president of
Mystery Writers of America, said: ``Part of the answer is the
influence of television. The writer can't be as general as before,
but must be more specific. When you see a show on television, you
see all the elements of a character's life. The author has to match
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Atmosphere and the vaguest generalities made up the architecture
of the old private-eye and puzzle-mystery stories. Mostly, even the
central character was little more than skeletal, no more deeply
sketched than a description of Marlowe's clothing. After
television, people expected their light reading to have more depth,
Ms. D'Amato said.
</P>
<P>
   To answer this growing expectation and sophistication on the
part of readers, writers gave their sleuths professions. This
started, in the mid-80s, what Ms. D'Amato calls the second golden
age of this genre. Now the reader not only gets a good detective
yarn but at the same time learns the elements of antiques
collecting or quilt making, picks up some recipes from the cook
detective, is instructed about the technology and science of crime
solving: DNA, listening devices, Internet information gathering.
</P>
<P>
   David Rosenthal, publisher of the Simon &AMP; Schuster adult trade
division, said that ``guns are ultimately boring, but the reader
(who probably has a job) can get a vicarious thrill with the
thought that if he had the time and experience he could solve any
crime,'' just as they do in the books. Certainly the new breed is
popular, with many of its authors regularly appearing on the
fiction best-seller lists.
</P>
<P>
   It may be the obviously smart thing to do, giving the sleuth a
profession. One of them is even a flaming red-haired public
relations flack. To me, they're hobbyists. They give me an itch.
How about collecting stamps between murders? Get your hooks into
that one. I don't need it.
</P>
<P>
   Now don't get me wrong. I don't like the beatings that come
along with the retainer, usually in the middle of the case, any
more than you would. But the scribbler needs them because every one
of these books, then or now, have a big soggy and saggy middle that
has to be got over. The easiest way to do that is to have the
detective worked over by some tough boys or to have the best
suspect turn up dead just when I think I've got him nailed.
</P>
<P>
   Me, I'm part of the bunch that still wants my sleuths, male or
female, professionals. Marlowe and Spade had a purity about them,
simple morality tales with no recipes or other stale yak coming
between the good and the bad. I've got no scruples about that. If I
want to learn to cook, I'll go to school. Or I'll hire some
Frenchman to teach me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
