<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MYSTERY-REVIEW-NYT     04-14 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MYSTERY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
` MYSTERY ' : SCOTLAND YARD'S DALGLIESH SWIMS AMONG THE LAWYERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   That word ``certain,'' as cleverly deployed by P.D. James in the
title of her most recent book and its adaptation for television
(``A Certain Justice''), allows for contrary meanings. Most
commonly, of course, it is a synonym for ``sure,'' as in a sure or
certain conviction. But it can also mean ``sort of,'' as in a
doubtful victory for the law, less satisfactory than fans have
learned to expect of Cmdr. Adam Dalgliesh of Scotland Yard.
</P>
<P>
   The three-part offering from ``Mystery'' that begins Thursday
night brings the thoughtful, observant, courteous, poetically
inclined detective (Roy Marsden) to the Inns of Court in London,
which in addition to providing office space, or chambers, to the
city's lawyers, or barristers, turns out to be a hotbed of
inns-fighting. That is useful to Ms. James and to inattentive
viewers, since it quickly provides half a dozen characters who
would not mind if that star advocate, the tough Venetia Aldridge,
was done away with.
</P>
<P>
   Among these candidates for villainy, you may recognize faces
from other British television imports, always a comfort. Anyway,
believe it or not, by the conclusion of Part I, Venetia, having
made enemies of practically everybody who uses the office
refrigerator, meets her bloodily bewigged end. (She is played by
Penny Downie, whom you may recognize as Kate Miskin, the
commander's right-hand woman, in her first incarnation; the latest
Miskin is Sarah Winman.)
</P>
<P>
   Meeting the mostly detestable suspects is fun, but once Venetia
is done away with and the team of Dalgliesh and Miskin begins its
desultory detecting, the tale shifts to a variety of Gothic
spooker. Soon there is another murder to worry about, and perhaps
another murderer.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers acquainted with Ms. James' plots know that she is not
about to pin guilt on any obvious contender, her specialty being
the unearthing of long-buried family secrets. But as the prime
suspects are eliminated, her story loses steam in a melodramatic
denouement that is not worthy of her reputation. The characters we
really want to know more about are those awful lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MYSTERY: A Certain Justice'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Thursday on PBS
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by Michael Russell and based on the novel by P.D.
James. Ross Devenish, director. Produced by United Film and
Television Productions and WGBH/Boston. Michele Buck, executive
producer for United Film and Television and Rebecca Eaton, WGBH.
</P>
<P>
   With: Roy Marsden (Adam Dalgliesh), Penny Downie (Venetia
Aldridge), Ricci Harnett (Gary Ashe), Flora Montgomery (Octavia),
Sarah Winman (Kate Miskin), Frederick Treves (Hubert St. John
Langton), Matthew Marsh (Drysdale Laud), Ian McNeice (Desmond
Ulrick) and Richard Huw (Simon Costello). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
