<SLUG> BC-IBRAHIM-JAZZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN JAZZ PIANIST'S DREAMS STILL LEAD HIM HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once, decades ago, on an ordinary afternoon outing
with friends, a teen-age boy in Cape Town stumbled upon a strange
looking house on a hill. It was an old house, with a corrugated tin
roof and a sprawling yard out front, and just the sight of it
filled him with an unfamiliar feeling of peace.
</P>
<P>
   When he grew into a man, becoming Abdullah Ibrahim, South
Africa's most celebrated jazz pianist, he would find that house
invading his dreams. During the years he lived in exile in New
York, he was haunted by the vision of that house, the afternoon sun
washing its yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came into exile, I thought regularly about this house,
the feeling it gave me,'' recalled Ibrahim, 64, a soft-spoken man
talking just below the din at a noisy sushi house in Manhattan.
``This was the wellspring of feeling I composed out of. When I went
back, my first project was to find that house.''
</P>
<P>
   When he went back home for the first time in 14 years in 1990,
Ibrahim, who will play many of his compositions this weekend at
Joe's Pub (at the Papp Public Theater), found that house and heard
the story that local residents told about it: that it had been
built as slave quarters centuries ago, and underneath it lay a maze
of underground tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   This was the local lore, anyway. Ibrahim tells the story by way
of explaining the strange dream life of the exile and also what it
was like for him to begin to discover his own country, freed from
its official policy of racial separation.
</P>
<P>
   Since returning to South Africa, Ibrahim, who is black, has had
many such discoveries. There was the ancient cave of Sudwola, a
kind of natural amphitheater near the Swaziland border, where he
played a concert two years ago. There was the museum in the heart
of Cape Town that had been off-limits to blacks; not long ago, he
played a concert there, too, and had its doors opened an hour
before the show, so the racially mixed audience could have a look
around. And there was Cape Town City Hall, once also beyond the
reach of most blacks, where Ibrahim has opened a music school.
</P>
<P>
   Born Adolphe Brand in 1934, he was dubbed Dollar Brand for his
practice of buying records from American seamen who docked at Cape
Town. He listened to Duke Ellington and Thelonious Monk, as well as
the gospel of his grandmother's African Methodist Episcopal Church.
He read Chinua Achebe and Leo Tolstoy. He changed his name to
Abdullah Ibrahim when he converted to Islam.
</P>
<P>
   But just as a generation of South African musicians _ he and
Hugh Masekela, the trumpeter, played in a trio _ were beginning to
invent a jazz tradition, restrictions tightened. It became
impossible, he said, to be truly creative. ``That takes time and
serenity,'' he said. ``This was one of the reasons we had to
leave.''
</P>
<P>
   With his wife, jazz vocalist Sathima Bea Benjamin, he left South
Africa shortly after the massacre at Sharpeville in 1962. They
stayed in Switzerland a while, played with Duke Ellington's band
and shuttled between the United States, Africa and Europe for the
next 15 years. Then, in 1976, after the uprising in Soweto, the
couple and their two children packed up and moved to New York City,
finally settling into the eclectic artists' fraternity at the
Chelsea Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But Cape Town never left him. In 1990, Jon Pareles, the chief
pop critic at The New York Times, wrote, ``In Ibrahim's music, the
rolling rhythms of Cape Town's township jazz meet gospel chorales
and shouts, Ellingtonian harmonies and spiky modernist passages,
bound together by an overarching warmth and dignity.'' The group he
built was called Ekaya, which means home.
</P>
<P>
   After Nelson Mandela was released from prison in 1990, Ibrahim
returned to South Africa. Three years ago, the couple bought a
house in Cape Town and his first grand piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to explain what exile can do,'' he said,
quietly considering his words. ``You dream you are at home. You're
meeting old friends and the joy, and you wake up to reality. There
is this blurred line between the known and the unknown, the seen
and unseen. For us, we cross over.''
</P>
<P>
   At home, ``we are in a frontier mode, because there is a
possibility to change things, not just superficially, but
radically,'' he said. ``Because of the situation we find ourselves
in, what we take for granted in other societies _ for example, a
music school _ it is not there.''
</P>
<P>
   He is unabashedly optimistic about the future of his country. A
certain kind of liberation, he said, has been won, but the task of
building remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the process from getting from point A to point B is
the most important, not arriving,'' he said, in one of his
typically oblique parables. At Town Hall in Manhattan, where he
played in late March, Ibrahim, who once composed exuberant songs
like ``Mannenburg,'' the anthem of the anti-apartheid movement,
played a quiet, meditative suite. Where once Ibrahim's tunes
conjured pictures of a rally in the streets, these songs were often
wistful, sometimes bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   Several of his old compositions, many accompanied by a string
orchestra, are collected on a new album, ``African Suite,'' to be
released in the United States in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not necessary to shout, but you can reach,'' he said of
his music now. ``It's much more direct and contemplative.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, he and Ms. Benjamin shuttle from Cape Town to the
Chelsea Hotel every year.
</P>
<P>
   Every time he returns home to Cape Town, he feels drawn to that
old house. Almost every day, he confesses, he takes a drive by. He
doesn't know why, but he suspects it is simply because he can,
because he doesn't have to dream about it anymore. ``It's an
unfinished portion of my life,'' he said, ``a project that needs to
be done. But what?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
