<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8232 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      04-14 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS HEARS FIRST-HAND ACCOUNTS OF KOSOVO REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senators were moved to tears Wednesday as three
ethnic Albanian refugees told them of being forced to leave their
homeland at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before a Senate panel on immigration, Vjosa Dobruna,
a pediatrician and human rights activist, said she was forced out
of town late last month by Serbian security units who ``demanded
money and beat us, both my sister and I. They beat my
brother-in-law very badly, threatening his wife (that) they would
kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobruna, who ran a community clinic in Pristina, the capital of
Kosovo, said she was forced to drive to the Macedonian border where
she waited in line for 56 hours. Eight others were packed inside
the car with no food and little water. Finally, after being allowed
to cross the border into Macedonia, they found conditions no
better, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deportees slept in (an) open, enormous muddy pit with
little or no water or food for the first two days,'' Dobruna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was personally kept from providing immediate aid to a
17-day-old baby suffering from severe dehydration. The baby died in
my hands _ a citizen of my town,'' she said, fighting back tears.
</P>
<P>
   But Dobruna said she considers herself lucky. Many of her
friends were among the ethnic Albanians killed by Serbian security
forces, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Izet Hima was a surgeon at the Gjakova hospital,'' she said.
``Serbian paramilitary police executed him in front of his wife and
two daughters and burned his house down.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing Dobruna's testimony, Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.,
blinking back tears, said it was difficult to keep his composure.
</P>
<P>
   He and other lawmakers said that even though they had read about
the Kosovo refugees, hearing live testimony made their plight real.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned and we will do everything we can,'' said
Senate Judiciary Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who also appeared to
be near tears.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Sen. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., chairman of the Senate
Judiciary Subcommittee on Immigration, which held the hearing on
the refugees, said, ``One of the goals of this hearing is to see to
it that we do not lose sight of the human face of this tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Aferdita Kelmendi, who runs a Pristina radio station, said she
was forced to leave the city on March 29 by two armed men who told
her and her family to follow their green Mercedes toward the
Macedonian border.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way other armed men wearing masks and dark uniforms
stopped them and demanded money ``or they would burn our cars with
us inside,'' she said. After she paid them, they let her and her
family continue their drive. Like Dobruna, she said she waited in
the car at the border for three days with no food and little water
before being allowed to enter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was starving and I was afraid for my life and the life of my
children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelmendi and Drobuna said the U.S.-led North Atlantic Treaty
Organization bombing campaign that started March 24 accelerated the
killing of ethnic Albanians and their removal from Kosovo, the
southern part of Serbia, which is the dominant republic of
Yugoslavia. But they said the killings and other atrocities had
gone on for years and had been increasing since January.
</P>
<P>
   Kelmendi begged the lawmakers to help the estimated 500,000
refugees who are currently living in camps in Macedonia, Albania
and Montenegro and the 700,000 ethnic Albanians who are still
living in Kosovo but have been forced from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they have no food,'' she said. ``We know they are
constantly afraid, saying to themselves, `maybe today they will
come and kill my brother, maybe today they will put my old mother
on a train and force her to live in a field, maybe they will take
my son and they will never see him again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mentor Nimani, a Pristina activist who helped track human rights
abuses in Yugoslavia, said his Serbian boss helped him leave the
country after Serbian authorities searched their office in early
March. Nimani was able to go to Belgrade nine days after the
bombing started. Then he went to Montenegro and finally to Albania
</P>
<P>
   There, he interviewed other refugees. Some told him that Serbian
guards forced groups traveling from Kosovo to Albania to stay
overnight on the Kosovo side of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``While they were trying to sleep in the open, loud speakers
played,'' Nimani said. ``They heard the voice of children screaming
as if they were being killed. They also heard the continuous
threats of the atrocities that would be committed against them,
including descriptions of how they would be killed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The three refugees who testified Wednesday also said they
eventually want to return to Kosovo to live in peace and have no
desire to be relocated to other countries. They asked that NATO
troops eventually be placed inside Kosovo to allow the ethnic
Albanians to return without fear of attack by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Taft, assistant secretary of state for population,
refugees and migration, told the Senate panel the Clinton
administration now has no plans to house 20,000 refugees at
Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, as it had once offered to do. It gave up the
plan after refugees made it clear they did not want to go so far
from their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   She said the administration is instead working with the Albanian
government to build more temporary camps to house the refugees
until it is safe for them to return to Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
