<SLUG> BC-JP-MORGAN-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
J.P. MORGAN'S EARNINGS JUMP 64%  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., regularly cited as vulnerable to a
takeover after successive quarters of weak profits, posted stellar
first-quarter earnings Wednesday, kicking off a year in which
management says the bank will finally prove its mettle.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, the nation's fifth-largest bank and heir to a blue-chip
investment banking legacy now threatened by larger rivals, said
earnings in the quarter jumped 64 percent, to $600 million, or
$3.01 a diluted share, compared with $366 million, or $1.80 a
share, in the quarter a year earlier. Analysts had been expecting
earnings of $1.73 a share, according to the First Call Corp., which
tracks company earnings. Revenue rose 25 percent, to $2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Morgan leaped $3.5625, to $132.875, Wednesday in heavy
trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's profits were buoyed by strong gains in its
bond-trading business, in which Morgan has long been an
international powerhouse, and by astute moves to hedge its exposure
to risky markets like Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan also profited handsomely from stock underwriting and
trading, as well as a strong showing from its derivatives business.
Morgan noted that overseas markets had calmed substantially since a
wave of currency devaluations and other financial woes began
washing across the globe almost two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in over five years the bank has
generated more than a 20 percent return on equity, so it's been a
long time in coming,'' said Diane Glossman, an analyst with Lehman
Brothers. ``But it's still a stretch to say that strong revenue
growth is a permanent condition at Morgan.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts remain hesitant to commit to the notion that
Morgan can count on continued growth and independence because they
still see the firm as overly reliant on bond trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to give them their fair due, but the trading numbers in
the quarter were so far above norms that you have to question the
sustainability of the results,'' said Judah Kraushaar, an analyst
at Merrill Lynch. ``But while there are still some questions about
their revenue and earnings mix because of their dependence on
fixed-income trading, they've made admirable gains in advisory
business like mergers and acquisitions and in asset management.''
</P>
<P>
   Another positive trend, analysts said, was Morgan's increasing
ability to get its once-expanding budget under control. The bank
said operating expenses, excluding a one-time charge in the quarter
a year earlier, rose about 11 percent, to $1.57 billion. But that
represented a smaller percentage of revenue than Morgan has
typically achieved _ a welcome sign, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Another large bank, Fleet Financial Group, also reported
first-quarter earnings yesterday. Fleet posted robust profits of
$438 million, or 72 cents a diluted share, up 36 percent from $323
million, or 53 cents a share, in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had been expecting Fleet to report earnings of 69 cents
a share. In trading on the Big Board, Fleet's shares rose 37.5
cents, to $43.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose to $2 billion from $1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet attributed its performance to strong results for most of
its businesses, especially credit cards, brokerage and investment
services, and commercial and mortgage banking.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Fleet, the ninth-largest bank in the country, agreed
to acquire the BankBoston Corp. in a transaction that is expected
to be completed later this year pending regulatory and other
approval. The merged bank would be the eighth largest in the
country.
</P>
</TEXT>
