<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORDERING SATELLITE IMAGES  
TIPSTERS REVEALED 
THE AOL GLITCH 
BABIES FOR GEEKS  
 BANNED IN TEXAS 
SHRINKING POWER SUPPLIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Texas)   (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Want to be the first on the block to have an aerial shot of your
house? Images taken from a Russian satellite _ with resolution said
to be sharp enough to see specific homes and even cars _ can be
ordered at www.terraserver.com.
</P>
<P>
   Aerial Images Inc. commissioned Sovinformsputnik, a branch of
the Russian Space Agency, to collect images covering 5 million
square kilometers of Earth in February 1998. The pictures are now
being loaded onto Terraserver, where Web surfers can order digital
or print images starting at $7.95. ``This type of imagery used to
be reserved for Cold War military planners,'' said John Hoffman,
president of Aerial Images.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people in the past only saw these types of images in
museums.''
</P>
<P>
   There are innumerable uses for the photos, Hoffman said.
``Political parties can use it to assess the neighborhoods they
want to target. People are using the imagery to lay out tower
structures for cellular towers. Or let's say you're planning a trip
to Paris and you want to get a bird's-eye view of the city.'' It
also makes you nostalgic for the Cold War, when you knew who was
spying on you.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA NAPOLI
</P>
<P>
   Hackers Reveal Identities of Online Police Tipsters
</P>
<P>
   After last month's riot at Michigan State University, the city
of East Lansing posted pictures on its Web site of suspects it said
had been involved in the violence and asked for tips to help track
them down. Police started to receive tips but soon learned that
their promise of anonymity to tipsters had a hole in it.
</P>
<P>
   Within a week, hackers had uncovered a hidden list of informers
who had filled out forms on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Taylor, information systems manager for the city, disabled
the Web-based form last week, as soon as he heard about the breach.
But the damage had been done. Someone had already sent e-mail
messages to Michigan State students describing how to break into
the Web site and view the list for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, not much hacking was required. To view data about
the informers, which was not protected by passwords, students had
to view only the source code behind the form of the Web page,
something most Web browser software can do. The code disclosed
exactly where the data was stored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously have learned from what we've done wrong,'' Taylor
said. The Web site, titled the Hall of Shame, is still up _ but now
tipsters are asked to call the police department.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
<P>
   Problems With Home Pages Are Being Addressed, AOL Says
</P>
<P>
   A glitch in American Online's Personal Publisher 3 editing tool
has prevented many users from creating or editing AOL home pages in
the past few weeks. Instead of getting an error message when the
program isn't running correctly, users are simply left hanging.
</P>
<P>
   ``It affects people in different ways,'' said Ann Brackbill, an
AOL spokeswoman. ``Usually, one of two things happens when those
people try to edit a home page. Either the system hangs _ they see
that little hourglass on screen _ or else they sit there and
nothing happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Some frustrated users have been venting on the AOL message
boards. The subject lines say it all: ``Patience is gone ... now
what do I do?'' ``What's Wrong?!?!?'' ``Take note, Case'' and ``I'm
going crazy'' were some of the postings this week as the company's
technical staff scrambled to fix the glitch.
</P>
<P>
   AOL users who encounter those problems should click on the
cancel button to escape. Then, Ms. Brackbill said, they should type
keyword: personal publisher, to see a list of technical solutions
to specific problems. ``There are work-arounds that you can use,
depending on whether you are unable to make changes or you can't
delete or you can't upload,'' she said. AOL members can also go to
the keyword Publishing Tools and follow instructions to download
another Web-editing tool, AOL Press.
</P>
<P>
   AOL expects to replace Personal Publisher, which dates from
October 1998, with 1-2-3 Publish within weeks. ``People will still
be able to use Personal Publisher if they want to, but 1-2-3
Publish will become the tool we promote,'' Ms. Brackbill said.
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHELLE SLATALLA
</P>
<P>
   From Virtual Petz to Babyz; 15 Months' Worth, Anyway
</P>
<P>
   Who says geeks can't bond? Mindscape Entertainment, the creators
of the Dogz and Catz virtual pets software, is introducing a
virtual baby for parents and older siblings to feed, cuddle, teach
and never, ever spank. Babyz can recognize your voice, grow hair
and teeth and learn good behavior, and _ here's where the virtual
comes in _ they stop growing at 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   Calling into question whether any of the software developers
have ever dealt with a 1-year-old, the infants are given free rein
in their home, which includes a playroom, living room, kitchen and
mice-filled attic. They can play with squirt toys (so close to a
keyboard?) and bang on a piano and drums. If they get too
fractious, they can be sent to grandmother's house, permanently.
You can then go back to the virtual adoption agency and get more
children, but you can never have more than three at a time.
</P>
<P>
   With a little deft cursor work, the caretaker can create two
on-screen hands to rock and cuddle the bunchkins. But if you ignore
them, they will cry and fuss. In the course of a month or so of
use, Babyz will age from 9 to 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   The software, initially for PCs only, is scheduled to be
available in November for $29.99, which will include a microphone
for voice recognition. Mindscape also tentatively plans to release
Baby 2.0 _ yes, 2-year-olds. Every time you open a new application,
it says ``mine.''
</P>
<P>
   _ TINA KELLEY
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Quicken Legal-Help Software Banned by Judge
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, it is now illegal to seek legal advice from a computer
program. A court ruling filed Monday put into effect a judgment
that the Quicken Family Lawyer Version 8.0 and Quicken Family
Lawyer '99 home legal-advice software can't be sold in Texas
because using them constitutes the unauthorized practice of law.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, senior judge Barefoot Sanders of the U.S.
District Court in Dallas wrote, ``The United States Supreme Court
has acknowledged that the state has an interest in regulating the
practice of law.'' He added, ``This interest will be substantially
harmed if it is not allowed to protect unwary individuals from
overly simplistic legal advice provided by a cyberlawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   The $30 program by Parsons Technology was prepared and reviewed
by lawyers and contains around 100 letters, worksheets and basic
legal documents, like wills and estate-planning papers, that users
can complete themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Parsons said the program ``is not intended to
replace professional legal services'' and that users were
specifically advised to talk to a lawyer if they had questions.
</P>
<P>
   The company is appealing and pursuing a legislative remedy. ``We
also would hope and expect that the injunction will be stayed by
the Court of Appeals because there has been no evidence that
indicates _ or even suggests _ that our product has done any harm
to anyone,'' said Eric Stone, vice president for the reference unit
of Parsons' parent company, The Learning Co. The Texas Unauthorized
Practice of Law Committee, financed by the state bar, filed the
suit in 1997 against Parsons and may consider action against other
companies with similar products.
</P>
<P>
   _ JUDE BIERSDORFER
</P>
<P>
   New Backup Power Supply Can Fit Inside a PC
</P>
<P>
   Uninterruptible power supplies, once considered necessary _ and
affordable only for mainframe computers and mainframe budgets _
have shrunk to a point where some can now be stuck inside a desktop
computer, powering it for about 20 minutes in case the electricity
fails.
</P>
<P>
   Most power backup units for desktops are about the size of a
shoebox. But the new Power Card from Guardian On Board fits inside
most PCs. The card comes in an ISA version, with a PCI version
coming to market shortly, and costs about $200.
</P>
<P>
   The Power Card's battery provides about three minutes of juice
for a user to close programs and safely shut down the computer.
</P>
<P>
   David Solomon, chief executive of Guardian On Board, said that
sticking the power backup inside a computer would lower maintenance
costs and conserve desk space. ``The single largest cause of data
loss, computer hardware damages and downtime are power problems,''
Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVEN E. BRIER
</P>
