</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-ANWAR-995&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIOTS FLARE IN MALAYSIAN CAPITAL AFTER EX-PREMIER'S CONVICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Anti-government riots erupted in the
heart of this orderly city Wednesday after Anwar Ibrahim, the
ousted deputy prime minister, was found guilty of corruption and
given an unexpectedly harsh sentence of six years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring that his conduct ``strikes at the very core of the
administrative system,'' Judge Augustine Paul found Anwar guilty of
all four charges that he abused his power as Malaysia's No. 2
official. He refused to give Anwar credit for the time he has
served in jail since his arrest last September.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Anwar appealed the verdict. But for now the
51-year-old Anwar, who was once groomed to be the leader of this
country, looks instead like the victim of a political feud that has
rocked Malaysia and generated sharp criticism of its strong-willed
leader, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
   As news of the verdict spread through Kuala Lumpur _ ending a
trial that has been a riveting daily spectacle for seven months _
several thousand people took to the streets in a show of outrage,
chanting anti-Mahathir slogans and waving placards proclaiming,
``The people are the judge.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was repulsed by water cannons and hundreds of riot
police wielding batons. But it quickly regrouped, and much of the
city was paralyzed as the police pursued the protesters in a
cat-and-mouse battle through the historic old town.
</P>
<P>
   As hulking red trucks sprayed the crowd, the protesters hurled
rocks and bottles at police, lighted bonfires on major streets and
chanted ``Reformasi!'' _ a rallying cry that originated in
Indonesia and now symbolizes the reform movement here as well.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall the mayhem seemed to have died down. But the
clashes were the worst here in months, with police firing multiple
rounds of tear gas at small pockets of Anwar supporters and beating
a human-rights advocate who tried to block the path of a
water-cannon truck. Police officials said 18 people had been
arrested, most at a mosque near the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very angry and upset,'' said Shidi Amin, a 38-year-old
businessman, as he watched protesters flee from riot police near
the main post office. ``They've tried to kill Anwar as a political
leader. But the people will not forget about him, even if he is in
jail.''
</P>
<P>
   The judgment against Anwar provoked anger overseas as well,
where the trial has become a referendum on political freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International condemned the verdict as a ``pretext'' to
remove Anwar from public life, while some foreign leaders, notably
Philippine President Joseph Estrada, expressed concern about the
Malaysian judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Clinton administration also criticized the
conviction. ``There were serious flaws in the way they proceeded
with this prosecution and we have communicated our concern with the
prosecution and with the entire process that led to this verdict,''
said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar himself reacted calmly to the verdict, gesturing to his
lawyers and tearful family members not to lose their cool. But in a
fiery statement in court, he repeated his assertion that he was the
target of a political conspiracy engineered by Mahathir, his mentor
turned rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been sentenced with a judgment that stinks to high
heaven,'' Anwar said from the dock in the spare courtroom here.
</P>
<P>
   His troubles began in 1997 when anonymous allegations about his
illicit sexual activities began circulating in the press. At first
Mahathir dismissed the reports and told Anwar to ignore them. But
later the police began to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar also began clashing with Mahathir about how to respond to
the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar, who was also finance minister, favored keeping the
financial markets open and hewing to the International Monetary
Fund's remedy for curing Malaysia's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir, notorious for blaming George Soros and other foreign
currency traders for Asia's economic slide, wanted to shield
Malaysia by erecting barriers to foreign investment and currency
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 1 Mahathir imposed sweeping controls on Malaysia's
markets; the next day, he dismissed Anwar. Three weeks later, after
Anwar led a rally of 40,000 against the government, he was arrested
on charges of having illicit homosexual affairs and of trying to
quash a police investigation.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 29 the government drew widespread international
criticism after the defendant appeared at his arraignment with a
black eye and bruised face. In a speech here last November, Vice
President Al Gore publicly rebuked Malaysia for suppressing
political freedom. A former police chief has admitted that he beat
Anwar in a police lock-up after his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The trial itself was marked by lurid evidence and bewildering
judicial reversals. Early in the proceedings, prosecutors paraded
through the court with a mattress said to contain semen stains from
Anwar. But later, after several of the men who had accused Anwar of
sodomizing them recanted, Paul amended the charges so the
government had to prove only that Anwar had hindered a police
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar acknowledged that when he was deputy prime minister, he
called police officers to his residence to express concern about
the charges made against him. But he denied that he had forced
anyone to recant.
</P>
<P>
   The political movement that Anwar was building before his arrest
lost much of its momentum during the trial. And with its popular
leader now barred from politics until 2008 by the terms of the
conviction, it is unclear whether the movement will ever regain
traction.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's wife, Wan Azizah Ismail, recently formed a new political
party to challenge Mahathir's coalition. Speaking after the
verdict, she said, ``We still maintain Anwar is innocent and is the
victim of a political conspiracy.'' Her voice cracking briefly, she
pledged to carry on her husband's crusade while he is imprisoned.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Opponents of the government said the harsh verdict would
galvanize Malaysians, who had followed the trial with mounting if
silent disapproval. The anti-government groups are focusing on
unseating Mahathir's party in parliamentary elections, which must
be held by June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a tremendous erosion of support in the political
community, and this decision will further erode that support,''
said Chandra Muzaffar, the vice president of Wan Azizah's National
Justice Party.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts said it was Malaysia's faltering economy that
had fanned the unhappiness toward the government. And with signs
that Malaysia is recovering from its recession, it is doubtful that
a large number of people will continue to call for Mahathir's
ouster.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir, who is 73 and is recovering from a lung infection, has
not commented on the verdict. But his new deputy, Abdullah Ahmad
Badawi, called on people to accept the judgment, and some analysts
said that after a day or two, most Malaysians will do that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
