<SLUG> BC-WNBA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WNBA, PLAYERS STRIKE DEAL, KEEP SEASON ON TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The WNBA and its players reached a collective-bargaining
agreement today, ensuring that the league's third season will begin
as scheduled June 10.
</P>
<P>
   A union representative said that a deal was complete and that a
conference call with Pam Wheeler, Women's National Basketball
Players Association director of operations, and Coquese Washington
of the New York Liberty and WNBPA executive council would be held
at 3:30 p.m. today Arizona time.
</P>
<P>
   Details of what is expected to be a four-year agreement were not
immediately available. But according to agent Bruce Levy, who
represents more than 30 WNBA and former American Basketball League
players, the deal likely will call for:
</P>
<P>
   A $30,000 minimum salary for veterans and $25,000 for rookies.
</P>
<P>
   A limit of three former ABL players per team and a fourth to be
allocated to each of the two expansion teams.
</P>
<P>
   Player contracts being guaranteed as of no later than the middle
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Year-round player health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Players to receive a small percentage of the league's
basketball-related income.
</P>
<P>
   A player advisory panel to have input into league operations.
</P>
<P>
   A 401(k) retirement plan with some league contribution.
</P>
<P>
   In-season housing and local transportation for players to
continue to be paid by the league.
</P>
<P>
   The league also is expected to announce plans to expand by four
more teams in 2000, to 16 total.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 80 players out of colleges and the ABL, which went
bankrupt in December less than halfway through its third season,
are expected at the WNBA pre-draft camp, which begins Thursday at
Moody Bible College in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The league draft is April 27. Training camps open May 14. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
