</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ORGANIZE-ART-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIRED ORGANIZERS CAN CREATE ORDER OUT OF COMPUTER CHAOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.C., Ga., Calif.)  (See also CIR-ORGANIZE-HELP) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JULIA LAWLOR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sally Silberman says a prayer to St. Anthony, the patron saint
of lost things, whenever she goes hunting for a file on a floppy
disk. It usually takes 15 minutes and repeated requests for divine
intervention to find what she is after.
</P>
<P>
   But now Ms. Silberman, a sales executive for the Kimball Office
Group who works out of her home office in Hackensack, N.J., says
there is light at the end of her e-mail list. She has turned to a
professional organizer, determined to clean up the electronic
clutter that clogs her desktop and laptop computers, voice mail and
multiple e-mail accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Silberman, who travels 100,000 miles a year for her job
selling office furniture, has boundless energy. In her spare time,
she teaches college classes, writes for trade magazines and coaches
executives. But being disorganized, she said, is holding her back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had so many things I was doing, I was in so many places at
once, that I had to find a way to manage all this information,''
Ms. Silberman said. ``It was standing between me and living up to
my potential. She regularly fills up her two office e-mail accounts
and often saves so many voice-mail messages that callers hear the
dreaded phrase ``This mailbox is full.'' She recently hired Ken M.
Diebold, a professional organizer for Priority Management Systems,
based in Bellevue, Wash., to help her become more productive.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of workers depend on electronic tools _ computers,
e-mail, voice mail, pagers, personal digital assistants and
cellular phones. But very few, it seems, escape the overflowing
e-mail In boxes and rapidly multiplying, poorly labeled computer
files of the electronic age. What many people have discovered is
that the virtual detritus of a typical working life can be just as
damaging to productivity as a desk covered with dogeared papers and
the remains of last week's takeout lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Many professional office organizers now offer not only to
straighten out paper files but also to show clients how to use the
electronic gadgets that are supposed to make lives easier. ``Why
don't people know this? Because they've never been taught,'' said
Barbara Hemphill, a professional organizer in Raleigh, N.C., and
author of ``Taming the Paper Tiger at Work'' (Kiplinger Books,
1998). ``Many of my clients are executives of very large
corporations who are really struggling with this issue. But
everybody thinks they're the only one with a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Denton, director of the National Association of
Professional Organizers, said: ``People have to develop systems to
manage the fact that information comes in so many different
formats, from so many different places. It no longer happens that
the mail lands on your desk at 10 in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 national study of more than 1,000 workers conducted by
the Institute for the Future, in Menlo Park, Calif., for Pitney
Bowes, a provider of mail and message services, found that the
average worker sent or received 190 messages per day through
various methods, including mail, telephones, e-mail, faxes, pagers
and cellular phones. Seventy-two percent of those surveyed said
that more than half of their messages were electronic, while 28
percent said more than half of their messages were delivered on
paper. The study also identified something it called message
escalation _ the tendency people have to not only send an e-mail
message, but also to fax a copy and leave a voice-mail message, all
on the same subject.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that an increasing number of workers conduct business
on the go makes it harder to keep information overload at bay.
</P>
<P>
   James R. Mason, president and chief executive of Beech Acres, a
nonprofit agency for children and families in Cincinnati, called
Ms. Denton last year. On any given day, he can be working at home,
at the office, in a hotel room or in his car. ``I was overwhelmed
with the sheer volume of data in front of me,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Denton found that Mason was keeping files on five hard
drives _ on an office desktop, on a drive he shared with assistants
and on an agencywide networked drive, as well as his home desktop
and laptop drives. He often could not remember which computer he
had used when he created a file. He also kept files on floppy
disks, which tended to disappear. He had no system for organizing
computer files, and his e-mail list had grown to 500 messages,
including 100 he had never read. He used a paper calendar, a
Franklin Planner, for appointments, but he was constantly
overbooked because his secretary did not always have access to the
calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Denton persuaded Mason to switch to an electronic calendar,
a Windows CE version of Microsoft's Outlook, which he installed on
a Cassiopeia palm-size personal computer he carries everywhere. The
calendar is synchronized with computers at work and at home so
Mason's secretary can check and update it. Mason can also read and
respond to his e-mail messages with his palm-size PC, which
eliminates facing a backlog of e-mail messages when he returns from
a business trip.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Denton also taught him to categorize his computer files into
action, reference and archive files and to put computer files and
e-mail messages into categories and folders.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Once you are committed to the concept of electronic
organization, one of the first things to decide is whether to use
paper or not for appointments, addresses, numbers and to-do lists.
Just as in the paper realm, there are several calendar software
products to choose from, like Outlook, ACT and Goldmine.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Silberman chose Outlook and spent several hours one day
recently in Diebold's office learning how to transfer the
information in her four-inch-thick calendar, including notes
scribbled on stick-on notes and scraps of paper, into her laptop.
Tired of lugging around her paper calendar, she decided to go
electronic after getting a Palm Pilot III. ``I'm going through
withdrawal because I'm used to writing everything down and seeing
it all laid out in front of me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another executive who got help from a professional organizer,
Bill Finlay, chose to keep his calendar on paper. Finlay, president
and chief executive of Helvoet Pharma, a pharmaceutical supply
company in Pennsauken, N.J., sought the assistance of Ira Chaleff
of the Institute for Business Technology, a white-collar
productivity consulting firm based in Boca Raton, Fla. Finlay
switched to ACT for scheduling and tasks in 1997, yet he still
carries a Franklin Planner when he is out of the office because he
considers his laptop too bulky and distracting to flip open at
meetings. ACT is designed to work with the Franklin Planner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a hybrid,'' Finlay said. ``I would love to meet the geek
who is completely electronic.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail is another issue. According to a 1997 survey of more than
1,500 white-collar workers worldwide sponsored by Priority
Management Systems, 72 percent of workers used e-mail in 1997, up
from just 41 percent in 1990. The number of e-mail messages tripled
between 1994 and 1997 in the United States alone, the study
reported, and is expected to almost triple again, to 6.6 trillion
messages, by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Gleeson, president of the Institute for Business
Technology, said most people who use e-mail did not know how to
organize it because they rarely got any formal training. Some
people need to check e-mail frequently, while others can get by
with checking no more than three or four times a day. Messages
should be dealt with as soon as they are checked _ acted on and
deleted, or transferred to category folders, or deleted
immediately. Some professional organizers suggest setting up
filters to screen out messages you know you do not want _ like
jokes from a certain person.
</P>
<P>
   People seem to give as little thought to organizing their
computer files as they do to organizing their e-mail or their
bookmarks of favorite Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Klung, a sales education and professional development
manager for Blue Shield of California in San Francisco, sought help
last year when she was having trouble finding files. A professional
organizer, Eve Abbott, taught her to categorize files according to
all the different responsibilities she has at work, to name them so
she would be able to find them later and to combine different types
of files _ like a word document, a spreadsheet and a graphic file
that she might have used for a project _ into one file listed under
the project's name. That way, Ms. Klung no longer has to hunt for
three different files in three different places.
</P>
<P>
   ``It saves me at least an hour a day,'' Ms. Klung said. ``It
seems so simple, but I hadn't been doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another person who needed help was Marilynn Mobley, who called
in Ms. Hemphill last year. After 15 years at International Business
Machines, Ms. Mobley left three years ago to start her own business
communications consulting firm, which she runs out of her home in
Marietta, Ga. She soon became overwhelmed, filling her
eight-gigabyte desktop computer to capacity and wasting up to two
hours a day looking for information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to the harsh realization there was no such thing as a
filing fairy, nobody coming into the office at night to take care
of things,'' Ms. Mobley said. She had only two ways to categorize
her files: ``stuff I sent'' and ``stuff I need to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hemphill helped her set up a system that included 32
folders, broken down by client, with subcategories for speeches,
consulting and research. She was able to cut the number of computer
files she had in half, to a little more than 2,000. She cleaned out
her e-mail in box and organized the 600 messages she wanted to
save.
</P>
<P>
   Now clients call Ms. Mobley when they cannot find a document. It
takes her just a few minutes to find a file and fax it. ``I walk
into my office with a different attitude,'' she said. ``I don't
have the sense of dread I once had. I cannot tell you how this has
saved my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
