<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRS-PUBLIC-ART-2TAKES     04-14 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-PUBLIC-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRS HEAD WORKING TO PUT SERVICE AHEAD OF REVENUE SO BOTH WILL
INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He gets up before dawn every day and runs five
miles, then heads for his government job without eating breakfast.
He does not need the work _ after all, he's sitting on a $40
million fortune he made running his own business _ but this may be
his biggest challenge yet.
</P>
<P>
   Charles O. Rossotti, the first IRS commissioner who is not a tax
lawyer, is pursuing a technological and cultural revolution with
the improbable goal of both making the service more efficient at
collecting taxes and making Americans happier about paying them.
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving 18 months ago, Rossotti has instituted a 24-hour
hot line for taxpayers, with an emphasis on reliable, courteous
service.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those now fielding calls are longtime auditors whose old
jobs were hunting for errors and finding cheating on tax returns
filed years earlier. To improve the accuracy of their responses,
the commissioner has undertaken a seemingly obvious step that
somehow eluded his predecessors: giving IRS employees ready access
to the Internal Revenue Code.
</P>
<P>
   He is also having those unfathomable audit notices rewritten in
plain English, with help from focus groups of taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The task before him is enormous. Not only must the IRS collect
$1.7 trillion this year, more than the gross domestic product of
Britain, it must also transfer billions of taxpayer records from
computer systems that date back to the Eisenhower administration to
modern disk storage and database systems that have yet to be
designed.
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti has little room to stumble. Before he arrived, the
agency wasted $4 billion on computer systems that proved to be
unworkable. And Congress, unlikely to tolerate a repeat of that
fiasco, is keeping a closer eye on the IRS than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after two years of inquiries that stirred widespread
outrage over mismanagement and abuse of taxpayers, lawmakers
approved a major overhaul of the agency. A board was created with
authority to oversee IRS management and policies, set a five-year
term for the commissioner and expand protections against abusive
tax agents.
</P>
<P>
   On top of everything else, Rossotti must win over many senior
executives and middle managers _ or replace them _ if his plans are
not to get lost in the bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   His admirers describe Rossotti, 58, as an organizational wizard
with the uncanny ability to see both the forest and the trees and
then decide which leaves need trimming and which need more
sunlight. Among his priorities is upgrading IRS laptop computers so
old that they still run on the outmoded MS-DOS operating system.
</P>
<P>
   And he has recruited his own team of senior executives from
business and state government, teaming them with career IRS
executives whom he chose for their track record in getting things
done.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest problem, Rossotti said in a recent interview, is
putting his vision of a customer service agency into focus for
98,000 IRS employees, many of whom have become jaded at the
spectacle of commissioners coming and going without leaving a
noticeable mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much change going on that it appears bewildering
to our people, and they don't understand why we are doing what we
are doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So Rossotti did something almost unheard of in the top ranks of
government. Instead of assigning subordinates and consultants to
churn up a new organizational table and write a report, he did the
job himself.
</P>
<P>
   On vacation with his wife in Naples, Fla., over the Christmas
holiday, Rossotti wrote down his vision for the IRS on his laptop
computer _ an exercise that led to a 68-page booklet, ``Modernizing
America's Tax Agency.''
</P>
<P>
   It begins with a new mission statement that takes a
revolutionary attitude toward taxpayers. The statement makes no
mention of the IRS's enforcement powers that have been the terror
of generations of Americans or of the pressing need to raise
revenue for the federal government. Rather, it emphasizes the
importance of putting on a friendly face for the agency's
``customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The old mission statement _ ``to collect the proper amount of
tax'' _ was replaced by this: to ``provide America's taxpayers
top-quality service by helping them understand and meet their tax
responsibilities and by applying the tax law with integrity and
fairness to all.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti also crammed the statement with practical details on
running the IRS, such as the need to install ergonomic work
stations for employees. ``I wanted to explain how all the different
parts fit together and not just move boxes around on the
organization table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to former commissioners, who often received more
money from Congress with promises that a dollar spent on
enforcement would generate several dollars in extra taxes, Rossotti
wrote that ``enforcement revenue is not a good measure of success
in achieving the strategic goal of service to all taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8283 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRS-PUBLIC-ART-2TAKES     04-14 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-PUBLIC-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: all taxpayers.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Audits, collections and criminal investigations currently
consume 40 percent of the IRS budget. And while Rossotti
acknowledged that such enforcement actions are needed, he suggested
that the carrot would be more effective than the stick in
persuading people to pay what they owed. (Even before he came
aboard, the IRS was shifting its emphasis to voluntary compliance,
reducing the audits of high-income returns to 1 in 60 last year
from 1 in 9 a decade earlier.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 98 percent of the revenue comes in without enforcement
action,'' he wrote, ``a 1 percent increase in voluntary compliance
would be roughly equivalent to a 50 percent increase in enforcement
revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Goldberg, the Bush administration tax commissioner, was one
of a handful of IRS critics sent a copy of the booklet with a
hand-signed note by Rossotti. He said he was impressed by its
content.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this ultimately is in the execution, but the vision
hangs together as a coherent theory of management,'' Goldberg said.
He said Rossotti was attacking a culture in place since the
enactment of federal legislation in 1952 that replaced politically
appointed _ and often corrupt _ tax collectors with civil servants.
</P>
<P>
   While reform ended most abuses, it also fostered a climate of
secrecy and suspicion that is at the root of much of the IRS'
recent malaise. Now, Goldberg said, Rossotti has laid out ``a
system designed to respond to taxpayers' expectations with an
explicit discussion that the notion is not to squeeze the last
dollar from the stone, that service to taxpayers is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Even longtime critics of the agency are impressed. ``At this
point, Rossotti is right on the mark,'' said Jeff Trinca, former
chief of staff of the National Commission on Restructuring the IRS,
a congressional commission. ``He is doing all the right things; he
understands the management, technology and training issues better
than anyone who has sat in that seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Rossotti's background, that is perhaps not surprising. He
earned a master's degree in business administration from the
Harvard Business School in 1964 and went on to become one of the
Pentagon whiz kids under former Defense Secretary Robert S.
McNamara, spending five years as assistant secretary of defense for
Systems Analysis.
</P>
<P>
   He left the government in 1970 to co-found American Management
Systems in Fairfax, Va., a computer consulting company that
specializes in showing businesses how to integrate technology into
their operations.
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti has also banned dollar quotas as a measurement of tax
collectors' performance. Many of his predecessors tried and failed
to put that change into effect, but unlike them, he has created an
alternative monitoring system that relies, in part, on taxpayers'
assessments. Moreover, he plans to base senior IRS executives' pay
partly on such issues as their success in resolving taxpayer
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti says his efforts to overhaul the IRS could take up to
nine years _ or could flop quickly. ``I'm no fool,'' he said.
``There's no guarantee that this will be successful. We could crash
and burn in any number of ways, but I think it's worth it, and I
think I can do it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He took on the task almost by accident. Two years ago, he got an
unsolicited call from an executive recruiter asking if he could
recommend someone with strong organizational skills and an
understanding of technology to head the agency.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Rossotti was chairman of American Management
Systems. ``I thought, now that would be an interesting job,''
Rossotti said, a smile lighting up his face. He said that his wife,
Barbara Margulies Rossotti, a corporate lawyer, told him he was
crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Crazy or not, he sure is busy. He has become so absorbed in his
new responsibilities, he says, that he rarely allows himself to
indulge in two of his favorite pastimes, playing his baby grand
piano or hitting the tennis courts. In his year and a half on the
job, he says, he has found time to have lunch with his wife during
the workweek exactly twice.
</P>
<P>
   He has even become a little careless in his usually impeccable
attire. The other day, he sported one of his custom-made British
suits, which matched his gray hair perfectly, a rich yellow necktie
and a natty pocket handkerchief. But his wing-tip shoes were dull
and scratched.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not polished?'' Rossotti asked in surprise before
gazing down at the offending footwear. Well, he added in his
defense, ``I just haven't had time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
