<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAYS-BUSINESS-SCHOOL-     04-14 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-BUSINESS-SCHOOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADITIONAL BUSINESS SCHOOLS MORE OPEN FOR GAYS, STUDENTS SAY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ When Evan Bachner attended Columbia Business
School 15 years ago, he could always tell who the gay students
were.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the ones who looked at their shoes when you looked
at them,'' Bachner said. He knew, because he was ``horribly not
out'' himself.
</P>
<P>
   So when Bachner, 42, found himself in an auditorium at Harvard
Business School describing his job as a Merrill Lynch vice
president at a recent conference for gay and lesbian MBA
candidates, his first thought, he said, was, ``This is so weird.''
</P>
<P>
   His audience of students attending their first gay and lesbian
business school conference did not find it so strange. In just the
last few years, the students say, their traditionally buttoned-down
business schools have become more open environments for gay people.
</P>
<P>
   New clubs for gay MBAs are popping up on campuses, while
established groups are strengthening their memberships. At
Columbia, the reorganized gay and lesbian business student
organization, called Cluster Q, went from no members last year to
45 this year. Paul Trout came out to his classmates at Indiana
University's Kelley School of Business a year ago, and immediately
founded a support group called the Inclusion Network. A group of
students at Boston University's School of Management are forming an
organization there.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's conference here, entitled ``From the Closet to the
Boardroom,'' was organized by two MBA candidates from Ivy League
business schools: James Robertson, from Yale, and Jason Stone, from
Harvard. About 150 students from 20 different schools, including
those at Dartmouth, MIT and Stanford, attended.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their growing visibility, gay students say the
transition to business school can be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Yale would be receptive,'' said Robertson, 33, who
worked most recently for the Names Project in San Francisco, making
an AIDS memorial quilt. ``But when I got there, I hesitated. I
said: `God, this is not the Names Project. This is not a place
where being gay is presumed.' And there was a little bit of culture
shock. It took me a while to get back my direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Being open about their sexuality is only the first of many
decisions they need to make, students say. Should you put your
lesbian club membership on your resume? How much of your personal
life should you share with a prospective employer and, once hired,
with co-workers?
</P>
<P>
   For Mark Guzdik, a business student at Columbia, there is still
a need for caution in discussing his sexual orientation _ though
not because of the forced secrecy that tormented Bachner years ago.
Guzdik considers discretion a good preparation for a career in
international media development, where he will have to fit into
different cultures and situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to learn how to temper my gay identity,'' Guzdik
said. ``In the business world, we have our private lives and our
public lives.''
</P>
<P>
   At the recent conference, some speakers encouraged students to
bring up their sexual orientation right at the job interview, to
find out how they would be treated by the employer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's absolutely a seller's market, and you guys are for
sale,'' said Tom Rielly, chairman of Planet Out, the gay and
lesbian online service. ``You don't need to go work at a place
that's homophobic.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone had such upbeat advice. Joseph Daniel is suing his
former employer, Dresdner Bank, which fired him a week after he
suggested that it offer health benefits to gay domestic partners.
(The company says his dismissal had nothing to do with that
suggestion or with his being gay.) He kept his sexual orientation a
secret for many years. ``I can still do a pretty good impersonation
of a straight fellow from Greenwich, Conn.,'' Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   Others warned that having a master's degree from a prestigious
school is not necessarily a protection from discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a cold, cruel world out there,'' said Carl
Rosendorf, senior vice president at barnesandnoble.com. ``Whether
it's the factory floor or the corporate board room, the issues are
the same.'' Still, he says his being openly gay sets an example for
his employees.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of charts and graphs, it was a business conference of
stories, sometimes very personal ones. Walter Schubert Jr., the
first openly gay man on the 1,365-member New York Stock Exchange,
described the stock floor as ``a football locker room'' that was
``all about intimidation'' when he decided to come out. But he
managed to hang onto his staff and his clients, and went on to
found the Gay Financial Network, a financial services Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Some speakers urged gay students to try for careers in Internet
businesses. David Blumberg, a venture capitalist, said he had just
raised $50 million for two start-up Internet companies, both run by
gay men.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really don't care what you do in your personal life,''
Blumberg said, describing fast-growing Internet companies as
libertarian meritocracies. ``People really get rid of the
extraneous and focus on what's important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
