A8293 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-MILITARY-AZR &LR;      04-14 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MILITARY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO DEMONSTRATES MILITARY'S LACK OF READINESS  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARS IN THE APRIL 15 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - So far, if anything positive can be extracted from the
war in Kosovo, it may be a resurgence in examination of America's
military history.
</P>
<P>
   Will the introduction of American ground forces into Yugoslavia
provoke this nation's next Vietnam? We've heard a lot of that talk
lately.
</P>
<P>
   Or will it be the next Korean conflict, where a more muscular
nearby player-state - in Korea, the Chinese; in Kosovo, the
Russians? - arrives to escalate the conflict into something truly
perilous?
</P>
<P>
   Even the geopolitics of the American Civil War have been debated
regarding Kosovo - should manipulative outside powers interfere at
all in a sovereign nation's internecine disputes?
</P>
<P>
   But at this stage in the Kosovo conflict, the most talked about
historical parallel has been between the American armed forces of
today and the nation's Army just prior to the two World Wars. Then,
the U.S. Army essentially did not exist. The dread today is that,
in terms of readiness to go to war, history is repeating itself.
</P>
<P>
   Sorties against Slobodan Milosevic's Serbia early in the
conflict were limited as much by a shortage of planes, bombs and
missiles as by any strategic resistence to hitting the enemy overly
hard. The Air Force says it is down to about 100 cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster the NATO forces attacking Yugoslavia, America's
military strength has been drained from some of the world's most
incendiary hot spots: air patrols over northern Iraq have dwindled
as planes are shipped to Italy; naval vessels critical to the
defense of South Korea now ply Adriatic waters.
</P>
<P>
   Most troubling, though, is the discouraging state of readiness
demonstrated by the assignment of 24 Apache attack helicopters to
the conflict, along with 4,800 support troops - up from the initial
2,000. This ``ready response`` team that was supposed to be on the
job within two weeks now won't be ready for a month or more.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Pentagon officials say they plan to approve sending 300
additional aircraft into the fray, a 60-percent increase in the
American flying force there. To support this buildup, the military
also said it expects to begin calling up reservists.
</P>
<P>
   In its most significant statement on America's military
readiness, the Clinton administration declared less than two years
ago that the nation was prepared to fight two major conflicts
simultaneously. The campaign against Milosevic is proving that
declaration a fraud.
</P>
<P>
   It is bad enough that the stated strategic goals of the Kosovo
incursion - bringing Milosevic quickly to his knees and protecting
the Kosovars - have proved foolishly optimistic. NATO's utter lack
of a relief plan for the half million Kosovo Albanians routed from
their homes belies claims that the Allies were prepared for
anything like that social catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   But if the intention was to wage war, logic would dictate that
they at least would have prepared for that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
