<HEADER>
A8308 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASA-HNS &LR;      04-14 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA LEADER DEFENDS STUDY OF ALL-FEMALE SHUTTLE CREW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE SNYDER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NASA Administrator Dan Goldin on Wednesday defended
the space agency's study of a possible all-female shuttle mission,
saying such a flight could inspire more young women to enter
science and engineering professions.
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation with reporters on a range of topics, Goldin
said he has been baffled by the ``negative connotations''
associated with the idea since it surfaced a few weeks ago. Some
critics have suggested that such a mission would amount to a public
relations stunt, a charge that also was made regarding Sen. John
Glenn's historic second space flight last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why everyone's bowels are in an uproar when
we even consider'' an all-female shuttle crew, Goldin said. ``How
many times does an all-male crew go up? Many. Who asks a question
about it? Does anyone say: `Why do you have an all-male crew?' I
don't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldin said the idea of an all-female crew was first raised by
Dr. Arnauld Nicogossian, NASA's associate administrator of life and
microgravity sciences and applications, who wondered out loud
whether women might be subject to different medical stresses in
space than men. Goldin said he instructed Nicogossian to review the
question.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Goldin said, he wants the agency to examine whether
NASA is launching women into space in proportion to their level of
representation in the astronaut corps. Of the agency's 144
astronauts, 33 are women. NASA has flown 28 female astronauts in
its history.
</P>
<P>
   Only when the possible scientific benefits and personnel issues
have been reviewed, Goldin said, will the agency consider the
potential ``inspirational'' benefits of an all-female shuttle
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of a particular mission on the public mood, Goldin
said, is a legitimate consideration for the space agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel that flying John Glenn was a stunt,'' he said.
``And the fact that most Americans had a tear in their eye and felt
good about their country and felt good about themselves because
John Glenn flew, I don't call that a stunt. I call that a part of
Americana, part of who we are and what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine Burke, executive director of the Society of Women
Engineers, said a shuttle crew made up entirely of women would
``catch the attention of young girls'' and perhaps attract them to
careers in science, engineering and technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has not been enough awareness-raising for girls to
understand that these professions are open to them, that it's not
just little boys who grow up to be astronauts,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin said he has established no timetable for a decision about
an all-female flight.
</P>
<P>
   On another topic, Goldin said he still expects the Russian Space
Agency to launch the much-delayed service module, a crucial
component of the international space station, before the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Because of financial problems in Russia, the service module is
19 months behind schedule. The module is to furnish the living
quarters and life support for the new station's first crew of
astronauts and cosmonauts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
