A8309 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN     04-14 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`APT PUPIL'   TRANSCENDS HORROR STORY LABEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use Friday, April 16 by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Sir Ian McKellen hadn't gotten an Oscar
nomination for ``Gods and Monsters,'' he certainly would have for
``Apt Pupil,'' which is out on video.
</P>
<P>
   McKellen plays Kurt Dussander, a Nazi war criminal who has been
hiding in America for years when a teen-ager discovers the old
man's real identity and blackmails him into telling stories about
his wartime experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Renfro plays the teen, Todd Bowden, a top high school
student who becomes fascinated with the Holocaust after studying it
and notices a resemblance between an infamous Nazi and the old man
he sees riding on a bus. His fascination turns to obsession as he
uses Internet databases and dusts Dussander's mailbox for
fingerprints in order to discover his true identity.
</P>
<P>
   After confirming who Dussander is, Todd confronts him and
demands: ``I want to hear all about it. The stories. Everything
they were afraid to tell us in school. No one can tell it better
than you.''
</P>
<P>
   At first the old man is reluctant, but realizing he is trapped,
he begins to relate the gruesome details: ``Although the gas came
from the nozzles at the top, still they tried to climb. And
climbing, they died in a mountain of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden then brings the old man a Nazi uniform, makes him put it
on and orders him to march around the kitchen: ``Attention! March!
Face right!'' Dussander protests, but Bowden reminds him, ``What
you've suffered with me is nothing compared to what the Israelis
would do to you. Now move!''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Dussander comes to life. It is a terrifying moment to
watch as McKellen transforms Dussander's body language. Suddenly
the tired old man throws 40 years off his shoulders and becomes a
frightening force.
</P>
<P>
   What develops is a bizarre relationship between Bowden and
Dussander, as the old man, curiously revitalized by recalling his
glory days, turns the tables on the teen, who has become trapped
because he hasn't turned Dussander in.
</P>
<P>
   While the cat-and-mouse game that ensues is fascinating, ``Apt
Pupil'' is more than the Stephen King horror story on which it was
based. In fact, it seems that a number of critics assumed it was a
horror story because of the source material. But ``Apt Pupil'' is
more a meditation on the insidious nature of evil.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bryan Singer (``The Usual Suspects''), the horror in
``Apt Pupil'' is, like ethic cleansing, man made. Does Bowden
become evil because he already was, or because he was open to it?
By placing the story some 40 years after the Holocaust, in the safe
suburbs of America, the film creates an emotional distance in which
to examine the question. Were all Germans evil? Were all Nazis?
Where do you cross the line and become evil? The film, in essence,
is asking all of these questions.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Apt Pupil'' is not totally successful (there is a bit
too much King plotting or plodding King), it remains a provocative
film with spectacular acting from McKellen. Meanwhile, Renfro shows
he is an actor to be watched. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If last weekend's Masters Tournament proved too exciting (or
boring), you might want to relieve the tension (or tedium) of
watching the pros agonize for five minutes before tapping in a
5-foot putt by checking out ``Caddyshack.''
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the funniest _ though not the best _ film about golf
(can there be a best film about golf?), ``Caddyshack'' was
rereleased on video recently by Warner Bros. in a special
19th-anniversary edition. That makes about as much sense as golf,
or the plot to this film directed by Harold Ramis (``Analyze
This'').
</P>
<P>
   But who cares? With Rodney Dangerfield, Chevy Chase, Bill
Murray, Ted Knight and a crazy gopher, there are enough laughs to
ignore the inane subplot. Mark Twain once described golf as a good
walk spoiled. ``Caddyshack'' is a good comedy spoiled, but some of
us keep watching (or playing) just the same. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8310 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0415-     04-14 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0415-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REFUGEE TIDE FLOWS AGAIN FROM KOSOVO, INCLUDING EARLIER GROUP
DENIED EXIT
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0415.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ The Yugoslav government's inexplicable policy
on refugees took another mysterious twist Wednesday when thousands
of Kosovar Albanians, including some missing since prevented from
leaving the country last week, began straggling across the reopened
border.
</P>
<P>
   Another 3,000 refugees had also entered Macedonia by train, foot
and car at two border crossings.
</P>
<P>
   It was still uncertain late Wednesday whether this would be the
flood tide of families that humanitarian aid workers have anxiously
awaited since the Serbian-dominated Yugoslav government suddenly
shut the border last week.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,000 had crossed into Albania by midnight, and there
were some indications that a major sweep of ethnic cleansing might
be underway.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 260,000 Kosovar Albanians are displaced within
Kosovo, according to the United Nations High Commission for
Refugees (UNHCR). They, as well as ethnic Albanians not yet driven
out of their homes, are candidates for a mass exodus.
</P>
<P>
   UNHCR officials expected Macedonia to receive 50,000 refugees in
coming days. The estimate was based on accounts from people in
Kosovo who said many people from the city of Urosevac, 20 miles
from the Macedonian border, were on the move.
</P>
<P>
   Albania has taken in 300,000 Kosovo refugees in the last three
weeks; Macedonia has had 120,000. The influx has strained the two
poor Balkan countries. Macedonia has said its new camps are almost
at capacity.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, many arrived on foot and many were making their
second, exhausting run at the border. Their stories finally
explained what happened to them, but still did not clarify the
Serbs' aim in earlier turning them back.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us can understand it,'' said Jaferr Deliaj, 50,
moments after his family of eight walked into Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Early last week Serb police stopped them before the border and
told them to go back home because the fighting was over, Deliaj
said. But when they got back to their village of Dveric, about 60
miles to the north, Serb militia were occupying the burned-out
remains.
</P>
<P>
   They told the refugees to go and stay in a school at a nearby
town. About 600 of Deliaj's townspeople remained in the school,
until Serb militia came to them on Monday and demanded once again
that they depart their native territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us the road is now open, so you must go to
Albania,'' said Deliaj, a farmer. Before they left, Serb forces
confiscated six of the group's tractors, including Deliaj's. His
family rode with a neighbor -- 40 people cramped for two days in a
tractor-hauled wagon -- until they got
</P>
<P>
   about three miles from the border. The gasoline ran out, so they
walked the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   None of the refugees interviewed indicated they had been used as
human shields, b
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
