<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8311 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARR15-COX     04-14 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STARR OFFERS DEFENSE OF CLINTON PROBE
 &HT;    840&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent Counsel Kenneth W. Starr, who had kept
his silence through hailstorms of criticism, answered back
Wednesday with an impassioned defense of his four-and-a-half-year
investigation of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm old-fashioned _ I believe that 'the truth shall set you
free,' `` he told the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee. ``And
for better or for worse _ I think it's always for better _ the
country knows the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending both the time and the expense consumed in the effort,
Starr said his office had followed federal rules for investigations
and dismissed many of the criticisms as theatrics, ``calumnies''
and ``outright falsehoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Testifying in his familiar soft voice for nearly three hours,
the man who went from being a widely praised jurist to one of the
most disliked public figures in the nation agreed with his critics
on one key issue: that Congress should not reauthorize the
Independent Counsel Act, which expires at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime opponent of the law, Starr called it ``structurally
unsound,'' ``constitutionally dubious,'' and even ``disingenuous,''
since it promises more independence than it can deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said it was a mistake to require an independent
counsel to deliver a final report to Congress, and he expressed
regret at the public release of so many of his sexually explicit
findings. He said he was sorry he hadn't impressed on Congress his
request to ``treat the material cautiously.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Starr blamed the Clinton administration and their
defense lawyers for turning his impeachment investigation into
abuse of power and perjury charges into a ``political game'' that
has damaged the public's confidence in the justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling that the Clinton team had ``declared war'' on him,
Starr said, ``There is a very formidable process of hurling
invective at duly constituted law officers. And I think that's bad
for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said White House supporters and the press made a
``carnival atmosphere'' outside the courtroom, obscuring the fact
that his team won nearly all its cases inside the courthouse. He
took obvious satisfaction from last week's announcement by U.S.
District Judge Susan Webber Wright that she had found Clinton in
civil contempt of court for giving false and misleading testimony
in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., if the independent counsel's
office could bring criminal charges against Clinton after he leaves
office, Starr answered, ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not say whether he would recommend such action, which
could become moot if the independent counsel law expires.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, a former U.S. appeals court judge, said his probe and an
earlier investigation of President Reagan both proved how White
House attacks can damage the public standing of an independent
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Starr came under renewed assault by some Democrats on the Senate
panel, which is currently considering whether to renew the
Independent Counsel Act or allow it to die, as is widely expected
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true that you were under merciless attack,'' Sen. Robert
G. Torricelli, D-N.J., told Starr. ``But it was not necessary to
pin a target to your chest on all occasions, either. And to be
fair, you were a contributor to some of your own public demise in
the eyes of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli ticked off a list of accusations against the Starr
probe, and Starr dismissed them as having no basis in fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the issues that have been bruited about the American
public and have come to be accepted as fact are calumnies and
false, absolutely falsehoods,'' he said. He added that some people
had testified before his grand jury and then ``lied to the American
people about what transpired.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said that he was never to blame for the keeping Susan
McDougal, a former Clinton partner in the Arkansas Whitewater real
estate venture, in shackles and in solitary confinement during her
imprisonment for her refusing to testify. That was the
responsibility of the U.S. Marshal Service and Attorney General
Janet Reno, Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   He also dismissed as untrue charges that former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky had her legal rights violated by
prosecutors, and added that his position has already been upheld by
the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Among Starr's other rebuttals:
</P>
<P>
   _ The $46 million cost was so high in part because an
independent counsel office must ``start from scratch'' and cannot
rely on the Justice Department's resources.
</P>
<P>
   _ The probe has been drawn out in large part because of White
House delays. Starr said that the administration has delayed the
process with numerous legal tactics.
</P>
<P>
   _ Despite charges that he has strayed beyond his jurisdiction,
Starr said that he had gone no farther than the attorney general
permitted. He pointed out that Reno had agreed to expanding his
probe to the Lewinsky matter, after she heard tapes indicating a
possible trade of a job for Lewinsky's silence on her sexual
relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Also at the hearing, the senators queried the special
three-judge panel that has the job of appointing independent
counsels.
</P>
<P>
   Under grilling from Democratic senators, U.S. Appeals Court
Judge David B. Sentelle denied that he had conferred with
Republican senators before selecting Starr, an active Republican,
for the post. Sentelle rejected the notion that independent
counsels should have no partisanship and cited Archibald Cox, a
Democrat who was the special Watergate investigator, as a model.
</P>
<P>
   As to complaints that the three-judge panel members remain on
the special panel for too long, Judge Peter J. Fay of the Fifth
Circuit told the senators, ``I had no desire to be reappointed,''
but accepted a new two-year term on the special panel at the
request of the circuit chief judge.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republican presidents had given him two judicial
appointments, he said, ``I'm about as apolitical as you can get.''
</P>
<P>
   The third member of the special panel of judges is Richard D.
Cudahy, a senior circuit judge in the seventh circuit in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
