<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans four pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Serbs say that Nato hit a refugee
convoy Wednesday, killing 75 civilians. NATO says it hit a military
convoy and that Serbs then massacred civilians to make it look as
if NATO had killed them. NATO says it has a videotape that supports
this. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE (Brussels) _ In a diplomatic drive to bring peace
to Kosovo, Germany unveiled a plan Wednesday calling for a one-day
suspension of airstrikes if Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
begins withdrawing troops from the province. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ About 1,000 citizens of
Belgrade came out Wednesday to bury Slavko Curuvija, an independent
publisher assassinated on Sunday. As air raid sirens sounded their
own peculiar dirge through the lime and chestnut trees, his
mourners tried to take courage from one another's public presence _
their refusal to be ntimidated in a troubled time. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BALKANS (Sarajevo, Bosnia) _ A larger look at the role of
NATO bombing and whether it undermines the effort of the U.S. and
its European allies to achieve peace and stability in the Balkans.
By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Military developments on Kosovo
from Washington. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Blace, Macedonia) _ Yugoslav forces in
southeastern Kosovo are accelerating and broadening a campaign of
expelling ethnic Albanians from across southeastern Kosovo,
according to accounts from refugees pouring across the border here
Wednesday. The new wave of attacks, growing food shortages and a
new Serb policy of allowing ethnic Albanians to freely cross the
border here has prompted a flood of refugees. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje, Macedonia) _ Prime Minister Ljubco
Georgievski Wednesday accused Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
of trying to destabilize his country and create ethnic and
religious tension in his southern neighbor. While the world was
focusing on the crisis of the ethnic Albanian refugees flooding
into his country, Georgievski, 33, and prime minister for only five
months, said the political and security dangers threatening his
country were far more serious. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kasaj, Albania) _ A remote and increasingly
dangerous stretch of the mountainous Albanian border with
Yugoslavia was hit Wednesday by Serbian shells and
automatic-weapons fire. NATO has called the series of attacks
provocations. But evidence appeared Wednesday to suggest that the
attacks that have forced dozens of Albanian families to flee are
primarily offensives against the Kosovo Liberation Army, which is
known to cross the border from Albania regularly to attack the
Serbian army. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ President Boris Yeltsin chose Viktor S.
Chernomyrdin, the former prime minister, Wednesday as special envoy
on the Balkans. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VOLUNTEERS-LAW (Washington) _ Looking at the legal
situation of Americans who go to fight in Kosovo. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHILDREN (Geneva) _ Kosovo refugees in northern Albania
are living in dreadful conditions and the situation is especially
difficult for children, who make up two-thirds of the refugees, a
United Nations envoy said today. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
