<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE BEGINS HIS UNDERDOG PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (with trim) 
 
By ALAN BERNSTEIN &HT;    c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   HUNTINGTON, Ind. _ With a few swipes at Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, former Vice President Dan Quayle began his underdog
presidential campaign Wednesday by portraying himself as a
toughened veteran of American ``culture wars'' and foreign policy
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murphy Brown is gone and I'm still here, fighting for the
American family,'' Quayle said at a campaign kick-off rally in the
town where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, his last year as vice president under President Bush,
Quayle said the ``Murphy Brown'' television show wrongly glorified
single motherhood. His remarks triggered a backlash by feminist
leaders and liberal critics. The show, starring Candice Bergen,
went off the air in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``Murphy Brown'' uproar was just one of a series of
controversies that may dog Quayle in the Republican presidential
contest for 2000. His spelling error on the word ``potato,'' for
instance, contributed to his image as an intellectual lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, 52, poked fun at his most famous gaffe. In a criticism
of ``fuzzy'' educational techniques, he said: ``No more creative
spelling, either. I tried that. It doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, a former U.S. senator from Indiana, vowed to press the
issue of moral values, against the advice of ``the Washington
establishment'' and some Republican strategists who consider the
subject divisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``In your hearts you know that prosperity without values is no
prosperity at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fight with the entertainment industry, Quayle said,
``I want to work with pop culture to get them to help us.''
</P>
<P>
   He connected his list of values _ faith, respect,
responsibility, integrity, courage and patriotism _ to President
Clinton's sex-and-lies scandal, saying the nation is ``coming to
the end of a dishonest decade of Bill Clinton and Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle singled out Gore, the likely Democratic nominee, for
calling Clinton a great president immediately after his
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What arrogance. What disdain for the values that parents are
trying to teach their children. What contempt for the rule of
law,'' Quayle said. ``This should not stand.''
</P>
<P>
   As the NATO bombing of Serbian forces in Yugoslavia continued,
Quayle said the foreign policy experience he gained in the Bush
administration, including diplomatic trips to 47 countries, makes
him uniquely prepared to take over the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not need another president who needs on-the-job
training,'' Quayle said. ``You can only get so much from the
briefing books and crash courses. You need experience on day one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, son of the president who picked Quayle as his running
mate, has virtually no foreign policy experience and has hosted
marathon meetings with foreign policy experts as he prepares to
battle Quayle and others for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In another reference to Bush that could also encompass Gore,
Quayle told a packed crowd in his old high school gymnasium that
``the presidency is not something that is inherited. It will not be
bought. It must be earned, and I intend to earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's father was a U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   Bush leads the early presidential polls among Republican voters
and is expected to announce Thursday that he has raised more than
$7 million. Quayle trailed with a little more than $2 million,
which is more than several other GOP contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for comment about Quayle's speech, a spokeswoman for
Bush's exploratory campaign committee said that the governor
congratulates Quayle on the launching of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``will treat other candidates with respect and run a
positive, forward-looking, issue-oriented campaign,'' spokeswoman
Mindy Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   On Quayle's remark about inheriting the presidency, Tucker said
Bush ``recognizes that he has a lot of work to do'' and looks
forward to explaining his ideas to voters across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Most early voter surveys show Quayle in the second tier of
Republican candidates, each with less than 10 percent of the vote
in party primaries while Bush and former American Red Cross
President Elizabeth Hanford Dole soar above.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's strategists said the former vice president will
strengthen his standing with a methodical campaign that capitalizes
on the support of social conservatives impassioned about issues
such as abortion. In that pursuit, Quayle faces competition from
commentator Pat Buchanan, activist Gary Bauer and publisher Steve
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Quayle vowed to force Congress to grant an
across-the-board 30 percent federal income tax cut. Federal budget
surpluses should be returned to the taxpayers rather than used to
shore up government programs for the future, he said. Inheritance
taxes should be eliminated, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, who opposes the use of ground troops in Kosovo and has
criticized the current U.S. role in the bombing attacks on Serbia,
said America should not get involved in ``every civil war around
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   As the newly minted vice presidential nominee, Quayle conducted
a 1988 press conference in Huntington that still echoes in the
history of media relations. Huntington residents and other Quayle
supporters booed and jeered reporters as they asked Quayle whether
he had taken advantage of special connections to join the National
Guard rather than serve in the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Wednesday, Quayle asked his boisterous but polite
audience to erase reporters' bad memories of Huntington. His
supporters responded by turning around toward a line of TV cameras
and cheering.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, born in Indianapolis, moved in 1996 to a suburb of
Phoenix. Taking over from 1996 Republican presidential nominee Bob
Dole, he has been running Campaign for America, a political action
committee that supports Republican candidates and causes.
</P>
<P>
   John Sununu, the former New Hampshire governor who served as
chief of staff of the Bush White House, co-chairs Quayle's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(EDITORS: STORY CAN END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Hill of the Houston area, who worked for Quayle when
Quayle was considering a presidential run in 1996, said the former
vice president's biggest problem is still the jokes and doubts
about Quayle's IQ.
</P>
<P>
   ``In politics it is very difficult to disprove a negative,''
Hill said. ``Dan Quayle could walk to Houston and San Antonio and
chew gum and rub his tummy all the way, and that would not
necessarily dispel what troubles some people about the vice
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Many political activists ``believe that Dan Quayle is damaged
merchandise,'' Hill said. ``He has been so thoroughly spoofed that
it is hard for many Americans to take him seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hill said he expects Quayle to be one of the last
candidates to drop out of the GOP race because he has the backing
of a committed core of conservative voters who think he was
crucified by the news media. ``There is an intensity of support
among his hard-core (supporters) that few other candidates can
imitate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
