</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGES-FISHING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL ALLOWS LIMITED SCALLOP FISHING ON GEORGES BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ Almost five years after they banned most
fishing in large swaths of Georges Bank, regulators agreed
Wednesday to allow hundreds of boats to return this summer to
harvest scallops that have grown fat and abundant since the
closing.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the New England Fishery Management Council
marked the first time it has allowed an increase in fishing in
5,000 square miles of closed areas since they were created in 1994
in a desperate bid to stop the depletion of cod and other fish
populations on and near Georges Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But regulators, fearful that the scallop boats could harm the
flounder and other fish that are still recovering from years of
overfishing, attached so many limits to the re-opening that some
scallopers were angry. At most, scallopers will be allowed to
harvest only one quarter as many scallops as they had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost as if you're inviting us not to go into the closed
area,'' said Debra Shrader, a scallopers' wife active in the
fishing advocacy group Shore Support. ``You're not giving us
anything in trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists were unhappy at the reopening of so-called
``closed area 2,'' also, arguing that the council was buckling to
political pressure from the scallop industry rather than finishing
the job of rebuilding the historic Georges Bank fishing ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``There remain a great deal of important unanswered questions .
. . I believe that we are moving too quickly,'' said Doug Hopkins
of the Environmental Defense Fund, the only professional
environmentalist on the Fishery Management Council, and the lone
vote against major provisions of the fishing plan.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's vote had been closely watched after US Commerce
Secretary William Daley _ who has veto power over the management
council _ urged the 17-member panel to consider allowing scalloping
in parts of the closed areas by June 15. As a result, the council
agreed to consider the idea rather than waiting until at least
March of 2000 as originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   Daley's letter to the council, written at the urging of US
Senator Edward Kennedy and US Representative Barney Frank,
politicized what had been an emerging success story on Georges
Bank: the recovery of scallops after just a few years relief from
fishing. Research last fall showed that the shellfish were eight to
20 times more abundant in closed areas than in open scalloping
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   But the fishing research also conluded that scallop boats might
catch almost as many yellowtail flounders as scallops in their
heavy chainlink dredges. Unlike the scallops, the yellowtails are
still at least five years away from reaching a population that
biologists believe can sustain normal fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's this going to do to me?'' asked Rodney Avila of New
Bedford, Mass., who fishes for yellowtail flounders, at Wednesday's
meeting. He said he was worried that, after years of sacrifice,
flounder fishermen could face more fishing limits because the
scallop boats accidentally caught so many flounder.
</P>
<P>
   Scallopers promised that they could greatly reduce the
unintentional catch of flounder, monkfish and other species _
called ``bycatch'' _ by increasing the size of holes in nets or
towing their equipment more slowly so that fish can escape.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fishery Management Council was taking few chances,
allowing each scalloper only three visits to closed area 2 for
30,000 pounds of scallop meat rather than the 12 trips for 120,000
pounds that the lead industry group, the Fisheries Survival Fund,
had wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, the scallopers will only get to harvest their
scallops if they make good on pledges to reduce bycatch. The
National Marine Fisheries Service will close the area once
scallopers catch a relatively small amount of flounder.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the council created a 3,000 square-mile buffer zone
around the portion of area 2 that will be re-opened to prevent
scallopers from cheating. Members had feared that dishonest boat
captains might offload their catch to boats waiting just outside
the restricted zone so that they could exceed the fishing limits.
</P>
<P>
   As a further deterrent to cheating, council members called for
paid observers to be posted on at least one in four scallop boats
going to the closed area this summer. Given the limited federal
funding for observers, some fishermen feared that this provision
alone could sink the entire reopening plan.
</P>
<P>
   Encumbered by all these conditions, scallop fishermen Wednesday
grumbled that the re-opened scallop grounds would not be the
economic shot in the arm they had hoped for. However, other
industry advocates said even a limited opening of the so-called
``closed area 2'' could pave the way for wider re-openings in
closed fishing grounds off the New England coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as a step forward, but we could do a lot better,''
said Fisheries Survival Fund consultant Ronald Smolowitz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
