</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEGINNING15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE 'BIG BANG': COSMOLOGY OR JUST 'SPECULATION?'
 &HT;    With BEGINNING-MOVIE.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Physicists and religious scholars brought their
different views of reality to a symposium on the origin of the
universe Wednesday, then went home unable to agree on enough to
even disagree on much.
</P>
<P>
   The nearest thing to a debate in a daylong exchange of views on
whether the universe is a place designed by a creator or the result
of a randomly occurring ``Big Bang'' was between two physicists.
</P>
<P>
   The models described by Alan Guth of the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology and Neil Turok of Cambridge University in England
differed in fundamental concepts of time and space.
</P>
<P>
   Turok, an associate of English cosmologist Stephen Hawking,
spoke of Hawking's hypothesized ``imaginary time'' and said six
extra dimensions of space-time may be necessary to explain the
development of the expanding universe from a minute
``instanton(cq).''
</P>
<P>
   Guth, the originator of the concept of ``inflation'' of matter
and space, described a different process, originating with the
instantaneous explosion of the infinitely small ``singularity'' at
which the Big Bang is thought to have occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions took up the first of three days of exchanges
between cosmologists, who have been increasingly excited by
accumulating discoveries of the past several years, and
theologians. The symposium is being sponsored by the American
Association for the Advancement of Science.
</P>
<P>
   Hindu philosopher Anindita Baslev of Aarhus University in
Denmark dismissed the discussions of Big Bang mechanics as
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not is reaped which has not been sown,'' she declared, quoting
from the ancient texts of her religion, which holds the universe is
eternal, without beginning or end. ``The origin of an event is
inconceivable without depending on a cause.''
</P>
<P>
   She called the Big Bang theories ``cosmological speculations.''
</P>
<P>
   But Guth said that with new observations from space-based
scientific instruments and improved understanding of the mysterious
quantum behavior of subatomic particles, it appears that the
``concept of cause and effect is not as strong as it used.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the term ``Big Bang'' does not accurately describe
the theories of cosmological inflation that most astrophysicists
accept today. In fact, ``Big Bang'' was originally coined by an
opponent of the theory in an effort to ridicule it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not attempt to describe what banged or why it banged
or what happened before it banged,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Faber, professor of astronomy and astrophysics at the
University of California, Santa Cruz, said she drew no data from
religious thought in her pursuit of physical explanations of the
universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here in a service role,'' she said. ``Cosmologies are
facts. I'm here to help communicate what science has to say about
what really happened and to describe the limits of what it can say
about what really happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert John Russell, a physicist who founded the Center for
Theology and the Natural Sciences at Berkeley University's Graduate
Theological Union, said it is not possible to separate physics from
philosophy or morality.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't pick up a physics textbook and not find it filled
with philosophy and morality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
