</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE WAR, KOSOVO WILL NEED A MARSHALL PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 18) , (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEESBURG, Va. _ It is a long way from the relative tranquility
of this historic town at the foot of the Blue Ridge mountains to
the devastation and tragedy on the plains and in the valleys of
Kosovo and its neighboring lands.
</P>
<P>
   But it is easy to imagine that Leesburg's most illustrious
resident of the past, Gen. George C. Marshall, would recognize the
hunger, disruption of lives, destruction of homes and businesses
and the illness and death of helpless refugees as a familiar sight.
</P>
<P>
   In microcosm, they replicate the tragic plight of war-battered
Europe that lay before Marshall's eyes in 1947 and that spurred him
to create the most benevolent program ever devised by one country
to aid other countries, including those it had defeated on the
battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Today's situation differs in many ways. When Marshall proposed
the plan that was to bear his name, he had just attended a lengthy,
often acrimonious meeting in Moscow at which Soviet leader Josef
Stalin repeatedly demonstrated his belligerence toward America and
the democracies of Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Adolf Hitler and Benito Mussolini, the tyrants who
had ignited World War II and its horrors in Europe, were dead, and
there was no one to interfere with the rescue of their stricken
countries, Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Although isolationism is not yet dead in the United States, it
is less a power than in the 1940s when many Americans, including
congressional leaders, were in the grip of xenophobia.
</P>
<P>
   But there are parallels between today and yesterday. Yugoslav
President Slobadan Milosovec's cruel policy of driving Albanians
from their homes is not far removed from Hitler's treacherous
treatment of the Jews. The catastrophe now engulfing the Kosovars
is similar to the one that destroyed lives and livelihood in Europe
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In the beleaguered Kosovo, we may foresee a period in which its
people will require the kind of assistance that the Marshall Plan
extended to Western Europe a half century ago.
</P>
<P>
   That concept was discussed last week at the NATO foreign
ministers' conference in Brussels, where attention also focused on
the hope of making Russia, a longime Yugoslavia ally, part of the
peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, the Cold War was on everyone's mind when Marshall, the
former World War II Army chief of staff who had become Harry
Truman's secretary of state, first proposed his plan for the
recovery of Europe. But still, he suggested that the Soviet Union
be included in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy is not directed against any country or doctrine but
against hunger, poverty, desperation and chaos,'' Marshall declared
at Harvard University on June 5 of that year. ``Its purpose shall
be the revival of a working economy in the world so as to permit
the emergence of political and social conditions in which free
institutions can exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Stalin agreed to accept American assistance in rebuilding
the Soviet economy, the world would have been a far different place
and wars in Korea and Vietnam might have been averted. But the
stubborn Soviet despot rejected participation in the Marshall Plan.
</P>
<P>
   In preparing his initiative, Marshall called on a remarkable
group of so-called ``wise men, including Dean Acheson, Robert
Lovett, George Kennan, Charles Bohlen and Will Clayton. Henry
Stimson, the grand old man of the Republican Party, who had served
in the Cabinets of several presidents, headed the national
committee to sell the Marshall Plan to the American people. Leading
the group's executive committee was former Secretary of War Robert
Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Truman decreed that the plan should bear Marshall's name rather
than his own. In his memoirs, Truman described Marshall, who later
won the Nobel Peace Prize, as the ``greatest living American'' and
declared: ``The Marshall Plan will go down in history as one of
America's greatest contributions to the peace of the world.'' He
was right.
</P>
<P>
   But the whole magnificent project might have failed in the
GOP-dominated 80th Congress had it not been for Michigan Sen.
Arthur Vandenberg, a pre-war isolationist who as chairman of the
Foreign Relations Committee who was able to persuade his fellow
Republicans to approve the $13.4 billion, four-year European
recovery plan.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall wisely urged that the initiative come from the European
countries themselves.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that the role of the United States should consist
of friendly aid in the drafting of a European program and of later
support of such a program as far as it may be practical for us to
do so.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, with a lot of hard work and bold leadership, the job was
accomplished. Until Milosovec began acting like the brutal
dictators of the past, Europe had lived in peace for an
unprecedented half century.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Leesburg, a visitor is shocked by the disrepair of
Dodona Manor, the once-stately house that was Marshall's home from
1941 until his death in 1959. Yet restoration has begun, and one
day it will gleam with renewed elegance.
</P>
<P>
   But even in its run-down condition, the house possesses some
furnishings and artifacts that stir the imagination. They recall
the greatness of the man who lived here and the fact that his
vision of 52 years ago remains pertinent and vital to the
well-being of Europe and the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
