<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ZHU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE LEADER ENDS US TOUR ON A JOCULAR NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ As President Clinton's administration revived
efforts to bring China into the World Trade Organization, Chinese
premier Zhu Rongji concluded his nine-day US sojourn Wednesday with
a quip-filled visit to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
and a Boston business lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu told Americans not to ``make such a big deal'' about their
roughly $50 billion annual trade deficit with China, calling it
relatively small and beneficial to both countries' prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   While hundreds of people picketed Zhu at both events and burned
flags to denounce China's repression of Tibetans and dissidents and
policy toward Taiwan, Zhu continued to work on projecting the image
of a younger, optimistic, more open Chinese leadership that even
has a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is not an adversary, let alone enemy, of the United
States, China is your trustworthy friend,'' said Zhu, 68, an
electrical engineer and former Shanghai mayor who is the nation's
third-ranking leader. ``China will never be a threat to the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking through translators to more than 1,200 people at MIT,
Zhu used one-liners in an attempt to deflect tensions over issues
such as alleged illegal Chinese contributions to President
Clinton's re-election campaign, military espionage and piracy of
copyrighted music and movies. He called them ``passing clouds'' in
otherwise increasingly sunny US-Chinese relations.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu noted that when he attended graduate school in China in the
late 1940s, many of his textbooks were photocopies of MIT books,
but he added, ``Whether they were pirated or not, I do not know.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhu recalled a conversation with MIT president Charles M. Vest
about astronomers ``probing the secrets of the universe,'' and
said, ``I was so afraid of the word `secrets' because that reminded
me of espionage'' and allegations that Chinese spies have stolen
sensitive US nuclear and military data.
</P>
<P>
   And in one of a half-dozen times he broke into English, Zhu
urged US business school graduates to apply for deanships opening
up at three new Chinese accounting academies being organized with
help from US Big Five accounting firms. ``I promise: I will pay
what you are paid here,'' Zhu said in lightly accented English.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu's visit to the US appeared to fail in its major aim when
Clinton made a last-minute decision last week to abort a deal to
bring China into the World Trade Organization. That would have
given China more influence over global trade in exchange for what
Zhu called ``major concessions'' on opening its 1.2 billion-member
market to foreign goods.
</P>
<P>
   However, facing criticism from business and congressional
leaders, Clinton late on Tuesday announced he wanted to resume
negotiations and get China into the trade group this year.
Clinton's move was widely perceived as an effort to bolster Zhu's
standing with Chinese leaders because he is seen as a pragmatic
reformer among the Communist leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu expressed regret that his trip has led only to agreements so
far on US agricultural exports to China. ``Can the Chinese people
live only on citrus and wheat? Yes, we can, but we want to live
better,'' Zhu said, urging the United States to lift bans on
exporting weather satellites and computers.
</P>
<P>
   But at stops that included two speeches to farmers and visits to
the Denver Broncos football training camp and a Chicago commodity
training floor, Zhu's affability has by most accounts scored points
for China. He told Boston business leaders he saw a marked drop in
hostility to China during his trip.
</P>
<P>
   At MIT, Zhu took three questions, one from Edward Wang, a
27-year-old MIT computer science graduate student who asked when
China would release Xu Wenli, a Beijing democracy activist already
jailed for 12 years who has been sentenced to another 13 years for
trying to organize a democratic political party.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu said he had talked so much about human rights on his US trip
``that I practically have blisters in my mouth. Human rights in
China have been improving from one day to the next. . . . We accept
that we still have shortcomings, and these shortcomings are ones we
are still working hard to address.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Xu, whose daughter attends Boston University, Zhu
said Wednesday's speech was ``not the time or place for me to go
into details.'' Wang said later he ``sort of expected'' an indirect
answer but was pleased to have a chance to keep pressure on to free
Xu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
