<HEADLINE>
KING COUNTY EMPLOYEE WORKS FROM HOME, IN FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NEIL MODIE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Lots of people, including a lot of bureaucrats,
telecommute these days. But few local government workers do it from
as far away as Patricia Terrell does.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell, a King County employee since 1994, has an office and a
desk at the county's Boeing Field, where she is the lease manager.
But she does most of her work from home.
</P>
<P>
   For Terrell, home is 3,000 miles away, in the Florida seaside
community of Port Orange, a suburb of Daytona Beach.
</P>
<P>
   That's where she and her husband, John Terrell, bought a house
last November and registered to vote in December, after selling
their condominium in Bellevue, Wash, a suburb of Seattle. But at
the behest of her superiors, she's still a King County employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize it's peculiar,'' Cynthia Stewart, the airport
manager, admitted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart said county managers have tried unsuccessfully to
find someone with Terrell's background in commercial property
management to replace her. At the same time, the airport is in the
middle of some complicated lease negotiations and an arbitration
proceeding that Terrell has been handling.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had to move to Florida for personal reasons and we were
just over a barrel, so we asked her if she would help us out this
way,'' Stewart said. ``Believe me, we were desperate, and she is a
very conscientious, hard worker.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said the Terrells moved to Florida to care for John
Terrell's ailing, elderly mother after he retired from his real
estate job.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Terrell flies to Seattle _ at her own expense _ to work
here about a week to 10 days each month, Stewart said. The
bicoastal employee worked full time at her $42,636-a-year job until
Jan. 1, and has worked about half time since then.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell would be hard pressed to find a more receptive local
government to telecommuting than King County's. County Executive
Ron Sims is a passionate advocate of telecommuting, e-mail, the
Internet and techno-everything.
</P>
<P>
   Sims said Tuesday that he does probably one-third of his job by
computer, much of it from home during off hours, and sees nothing
wrong with Terrell's arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Letting county employees telecommute ``is difficult for
supervisors because they know you're working, but they don't see
you,'' Sims said. ``But you have to ask: Does a person work any
better because they're in front of you?... If a body of work is
being done and you can look at the body of work'' to confirm it,
then it's OK, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sims said King County is looking for opportunities to let select
employees telecommute ``because it's a commuter reduction, a
congestion reduction strategy, and it appears to be the wave of the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said she wouldn't have approved Terrell's telecommuting
arrangement ``unless I could see evidence of her work, and in her
case I can see the evidence of her work.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrell, reached by telephone at her Florida home Tuesday,
referred most questions to Stewart. But she noted that King County
``allows people to telecommute for maternity leaves and other
unusual situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Clancy, the county's leasing supervisor and Terrell's
immediate superior, said the county hasn't found an equally
qualified person to replace her because the salary for the position
can't compete with the private market. And Terrell's job is of
limited duration, to be merged with another lease-managing position
a few months from now.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy admitted that the distance of Terrell's telecommute is
unusual. But having her across the country, he said, isn't much
different electronically than from having her across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when I e-mail her from here, when it's 5 o'clock here
and 8 o'clock there, I get an immediate response,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
