<SLUG> BC-KIDS:WRESTLING-art-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S ALL THE RUMBLE ABOUT PRO WRESTLING? 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Includes one color slide of WCW wrestler Bill Goldberg. (Credit:
Courtesy of Tiger Electronics.) 
 KELLY DEGARMO 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its lively action, wicked characters and twisted humor,
professional wrestling ranks as one of the hottest spectator sports
among boys. But a new study suggests it contains more obscene
gestures and sexual messages than actual wrestling moves, reports
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   One of the sport's heroes, Stone Cold Steve Austin, rose to the
top by glamorizing foul language and flipping his middle finger.
His official WWF site on the Internet reveals it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm basically just a redneck from Texas who worked his way up
from the loading docks,'' Austin told CLASS ACTS.
</P>
<P>
   Young wrestling fans admit the sport is sometimes gross, even
fake _ but still amusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't watch it because we think it's real, we watch because
it's fun and entertaining,'' student Jay Key told CLASS ACTS. ``We
know shows like ``Seinfeld'' and ``ER'' aren't real either, but we
watch them, too.''
</P>
<P>
   RATINGS ROCK
</P>
<P>
   Ratings of cable USA's ``WWF RAW Is War'' and TNT's ``WCW Monday
Nitro'' are up nearly 40 percent from last year. (WWF stands for
World Wrestling Federation and WCW-nWo is World Championship
Wrestling _ New World Order.) Last week's issue of TV Guide reveals
that the programs are extremely popular among viewers in part
because of the edgy pranks. Ratings indicate 24 percent of WCW
viewers are between the ages of 2 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   Youths say they like the actions and personalities of the
wrestlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pro wrestling is fun to watch because you never know what is
going to happen next,'' said Tommy Chenault, 10, a student. ``For
example, on `Massacre' during February, Stone Cold was facing
Vincent McMahon in the Steel Cage fight. Paul White, known as the
Giant, came and threw Stone Cold through the steel cage and broke
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some of his buddies, Tommy doesn't control the TV remote.
His parents closely monitor what he watches. Although a fan, he
admits the sport can get a little gross to watch, especially when
the ``Undertaker'' starts his bloodbath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, if they go too far, it's kind of sick to watch,''
Tommy said.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy's mom, Cindi Chenault, a substitute teacher, said the
sport is influencing young boys. There's a lot of mimicking of the
wrestlers' behavior, such as grabbing private parts and doing choke
holds around the neck, she said. She suggests youths talk to their
parents about the wrestlers' behavior, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   TOO OBSCENE?
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by Indiana University, commissioned by ``Inside
Edition,'' of 50 ``WWF Raw'' episodes last year on the USA network
turned up a staggering number of profane incidents, AP reports. WWF
places a parental warning on ``WWF Raw.''
</P>
<P>
   The study's researchers counted instances of characters grabbing
their crotches and making obscene and sexual gestures. One segment
featured a satanic activity in which people supposedly drained
blood from a ``dead'' wrestler and drank it.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestlers are constantly being struck by objects like garbage
cans or night sticks, said Indiana University Professor Walter
Gantz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow they manage not to hurt each other,'' Gantz said.
``I'm not certain that a 10-year-old realizes that they are skilled
at doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy disagrees. He said he and his friends know the moves are
fake and therefore the violence doesn't seem so bad. ``It's violent
but not that violent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   VIEWPOINT: WHAT IS THE ATTRACTION TO WRESTLING?
</P>
<P>
   It may be fake, but there's no denying the popularity of
wrestling. CLASS ACTS asked readers, ``What is the attraction to
wrestling and why is it so much fun to watch?''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the responses:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people watch wrestling not just for the matches, but
for the way the characters interact with each other and the story
behind each character,'' said middle school student Rob Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like wrestling because it's fast-paced and exciting. And I
like the Undertaker because of his moves,'' elementary school
student Craig Souder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really watch or like wrestling, because I believe it's
just actors portraying angry men who just got out of jail or
something. But most ofmy family watches it and I think I know what
attracts them to WWF. You have your roaring crowds, your big
`heroes' of the arena, your bright lights and the promise of a
fight,'' said Allie Bolton, elementary school student.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think kids watch wrestling because it has violence, like
fighting, and kids like violence ... They watch it to be cool, like
if that person hears other kids talk about wrestling, they'll start
watching to try to fit in,'' said David Smith Jr., elementary
school student.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite tag-team wrestlers are the New Age Outlaws. They
are really cool. Sometimes they will get aggressive, too, and they
are funny ... There is one person who gets real crazy and he is my
favorite wrestler. His name is Stone Cold Steve Austin. When the
manager gets Steve mad, he will get anything he can in his hands
and will use it to hurt the manager,'' Rafael Vazquez, middle
school student, told CLASS ACTS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started watching it with my brother for one reason _ those
guys from Generation X are really cute,'' added high school student
Meagan Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   But high school student Jennifer Leatherwood admitted ``I don't
watch it. It's too fake for me.''
</P>
<P>
