<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:MOVIES:EDtv-art-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
 
 MOVIE REVIEW: ``EDtv''  World rights. 
 Includes one color slide of of Matthew McConaughey in a scene from
the movie ``EDtv.'' (Credit: 1998 Walt Disney Pictures.) 
 By THANE TUTTLE 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``EDtv''
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Matthew McConaughey, Jenna Elfman, Woody Harrelson,
Sally Kirkland, Martin Landau, Ellen DeGeneres, Rob Reiner, Dennis
Hopper and Elizabeth Hurley.
</P>
<P>
   Plot: Ed (McConaughey) is selected by a floundering network,
TrueTV, to have his life filmed live. Although he starts off
slowly, Ed soon becomes involved with his brother's girlfriend.
While this does increase Ed's ratings, it sets him at odds with the
rest of his family. Now, Ed must deal with both his family's
resentment and his new girlfriend's growing dislike of cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Although ``EDtv'' is very similar to ``The Truman
Show'' in both concept and execution, it differs from ``Truman'' in
its focus. While ``The Truman Show'' is about a man finding out
that his life is being filmed, ``EDtv'' is about a man who has to
deal with his new-found fame.
</P>
<P>
   Director Ron Howard gets the film off to a rocky start, but
after the first 15 minutes, the film becomes genuinely funny.
Nearly all of the jokes are good, but some may be too mature for
younger audiences. The most annoying thing about the movie is the
all-too-frequent use of Pepsi advertisements. There are frequent
close-ups of Pepsi cans and machines. And at one point, Ed even
says that he prefers Pepsi to Coke.
</P>
<P>
   Reason for rating: The PG-13 rating is for language, partial
nudity, and blatant innuendo.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewer's 1 - 10 score: 8.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
