<HEADLINE>
A BRIEF LOOK AT THE NEWS 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 c. 1999 Compiled from reports by The Associated Press and Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHERE'S THE FORCE WHEN YOU REALLY NEED IT?
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ Ewan McGregor says playing young Obi-Wan Kenobi in the
new ``Star Wars'' movie wasn't all swords and special effects.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the filming was ``the epitome of tedium,'' the
28-year-old Scottish actor admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work was so complex with all the special effects and stuff
that I found myself hanging around for days,'' he said. ``I was
frowning a lot. It became just a frowning exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   The George Lucas-directed movie, ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace,'' is the first installment in the much-anticipated
three-part prequel to the blockbuster space trilogy. It comes out
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Boredom didn't stop McGregor from signing up for the two other
``Star Wars'' movies, which are to be completed by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm just an actor who can't say no. Besides, there's
nothing cooler than being a Jedi knight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NO BUTTS ABOUT IT, YOUNG MORE VULNERABLE TO SMOKE DAMAGE
</P>
<P>
   Even if teen-agers who smoke quit as adults, they may inflict on
themselves long-lasting damage that can put them at high risk for
lung cancer later on, new research shows.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have known that tobacco smoke's brew of
cancer-causing chemicals latches on to the genetic material DNA,
forming compounds called adducts, which set the stage for cancer.
Now a study suggests that young smokers may be more susceptible to
this chemical damage.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at lung tissue from 143 lung-cancer patients,
researchers found that among 79 ex-smokers, those who picked up the
habit as teen-agers had more DNA adducts in their tissue than did
ex-smokers who had started later in life.
</P>
<P>
   This study's evidence may also aid in convincing kids never to
take up smoking, said Dr. Alex Prokhorov, a behavioral scientist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge to find some meaningful message threvents
kids from smoking,'' he said. ``They don't see immediate effects of
smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   STUDENTS WILL MIND THE STORE
</P>
<P>
   GRANDVILLE, Mich. _ When students in three western Michigan
school districts talk about the school store, they don't mean a
closet stocked with pencils, erasers and notebook paper.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it's a ``laboratory,'' soon to open in a shopping mall,
that will teach retailing skills that can be used after graduation.
Backers say it may be the first mall store run by students in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Together with General Growth Properties Inc. based in Chicago,
60 students in grades 6-12 will design, market, stock and staff the
store to be known as ``School Spirit!!!''
</P>
<P>
   The 1,118-square-foot store will look like any other sportswear
retailer, except that sweatshirts and baseball caps will bear
school logos and the staff will work for school credit and minimum
wage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
