<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8363 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-0415-CO     04-14 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-0415-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EXPERTS: WINDOW TO DEPLOY GROUND TROOPS IN KOSOVO CLOSING
 &HT;    500&AMP;add
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0415; KOSOVO-STRIKES-0415.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The enormous human crisis building in Kosovo with
hundreds of thousands of Kosovar Albanians hiding in forests from
Serb forces is pressing the issue of sending ground troops into a
matter of grave urgency, a group of military and foreign policy
experts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the White House on Wednesday dismissed a question about
President Clinton's plans for ground forces with a blunt ``he still
has none,'' some experts fear there's no time left to think about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principal reason for not waiting,'' said Richard N.
Haass(CQ), director of foreign policy studies at the Brookings
Institution, ``is not simply that the Serbs might be digging in...
but it's the plight of the internally displaced. At some point I
want to make sure there are some Kosovars left to save.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress agreed earlier this week to postpone a debate on the
issue, but the White House and NATO continue to emphasize the value
in letting weeks of bombing accumulate on Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic as a way to get him out.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea summarized the strategy
this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in a situation where the correlation of forces
is turning to NATO's advantage with every passing day because every
day Milosevic has less, and every day we have more.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, the alliance acknowledges that it has no
solution for the riddle of how to feed scores of stranded, starving
ethnic Albanian refugees while it wages its campaign of gradual
degradation of the Serb military.
</P>
<P>
   ``A war of attrition does nothing to protect the people whose
lives and welfare are at stake,'' Haass said. ``The assumption (of
the air campaign) is time is not a factor, and I just don't think
that assumption is accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the equation is the physical reality that a call to
deploy troops into Kosovo would take weeks to execute, as evidenced
by the recent experience with NATO's request for 24 Apache
helicopters from the U.S. Army. The helicopters, and their massive
support structure of personnel, are expected to arrive in the
Balkans at the end of this week, more than two weeks after NATO
first sought them.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in Desert Storm, which was preceded by a lengthy build-up
of forces called Desert Shield, the United States would have to
start nearly from scratch to assemble a decisive force to
participate in the liberation of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Vickers, who studies military issues at the Center for
Strategic and Budgetary Assessment, said he thinks the United
States will need to commit 80,000 troops to help NATO retake enough
of Kosovo to save the lives of those trapped in its forests. And he
estimates that it'll take up to three months to get them into
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the question is, 'Could we sustain the air campaign for
that long?'' Vickers said. ``There are no short answers.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add begins.)
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said they last reviewed the potential need
for ground forces late last summer, when diplomats were crafting a
peace plan that included an international peace-keeping force. That
``assessment'' hasn't been updated since NATO went to war with
Belgrade, Serb forces flushed Kosovar Albanians out and untold
thousands ended up stranded in the wilderness without access to
food or shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I'm not too interested in whether they have plans,
they know how to deploy forces,'' said Michael E. O'Hanlon, who is
a military analyst, also at Brookings. ``We know how to move fast,
the question is do we do it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon believes the U.S. could deliver a single brigade, about
4,000 troops, in a week to meet up with 12,000 NATO troops already
in Macedonia and another 4,000 U.S. Marines on ships in nearby
waters. Also, U.S. and NATO bases in Germany could provide
additional troops to create a large force in short order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think weeks is the way to think about the first (group),''
he said. ``You may be able to start to put people into Kosovo in a
couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   But there remains the matter of when to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should deploy immediately,'' O'Hanlon said. ``Deploy forces
to Italy immediately to have them ready. We shouldn't waste any
more time on that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
