helicopters from the U.S. Army. The helicopters, and their massive
support structure of personnel, are expected to arrive in the
Balkans at the end of this week, more than two weeks after NATO
first sought them.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in Desert Storm, which was preceded by a lengthy build-up
of forces called Desert Shield, the United States would have to
start nearly from scratch to assemble a decisive force to
participate in the liberation of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Vickers, who studies military issues at the Center for
Strategic and Budgetary Assessment, said he thinks the United
States will need to commit 80,000 troops to help NATO retake enough
of Kosovo to save the lives of those trapped in its forests. And he
estimates that it'll take up to three months to get them into
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the question is, 'Could we sustain the air campaign for
that long?'' Vickers said. ``There are no short answers.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add begins.)
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said they last reviewed the potential need
for ground forces late last summer, when diplomats were crafting a
peace plan that included an international peace-keeping force. That
``assessment'' hasn't been updated since NATO went to war with
Belgrade, Serb forces flushed Kosovar Albanians out and untold
thousands ended up stranded in the wilderness without access to
food or shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I'm not too interested in whether they have plans,
they know how to deploy forces,'' said Michael E. O'Hanlon, who is
a military analyst, also at Brookings. ``We know how to move fast,
the question is do we do it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon believes the U.S. could deliver a single brigade, about
4,000 troops, in a week to meet up with 12,000 NATO troops already
in Macedonia and another 4,000 U.S. Marines on ships in nearby
waters. Also, U.S. and NATO bases in Germany could provide
additional troops to create a large force in short order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think weeks is the way to think about the first (group),''
he said. ``You may be able to start to put people into Kosovo in a
couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   But there remains the matter of when to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should deploy immediately,'' O'Hanlon said. ``Deploy forces
to Italy immediately to have them ready. We shouldn't waste any
more time on that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
