<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTORNEY-DRUGS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD COMES CRASHING DOWN ON FORMER PROSECUTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Will Miller, a former prosecutor who now faces five
felony drug charges, has a pretty good idea what the future holds.
And it makes him shudder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to prison; I know that,'' Miller said from the
kitchen table of his Seattle home yesterday. ``I will probably lose
my house, and I will probably lose my job. I know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller fell from being a well-respected prosecutor to, by his
own admission, a drug addict who spent every dime he could raise to
pump methamphetamine into his veins. But even after he righted
himself and began a new career as a defense attorney, a mixture of
drugs, love and stupidity pulled him back down.
</P>
<P>
   The end announced itself with the pounding on his front door in
February. King County narcotics officers broke in to arrest him,
culminating an investigation in which Miller sold drugs to an
undercover agent three times.
</P>
<P>
   He admits that he sold the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all my fault,'' he said Tuesday in his first interview
since he was charged.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably not smart to grant an interview, he concedes.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller, who put criminals away for 10 years in New York,
then Seattle, said he wants to counter what he sees as a campaign
against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of getting smeared, my name and my reputation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And he complained that he was set up, then denied a plea deal
most people in his situation would get.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like they've gone out of their way to take me down,''
Miller, 37, said during an interview in which he frequently broke
down into tears.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Canova, the state assistant attorney general who is
prosecuting Miller, could not comment on the details of the case.
But he denied that he had treated Miller unfairly or that he is
harshly prosecuting Miller because of publicity Canova got last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Those news reports came after an initial investigation ended
with Canova deciding not to charge Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Miller faces more than 10 years in prison if convicted.
The best Canova has offered him is a deal of four years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is out of money and about to default on his mortgage. His
telephone has been turned off, and his legal problems have all but
dried up his business prospects. So the only lawyer he can afford
is himself.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Douglas Willas Miller stood on the other side of the
law. He spent one internship away from Duke University Law School
at the district attorney's office in Brooklyn, working homicides.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was hooked. It was a job where you followed the truth, he
said. Guilty people were prosecuted; the innocent were set free.
</P>
<P>
   From 1988 to 1995, he was a full-time prosecutor in New York,
working sex crimes in Brooklyn, then Queens. He was good at his
job, from press reports and according to spokesmen at those
offices.
</P>
<P>
   His life was so charmed that he even escaped a bullet.
</P>
<P>
   A mugger shot at him on a Brooklyn street 1991, but the bullet
only grazed his head. The New York Post proclaimed him ``Miracle
Man!'' worthy of its front page. Miller keeps a framed copy in his
home.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn by the beauty of Seattle, Miller went to work for the King
County Prosecutor's Office in 1995. He gave up his seniority in New
York and started over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I did was win cases,'' he said. By his count, 16
of 17 King County juries gave him convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was different in polite Seattle. He didn't mind
confrontation in the courtroom. He was open about his sexuality,
too, he said, talking about the men in his life.
</P>
<P>
   One he met was Jeff Vinson. By September, the two moved in
together, and in November, Miller filed with the county to make
Vinson his domestic partner, eligible for his health benefits.
Miller still calls Vinson his spouse.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1997, Miller moved into a new position,
supervising new prosecutors in misdemeanor courts. He also began
snorting methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson, who would later lead narcotics officers to Miller, liked
to stay out all night, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller existed on three or four hours of sleep a night, and then
went to work, he said. And he used methamphetamine four times a
week.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his career, he began showing up late for
work.
</P>
<P>
   One time was on the morning of March 2, 1998. A call from
Miller's secretary woke him at 10 a.m. In a rush, he grabbed his
briefcase and art case _ Miller sketched in the courtroom _ and
left. A search of the art case by courthouse security turned up a
scale, a drug pipe and a small amount of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the items belonged to Vinson. And his lover backed
him up. But the damage was done. Miller resigned as a prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started shooting up the day after I resigned. I had a
nervous breakdown. I didn't know what I was doing with my life,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He went to work as a defense lawyer. He stopped injecting drugs,
but still used them, he said. He ordered Vinson out of his house.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, an investigation in the courthouse incident
continued. The case was turned over to Canova to avoid an
appearance of a conflict of interest inside the King County
Prosecutor's Office.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Canova decided not to prosecute.
</P>
<P>
   That decision met with some critical press reports. Canova
himself had been an unsuccessful candidate for the Washington
Supreme Court that year.
</P>
<P>
   Canova and the criminal justice system had a score to settle,
Miller contends. Canova, he asserts, made him a ``whipping boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Canova flatly denies that he is prosecuting Miller in response
to bad press or to further his political career.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, Vinson contacted a King County
detective around the start of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson contended that Miller was dealing drugs, which Miller
denies. And Vinson said the statement that he had made about the
courthouse incident in March 1998 was false.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said Vinson called him three times, asking him to sell
methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   Canova said he cannot comment on any of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In January and February, Miller sold drugs to the undercover
officer three times. Then came the raid on his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I realized it was the police,'' Miller said, ``I knew it
was all over.''
</P>
<P>
   The drug use stopped that day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now Miller's only defense is to claim entrapment. That will
require finding Vinson, whose whereabouts are unknown to Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Canova said Miller can question Vinson through the normal legal
channels.
</P>
<P>
   What Miller wants is a lesser sentence than Canova is willing to
recommend. That would allow the former prosecutor to go to a work
ethic camp instead of the harsher environment of a prison.
</P>
<P>
   Canova said he cannot discuss plea offers.
</P>
<P>
   If he can't get a deal to his liking, Miller said he will ask a
judge to remove Canova for what he contends are unethical and
immoral actions, then ask for a change of venue. In a new locale,
he said, he might get a better offer.
</P>
<P>
   But to the veteran prosecutor, the outcome doesn't seem much in
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was stupid,'' he said, ``and I will go to prison for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
