<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMINEM-RAPPER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIP-HOP STAR EMINEM'S LYRICS ARE ANYTHING BUT VANILLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``My name is ... my name is ... my name is ... Slim Shady.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? Ought to. These days, ``My Name Is,'' the
flagship single of Detroit rapper Eminem's debut CD, ``The Slim
Shady LP,'' is, almost literally, anywhere there's radio waves.
</P>
<P>
   Tune in a pop station, or an alternative-rock station, or a
modern R&AMP;B station, and ``there he is again,'' this crazy white boy
with the nasty mouth whom nobody had ever heard of as recently as
Christmas. He's rapping about impregnating a Spice Girl, driving
drunk, smacking his English teacher, finding out that his mom does
more drugs than he does, and about the Incredible Hulk and Dr. Dre.
</P>
<P>
   An all-purpose, wide-screen blast of pop-culture references,
fantasy and young-adult frustration, ``My Name Is'' has propelled
24-year-old Marshall Bruce Mathers III to hip-hop superstar status
in less than two months. He has sold more than 500,000 copies of
the profanity-filled ``Slim'' and appears on the cover of the
current issue of Rolling Stone.
</P>
<P>
   What to make of this? That's the funny part _ ``My Name Is''
certainly qualifies as a mass-appeal novelty song, what KRBV/100.3
FM program director Carmy Ferreri calls ``quirky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something different _ it stands out on the radio,'' he
says, explaining why the song is being played on his Dallas-Fort
Worth station amid the likes of Mariah Carey, Whitney Houston and
Brandy. ``It's sort of like (Bobby McFerrin's) `Don't Worry, Be
Happy.' Everybody played it _ pop stations, rock stations, even
country stations.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all it is. For all the suddenness of Eminem's
rise, for all the ways in which this blond-kid-goes-supernova
recalls the big-bang ascension of Richardson homeboy Vanilla Ice
with ``Ice Ice Baby'' back in 1990, there's something else afoot.
Eminem long ago got respect from the black hip-hop community, the
hard-core guys who put out songs that don't get played on
KHKS/106.1 FM and KDGE/94.5 FM _ or even KRBV.
</P>
<P>
   Those musicians and producers, both in Detroit and around the
country, genuinely respect Eminem, in part because of his
association with superstar rapper/producer Dr. Dre (who produced
three tracks on the CD) and in part because he simply has the
goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of American music is that white people spin black
music and make it accessible to a broader audience,'' says Janine
Coveney, hip-hop editor of ``Gavin.'' ``And there's some resentment
about that in the black music industry. But there's none of that
with him. He's dope. His lyrics are amazing. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Eminem's lyrics vary greatly from song to song _ and it's not
always pleasant. For example, on ``97' Bonnie &AMP; Clyde,'' a parody
of Will Smith's pro-family ``Just the Two of Us,'' he fantasizes
about enlisting the help of his daughter to dispose of the body of
her mom, whose throat he has slit after she hit him with a
restraining order.
</P>
<P>
   Other songs mention sex with minors, goof on Kurt Cobain's
suicide, and discuss what a pain it is to help a date who has
overdosed on hallucinogenic mushrooms. Then again, there are
others, such as ``If I Had'' and ``Rock Bottom,'' that find him
ruminating about a life of dead-end jobs and meager paychecks, real
slice-of-life stuff from a guy who grew up in a tough inner-city
neighborhood and worked as a cook before the CD blew up.
</P>
<P>
   The violence and misogyny on ``Slim Shady'' has earned Eminem a
scathing editorial from Billboard editor Timothy White. But it's
precisely his darker, rougher lyrics that have landed his song on
the playlists of alternative stations that rarely, if ever, feature
hip-hop artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got an edgier attitude _ that's why a lot of alternative
stations have embraced him,'' says Alan Smith, music director and
assistant program director of KDGE, the Edge, in Dallas-Fort Worth.
``The audience likes that. It's not happy _ if he had been, we
wouldn't have looked at it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Eminem may play a pivotal role in bringing hip-hop to
alternative stations, according to Mike Peer, music director of New
York's WXRK. ``He bridges the hip-hop and alternative worlds,''
says Peer. ``He has elements of alternative music, with the image
and the lingo and the references to Nine Inch Nails, with the beats
of a hip-hop record.''
</P>
<P>
   Eminem has arrived at a time, says Peer, when hip-hop is ``a
huge force in white suburban America,'' outselling hard rock _ and
just about everything else, for that matter. Young males, his
target audience, find the elements of street culture and danger
that used to be provided more often by hard-rock acts. By playing
Eminem, Peer says, he can appeal to the guys who want to hear Tool
and Jay-Z and DMX _ and keep them from flipping to another station.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can do that, you'll clean up,'' he says. ``Young white
kids are leaving rock 'n' roll in droves to listen to rap, because
``their parents don't get it.'' Their parents get the Stones. They
don't get rap _ and that's the appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
