<HEADER>
A8375 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITUARY-MERRILL-BOS &LR;      04-14 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-MERRILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILBERT E. MERRILL, 78; NATURALIST RAN SCIENCE MUSEUM PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gilbert E. Merrill, a naturalist who was director of education
at Boston's Museum of Science and the first director of the Squam
Lakes Science Center in Holderness, N.H., died following surgery
Monday in St. Vincent Hospital in Worcester, Mass. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career, as the assistant director of education at
the Museum of Science during the 1950s, Mr. Merrill logged
thousands of miles on New England highways as he brought Spooky the
Owl, the museum's ``goodwill ambassador,'' on public appearances.
During the presentations, Mr. Merrill delivered lectures on natural
history and put the keen-eyed predator through its paces.
</P>
<P>
   While Mr. Merrill piloted the car, the horned owl paced back and
forth across the top of the front seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plainly,'' Mr. Merrill said in a story published in the Globe
on Jan. 7, 1954, ``the owl is very fond of motoring. He never
misses a thing when we're riding. Spooky can spot a bird or an
animal before I do. When he gets bored with looking out the window,
he leans against my head, or monkeys around with the back of my
neck. The only place he doesn't like is the Sumner Tunnel. The
flicking lights upset him.''
</P>
<P>
   The bird was the museum's roving ambassador until its death in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Merrill was born in Salem, Mass. and raised in Danvers. He
graduated from Tufts University and earned a master's degree in
biology at Williams College.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, he served in Europe as a medic in the Army.
</P>
<P>
   He was a professor of biology and environmental science at
Elmira College in New York, and had long affiliations with the
Holderness School in New Hampshire and the Tanglewood Nature Center
in the Berkshires.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, RoseAnne (Barry); four daughters, Anne Walsh
of University Park, Md., Jane E. of Albuquerque, Elizabeth Burnham
of Beverly, Mass., and Polly Curran of Wenham, Mass.; a son,
Gilbert L. of Worcester; a sister, Virginia Byrd of Danvers; and 10
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
