u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-EUROPE-2TAKES-     04-14 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-EUROPE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN LEADERS OFFER KOSOVO PEACE PLAN; U.S. SEES LITTLE CHANCE
OF SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
   (ac) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Joining in the search for a diplomatic
solution to the crisis in Kosovo, leaders of the 15 European Union
countries presented a plan Wednesday under which the province would
be placed under temporary European administration if Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic agreed to withdraw his forces and
allowed hundreds of thousands of Albanian refugees to return.
</P>
<P>
   American officials gave the European initiative, and a more
detailed one separately made public by Germany on Wednesday, little
chance of being accepted by Belgrade. NATO reiterated that it would
continue bombing military targets in Yugoslavia until Milosevic
withdrew all police and military units from Kosovo and allowed its
Albanian population to return.
</P>
<P>
   But the European proposal could break new ground by signaling to
Yugoslavia's leaders and to Russia that the United States and the
North Atlantic alliance it dominates do not have to be the only
players if Milosevic is interested in any outcome in Kosovo other
than his own fiery end.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials here said that Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright had also discussed some of the ideas in the European plan
in Oslo on Tuesday with Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov.
However, a senior administration official denied Wednesday that
specific details of the plan had been discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no discussion of a _ quote _ German plan _
unquote,'' he said. ``We did discuss the need for a Serbian
withdrawal from Kosovo and how it would be implemented, the ideas
behind a German plan. But I don't believe that there was any
discussion of the specifics of what the German government has now
unveiled.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO continued bombing Serbian military targets on Wednesday
despite more bad weather over the Balkans, and Serbian officials in
Kosovo said that an attack on a convoy of vehicles had killed
scores of Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The allied command said that planes had attacked a convoy of
military vehicles near a highway bridge just east of Djakovica at
3:30 p.m. Wednesday, and that the planes had taken fire from
antiaircraft artillery and hand-held surface-to-air missiles. The
command said it could not confirm that the bombing had caused
civilian casualties but said the incident would be fully
investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Summarizing the discussions of the European leaders, German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said Wednesday night that the goal of
both diplomacy and of NATO military action was to create a change
in Yugoslavia that would stop Serbian attacks on Albanians, who
made up 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million people before Serbian
paramilitary units and Yugoslav soldiers began a campaign to drive
them out of the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heads of state and government reiterate their
determination not to tolerate the killings and deportations in
Kosovo,'' Schroeder said, ``and believe that the use of the most
severe measures, including military measures, was both necessary
and justified.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that European leaders now considered ``establishment of
an international interim administration which the European Union
could take over'' an essential part of an eventual peace settlement
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Other parts of a settlement package that the leaders had
discussed, Schroeder said, included a police force that would
reflect the province's ethnic composition, elections and
``deployment of international military forces that will guarantee
protection for the whole population of Kosovo.'' The NATO allies
insist that any such force should be led and commanded by the
alliance, possibly under a mandate from the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The European leaders insisted that the United Nations, the
European Union and Russia should all play a role in the diplomatic
resolution of the crisis. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who
attended the European Union discussions Wednesday, said that all
the members of the U.N. Security Council would be consulted about
the European proposals.
</P>
<P>
   But unless Milosevic suddenly gives up and accepts a diplomatic
solution, the only way to impose one on him remains the bombing
campaign, now being carried out by about 1,000 American, British,
French, Dutch and German warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The original German proposal suggested a 24-hour suspension of
the bombing if Milosevic began pulling forces out of Kosovo by
deadlines set by Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   But Britain is staunchly opposed to any letup of the bombing
until an international military force can go into Kosovo and the
refugees are allowed to return to their homes in peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not going to be a halt to the NATO action until the
demands that we have set out, which are entirely reasonable,
humane, civilized demands, are met in full,'' Prime Minister Tony
Blair said Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to allow Milosevic to get away with the
policy of ethnic cleansing. He will be defeated on that policy and
the military objectives that we have set at the beginning of this
campaign will be seen through in their entirety, in their
entirety,'' Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia has so far refused to discuss any kind of
international force in Kosovo. Russia, a permanent member of the
U.N. Security Council with veto power over its decisions, has said
it would approve such a force only if Milosevic was willing to
accept it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Under the original German plan, which Foreign Minister Joschka
Fischer discussed with the United States, Britain, France, Canada
and Italy at a NATO meeting here on Monday, the U.N. Security
Council would set firm deadlines for Milosevic to start and finish
a withdrawal of all Serbian and paramilitary forces from the
province.
</P>
<P>
   If he began withdrawing, according to the proposal, NATO forces
would break off air strikes for 24 hours. If the Serb police and
army troops kept withdrawing, the 24-hour pause would be extended
as long as they kept pulling out, with peacekeepers moving in as
the Serb forces left.
</P>
<P>
   American and other allied officials reacted to the German plan
skeptically, but apparently agreed to see if the Russians would
help try it out on Belgrade. ``Nobody thinks it will work,'' an
American official said. ``First of all, Milosevic will never accept
it. But at this point, everybody is willing to try everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, James P. Rubin, State Department spokesman, said,
``The main point in the German plan that's relevant here is that
this would be done ideally by resolution of the Security Council,
which would be fine with us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Acceptance of a plan to surrender Kosovo to international
administration would mean, for the fiercely nationalist Milosevic,
giving up Serbian sovereignty over historically Serb territory,
something not even required in the plan he refused in negotiations
at Rambouillet Castle in France this winter.
</P>
<P>
   His refusal to accept that plan's proposals _ to leave the
province under Serbian sovereignty but give its 1.8 million
Albanians political and legal autonomy _ set off the NATO bombing
that began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   An outline of the original German plan released by the Foreign
Ministry in Bonn on Wednesday proposed an international
peacekeeping force under United Nations auspices that should be
``robust.'' The report said that the force should not be hamstrung
by the ``double key'' arrangements that made U.N. peacekeepers and
NATO forces unable to launch any military operations unless both
civilian officials and allied military officers agreed on them. But
no such language found its way into the European consensus
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the scenario outlined by Bonn, the peacekeepers from
participating countries could begin moving into Kosovo as the Serbs
withdrew from the province, and when the entire peacekeeping force
was in place, it would begin disarming and demilitarizing the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   And the Bonn plan also proposed that the international observers
sent in by the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
last October and withdrawn just before the NATO bombing began last
month would go back in, ``under new conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied air forces would continue to patrol the skies and react
to Serb threats to security in Kosovo, the plan says, and the
nearly 20,000 allied soldiers planned for refugee relief operations
in Macedonia and Albania would receive other assignments yet to be
determined.
</P>
<P>
   The European consensus did not stretch far enough to embrace the
entire proposal, but according to Schroeder, it did reaffirm plans
announced last week for the European Union to provide $160 million
for refugee relief and $107 million to Albania, Macedonia and
Montenegro to help them provide for the hundreds of thousands of
refugees who have fled to those countries.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder also said that the European Union would convene a
conference on southeastern Europe to consider ``further
comprehensive measures for the long-term stabilization, security,
democratization and economic reconstruction of the entire region.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the countries in the region have the right to aspire to
the European Union,'' he said. German officials believe that even
Serbia, if it turns to democracy and a free market economy, has the
same right, and hope that the perspective will eventually lead it
to change the disastrous course it has followed through the 1990s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
