<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FOCUSING ON THE PLAYOFF GAME, NOT THE OPPONENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Down the stretch they come, the regular season all but
in their dust, and now the Bruins look ahead to see the who, what,
and where of the playoffs coming up around the bend.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be the Senators, the Devils, the Hurricanes? With the
regular season set to close Sunday, will the horses in the Eastern
Conference continue to careen off each other and reshuffle their
order of finish right to the wire?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't care who we play,'' coach Pat Burns said after
Wednesday's practice in suburban Wilmington, a mantra torn from the
pages of the Coach's Guide and Handbook. ``I don't want to discuss
the playoffs. It's (not important) where we're going to finish _
it's how we're going to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins visit the FleetCenter Thursday, the first of three
formidable opponents the Bruins will face in their
made-for-the-postseason tuneup. The Sabres are here for a Saturday
matinee and then the Bruins travel to Philly for a season wrapup
vs. the Flyers. All three opponents also are headed to the
playoffs, each one wondering who they'll draw in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the standings Wednesday morning, the Bruins would be
headed to Ottawa next week for a best-of-seven series vs. the quick
and nimble Senators. Only a slight reshuffling would have them
instead headed to Exit 16W to face the broad-shouldered Devils. If
they were to win all three of their final matches, then the
playoffs would find the Bruins in Greensboro, N.C., suiting up
against the former Forever .500s ( a.k.a. the Hurricanes).
</P>
<P>
   So here's what we know after 79 games of the regular season: the
Bruins are in the playoffs; otherwise, consult this space for
shift-to-shift updates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ottawa's got very stong goaltending,'' said Bruins netminder
Byron Dafoe, who'll be back in the pipes, in pursuit of his 31st
victory (and perhaps 11th shutout). ``In fact, that's one thing
they all have in common: great goaltending _ that's why they are
where they are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins only recently got their No. 1 netminder, Tom
Barrasso, back in action. They've been in a free fall for much of
the second half, due in part to Barrasso's broken hand (a cracked
bone near the wrist). If the Senators and Devils are the divisional
favorites, the Penguins rate as the darkhorse, the biggest hole in
their game closed by Barrasso.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ottawa is a very skilled and talented team,'' said Dafoe,
assessing the field of the Bruins' prospective opponents.
``(Alexei) Yashin has had an unbelievable year. Then you go to New
Jersey, a big, strong, disciplined team. They're like a machine out
there _ all parts are moving in the same direction. Carolina's more
well-rounded than some people think, with a good offense and
(goaltender Arturs) Irbe doing just a great job in net.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you ask, `Who do you want to play?' What matters to me,
right now, is that we've got three games left with teams all around
us in the standings, and I'd love to win all three just to keep up
the momentum going into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have won five of their last six games, a run that
included a 5-2 triumph in Florida that clinched their second
consecutive trip to the postseason. They enter Thursday's action
with a 37-29-13 mark with a chance to win 40 games for the first
time since the 1995-96 season. To improve on their 91-point season
of 1997-98, they need to capture five of the six points available
in these three remaining games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no soft or easy teams,'' said Ray Bourque, also
assessing the field of possibilities with three games to go. ``One
team may have more experience, another might have more speed or
skill, but you have to compete against all these teams. There are
some interesting matchups, be it first place vs. eighth, 2-7, 4-5,
2-3, what have you . . . and it's not going to be easy for
anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
