<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BUSH SPEAKS OUT ON FOREIGN POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``I believe we ought to be slow to engage our
military, slow to commit our troops,'' says Gov. George W. Bush,
``but when we do so, we must do so to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he think it was a mistake for President Clinton to say
specifically we would not send in ground troops?
</P>
<P>
   ``I do. I do. I think we ought to leave all options on the
table, but I think those tactical decisions ought to be made by
military planners and not by politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that include the option of massing NATO troops on the
borders of Kosovo? ``If that is what the military advisers
recommend, the answer would be yes.'' Bush cautioned that he did
not have the full intelligence at his fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   What's our mission there? ``Our objective is to remove the
Serbian troops from Kosovo and have the Kosovars returned to their
homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Remove Slobodan Milosevic from office? ``I think he ought to be
treated as a war criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Independence for Kosovo? ``I do not believe that ought to be the
immediate objective. It could be a long-term objective, but not the
short-term.''
</P>
<P>
   Why are we involved in this, anyway? ``The actions of Milosevic
are destabilizing, and a stable Europe is in America's best
strategic interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush's staff had failed to warn him that the stated
purpose of my visit was to examine his foreign-policy views, he
could not very well throw me out of his office. So he gulped and
took the plunge that he mistakenly thought would be premature.
</P>
<P>
   Should we urge admission of China to the World Trade
Organization? ``I believe that if we were to turn our backs on
China, on an entrepreneurial class that is just beginning to grow
there, it would be a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The theft of nuclear secrets, the illegal Chinese campaign
contributions _ that doesn't upset him? ``Sure, I am upset about
that. . . . That does not necessarily say that we should stop
trading if it is good for American producers and good for American
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   No retaliation for that, or for the crackdown on human rights in
China? ``Do I think we ought to sanction trade as a result of that?
No, I don't, is my answer to the question. . . . I think we ought
to be very careful about the application of unilateral sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   Should we tie admission of China to the WTO to Taiwan's
admission, on the same basis as Hong Kong? ``No, I would not. I
would hope, expect, Taiwan to come in at some point in time, but I
would not have tied it in as a condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting my visible dismay, the Texas governor added: ``We need to
make sure that China understands there are limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush thinks Clinton sent a ``mixed signal'' in crossing the
Pacific to visit only China last year. ``The president should visit
our friends. China is not our friend in the Far East. Our friends
are Japan, Taiwan and South Korea. He didn't visit our friends. I
think it is important that we maintain our friendships and always
remember who our friends are.''
</P>
<P>
   That brought us to Israel. I recalled how both his father,
President Bush, and President Clinton made clear their preference
for Labor over Likud in past Israeli elections. How about him? ``I
don't think Americans ought to be picking sides when it comes to
Israeli elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Move the U.S. Embassy to Jerusalem? ``Peace has to be negotiated
between the parties involved. And I am confident that they are
going to be able to resolve Jerusalem in a way with which the
Israelis are comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great trip to Israel,'' he went on, relaxing for the
first time. ``I had a very good visit with Benjamin Netanyahu and
with Ariel Sharon. I met the opposition leader, Ehud Barak, who is
now running for prime minister. It was a great experience. I saw
the Arrow missile system in action, an intermediate-range
anti-ballistic-missile system that works, much of it funded by us.
It will help prevent our friend and us from being blackmailed.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm out of space. Next column: ``George Dubyuh'' on Russia and
the IMF, the ABM treaty, Iraq, Iran, North Korea and the
foreign-policy split in the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   As the candidate says, ``I've been studying up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
