u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GRIER-BO     04-14 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GRIER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIER AFTER HIGHER PICK IN DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Bobby Grier has spent the last several weeks
watching a lot of video of Ricky Williams amd Edgerrin James. But
it appears somewhere in the tape rack, Grier has slipped a tape or
two of Mark McGwire because it's obvious following Wednesday's
predraft press conference at Foxboro Stadium that Grier wants and
needs to hit a home run with Saturday's draft.
</P>
<P>
   Grier, who is in control of the 20th and 28th picks in the first
round, confirmed what had been reported the past 10 days _ that he
is trying to move up, ideally to Washington's fifth spot, where he
could take a running back such as Williams of Texas or James of
Miami. Grier said he thinks his chances of doing so are
``reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he's had talks with teams below Washington to trade
up and fill needs other than running back, which is a glaring hole
because of Robert Edwards's career-threatening knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots move up to five, they should have a clear shot
at James. And if the Indianapolis Colts, who draft fourth, decide
to draft a defensive player, which they desperately need, Williams
also could fall to five.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland still could have a say about that, though. The Browns,
at No. 1, are trying to feel out negotiations with Kentucky
quarterback Tim Couch and if they think they won't be able to sign
him, the Browns may look to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Grier said he's talked with Washington general manager Charlie
Casserly several times over the past week, most recently last
weekend. Casserly confirmed that he had talked to Grier, but the
Redskins are saying they don't think there's much chance of a deal
coming about. Washington reportedly has interest in defensive
back/receiver Champ Bailey of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Ravens, who pick 10th, had talked about swapping
picks with the Redskins so they could take a quarterback, but it
appears they'll still be able to take a quarterback or a top
receiver if they stay put.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Rams, who pick sixth and also covet Williams, also
are trying to swap spots with the Redskins. And the New Orleans
Saints have offered their entire draft and possibly their No. 1
pick next year.
</P>
<P>
   Grier, however, feels he might be able to top the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two No. 1 picks, a second-round pick, and two
third-rounders,'' said Grier. ``The Saints have only one
first-round pick and no second-round pick.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first three rounds, the Patriots have the 20th, 28th,
53d, 84th, and 93d picks while the Saints have the 12th and 73d.
Grier also spoke of possibly giving up a first-round pick next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we're willing to expend picks is because the two
running backs are exceptional,'' said Grier. Last year, the
Patriots tried to move up to Oakland's fourth spot to take Charles
Woodson but the price was too high. Ditto with the Bears' No. 5
slot for Curtis Enis.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who obviously would require a major contract (Woodson
received an $8 million signing bonus last season), would be a great
fit in New England because he loves Boston and has many friends in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Grier said that he saw little difference between Enis, Fred
Taylor, and Robert Edwards a year ago, but this year Williams and
James are head and shoulders above the pack. Grier said if the team
didn't draft Williams or James, they would likely fill other needs
in the first round and think about a running back later on. He said
the second tier of running backs is led by LSU's Kevin Faulk,
Mississippi State's J.J. Johnson, and Boston College's Mike Cloud.
</P>
<P>
   Grier, who is in charge of the Patriots' draft picks for the
third year following the Bill Parcells era, said he doesn't feel
any added pressure to make the right choices in this draft just
because the 28th pick is the final compensation pick from the Jets
for Parcells. He said of the four players already chosen as
Parcells compensation, ``Damon Denson has a chance to be a starter
for us'' and of wide receiver Tony Simmons, ``there was only one
player better'' that being Randy Moss, whom Grier had taken off his
draft board. The other Parcells picks were Sedrick Shaw, who has
been a bust, and Greg Spires, a situational pass rusher.
</P>
<P>
   Grier also may be willing to give up a veteran player or two to
sweeten a deal with the Redskins. The Patriots probably won't be
able to sign both Ty Law and Lawyer Milloy, and with the team
looking to open a spot in the defensive secondary for Tebucky
Jones, Milloy might be made available.
</P>
<P>
   Grier said that teams haven't asked for specific players yet,
but ``we haven't closed the door on anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier is close to closing the door on any chance of acquiring
Colts running back Marshall Faulk, who is being shopped to several
teams, but not the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hard to make a deal within the division,'' said
Grier. He did say, however, he may try to work a deal for a running
back if he can't get Williams or James in the draft. Adrian Murrell
of the Arizona Cardinals is on the market.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots stay put, they likely will try to fill needs on
both lines with their first-round picks and possibly go for a back
in the second or third rounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
