<HEADLINE>
FLEET EARNINGS RISE 36 PERCENT IN FIRST QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Striding into its planned merger with BankBoston Corp.
on a solid footing, Fleet Financial Group Inc. reported a strong 36
percent rise in first quarter earnings Wednesday, exceeding Wall
Street's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The growth, which the Boston-based bank attributed to recent
acquisitions in the credit card and asset-based lending businesses,
pleased industry analysts, who said New England's largest bank was
a bulwark of strength and set to grow more.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were strong earnings across the board and they set the
foundation for the merger going forward,'' said Carla A. D'Arista
of Friedman, Billings, Ramsey &AMP; Co. Fleet is acquiring BankBoston
to form the nation's eighth-largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   For the first three months of 1999, Fleet said net income rose
to a record $438 million, or $0.72 per share, from $323 million, or
$0.53 a share, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The results beat estimates of $0.69 a share by First Call Corp.,
the Boston-based company that compiles analysts' predictions. For a
regional bank, such a margin of outperformance is impressive,
analyst Edward Najarian of Wheat First Union said.
</P>
<P>
   Results from the first quarter of 1998 were depressed by a $44
million charge _ equivalent to $0.07 a share _ from Fleet's
acquisitions of discount brokerage Quick &AMP; Reilly Group Inc. and
the credit-card operations of Advanta Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But Fleet, like many other major banks, still had strong growth
in the most recent quarter _ evidence that the bank's strategy of
branching out into financial services is succeeding. ``It was a
spectacular quarter,'' Fleet's chief executive, Terrence Murray,
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue in the latest period rose 21 percent to $1.9 billion,
fueled by Fleet's recent acquisition of Sanwa Bank Ltd's US leasing
and lending company. Net interest income grew 11 percent to $1
billion, driven by Sanwa and the acquisition of $1.3 billion in
credit-card receivables from Household International Inc. in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, revenue from credit-card operations rose sixfold to $30
million, while earnings from Quick &AMP; Reilly nearly doubled to $47
million. The brokerage's earnings include revenue from Fleet's
market-making specialist unit, acquired from Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
last year.
</P>
<P>
   One fly in Fleet's champagne glass last quarter was a rise in
the company's charge-off ratio _ essentially, bad consumer debt
that the bank writes off. Fleet's ratio increased to a relatively
high 7.4, equivalent to around $12.7 billion in written-off debt,
D'Arista said. Fleet, now the nation's ninth-largest bank, with
$104 billion in assets, is also struggling with a lawsuit against
Advanta, which it claims overcharged Fleet for its credit-card
receivables.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet shares, which fell immediately after the BankBoston merger
was announced but have since risen, nudged up 3/8 Wednesday to
close at 43 7/16 on the New York Stock Exchange. Analysts said
Fleet's stock price underestimates the value of Quick &AMP; Reilly,
which operates SureTrade, an on-line brokerage that Fleet started
18 months ago and now wants to spin off. Najarian said Quick &AMP;
Reilly could be worth anywhere from $5 billion to $8 billion _
figures he said could boost Fleet's stock price by at least 20
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
