<SLUG> BC-BEGINNING-MOVIE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GINGRICH ALMOST HELD BACK 'BIG BANG'
 &HT;    With BEGINNING.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Producers of a new Smithsonian Institution
educational movie on the origin of the universe almost banned the
words ``Big Bang'' and ``evolution'' from the script for fear they
could keep the movie from being shown in the South.
</P>
<P>
   In its final form, the movie, ``Cosmic Voyage,'' does refer to
those sometimes controversial ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But fear of how ``Newt Gingrich Republicans'' might respond
caused Smithsonian officials to temporarily ban the terms from the
script, said Joel Primack, a professor of physics at the University
of California, Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was produced to be shown in specialty theaters such as
the Smithsonian's own Imax facility, which features a huge
wraparound screen and sophisticated sound system to create ``being
there'' sensations.
</P>
<P>
   Primack presided Wednesday over a scientific conference in which
cosmologists and theologians discussed the origin of the universe.
During a break, he recalled his involvement in initial work to
create the movie in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was right after the Newt Gingrich Republicans had taken
over the House and the Senate in 1994,'' he said, ``and one of the
first things that this new Republican majority did was go after the
head of the Air and Space Museum, Martin Harwit.''
</P>
<P>
   Harwit, the first astronomer ever named to head the
Smithsonian's popular space museum, resigned in the aftermath of
veteran organizations' displeasure over the tone of a planned
exhibit of the Enola Gay, the B-29 bomber that dropped a nuclear
weapon on Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Primack said at one point, questions were raised over whether a
movie that contained references to the hypothesized spontaneous
creation of the universe in the ``Big Bang'' or the Darwinian
evolution of life on Earth ``could ever be shown in the American
South.''
</P>
<P>
   In an atmosphere dominated by fear because of Harwit's
resignation, Smithsonian officials told scientists working on the
script to leave the two terms out.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Primack said, ``things calmed down and the people in
charge had a little bit more courage than before, and we went back
into the script and made it a little bit closer to what we had in
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
