<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8385 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILOSEVIC-FUNDS-BOS &LR;      04-14 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILOSEVIC-FUNDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SETS SIGHTS ON MILOSEVIC FINANCIAL ASSETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ UN sanctions may have crippled Serbia's
economy, but Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and his inner
circle have become multimillionaires through their control of
state-controlled monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   As the NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia gathers steam, US
officials say they have secretly stepped up their efforts to locate
and seize those assets from overseas accounts in Russia Greece,
Cyprus and elsewhere. They say they believe Milosevic's illicit
financial empire _ which they describe as ``Serbia Inc.'' _ is
being used to finance Serbia's war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at ways to increase pressure economically and
financially on Milosevic,'' said a senior US official familiar with
the covert effort. ``We intend to undercut his ability to conduct
military operations and sustain and maintain his national
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The covert operation is aimed at cutting off Serbia's ability to
buy weapons and jet fuel, feed troops, repair tanks and power their
radar systems. It has also provided grist for NATO propagandists
seeking to portray Milosevic, his family and his inner circle as
corrupt scam artists with little concern for the hardships faced by
ordinary Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   US officials say American intelligence agencies, preoccupied
with the hunt for war criminals and the security of American forces
in the Balkans, have missed countless opportunities to cut into the
Serb leader's war chest. They said numerous initial requests to the
CIA and Defense Intelligence Agency by US Ambassador Robert Gelbard
_ who has spearheaded the administration's hunt for Milosevic's
assets _ yielded little.
</P>
<P>
   But an official familiar with the operation has received growing
support during the last year from high-level administration
officials, the Treasury Department and the three key US
intelligence agencies _ the CIA, the DIA and the National Security
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   US intelligence has uncovered evidence that Milosevic's brother,
Boris Borislav, the Yugoslav ambassador to Moscow, and Serbian
banker Bogoljub Karic, have laundered hundreds of millions through
several banks in Russia, including the Moscow based branch of
Karic's bank, according to a US official familiar with the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karic is a key board member of Serbia Inc.'' the official
said. ``We will get them,'' said an administration official
involved in the effort.
</P>
<P>
   US and British officials say they also have evidence of money
laundering in Greece and Cyprus. But Washington has been reluctant
to disclose details that would embarrass the Cypriot government
when it was engaged in a diplomatic effort to free three American
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Former US diplomats and intelligence officials say that efforts
to financially squeeze Milosevic has been painstaking. Tracking the
flow of illicit money through the secretive international banking
and financial system is extremely difficult. And Washington's
attitude toward Milosevic _ who was instrumental in negotiating an
end to the Bosnian war at Dayton, Ohio _ frequently shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has always been ambivalent'' about how
aggressively it should pursue Milosevic, said a former US
intelligence official.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has been able to take advantage of that ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1997, several months before Milosevic began his military
offensive against ethnic Albanian rebels, the West allowed the
Serbian regime to obtain billions of dollars through the sale of
private assets.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a joint venture by two NATO allies _ OTE Telecom
of Greece and Telecom Italia _ purchased 49 percent of the Belgrade
state telephone company for $880 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was handled by an investment bank from Britain, NatWest
while the American accountancy firm Price Waterhouse advised the
Serbian communications ministry, according to Pyramid Research of
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade claimed to use the money to pay pensions, and to reform
the postal and telecommunications infrastructure, according to
Julie Altman, a telecommunications analyst at Pyramid. But she said
it was impossible to determine how the money was spent.
</P>
<P>
   Others suspect the money helped finance the military's offensive
in Kosovo in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has been his war kitty,'' said Mark Kirk, a staffer at
the Republican House International Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week, Britain has disclosed details on the web of
offshore holdings that have kept Milosevic in power. Relying on
American intelligence, Britain's Foreign Minister Robin Cook said
that Milosevic stashed millions in offshore banks, and purchased
villas in Corfu, Crete and Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said Milosevic's son, Marko, is sitting out the war in a
villa in Greece. Marko Milosevic own a bakery, a duty-free import
business and the Madonna discoteque in Pozarevac, Milosevic's home
town.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Maria, owns a radio station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell the people of Serbia how much wealth you have sucked out
of Serbia during the same years they have been impoverished,'' Cook
said on April 7. ``Let them see the luxury yacht you keep in Greece
while they struggle to make ends meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Britain's Defense Minister George Robertson identified
key government ministers who have been rewarded for their loyalty
to Milosevic with lucrative state monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   Mirko Marjanovic, the prime minister of Serbia, is president of
the country's natural gas monopoly, Progress.
</P>
<P>
   Nikola Sainovic, the deputy prime minister of the federal
republic of Yugoslavia, heads the RTB Bor Copper Mine. And Dragan
Tomic, the speaker of the parliament, is director of NIS
Jugopetrol, which has a near monopoly on oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corruption and nepotism,'' Robertson said ``are...the cancer
at the heart of Milosevic's empire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He corrupted the system,'' said Milan Panic, a California
pharmaceuticals executive and former Yugoslav prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each minister is also the manager of a large business. Some of
them were decent people before he corrupted them.''
</P>
<P>
   Panic said Milosevic recently confiscated more than $170 million
in assets from a Belgrade-based subsidiary of his pharmaceuticals
company, ICN.
</P>
<P>
   ``That money all went into financing Milosevic's adventures such
as the Kosovo war,'' said Panic. ``He is draining the last of our
economic resources.''
</P>
<P>
   But Panic said that he believes Milosevic is running out of
money. He said that senior Russian officials have warned that they
would stop selling him fuel unless he paid his bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you are going to find billions of dollars in his
accounts,'' he said. ``I would let him have all the money if he
would just resign and leave the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
