<SLUG> BC-SENATE-OLYMPICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS DEBATE OLYMPIC REFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Olympic scandal moved to Capitol Hill
Wednesday, as frustrated senators wrestled with how quickly they
should use the US tax code and other laws to force reforms on the
International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing of the Senate Commerce Committee, a consensus
appeared to emerge that it would be a mistake to take immediate
action on proposals that would dramatically alter Olympic financing
mechanisms and weaken the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Among those proposals are stripping the IOC's tax-exempt status,
denying tax deductions to its corporate sponsors, and redirecting
lucrative television rights fees to its US affiliate, the United
States Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the worst thing at this moment is to threaten some
kind of Draconian measure,'' said committee chairman John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican from Arizona echoed the hearing's lead witness,
former Senate majority leader George Mitchell, who said rash action
by Congress could derail the IOC's internal reform process and
jeopardize funding for athletes. Mitchell served as chairman of an
independent ethics commission assembled by the USOC.
</P>
<P>
   But not all of McCain's colleagues were willing to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we all waiting on?'' asked Ernest Hollings, a
Democrat from South Carolina, who was among several senators
calling for the ouster of IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch. In
a reference to the IOC's home city in Switzerland, Hollings
demanded, ``Heavens above, we've got to . . . clean up Lausanne.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollings then implored his old friend Mitchell to drop the
diplomatic role of Northern Ireland peacemaker and ``give us some
marching orders here and tell us what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mitchell demurred, saying, ``I don't believe one can fairly
make a conclusion at this time on whether legislation should be
enacted.'' He said Congress should give the IOC until the end of
this year to clean house with help from a reform panel called IOC
2000, whose newly appointed members include Henry Kissinger and the
organizer of the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles, Peter
Ueberroth.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's hearing marked the most notable response by Congress
to allegations of bribery and influence peddling surrounding the
choice of Salt Lake City as host of the 2002 Winter Games. Ten IOC
members have resigned or been expelled in the worst scandal in
Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
   While committee members generally supported a methodical
approach to enacting laws that would affect the IOC's primary
funding source _ an estimated 60 percent of Olympic revenues come
from the United States _ there was widespread support for
immediately including the IOC under the chief US law against
bribery of foreign officials.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that by the end of the day he would file legislation
to amend the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act to include a ban on
bribery of IOC members. Mitchell's commission and the USOC last
month recommended that President Clinton issue an executive order
applying the bribery law to the IOC, but Justice Department
officials have said privately they doubted it could be done as the
statute is now written, making action by Congress necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the sharpest moments of the hearing came when McCain
peppered IOC members Anita DeFrantz and Jim Easton, both US
citizens, with questions about the IOC's willingness to accept the
Mitchell commission's recipe for reform, including term limits for
IOC members; election of IOC members by national Olympic
committees; and immediate public release of IOC meeting minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Other than term limits, which they both supported, one or the
other expressed reservations or opposition to the rest of the
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   McCain appeared particularly angered by DeFrantz's support for
keeping IOC meeting minutes secret for 10 to 20 years, which she
said was necessary to protect IOC members in their home countries.
McCain said DeFrantz's position ``flies in the face of everything
I've ever thought in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFrantz and Easton appeared in place of Samaranch, who declined
McCain's invitation to attend. Easton confined his remarks to an
apology to McCain, whom Easton had suggested was using the issue as
a publicity ploy for his presidential aspirations. McCain accepted
the apology.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had warm praise for another witness, USOC president Bill
Hybl, whose organization McCain said had accepted its share of
blame for the Salt Lake City mess and responded quickly to the
Mitchell commission's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Though most senators on McCain's committee appeared content to
withhold judgment on laws affecting the IOC's financial status, not
all members of Congress are so inclined. On Monday, two
representatives from New York, Democrat Henry A. Waxman and
Republican Rick Lazio introduced a bill to ban US corporations and
individuals from financially supporting the IOC until it adopts the
Mitchell commission's recommendations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
