<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE HANDING OUT WRONG KIND OF TICKETS, SAY RESIDENTS OF SUBURB 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN MAKEIG 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ All Carl Dahlberg wants is for people driving down
Sunset Boulevard to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   As the concerned father of an 18-month-old boy, Dahlberg worries
so much that he sometimes rushes out into the street waving his
arms to make drivers hit their brakes in West University Place, a
Houston suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become sort of a racetrack out there,'' said Dahlberg, a
physician specializing in pulmonary problems. ``The speed limit's
30 miles an hour, and these people are going 40 or 50. We almost
had a child hit out there six months ago, and I've been at my wits'
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by what they consider the suburb's inability to
reduce speeds along one block of Sunset _ a stretch used as a
shortcut by many drivers _ Dahlberg and his neighbors went further
and posted their own yellow signs along the curbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children at play,'' the signs stated.
</P>
<P>
   But West University police, enforcing an ordinance aimed at
keeping signs for political candidates from decorating roadways,
informed residents the signs had to be moved out of the public
right of way.
</P>
<P>
   That meant repositioning the small signs on the sides of the
sidewalks farthest from the street _ in places where they were less
visible to motorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meanwhile,'' Dahlberg said, ``the speeders got even worse.''
</P>
<P>
   That led residents to move their signs back out to the curbline,
which promptly earned them warning tickets from police.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Police Department does what they're supposed to do, and
they asked (residents) to move their signs,'' City Manager Sherman
Yehl said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers wrote tickets, Yehl said, because other Sunset
Boulevard residents complained about the signs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, for about a year, the people who put up the signs
have been writing increasingly harsh letters to the city and
circulating petitions containing dozens of signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Yehl, saying the city lacks the ability to watch Sunset
Boulevard around the clock, indicated some plans are under way to
force motorists to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   One approach might be ``traffic bubble-out curbs,'' which narrow
the width of streets and make it difficult to go too fast, Yehl
said.
</P>
<P>
   If police begin handing out real tickets to sign-posting Sunset
Boulevard residents, one of them, attorney Steve Monks, is prepared
to go to court and battle on behalf of his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give them discounts,'' he promised.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
