<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-850&AMP;A     04-14 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK IN THE FRAY, YELTSIN SHOWS HIS ENEMIES WHO'S BOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Just a week ago, things were looking dire for President
Boris Yeltsin. The Communist opposition had set a date for his
impeachment. A fast-moving corruption inquiry was knocking on the
gates of the Kremlin itself. NATO bombs over Yugoslavia threatened
to damage not only Russia's relations with the West, but also the
tenets of the country's fragile democracy.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that Yeltsin, always at his best when things could
not be worse, returned to the fray. Back in the Kremlin after a
long convalescence, the 68-year-old president held a series of
meetings, rattled a few sabers, floated a few rumors and dropped a
few hints, all intended to prove once again that for all his
physical and political weaknesses, he is still boss.
</P>
<P>
   It may be only a passing victory, but for the moment anyway,
Yeltsin's opponents seem to have been disarmed. The impeachment
drive has been slowed, if not stalled. The corruption inquiry looks
headed for an impasse, as top Russian politicians, after heavy
wooing by the Kremlin, back away from their support for Yuri
Skuratov, the prosecutor under fire who has been enlisted by
anti-Yeltsin forces.
</P>
<P>
   And so far Yeltsin seems to have managed to ride the tiger of
Russia's anti-Western mood long enough to stay ahead of his more
bellicose opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In all this, Yeltsin has been helped by the ineptitude of his
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not that he is such a brilliant chess player,'' said
Leonid Radzikhovsky, a political commentator for the newspaper
Sevodnya. ``It is just that it's easy to win when your opponents
can't tell the difference between a pawn and a knight.''
</P>
<P>
   As a lame-duck president with one year left in his term, Yeltsin
these days is not looking to stage a comeback. His popularity
ratings are so low he probably couldn't be elected to the City
Council in Yekaterinburg, his hometown. But he is intent on keeping
power _ always the name of the game in Russian politics _ and in so
doing, has emerged once again as the key defender of Russia's
hard-won democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not a charismatic leader anymore, to put it mildly, and
there is great popular resentment against him, but it is clear that
we need to hold on to Yeltsin as long as possible so as not to
allow these other fools to take his place,'' Otto Latsis, a veteran
political commentator, said in an interview. ``Whether he is
defending himself or his record, the situation is the same: The
defender of liberal ideas in Russia is still above all Yeltsin.''
</P>
<P>
   For better or for worse, he might have added. Like many
liberals, Latsis saw his faith in his president severely damaged by
the war in Chechnya. For others, the Yeltsin era will be forever
blighted by the rampant corruption and abuses of power openly
tolerated by the Kremlin in the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent public statements, Yeltsin has again confirmed his
credentials as a democrat, ruling out the abolition of direct
elections of Russia's regional governors and a ban on the Communist
Party, and defending _ as he always has _ the freedom of Russia's
unruly press.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after the financial collapse last summer, a majority of
Russians are just plain bitter _ bitter about being poor, and now
after NATO's show of strength in the Balkans, bitter about being
weak. Wages in Russia are now on average 71.8 percent of what they
were a year ago, and a staggering 38.2 percent of the people are
living beneath the poverty line, compared with 22.4 percent in the
first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Given this sour mood, nobody would declare an end to Russia's
recurrent political warfare, let alone predict how it will turn
out. If anything, with parliamentary elections just eight months
away, the fight has moved to a new and increasingly intense phase.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from Yeltsin's recent remarks, his fears for a reversal
in the course he set for Russia since 1991 now rest not so much in
the Communist-dominated Parliament but in the government of Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov, the former foreign minister whom he
himself appointed last September.
</P>
<P>
   The friction between Primakov and Yeltsin is now an open secret,
after Yeltsin stated publicly last week that his prime minister was
``useful'' _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later, we will see,'' he said, raising the specter of yet
another government shuffle that would likely produce a dangerous
confrontation between the president and Parliament, as occurred in
1993. A less radical option would be the replacement of the two
Communist ministers in Primakov's Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   There are varying theories for Yeltsin's displeasure with
Primakov. One holds that Yeltsin is simply jealous of Primakov's
popularity (the prime minister is Russia's most trusted leader,
according to opinion polls) and his stature, both at home and
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   But another theory, more widely held, has to do with the growing
suspicion that Primakov's alliance with Yeltsin's Communist
opposition _ the basis of a much vaunted political stability that
has been Primakov's main achievement _ is not just tactical, but
rather a strategic platform for the coming elections.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``He is afraid to leave this government in place until the
elections, allowing it to draw more and more money for the
Communists in the agrarian and military-industrial sector,'' said
Radzikhovsky, who has written that Yeltsin's quandary in his last
year is how to thwart his longtime opponents from legally usurping
his historic legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has also publicly revealed his uneasiness with
Primakov's political instincts, which at times seem more in line
with a Soviet-era apparatchik than a post-Communist politician. The
prime minister's loyalty to the president has also seemed at times
sluggish: It wasn't until last Saturday that Primakov came out
openly against impeachment, and for the ouster of Skuratov, whose
future is to be decided next week by the Russian Parliament's upper
house.
</P>
<P>
   With his reminder that Primakov serves at the pleasure of the
president, Yeltsin sent out a heavy-handed signal. That signal was
reinforced on Tuesday by a lengthy meeting with Mayor Yuri Luzhkov
of Moscow, a leading contender for the presidency in next year's
elections, who after months of chilly relations has emerged the
Kremlin's favorite heir apparent _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   Political commentators noted that Yeltsin has already enlisted
the support of Luzhkov, who on Tuesday denounced the attempts to
impeach the president. His next move, some predicted, could be to
join other members of Parliament's upper house in withdrawing their
support for Skuratov.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Yeltsin seemed on his way to putting his house back
in some kind of order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The panicky sensation of losing the last chance to keep power
that has long tormented the presidential strategists has given way
to some wholly sensible actions,'' Yelena Tregubova wrote in the
newspaper Kommersant on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
