<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA'S HINDU COALITION LOSES MAJORITY   IN PARLIAMENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI _ The Hindu nationalist-led coalition that has
governed India for the past year lost its parliamentary majority
Thursday when its largest coalition partner, a state party from
Tamil Nadu headed by the temperamental former actress Jayalalitha
Jayaram, formally withdrew its support.
</P>
<P>
   President K.R. Narayanan, after meeting with Jayalalitha _ who
is known here by her first name _ and leaders of the opposition,
directed the government to seek a confidence vote in Parliament.
Narayanan did not set a deadline for the vote. Parliament
reconvenes Thursday after a recess to take up the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the government asks for the lower house of Parliament to
begin considering the confidence motion right away, there would
probably be several days of floor debate before a vote that gave
both the incumbent government and those who sought to oust it, time
to bargain for the votes it would take to win.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where political power has splintered, and regional
and caste parties now hold the balance of votes needed to govern,
it has proved very difficult to put together a stable, lasting
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, who heads the Hindu
nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, said Wednesday that he was
confident his ruling coalition would stay in power, but that to do
so his government would have to win over a handful of tiny, fickle
political parties that are now playing hard to get.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the opposition Congress Party, which has dominated
Indian politics for most of the past 50 years but now has the
second-largest block of votes, said they will try to cobble
together a new majority.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has presented itself as the party that will champion a
secular approach to governing that serves all of India's religions
and castes, in contrast to the Hindu nationalists, whom Congress
accuses of playing on religious differences for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress succeeds, its coalition would probably wind up
depending on the same Jayalalitha who is facing numerous charges of
corruption and who has made the current government's life miserable
for months.
</P>
<P>
   Since last summer, she had harshly and repeatedly criticized the
government of which she was a part for an ever-shifting set of
reasons, most recently for refusing to get rid of the defense
minister, George Fernandes, who had been accused of corruption by
the fired naval chief, Adm. Vishnu Bhagwat.
</P>
<P>
   Congress' willingness to put together a new coalition marks a
shift in strategy. Sonia Gandhi, president of the party, had taken
the position that it would be better if the party could rebuild
both its grass-roots organization and its vote base in Parliament
before reclaiming power.
</P>
<P>
   But two weeks ago, the enigmatic Mrs. Gandhi _ who usually lets
other politicians come to her _ visited a reception in honor of
Jayalalitha, who heads the All India Anna Dravida Munnetra
Kazagham. The two women are expected to meet again soon to talk
over the formation of a new government.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear that Congress can put together a majority
coalition. There are serious conflicts within the opposition. For
example, officials in the Communist Party of India (Marxist) have
said they will have no part of any coalition that has Jayalalitha
as a member.
</P>
<P>
   But Jayalalitha met with leaders of the Communist party
Wednesday. Afterwards, smiling, she said coyly to the throngs of
waiting reporters, ``Why are you so sure AIADMK wants to be part of
the new coalition?''
</P>
<P>
   Jayalalitha is now holding court in the largest suite at the
Maurya Sheraton Hotel. Her former allies seem to be taking the
opportunity to strike back.
</P>
<P>
   A grim-faced Venkaiah Naidu, spokesman for the Bharatiya Janata
Party, accused her of betrayal and of conspiring with the Congress
Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will succeed in defeating the game plan of our political
rivals,'' he vowed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
