<HEADER>
A8396 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-FRATRICIDE-2TAK     04-14 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-FRATRICIDE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF JAPAN'S LONG TORMENT, A TALE OF MURDER IN THE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
 (rk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSAKA, Japan _ Shigeru Ishimura was hard at work at his father's
bankrupt welding company when he heard a groan coming from across
the small yard that separated the office from the factory.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing down his tools, he ran to his father's office. What he
saw there last Sept. 16 is etched into his memory as if by acid.
His uncle was slumped on the floor, a knife sticking out of his
belly. His father's hand was wrapped around the knife.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, the recession strangling Japan's economy is playing
out in personal tragedies, as business owners struggle to keep
their companies afloat, workers find themselves jobless and
housewives wrestle to stretch shrinking family budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Few of these private epics ever surface, however. Japanese take
pride in their ability to endure suffering while presenting a
serene face to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of the Ishimura family offers a rare window on the
private anguish inflicted by a prolonged recession.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost unheard of for Japanese to speak openly about
matters that shame them and their families. The Ishimuras
repeatedly resisted speaking to a reporter, who finally convinced
them to share their story after attending a trial session and
meeting their lawyer. Shigeru said he decided to speak out in hopes
of explaining what his father did and because he felt he had
nothing more to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Murders, though increasing, are rare _ only 1,338 in 1998, in a
population of some 125 million _ and fratricide is usually little
more than the stuff of bad samurai dramas. But for the Ishimuras,
the strains imposed by the recession exploded into just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lives have turned 180 degrees,'' said Kinoku Ishimura,
Shigeru's mother. ``I can't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her days now revolve around visiting her husband, Satomi, in
prison, where he awaits trial for killing his brother, Kagenori.
</P>
<P>
   The daily visits are heart-breaking. Her husband is frail and
cries frequently. Listening to an employee who was at the scene of
the murder testify in February, Satomi spent the whole court
session shaking his downcast head and grimacing in apparent horror
at the description of his own actions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Mrs. Ishimura takes heart that he is crying at all. ``His
tears have come back, and he's remembering critical moments of the
incident,'' she said. ``I think that's positive. At the beginning,
he could not even cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearings are held about once a month in Osaka before a judge who
will determine Satomi's fate. Murder can be punished by death in
Japan, but it is unlikely in this case, lawyers said, given that
this was Satomi's first crime and that he has a long history as an
upstanding citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Satomi Ishimura once epitomized the Japanese economic
miracle. Koyo Welding, the business he founded with a
brother-in-law, was a high-flying success, making metal doors for
industrial purposes.
</P>
<P>
   As the second son in his family, Satomi had made his own way in
the world. His father had doted on his elder brother, Kagenori.
``My grandfather had great expectations that his eldest son would
become something,'' Shigeru said.
</P>
<P>
   So while Shigeru's uncle was becoming something, his father
worked. ``He worked from the morning until late in the evening,
every day, all the time, and my grandfather changed his mind about
his sons,'' Shigeru said. ``He began placing a lot of faith in my
father and less in Kagenori.''
</P>
<P>
   His grandfather was not the only one impressed by Satomi's
business sense. Shigeru, who is Satomi's oldest son, remembers
bankers calling on his father, urging him to expand, expand,
expand. And expand he did, opening a second factory in 1989 and a
third in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father made some money and was a bit of a success,''
Shigeru said. ``He owned three plants and the real estate
underneath them, and he had a nice family and a good life.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the time the third factory was completed in 1991, Japan's
economic miracle had gone bust, and Koyo's business shrank and
wobbled.
</P>
<P>
   Shigeru's father tried to sell off the land under his factories
to pay off his debts, but land prices had collapsed. And the
bankers that once were so eager to lend him money now wanted to be
repaid. ``If we hadn't been so adventurous and built the third
plant, we wouldn't have had to go bankrupt,'' Shigeru said.
</P>
<P>
   He and his mother still have trouble believing the family
business failed. Instead, they say that Kagenori deliberately
ruined the business so that he could reap the profits that can be
made from liquidation. That betrayal, they believe, drove Satomi to
madness and murder.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, counters Shinsuke Ishimura, Kagenori's only son. ``I
don't know what Shigeru told you, but we were indignant at the
one-sided stories that ran in the local press that described my
father as a bad guy who tried to take over the company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He declined, however, any further discussion of the matter. ``I
talked with my relatives about whether or not I should do an
interview, and I have decided not to because for us it is a sad
story that we don't want to touch on any more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Shigeru, his mother and their lawyers insist that Kagenori
was a small-time gangster affiliated with one of the many yakuza,
or organized crime families, that rule the underground economy
here. They say he made his living by working his way into
struggling businesses and milking them to death, one of the many
shadowy enterprises that the yakuza engages in here, where
liquidation is not the respectable business it is in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``My uncle was quite good at making money out of bankruptcies,''
Shigeru said. ``He would find a company on the brink of failure and
convince the owners that they could make 1 billion or 2 billion yen
by putting their company in bankruptcy.''
</P>
<P>
   Until a year or two ago, his uncle and his father had maintained
a rather distant relationship. Then his uncle suffered a heart
attack in late 1996 and ended up in the hospital, and Satomi paid
some of the expenses, according to Shigeru.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After Kagenori left the hospital, he and Satomi grew closer.
Satomi seemed willing to give his brother a second chance, and
Kagenori seemed like a changed person.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, business conditions grew tougher and tougher for
Satomi's business, Koyo Welding. Last spring, it needed money but
no banks would extend loans and business was slow. By May, it was
effectively bankrupt, with about $17.6 million in debts.
</P>
<P>
   Kagenori suggested he had connections in the financial community
who could help bail Koyo out, so he became an adviser to the
company and started frequently showing up at the offices.
</P>
<P>
   Shigeru said his uncle offered to help his father obtain a loan,
but never did so.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Mrs. Ishimura said, Kagenori was encouraging
her husband to commit suicide. Terushi Sugimoto, a former employee
of Koyo, testified in court in February that once, over a dinner at
a restaurant, he had heard Kagenori tell his brother that many
business owners were committing suicide to take responsibility for
their companies' failures and that it was an idea he should
consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were talking and I didn't think it was good manners to
listen to their conversation,'' Sugimoto testified. ``But I did
notice the word suicide was mentioned a number of times.''
</P>
<P>
   As the company's situation continued to worsen, Shigeru's uncle
convinced his father to write promissory notes to himself in the
company's name that would allow him to get cash on a short-term
basis. To cash in some of the notes, they had to go to the black
market, where they paid more than half of the face value in fees _
and then the uncle also demanded a fee, according to Shigeru and
his mother.
</P>
<P>
   As it became clear that Koyo was headed for bankruptcy, Satomi's
mental state plummeted. ``He was different,'' Sugimoto, the former
employee, recalled in court testimony. ``His face looked different,
and the tone of his voice was like a child's. I really thought
something was the matter with him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of July, Mrs. Ishimura insisted that her husband
go to the hospital. ``He wasn't my husband any more,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   He began taking tranquilizers and sleeping pills and seemed to
stabilize.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 5, the company defaulted on one of its promissory notes,
which often precipitates bankruptcy in Japan. Satomi and his
brother quarreled over whether the company should be liquidated to
raise cash or whether, as Satomi wanted, it should pursue a
court-administered bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Mrs. Ishimura and her husband fled to a house they
had rented in a nearby suburb to escape their creditors. She had
bought a knife at her husband's instruction, and he brought it
along.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me, `Let's commit suicide together, please die with
me,' '' Mrs. Ishimura said, her eyes pooling with tears at the
memory. ``I accepted his request and was committed to die with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to change my mind after looking at my children's
faces,'' she said after a pause. ``If my children lost us, my
brother-in-law would be able to ruin our whole family.''
</P>
<P>
   She convinced her husband not to kill himself, and they returned
to their home next to the company's factory in Daito City, just
outside Osaka.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 9, Satomi met with Kagenori for the first time since the
bankruptcy. No one knows what was said between them, but Satomi
returned home agitated and restless. ``I could see immediately that
he was in a very bad state,'' Mrs. Ishimura said. ``I thought he
had gone mad.''
</P>
<P>
   With two of his sons restraining him, the family rushed Satomi
to a psychiatric hospital, where he was given medication to sedate
him.
</P>
<P>
   Midmorning on Sept. 16, the phone rang at Shigeru's house, where
the family was then staying. It was Kagenori. After hanging up,
Satomi insisted on going to the office to meet his brother.
</P>
<P>
   Keiko, Satomi's daughter, drove him there and went on to the
bank. She had just finished her errand when her mobile phone rang.
It was her brother Shigeru, telling her that her father had killed
her uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Satomi used the knife he meant to kill himself with.. He has
never attempted to deny the murder. Indeed, he directed Sugimoto to
call the police.
</P>
<P>
   When the police arrived, Satomi walked to them, thrust out his
wrists and said, ``I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the following months, the Ishimura family has regrouped. Its
savings are gone, tied up as they were in the business. Satomi's
defense has eaten up any money that materialized from the
bankruptcy and is going to cost more. The whole family is living
together in Shigeru's tiny house on a narrow street of an Osaka
suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Each of Mrs. Ishimura's days revolves around the visit to see
her husband, a trip that takes half an hour each way for an
appointment that lasts 15 minutes and takes place through glass.
Keiko, a former kindergarten teacher who is now unemployed, serves
as her mother's driver.
</P>
<P>
   Satomi's mother died recently, but the family has not told him
yet. His youngest son, Mamoru, is finishing college and working
part-time to support his family. Yutaka, another son, works in a
pachinko parlor; his income also goes to the family budget.
</P>
<P>
   Shigeru, who grew up expecting to take over his father's
business, has started his own business making fire-proof doors,
which are a necessity in earthquake-prone Japan. He is working
18-hour days. He made no money in September and October but has
been able to pay himself a small income thereafter, which he gives
to his mother.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent letter to his wife, Shigeru's father rued the day he
ever invited his brother into his life. ``His promises for
arranging loans were all fake,'' he wrote. ``It is a very stupid
story, but as president, I had a responsibility to rehabilitate my
company for my family, the bank and my employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was for that reason that I let my brother in. That was the
stupidest mistake of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
