<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ Serbian forces shell an Albanian
village as NATO capitalizes on clear weather to step up air raids
inside Yugoslavia. Meanwhile, European leaders consider a German
peace proposal that calls for a 24-hour halt to the bombing if the
Serbs begin pulling troops out of Kosovo. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-KOSOVO (Washington) _ Senators were moved to tears as
ethnic Albanian refugees told them of being forced to leave their
homeland at gunpoint. Testifying before a panel on immigration, a
pediatrician and human rights activist said she was forced out of
town late last month by Serbian security forces who ``demanded
money and beat us, both my sister and I.'' By JENNIFER CORBETT
DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NASA (Washington) _ NASA Administrator Daniel Goldin defends the
space agency's study of a possible all-female shuttle mission,
saying such a flight could inspire more young women to enter
science and engineering professions. By MIKE SNYDER. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ALBANIA-REFUGEES (Durres, Albania) _ Refugees from Kosovo are
pinning their hopes on a ground war and say it is needed if they
are to return home. By DUDLEY ALTHAUS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-CORRUPTION (Houston) _ A General Accounting Office study
has found that drug interdiction efforts in Arizona, California,
New Mexico and Texas are compromised by federal officials who are
on the payrolls of drug cartels. The report concludes that
corruption is a ``continuing and serious'' threat along the
Southwest border. By DEBORAH TEDFORD.
</P>
<P>
   QUAYLE-2000 (Huntington, Ind.) _ Taking a few swipes at Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, former Vice President Dan Quayle announces his
bid for the Republican presidential nomination by portraying
himself as a toughened veteran of ``culture wars'' and foreign
policy challenges. By ALAN BERNSTEIN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN-2000 (Midland, Texas) _ Republican presidential
candidate Pat Buchanan preaches to two choirs in Texas: to oil
producers about the ``flood of cheap foreign oil'' and to an Odessa
Veterans of Foreign Wars group on the ``debacle in Kosovo.'' By
R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   SPEED-FLAP (Houston) _ Residents of suburban West University,
upset by the number of speeding motorists, decided to take matters
into their own hands. They erected signs in their yards saying
``Slow, Children at Play.'' Then they got tickets, for violating
city ordinance prohibiting yard signs. City officials say they are
looking into the problem. By JOHN MAKEIG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NYUGEN (Houston) _ All Dat Nyugen has done over the past
four seasons is rewrite the defensive record book at Texas A&AMP;M _ a
school known for its ``Wrecking Crew'' defenses over the past
decade. Yet as the NFL Draft approaches this week, Nyugen finds
that NFL scouts still have doubts about him. He is too small, they
say. He says otherwise. By JEROME SOLOMON.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (San Francisco) _ The Houston Astros send Jose Lima
to the mound as they seek their second consecutive victory over the
San Francisco Giants. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ The Houston Rockets take on the
Vancouver Grizzlies in the first of back-to-back home games. By
JONATHAN FEIGEN. With: BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
