<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, April 15. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
EDIT-MILITARY (Phoenix) - Sp far, if anything positive can be
extracted from the war in Kosovo, it may be a resurgence in
examination of America's military history. Will the introduction of
American ground forces into Yugoslavia provoke this nation's next
Vietnam? We've heard a lot of that talk lately.
</P>
<P>
   Or will it be the next Korean conflict, where a more muscular
nearby player-state - in Korea, the Chinese; in Kosovo, the
Russians? - arrives to escalate the conflict into something truly
perilous? Story moved in the ``K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EDIT-CLINTON (Phoenix) - It is the perfect epilogue to a sorry
burlesque. Just as the cheating husband tries to sneak up the
stairs to bed, the long-suffering wife knocks him upside the head
with a rolling pin.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody deserved a figurative clobbering at the hands of justice
more than Bill ``Tom Cat'' Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately, Lady Justice _ played by Judge Susan Webber
Wright _ delivered the well-placed blow with her contempt citation
against the president. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COMPUTER-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Some days you just never know what
you'll find in the old e-mail bag.
</P>
<P>
   Take last Friday, for example. There in my e-mail box was a
message from Harold Temmer asking, essentially, whether it was
possible for a dead man to use Temmer's computer to communicate
with the living.
</P>
<P>
   You read that right. I'm not making it up. By DAVID HOYE. Story
moved in the ``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Here's one thing that I know for sure:
There's nothing funny about taxes.
</P>
<P>
   On April 14 of last year, I passed a ``tax assistance center''
on my way to get a Subway sandwich in a strip mall.
</P>
<P>
   Through the huge, clear panes of window glass, I saw the
horrible vision of a world in limbo. Patrons sat in chairs against
the walls, waiting for their turn at assault, their jowls drooping,
their shoulders hunched as they clutched their pithy W-4s as the
clock above them ticked, ticked, ticked. By LAURI NOTARO. Story
moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
WILSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ He's a symbol of rugged individualism,
masculinity and the American West. He's bigger than anybody or
anything ever dreamed up to promote a product. Not even the death
of two men who played him in commercials has dented the Marlboro
Man's deadly grip on smokers. By STEVE WILSON. Column will move in
the ``K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Undated) - The judge and prosecutors in Dr. Jack
Kevorkian's murder trial proved beyond a reasonable doubt that they
are hypocrites or fools, or both. Either way, Kevorkian is an
innocent man. If these people honestly believed Kevorkian was a
killer, they'd be prosecuting the person who helped him commit the
crime. The ``victim's'' wife. By E.J. MONTINI. Story will move in
the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL;
</P>
