<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-LUCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCK OF THE LOTTERY BRINGS JOY, SADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- As it turned out, while the Nigerian cab driver was
being hounded into hiding, the Chilean nanny was in Louisburg
Square, quietly planning a new life of profound fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts' biggest money mystery reached its denouement
Wednesday under the glare of TV lights when Maria Grasso, the
richest individual lottery winner in US history, calmly claimed her
prize.
</P>
<P>
   As she marveled at her luck and the luxury it will bring, the
winner had only sympathy for the taxi driver, who for days was
wrongly believed to hold the ticket to life on Easy Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I feel sorry for him,'' Grasso said of cabbie Patrick
Okusanya. ``I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of the two immigrants _ the man who hired a lawyer to
insist he had not won and the woman who prudently sought counsel
before emerging victorious _ is a dramatic story about reversal of
fortune and fascination with instant wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God! The babysitter's a millionaire,'' said Lisa de Roetth,
a neighbor of venture capitalist Chris Gabrieli, who employed
Grasso as a nanny and a cook at one of Boston's most exclusive
neighborhoods. ``There ought to be little miracles in life. And
there's magic in this.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are also elements that captivate lottery players and
spectators from coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   At base, specialists say, the lottery is about envy and greed,
and glee for the winner _ as long as he or she conforms to the
Horatio Alger dream that propels the betting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rags-to-riches story and deep down inside of us we all
have a little bit of envy for what someone else has,'' said Robert
Butterworth, a Pittsfield native and Los Angeles psychologist who
has studied lottery wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people are not millionaires and when somebody like us or
someone in worse shape than us wins, it reinforces the idea that
there might be a chance some day for us, too,'' said Butterworth.
</P>
<P>
   Robert H. Frank, an economics professor at Cornell University
and author of ``Luxury Fever,'' said the intense publicity
surrounding lottery winners comes from the public's fascination
with how unimaginable wealth will affect regular people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a vivid tranformation of someone's life that's just very
interesting to watch,'' Frank said. ``It's a transformation that
many of us fantasize about and we can construct a more vivid
fantasy if we can see it happening to someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of last week's Big Game jackpot, fantasy often
substituted for fact.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after officials for the six-state Big Game lottery
determined where the winning ticket had been purchased in Boston, a
fleet of television trucks and a battalion of reporters descended
on the Star Market in the Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that caromed around the city were amplified when drivers
for a local taxi firm said they had detected the winner and were
willing to provide delightful details:
</P>
<P>
   He was an African immigrant. He worked 60 hours a week. Someone
had seen his ticket. When they shouted, ``Oh my God, you won!'' the
startled cabbie drove away and did not answer radio dispatches.
</P>
<P>
   As lottery officials warned against speculation and rumor, the
search for the reluctant winner only intensified as the week wore
on.
</P>
<P>
   There was confusion about the number of the cab that the
supposed winner had been driving. There were denials from some
cabbies, secrecy from others.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, a weary Okusanya left messages on a reporter's
answering machine: ``Please I want you to stop it. For my security
reason, stop going around telling people.''
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer said flatly he did not win.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Okusanya _ pursued by network magazines and TV
tabloid shows _ emerged to deny it in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story that he won was made up entirely,'' John M. Ricci,
the attorney, said Wednesday. ``We'd love to know where it came
from. One day, his life is normal. He's going about his business.
He's got friends. He's got sports activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he wakes up to find that's all gone because the entire
world is hunting him down,'' Ricci said. ``It doesn't seem fair to
me that, based on rumor, something ends up on the front page of the
(Boston) Herald or the front page of the Globe.''
</P>
<P>
   While Okusanya vigorously denied that his fortunes had changed,
Grasso was across town, secure in the knowledge that her
babysitting days were numbered.
</P>
<P>
   She had checked her ticket against the television announcement.
Then she checked it again. ``I couldn't believe it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso put the slip of paper that carried enormous wealth into
safekeeping while she consulted with lawyers and prepared to
carefully step into the public spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get legal advice and clear (my) mind,'' she said
Wednesday, wearing a broad smile. ``This is a pretty big day for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, too, for Okusanya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for Patrick because it's going to help him get this
behind him,'' said Ricci, still confounded by the media storm that
encircled his client.
</P>
<P>
   It's a storm that has blown up before, when fate aligns the
numbers to confer vast riches on regular folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a society we are fascinated with the `big score' in any
number of ways _ whether it's what Bill Gates' net worth is this
week or what Michael Jordan makes or the latest overnight Internet
billionaire,'' said John Helyar, who has written about lottery
millionaires for Money Magazine. ``The lottery really represents
the one way that the little guy can achieve the big score.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day you're a baby sitter from Chile and the next day
you're a zillionaire. It's the one way that the Average Joe, the
blue-collar person can participate in that Big Score game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
