<HEADER>
A8418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTA-FIRE-NYT     04-14 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-FIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEROIC RESCUE PERSUADES ATLANTA'S MAYOR TO GRANT FIREFIGHTERS A
RAISE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID FIRESTONE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The loudest cheers at the ceremony honoring Matt
Moseley on Wednesday afternoon came from his fellow firefighters,
and not just because he transfixed the country on Monday in the
breathtaking rescue of a construction worker trapped high above an
inferno.
</P>
<P>
   No, Moseley became a particular hero to his colleagues with an
action the next morning that may have required even more bravado:
He urged Mayor Bill Campbell to end a longstanding feud with the
firefighters union, and give its members a long-sought raise.
Campbell agreed to do it.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoon, at Moseley's behest, the mayor sat down
with union leaders and agreed to seek a bonus of up to $2,000 for
the city's 800 firefighters, along with new breathing masks to
replace devices that the union says are defective. It was the first
time in his six years in office that he has met with the union,
which has endorsed his opponents, and it required ingesting some
crow. But he said Monday's spectacle swept away petty disputes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being there on the scene, seeing the incredible heroism, I was
truly moved,'' he said in an interview. ``I thought it was a good
opportunity for us to metaphorically overcome all our differences.
It seemed like if they could do that, and rescue this guy from a
crane in a burning building, I could certainly sit down and talk to
these firefighters.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell is a man of storied pride, and his disputes with a
lengthy series of enemies have been enduring. After receiving
repeated criticism from The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, for
example, he announced a few years ago that he would no longer read
the city's daily newspaper, a vow he insists is still in effect.
</P>
<P>
   But for both Campbell and his city, the rescue on Monday became
one of those collective moments of redemption in which an entire
populace can partake of an individual's bravery. Thousands of
downtown workers gathered open-mouthed at their skyscraper windows
watching a state helicopter lower Moseley on a rope to the edge of
a construction crane where Ivers Sims, the crane operator, lay
prostrate amid intense heat. At the base of the crane 200 feet
below, a landmark cotton-bag mill was burning in the city's largest
fire in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Millions more saw the rescue on a live television broadcast that
was carried nationally. When Campbell honored the rescue workers at
a ceremony Wednesday, throngs of small children surrounded Moseley,
begging him to sign their outstretched palms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dramatics of the moment clearly put additional pressure on
the administration, and for that matter the City Council, to do
something else for the firefighters,'' said Robb Pitts, the
council's president. ``People were saying shame on you all for not
paying them more, and the city was kind of backed into a corner by
the tide of the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he didn't know the origin of the dispute with the
firefighters, but union members and other elected officials said it
resulted from the union's endorsement of Campbell's opponents in
1993 and 1997. Last year, after the union criticized the city's
black fire chief, Campbell, who is also black, said the criticism
was motivated by racism.
</P>
<P>
   The union, whose membership is about half African-American,
denied this, and relations got worse. Earlier this year, the mayor
and the council gave a $2,000 raise to the police but not to the
firefighters, a decision that David Rhodes, the union president,
said was the ``ultimate insult.'' Firefighters make between $26,500
and $34,000, and many officials at City Hall have maintained that
their jobs are not as dangerous as those of police officers.
</P>
<P>
   When Moseley met the mayor at a television appearance Tuesday
morning, he could not resist the opportud to
be said.'' Less than a day after the helicopter set him and Sims
down on solid ground, the union's leadership had been invited to
City Hall and given almost everything they requested.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, I'm glad it happened,'' said Campbell, looking
almost wistful. ``If you don't grow and mature, then you lose the
essential nature of humanity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
