<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, April 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a burst of heavy snow whitened the landscape of
eastern Colorado as cold, moist air was directed southwest into the
Front Range of the Rockies. On Thursday, the low pressure
responsible for the late-season snow will intensify as it moves
into the Mississippi Valley, bringing a potpourri of inclement
weather to portions of the central and eastern states.
</P>
<P>
   Warm, humid air surging north from the Gulf of Mexico will set
the stage for scattered strong thunderstorms from Kentucky to
Alabama and north Georgia. A few of these storms will be quite
formidable, capable of producing hail and damaging winds. The
highest risk for destructive storms will be in Kentucky and
Tennessee. Meanwhile, a large swath of rain with embedded
thunderstorms will occur from northern Illinois to Ohio as the Gulf
moisture is lifted up and over a warm front near the Ohio River.
</P>
<P>
   A narrow stripe of wind-blown snow will fall on the northwest
periphery of the Mississippi Valley low, causing several inches to
accumulate from north-central Kansas to southern Minnesota. Farther
west, strong winds from the northwest will buffet the Plains
Thursday with local gusts near 50 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Gusty winds from the north and east will also affect the
Southwest. These offshore winds, combined with abundant sunshine,
will propel 80-degree heat to the southern California coast.
</P>
<P>
   Dry weather will cover most of the Eastern Seaboard Thursday.
Plenty of sunshine will occur across southern New England while
clouds thicken along the Middle Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Large Hail
</P>
<P>
   Baseball-sized hail pelted parts of western Texas on Tuesday
evening as a bevy of severe thunderstorms erupted. Within
thunderstorms, updrafts of air must be sufficiently strong for
embryonic hailstones to grow to large sizes while suspended high in
the subfreezing upper parts of an intense thunderstorm. Hailstones
grow as tiny water drops freeze on contact. Once they become too
heavy for updrafts to support, hailstones careen toward earth. In
the case of the Texas hailstorm, the speed of rising air must have
been at least 60 mph in order to support the giant stones aloft.
</P>
</TEXT>
