<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIA BLAMES NATO FOR DEATH OF 75 KOSOVARS  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Yugoslavia claimed Wednesday that stepped-up NATO
air attacks struck two convoys of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo,
killing 75 and injuring 25. The Pentagon said Serb forces may have
slaughtered civilians after military vehicles at each end of the
columns were hit.
</P>
<P>
   European leaders, meeting in Brussels, Belgium, with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, pondered a German cease-fire proposal
that the White House welcomed guardedly _ at the same time the
Clinton administration ruled out a quick bombing halt.
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces again shelled a region of the Albanian border near a
town that troops of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic held
briefly on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the military action and diplomatic maneuvering, NATO
spokesman Jamie Shea argued that the vise was closing on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no longer a question of if we win, but when,'' Shea
said.
</P>
<P>
   The government-controlled Serb Media Center in Pristina, capital
of Kosovo, said two columns of refugees were fired on by NATO
planes near Djakovica. In one of the incidents in southwestern
Yugoslavia, the center said, a refugee column of more than 1,000
people was hit twice. It described the refugees as mostly old
people and children.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav Foreign Ministry spokesman Nebojsa Vujevic denounced
the strike as a ``crime against humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon confirmed NATO airstrikes in
the area but said U.S. military officials did not have ``the full
facts'' about the incident. Bacon quoted U.S. Gen. Wesley Clark,
NATO military chief, as saying Serb ``military people got out and
... began to attack civilians in the middle of the convoy.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Pentagon sources said allied military personnel were
scouring in-flight tape looking for footage to buttress their
version of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO statement said allied pilots ``state they attacked only
military vehicles. We cannot confirm press reports alleging that
these attacks may have caused civilian casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO and the White House met the latest Yugoslav claim with
countercharges that Serb aircraft had begun to attack refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Shea laid another humanitarian disaster at Milosevic's feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, one of the most appalling stories is simply of large
numbers of Kosovar Albanians being herded around Kosovo like groups
of migratory cattle, sent to the border, then sent back to their
villages by Serb security forces, then told to leave again, as if
they are sort of pawns being moved around on a chess board,'' Shea
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Brussels meeting of European Union leaders, German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder outlined a proposal that would allow a
24-hour halt to NATO airstrikes once Milosevic begins to withdraw
forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The White House sought to picture the Schroeder proposal as only
an amplification of the NATO demands that Milosevic withdraw all
Yugoslav forces from Kosovo, agree to deployment of an
international security force and allow the return of Kosovar
Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair said NATO's conditions must be
met ``without compromise or half measures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions that NATO set down are the absolute minimum to
make sure this policy of `ethnic cleansing' is defeated,'' Blair
said.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said there was no guarantee the German proposal would
work, but he pledged to circulate it.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, military and administration officials,
including Army Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, briefed House and Senate members and warned, participants
said, that the NATO air campaign could last well into the summer.
</P>
<P>
   At his daily news briefing, Shea held out the hope that
Milosevic, seeing his military assets being beaten down, would
yield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had to calculate into his planning the fact that NATO is
not going to be bought off or is not going to be divided,'' Shea
said. ``And he may be a cynical man, but I think he's also, deep
down, a rational man, and eventually he will have to realize that
he has no option but to comply with the demands of the
international community.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Giuseppe Marani, a NATO military planner, said that in the
24 hours ending at noon Wednesday, five waves of NATO planes flew,
two were canceled and two missions were only partially executed
because of bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said the attacks focused on bridges, air defense, command
installations, fuel installations and lines of communication.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
