<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE DEMOCRATS BEGIN DRIVE TO FORCE VOTE ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE
REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Democrats on Wednesday launched a petition
drive to buck Republican leaders and force a vote on campaign
finance overhaul. It marked the opening salvo in a battle over the
issue that promises to be as spirited and convoluted as it was last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Although majorities in both houses of Congress support
legislation to impose more stringent controls on campaign
contributions, particularly the unlimited and unregulated donations
known as ``soft money,'' Republican leaders have blocked such
changes since their party took control of Congress in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   A similar petition drive last year forced House leaders to allow
legislation sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and
Martin Meehan, D-Mass., to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   But the leaders used a variety of procedural tactics, including
weeks of truncated late-night debates, to delay the vote until late
in the year and then block a vote in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats said that this year's petition drive was an
attempt to compel action earlier this year and give proponents a
better chance to rally the support necessary for legislation to
pass both chambers before next year's campaigns kick into high
gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must act now, in a non-election year,'' Rep. Tom Allen,
D-Maine, said on the House floor on Wednesday morning. ``If you
thought that the presidential election year of 1996 was awash in
soft money, 2000 promises to be a deluge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill finally got 61 Republican votes and passed
the House by a decisive margin of 252 to 179 votes last August just
before Congress' summer vacation. But the Senate, which had seen a
companion measure filibustered to death earlier in the year, had no
appetite for another go-round.
</P>
<P>
   This year's petition, sponsored by a group of conservative House
Democrats headed by Rep. Jim Turner of Texas, would limit the
debate on the Shays-Meehan bill or any alternative measures to a
maximum of 17 hours. The petition needs 218 signatures, or a simple
majority of House members, to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   By early Wednesday evening, 184 Democrats and the one
independent member of the House had signed it, a measure of the
ardor Democrats bring to the issue and their desire to put
Republicans who oppose campaign finance overhaul on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Although enough Republicans in the House support such
legislation so that it will likely pass once it comes up for a
vote, none had signed the petition by early evening. For the
moment, they were heeding insistent appeals from party leaders to
leave the timing on campaign finance overhaul in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker, Rep. Dennis Hastert of Illinois, told reporters at
a news conference on Wednesday: ``I expect some kind of campaign
finance reform bill will come forward sometime this year. But I
can't tell you when.''
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats accused Republican leaders of once again trying
to doom legislation by delaying it and said that the House must
pass a bill in the next few months if there is any chance for a
measure to muster the requisite number of votes in the Senate,
where it faces more formidable obstacles, especially from Sen.
Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell heads the Republican Senatorial Campaign Committee,
which provides money to candidates, and the Senate Rules Committee,
which handles election law legislation. Last year, he led the
successful filibuster that killed the bill in the Senate. Only 52
senators of the 60 needed voted to bring the bill to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Asked on Wednesday if he would take the same steps to prevent a
bill from coming up for a vote this year, McConnell answered, ``Is
grass green?''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the co-sponsor of the Senate
version of the campaign finance bill with Sen. Russell Feingold,
D-Wis., expressed guarded optimism for a bill's chances in the
Senate this time around. ``There's a much better opportunity if the
House passes it early on,'' he said in an interview on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill would not only eliminate soft money but
also severely restrict the ability of independent groups to plow
money into advertisements that attack or endorse candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of such regulations say they are necessary to lessen
the influence of wealthy interests in campaigns; opponents like
McConnell say the regulations would restrict free speech and
unfettered participation by Americans in the political process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an utter disaster,'' McConnell said of such a scenario,
adding: ``That kind of bill is not going to pass the Senate just
because it'll pass the House.''
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely that kind of resolve that the Democrats hope to
overcome by beginning a petition drive earlier this year than they
did last year and inaugurating it with such a dramatic flourish.
</P>
<P>
   They gathered by the dozens for a news conference outside the
Capitol on Wednesday morning, then marched en masse up the steps
and onto the floor of the House to form a dense, snaking line in
front of the petition.
</P>
<P>
   If the number of petition signers neared 218, Republican leaders
might move to bring the legislation up under rules and procedures
they could control _ as they did last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
