<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-GAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY NET OFF 16.8 PERCENT IN 1998 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Fidelity Investments, the nation's biggest mutual fund
firm, said Wednesday that net income plunged 16.8 percent last
year, mostly due to big spending on technology projects and work to
remedy in-house systems for the millennium computer bug.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston-based fund behemoth reported revenue rose 15.3
percent to $6.8 billion from $5.9 billion, mostly on the strength
of Fidelity's ownership of Colt Telecom Group plc, a booming
telecommunications company based in London.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers show that while returns by Fidelity's funds have
improved dramatically, privately-held Fidelity is struggling to
regain an edge with investors.
</P>
<P>
   After years of sluggish performance, Fidelity stock funds are
once again doing well. Last year they had their best gains in five
years, beating 73 percent of their competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity portfolio managers, now more disciplined and better
supervised, have forsaken wild bets of recent years to focus on
high-returning large company stocks. Research teams and personal
review processes have been beefed up, and the firm has spent
heavily to use legendary stockpicker Peter Lynch as a sales magnet.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes haven't translated into strong sales.
</P>
<P>
   While Fidelity's net sales of mutual funds of all stripes nearly
doubled last year to $32.6 billion, sales of stock funds _ the
company's benchmark product _ dropped by half. Fidelity said it
recorded 1998 net sales of $8.5 billion in equity funds, far below
the nearly $15 billion it took in during 1997. It also sold $4.4
billion in bond funds and a whopping $19.8 billion in money markets
funds last year, figures that reflect investor caution during a
volatile market.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast the Vanguard Group, a big competitor, took in nearly
$49 billion last year, according to Financial Research Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the lower sales, Fidelity's 24.4 percent growth in assets
under management, to $765 billion, came mostly from last year's
rising stock market. A bull market translates into heftier fees,
which are calculated as a percentage of assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``While reasonable, Fidelity's overall corporate results were
somewhat disappointing,'' said Eric Kobren, publisher of the
independent Fidelity Insight newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   There are other challenges at the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Fidelity's renewed focus on its flagship mutual-fund
operations, including recent sales of non-core businesses, the firm
is once again looking to avoid putting all its eggs in one basket.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the highly-successful Colt, which Fidelity acquired
several years ago, Fidelity chairman Edward C. ``Ned'' Johnson III
wrote in the report that Fidelity ``must continue to make strategic
investments that may bear fruit in the future and diversify our
business to be less subject to stock market cycles.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also said Fidelity must balance growth by retaining
``the entrepreneurial spirit of a small company'' _ no mean feat
for the giant, which manages the retirement funds of on in four
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, long intrigued by technology, throws hundreds of
millions of dollars at pet technological projects every year.
Rather than buy from vendors, Fidelity designs all its own computer
systems. It is spending heavily to create a sophisticated
voice-recognition system to enable customers to trade via telephone
and has beefed up its Web-based trading capabilities. Over 70
percent of Fidelity's commissionable brokerage trades were
conducted on line last year, more than double 1997's amount.
</P>
<P>
   While Fidelity declined to state how much it spent on technology
last year, the firm will spend a total $300 million readying its
systems for Y2K, according to Jim Lowell, publisher of the
independent Fidelity Investor newsletter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
