A8433 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKFARM15-COX     04-14 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKFARM15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black farmers to divvy $2 billion settlement
 &HT;    By Peter Scott
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Roughly 20,000 black farmers will divide up to $2
billion in the settlement of a 2-year-old race discrimination
lawsuit against the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, approved by U.S. District Judge Paul L. Friedman
and announced Wednesday, is believed to be the largest recovery in
a U.S. civil rights case. Black farmers on average will get
$100,000 to $200,000, estimated Alexander Pires, the lead attorney
representing the farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so happy to get this over with after two years of
litigation,'' Pires said from his office in Washington. He conceded
that some black farmers are opposed to the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   And Friedman acknowledged in his 66-page opinion that the
settlement does not correct years of discrimination that has led to
a decline in the number of black farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ... proposed settlement ... will not undo all that has
been done. Despite that fact, however, the Court finds that the
settlement is a fair resolution of the claims brought in this case
and a good first step towards assuring that this kind of
discrimination that has been visited on African American farmers
since Reconstruction will not continue into the next century,'' the
judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Agriculture Dan Glickman said he believes the
settlement is fair and just. ``We will work to quickly and
efficiently implement this settlement agreement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Georgia's estimated 1,329 black farmers are expected to
meet in Macon on Saturday to discuss the judge's decision, said
Melvin Bishop, president of the state chapter of the Black Farmers
and Agriculturalists Association.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of Friedman, the settlement contains a provision
allowing a panel of retired judges to review settlement claims in
individual cases of discrimination. Arbitrators in those cases will
answer to Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, worked out by Pires, civil rights attorney J. L.
Chestnut of Selma, Ala., and government attorneys, awards farmers
with limited proof of discrimination $50,000, plus $12,500 to pay
taxes on that amount. Their USDA debts will be written off,
boosting damages for individual farmers to between $100,000 and
$200,000. Farmers with more far-reaching claims can take them to an
arbitrator for possibly higher settlements.
</P>
<P>
   In their lawsuit, black farmers charged that for the last 15
years, the USDA has discriminated against them by violating the
1964 Civil Rights Act and the Equal Credit Opportunity Act when
processing applications for farm programs and loans. The farmers'
claims were supported by studies, the USDA, and an admission by
Glickman that they were treated differently.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
