</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DEALERS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lobbying gets heavy over bill on car sales
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Internet is never mentioned in a 15-page bill
passed by the General Assembly this year to regulate relations
between auto manufacturers and the franchise dealers who sell their
cars.
</P>
<P>
   But several groups outside the auto industry are lobbying Gov.
Roy Barnes to veto the legislation out of concern that it will harm
consumers' ability to find better deals by buying products online
and will undercut the state's efforts to promote high-tech
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can buy a book, a CD or an airline ticket over the
Internet, I don't see why I shouldn't be able to buy an
automobile,'' said Richard Keck, attorney for the Georgia
Electronic Commerce Association. ``In Georgia, we're trying to be
seen as a pioneer in electronic commerce. This bill would be a
smack in the face at that.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Barnes has been silent on the bill. The governor faces a
May 3 deadline for signing or vetoing the bill. After that, it
becomes law automatically.
</P>
<P>
   The bill says auto manufacturers cannot ``offer to sell or sell,
directly or indirectly, any new motor vehicle to a consumer in this
state, except through a new motor vehicle dealer.'' It also makes
it illegal for a manufacturer to ``engage in business as a
dealer.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Davis, an attorney for King &AMP; Spalding, which represents
General Motors, thinks ``this would certainly prohibit sales over
the Internet by the (auto) manufacturer.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Dubose Porter (D-Dublin), who sponsored House Bill 356,
argues that car makers are whipping up the Internet issue to kill a
bill that gives dealers protection from heavy-handed manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers, who are committed to heavy overhead costs, felt
threatened when Ford recently made an unsuccessful overture to buy
stakes in several north Atlanta Ford dealerships. They worried Ford
would find ways to favor the dealerships it partially owned.
</P>
<P>
   Auto dealers have a powerful lobby, with their bill carried in
the Senate by Majority Leader Charles Walker (D-Augusta), one of
Barnes' key African-American supporters in his 1998 election
campaign. On the other hand, Barnes has portrayed himself as a
high-tech advocate by launching an expensive state initiative to
educate engineers to feed Georgia's growing electronics industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Industry Association, which represents more than 100
businesses employing more than 82,000 Georgians, and the Georgia
Textile Manufacturers Association are among those lobbying Barnes
to veto the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Barnes is wisely investing tax dollars in promotion
of intellectual capital and high-tech industry development,'' said
James A. Adams Jr., president of GIA. ``But it will be worth
nothing if Georgia's public policy prohibits Internet sales by the
product makers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Morie, president of the Georgia Automobile Dealers
Association, said he was surprised groups outside the auto industry
care so much about an auto bill. ``Somebody's fueling this fire,''
Morie said. ``It's scare tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech economics Professor Mark J. McCabe, a former
economist with the Antitrust Division of the U.S. Justice
Department, said the bill would protect dealers at the expense of
consumers, who he thinks would tend to pay more for cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The antitrust laws of this country are meant to protect
competition in the marketplace, not competitors,'' he wrote in a
recent letter to Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
