A8435 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREAKNIK-CONVENTIONS1     04-14 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREAKNIK-CONVENTIONS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Few problems predicted for conventioneers in Atlanta over
Freaknik weekend
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the past, there have been occasions when they mixed
like oil and water. But this weekend, officials expect few problems
between visitors in town for Freaknik and those in the city for
conventions and meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason is the city expects a smaller Freaknik crowd,
said Bill Howard, vice president of marketing, tourism and
communications for the Atlanta Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau. Last
year, an estimated 50,000 were in town for the annual street party,
and even that was down from previous years.
</P>
<P>
   It reached chaotic proportions in 1995, when about 200,000
Freaknik visitors converged on the city, clogging downtown streets
and interstates.
</P>
<P>
   What the city doesn't want is a repeat of 1997, when TruServe,
parent company of True Value Hardware, held a convention of 15,000
retailers in Atlanta during Freaknik weekend. Conventioneers were
so upset by the crowds and traffic jams that Mayor Bill Campbell
went to Chicago later and apologized to TruServe's president and
chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do feel, based on the amount of interest _ or lack of
interest _ that we've seen, that the event is likely to be smaller,
and we are anticipating the impact on conventions and activities in
the city will not be significant,'' Howard said. ``In the past,
we've gotten a lot of inquiries, but the calls are way down this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, to be ``responsible,'' Howard said the bureau passes on
as much information as possible to groups coming to the city during
Freaknik weekend. He said the city's traffic plan will help keep
congestion around downtown to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Convention planners are doing their part as well. Many said they
have gotten wise to the goings-on of Freaknik and often schedule
events at the convention site so attendees have few reasons to
venture outside.
</P>
<P>
   Others contract with bus companies to ferry conventioneers
around and advise exhibitors to ship freight in advance to avoid
delays
</P>
<P>
   Several conventions will be in town during the Freaknik weekend,
according to the ACVB calendar, including: the Military Chaplains
Association of the USA, which will bring 125 participants; the
International Tunnel &AMP; Turnpike Association, with 300; and the
International Association for Management Education, with 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We booked this piece of business about five years ago,'' said
Anita Craig, director of conferences for the International
Association of Management Education. ``It wasn't until much later
that we became aware of the possibility that we would be happening
in concert with this activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig estimates about half the convention visitors will arrive
on Saturday for the IAME conference at the Atlanta Hilton. Several
events, including a tour of CNN and a reception at the World Of
Coca-Cola at Underground Atlanta, won't occur until Freaknik is
winding down or ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're really trying to do is to get some information from
city officials about strategies for traveling,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, some conventions end right before Freaknik begins
or starts on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   For instance the Association for Information &AMP; Image Management
convention, which was expected to bring about 37,000 people, ends
today, but some people likely will stay over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to be an issue for us,'' said
spokesman Evan Weisel. ``The exhibits end at 4 p.m. on Thursday and
we will start breaking down that afternoon through the night.''
</P>
<P>
   But conventions and Freaknik won't be the only draws in the city
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Atlanta Hawks take to the courts against the Orlando Magic
at 7:30 p.m. Friday at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   _ About 1,200 people have paid between $50 and $75 each to
attend the Biltmore Diamond Jubilee from 5:30 p.m. until midnight
Saturday. The event is a benefit for the Atlanta Preservation
Center.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also on Saturday, there will be a 7:30 p.m. semi-pro soccer
league game at DeKalb Memorial Stadium on North Indian Creek Drive.
Traffic leaving the soccer game will not be allowed to exit onto
Memorial Drive. Instead, it will be routed from North Indian Creek
Drive through Clarkston to Ponce de Leon Ave., and Interstate 285
North.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
