<HEADER>
A8436 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTH-WILDFIRES15-COX     04-14 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-WILDFIRES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dry season filled with wildfires expected in South
 &HT;    By John Harmon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fields too dusty to plant in South Georgia. Wildfires
flaring up from the Everglades to the Appalachian Mountains. A
Chattahoochee River tumbling whitewater down from the North Georgia
hills at less than half its normal volume.
</P>
<P>
   A dry winter and spring are slowly pointing toward a drought
summer throughout most of Georgia, Florida and parts of Tennessee,
Alabama and the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   The trends indicate the summer of 1999 could return the region
to the parched 1980s, a time when water shortages plagued metro
Atlanta, farmers suffered crop failures and reservoirs like Lake
Lanier dropped water levels to show muddy, red banks all summer
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get some significant rain in the next month, we
will experience the same drought conditions we had in the 1980s,''
predicted Jack Bushong, a hydro-meteorologist with the Southeast
River Forecasting Center, a branch of the National Weather Service
that predicts stream flows.
</P>
<P>
   An indication of a likely drought in Georgia is the fact that
all major rivers in the state are flowing at one-third to one-half
of normal this month, a time when those streams should be cresting
from spring rains, Bushong points out.
</P>
<P>
   Already, scores of wildfires are scorching chunks of the
Southern landscape from the mountains to the sea.
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, the dry weather contributed to a brush fire
along Ga. 400 Wednesday afternoon. Thick smoke from the pine-straw
blaze halted northbound traffic for about 15 minutes and caused a
traffic backup to Interstate 285.
</P>
<P>
   In Tennessee, jail inmates and the Air National Guard were being
used to battle forest fires in the central and eastern sections of
the state. More than 4,000 acres have burned in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, where raging wildfires last year ruined the Fourth
of July tourist season, Gov. Jeb Bush on Tuesday declared a state
of emergency and may call out the National Guard to help fight
fires popping up from the fringes of Miami in the south to near
Jacksonville in the north.
</P>
<P>
   The past two days, Georgia has had more than 200 wildfires
covering more than 6,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Campers were evacuated from Stephen Foster State Park in the
Okefenokee Swamp last weekend in the wake of a 600-acre blaze that
is still burning. In the high country of North Carolina, the U.S.
Forest Service has banned all campfires expect those in designated
fire rings and grills in the Pisgah and Nantahala National forests.
</P>
<P>
   Climatologists are blaming the trend on La Nina, a cooling of
Pacific waters off the coast of South American that affects global
weather. While El Nino is famous for bringing storms to North
America, experts say La Nina tends to cause drought in the
Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   The wildcard in all the predictions by weather experts is the
fact that La Nina years also tend to produce more tropical storms
and hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could get all the rain back at once and that's not
necessarily a good thing,'' says Mike Helfert, director of the
Southeast Regional Climate Center in Columbia, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   For now, what concerns experts is that winter and spring rains
were far below normal throughout much of Georgia. That is the time
of year when rain and snow seep into the earth to recharge the
groundwater tables. It is groundwater boiling up from springs that
feed rivers like the Chattahoochee and Etowah during the normally
drier summer and fall seasons. The Chattahoochee, which flows into
Lake Lanier, and the Etowah, which flows into Lake Allatoona,
provide most of metro Atlanta's drinking water. Right now, both
lakes are three feet below normal for April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a concern for us, but it's too early to draw any
conclusions,'' said Rob Holland, spokesman for the U.S. Army Corps
of Engineers, the agency that manages the two reservoirs vital to
Atlanta. ``The weather can change pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the Southeast Region Climate Center scientists are
predicting that current drought conditions in Florida and South
Georgia will likely expand northward over the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long-range forecast is for hotter than normal and dryer
than normal this summer,'' says Helfert. ``Atlanta could be in for
a long, hot and dry summer. And there are lot more people there to
put demands on the water supply than 13 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past several weeks, a weather pattern has emerged that
blocks most of the moisture of cold fronts from reaching Georgia,
Florida and parts of the Carolinas, Alabama and Tennessee, said
Helfert.
</P>
<P>
   A ridge of hot, dry air is holding steady over the Southeast.
The wedge of higher pressure is forcing cold fronts to go north and
what moisture does make it through the ridge falls only as light,
scattered showers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take a powerful cold front to break through this
ridge, but we are running out of time for that to happen,'' Helfert
added.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
