<HEADER>
A8438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-DEBATE-700&AMP;ADD     04-14 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-DEBATE-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI PRIME MINISTER CAUGHT OFF GUARD DURING LIVE TV DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is usually the
supreme master of the television screen, his gaze more direct than
any anchor's, his language more focused, authoritative and
articulate than any other politician's in this country.
</P>
<P>
   And so it astonished Israelis to see him unfocused, rattled and
on the defensive in a live, informal debate Tuesday night with his
former defense minister, Yitzhak Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai, the Center Party candidate for prime minister,
skewered his former boss as untrustworthy, while the prime
minister, looking ashen-faced and stunned, shuffled his papers as
if searching for the best response. Ehud Barak, the Labor Party
candidate, chose to absent himself, perhaps with keen foresight,
since he emerged as above the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Close associates have never seen Netanyahu, the Likud Party
leader, at such a loss for words.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai, with a knowing smirk on his face, not only jabbed at
Netanyahu's weak spots but also mocked him, sometimes laughing at
the prime minister's answers.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Netanyahu by his nickname, Bibi, he attacked him as
Barak never could, from the vantage of someone who knows well how
the prime minister behaves behind closed doors. Mordechai described
him as too impatient to listen to others during Cabinet meetings,
and too arrogant to interpret defections from his Cabinet and from
his party as reflections on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there is something really wrong with you, with your
values, your behavior and your trustworthiness?'' Mordechai asked,
staring at the prime minister. ``What? Everyone's wrong and only
you're right?''
</P>
<P>
   The judgment by Nachum Barnea, a political columnist for Yedioth
Ahronoth, a leading Israeli newspaper, was, ``Netanyahu, the
television wiz, was beaten on his home court.''
</P>
<P>
   One television critic likened it to an episode of ``The Jerry
Springer Show'' titled ``Israeli Prime Ministers and the Defense
Ministers Who Hate Them.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also the most riveting moment so far in a campaign that
has been strangely lackluster: ``a long drawn out, dismal play in
which there has been little ado about nothing,'' in the words of
the writer Gideon Samets.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that last night was important, even very
important, a kind of turning point,'' said Yaron Ezrahi, a
political scientist at Hebrew University, speaking on Wednesday.
``It offered the first public evidence that Netanyahu is
defeatable. It showed the chinks in the armor of the invincible
political manipulator. Can the emperor in `The Emperor's New
Clothes' recover by getting dressed and reappearing in the parade?
That is the question.''
</P>
<P>
   In the attenuated election race, which began in December when
Netanyahu's right-wing coalition government was dissolved, all
three major parties have been vying for the many voters in the
political center by de-emphasizing their ideological differences.
It has made for dull interaction.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu and Barak have been running neck in neck in the polls,
with Mordechai trailing. But many Israelis do not trust the polls
since they failed to predict Netanyahu's victory in 1996. Political
commentators here like to twist an adage, saying Israelis tell the
truth to the pollsters, but lie in the voting booth.
</P>
<P>
   For this debate, television viewership was very high, with 44
percent of the 1.5 million Israeli households watching, more than
saw the popular Miss Israel beauty pageant.
</P>
<P>
   For many the debate seemed to underscore two things: that the
race is a referendum on the performance and credibility of
Netanyahu, who may be showing uncharacteristic signs of strain, and
that Mordechai, underestimated throughout his career, plays a
pivotal role, even if it is more as spoiler or kingmaker than as
potential prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, political commentators noted that Netanyahu's strategic
accomplishment during the debate was to push Mordechai to say
publicly that he would not withdraw. If Mordechai did pull out and
join forces with Barak, polls indicate, they would trounce the
prime minister in the first round of voting. With Mordechai in, no
one will get a majority on May 17 and there will be a run-off
election on June 1, the polls show.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The freewheeling debate sizzled with the unresolved tensions
between the politicians. Early this year, Netanyahu dismissed
Mordechai as defense minister, and he did so live on television, at
the top of the evening news. Mordechai almost immediately left
Likud to lead the fledgling Center Party, whose principal aim is to
oust the incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting back, Netanyahu called it ``a party of losers'' that
stood for nothing but ``hate'' _ of him.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other Cabinet members, Mordechai had never publicly aired
his disagreements with Netanyahu. Popular with Israelis for what
they perceive as his decency, he is not known for personal attacks.
Perhaps then Netanyahu did not expect the assault; perhaps he was
tired from round-the-clock campaigning while continuing to run the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israeli voters may have been turned off by Mordechai's
treatment of a prime minister. ``Bibi, relax, don't lose your
cool,'' Mordechai said at one point, laughing at him. ``I know what
you look like when you lose your cool.''
</P>
<P>
   When Netanyahu tried to portray himself as the leader who
oversaw an era relatively free of terrorism, Mordechai immediately
retorted that he, as defense minister, was in charge of security.
</P>
<P>
   Like boxers, both candidates had teams who rushed in to freshen
their makeup and offer strategic counsel during commercial breaks.
But Sima Kadmon, a political writer for Yedioth Ahronoth, did not
think that Mordechai, motivated by the desire to ``exact
retribution against his ex-boss,'' needed all that help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mordechai didn't need any coaching,'' she said on Wednesday.
``He didn't need any papers. The person scrambling after the papers
and charts was, oddly enough, the grand master of television. He
lost his tongue last night.''
</P>
<P>
   One adviser to Netanyahu likened the event to the Nixon-Kennedy
debate in 1960, saying Netanyahu won the debate on ideas _ there
was some discussion of issues _ but lost it in body language.
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts said the real winner was Barak, whose chief
opponent's character was brutally attacked _ by someone else. Barak
chose on Wednesday to dismiss both opponents in the same breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we saw last night was a good show for television,'' he
said. ``It gave a lot of insight into the way the country was
managed for the last two and a half years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
