<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8442 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTTERY-WINNER-BOS &LR;      04-14 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-WINNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILEAN IMMIGRANT CLAIMS $197 MILLION LOTTERY PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ AND JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRAINTREE, Mass. _ She lived in one of the grandest homes on
Beacon Hill, a brick townhouse in exclusive Louisburg Square. But
until last week, Maria J. Grasso was hired help, a live-in
babysitter who cared and cooked for the four children of
multi-millionaires Chris and Hilary Gabrieli.
</P>
<P>
   Not any more.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Chilean immigrant who has spent the last three decades
caring for other people's children, is richer than her former boss.
And as the single winner of the $197 million Big Game lottery _ the
second largest jackpot in U.S. history _ she'll never have to work
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had the time to think clearly but I have a lot of
plans. I want to help my family with this big fortune,'' Grasso
said Wednesday, standing before a slew of reporters at State
Lottery headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso, a 54-year-old divorced mother of two, wore a crisp navy
suit speckled with gold at the wrist and along the collar _ one of
the few indulgences she has made since her windfall, said her
attorney Robert Jahrling.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour before the press conference, Jahrling deposited
Grasso's check for $70,244,814.02 _ her lump sum payment minus
$34.5 million in taxes. It amounts to $104 million because she
chose a lump sum payment, rather than the total amount spread out
over 26 annual installments.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement laid to rest intense, persistent speculation
that a Nigerian taxi driver named Patrick Okusanya had won. On
Friday, after published reports included his full name, Okusanya
sought the help of an attorney to set the record straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not win,'' he insisted, even as rumors grew that the
winning ticket was locked in his attorney's safe.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso, for one, said she felt bad for Okusanya and wished she
could've spoken up earlier, but couldn't because she wanted to
consult lawyers first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt sorry for him,'' Grasso said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with a faint accent, Grasso recounted the moment that
changed her life.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday night, she sat down to watch the nightly news and
jotted down the lottery numbers as they were drawn. She debated
with herself over whether she should check her ticket right then or
wait until later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to check them right away but then I said, `Oh, I
will check them,' and I did and I couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   In one hand, she held the numbers she had written down. In the
other was the winning ticket. But, she thought, how could she have
won?
</P>
<P>
   So she waited anxiously till the end of the news, and checked
again when the winning numbers were flashed one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it. I couldn't believe it,'' Grasso said.
``I couldn't sleep that night. I couldn't believe it could be me. I
thought, `It can't be me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That night, Grasso said she kept the ticket by her side on the
bed. The next morning, she told Hilary and Chris Gabrieli _ and she
quit her job.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso said she had purchased three tickets at the Star Market
in Boston's Fenway neighborhood while shopping for groceries for
the Gabrieli family. Grasso said she usually doesn't play the
lottery, but was enticed by the signs declaring the huge jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   She purchased one ticket with three chances to win, picking the
numbers randomly. The odds of winning the jackpot: one in 52
million.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso said while she doesn't have specific plans for the money,
she will ``take care of my large family'' including her parents in
Santiago, Chile, as well as her daughter and son, both college
students raised in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In her native Santiago, Grasso's jackpot quickly became national
news. At 12:30 p.m., Grasso's older sister, Ana Luisa Becerra
appeared on Television Nacional de Chile.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very good sister,'' Becerra said. ``She will help us
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Becerra said that Maria has labored all her life and deserved to
win. ``She suffered. She had to go outside the country and help
support us.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour after Becerra appeared on television, reporters had
surrounded the family home in La Reina, a tree-lined neighborhood
on Santiago's east side. The family ultimately fled to a hide-a-way
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Louisburg Square Wednesday, peals of laughter and whoops
of delight rang out from the Gabrieli kitchen, where the Gabrieli
children were watching Grasso on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our Maria,'' said one young voice. ``Oh, yay! Hooray
Maria!'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   The downstairs windows were covered with black paper to block
prying eyes of reporters _ a sharp contrast to the openness of the
family during Gabrieli's failed campaign for a seat in Congress
last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Gabrieli, a venture capitalist and co-Chairman of MassINC., a
public policy institute, spent $5 million on his failed campaign.
He placed sixth in last summer's primary.
</P>
<P>
   The news of Grasso's fortune rippled past the potted topiary
shrubs on the Gabrielis' home and quickly spread throughout the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Substitute postman Chris MacDonnell said he had not met Grasso,
but he'd sure like to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanna know her so I can ask her to marry me,'' said
MacDonnell. He added that already has a wife, but she might
understand.
</P>
<P>
   But one prim neighbor scoffed at the idea of going public with
the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gabrielis are being so open,'' said the woman in a smart
black suit who declined to give her name. ``I wouldn't tell a soul
if I won.''
</P>
<P>
   Grasso lived with the Gabrielis for 2 1/2 years, and came to
know them as a second family, particularly since her grown children
were away at college.
</P>
<P>
   While Grasso declined to give details about her children,
associates said her son is studying for the priesthood in New
Jersey and her daughter is married and studying in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso was 26 when she arrived in New York City in 1971 to visit
a friend, but liked the city so much she decided to stay, said Ray
Howell, a public relations representative she was urged to hire.
Howell said he's unclear whether she arrived with a visa allowing
her to visit.
</P>
<P>
   She married in 1976, but it ended a decade later. Her first job
was very much like her last _ a live-in nanny.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her time in New York, Grasso tended to find jobs as a
caregiver. She was a teaching assistant at a day treatment center
for mentally disabled adults, and later in the Staten Island public
school system while working part time for United Cerebral Palsy of
New York State.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso earned a General Education Diploma in New York and
attended college there, but ultimately moved to Boston in 1996. A
newspaper ad led her to a full-time, live-in job with the Gabrieli
family.
</P>
<P>
   Though she'll never have to work again, Grasso said she intends
to stay involved with special-needs children and those with
physical disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can't do it physically,'' Grasso said. ``This would be a
chance for me to give something.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Jonathan Franklin contributed to this story,
reporting from Chile.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
