<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8446 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNSEL-LAW-ART-NYT &LR;      04-14 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNSEL-LAW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR DEFENDS HIS ACTIONS AT HEARING INTO FUTURE OF INDEPENDENT
COUNSEL LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Mich., Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rebuked by Democrats at a Senate hearing Wednesday,
Kenneth Starr defended his prosecutorial tactics and judgment in
the investigation of President Clinton's relationship with a former
White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to go out on the steps of the courthouse and
say, `The prosecutor is out of control,' '' Starr declared
indignantly when senators referred to him as a legal zealot whose
inquisitorial approach had ignored professional standards for
federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr, whose professorial demeanor cracked several times
during the hearing, said that the courts had never reproached him.
``How frequently does the judge supervising the grand jury say,
`The prosecutor is out of control'? To us, none. Not once have we
been found to have conducted ourselves inappropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   In more than three hours of testimony at a hearing of the Senate
Governmental Affairs Committee, which is considering changes in the
independent counsel law, Starr insisted that he had followed
Justice Department rules that apply to all federal prosecutors.
Democrats expressed skepticism at Starr's announcement that he
opposed reauthorizing the statute that had created his multipronged
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you live long enough, you'll experience everything,'' said
Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., after Starr defended his own
inquiry while he recommended jettisoning the independent counsel
law, whose failings were underscored for many lawmakers through
Starr's own conduct in the Monica Lewinsky case.
</P>
<P>
   Sen Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., who is not a Governmental Affairs
Committee member, issued a statement saying that Starr's remarks
were ``like Jack the Ripper calling for more neighborhood patrols
because of the surge in victims.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has told Starr that it plans to open an
inquiry into his operation, including his handling of Ms. Lewinsky
at the outset of the inquiry. It will also examine whether Starr
failed to disclose possible conflicts of interest in January 1998
when he asked Attorney General Janet Reno to expand his
jurisdiction to investigate the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry has been slow to get under way because of conflicts
between Starr and Ms. Reno over how it will be conducted. Ms. Reno
has wanted to ensure that she retains her authority to discipline
independent counsels, and Starr has insisted that no investigation
should undercut his independence from the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans sought to shelter Starr from partisan attacks. Sen.
Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., the chairman of the panel, lavished praise
on Starr's prosecutorial record, saying that he had obtained a
dozen guilty pleas and convictions and ``weathered withering
attacks, some of which were exceedingly personal and
vituperative.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., regarded as one of the Senate's
most knowledgeable students of the independent counsel law,
criticized Starr for conduct not intended under the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my judgment, you've gone beyond what an average prosecutor
would do in the investigation of a private citizen,'' the senator
said, adding: ``You've spent millions investigating possible
perjury in a civil suit that top prosecutors of both political
stripes who were not personally involved in the matter have said no
reasonable prosecutor would pursue.''
</P>
<P>
   Also testifying about the independent counsel law was Judge
David B. Sentelle, the head of the panel that appoints such
counsels, who said that lawmakers could not expect the panel to
review the conduct of those they appoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``My answer is that the panel can exercise no or at least
virtually no oversight,'' he said, because the Supreme Court had
ruled that such an oversight function would erode the authority of
the executive branch.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard J. Durbin, D-Ill., asked Starr what he would do if
the statute was not renewed when it lapses in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the statute lapses the independent counsel is called upon
to make a professional judgment as to whether it is required that
he continue certain matters,'' Starr said. ``And that's a judgment
that I haven't had to face yet. But presumably I may or will have
to face that on June 30th.''
</P>
<P>
   Durbin shot back, ``And it is possible that Congress may
intervene and decide that in its judgment it's time for you to head
off to some university, or whatever your future plans may entail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to do that once, senator,'' Starr responded, referring
to a plan he once had to take an academic post at Pepperdine
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you did,'' Durbin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't work out,'' Starr went on. ``But maybe you can do it
for me, senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Durbin stared at Starr. ``Be careful what you wish for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
