A8448 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRS-SENATE-NYT &LR;      04-14 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL APPLAUDS CHANGES AT IRS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A year after sharply criticizing the Internal
Revenue Service, saying it abused taxpayers, members of the Senate
Finance Committee praised the new tax commissioner, Charles O.
Rossotti, Wednesday for beginning fundamental reforms.
</P>
<P>
   But they were far from sure that the problems had been entirely
solved. Republicans expressed fear that abuses would continue,
while Democrats warned that reform would fail without more
financing. Sen. William V. Roth Jr., R-Del., who is chairman of the
committee, in praising Rossotti for his initial reform steps, said
he was implementing the spirit as well as the letter of the IRS
restructuring law that Congress passed last year.
</P>
<P>
   Then he began pressing Rossotti about who had been disciplined
for past abuses and what was being done to create a culture ``that
is intolerant of abuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti replied that he disciplined 12 officials in September
for using dollar quotas in collections. He said such quotas had not
only been banned but also that he had made regulations that would
result in new ways of measuring performance, such as how well
officials serve customers, as the IRS now calls taxpayers. He
detailed several changes he had made to encourage the flow of ideas
within the agency and to protect whistle-blowers from even subtle
forms of retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Connie Mack, R- Fla., said he was concerned that despite
the outrage flowing from last year's hearings ``SWAT-team tactics''
were increasing. He cited a report on Tuesday by William H.
Webster, former director of the FBI and CIA, about abuse of
taxpayers by IRS criminal investigators.
</P>
<P>
   But Webster, whose report cited isolated examples of misconduct
but no systematic abuse, did not dispute the need for armed raids.
He said only that agencies with more appropriate training should
conduct them on behalf of the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti, who said that he expected his $8.2 billion budget to
be the same next year, outlined plans to retrain all employees and
replace an outmoded computer system.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Democrats said that without extra money the costs for
training and new computers would have to be financed by making deep
cuts in audits and other enforcement actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to collect what is owed,'' said Sen. Kent Conrad,
D-N.D., and a former tax commissioner of that state. He said that
IRS audits of the highest income taxpayers had fallen to 1 in 60
last year from 1 in 9 a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., who has played a crucial role in
changing the IRS, repeatedly pressed for more financing, but none
of the Republicans said a word about increasing the IRS budget.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, the IRS budget, adjusted for inflation, has declined
5 percent, while the number of tax returns has grown nearly 12
percent and tax collections have grown 62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey emphasized the need for the independent nine-member IRS
oversight board that was called for in the IRS restructuring act,
``so its chairman can come before this committee and say, `Sen.
Roth you are making our job of reform hell because you are not
getting us the money we need to do the job.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton missed a January deadline to appoint six citizens to the
board, which will also include the tax commissioner, the Treasury
Secretary and an officer of the Treasury workers union. Senators in
both parties were critical of delay.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Toiv, a White House spokesman, responded that the law set
an unrealistic deadline for finding the six citizens and
investigating their backgrounds. He said the appointments would
soon be announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
