<HEADER>
A8445 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-CARTER15-COX     04-14 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-CARTER15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It takes a village to make a Carter
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOCHIEL, South Africa _ Here, they call him Musa.
</P>
<P>
   The word means ``kindness'' in Zulu, but Jason Carter says
that's not necessarily why these villagers on the eastern edge of
South Africa call him that. It just happens to be a common name.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear, though, is that they love him. Everywhere he
walks, people hail him from the yards of their huts or from the
roofs they are repairing, and he answers in fluent Zulu, sharing a
joke, a smile, a wave _ and, it seems, more than a little of
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was up to me, I would stay with him forever,'' said
Lucky Sipho, an occupational therapy assistant who lives in
Lochiel. ``I wish he could be in South Africa to be employed
permanently.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Carter has given something to Lochiel, a little village
that time and Pretoria have forgotten, it is obvious, too, that
Lochiel has given something back to him.
</P>
<P>
   For in this village, while serving in the Peace Corps, Jason
Carter _ grandson of former President Carter, great-grandson of
Peace Corps volunteer Lillian Carter _ has found himself.
</P>
<P>
   To watch him in action is to see someone fully alive. He brims
with vitality. He lopes up the village hills. He grins as he greets
the multitude of friends he has made. He cannot wait to explain the
insights he has gained into South Africa, and everything he sees _
a house, a road, even the telephone wires _ reminds him of
something else he's figured out about the place.
</P>
<P>
   His mind is so active, there will never be time enough to tell
it all. The words tumble one over the other in his excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, 23, is the son of Jimmy Carter's son Jack, a commodities
trader. He left Atlanta on Jan. 16, 1998, as part of the second
group of Peace Corps volunteers ever to serve in South Africa. By
August, when the fourth group of volunteers arrives, about 110
volunteers will be in the country.
</P>
<P>
   After three months of training, both in Zulu and more generally
in how to be a Peace Corps volunteer, Carter arrived in Lochiel on
April 14 of last year.
</P>
<P>
   He lives in a masonry cabin, part of a hotel built by a Scotsman
in the 1920s. The room is bare but for a bed, some shelves and
Carter's laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   On one shelf sit two caps _ one bearing the logo of the Atlanta
Falcons, the other from the USS Jimmy Carter, a nuclear submarine
the Navy named last year in honor of his grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Carter spends his spare time these days reading ``Taking
Charge,'' a book based on Lyndon B. Johnson's White House tapes.
But his most prized possession _ the only thing he says he's ever
felt like showing off to other people _ is another book: ``Long
Walk to Freedom,'' the autobiography of South African President
Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the front cover, the book bears this inscription: ``To
Jason, Musa, Best wishes to one of our impressive future leaders.
Nelson Mandela. 6-4-98.''
</P>
<P>
   The main job of Peace Corps volunteers in South Africa is to
help rural schools recover from the effects of decades of neglect
under the apartheid policy of ``Bantu education.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bantu Education Act was introduced in 1953 by Hendrik
Verwoerd _ the apartheid government's minister of Native Affairs
and later prime minister _ who described its purpose this way:
``Natives will be taught from childhood to realize that equality
with Europeans is not for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bantu education was opposed prominently by an anti-apartheid
activist named Nelson Mandela, who said at the time that it was
``an inferior type of education designed to relegate Africans to a
position of perpetual servitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was that in the early 1970s, the government spent 16
times as much on each white student as on each black one. Although
that disparity was cut in half toward the end of the apartheid era,
the effects of that official neglect will linger for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Sisukumile Secondary School in Lochiel, for example, has no
electricity, no science lab, not nearly enough textbooks and no VCR
or television to show instructional videotapes, said the principal,
July Amos Tshabalala.
</P>
<P>
   The average class size is 60. Most parents are illiterate,
unconvinced of the benefits of education and unsupportive of their
children's studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids do not have role models,'' Tshabalala said. ``They
have no one to emulate.''
</P>
<P>
   The government pays the teachers' salaries, but nothing else,
Tshabalala said. To meet the school's other expenses, he charges
each student 30 rands a year, about $5. He tried to double the fee
last year, but backed down in the face of a strike.
</P>
<P>
   With 700 students, that gives him a budget of $3,500. Of that,
he spent $1,500 burglar-proofing the school. About $470 went to buy
paper. Then there's money for sports _ uniforms, balls and other
equipment _ and precious little else.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are those the only problems, said Carter. It is not uncommon
to see a child having an epileptic seizure in school for lack of
medicine. Some children walk long distances to school and faint in
class for lack of food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any really grandiose ideas about how much I'm
going to accomplish,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   But he is trying to make small improvements where he can _
improvements that will last after he has gone. He is teaching
administrators to use a computer that was donated by an outside
organization a year ago, but never turned on. He is helping set up
a library at the secondary school, where he also works once a week
as a guidance counselor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing a great job,'' Tshabalala said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter works mostly with the primary school, where he is having
teachers meet regularly so they can help one another solve
problems. He is helping implement a new outcomes-based education
curriculum _ geared more to problem solving than to stuffing
students with facts _ that is being put in place nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   And when he runs into trouble, he consults Serena Hayes, a
teacher who is a Peace Corps volunteer in a nearby village, a sight
that initially stunned the people of Lochiel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see that I'm a white male and she's a black woman, and
I'm asking her for help,'' he said. ``Which is a big thing. It's a
sight to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter has seen the Third World before, having worked with the
Carter Center in the Caribbean, Africa and the Middle East. What
astonishes him most about South Africa is not that Third World
conditions exist, but the contrasts that persist within the
country.
</P>
<P>
   In upscale suburbs of Johannesburg, with their concentrations of
Mercedeses and malls, one could just as well be in London or New
York or Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But in Lochiel, as in much of rural South Africa, people live in
traditional homes made of mud and sticks and the schools have no
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really want people to understand about South Africa,''
Carter said. ``And one thing you've got to understand is that it is
a First World country. And the other thing you have to understand
is that it is a Third World country.''
</P>
<P>
   In the city, there is a stock exchange. In the village, there is
no water safe to drink.
</P>
<P>
   All around him, Carter sees metaphors _ the highway on which
cars whiz by without even knowing they've passed a village; the
electric wires that run overhead without stopping. Traffic,
telephones, electricity and progress have passed by Lochiel as if
it were not even there.
</P>
<P>
   But Carter stayed, and it has been to his benefit.
</P>
<P>
   When he leaves the Peace Corps next year, the Duke University
graduate will probably go to law school. It will be hard for him to
leave Lochiel, Carter said, but he knows that, in important ways,
the gifts of Lochiel will never leave him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' he said, ``is where I've become who I'm going to be.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
