<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8455 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADVANCED-MICRO-LOSS-N     04-14 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVANCED-MICRO-LOSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCED MICRO DEVICES POSTS HUGE LOSS FOR QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With the market already limping from Tuesday's
earnings report by Intel Corp., the massive first-quarter loss
reported Wednesday by Advanced Micro Devices Inc. sent investors in
technology stocks scrambling for the exits, leaving NASDAQ with a
75-point drop, its eighth largest point decline ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen a permanent _ and I emphasize the word
`permanent' _ change in the microprocessor business, and I don't
think prices will ever recover,'' said Drew Peck, an analyst with
S.G. Cowen. Noting that the basic design behind Intel and Advanced
Micro's microprocessors is now 20 years old, he said that ``PCs and
microprocessors have stagnated in their technology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No longer is the PC business driven by technological
advancement,'' Peck said. ``It's driven purely by price.''
</P>
<P>
   And the brutal price competition of the last two years is now
exacting a heavy toll.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro had warned on three occasions that the quarter
would be weak, and the actual loss was slightly smaller than
analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended March 28, Advanced Micro reported a loss
of $128.4 million, compared with a loss of $62.7 million in the
comparable period a year ago. Revenues rose 17 percent to $631.6
million, from $540.9 million in the first quarter of 1998. The
results for the first quarter include a charge of $15 million for
restructuring and other special charges.
</P>
<P>
   AMD's loss was equivalent to 88 cents a share, or 81 cents a
share without the restructuring and other charges. Analysts, who
had been projecting a loss of 9 cents earlier in the quarter, had
by Wednesday upped that to 92 cents, according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues declined 20 percent from the $788.8 million reported in
the fourth quarter, which ended Dec. 27, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Those results, widely viewed as devastating, further clarified
what Intel's modest revenue shortfall Tuesday only hinted at _ that
the pricing environment for microprocessors, the silicon brains of
personal computers, is the worst it has ever been.
</P>
<P>
   But while Intel eked out earnings of 57 cents a diluted share _
in line with analysts' expectations _ through manufacturing
efficiencies and cost savings _ Advanced Micro struggled to make
projected volumes of its AMD-K6-2 microprocessors, particularly the
faster chips, which command higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   And on top of disappointing first-quarter results, Intel warned
Tuesday that second-quarter sales would be flat or slightly lower,
a direction the company attributed to seasonal factors.
</P>
<P>
   Further fueling investor anxiety Wednesday was the fact that
both chip makers' earnings reports followed a warning from Compaq
Computer Corp. on Friday that its first-quarter results would fall
far short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, this week has also seen strong comebacks by two
recently troubled technology companies. Tuesday, Motorola Inc.
reported a 20 percent rise in profits, mostly as a result of its
cellular telephone business, and Apple Computer Inc., which was all
but written off by the market in the last few years, Wednesday
released solid net income well above analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro shares closed Wednesday at $14.75, down 75 cents,
on the New York Stock Exchange. Intel closed at $57, down $3.50, in
NASDAQ trading.
</P>
<P>
   At least for the immediate future, the basic arithmetic leaves
little hope for much improvement. With a $500 personal computer
offering most of the performance and features of a $1,500 PC,
nearly all of the industry's growth has shifted to the low end.
There is no room for a $500 microprocessor in a $500 PC, so the
bulk of Advanced Micro and Intel's sales volume has shifted to less
costly chips.
</P>
<P>
   Intel can still make respectable profit margins with
lower-volume high-end chips for workstations, but Advanced Micro,
which does not make a workstation-class microprocessor, saw the
average price for its processors drop to $78 during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   At National Semiconductor Corp., whose Cyrix unit has also
shared in that pain, chief executive Brian Halla blamed ``Intel's
jihad against AMD and AMD's production problems'' for the weakness
in the microprocessor business. Last month, National reported a
smaller than expected loss for its third fiscal quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Wednesday, AMD chairman and chief
executive W.J. Sanders said, ``The best thing that can be said
about the first quarter is that it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders added, ``The significant decline in revenues reported by
AMD in the first quarter was almost entirely due to previously
reported AMD-K6-2 microprocessor yield issues.'' Yields improved in
the final weeks of the quarter, he said, asserting that the company
believed it would hit its goal of shipping five million units in
the current quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Peck remained skeptical. ``If they spend enough time and money,
presumably they can iron out the kinks in the manufacturing
process,'' he said. But he added that even if the yields can be
improved, there would be no foreseeable letup in pricing pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Intel, execution is quite good,'' he said, ``so some of
this is being disguised. For the time being, there's the appearance
of normalcy at Intel, but underneath they are facing the same kind
of turmoil.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
