<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8450 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-TURNER15-COX     04-14 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-TURNER15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S. Africa feels like home to ex-Georgian
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOCHIEL, South Africa _ Moses Turner has traveled such a long
road since his childhood in the Timothy Road neighborhood of
Athens, Ga., that he has almost come full circle.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in the Georgia of the 1940s and '50s, the son of a
carpenter and a maid. Water in his neighborhood had to be drawn
from a well. Turner was the first person from his community ever to
go to college.
</P>
<P>
   But he couldn't go to the University of Georgia, even though it
was in his back yard, because UGA in 1958 accepted no black
students. So he attended Albany State, in southwest Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to school, the best I could hope to be was a
teacher or a preacher,'' he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end his career took a different arc. After serving in
the Army in Germany, where he developed an interest in
international travel that never left him, he became a dean at Texas
Tech and then spent 15 years at Michigan State, part of that time
as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from Timothy Road to become one of the chief executives
of a major educational institution _ ``that's a fair jump,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at the age of 60, Turner has turned his career in a
different direction. As the new country director for the Peace
Corps in South Africa _ he began work here in March _ he is working
with a black population struggling to recover from years of racial
segregation, inferior education and an internalized sense of low
status that has outlived the official end of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   It's a job for which he feels well-prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see many circumstances here which reflect the experiences of
a black growing up in rural Georgia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Turner still has ties to Georgia. His daughter, Shaul Turner,
was until recently an on-air reporter with Atlanta's WXIA, and his
sister, Myrtle Scott, owns a string of barbershops in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Turner plans to be an active country director, consulting often
with South African authorities and checking on Peace Corps
volunteers in the villages where they serve, just as he recently
visited Jason Carter, the grandson of former President Jimmy
Carter, in the village of Lochiel, near South Africa's border with
Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
   The Peace Corps, unwelcome here during the apartheid era, has
operated in South Africa only since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, volunteers serve only in two provinces _ Mpumalanga
and the Northern Province _ and only in villages.
</P>
<P>
   Turner would like to expand to other provinces over time _ and
to the townships, the sprawling, densely populated areas that are
home to many poor urban blacks.
</P>
<P>
   But the issues in the townships are more complex, and the safety
of volunteers there is more troublesome, so for now, he said, the
Peace Corps will stick to the villages.
</P>
<P>
   Turner believes the Peace Corps in South Africa can fulfill its
original mission more fully than it has yet anywhere in the world.
One step is having a far more diverse group of volunteers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the world, only about 3 percent of Peace Corps
volunteers are nonwhite. In South Africa, the number is more than
35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That allows people in South Africa to see the true diversity of
the United States, and it compels volunteers, as they live and
train with other volunteers, to work through their own feelings
about race, Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the international spotlight on South Africa as it
works to make its 5-year-old democracy function, the operation here
can be the flagship for the Peace Corps around the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do it well, people will know about it,'' he said. ``If
we screw it up, people will know about it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
