<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8451 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALA-LOTTERY15-COX     04-14 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-LOTTERY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama lawmakers approve lottery
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ Critics invoked the Bible, Sunday school,
innocent grandchildren and cherished Mommas, but even in this
bedrock conservative state, it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   State senators approved Gov. Don Siegelman's controversial
lottery bill Wednesday, clearing the way for residents to vote on a
referendum to establish state-sponsored games to fund education.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a historic moment for the state of Alabama,''
Siegelman said at a news conference after the vote. ``The future of
generations of Alabama children is now in the hands of the
voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he signs the legislation, Siegelman will set the date for
the referendum, which some officials said could come as early as
October 12 when Birmingham and Montgomery hold municipal elections.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina also appears headed for a vote on a statewide
lottery this year. Both the House and Senate have passed lottery
bills and are now working out the differences between the two
versions.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, the 24-11 vote on the constitutional amendment
already approved by the House came after lottery opponents staged a
16-hour filibuster that carried over into the wee hours Wednesday,
with bleary-eyed, gravel-voiced senators trading hourlong turns at
the podium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't some little old bill that doesn't mean much,''
railed Sen. J.T. ``Jabo'' Waggoner, a leader of the small, mostly
Republican coterie of lottery opponents. ``This is an issue that
will affect our lives and our state for generations to come. This
is not what I want to be remembered for.''
</P>
<P>
   But Waggoner and other doomsayers were swept aside by a tide of
pro-lottery sentiment triggered in part by the success of Georgia's
lottery and the gambling-fueled boom along the Mississippi Gulf
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that hundreds of millions of dollars have left
this state to buy lottery tickets in other states,'' Siegelman said
Wednesday as he prepared for the campaign to sell the lottery to
voters. ``We want to capture those dollars and keep them Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia officials have said it's too early to tell if an Alabama
lottery might hurt sales there.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0415-C     04-14 1611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0415-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A DAY DISASTER, DIPLOMACY AS NATO BOMBING CONTINUES
 &HT;    1100&AMP;add
 &HT;    With JOURNAL-KOSOVO-0415; KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0415;
KOSOVO-TROOPS-0415.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ U.S. and NATO officials launched a probe
Wednesday into an apparent military attack that killed as many as
70 ethnic Albanians in a refugee convoy moving through Yugoslavia's
embattled Kosovo province near this border outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the incident were sketchy and in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   By late Wednesday, however, investigators with the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) said refugees
reporting firsthand knowledge of the incident suggested that the
attack was staged by Serb troops who wanted to make it appear that
the killings were the work of NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking to my guys on the radio, they are convinced it's a set
up,'' Owen O'Sullivan, head of the OSCE field office in Kukes, said
late Wednesday night. The OSCE is a multinational organization
based in Vienna that groups the United States and more than 50
countries from western and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a lot of stories (from refugees) that suggest it
was not NATO,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The convoy disaster occurred as Germany floated a peace proposal
that reportedly would allow Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic,
president of Yugoslavia, a 24-hour reprieve in the NATO air
strikes, if he agrees to the terms the alliance has set forth for
peace.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials said the initiative was a
``constructive'' step toward keeping the diplomatic door open. They
dismissed out of hand, however, a suggestion by Milosevic that
United Nations monitors might take the place of NATO peacekeepers,
as the alliance has insisted upon, once the current conflict ebbs
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very useful effort and a necessary effort to begin
reflection in the alliance,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said of the
German proposal. ``But it's simply at the moment what you might
call a food-for- thought paper, a discussion paper, to provoke this
necessary reflection.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from halting the bombing, officials with the Clinton
administration insisted that they would continue to intensify the
air campaign. The point was underscored with the deployment of 24
additional F-16 fighter/bombers and four more A-10 combat attack
jets. The aircraft, part of some 80 fresh warplanes and refueling
tankers the Pentagon approved last weekend for the NATO mission,
are due to arrive at Aviano Air Base in Italy on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By this weekend, the Pentagon is likely to order 300 more
warplanes and support craft to join the mission, said Pentagon
spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the first of 24 Apache combat helicopters were
scheduled to fly out of Germany on Wednesday and arrive at a base
in Albania on Thursday. All of the helicopters were scheduled to be
in place in Albania by Saturday, though it wasn't clear how soon
they might be flying missions into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will persist relentlessly, and with determination, until
the crisis ends on acceptable terms,'' Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said in Washington. ``Serb security forces must leave so
that the refugees can re-enter, an international security presence
must be permitted, and the people of Kosovo must be given the
democratic self-government they have long deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic offered no such guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Citing mounting reports from eyewitnesses inside Kosovo, State
Department spokesman Jamie Rubin for the first time officially
accused Serb forces of using rape as a weapon of terror in a
campaign of repression that has driven up to 1.4 million ethnic
Albanians from their homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It often takes time to confirm these reports,'' Rubin told
reporters, ``but there are so many credible reports from throughout
Kosovo that the conclusion is inescapable that Milosevic's forces
are using rape as a weapon of terror in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of the continuing atrocities unfolding inside
Kosovo, the Pentagon produced a detailed map identifying more than
100 villages and towns across the tiny province that have been
torched, shelled or otherwise destroyed by rampaging Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said NATO had verified at least three areas inside Kosovo
where military units continue to shell civilians, and the
Pentagon's Bacon said U.S. officials have received reports in
recent days of Serb helicopter attacks on refugee convoys.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the reports had not been independently verified. They
echoed earlier incidents that were verified, however, by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said NATO had also received reports of three more mass
graves, including one near Pristina reportedly containing 100
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most appalling stories is simply of large numbers
of Kosovar Albanians being herded around Kosovo like groups of
migratory cattle, sent to the border, then sent back to their
villages by Serb security forces, then told to leave again, as if
they're sort of pawns being moved around on a chess board,'' said
Shea.
</P>
<P>
   ``This permanent movement, lack of shelter,'' Shea said, ``is
producing incidences of typhoid, cholera, scabies and pulmonary
infection.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials estimate that there are somewhere
between 500,000 and 750,000 ethnic Albanians inside Kosovo that
have been driven from their homes. Many are concentrated in rugged
mountain areas more than a mile high, with little if any food or
shelter, to escape the depredations of the marauding Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO pressed its around-the-clock air campaign into their
23rd day with fresh attacks early Thursday, Shea said the
intensifying pressure the raids are placing on Serb forces in the
field and their support structures around Yugoslavia were quickly
turning the tide against Milosevic and his army.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Pentagon officials showed clips Wednesday of successful
attacks over the previous 24 hours on 14 major targets in Kosovo
and elsewhere across Yugoslavia -- a huge fuel storage and
distribution center in the provincial capital of Pristina, a
bridge, a railroad tunnel and other sites -- as well as tanks,
armored personnel carriers and military trucks supporting Serb army
and police forces.
</P>
<P>
   With NATO building toward a 1,000-aircraft armada over the
coming week, Shea said the arithmetic of the campaign is working in
favor of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day Milosevic has less, and every day we have more,''
said Shea. ``So this situation cannot go on indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   In a harrowing new episode in the Kosovo crisis, refugees in a
convoy along a road near the southwestern town of Dakovica came
under a withering attack.
</P>
<P>
   Two starkly different versions of events quickly emerged.
</P>
<P>
   State-run television in Yugoslavia blamed the attack on NATO
pilots, saying they bombed the refugee convoy.
</P>
<P>
   If correct, that would be the single worst case of civilian
casualties in the three-week-old air campaign and the second major
incident this week involving civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Footage of the catastrophe was replayed over and over in
Yugoslavia, replete with scenes of children and elderly people
alike weeping and nursing what appeared to be serious wounds, after
their rag-tag convoy of tractors, wagons, livestock and carts came
under attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said the issue is being investigated and details
could be available as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters in Brussels, pilots involved in the mission
told U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO supreme allied commander,
that they bombed military vehicles shortly after 3:30 p.m. (local
time) in the area where the convoy was attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They believe they hit only military vehicles,'' Bacon told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots, and the forward command aircraft that guide each
plane's individual bombing run, are under orders not to bomb unless
they can identify their target.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to tell the difference between a tractor and a
tank,'' said Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles Wald. ``Unless they're
sure, they will not drop.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark told Bacon that he had received independent, but not yet
verified, reports that Serb troops had positioned military vehicles
near the front and rear of a refugee convoy. Clark was
investigating reports that the Serbs, after being hit by the NATO
attack, turned their fury on the civilians, attacking them with
gunfire and grenades.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he might have intelligence imagery to support that
claim as early as Thursday. He was looking into whether an unmanned
surveillance aircraft, a drone called the Predator, was in the area
at the time of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what the full facts are,'' Bacon said. ``We have
what Gen. Clark believes to be the facts, but he says the whole
thing is under review.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan had two teams of OSCE investigators trying to track
down what happened to the refugee column that came under assault en
route to this border town earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   He said none of the refugees who spoke to his teams said they
believed the assault came from a NATO plane.
</P>
<P>
   A translator for the humanitarian group Doctors of the World
said a woman had been treated in the white medical tent around 5:30
p.m. (local time) for wounds she said were caused by a hand grenade
or bomb. The woman had been transported out and had not given a
clear story of how she sustained the wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8453 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0415-C     04-14 1611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0415-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A DAY DISASTER, DIPLOMACY AS NATO BOMBING CONTINUES
 &HT;    1100&AMP;add
 &HT;    With JOURNAL-KOSOVO-0415; KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0415;
