<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran upbeat about modest profit
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AirTran regained some financial altitude in the first
quarter, posting a modest profit that beat analysts' forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's second-largest airline also said cash reserves grew,
lessening the threat of a liquidity crunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're feeling better about the year than we did in January,''
said Chairman and Chief Executive Joe Leonard, who took over the
Orlando, Fla.-based carrier's recovery effort three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran Holdings Inc. reported a profit of $3 million, or 5
cents a share, vs. a loss of $7.9 million, or 12 cents a share, a
year earlier. Revenue rose to $119.9 million from $94.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had predicted a loss of 3 cents a share, according to
First Call. AirTran stock rose 47 cents to $5.47 in heavy trading.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly profit was only the second since ValuJet acquired
AirTran in 1997 and adopted its name. The enlarged carrier made
money in the spring quarter of 1998 but then fell back into the
red.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, an industry veteran who has brought in other top
managers, announced the first-quarter results on the last day of
Robinson Humphrey's investment conference in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   He said the rebound reflects the growing success of several
prior initiatives, such as business-class service, along with
stabilizing costs after two years of restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Ridership grew 14.8 percent on a 9 percent seat capacity gain in
the quarter. ``We are starting to get repeat customers. I think
we're building sort of a cult following,'' said Leonard, who
acknowledged low fuel prices also played a role.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said he expects few route changes in 1999 but added that
the carrier has asked for government help in gaining access to key
airports, such as Newark and Washington-Reagan National.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson Humphrey analyst James Parker said AirTran ``isn't out
of the woods yet.'' He said the carrier is benefitting from
enormous travel demand and ``spill'' traffic from Atlanta rival
Delta Air Lines, which reports first-quarter earnings today.
</P>
<P>
   Parker also said Delta may be softening its competition with
AirTran because of political heat on big carriers over service and
predatory tactics.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran said cash reserves, which had dwindled to $24 million at
the end of 1998, grew to $58 million at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said AirTran is negotiating for financing to buy 50 new
Boeing 717 jets. It's to get eight 717s this year, starting in
September. Leonard said the plane's arrival ``will transform this
company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will dramatically lower our operating costs and will
indicate that we're back and back for real with the most modern
equipment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard also said AirTran recently won approval to fly Defense
Department personnel, which should boost revenue growth. As
ValuJet, the carrier had failed to get defense approval, based in
part on a review of operations and safety. A defense spokesman did
not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
