<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-PERU15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth seeks share increase
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth Corp. plans to tighten its grip on the
Peruvian communications company in which it invested two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said Wednesday that BellSouth will offer 50
cents a share _ about $16 million _ to boost its share from 59
percent to at least 74 percent control of Tele 2000, a company that
has 237,000 customers for its wireless phone service, cable
television and paging.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth plunked down $112 million to purchase its initial
stake in the company, which then had a license to serve only the 7
million people in the Lima area. Since then, Tele 2000 has won the
right to serve the rest of Peru, whose total population is more
than 24 million people.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is the largest outside investor in Latin American
telecommunications. Last year, with uncertainty about the region's
economy rising, BellSouth basically passed on the chance to win new
licenses in Brazil, but extended its investment in other
properties. BellSouth also increased its share of telecom companies
in Ecuador and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   The stock in Tele 2000 is being sold by a still unnamed partner
in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
