<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Overall executive pay skyrockets
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Executive pay, already stratospheric, advanced 36
percent last year, thanks to pay structures that linked
compensation to the stock market, Business Week (April 19) reports.
Through big stock option grants, the average CEO earned $10.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   But that's peanuts compared to the top CEOs, headed by Walt
Disney Chief Michael Eisner's $575.6 million. The biggest portion
of that annual compensation _ $569.8 million _ was in stock options
and other long-term compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The others in the Top 5 were CBS chief Mel Karmazin, $201.9
million; Citigroup's Sanford Weill, $167.1 million; Stephen Case of
America Online, $159.2 million, and Intel's Craig Barrett, $116.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola chief M. Douglas Ivester ranked 10th at $57.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are staggering,'' said Business Week, ``but so is
the performance of America's business.'' Top pay in 1998 was 442
percent better than it was in 1990, reflecting the decade's
business boom and related bull market in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders have become increasingly angry during the '90s at
the size of executive pay, but Business Week notes it's not a new
issue.
</P>
<P>
   In 1933, irate shareholders filed the first lawsuit over pay
after America Tobacco Co. paid President Georgia Washington Hill
$1.3 million. It did some good, because a year later the then-new
Securities and Exchange Commission decided shareholder proposals on
pay and other issues should be included in the proxies voted on at
annual meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Puncturing market
</P>
<P>
   Money (May) takes a look at well-known pillars of investing
wisdom, debunks some of them and points out how the others have
been misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks are supposed to outperform bonds over the long term, for
example. While true, the size of the annual return may fall below
the alleged 10 percent to 12 percent annual rate by the time
transaction costs and other expenses are factored in.
</P>
<P>
   Of more value, perhaps, Money adds a new section in its May
issue dedicated to helping individuals use the Internet as an
investment source.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Mutual Funds (May) focuses on mutual fund groups specifically
for retirement planning.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the ``whatever happened to'' department, U.S. News &AMP; World
Report (April 19) says Texas billionaire and two-time presidential
candidate Ross Perot is ``all business now'' after the Feb. 2
initial public stock offering of his technology services company,
Perot Systems.
</P>
<P>
   _ The U.S. economic ``model'' is held to be the clear world
winner, but The Economist (April 16th) says the performances of
other nations compares favorably in terms of good and bad points.
Germany is the closest rival.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
