<SLUG> BC-WARNER-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER POSTS POSTS HEFTY EARNINGS GROWTH FOR QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Time Warner Inc. said Wednesday that it posted a
solid profit in the first quarter based on strong growth at its
cable television networks and the Warner Brothers film studio.
</P>
<P>
   Net income for the first quarter was $138 million, or 10 cents a
share before preferred dividends, compared with a loss of $62
million, or 12 cents a share, in the comparable quarter a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for Time Warner and Time Warner Entertainment, which
includes the company's stake in Warner Brothers, Home Box Office
and the majority of its cable systems, rose 2 percent, to $6.2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Operating cash flow, or earnings before interest, taxes and
amortization, rose 47 percent, to $1.25 billion, compared with $852
million in the quarter a year earlier. Analysts and investors use
cash flow to analyze the performance of indebted companies like
Time Warner because it focuses on how the underlying businesses are
doing.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the company's business segments performed well, and some
had turnarounds. The film studio, which had struggled, saw profits
jump to $346 million from $119 million. However, $215 million of
that leap was attributed a pretax gain from the early termination
and settlement of a long-term video agreement with
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Inc., a unit of P&AMP;F Acquisition Corp. Without
that gain, the division's profit, fueled by the success of new
releases such as ``You've Got Mail'' and ``Analyze This,'' rose 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Dixon, who follows Time Warner for Paine Webber, said the
earnings were better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Still, shares of Time Warner fell $3.50, to $73.50.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings for Home Box Office jumped a record 20 percent, to $184
million, compared with $153 million in the quarter a year earlier.
Both subscription and ad revenue showed strong growth.
</P>
<P>
   The cable division also reported a stronger performance as cash
flow rose to $403 million, compared with $381 million in the
quarter a year earlier. That was a 10 percent increase after taking
into account some transactions last year.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings Wednesday with analysts and reporters, Time Warner
chairman Gerald Levin said the music division would be a key area
for growth on the Internet. And though Time Warner does not have a
separate company related to the Internet, Levin did not rule out
creating one. Analysts think he may do so with Roadrunner, CNNfn or
Columbia House.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it planned to spin off its operations that
provide businesses with telephone systems. The operation, which is
not a strategic fit for Time Warner, had 1998 sales of $122
million. The company did not put any time frame on the spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The telephone business is a different area of the company,''
said John Tinker, who follows the company for Nationsbanc
Montgomery Securities. ``It is capital-intensive and it is not a
core part of their business.''
</P>
<P>
   And the company said it was creating five Internet ``hubs'' for
common interest groups for its businesses, including entertainment,
life style, news, sports and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is to create a common engine underneath the five
that would provide each with the normal services provided by an
Internet portal such as e-mail and chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a consumer could go to the business hub at CNNfn
and get business news from CNNfn, Fortune and Money, chat with
investors and do stock transactions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
