<SLUG> BC-ROB-HUMPHREY-CONFERENCE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring founder hints of future deals
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Could MindSpring acquire the Microsoft Network or
strike a deal with a telecommunications company? Neither is out of
the question, according to Charles Brewer, MindSpring founder,
chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft might not be in the ISP (Internet service provider)
business for the long haul,'' Brewer told the standing-room-only
crowd at the Robinson-Humphrey Institutional Conference at the
Ritz-Carlton Buckhead. MSN is Microsoft's online service with
approximately 2 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer told the audience to watch for ``relatively dramatic
announcements'' regarding DSL, or digital subscriber line, and
content partnerships. Brewer is cautiously optimistic about the
possibilities of striking a deal with telecom companies such as
BellSouth to offer MindSpring DSL service. He said once-strained
relations with telecom companies were easing:
</P>
<P>
   ``They want the traffic. They don't care if it's over their own
network or MindSpring.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's comments may be indicators of what MindSpring plans to
do with money raised Wednesday from its public offering of 2.76
million common shares and an offering of 5 percent convertible
subordinated notes due in 2006 for $179.98 million. The offerings
were conducted under its shelf registration for up to $800 million
of debt and equity securities. Industry analysts say the money is
being put in reserve for MindSpring's growth. The company won't say
just how much money it raised from the offering, but based on
current stock valuations the amount could total approximately
$469.78 million.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer did acknowledge that current valuations in the IPO, or
initial public offering, market may slowacquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
