<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHIVES-RECIPES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Versatile chives good place for novice to start
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The stand of chives in the garden is already 8
inches tall. There is plenty to try these and other recipes. The
plant will just keep growing. For a summer-long harvest of new,
tender leaves, cut the plant back after flowering.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, when recipes call for chives they are best added at
the end of any cooking time because heat dissipates their flavor
and color.
</P>
<P>
   Mashed potatoes seem like cold-weather comfort food, but the
addition of lemon peel and fresh chives bridges the seasons. For
mashed-potato lovers, these are a wonderful addition to your
repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   MASHED POTATOES WITH LEMON AND CHIVES
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup snipped fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds Russet potatoes, cut into 1-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup buttermilk, warmed
</P>
<P>
   Melt 3 tablespoons of the butter in a small, heavy skillet over
low heat. Add garlic and saute 1 minute without browning. Mix in
lemon zest and chives. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cook potatoes in a large pot of boiling, salted water until
tender, about 15 minutes. Drain. Return potatoes to pot and mash.
Add the chive mixture and 1/3 cup of buttermilk and the remaining 3
tablespoons butter. Mash together. Add remaining buttermilk if
necessary to achieve the proper texture. Season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per person: 346 calories; 17.6
g fat; 47 mg cholesterol; 220 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recipe from Bon Appetit
</P>
<P>
   Chefs who have used herbs in all kind of flavored oils naturally
came up with chive oil. It is a pretty green oil with a light chive
taste. Don't be tempted to use extra-virgin olive oil, which can
overwhelm the delicate onion flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The oil is particularly pretty dribbled on white plates when
serving meats, seafood and poultry, and steamed vegetables. It also
makes a pretty presentation drizzled over creamy soups.
</P>
<P>
   CHIVE OIL
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1/2 cup
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup chives cut into 2-inch lengths
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup canola oil
</P>
<P>
   Drop the chives into boiling water for about 5 seconds, then
drain in a sieve and cool under running water. Drain well, then pat
dry between paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the chives and oil in a blender and blend until smooth.
Place in a glass container and refrigerate, covered, overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the oil through a fine sieve, pressing hard on the solids.
The oil will keep for about a week. For safety's sake, it must be
refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per tablespoon: 122 calories;
13.7 g fat; no cholesterol; no sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Chive butter is one of those staples that can be kept in the
freezer to be sliced off when needed to add a colorful burst of
flavor when needed. For another dimension, add a tablespoon of
Dijon mustard to the mixture before chilling.
</P>
<P>
   Have it ready to top little new potatoes that have been simmered
in salted water for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   CHIVE BUTTER
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced chives
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Combine the butter, chives and lemon juice in a blender or mini
food processor and blend. (The mixture can also be pounded in a
mortar and pestle.) Add a pinch of salt and 3 to 4 grindings of
black pepper. Spread the mixture on aluminum foil, shaping into a
long rectangle. Roll into a log and chill until firm. Use on
grilled meats, fish and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per tablespoon: 81 calories; 9
g fat; 25 mg cholesterol; trace sodium.
</P>
<P>
   The following recipe was inspired by one in The Herbal Palate
Cookbook by Maggie Oster and Sal Gilbertie (Storey, $29.95). It
would also work well with pork chops or boneless chicken breasts.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED LAMB CHOPS WITH ORANGE-CHIVE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   6 large shoulder lamb chops about 3/4-inch thick, about 2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup canola oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup brandy
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   1 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Additional minced chives for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Combine 1/4 cup orange juice, oil, 2 tablespoons chives and
pepper and pour over chops. Marinate, refrigerated for about 4
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat. Pat chops
dry, sprinkle with salt and brown them, about 3 minutes a side.
Remove to a plate and cover to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Add the shallots to the pan and cook, stirring, for about 2 to 3
minutes, or until soft. Add the brandy and 2 tablespoons chives and
cook until almost all the liquid has evaporated. Add 1 cup orange
juice and simmer until reduced by half. Return the chops to the pan
to finish cooking for another 2 to 4 minutes and to coat the chops
with the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle with fresh chives when serving.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per person: 363 calories; 21.8
g fat; 103.5 mg cholesterol; 81.6 mg sodium. (Actual fat will be
less because not all of the marinade is absorbed).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
