<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEXTEL-MCI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCI EXECUTIVE TALKS DOWN A WIRELESS DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The directors of Nextel Communications Inc., one of the nation's
biggest wireless telephone companies, convened Wednesday to
consider whether to sell their company to MCI Worldcom Inc., even
as one of MCI Worldcom's top executives said his company was in no
hurry to build a wireless business.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom, the No. 2 long-distance carrier, has discussed a
potential takeover with Nextel over the last few weeks, but John
Sidgmore, MCI Worldcom's vice chairman, said Wednesday that the
company could bide its time on becoming a wireless carrier. Nextel
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom has long held that it does not need a wireless
business. Many analysts believe, however, that in the long run MCI
Worldcom would be better off with a wireless unit than without one.
The problem for MCI Worldcom is that a major wireless acquisition
could be costly and dilute its earnings for years.
</P>
<P>
   So Sidgmore's comments may have been a gambit to beat down
Nextel's stock to make a purchase less costly. According to
executives close to the talks, Sidgmore has been the cheerleader
for a Nextel deal among MCI Worldcom's top management. The
executives said that Bernard Ebbers, the chief executive, was in
some ways in the middle, while Scott Sullivan, the chief financial
officer, had lobbied against one.
</P>
<P>
   Sidgmore's comments may also reflect the strategic reality that
MCI Worldcom seems to have more choices for expanding into wireless
service than Nextel has for being acquired. MCI Worldcom could
cobble together regional wireless companies or even take a run at
Sprint and its wireless business.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that Craig McCaw, the pioneer wireless
executive, who owns 20 percent of Nextel, would like Nextel to be
sold. He could make a tidy profit and escape the expense of
regularly exercising Nextel options.
</P>
<P>
   Nextel shares closed at $37.50 Wednesday, up $1.50. Nextel's
management would love to sell the company for more than $50,
executives close to the talks said, but the most that MCI Worldcom
seems willing to consider paying is in the low 40s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8471 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-500&AMP;     04-14 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACEDONIA'S LEADER SAYS MILOSEVIC IS TRYING TO `DESTABILIZE' HIS
NATION
</HEADLINE>
  (ac) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ The prime minister of Macedonia has accused
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia of trying to
``destabilize'' Macedonia by driving tens of thousands of ethnic
Albanians across the border and upsetting his country's fragile
ethnic and religious mix.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister, Ljubco Georgievski, who has led Yugoslvia's
southern neighbor for five months, said on Wednesday that by
expelling more than 140,000 Albanians from Kosovo to Macedonia,
Milosevic had handed him a potentially explosive situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been these expulsions,'' Georgievski said. ``And by
them Milosevic practically wanted to destabilize Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of refugees who have entered the country over the
last few weeks is equal to 7 percent of Macedonia's population of
two million. ``It would be like having 20 million Mexicans coming
into the United States in one day,'' Georgievski said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister has had to balance this influx of people with
a divided population, a significant proportion of whom support or
at least feel sympathy for Serbia. Forty thousand Serbs live in
Macedonia, and Macedonians, who are the majority, are also Eastern
Orthodox Christians. Albanians, who are mostly Muslim, represent 30
percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Although Macedonia could pride itself on being an example of
ethnic tolerance in the Balkans, the war has inevitably polarized
opinions, the prime minister noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that people have been made to chose between the
Albanians and Serbs,'' Georgievski said. ``It should not be a
question for a country that already has quite a complicated
political life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is playing on the fact of Christian-Muslim conflict.
I think we were very close to it,'' he said. ``He is playing to the
fears of the Christians that a surplus of refugees will make
Muslims predominant.''
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister, whose country is home to 12,000 NATO troops
sent here as peacekeepers in 1995, has walked a precarious
tightrope between NATO and Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   He is determinedly pro-West and pro-NATO, despite the fury this
has provoked from Belgrade and even from many in Macedonia. He said
his government's aim was to be accepted as a full member of NATO as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee crisis has provided one more sour note in a
relationship with Milosevic. Georgievski, who describes himself as
an anti-Communist and an advocate of Macedonian independence since
the 1980s, noted that Milosevic refused to recognize Macedonia for
five years after it gained independence from Yugoslavia in 1992 and
that the Yugoslav president still disputed their shared border.
</P>
<P>
   The border dispute made the capture of the three American
soldiers on March 31 a particularly sensitive issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbia does not recognize the border and disputes about 10
points along it,'' Georgievski said. ``So I assume because of this
dispute they could say that they were on their territory, and we
say it was on ours.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The incident also raised concerns over Serbian attacks. A
Macedonian soldier was killed last week at a border post.
Georgievski said, ``No one has proved who fired. And it could have
been a provocation. So we withheld blame.''
</P>
<P>
   He aadded that, ``Yugoslavia has declared us aggressors and is
sending us daily diplomatic notes'' that protest NATO's use of
Macedonian airspace for its bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Although NATO support aircraft fly over the country _ ``You can
hear them,'' Georgievski said with a shrug _ Macedonia had not
given NATO permission to use its territory or air space to attack
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   The particular fear among Macedonians is that the Albanians want
to create a ``greater Albania,'' which would eat into western
Macedonia. Albanian leaders in Macedonia have been careful to play
this down and voice full support for the territorial integrity of
Macedonia. Yet the issue remains in the back of the minds of many
Macedonians.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions have been played out in other ways, too. Police
officers have come in for strong criticism for their often callous
treatment of the Albanian refugees. When asked about the treatment,
Georgievski defended the authorities. He said they faced an unusual
security and immigration nightmare and had at least managed to
avoid a catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot find one refugee who was seriously injured,'' he
said. ``And there has been no disease or epidemic. So in the whole
chaos the Macedonian police passed this test.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a state we have had a difficult 20 days. And I think we
passed this exam.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8475 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SCANDAL15-COX     04-14 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panel decries IOC's reform pace
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Members of a Senate panel on Wednesday warned the
International Olympic Committee to institute prompt reforms or face
congressional sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Several senators called for the resignation of IOC President
Juan Antonio Samaranch because of the Olympic gift-giving scandal.
But former Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine recommended
several structural reforms to the world body, and members of the
Senate Commerce Committee said they would give the IOC more time
before seeking to enact potentially serious financial sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be given the chance to take the necessary action
on their own,'' Mitchell told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Early last month, Mitchell delivered a report to U.S. Olympics
officials critical of the IOC for tolerating a culture in which IOC
officials who decided Olympic host cities accepted free travel,
scholarships and lavish gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The report also criticized U.S. Olympic officials for lax
oversight of the Salt Lake 2002 bid and recommended broad
structural changes to the IOC. Among the changes were to impose
term limits on IOC members, make their elections more democratic
and open the committee to annual, independent auditing.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's Senate hearing was staged in part to keep the
pressure on Samaranch and other IOC members to implement the
changes. But senators and even some members of the oversight
commission that developed Mitchell's recommendations expressed
frustration with the IOC's initial response.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman John McCain (R-Ariz.) noted that the IOC has yet to
name more than a dozen persons to a 20-member panel that will make
its own recommendations to the IOC executive committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure the IOC views with the same seriousness the
comments of the Mitchell commission,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Distancing himself from Mitchell's more diplomatic approach,
former White House chief of staff Ken Duberstein, co-author of the
Mitchell report, told the panel that he does not think the IOC is
committed to reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recommended strong medicine for the USOC and the IOC,''
Duberstein said. ``The USOC followed the doctor's orders. The IOC
seems to be looking for a second opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC was represented at Wednesday's hearing by the United
States' two IOC members, Anita DeFrantz and Jim Easton.
</P>
<P>
   The two said they could support only one of the Mitchell
commission's four recommendations _ term limits for IOC members.
Both members took issue with the Mitchell commission's
characterization of the IOC as having fostered a ``culture of
improper gift giving'' for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The corruption was isolated to people who are no longer with
us,'' said DeFrantz, referring to the six members expelled by the
IOC and the four who resigned under threat of expulsion. ``It's not
right to paint all of the IOC with the same brush.''
</P>
<P>
   The members even balked at the suggestion that IOC board minutes
should be made public rather than kept embargoed for 10 years, as
is the current practice. Easton said the embargo was needed to
protect IOC members who could be punished back home for comments
that could be perceived to be disloyal to their native lands.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC will convene in June, when its 20-member review panel is
expected to meet for the first time. DeFrantz said all panel
members would be appointed by month's end.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said Congress should give the IOC until the end of the
year to propose and adopt reforms, although he suggested that
Congress could consider legislation concurrently in order to
demonstrate U.S. resolve.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he will introduce legislation to bring the IOC under
the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, which would make IOC members
subject to U.S. bribery laws.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Rick Lazio (R-N.Y.) and Henry Waxman (D-Calif.), brought
legislation this week that would bar U.S. companies from giving
sponsorship money to the IOC until the group adopts Mitchell
commission recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Congress should not rush such sanctions, for fear of
having an adverse impact on the programs that fund athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go slow on something like this,'' McCain said. ``Anything
that would harm the Olympic movement we have to be very careful
about.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
