Senate Commerce Committee said they would give the IOC more time
before seeking to enact potentially serious financial sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be given the chance to take the necessary action
on their own,'' Mitchell told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Early last month, Mitchell delivered a report to U.S. Olympics
officials critical of the IOC for tolerating a culture in which IOC
officials who decided Olympic host cities accepted free travel,
scholarships and lavish gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The report also criticized U.S. Olympic officials for lax
oversight of the Salt Lake 2002 bid and recommended broad
structural changes to the IOC. Among the changes were to impose
term limits on IOC members, make their elections more democratic
and open the committee to annual, independent auditing.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's Senate hearing was staged in part to keep the
pressure on Samaranch and other IOC members to implement the
changes. But senators and even some members of the oversight
commission that developed Mitchell's recommendations expressed
frustration with the IOC's initial response.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman John McCain (R-Ariz.) noted that the IOC has yet to
name more than a dozen persons to a 20-member panel that will make
its own recommendations to the IOC executive committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure the IOC views with the same seriousness the
comments of the Mitchell commission,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Distancing himself from Mitchell's more diplomatic approach,
former White House chief of staff Ken Duberstein, co-author of the
Mitchell report, told the panel that he does not think the IOC is
committed to reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recommended strong medicine for the USOC and the IOC,''
Duberstein said. ``The USOC followed the doctor's orders. The IOC
seems to be looking for a second opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC was represented at Wednesday's hearing by the United
States' two IOC members, Anita DeFrantz and Jim Easton.
</P>
<P>
   The two said they could support only one of the Mitchell
commission's four recommendations _ term limits for IOC members.
Both members took issue with the Mitchell commission's
characterization of the IOC as having fostered a ``culture of
improper gift giving'' for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The corruption was isolated to people who are no longer with
us,'' said DeFrantz, referring to the six members expelled by the
IOC and the four who resigned under threat of expulsion. ``It's not
right to paint all of the IOC with the same brush.''
</P>
<P>
   The members even balked at the suggestion that IOC board minutes
should be made public rather than kept embargoed for 10 years, as
is the current practice. Easton said the embargo was needed to
protect IOC members who could be punished back home for comments
that could be perceived to be disloyal to their native lands.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC will convene in June, when its 20-member review panel is
expected to meet for the first time. DeFrantz said all panel
members would be appointed by month's end.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said Congress should give the IOC until the end of the
year to propose and adopt reforms, although he suggested that
Congress could consider legislation concurrently in order to
demonstrate U.S. resolve.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he will introduce legislation to bring the IOC under
the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, which would make IOC members
subject to U.S. bribery laws.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Rick Lazio (R-N.Y.) and Henry Waxman (D-Calif.), brought
legislation this week that would bar U.S. companies from giving
sponsorship money to the IOC until the group adopts Mitchell
commission recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Congress should not rush such sanctions, for fear of
having an adverse impact on the programs that fund athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go slow on something like this,'' McCain said. ``Anything
that would harm the Olympic movement we have to be very careful
about.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
