<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8478 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-ECONSCENE-ART-2TA     04-14 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-ECONSCENE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: TAX BITE COMES WITH SET OF SAW TEETH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on tax rates by family income is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's April 15, time to complain about how taxes have become too
high. And the House will vote once again Thursday on a
constitutional amendment that would require a two-thirds majority
to pass future tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   But the real problem with the income tax system, many economists
say, is not that the typical family pays too much tax but rather
that Washington has made the tax code numbingly complex, wasteful
and irrational.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of ways to collect the same amount of money
from the same groups of taxpayers but with a fraction as much
damage to the economy. One alternative has been offered by Rep.
Richard Neal, D-Mass., who proposed an overhaul Wednesday that
would knock out needless complexity.
</P>
<P>
   There are good arguments for a flat code that sets the same tax
rate for nearly everyone. There are good arguments for a
progressive code that raises tax rates as family incomes rise.
</P>
<P>
   But there is hardly anyone who thinks the rate structure of the
existing code makes good sense. By statute, there are five tax
brackets, ranging from 15 percent to nearly 40 percent. The
marginal rate _ the highest rate that families pay on the last
dollars earned _ is supposed to rise with income. But the rates
that families actually pay are anything but smooth and predictable.
Marginal rates jump up and down in chaotic fashion, in a pattern
that Kevin Hassett, an economist at the American Enterprise
Institute, calls a ``skyline.''
</P>
<P>
   The saw-toothed tax rates are a product of credits and
deductions added to the code primarily in the 1990s _ only a few
years after Congress passed the Tax Reform Act of 1986 to simplify
the code. These tax cuts impose high marginal rates, a bizarre fact
that follows from congressional attempts to limit the lost revenues
from its tax cuts by phasing out credits and deductions as family
income rises. Phasing out a tax cut raises the tax payments of a
family as its income rises, in effect raising its marginal tax
rate.
</P>
<P>
   Marginal rates matter because it is the tax on additional
earnings that affects decisions by workers, especially spouses, to
find paying jobs, seek higher-paying jobs, work overtime and save.
Studies show that women are especially sensitive to marginal rates
when deciding how much they will work outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple tax credits and deductions _ each with their own
phase-out schedule _ produce Hassett's jagged skyline. The marginal
rate starts out at 21 percent for some low-income families, drops
to zero for certain kinds of families earning about $30,000, shoots
back to over 40 percent for some families earning about $80,000,
falls to 28 percent for families earning about $100,000 and
continues in this seesaw pattern for wealthy families.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the earned-income tax credit, the jewel of the
country's anti-poverty program, which adds up to about $3,800 to
the paycheck of low-paid workers. It begins to phase out at a
family income of about $12,000, reducing family income by 21 cents
for every extra dollar it earns. The child tax credit, passed in
1997 and now set at $500 for each child, begins to phase out at a
family income of about $110,000. The $1,500 credit for the first
two years of college tuition and the $1,000 credit for job training
and graduate study passed in 1997 begin to phase out at about
$80,000. Deductions for interest on student loans start phasing out
at about $60,000. Deductions for individual retirement accounts
begin to phase out at about $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The phasing out of these credits and deductions adds enormous
complexity to the code. With complexity comes, says Professor Alan
Auerbach of the University of California at Berkeley,
``deception.'' He says that ``few families know how much tax they
will owe on the income of a second earner because few know how all
these phase outs combine.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the marginal rates become quite high. A two-earner
family with a income of around $100,000 pays about 40 cents of each
extra dollar it earns in Federal income taxes. Add in Social
Security, Medicare and state and local taxes and the rate can climb
above 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the code imposes high marginal rates does not mean
that it imposes high tax payments. Recall, the saw-toothed pattern
of marginal rates reflect tax cuts passed in 1997 and earlier.
Republicans in Congress and on the campaign trail point to
different statistics to buttress their accusation that tax payments
have grown too heavy under President Clinton. Clinton's 1993 tax
increase, passed over their opposition, has driven tax collections,
as a share of the national economy, to their highest level in
history except for a brief interval in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But the accusation, says Auerbach, is misleading. For starters,
the share of federal tax revenues in national income bounces around
but almost always hovers close to 20 percent. At 20.5 percent
today, it is only modestly above the historical record. The rise
has been fueled by taxes on capital gains created by soaring values
on Wall Street as well as a shift in the share of income accounted
for by wealthy families in the highest tax brackets. Moreover,
Congress raised taxes in 1990 and 1993 to balance the budget. Yet
even after these tax increases, Americans pay less federal tax than
the citizens of nearly any other industrialized economy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the conventional wisdom about the tax burden is wrong,
says Iris Lav of the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities. With
the single exception of 1983, taxes on typical middle-income
families have fallen to their lowest level in more than two
decades. For many families, it would be necessary to go back even
further. Auerbach and William Gale of the Brookings Institution
estimate that a family of four in the middle of the income
distribution ($55,000 in 1999) will pay about 7.5 percent of its
income in federal income taxes. That is the lowest tax rate since
1966. Families at half the median are paying the lowest taxes since
1955. Even families at twice the median are paying the lowest tax
since 1972. Only the rich are paying more tax.
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach echoes another criticism that economists of all
political stripes level at the 1997 tax breaks. ``They are
gratuitous, serving no important economic function.'' Hassett
points to studies that predict that the tuition and job training
tax credits, for example, will go to families that would pay for
higher education without the government's help. The credits are
likely to do little more than encourage colleges to hike tuition
and cut financial aid because their applicants have more money
courtesy of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach offers a sensible correction, reflected in part by
Neal's bill. Even if Congress insists on preserving the package of
1997 tax credits and deductions, Auerbach says, it could apply them
equally to everyone. Eliminating the phase outs would eliminate the
hills and valleys of Hassett's skyline. To pay for this reform and
yet preserve a progressive tax code, Auerbach would raise the
statutory rate on wealthier families.
</P>
<P>
   Phaseouts will not disappear easily. Wednesday, Clinton proposed
tax-deductible retirement accounts for low- and middle-income
families _ a new credit that, no surprise, he would phase out. Add
another jag to Hassett's skyline. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-GENOME-MAP-890&AMP;AD     04-14 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENOME-MAP-890&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 DRUG MAKERS POOL EFFORTS TO FIND GENETIC ROOTS OF DISEASES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mass., Md., Mo.)   (rk) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten pharmaceutical companies and the Wellcome Trust of London
said Wednesday that they would pool efforts to create a fine-scale
map of the human genome. Their goal is to speed the discovery of
the genetic variations that underlie disease, and hence of new
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The map should also help in devising a new category of genetic
tests that will better match drugs to individual patients, an
activity sometimes referred to as ``personalized medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   The consortium's work is intended to build on the human genome
project, the effort to decode the three-billion-letter genetic
blueprint that resides in every human cell. A group of public
institutions are racing against the Celera Corp. of Rockville, Md.,
to be first to complete the project.
</P>
<P>
   The human genome project will produce a common, or consensus,
DNA sequence. But it is the variations from the consensus that make
each person genetically unique. Of particular medical interest are
the variant genes that predispose some people to disease and
protect others. The new consortium aims to identify a large enough
set of markers along the DNA that researchers can pinpoint the
variant genes that contribute to each disease of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Research consortiums of private industry have been formed
before, as in the semiconductor industry's joint project known as
Sematech, and do not violate the antitrust laws as long as they
focus on very early stage, pre-competitive research. But the new
consortium is highly unusual in that the results of its research
will be made available to the public at the same time as to its
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know a prior agreement like it,'' said Francis
Collins, director of the human genome project at the National
Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said the consortium's work would accelerate the search
for disease-associated genes and would complement the national
institutes' own efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium's principal backer, the Wellcome Trust, the huge
London charity specializing in support of medical research and
health care, is putting in $20 million, and the companies will
provide a further $25 million. The nonprofit enterprise, known as
the SNP Consortium, will be based in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Morgan, the Wellcome Trust executive responsible for
genome research, said he hoped the map would become an accepted
standard for drug regulatory agencies in Europe and the United
States. The original budget for the map was $150 million, he said,
but new advances have reduced the expected cost by two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   The participants say that by making the genome map publicly
available, the pace of discovery will be faster than if any company
tried to hoard the information for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this kind of tool should be publicly accessible
because it allows all medical researchers to add to what's being
discovered,'' said B. Michael Silber, a research director at Pfizer
Inc., a member of the consortium.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, by banding together the companies avoid duplication
of effort and gain access to scientists in the academic
laboratories that are pioneering exploration of the genome. A
public genome map also diminishes the chances that biotechnology
companies like Genset and Celera, which are developing private
maps, will be able to lock up broad swaths of the genome with
patent claims.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium's mapping work will be carried out by the genome
centers at Washington University in St. Louis, the Whitehead
Institute in Cambridge, Mass., and the Sanger Centre in England,
the major centers of the publicly financed work on the human genome
project.
</P>
<P>
   Each will be given six DNA sequencing machines, of a powerful
new model costing $300,000 apiece. The centers' efforts will be
coordinated by Lincoln Stein of the Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory
in Long Island, N.Y. Stein is an expert in bioinformatics, the use
of computer programs to analyze genetic information.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium's goal is to identify and locate, within two
years, 300,000 map points along the set of human DNA molecules, or
roughly 1 every 10,000 nucleotides, as the units of DNA are known.
That is the spacing necessary to provide a reasonable chance that
at least one map point will lie in or near any gene of interest.
</P>
<P>
   The map points along the DNA are themselves components of the
genetic material. They are single nucleotide positions, at which at
least 1 percent of the population has a nucleotide different from
that of the standard sequence. These one-letter differences are
known to geneticists as single nucleotide polymorphisms _ SNPs,
pronounced snips, which is why the new mapping effort is called the
SNP Consortium.
</P>
<P>
   Because working genes account for only 3 percent or so of the
human genome, most SNPs fall in the nonfunctional regions of DNA
and make no difference to the individual. But because the SNPs are
easy to identify, they form ideal markers for distinguishing one
region of DNA from another.
</P>
<P>
   Though genes get shuffled in each generation, the set of SNPs
close to a given gene is likely to be inherited along with it and
can be used to identify it. By looking at a family in which
diabetes, say, is prevalent, geneticists can hope to spot the many
genes that probably contribute to the disease by recognizing
patterns of SNPs that turn up in the diabetes sufferers but not in
unaffected individuals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like the concept of open software, in which programmers around
the world contribute to improving a publicly accessible program,
the new genome map is intended to grow and develop at the hands of
all its users. The human genome is so vast and so complex that
biologists believe it will take decades to annotate the sequence
fully, explaining the function of every gene and the origin and
effects of each of its many variants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the concept of empowering the individual
investigator,'' said C. Thomas Caskey, president of the Merck
Genome Research Institute. Though most drugs are discovered by
pharmaceutical companies, ``95 percent of all discoveries'' that
lead to new drugs are made outside of the pharmaceutical industry,
Caskey said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the genome mapping consortium was developed by Alan
Williamson, a former executive of Merck &AMP; Co., although Merck
decided in the end not to join. The member companies, 10 of the
world's 20 largest pharmaceutical concerns, are Bayer AG, the
Bristol-Myers Squibb Co., Glaxo Wellcome PLC, Hoechst Marion
Roussel, Roche Holding Ltd., Novartis AG, Pfizer Inc., Searle SRL,
SmithKline Beecham PLC and the Zeneca Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson, who is now a consultant in England, said that with
the map in the public domain, its accuracy could be guaranteed, a
matter that will be of importance to regulatory authorities
assessing drugs that are based on the map's information. Further,
if there are controversial findings, relating perhaps to
differences among ethnic groups, ``they ought to be checkable and
verifiable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The SNP map is to be constructed from the DNA of individuals
drawn from the four principal human population groups, those of
Africa, Asia, Europe and pre-Columbian America.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are talking about building a genome map, it should be a
real catalog of human variation and not just northern Europeans,''
said Collins, of the National Institutes of Health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
