<SLUG> BC-BURGER-KING-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: BURGER KING PLANS OVERHAUL OF RESTAURANTS AND IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Nev., Fla.)   (bl)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moving to improve its image, food and sales, Burger King Corp.
said Wednesday that it would overhaul its 10,000 restaurants with
new kitchens, modifications to drive-through windows and elaborate
redesigns of the buildings and the company logo.
</P>
<P>
   The flame-broiled concept will remain, but customers can say
goodbye to those boxy structures huddling in the middle of the
shopping mall or along the interstate that have long meant Burger
King. The new restaurants are supposed to be elongated statements
with intersecting jutting planes and a fast-food interpretation of
a clerestory window. Inside, the kitchen will permit views of the
cooking process, flames and all. A children's playground is also
part of the plan. The prototype, hurriedly built in Reno, Nev., is
scheduled to open Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The logo has been recast as slicker and more contemporary. It
has spunkier lettering, and its burger image has been manicured to
make its bun look more like the kind of bread used for panini; a
blue crescent swooshes around three-quarters of the image. The
company also wants to improve service, with restaurants ordered to
focus on ``flawless execution.'' They will be monitored by
``mystery shoppers,'' people hired to pose as customers who then
report to headquarters on how they were treated.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, regarded as among the most extensive in the
ultracompetitive industry, were announced to franchisees Wednesday
in Reno, where Burger King is having an annual business meeting.
</P>
<P>
   While McDonald's Corp. reconfigured its kitchens last year to
improve the way its food tastes, the steps that Burger King is
taking are seen as going well beyond that. Analysts wondered how
much the new restaurants would cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like they are going a little too far in some of these
changes,'' said Howard Penney, who follows the restaurant industry
for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``The look is good, but this is a
franchise business. The ultimate success is going to depend on the
cost of the building and the sales generated from that building.''
</P>
<P>
   The average Burger King now rings up about $1.1 million in sales
a year, the company said. With the changes in design and service,
the company hopes that number will grow significantly. Penney said
that for every dollar invested in a new building, a typical
franchisee needed to bring in another dollar of business to make
the investment worthwhile. ``That leads me to believe that it is
not likely you will see this widespread anytime soon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burger King has been inching forward over the last several years
and gaining market share, company executives said, and the changes
announced Wednesday are supposed to continue that trend. ``We have
a lot of momentum, but all along the way we've known that in order
to continue our momentum, there were certain things consumers were
telling us about our brand that we needed to do,'' said Paul
Clayton, president of Burger King's North American division. The
company is a unit of Diageo PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes that customers demanded, he added, were ``less
stress at the drive-through,'' where about 60 percent of Burger
King's sales are made. ``And they want it faster,'' he said.
Kitchen redesigns will make that possible, he said, and the company
is even adding a ``customer courtesy zone'' where people can pull
over, request more napkins or condiments and someone from the
restaurant will deliver them to their cars.
</P>
<P>
   The look of many Burger King restaurants was also a concern, he
added. ``We know there's a large portion of our restaurant
portfolio that is dated and tired and needs refreshing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton would not disclose how much the Reno prototype had cost
to build, saying that because it was put up on an accelerated
schedule in time for the meeting, the cost would not be
``appropriate to discuss.''
</P>
<P>
   The company will remodel 43 restaurants that it owns in Orlando,
Fla., a project that will be finished late next year. ``We won't
know what the system costs are until we leverage the economies,''
Clayton said. Still, the company plans to offer ``a bundle of
incentives and investment options'' that are intended to help
franchise owners redo their restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Burger King said it had signed a new 10-year
contract with Coca-Cola Co. to provide soft-drink fountain service
at its restaurants. The contract, which begins Oct. 1, had been
hotly contested by Pepsi-Cola, a unit of Pepsico, and analysts
speculated that Coca-Cola had to sweeten its offer considerably to
retain the business. About 17 percent, or $1.75 billion, of Burger
King's $10.3 billion in sales last year came from soft drinks,
according to Jim Watkins, the company's vice president for
marketing. Fountain soft drinks have large profit margins for
restaurants, although margins for concentrate makers are smaller.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe our agreement is going to create many, many
opportunities for profitable growth for Coca-Cola and for Burger
King by building their soft-drink business,'' said a Coca-Cola
spokeswoman, Polly Howes.
</P>
<P>
   But a Pepsi-Cola spokesman insisted the deal had been costly for
Coke. ``Coke is making one more bizarre investment that their
shareholders are never going to see a return on,'' said the
spokesman, Jeff Brown, who estimated that whatever concessions
Coca-Cola made to Burger King would have to be matched at
McDonald's as well. Ms. Howes said every Coca-Cola customer had
specific terms ``that are based on mutually beneficial
arrangements.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big victory for Coke, but I would imagine Coke's
margins on this are less than their historic margins in the
fountain business,'' said John D. Sicher, publisher of Beverage
Digest. Still, he added, ``having a big fountain account like
Burger King provides a benefit over and above the sale of
products.'' He said, ``It is a valuable medium for brand visibility
and provides a huge sampling opportunity for a company's
products.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr Pepper/Seven Up Co., a division of Cadbury Schweppes, also
won a contract to install one spigot serving Dr Pepper in every
Burger King in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
