<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE COMPUTER REPORTS STRONG 2ND QUARTER 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Reporting its second-quarter earnings Wednesday,
a resurgent Apple Computer Inc. again beat analysts' earnings
estimates. Apple said strong demand for its iMac and G3 machines
increased unit sales by 27 percent, or nearly twice the industry
average.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's renewed fortunes are all the more striking at a time
when the rest of the personal computer industry is mired in price
wars and slowing growth. Last week the Compaq Computer Corp., the
world's largest PC manufacturer, warned that earnings for the
current quarter would fall far short of estimates, and on Tuesday
the Intel Corp. said sales for its first quarter were slower than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the doom and gloom out there in PC land,'' said
Charles R. Wolf, an analyst with Warburg Dillon Read. ``Apple
dances to its own tune, and it's a happy tune. At some point,
you've got to believe, and I think we're getting closer to that
point, especially since the second half of the year will be
punctuated by a lot of new products.''
</P>
<P>
   Because its computers do not adhere to the Wintel standard _ the
Microsoft Corp.'s Windows operating system and Intel's
microprocessors _ Apple was considered weakened and irrelevant for
years. But now, with the Wintel market increasingly the same
regardless of brand, Apple has repositioned itself in the PC market
through ease of use and appealing industrial design.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple, fortunately, does not make a Wintel machine,'' Wolf
said. ``Design counts, simplicity counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple shares closed at $35.5313 Wednesday, up 90.62 cents, in
Nasdaq trading. For the quarter that ended on March 27, Apple
reported earnings of $135 million, or 84 cents a diluted share,
compared with $55 million, or 38 cents a share, in the year-ago
quarter. Revenue rose 9 percent, to $1.53 billion from $1.41
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The second quarter's results included $42 million in
extraordinary gains _ $50 million realized in the sale of two
million shares of ARM Holdings PLC, partly offset by a charge of $8
million associated with improving the flexibility and efficiency of
manufacturing operations. Without these nonrecurring items, Apple
said earnings for the quarter would have been $93 million, or 60
cents a diluted share.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Apple to earn 57 cents a share, according
to the First Call Corp., which tracks results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep making really great computers that people want to
buy,'' Steven P. Jobs, Apple's interim chief executive, said in a
telephone interview. ``I don't think they were doing that 18 months
ago when I got here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jobs, the Apple co-founder who is almost universally credited
with turning around the company that had once exiled him, said
Apple had reached new levels of operating efficiency. Inventory, he
said, has been reduced to just one day, below even that of the Dell
Computer Corp., and cash and short-term investments have been
increased to $2.9 billion, from just over $1 billion when he
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Apple said it was increasing the speed of the iMac
to 300 megahertz, from 266 megahertz, while keeping the price at
$1,199. Apple also announced Wednesday the early call for
redemption on June 1 of all of its 6 percent convertible
subordinated debentures due June 1, 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
