<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL FIELD WORKERS IN TEXAS APPLAUD PAT BUCHANAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ODESSA, Texas _ More than 700 oil field workers who fear losing
their jobs to low prices and foreign imports warmly applauded
Republican presidential candidate Pat Buchanan as he promised
Wednesday to restore America's ``energy independence'' through oil
import fees.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan told the crowd at a local Veterans of Foreign Wars hall
that such fees would save the domestic oil industry by creating a
floor the foreign oil producers could not undercut in U.S. markets.
Buchanan said OPEC and Iraq have flooded the nation with cheap oil
with the intent ``to kill the American oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then OPEC and the foreign producers will have control of the
United States,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Oil field service worker Duane Moreland, 56, said Buchanan now
has his vote ``hands down'' for the GOP presidential nomination
over Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who opposes oil import fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, I would have voted for George Bush without
question. But now his ego has gotten so big and he's so politicized
that he won't even address an issue, certainly not our issue,''
Moreland said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreland said Bush could have used his office as a ``bully
pulpit'' to push for oil tariffs to protect the domestic oil
industry. But Moreland said Bush has avoided the issue because ``it
would be politically unpopular to the rest of the country'' where
people want low-cost fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Ramirez, president of the Kermit chapter of the League of
United Latin American Citizens, said he lost his job as a pipeline
worker because of the oil slump.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez said he voted for Bush's re-election as governor last
year, but now he is open to voting for Buchanan for president
because he is talking about taking actions that will help average
oil field workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor passed the tax break for the ivory tower guys,''
Ramirez said. ``The worker didn't get anything extra, like the
Band-Aid the independents got.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush recently signed an emergency tax break for the owners of
marginal oil and gas wells, releasing them from paying state taxes
when oil prices fall below $12 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said Bush differs sharply with
Buchanan on trade issues because the governor believes in ``free
and fair trade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Bush) opposes an import fee. He believes it would create a
protectionist war ... that ultimately would hurt American
workers,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent his childhood in neighboring Midland, Texas, and
later worked there for about 10 years running an oil exploration
company.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who is paying a private courtesy call on Bush
Thursday, avoided any direct criticism of the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Besides their differences on oil import fees, Bush supports the
North American Free Trade Agreement while Buchanan opposes it,
saying NAFTA has ``taken America's Sun Belt and shifted it south of
the Rio Grande.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan told his Odessa audience that contradictory national
policies have hurt the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last summer, we're bombing Saddam Hussein, American
fighter-bombers, while he's selling us 500,000 barrels of oil a day
at $8 and 1/2. He's bombing West Texas,'' Buchanan said. ``What is
going on in this country that Saddam Hussein can bomb us with this
imported oil at the same time we're bombing him?''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan also toured the oil-drilling firm of Permian Producers
Inc. in Midland, where $4 million drilling rigs are sitting idle.
Company owner Tom Carman said he is in danger of going out of
business because he has a contract with Texaco to drill five wells
in New Mexico, but cannot start because the drilling site is the
nesting grounds of prairie chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said such kowtowing to prairie chickens could cost
Texas 1,000 jobs directly or indirectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on when we are more worried about chickens than
the 1,000 people who depend on Tommy Carman?'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Carman, who employs 25 people, said he has not decided who to
support for president. But he said Bush's tax break for marginal
well owners was a ``token amount.'' Carman said he is impressed by
Buchanan's talk of an overall fix for the oil industry but also
would like to have Bush tour his facility.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
