<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8497 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-2TAKE     04-14 0345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
 
BRUSSELS, Belgium: Wednesday evening.
<TEXT>
<P>
   By all accounts, the situation of civilians in Kosovo has become
increasingly desperate. NATO says there are about 260,000 displaced
civilians inside the province, bases its estimates on figures from
the U.N. refugee agency.
</P>
<P>
   American and British officials have said the number may reach
700,000 or even higher, using what a NATO military spokesman,
Italian Brig. Gen. Giuseppe Marani called a worst-case estimate.
</P>
<P>
   NATO insists it is not able to help the displace civilians
inside Kosovo because its transport planes might be shot down if
they tried to drop relief supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Hunger and disease are not the only threats the displaced
Albanians face in Kosovo, the alliance says. British officials
disclosed Wednesday that Ratko Mladic, the former Bosnia Serb
military commander who has been indicted by the War Crimes
Tribunal, was leading a Serb paramilitary group in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Zeljko Raznatovic, also known as Arkan, was also seeking
recruits in prisons in Yugoslavia to augment his paramilitary band
in Kosovo, British officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Serb units have been systematically raping young ethnic Albanian
women at a Serb checkpoint just a few miles from the border with
Albanian, according to refugee reports monitored by British
officials.
</P>
<P>
   In its effort to mobilize public opinion, NATO has said that it
is Milosevic who has put the Kosovars in jeopardy. To drive home
its point, the alliance has shown reconnaissance photos of long
lines of civilians along roadsides and in makeshift shelters.
Western officials say that Milosevic is depriving the refugees of
food and assistance and has even shelled them on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are citizens of his country,'' Clark said
Tuesday. ``That's what he has said all along. He needs to
demonstrate his leadership and concern for his own citizens, who
are being held out there hostage, isolated, and starved.''
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade, however, has sought to pin the blame on NATO, saying
the air strikes had worsened their plight.
</P>
</TEXT>
