<SLUG> BC-CT-HARTFORD-PAPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARTFORD COURANT BUYS LOCAL ALTERNATIVE WEEKLY 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., Conn., Md.)   By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Two weeks ago, the irreverent tabloid editors
at The Hartford Advocate published an April Fool's parody of the
city's only daily, The Hartford Courant, lampooning ``America's
Oldest Continuously Published Newspaper'' as ``America's Lamest
Continuously Published Newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartford Advocate, meet your new boss: The Hartford Courant.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, The Courant announced it had bought The Advocate and
its four sister publications in Westchester County, N.Y., Fairfield
County, New Haven and western Massachusetts. Purchase terms were
not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper industry analysts said it was one of the first times a
major American daily had taken over the major alternative weekly in
its home city, representing a novel extension of the monopoly on
local voices enjoyed by publishers in one-newspaper cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the other shoe people have been waiting for,'' said
Abe Peck, an associate dean of the Medill School of Journalism at
Northwestern University, who is an authority on the underground
press of the 1960s. ``The alternative is now the mainstream. The
alternative press emerged as a voice beyond the massified downtown
dailies. Now, we're just talking about an alternative tone.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement seemed to point to the convergence of two
publishing trends, experts said. Alternative weeklies, like The
Village Voice in New York, which have grown in number and girth as
they emerged as a successful way to reach younger and hipper
readers, began aggregating into regional and national chains.
Dailies began acquiring suburban papers and shoppers as a defense
against the loss of advertising or readers.
</P>
<P>
   The five weeklies purchased by The Courant are owned by New
Mass. Media Inc. of Hatfield, Mass., and have a combined
circulation of 270,000. The Courant, which on Monday was awarded
the Pulitzer Prize for breaking news for its coverage of a killing
spree at the state lottery headquarters, has a circulation of
211,000 daily and 303,000 on Sunday. It is owned by the Times
Mirror Co., the parent of The Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Petty, the publisher of The Courant, said in a letter to
employees that the publications would remain separate. ``We believe
the alternative press can play an important role in keeping all
media, including The Courant, on its toes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But some readers reacted with alarm to The Courant, seen as
reliable but bland, adopting the lively Advocate chain. The local
arts community treated Wednesday's announcement like a death in the
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is big brother taking over,'' said Alyssa S. Peterson,
owner of NetFX, a Web design firm. ``The Advocate is everything The
Courant isn't. Where do we go now?''
</P>
<P>
   Richard M. Karpel, the executive director of the Association of
Alternative Newsweeklies, said he found Wednesday's announcement
disturbing, and hoped other dailies did not do the same in their
areas. ``Centralized management would strip out the idiosyncrasies
that make the alternative paper worth reading.''
</P>
<P>
   Times Mirror publishes four daily newspapers in the Northeast:
Newsday on Long Island, The Courant, and, also in Connecticut, the
Greenwich Time and The Advocate of Stamford. Mark H. Willes, the
chairman of Times Mirror, said The Hartford Advocate and its sister
weeklies ``connect with a readership that we have not been as
successful with: the younger age group.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to find a way to reach out to literally every
segment we can in our markets,'' Willes said in a telephone
interview. ``Any time you can give either your readers or
advertisers, or both, more alternatives, we think you can grow your
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The chain began with The Valley Advocate in Amherst, Mass.,
first published in 1973. The headquarters later moved to Hatfield,
and the chain's founders helped start each of the four other
papers. The Hartford Advocate is the largest, with a circulation of
70,000. It has 23 of the chain's 135 employees.
</P>
<P>
   All the newspapers are distributed free. The Valley Advocate now
has a circulation of 65,000. The New Haven Advocate, started in
1975, has a circulation of 55,000. The Fairfield County Weekly,
started in 1978, has a circulation of 50,000. The Westchester
County Weekly, started in 1993, has a circulation of 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   John Morton, a newspaper analyst of Silver Spring, Md., said the
purchase made good business sense. ``It moves Times Mirror in small
way into a culture that they haven't been in before,'' he said.
``The problem that daily newspapers have is appealing to people in
the 18-to-35 age group. Clearly the alternative weeklies are
prospering in that niche, and that makes them attractive properties
to daily newspaper companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Stern, who publishes seven major weeklies, including The
Village Voice, said he was surprised that daily newspapers had not
found this strategy before. ``The demographics at almost all of the
major dailies begin at an age level where the alternatives leave
off. The alternatives continue the collegiate atmosphere: two or
three or four people live in an apartment, and someone brings home
the local weekly.'' The owners, Geoffrey Robinson and Christine
Austin, visited each paper Wednesay to explain the decision to the
staffs. Both said the purchase by a media giant constituted a
vindication of alternative weeklies.
</P>
<P>
   The Advocate's editor, Janet Reynolds, mentioned several Courant
features that she thinks were inspired by her newspaper, including
Cal, a tabloid arts section published on Thursday. ``They're trying
to be trendy and cutting edge, but instead it comes across as
patronizing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She stopped. ``I may be talking myself out of a job,'' she said
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Francis J. Zankowski, publisher of The Hartford Advocate, said
he intended to maintain ``a strong and independent voice.'' Would
he still publish that parody issue of the ``Hartford Not So
Current''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ab-so-lutely,'' Zankowski said, pounding his desk mirthfully.
``It's even funnier now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
