<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIAN-REFUGEES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME REFUGEES IN ALBANIA READY TO FIGHT BACK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURRES, Albania _ Sitting in a cold tent with rainwater
trickling across the floor, Hadja Berani said she has decided to
join the ethnic Albanian guerrillas battling the Serbs in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to fight,'' said Berani, 22, as she glanced down at
her soaked stocking feet and wrapped her arms around her shoulders
in an effort to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has got to end quickly,'' she said of the misery in the
sprawling refugee camp that has sprung up on the edge of this dingy
port city.
</P>
<P>
   Berani said she plans to join her 20-year-old brother, Fuad, who
stayed behind in Kosovo to fight with the guerrillas when the rest
of the family _ fearing murder at the hands of the Serbs _ fled the
province two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, others of the estimated 300,000 Kosovars who
have poured into Albania since the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia began
share Berani's intentions to take up arms, which they see as a way
to end the conflict quickly. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Training of troops for the ethnic Albanian Kosovo Liberation
Army is reportedly under way near Albania's border with Yugoslavia.
Young men who say they plan to join the guerrillas have been
arriving in Albania on the ferry boat from Italy each day.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Kosovar refugees say, however, that they expect the
crisis to be resolved by NATO ground troops within a few months, if
not weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is up to NATO soldiers and equipment,'' said Avdi Morina, a
37-year-old lab technician who now lives with his wife, two
children and about 900 other refugees in the cramped barracks of an
army training camp on the outskirts of the Albanian capital of
Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are bombing, but now is the time to go in,'' Morina said.
``What are they waiting for? Ground forces are the only way.''
</P>
<P>
   Such sentiments are apparently shared by some members of the
U.S. Congress, who asked President Clinton on Tuesday to begin
preparing for a ground war. Clinton, however, insisted that the
bombing campaign needs more time to work. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Thousands of NATO troops have been pouring into Albania.
Officials say the soldiers are here to aid the humanitarian mission
of caring for refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Private relief agencies and NATO military planners seem to be
preparing for a long stay.
</P>
<P>
   Tons of aid _ including food, bedding, clothing and medical
supplies _ have begun arriving in Albania daily, both by ship
through the port of Durres and on the dozens of cargo flights
landing at the airport outside Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   Military helicopters from the United States, France and
Switzerland have ferried the aid to refugee camps near the Kosovo
border and elsewhere in Albania. Food and other goods have been
loaded onto flatbed trucks lining the narrow road near the airport
runway each day.
</P>
<P>
   Swarms of four-wheel drive vehicles carrying relief workers and
foreign officials have overwhelmed the country's narrow, rutted
roads, adding to already monumental traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the start,'' said Corinne Woods, a worker for the
private aid agency Save the Children, as she passed out supplies to
refugees at a camp one day earlier this week. ``We're going to be
here for four or five years. Either here or in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Kosovar refugees continued to enter Albania and
Macedonia on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the Kosovars who earlier fled their homes, the men,
women and children who passed through the small Albanian border
post of Hani i Hoti had been stripped of their identity papers and
money.
</P>
<P>
   Once out of Yugoslavia, the refugees were registered by Albanian
officials, who wrote their names and home towns in a ledger. The
Kosovars were then loaded onto buses and taken to a basketball
coliseum in the nearby city of Shkodra.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to wait to see what happens, what we'll have to do,''
said a weary Mustafa Almetas, 48, who arrived at the Shkodra
coliseum with his wife and five children from the Kosovo town of
Cerle one day earlier this week. ``We can't go back as long as
there is no security.''
</P>
<P>
   The Almetas family joined about 1,500 earlier arrivals, whose
foam mattresses already were packed tightly on the basketball
court.
</P>
<P>
   With little space left on the floor, the Almetases were ushered
into low-backed plastic seats lining the perimeter of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Young Albanian volunteers handed out plates of canned beef stew
and chunks of bread provided by the United Nations. Foreign relief
workers waded through the crowd, passing out toothbrushes, soap and
other necessities.
</P>
<P>
   After he ate, Almetas stumbled across the floor of the
basketball court, threading his way through the narrow aisles
separating the mattresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they'll find us a place to sleep,'' a worried Almetas
said. ``But I don't see any place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what we'll do,'' he said. ``I just don't know
what we'll do at all.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
