u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-POLICY-675&AMP;ADD-N     04-14 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-POLICY-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIZABETH DOLE QUESTIONS CLINTON'S BALKAN POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.) (mk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, Md. _ Elizabeth Dole accused the Clinton
administration Wednesday night of conducting a Balkan policy that
``encourages adversaries to shift strategies, wait it out, or
attempt to break our alliances.'' She called on President Clinton
to ``build up and deploy the forces necessary to win the war'' in
Kosovo, including sending ground troops if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to midshipmen at the U.S. Naval Academy that her
campaign billed as a major foreign policy address, Mrs. Dole, a
Republican presidential contender and the only woman in the race,
also sharply criticized Clinton's credibility and steadfastness of
purpose in his approach to both Iraq and Yugoslav aggression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credibility counts,'' she said. ``And if you have any
questions about that, look at the U.N. weapons inspections mess in
Iraq or today's tragedy in Kosovo. When tough deadlines are set and
then repeatedly postponed, when the other side appears to break its
agreements with impunity, when we accept half- promises, we send
the wrong signal about our values and our will.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole's speech placed her firmly in the internationalist
wing of her divided party and allowed her to show that a woman can
talk tough on military matters. Unlike the growing number of
Republicans in Congress who disdain international organizations,
she emphasized the importance of NATO as well as world financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our leadership in international trade and monetary
organizations is essential for upholding our core economic
interests and promoting worldwide economic growth,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For Mrs. Dole, the speech served several particular purposes.
She has lagged toward the back of the Republican field in fund
raising and could benefit from respectful notices in the foreign
policy arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a circle in politics,'' acknowledged one of her
advisers. ``Good poll numbers raise money. Good press gets you good
poll numbers. Good press gets you money.''
</P>
<P>
   Some political commentators, particularly at this moment of
crisis overseas, have questioned whether Mrs. Dole has had any
experience that would give her a mastery of military matters.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again Wednesday night she sought to show that she does
have international experience. She spoke descriptively of visiting
world trouble spots like the borders of Rwanda and Bosnia as
president of the American Red Cross and of meeting with Solidarity
leaders in Poland in 1989 as labor secretary. And she mentioned her
role as a negotiator with China on aviation and maritime matters as
transportation secretary.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster that experience, she announced Wednesday night that
she will leave on Thursday for Macedonia and Albania to visit camps
of Albanian refugees from Kosovo and meet with local leaders. Her
husband, former Sen. Bob Dole, met with Albanian leaders in Kosovo
last month as an envoy for the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning Clinton by name, Mrs. Dole deplored American
commitments ``caged in hesitation'' and said, ``Long experience
teaches that when we've committed military forces to a rightful
goal, we should use all the power necessary to achieve it.'' She
said she would endorse the use of ground forces if NATO commanders
and the Joint Chiefs of Staff said they were necessary.
</P>
<P>
   At a time of debate over the role of the U.S. military in the
post-Cold War world, when conservatives say that U.S. forces have
strayed from their primary military role, Mrs. Dole embraced the
kinds of refugee relief operations that NATO troops are carrying
out near Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled flying to Zaire (now Congo) to see the camps for
those fleeing massacres in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the plane's window I saw a huge mass of people in the
choking dust and heat,'' she said. ``I also saw jeeps and trucks
with our beautiful red-on-white cross _ and an enormous C-141
military aircraft, unloading critical supplies. To those who
criticize the military's role in such rescue efforts, I'll just say
there are simply times when nobody else can do the job.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole noted that some people ask why the United Nations and
regional bodies cannot take care of regional problems. ``The answer
is simple,'' she said. ``Wherever America's national interests and
our national values intersect, this nation must lead. That includes
using military force when necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes she sidestepped hard questions. She failed to say
whether she thought the U.S. forces should have intervened to stop
the Rwanda conflict.
</P>
<P>
   On China, she endorsed engagement, but called simultaneously for
Beijing to be pressed harder on human rights and in trade
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time she said the United States should ``stand by
our friends in Taiwan.''
</P>
<P>
   But when a midshipman questioned her pointedly on how far the
United States would go to defend Taiwan against China, she replied:
``I think there are some things that I want to look at very, very
carefully before I give you a definitive answer. I am not yet an
announced candidate, much less the elected nominee of the party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
