<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8510 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MP3-SFCHRON &LR;      04-14 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MP3-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Making Digital Tunes Big Business
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Benny Evangelista &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The grassroots popularity of free MP3 songs on the Internet has
quickly reshaped the future of the worldwide music industry.
</P>
<P>
   But now that two of the biggest players in technology, Microsoft
and IBM, are competing to bring Internet music to the masses, it
should hasten the day when mainstream consumers can buy and
download digitized Top 10 hits.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  And that same competition could eventually push MP3 out of
the spotlight, said analyst Mark Hardie of Forrester Research Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its 15 seconds of fame is not going to go on for much more,''
said Hardie of the MP3 format, which in the past year moved from
being an obscure audio compression technology to the second-most
requested topic on Internet search engines, right behind sex.
</P>
<P>
   The free format caused a revolution among teens and young adults
who were able to copy, trade and distribute songs from both popular
and unknown artists.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 software compresses the size of song files so they can be
sent more quickly over the Internet. MP3 songs can be played back
on a computer or a portable, Walkman-like device.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But the music industry said MP3 fans break copyright laws and
blamed pirated MP3 songs for a recent drop in CD sales to young
consumers. MP3 proponents say big record companies are hyping
piracy issues to mask their real concerns that the format could
undermine the industry's elaborate CD distribution and revenue
stream while transferring more power to individual artists and
independent labels.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high. In a recent report, Forrester Research
predicted the downloading of music from the Internet will add $1.1
billion in revenues to the U.S. music industry by 2003 as the Web
turns ``from a pirate's paradise to the (music) industry's
e-commerce growth engine.''
</P>
<P>
   Several developments this week show technology companies are
serious about making digital music big business.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest announcement came from Microsoft, which hosted a
splashy Los Angeles party at the House of Blues Tuesday night to
announce trial versions of its new Internet audio software, called
Media Technologies 4.0.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The program, which the Redmond, Wash., software giant will
distribute for free with its Windows operating system and over the
Internet, can compress songs to a size about twice as small as
available with MP3, so music can be downloaded more quickly and
take up less memory when stored on a computer hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Gary Schare, Microsoft media technologies product manager,
said a song that is 40 megabytes on a CD-ROM can be compressed to
about 4 megs using MP3 and to about 2 megs using Media
Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Media Technologies also enables artists and record labels to
protect copyrights with built-in encryption, or if they chose,
distribute free music for promotional purposes as some are doing
now with the MP3 format, Schare said. The MP3 format by itself does
not provide copyright protection.
</P>
<P>
   The new format also plays FM-quality audio and video files
directly from Web sites, which puts Microsoft in competition with
RealNetworks Inc., the Seattle company whose RealPlayer software
``streams'' audio and video files to about 55 million Web surfers.
The MP3 format can't be used to stream audio in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, RealNetworks said it was teaming with IBM to
develop secure Internet music download software that would compete
with Microsoft's Media Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Questions still remain whether the big five record labels, which
reportedly are wary about siding with Microsoft, will use the new
technology to sell music. Music and technology industry leaders
have formed a consortium to hash out common standards to sell songs
on the Internet, but the process will take another year to
complete.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But analysts say Microsoft's &LR;   &LR; marketing of its Internet
music technology will push the market even faster.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft ``may not always start the market, but they're masters
at entering into it,'' said Ron Rappaport, an analyst with Zona
Research Inc. in Redwood City. ``Microsoft lands wherever it
believes the market opportunity is large enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition could eventually eclipse the MP3 format, which
flourished when it stood alone on stage. While nobody is predicting
an immediate demise of the MP3 phenomenon or that the format will
disappear entirely, analysts say consumers will eventually
gravitate toward better technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Hardie said Media Technologies produces slightly better quality
sound than an MP3 file, but its ability to create smaller files is
the major advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said MP3 is going to fade when commercially viable
solutions are available,'' Hardie said. ``It won't disappear
overnight. But its quality is limited, it can't get much better. If
you are a band, if you want to distribute your music online, you'll
want it in the best quality you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Grady, marketing director for GoodNoise Inc., a Redwood
City company that is trying to become an online digital music
seller, believes the MP3 format for now will endure because its
popularity is not based on the technology, but freedom of choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``What (MP3 fans) are excited about is the flexibility MP3 gives
them with their music, the fact that you are now empowered to buy
music in new ways and organize it the way you want,'' Grady said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost a certainty that something will replace MP3 as a
compression technology,'' he said. ``But MP3 has taken off because
of its availability and ubiquity, not because it's great
technology.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
