<HEADER>
A8512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-U.S.-600&AMP;ADD-NY     04-14 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA LEADER ENDS U.S. VISIT WITH TRADE TALK AT MIT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., Ill.)  (rk) 
 By   JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Chinese Prime Minister Zhu Rongji has a
theory about his country's trade surplus with the United States,
and he went on a shopping spree to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Scouring department stores during a stop in Chicago, he
collected athletic shoes made by Nike, Reebok and Adidas. Each pair
had a ``Made in China'' label, but the prime minister said it is
hardly a glorious business. He compared the prices with ones in a
similar survey he did a decade ago and found that the average price
of a pair has declined, to about $80 from $120.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even 15 years ago America did not produce many of these
goods,'' Zhu said in a speech devoted to trade at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology here Wednesday. ``Now, you could not find
anyone willing to make them in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   It was with such elementary logic that Zhu tried to debunk an
often heard complaint about China: that it has become an exporting
power at America's expense. China makes the things Americans do not
want to make, the prime minister said. Besides, he added, the U.S.
estimate of China's trade surplus, $57 billion last year, is
probably too high.
</P>
<P>
   The speech was the longest and most detailed of any during Zhu's
nine-day visit, which ended Wednesday with his departure for
Canada. Where others see U.S.-China relations revolving around
issues like human rights, strategic cooperation and political
reform, Zhu sees the two countries getting along so long as trade
between them flourishes.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by a student attending his MIT speech to release the
Chinese dissident Xu Wenli from prison, Zhu complained about the
amount of time he has spent talking about human rights on his trip.
``I practically have blisters on my mouth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The opposite is more the case. He has given meager lip service
to human rights while speaking several times each day about trade,
specifically China's bid to join the World Trade Organization. It
was only after his long discourse on trade Wednesday that he warmed
up to making a broader assessment of relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that you see the strategic nature of our
relationship,'' Zhu said. ``We are not your enemy. We are your
trustworthy friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhu ran into the biggest demonstrations of his visit on his
final day. Cambridge is home to Harvard as well as MIT, and
students often turn out in large numbers to see, or shout at,
prominent visitors. But these protests had a twist: most people
were Chinese, and they were divided almost equally into pro-China
and anti-China groups.
</P>
<P>
   Two organizers of demonstrations in Tiananmen Square a decade
ago, Wang Dan, now a Harvard student, and Chai Ling, now an
executive with an Internet company, led the group protesting
China's human rights record. ``No arming China with trade,'' read
one banner.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also many Chinese who carried China's
yellow-on-red national flag, sometimes together with an American
flag. ``I love Zhu the most,'' said Cheng Wenhao, 26, a student at
Yale University in New Haven, Conn., who drove to Cambridge for the
prime minister's visit. He carried a bouquet of Chinese flags and a
picture of Zhu.
</P>
<P>
   A brief scuffle broke out between pro- and anti-China camps
after they tried shouting each other down with bullhorns, but
police quickly separated the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu came to MIT in part because, even as prime minister, he
continues to serve as honorary dean of the business school at
Beijing's Qinghua University, often called China's MIT for its
dominance in engineering and the natural sciences. Qinghua, Zhu's
alma mater, has a sister-school relationship with MIT.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That may be why Zhu considered MIT the right venue for his trade
speech. When Jiang Zemin, China's No. 1 leader, visited the United
States 18 months ago, he made his keynote address down the street
at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   But Zhu's real intended audience was the U.S. Congress. He was
seeking to counter some legislators' arguments that the trade
deficit with China results from that country's unfair trade
practices. Many of these people also oppose China's joining the
world trade regulatory body, Zhu's crusade.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu does not deny that China has become an exporting power. But
he said the goods his country produces are frequently those that
developed countries, and increasingly even newly developed
countries in Asia, can no longer produce cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, about 70 percent of China's total exports to the
United States consist of products that are processed rather than
manufactured from scratch. That means that Chinese companies import
component parts and assemble them before exporting the finished
product.
</P>
<P>
   Athletic shoes are his favorite example. Though they are made in
China, foreign rather than Chinese factories do most of the work,
he said. Of the $120 sale price, $20 reflects production costs, and
only $2 goes to Chinese workers, Zhu estimated. ``China's added
value is very low,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister also said that if the United States really
wants to reduce its trade deficit, it should not apply restrictions
on exports of high-technology goods. He cited the Clinton
administration's recent decision to limit the export of satellites
and computers that China wants to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just want to export citrus and wheat to China, OK, the
door is open,'' Zhu said, referring to a new accord to free up
trade in those commodities. ``But the Chinese people want to live
better. For that, they need to buy your technology, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
