<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8513 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUILDPC-SFCHRON &LR;      04-14 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUILDPC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Chip Here, Drive There, You're Done
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By David Einstein &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
By building your own PC, you can:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Save a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; B:  &LR; Skin your knuckles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; C:  &LR; Ruin a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; D:  &LR; Have something to boast about at the next office party.
</P>
<P>
   If you picked B, C and D, you win. But if you think you'd save
money by putting together a computer from scratch, think again.
You'd be lucky to match the price PC-makers are charging these days
in their zeal to undercut the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, you can build yourself a bare-bones multimedia
system for well under $1,000 and a high-powered one for under
$1,500. And the best part is you have control over what goes in it.
You can select the components that fit you.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose, for example, that you're into gaming. By constructing
your own PC, you can include the latest 3-D graphics card and a
state-of-the-art sound card, rather than settling for the
less-robust multimedia technology that comes with most PCs.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a logical mind, are fairly good with your hands and
possess the patience of Job, there's no reason you can't skip steps
B and C above and build a PC. And if you do it right, it probably
will only take a couple of hours. Believe it or not, computers go
together pretty easily, thanks to industry standard connections for
all major components.
</P>
<P>
   To become your own computer company, you'll need these
components (you can get them at a big computer store or by mail
from a catalog company such as Tiger Direct at
 &LR; www.tigerdirect.com &LR; ):
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Case for the system &LR; : around $60. Cases come in desktop or
tower models, and they usually include a power supply with
connections for various components.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Motherboard &LR; : $75 to $150. This is the big green circuit board
to which everything else inside the case &LR;   &LR; attaches. Get one that
includes connection ports for the keyboard, mouse, printer and
other peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Processor, such as a Pentium II, a Celeron or an AMD K6 &LR; : $100
for a 333 MHz chip to $750 for a Pentium II 500.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Memory chips &LR; : $100 for 64 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Hard drive &LR; : $175 for 8 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _CD-ROM drive &LR; : $75.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Floppy drive &LR; : $35.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _A long drive in the country &LR; . That comes later and helps you
forget all about the PC.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Video card and sound card:  &LR; $50 to $200 (video card); $30 to
$100 (sound card). These aren't necessary if you get a motherboard
that comes with built-in sound and video.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Keyboard &LR; : $30 to $50.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Mouse &LR; : $15 to $50.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Modem:  &LR; $50.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Monitor &LR; : $225 for 17-inch model.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Speakers &LR; : $30 to $100.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Windows 98 &LR; : $170, includes some starter software.
</P>
<P>
   You can also buy bare-bones kits that include the motherboard
with sound, video and a case at a discount.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, PC components are interchangeable. Any floppy
drive, modem or monitor will work in any system. Motherboards,
however, are designed for specific processors, so make sure to
choose a motherboard that works with the chip you get.
</P>
<P>
   Also, look for a motherboard with enough expansion slots to
accommodate cards you may install for sound, video and other
peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   To turn all this stuff into a PC, you'll need a screwdriver and
perhaps a small wrench. Set up a work area that's free of static,
because static can fry your motherboard and other components.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, have at the ready instruction manuals that came
with the parts. They'll be useful.
</P>
<P>
   First, connect the processor to the motherboard. If you have a
Celeron or Pentium II, you'll need a special mounting bracket. And
don't forget to plug the chip's fan into the motherboard. Powerful
chips need to stay cool.
</P>
<P>
   Then plug the memory chip or chips into the motherboard.
</P>
<P>
   Attach the motherboard to the case. Then connect the power
supply to the motherboard.
</P>
<P>
   (Safety note: Don't plug the case into the wall until you're all
done, OK? Wouldn't want to lose a reader to electrocution.)
</P>
<P>
   With the motherboard installed, you can mount the hard drive,
the floppy drive and the CD-ROM. They slide into the case from the
front and are secured with screws that come with the case or with
the devices.
</P>
<P>
   Each drive must be connected to the motherboard with a flat
cable (also called a ribbon cable) that comes with the drive. Also
hook up each drive to a plug extending from the power supply.
</P>
<P>
   The case has a power button, a speaker and lights to show when
various drives are in use. You'll have to attach the wires for
those things to the motherboard, which should have clearly marked
connectors along one side.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, install audio, video and other cards, such as an
internal modem. You can put them into any slot they fit. And don't
forget to connect the CD-ROM drive to the sound card, so you can
listen to music CDs.
</P>
<P>
   That's it, the hard part's over. Check the motherboard manual
for instructions on starting the system. You also probably will
have to install setup software for the hard drive, the video and
sound cards and the modem.
</P>
<P>
   There, that wasn't too hard, was it? Was it? You still there?
Hello????
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
