<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8518 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON &LR;      04-14 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Web's Threat Prompts Newspapers to Put Up
Money-Losing  Sites 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The irony seemed obvious. Top newspaper editors in town for a
conference this week heard the same message from a lineup of
speakers from Internet companies: Change or die. Embrace the
Internet and stop killing trees.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the people calling for change lose money hand over fist. The
companies they say need radical restructuring are highly
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Excite chief executive George Bell, whose Web portal lost $37
million last year, was among the most fervent proselytizers on
stage at the American Society of Newspaper Editors convention at
the Fairmont Hotel. He said more people get their news from Yahoo
and Excite than from any newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   That's the sort of threat that's prompted newspapers all over
the country to put up their own money-losing Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Editor and Publisher magazine reported that Web losses are
mounting for publicly traded newspaper companies. Web-related
losses last year were $20 million at Times Mirror, $35 million at
the Tribune Co., $23 million for Knight Ridder and almost $15
million for the New York Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   I can just hear the Internet execs saying that's a step in the
right direction. Even Andy Grove, the chairman of Intel Corp. _ one
of the world's most profitable companies _ warned the editors that
they'll have to shell out some bucks to avert the impending crisis
when everyone gets their news from the Web and stops reading
newspapers. ``You cannot save yourself out of trouble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No, but there are some steps newspapers can take. I spoke last
month with Ed Manning, director of sales and marketing for Thomson
Interactive Media, the Web arm of a Connecticut company that owns
68 daily newspapers in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Manning's message: Newspaper Web operations don't need to lose
money. Thomson made $3 million last year from its Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We preach a sustainable evolution to the Internet,'' Manning
said.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers shouldn't start by simply digitizing their print
product, he said. Instead, start with classified ads, a
money-maker. Charge existing customers more to put their
classifieds online, and even more to put hot links in their ads.
</P>
<P>
   Papers can also cut costs by hiring another company to host the
Web site, instead of buying expensive computers and adding staff,
Manning said.
</P>
<P>
   Other items well-suited for the Web are special sections, like a
wedding guide, which Manning said ``appears in print in March or
April and then it goes away. What a perfect product to put
online.''
</P>
<P>
   And each day, they should promote the Web site in print. ``They
have one of the most tremendously coveted marketing tools of any
media company. Microsoft covets it,'' Manning said. ``Every day,
they've got the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NET MAG BATTLES:  &LR; At the dawn of the Internet economy, only
die-hard techies understood what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   That was just last year.
</P>
<P>
   In a case of great timing, two Bay Area magazines launched to
cover that ``Internet economy'' _ the way the Internet is pushing
its tentacles into every facet of business _ at just the time that
the Net became  &LR; the  &LR; story on every business person's mind.
</P>
<P>
   As the two new magazines, the Industry Standard and Business
2.0, mark their first anniversaries this month, their leaders say
their readership has expanded. Instead of the original target
market of nerds at high-tech companies _ the so-called chief
information officers, or CIOs, who buy a company's computer systems
_ the magazines are increasingly ending up in the hands of top
decision-makers at a range of consumer companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has really started to push the technology
question out of the CIO's office and into the CEO's office,'' said
Steve Thompson, publisher of the Industry Standard. The Standard's
circulation has grown to 100,000 per week, much of that unpaid.
</P>
<P>
   Business 2.0's latest reader survey shows that 64 percent of
readers work for companies that existed before the Internet, and
that 85 percent of readers hold managerial or professional-level
jobs. The monthly has a paid circulation of 140,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Each magazine was founded by alumni of Wired magazine, with
former Wired managing editor John Battelle now the president of the
Standard, and former Wired features editor Jim Daly the editor in
chief of Business 2.0.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For all their common ground and lineage, the magazines differ
in many respects. The Standard occupies brick and timber offices on
San Francisco's Battery Street, near bustling Broadway and the
Financial District. Business 2.0 is tucked in a secluded office
building in Brisbane, not far from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   They're both owned by computer magazine publishers, but the
Standard is the product of massive International Data Group, the
Massachusetts publisher of the wildly popular series of ``Dummies''
books, while Business 2.0 is published by comparatively small
Imagine Media, best known for computer gaming magazines.
</P>
<P>
   As a monthly, Business 2.0 has more long ``business strategy''
stories. ``We're not scoop-oriented,'' Daly said. ``I'm not sure
the world needs any more scoops.
</P>
<P>
   Although Business 2.0's Web site leaves a lot to be desired,
especially for a magazine devoted to the Net, Daly said an upgrade
is just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Industry Standard each week publishes a breezy
digest of recent news and opinions, with one or two longer
features. Its 30 news staffers work on a Web site that's updated
daily, and the magazine also produces e-mail newsletters and runs
conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no category for us,'' said Battelle. ``These are new
models, and it's fun. (The Standard) takes the best aspects of
trade publishing and the best aspects of business publishing. For
lack of a better term, it's diagonal, or horizertical.''
</P>
<P>
   And yes, I'm sorry to report that he really did say
``horizertical,'' although he did seem to regret it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ZD ZANINESS:  &LR; It's always a little funny when the offspring
grows bigger than the parent. But things are almost ridiculous in
the case of San Francisco's ZDNet, which rolled out its own stock
offering while remaining part of computer magazine publisher
Ziff-Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ZDNet's tracking stock, which trades on the Nasdaq under the
symbol ZDZ, has rocketed to a market valuation of more than $2.9
billion. That's more than the $1.9 billion the market says parent
Ziff-Davis, which trades under the symbol ZD, is worth.
</P>
<P>
   That's not just weird, it's absurd. First, a tracking stock
isn't the same as investing in just ZDNet. It's a stock that
measures ZDNet's prospects, but actually exposes investors to all
liabilities of Ziff-Davis, which continues to own 85 percent of
ZDNet.
</P>
<P>
   But the really strange part is how ZDNet could possibly be worth
more than Ziff-Davis itself.
</P>
<P>
   Ziff-Davis, which is based in New York, has been around since
1927, employs more than 3,200 people, and publishes more than 30
magazines with a worldwide circulation of 8 million. Its products
include PC Magazine, InterActive Week, Yahoo Internet Life, Family
PC and Macworld.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Ziff-Davis lost $78 million on revenue of $1.1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ZDNet is a puny offshoot, by comparison. It employs 300 people
(half in San Francisco, the rest mostly in Cambridge, Mass.). It
lost $7.9 million on revenue of $56 million in 1998. Although it
produces original content, it also gets about one-fifth of its
content from Ziff-Davis magazines.
</P>
<P>
   It just goes to show: Wall Street thinks that content is worth
more when it's translated from the glossy page and put into digital
bits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
