<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORLD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 E-commerce Is the Word At Trade Show   By Jon Swartz 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Los Angeles _ &UR;  &LR; Hundreds of Internet companies are giving e-commerce
a hard sell at Spring Internet World here.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech trade show, which runs throughout the week at the
cavernous Convention Center, is expected to draw 40,000 people, who
are a mixture of consumers, tech company executives and
brick-and-mortar retailers.
</P>
<P>
   A dizzying number of the 600 companies exhibiting on the
convention floor or in nearby hotel suites were promoting
e-commerce, either selling products directly to consumers over the
Internet or supplying the software for others to build their own
retail Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle of Redwood Shores led an infantry of companies with
e-commerce announcements. It plans new software for
business-to-business transactions on the Internet, one of the
fastest-growing e-commerce segments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the Gold Rush of the 19th century, you'll find
that those people who made money are the ones who provided the
picks and shovels,'' said Jeremy Burton, vice president of server
marketing at Oracle. ``We want to provide the picks and shovels to
the e-commerce gold rush.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, many thought banner ads, the static promos that
are fixtures at the top of a commercial Web site, would be the big
bread winner. But Web users are increasingly tuning them out and
instead buying more goods over the Net. E-commerce is projected to
be a $37.2 billion market this year, according Keenan Vision, a
market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are shopping more on the Web as it becomes more
popular and they have fewer concerns about supplying their
credit-card information online,'' said Paul Gauthier, co-founder
and chief technology officer of Inktomi Corp. His San Mateo company
recently launched a shopping area on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier said the online industry has reached a ``transition
point'' in how it expects to generate revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is e-commerce, e-commerce and e-commerce,'' said Katrien De
Graeve, a teacher from Brussels. ``Every TV commercial here has
`WWW' at the bottom of the screen. In Belgium, maybe two out of 10
ads do that. But we, too, are getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Launchpad, an exhibit-within-an-exhibit for three
dozen eBay-wannabes, several companies are eschewing
business-to-business e-commerce with some unconventional business
plans.
</P>
<P>
   _SpeedVu.com is producing some of the first TV-style ads for the
Web. The company has already produced spots for Lexus and
Investor's Business Daily that run about 10 seconds. In one Lexus
spot, a car zooms across the bottom of an auto Web site
 &LR; (www.freeway.com) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason banner ads are ignored is because they are
constantly on your screen,'' said Curt Hutten, president of the
Newport Beach company. ``No one would tolerate a banner ad during
`Seinfeld.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are spending $20 million to develop TV-like content
on a free Web site, yet customers refuse to look at it because of
banner ads,'' he said. ``So why not create TV-inspired ads? That's
what the public is accustomed to.''
</P>
<P>
   _The Humor Network &LR;  (www.joke-of-the-day.com) &LR;  _ which, all
kidding aside, calls itself ``the world's largest portal for
jokes'' _ said it has acquired the definitive San Francisco jokes
site. That Web page will debut in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Targan, ``jokemaster'' and founder of the New York firm,
added that the site has kicked off a political section that pokes
fun at the 2000 presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   _SportsID.com &LR;  (www.sportsid.com)  &LR; yesterday unveiled an
instructional Web site for sports enthusiasts. Some 500 video
segments _ ranging from two minutes to 20 minutes _ provide how-to
advice from professional athletes, such as former 49er Ronnie Lott,
and coach on everything from throwing a fastball to traversing a
kayak through rapids.
</P>
<P>
   _Jotter Technologies Inc.  &LR; (www.jotter.com)  &LR; is offering free
software that acts as a Web assistant. The program automatically
fills out electronic template forms for users, reminds them of
important dates with a built-in calendar and aids them in making
travel arrangements. The assistant even allows consumers to choose
what banner ads appear on their computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   _V-Star, a Southern California startup, said disclosed  &LR; it is in
the final stages of testing software that would allow consumers to
simultaneously download and view animations without clogging up
their Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, an Internet show also can be a haven for the
downright wacky.
</P>
<P>
   _Talkingweb, a German company, stirred plenty of buzz with a
voice-activated Web browser it is testing. The software program
would allow computer users to access and navigate the Internet via
a telephone _ and without a PC. Company executives were scouring
the 350,000-square-foot floor looking for telephone companies to
adopt the product.
</P>
<P>
   _eFax.com said it will make available in May technology that
enables consumers to send faxes over the Internet for $3 to $5 a
month. In February, the Menlo Park company began offering a free
service for receiving faxes via the Net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
