<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Speier called up; Winkelsas sent to Greenville
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Braves called up reliever Justin Speier from
AAA Richmond on Wednesday after a deadline passed that prevented
them from bringing up a 40-man roster player who was assigned to a
minor-league roster out of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Speier fills Mark Wohlers' roster spot, as Joe Winkelsas, a
nonroster invitee to the major-league camp in spring training, is
on his way back to AA Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   Speier, the 25-year-old son of former major-league infielder
Chris Speier, was acquired by the Braves from Florida the last week
of spring training in a trade for a player to be named later. He
pitched in the Cubs organization last season until July 31, when he
was traded to the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   In one appearance for the Cubs and 18 for the Marlins last
season, Speier was a combined 0-3 with an 8.71 ERA. He had 17
strikeouts but allowed seven home runs in 20 2/3 innings pitched.
</P>
<P>
   He throws a low-to-mid 90s fastball, slider and split-finger
fastball. He brings the number of Braves relievers who can hit the
mid 90s to four, along with John Rocker, Rudy Seanez and Kevin
McGlinchy.
</P>
<P>
   Part of his problem has been controlling his other two pitches.
But Speier spent three months in Puerto Rico playing winter ball,
working on locating his slider and splitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got in a groove down there and it carried over this
spring,'' Speier said.
</P>
<P>
   Speier made appearances in both exhibition games in Atlanta,
giving manager Bobby Cox a chance to see what he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his two appearances, it looked to me like he could pitch up
here,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   In two outings for AAA Richmond this season, Speier had one save
and a 4.50 ERA. He had just taken a flight into Richmond from
Charlotte on Wednesday morning when he was told to get back on a
plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited about being with a championship team,''
Speier said.
</P>
<P>
   Winkelsas made only one appearance in his five days. He gave up
four hits and two runs and recorded only one out.
</P>
<P>
   Airtime
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine spent seven hours Wednesday morning
and afternoon shooting a Nike shoe commercial, that came with a
perk. Their co-star was Heather Locklear.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine said the gist of the commercial was that if Mark McGwire
is popular with women because of his home runs, he and Maddux work
on their hitting in hopes of gaining the same popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a home run in batting practice and as soon as I hit it,
she's like `Hi Tom,' '' Glavine said of the ``Melrose Place'' star.
</P>
<P>
   They still have several hours more of shooting to do _ this time
without Locklear _ but may complete it by this weekend in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tedious process, but it's neat when it's all done,''
Glavine said.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   McGlinchy, who was hit in the right hand by a grounder on
Monday, was fine by Wednesday. ... Entering Wednesday's game, the
Braves were 3-1 when they don't hit a home run, 2-2 when they do.
Braves pitchers had allowed 10 home runs this season, nine of them
solo, seven of them allowed by starting pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
