<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-QB15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Tech reserves fight for the right to back up Hamilton
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ George Godsey awoke early Tuesday to attend physics
class. It might have been the lightest studying the Georgia Tech
industrial engineering major would do all day.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with interactions of matter and mastering the atomic
scale could be considered simple duty compared with learning the
intricate football offenses of Yellow Jackets coordinator Ralph
Friedgen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot on the quarterback,'' said Godsey, a redshirt
sophomore. ``It takes a lot of studying and knowing what to do when
you get out there. The offense depends on the quarterback making
the right decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2, 202-pound Godsey and redshirt freshman Jermaine
Crenshaw, 6-1, 203, are vying this spring to back up All-America
candidate Joe Hamilton on a team that has aspirations for a
national championship in 1999. The winner probably will position
himself as Hamilton's heir apparent.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, he will have to satisfy Friedgen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just grasping all the different formations of our offense is
only a start,'' Friedgen said. ``Having to read defenses is the
toughest part. They are so involved in knowing where all the
offensive players are, it can be a challenge to focus on the
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   To say Tech's offense guided by Friedgen was imaginative last
season while going 10-2 and averaging an ACC-best 35.5 points per
game would be an understatement. Hamilton, a senior, led a diverse
offense that mixed option runs with pro-set passing.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackets, who rushed for 2,021 yards and passed for 2,250,
sport more looks than Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little bit of everything,'' Friedgen said. ``We can be
one-back or two-backs. We can go no tight ends, one tight end or
two tight ends. Sometimes I wish we had more tight ends.''
</P>
<P>
   There are at least 100 basic plays in the offense, each of which
can be run five different ways. Crenshaw, from Greenville, Ala.,
demonstrated before he arrived at Tech that he was capable of
making the right call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I committed to Alabama,'' Crenshaw recalled. ``Coach (Mike)
DuBose was going to try me at quarterback, but he was going to
bring in three more. I didn't want to be in that type of situation.
Here, they liked me at quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   And still do.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's first major scrimmage, the duo shared first-team
play with Hamilton, while also splitting time with the second unit.
Crenshaw's numbers _ 4 of 7 passes, 33 yards, plus 35 rushing yards
_ topped those of Godsey _ 2-of-8, 22 passing yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crenshaw did some nice things out there,'' head coach George
O'Leary said, ``and at times Godsey had some plays. It all depended
on what team they were with.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Godsey, from Tampa, appeared in six games,
including a 5-of-10, 63-yard passing effort against Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to improve every day from where I left off at the
end of last year,'' he said. ``I want to be 10 times better a
player when I get out there (and) have a lot of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players credit Friedgen's acumen as a teacher for lifting
them to this point. Now, the rest is up to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Friedgen doesn't settle for anything but your very
best,'' Crenshaw said. ``You can complete a pass, but you still
have to explain to him why you went to that receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be able to step in without us missing a beat. I want
to run the offense with confidence. And after Joe graduates, I
don't want us to have to build up another quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
