<HEADER>
A8524 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-HOLTZ15-COX     04-14 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-HOLTZ15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South Carolina a `good fit' for Holtz
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Lou Holtz laughs long and hard when he's asked,
``What's a nice coach like you doing in a place like this?''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz, one of the top coaches in college football, has had
various levels of success in a 27-year coaching career that
includes stops at William &AMP; Mary, North Carolina State, Arkansas,
Minnesota and Notre Dame. Now, at age 61, he's probably facing the
ultimate rebuilding program at South Carolina _ a program that has
only had one season with more than eight victories in 107 years and
is coming off the worst season in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Long known for his one-liners, as well as his coaching ability,
Holtz, fourth among Division I active coaches with 216 victories,
has returned to the sideline after leaving Notre Dame following the
1996 season and spending two years as a television analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Have the other SEC coaches called to welcome him to the league?
``Some of them have and some haven't,'' Holtz said. ``Most of the
ones that called were the good ones. They were probably thinking,
`We got us a real fish here.'''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina certainly is paying attention to Lou Holtz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I think it's been a pretty good fit here for me,'' he
said. ``It's been a better fit for me than for the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz made a dramatic entrance into the state in December when,
during his initial press conference, he made an off-hand comment
that he was amazed at the amount of litter on the state's highways.
</P>
<P>
   His trash-talking brought about an unbelievable response that
has resulted in an unprecedented statewide litter-prevention
crusade. Last weekend, Holtz had his football team out on the
highway picking up litter during his ``Don't be a Dirty Bird'' day.
He also has taped public-service announcements encouraging
residents not to litter.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz says his task in Columbia may be more daunting than those
he's faced in the past. ``It's a little more difficult than my
other situations,'' he said. ``Maybe it's the most difficult,
because of the schedule and because of the expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach also has his detractors, many of whom think he's in
Columbia only as a public-relations ploy by the university to spiff
up its low athletic profile. They say Holtz is marking time until
he can hand over the coaching reigns to son Skip, who serves as his
offensive coordinator and associate head coach.
</P>
<P>
   But those critics have yet to see Holtz in action on the
practice field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's enjoying himself, enjoying the job,'' says Kerry Tharp,
an associate athletics director at the school. ``You go out and
watch practice and he's everywhere. He's grabbing them by their
helmets, jumping in their faces. He's engaged.''
</P>
<P>
   The often apathetic student body also is paying attention. When
Holtz scheduled a campus-wide address on the state of the football
program, more than 4,000 turned out to see their savior and hear
what he had to say.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what's happening on the periphery, Holtz has sold
himself to those who matter most _ his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to play for him,'' said Darion Hutcherson, a
linebacker who played at Atlanta's Douglass High. ``He's
enthusiastic. He lives for the game of football. The first day we
met him, we knew he had fire. After we met him, we were ready to
play right then. He can do his part, but it's the players who've
got to have the desire. He's going to be sure that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Kerry Hood, an alum of Atlanta's Harper-Archer
High, says he's sold 100 percent. ``He's the most intense,
in-your-face coach I've ever had,'' Hood said. ``He won't allow you
to fail.''
</P>
<P>
   After the spring game Saturday, Holtz says, the really critical
time begins for his squad. ``What kind of year we have will depend
on what we do over the summer in individual workouts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the workers seem willing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a little kid growing up, I watched Notre Dame play
and dreamed of playing for a guy like that some day,'' Hood said.
``It's like a dream come true that he's here.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz has done his best to keep things in perspective, as much
for the fans as for himself. ``Based on what we have here now,''
Holtz said, ``we can't be competitive this year. But then again, I
don't believe in four-to-five-year rebuilding efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   So where do the Gamecocks stand today and for the future?
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't going to be an overnight turnaround,'' Holtz said.
``I'm not a miracle worker.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
