<SLUG> BC-DOLE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE TO VISIT BALKANS, BACKS U.S. GROUND TROOPS IN KOSOVO 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Likely Republican presidential candidate Elizabeth
Hanford Dole on Wednesday joined a growing crowd of politicians who
say President Clinton should consider sending ground troops into
Kosovo if his military advisers urge such action.
</P>
<P>
   The former Red Cross director elaborated her position on Kosovo
as part of an address on international affairs at the U.S. Naval
Academy in Annapolis, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Dole initially supported the airstrikes ordered by Clinton,
citing the region's strategic importance and humanitarian concerns.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday's remarks bring her in line with the more hawkish
voices in the Republican Party, which have been led by rival
presidential contender Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long experience teaches that when we've committed military
forces to a rightful goal, we should use all the power necessary to
achieve it,'' Dole said, according to a copy of her prepared
remarks. ``To accept the status quo is to risk defeat, defeat for
NATO and defeat for humanitarian _ and very American _ objective of
preventing genocide where we can. Does that mean ground troops? If
the NATO commanders and the Joint Chiefs of Staff say that ground
troops are required to accomplish our goals, then my answer is
yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole's speech to the midshipmen came as she prepared to travel
to Macedonia and Albania Thursday to visit the refugee camps filled
with ethnic Albanians pushed out of Kosovo by the Serbs. She will
return to Washington on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A Dole aide said she had been invited to the camps by the first
lady of Albania and a refugee organization, Mercy Corps
International of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's trip and her speech at the Naval Academy appear designed
to contrast her foreign policy experience to some of her
competitors, particularly Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Dole talked about her travels as head of the Red Cross to
troubled regions of the world, including Bosnia and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has had virtually no foreign policy experience, has
been criticized for stands considered vague and evolving on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Bush also appeared to be moving in the direction of a
tougher military action. He said that ``once the military is
engaged, it must be engaged with one thing in mind, and that is
victory.``
</P>
<P>
   Dole criticized the Clinton administration for the decline in
defense spending, which she said has caused lowered readiness,
reduced morale and and aging equipment.
</P>
<P>
   She also suggested that the current international problems may
have been caused by the president's lack of credibility stemming
from his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credibility counts,'' she said. ``And if you have any
questions about that, look at the U.N. weapons inspections mess in
Iraq or today's tragedy in Kosovo. When tough deadlines are set and
then repeatedly postponed; when the other side appears to break its
agreements with impunity; when we accept half-promises; we send the
wrong signals about our values and our will.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
