<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8526 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT15-COX     04-14 0279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Browns settle on Couch at No. 1
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The only thing that will keep Kentucky quarterback Tim
Couch from being the first pick in Saturday's NFL draft is if
Cleveland Browns officials decide in the next 48 hours that his
contract demands are excessive.
</P>
<P>
   After months of deliberation, the Browns on Wednesday settled on
Couch over Oregon quarterback Akili Smith as the top choice for the
resurrected franchise. Cleveland is expected to accelerate the pace
of talks with agent Tom Condon, with the goal to complete a
contract agreement before the draft begins Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal could be for seven years and be worth as much as $44
million, with the signing bonus about $12.5 million. Condon
represented former Tennessee quarterback Peyton Manning, last
year's No. 1 overall pick, and negotiated his landmark contract
with the Indianapolis Colts. Should the negotiations falter,
Cleveland officials will turn to Smith, whom they regard as nearly
the equal of Couch. In some physical areas, including arm strength,
Smith is the better prospect. Rookie coach Chris Palmer said early
this week that the pair was ``neck and neck.'' The team has ruled
out drafting Heisman Trophy tailback Ricky Williams of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Couch performed well Sunday, throwing 115 passes in a 90-minute
workout administered by Palmer in Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the 1971 draft, quarterbacks are
expected to be the first three choices, with Donovan McNabb of
Syracuse joining Couch and Smith as top prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
