<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0435 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8527 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMETOWN-HEROES15-COX     04-14 1670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMETOWN-HEROES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DuPont High's two ball belles
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLE, W.Va. _ Across the Kanawha River, the road signs along
Cabin Creek hollow proudly proclaim: ``Home of Jerry West, NBA
great.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the other side of the Chelyan Bridge, where the DuPont
chemical plant lights the valley sky even at midnight, there is
nothing to let you know that Belle _ population 1,421 _ and the
neighboring unincorporated community of Rand can claim two big-time
hometown heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a while for the Jerry West signs to go up,'' said Jim
Fout, athletics director and basketball coach at DuPont High
School, which is consolidating with West's East Bank High to form a
new school next fall. ``Randy and Jason are only rookies.''
</P>
<P>
   True. But not since Bill Russell and Frank Robinson more than 40
years ago have two first-year players from the same high school
made as big a major-league splash as Randy Moss and Jason Williams,
DuPont High class of 1995 and 1994, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   That Moss and Williams come from the same small school in
Appalachia and have traveled winding paths more treacherous than a
narrow mountain road make their stories even more intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're real proud of what both those boys are doing,'' Belle
Mayor Larry Conley said. ``I hope things keep going well and
neither of them have any more trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   West, who grew up in a simpler time, has always been revered in
West Virginia. East Bank, a coal town of 892, changed its name to
West Bank in his honor for a day, twice _ after he led his high
school to the state title in 1956 and again when he completed his
All-America career at West Virginia University.
</P>
<P>
   Young fans snap up Minnesota Vikings jerseys with Moss' No. 84
as soon as they arrive at stores in the West Virginia capital of
Charleston, about 10 miles up the Kanawha River. Williams'
Sacramento Kings jerseys are expected to go just as fast when they
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   But Moss and Williams are still eyed with suspicion by many
older West Virginians, who have hungered for someone or something
to bring lasting honor to their often-maligned state since West
retired from the NBA in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Moss, whose much-chronicled troubles began when he was arrested
after a hallway brawl late in his senior year of high school,
burned bridges by making some negative remarks about West Virginia
to a Minnesota reporter just before his record NFL rookie season
with the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who has brought a little of Pete Maravich back to the
NBA and dominates ESPN highlights, also has been too blunt for his
own good at times, especially when admiting to the marijuana use
that caused him to be kicked off the University of Florida
basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither Randy nor Jason is the kind of person some people
think they are,'' said Fout, their old DuPont basketball coach.
``But at times, both have been their own worst enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't learn from Randy's mistakes. I had to make my own,''
said Williams, who like Moss saw his draft position in the first
round drop because of character questions.
</P>
<P>
   But for a while, it looked as if Moss and Williams were headed
to making the area's infamous All 7-Eleven team, rather than
reaching major-league stardom. The parking lot in front of the
one-stop gas, food and liquor store near the school is where failed
athletes and others with little to look forward to have hung out
for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the things that happened, we were both in that let-down
category,'' said Moss, who spent several months in jail for a
probation violation before getting a chance to shine at Marshall
University. ``But now it is nothing but smiles to know that both of
us are doing good.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss, 22, and Williams, 23, were reunited in late February when
Sacramento played in Minneapolis against the Minnesota
Timberwolves. The two spent time together the night before, and
then Moss took in the game, wearing one of Williams' No. 55 Kings
jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything Jason does in the NBA, I've already seen in high
school,'' said Moss, a year behind Williams in school. ``He was
doing all that stuff way back then. It's not new to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Moss, who attended different elementary schools,
didn't meet for the first time on a basketball court or football
field, but rather on the Little League baseball diamond behind
DuPont High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always scared when I had a bat and Randy was pitching,''
Williams said in his mountain twang. ``He was real wild.''
</P>
<P>
   At DuPont Junior High, Williams was the football quarterback in
ninth grade and eighth-grader Moss his favorite target. As you can
imagine, it was an unstoppable combination.
</P>
<P>
   But when Williams entered high school, he gave up football and
baseball to concentrate on his only real love _ basketball. Moss
was a standout in football, basketball, baseball and track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is everything to Jason,'' said his father, Terry, a
retired West Virginia State Trooper who recently moved to
Sacramento to be near his son. ``Without it, I really worry about
him. He never had much interest in anything else. He always hated
school.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jason was growing up, his father helped provide security at
the high school, and they lived in a double-wide mobile home next
to the parking lot. That meant Jason always had a place to play
basketball _ any time, day or night.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter when, you always would see Jason in the gym,'' Moss
said. ``He about lived in there, coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually by himself, Williams would concentrate on his passing
and dribbling, rather than on his shot. Wearing weights on his
ankles and occasionally gloves, he would circle the tiny gym,
boucing the ball off the wall with either hand. He spent even more
time there after his parents divorced.
</P>
<P>
   All of Williams' extra work, however, never produced a state
title for DuPont. With Moss leading the way, the Panthers won state
football titles in 1992 and '93, but DuPont shot an air ball in
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two best players in the state, and we choked,'' Moss said,
referring to the 79-73 loss to Martinsburg in the 1994 state title
game when he was a junior and Williams a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Fout disagrees. ``They had 27 and 26 points. It wasn't their
fault we lost. But I'll take that game with me to my grave.''
</P>
<P>
   No high school ever has produced two rookie-of-the-year winners
in a 12-month period. McClymonds High School in Oakland, Calif.,
came the closest. Baseball Hall of Famer Frank Robinson won the
honor in the National League in 1956, and basketball great Bill
Russell placed second in the NBA voting after the 1956-57 season.
</P>
<P>
   Moss won NFL honors last fall and Williams is one of the top
five candidates in the NBA this season. ``I'm yelling it, `Rookie
of the year,''' Moss said about Williams in a television interview
on TNT early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Toronto's Vince Carter wins the award, there is no
denying the impact of the two players from little DuPont, which
once had 1,300 students but now is down to fewer than 600.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all like a fantasy,'' said Fout, who was a standout
player at DuPont in the mid-1960s and a teammate of Jason's father.
``I can't believe two players from a school this size are doing
what they're doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, DuPont and East Bank, which now has fewer than 500
students, will become middle schools and a new four-year Riverside
High School will open in the Quincy area, east of Belle.
</P>
<P>
   But the framed color photos of Moss and Williams will remain in
the DuPont gym, on the wall where Jason used to bounce the ball at
all hours of the night. The old black-and-white photo of West _
wearing No. 12 instead of his famous 44 _ will remain at East Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want the new school to start fresh,'' said Fout, who will
be basketball coach and athletics director at Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Moss and Williams, the new school will have a deal
with Nike. The free shoes will be appreciated, but memories of
DuPont and East Bank will die hard. Together, they won nine state
titles in football, although only one in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that those schools are closing,'' said West,
now vice president of the Los Angeles Lakers. ``Progress or not,
it's sad. Real sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Reynolds, personnel director of the Sacramento Kings,
said, ``They ought to bottle that water back there and make a whole
lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be more valuable than coal.
</P>
<P>
   JASON WILLIAMS FILE
</P>
<P>
   Birthdate: Nov. 18, 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Home: Belle, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   High school: Two-time AAA all-state basketball pick and Gatorade
state player of year as senior. Kanawha County player of year as
junior and senior.
</P>
<P>
   College: Played only 48 games in four years _ 28 at Marshall in
1995-96 and 20 at Florida last season _ before being kicked off the
Gators for testing positive for marijuana twice. Averaged 17 points
and nearly 7 assists at Florida.
</P>
<P>
   NBA: Taken by Sacramento in first round (7th overall) after
junior year. One of leading candidates for rookie of the year
because of his flashy play. Averaging 12.7 points and 5.5 assists
per game.
</P>
<P>
   RANDY MOSS FILE
</P>
<P>
   Birthdate: Feb. 13, 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Home: Rand, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   High school: Three-time AAA all-state pick in football and
basketball. Player of year in both sports as senior, when he
averaged more than 30 points per game. Also played baseball and was
a state champ in track and field.
</P>
<P>
   College: Played two seasons at Marshall after losing his
scholarship to Florida State when he tested positive for marijuana
and was jailed for violating his probation on an assault charge
from a high school fight. Caught 53 TD passes _ at least one in
each game _ and won Fred Biletnikoff Award as top college receiver.
</P>
<P>
   NFL: Taken by Minnesota in first round (21st overall) after
sophomore year. Made the Pro Bowl and was named NFL rookie of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
