<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8529 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE-SFCHRON &LR;      04-14 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Apple Beats Estimates _ Profits Soar
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By David Einstein &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Yum'' says an ad for Apple Computer's iMac computers, which come
in strawberry, blueberry and three other colors. Apple's stock may
look pretty tasty too this morning in the wake of the company's
sixth straight profitable quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the results reported yesterday marked the best
performance yet for Steve Jobs, the prodigal son who became interim
chief executive in July 1997 and guided the Cupertino company back
after it had foundered under two previous leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by continued success of the iMac as well as strong sales
of the powerful and equally Jetson-like G3 models, Apple's income
from operations in the second quarter soared a better-than-expected
69 percent to $93 million (60 cents a share) from $55 million (38
cents) in the same quarter last year. Analysts had expected around
57 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the news came after the market closed, Apple's stock
jumped $1.13 to $35.75 as word of the stellar quarter got around
the Street.
</P>
<P>
   The rise also may have reflected investor reaction to Apple's
appointment yesterday of former Volkswagen marketing executive
Steve Wilhite as vice president of worldwide marketing. The
47-year-old Wilhite, who worked on the marketing campaign for the
new VW Beetle, has already joined Apple and is reporting directly
to Jobs.
</P>
<P>
   During the three months ended March 27, Apple's revenues rose 9
percent to $1.53 billion. The company said it shipped 827,000
computers, including 350,000 iMacs, the cute-as-a-button computers
that have been a hit with first-time buyers looking for a machine
with which to surf the Web. More than 1.1 million iMacs have been
shipped since their introduction last August.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Apple's second-quarter shipments were 27 percent higher
than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're delighted with the quarter's results,'' Jobs said in a
telephone interview. ``Apple has a plan and is executing it. The
plan has a lot of components, but the heart of it is coming up with
a great product strategy and making the best PCs in the world _ in
particular for getting on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he intends to scratch the ``interim'' off of his title
and become permanent CEO, Jobs, who also runs the Pixar animation
company, said, ``I really haven't had much time to think about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts yesterday, Apple Chief
Financial Officer Fred Anderson listed several factors that helped
the company beat Wall Street projections for the fifth straight
quarter:
</P>
<P>
   _Apple's share of the U.S. desktop market climbed as high as
12.5 percent during the quarter, according to ZD Storeboard. That
was more than double the company's market share a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   _In an industry where profits have been squeezed by dramatic
price declines, Apple's gross margins increased year-over-year from
24.8 percent to 26.3 percent. A big reason was the increased sales
of G3 machines, which are Apple's most expensive.
</P>
<P>
   _Apple ended the quarter with just one day of inventory, pacing
the industry and besting Dell Computer for the third quarter in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   _In an indication that Asia's economy may be recovering, Apple
said its hottest geographical market was Japan, where shipments
rose 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said the company is confident its shipments and
revenues will surpass the industry as a whole for the rest of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple is clearly back on track,'' said analyst Tim Bajarin,
president of Creative Strategies in Campbell. ``I don't see any
reason they won't be able to keep this momentum going, at least
through the end of this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple took an $8 million charge in the just-completed quarter to
cover outsourcing of some computer assembly. It also recorded a $50
million gain from the sale of part of its stake in chipmaker ARM.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
