<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8531 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYMANTEC-SFCHRON &LR;      04-14 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMANTEC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Symantec Picks Boss _ IBM Exec
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Benny Evangelista &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Ending a four-month search, Symantec Corp. yesterday named
high-ranking IBM executive John W. Thompson as the antivirus
software-maker's new chief executive, president and chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, 49, replaces Silicon Valley pioneer Gordon Eubanks,
who today officially takes over as CEO of Oblix Inc., a Mountain
View company in the emerging field of business directory software.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled and I'm energized I was selected and I'm ready to
get going,'' Thompson said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Thompsonn, a graduate of Florida A&AMP;M, worked at IBM for 28
years, most recently as general manager of IBM's Americas unit,
which had $37 billion in 1998 sales and 30,000 employees. Symantec
said the division, which handles Internet and electronic commerce
business accounts, accounted for 10 percent of all information
technology spending in North, Central and South America.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has been mentioned as a possible successor to current
IBM Chairman &UR;  &LR; Louis Gerstner, who last year signed a contract
extension that will keep him in that post for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted the chance to run my own company,'' Thompson said.
``There can only be one CEO of a large company.''
</P>
<P>
   His decision to leave IBM came from ``the opportunities at
Symantec, not something I was running away from at IBM,'' he said.
``The size of the business is less important than your sense of
importance to customers. What Symantec does is of great importance
to customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson previously headed IBM's personal software products
group and was in charge of developing IBM's OS/2 computer operating
system. Even though the operating system was eventually squeezed by
the dominant Windows NT platform, analysts said Thompson brings
Symantec a history of success and contacts in corporate software
sales, which is a key battleground for Symantec.
</P>
<P>
   Cupertino's Symantec, which posted $574 million in revenues last
year, has 2,300 employees and faces stiff competition from No.1
antivirus and computer-utilities-maker Network Associates Inc. of
Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson ``brings a lot of credibility to the company,'' said
analyst Robbie Owens of Pacific Crest Securities. ``He can
accelerate Symantec's move into the corporate side of the business.
He's got the relationships and that's key in this space.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson also becomes one of the most prominent African American
CEOs in Silicon Valley at a time when civil rights leaders are
pushing high-tech companies to expand boardrooms, employment and
marketing to include more minorities and women.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, for example, visited executives at SGI
and Apple Computer on Monday as the next step in his Rainbow/PUSH
Coalition's Wall Street Project. The project, which has purchased
stock in Symantec and 50 other Silicon Valley companies, aims to
bridge a so-called Digital Divide.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's qualified, experienced and accomplished,'' said Butch
Wing, California coordinator for the Rainbow/PUSH Coalition. ``We
applaud his appointment and hope this opens the doors for other
people of color to become CEOs and decision makers in the high-tech
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks said he supports the Wall Street Project's goals and is
a fan of Jackson, but said the fact that Thompson was African
American played no part in the company's decision to hire him as
CEO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think in those terms, we think in terms of getting
the job done,'' Eubanks said. ``Symantec attracted a top-notch
executive, one of the handful of the best executives of IBM.''
</P>
<P>
   In a teleconference, Thompson said that at IBM, he ``never
thought of myself in the context of the most highly placed African
American. I was really focused on being the most effective leader I
can be. If my acting as a role model or a guide post (shows) that
it can be achieved, I'm delighted with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Symantec's current chairman, Carl Carman, will remain on the
board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Symantec closed at $14.13, up $1.13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
