<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8533 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-LINEBACKERS     04-14 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-LINEBACKERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Claiborne, Katzenmoyer, Kearse destined to excel as NFL linebackers
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Call this the tale of three linebackers who could become perennial
Pro Bowl selections, all underclassmen with almost unbelievable
God-given ability. They have taken different routes to the NFL, but
all will be No. 1 draft choices Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California's Chris Claiborne is the best middle
linebacker prospect in years. He is what Ohio State's Andy
Katzenmoyer was supposed to be after his extraordinary freshman
year.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's Jevon Kearse is the most physically gifted of the
group, but he enters the draft without a true position. He is best
suited for the weak side in a 3-4. Ideally, he would only have to
play end in passing situations.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne will be among the first six picks. Kearse will be gone
by the 10th pick. Katzenmoyer will be a first-round selection, but
no one is sure which team will draft him.
</P>
<P>
   If Claiborne, Kearse and Katzenmoyer could take their best
college season and apply it to the NFL, they will become stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where I'll be drafted, but I think I'm one of the
top defensive players in the draft,'' Claiborne said. ``I'm no
longer worried about when I go. Wherever I go, though, I'm going to
make an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne is so talented he can play inside or outside. Seldom
will you find a middle linebacker who drops into coverage so well.
He led the Trojans with six interceptions last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bring everything to the table,'' Claiborne said. ``I'll even
play special teams. I'm fast. I'm a big hitter. I'm very consistent
in what I do. I play the pass and run very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne has outstanding size and speed. There is nothing he
can't do on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis has the fourth pick. The Colts could select
Claiborne. He is familiar with the Colts because he has done his
homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just a couple of points away from winning more
games,'' he said. ``All they need now is some defensive players to
come in and make plays. I've looked at every team I've felt could
draft me to see how I'll fit into their system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll definitely do my job. When you play football, it's not
about turning the whole defense around. It's about doing your job
and being consistent in what you do. I'm going to work hard every
day and learn the system, help them make calls. If the coach feels
confident in me, I'll bring that confidence on the field, make
plays and make the fans happy.''
</P>
<P>
   During his redshirt freshman year in 1996, no linebacker in the
country made more plays than Katzenmoyer. He was excellent as a
sophomore, too, and there was talk that he would try to enter the
NFL draft and take the league to court if he had to. Instead, he
stayed in school, was used differently, and his performance
suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot more pressure on me, but I didn't think the
season was difficult,'' Katzenmoyer said. ``There's a huge amount
of pressure when you play middle linebacker at Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I contributed everything I could. I did what the
coaches asked me to do. We ended up finishing second (in defense).
We were the No. 1 run defense in the country. I thought we did
pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   After his freshman year, Katzenmoyer was supposed to be the next
Butkus. He was supposed to corner the market on awards. Last
season, he didn't win any.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was because of the hype,'' he said. ``If you get
the hype, you have a better chance of going to the ceremony and
getting the award. Sportswriters all over the country vote on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer had a reputation for partying too much. He had
problems with grades and alcohol. He refused to be interviewed by
the media all season, a decision he regrets.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer has no regrets about not testing the NFL's
underclassman rule after his sophomore season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been ridiculous,'' he said. ``Why would I
waste my time in court for a year when I can keep playing football
in college?
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't difficult to come out this year. It wasn't the
easiest of decisions, but it wasn't really that difficult. I sat
down with my parents, talked it over and made my decision in 10
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Some scouts like Katzenmoyer on the outside to take advantage of
his speed and recklessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can play both,'' he said. ``I think I have the best
of both worlds. My style is to attack. When I'm allowed to attack,
I'll run right through you. I don't want anything to get in my way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I've matured. I'm more knowledgeable about the game.
I really think I played the best last season that I've played in
three years at Ohio State. I did everything I was asked. I made few
mistakes. I didn't have the numbers, but we had a great defense,
and I put out a great effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I'm ready for the next level. This next step is a huge
challenge. Hopefully, I'll be able to live up to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Katzenmoyer, Kearse believes that his potential to play
more than one position is a blessing rather than a curse. Kearse
might be a super outside linebacker or defensive end. The scouts
agree that he has the ability to become a dynamite pass rusher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call me `Slash,''' Kearse says, laughing because he knows that
nickname belongs to Steelers quarterback Kordell Stewart. ``Some
teams say if I put on another 15 pounds and keep my speed, I'll
play end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others say I can play end at this weight. Some think I should
lose weight to play outside linebacker. I love to rush the
quarterback, but it doesn't matter which position I play. Mainly, I
like a scheme where I can do both.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearse is 6-4{, 262. He consistently runs the 40 in the 4.5s At
his individual workout in March, he ran in the 4.4s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited about the draft,'' he says. ``I want to be an
impact player from day one. I want to just take over the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
