<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, APRIL 15
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   B-SINGER-BIOETHICS-NYT (moved on Friday, Apr. 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Apr. 9,
about the appointment of Peter Singer, a defender of euthanasia, to
a chair in bioethics at Princeton University misidentified the
university where he now teaches. It is Monash University in
Melbourne, Australia, not the University of Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   The article also misidentified a scholar from the American
Enterprise Institute who commented on Mr. Singer's position. She is
Christina Hoff Sommers, not Christina Hawke Smith.
</P>
<P>
   BC-EPA-SUV-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Apr. 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Apr. 13,
about a plan to toughen Federal pollution standards for gasoline
and automobiles misstated the reaction of Senator James M. Inhofe,
Republican of Oklahoma. He is drafting legislation to modify the
new standards, which have not yet been issued. His bill would not
cancel them.
</P>
<P>
   BC-FAA-Y2K-NYT (moved on Sunday, Apr. 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Apr. 11,
about a test of how the nation's air traffic control system might
operate when the date rolls over to the year 2000 incorrectly
described the part of the drill involving a Federal Aviation
Administration plane. While the computer that controlled the radios
between the plane and the air traffic controller were rolled over
to simulate the year 2000, the radar screens monitoring the plane
used the correct current date so that the plane could be safely
watched.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT (moved on Monday, Apr. 12)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Apr. 12,
about exercise machines that allow users to surf the Internet
misstated the given name of the chairman and chief executive of the
Can Do Club, a fitness center in Wayne, N.J., that has the
equipment. He is Stuart Polevoy, not Steve. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
