<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER EARNINGS STRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Time Warner Inc., continuing its stellar
performance, reported first-quarter results that blew through Wall
Street's forecasts and reflected strength in all of its businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time Warner has become the premiere entertainment and cable
company in the world,'' said analyst Barry Hyman of Ehrenkrantz
King Nussbaum. ``There was not a single disappointment in the
earnings report.''
</P>
<P>
   The conglomerate posted profits of $138 million, or 10 cents a
share, easily beating the consensus estimate of a loss of 4 cents a
share. The 1998 quarter saw a loss of $62 million due to poor music
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues rose 2 percent to $3.27 billion while cash flow, a key
for debt-heavy media concerns like Time Warner, soared 47 percent
to $1.25 billion, aided by a $215 million gain from termination of
MGM's video distribution pact. Time Warner ended last year with
$16.5 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been heartened by Warner Bros., the Burbank-based
film-TV business, which rose 10 percent in cash flow to $131
million without the MGM gain as ``You've Got Mail'' and ``Analyze
This'' beat forecasts. Its movie business has rebounded with ``The
Matrix'' and solid forecasts for ``Austin Powers 2,'' ``Wild Wild
West'' and ``Eyes Wide Shut.''
</P>
<P>
   Music posted a 10 percent increase to $102 million on strong
sales by Cher, Alanis Morissette, Sugar Ray, Jewel and Madonna;
Cable-TBS rose 20 percent to $184 million and Cable-HBO was up 15
percent to $125 million; publishing gained 11 percent to $94
million; cable operations rose 6 percent to $403 million.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which has doubled in value in less than a year,
touched an all-time high of $78.625 before falling back to $73.50
for a $3.50 loss as part of a sell-off of large-cap issues.
``Today's loss was market-driven and had nothing to do with the
earnings,'' Hyman said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
