<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      04-14 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES BILL THAT ALLOW LOCAL CHALLENGES TO 2000 CENSUS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Texas, Mo., Calif.)   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a partisan brawl, the House Wednesday night
approved a bill that would allow local officials to challenge the
accuracy of next year's census and to demand a recount of any
neighborhoods where they suspected errors.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 223-206. Only four Democrats voted for the bill,
and only one Republican, Rep. Constance A. Morella of Maryland,
voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans said the bill would increase the accuracy of
the census. But Democrats said it was intended to frustrate the
Clinton administration's ambitious plans for statistical sampling
to correct the expected undercount of blacks, Hispanic Americans
and poor people, who tend to favor Democratic candidates when they
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The White House strenuously opposed the bill. The outlook for
the legislation in the Senate is not clear because senators have
not focused on it.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Secretary William M. Daley said he would urge Clinton
to veto the bill if Congress passed it. In an interview, Kenneth
Prewitt, director of the Census Bureau, a unit of the Commerce
Department, said, ``It's courting disaster to insert a major new
operation of this magnitude into the census process.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said the bill raised the question of who was better
equipped to spot mistakes in census tallies: local officials, who
deal with local residents every day, or federal statisticians in
Washington, who would adjust the figures. Many social scientists
have endorsed the use of statistical sampling, but Republicans said
they could never trust the Clinton administration to use it in an
even-handed way.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the House Republican floor leader,
said: ``You should be counted in your home. You shouldn't be
estimated. The process of local review reveals where the count
wasn't complete or accurate. Should we ask the mayor and local
officials, or should the federal government use some abstract
mathematical model, defined by the Clinton administration, which
has politicized everything it has touched in this government?''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the House Democratic leader,
described the census as ``the last great civil rights issue of this
century.'' Rep. Carolyn B. Maloney, D-N.Y., said Republicans ``want
errors left in the census because they believe that those errors
create a political advantage for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., said Democrats were ``playing the
race card,'' impugning the motives of Republicans. ``To argue that
the government must do statistical sampling because we are racist
is one of the most slimy political arguments I have ever heard,''
Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Billions of dollars of federal money for roads and bridges,
education, health care and law enforcement ride on the census
results.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill approved Wednesday by the House, the Census
Bureau would provide local officials with certain preliminary data,
including the number of housing units on each block, a complete
address list and the total population count for each governmental
unit. Local officials could assert, for example, that the Census
Bureau had used the wrong geographic boundaries for a city or
county, missed a cluster of housing units or listed housing units
in the wrong location. The Census Bureau would have to investigate
such complaints and ``correct any miscounts,'' by recanvassing
blocks where there were possible problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
