<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS TAKE PROFITS, WITH DOW GAINING BY 16.65 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a session showing exceptional shifts in focus,
investors Wednesday cashed in profits in high-flying technology and
consumer stocks and switched their money into neglected issues that
would benefit from revived world economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   When the churning ended, seven of the 30 components of the Dow
Jones industrial average had surged more than 3 points, with Alcoa
jumping 6 9/16 to 53\, and six Dow stocks had more than 3 points,
with Wal-Mart down 5 15/16, to 98|.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-chip gauge eked out a 16.65-point advance to 10,411.66,
its third straight record but well off its day's high. It was ahead
by 131-points at mid-day. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index,
however, fell 0.83 percent for the session, and the NASDAQ market
slumped 2.95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely the beginning of a sector rotation going on
that could become violent, given the relative valuations,'' said
Rosanne Cahn, equity economist at CS First Boston. ``All the stuff
that's cast a pall over the industrial cyclicals is starting to
turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few sessions investors have started to gravitate
toward such economically sensitive industries as paper, chemicals,
metals and machinery on the belief that foreign economic crises are
abating and that world economic growth will pick up, aided by last
week's European interest-rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a select handful of favorite big-name stocks
have vaulted ever higher. ``Investors are taking another look at
price-to-book and price-to-earnings ratios,'' said Daniel Eagan, a
portfolio manager at Black Rock in Philadelphia. ``The high
valuations are causing them to look for other opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the winners were Dow Chemical, up 8, to 109{; Georgia
Pacific 6|, to 91\; Caterpillar 5 15/16, to 60 11//16, and Nucor, a
steel company, 3{, to 55 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a market that's moving away from the defensive names,
with people attracted to cyclicals,'' said Gary Dickinson,
portfolio manager at Columbia Partners in Washington, ``Most of the
problems of the global economy may be behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors' interest in smaller stocks has also picked up in
recent sessions. The Russell 2000 index pushed up Wednesday
morning, briefly moving into plus territory for the year before its
substantial gain largely evaporated during the afternoon. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's index of small-capitalization stocks posted a
1.15 percent gain Wednesday, trimming its decline so far this year
to 7.37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., which reported a much bigger earnings
increase than Wall Street expected, soared as high 140 1/16 before
succumbing to profit-taking to close at 132~, leaving it a gain of
3 9/16. Boeing rose 3], the biggest gain in five months, to 38 on
optimism about its earnings report Thursday. Time Warner beat
earnings expectations but fell 3{, to 73{, although it traded
after-hours as high as 78|.
</P>
<P>
   TRW, which warned of lower profits, fell 1 1/16, to 41 15/16,
after hitting a 52-week low.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage houses joined technology and drugs among the weakest
sectors. Schwab tumbled 12\, to 138\, Merrill Lynch 5 5/16, 92 1/16
and Knight/Trimark 17 7/16, to 100 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Intel slumped 3{, to 57, America Online 8 7/16, to 150~, Dell 2
5/16, to 38[, Microsoft 4\,, to 85~, Amazon.com 10], to 168 and
Ebay 10, to 162~.
</P>
<P>
   Merck, Pfizer, Schering Plough and American Home Products each
fell more than 4 points, while Lilly and Warner-Lambert fell more
than 3.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, volume climbed to a hefty 952
million shares, with advancing issues outnumbering declining ones
by 1,766 to 1,285. A total of 113 issues hit new 52-week highs
while 63 made new lows.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilshire 5000 index, which includes nearly all American
stocks, fell 1.43 percent to pare its gain so far this year to 7.01
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
