A8555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      04-14 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FROM NYC POLICE UNION, A VOTE WITH MYRIAD MEANINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association
cast a vote of no confidence in Police Commissioner Howard Safir,
the true meaning behind that unanimous vote remains as clear as the
inner workings of the PBA itself _ which is to say, not clear at
all.
</P>
<P>
   In another era, a no-confidence vote from the police union would
signal to the commissioner that he should begin removing those
Kiwanis plaques from the office wall. But these days, the
commissioner is able to interpret a union denouncement as a
perverse endorsement, knowing that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani would
never allow himself to be seen as bowing to union pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Then why did James ``Doc'' Savage, the acting PBA president, put
such a motion before the union's 400 delegates Tuesday? And why was
it unanimously approved?
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Savage's decision and the subsequent mandate
reflect the distrust that pervades all quarters of the city Police
Department, from the administrative offices to the rank and file to
the troubled union that is supposed to represent the interests of
its 27,000 members. It also suggests the kind of tactics to be
expected in the no-holds-barred campaign for PBA president, a
campaign in which candidates are trying to gauge exactly how hard
to attack the Giuliani administration.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it indicates that although his job appears safe, Safir
has allowed himself, through a recent spate of questionable
decisions, to become a useful symbol of poor judgment in a
department that tries to promote an image of having no tolerance
for such transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   At least three factors are at play in what, for lack of a better
term, can be called police politics.
</P>
<P>
   First, many officers have never forgiven either the PBA or the
Giuliani administration for agreeing to a five-year contract that
brought no pay increases in the first two years. They call it
``zeroes for heroes.'' As the city gained international renown for
its reduction in crime, the officers found the wage freeze all the
more galling.
</P>
<P>
   Second, there is the death of Amadou Diallo, an unarmed African
immigrant who was repeatedly shot by four white officers in the
Bronx in February; the officers now face murder charges. Many
police officers feel that the dynamics of the shooting were created
by the Giuliani administration's insatiable demand for ever-lower
crime statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, there is Safir himself, a former federal law enforcement
official with a decidedly cold public persona. He is widely seen as
Giuliani's stunt double at the Police Department. He has also not
endeared himself to police officers by boasting that he has fired
more of them than any previous commissioner, at the same time that
he is criticized by civil rights advocates for not being tough
enough on errant officers.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Safir has been subjected to public scrutiny and
ridicule for several decisions, among them sending detectives to
the home of a woman who had been involved in a minor car accident
with his wife, and traveling to the Academy Awards in Los Angeles
on the private jet of a corporate executive. In every case,
Giuliani has expressed support for his longtime friend.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Tuesday, Savage asked 400 union delegates gathered at
the Terrace on the Park in Queens to pass a resolution calling for
Safir's suspension. The acting president knew exactly what
emotional buttons to press. In particular, he accused the
commissioner of reneging on a promise to cut short the 30-day,
no-pay suspension of the four officers indicted in the Diallo case,
a charge that resonates on many levels, despite Safir's denial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delegates have wanted to take a piece out of Safir for a
long time for his policies, especially his disciplinary policies,''
Savage said.
</P>
<P>
   But his opponents say that Savage needed to assert himself in
some way, to take action that would counter his soft-spoken
demeanor and diminish memories of his links to the PBA leadership
that agreed to the controversial contract. The election is in June.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates for union office rarely desire the endorsement of
management, but the police commissioner may have inadvertently
aided Savage by favorably invoking the name of one of his
opponents, James Higgins, another veteran PBA executive board
member. ``I agree with Higgins of the PBA that this is a publicity
move by Doc Savage, who's desperate in this election to get
elected,'' Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins said he would not accept the endorsements of either
Giuliani or Safir (not that either would ever endorse a candidate
in a union election). Still, he said, he would work to re-establish
communication with City Hall, since the union's policy of burning
bridges has worked to the disadvantage of the membership.
</P>
<P>
   There are three other candidates for PBA president, including
Pat Lynch, who describes himself as a reformer. In interviews and
in press releases, he projected a general disgust with virtually
all the principals involved.
</P>
<P>
   Both Savage and Higgins, Lynch said, were part of the entrenched
PBA leadership, and as for Safir, he said, ``He doesn't have the
confidence of the police officers, and he never has.
</P>
<P>
   ``This no-confidence vote should have been called for months
ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
