<SLUG> BC-OUT-HIKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONEY TREK IS PURE POETRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ There is something about bagging a summit, no
matter how small or inconsequential, that prompts prose. Some of
the finest area examples are found in the registry at the top of
Sandstone Peak, at 3,111 feet the tallest point in the Santa Monica
Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made it alive. Everest was easier than this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mountains. Bold, intense, massive. Always climbing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all look for strength, love, divine order and happy
thoughts. We all find it in our own way.''
</P>
<P>
   Now string that hike out from the mountains' high point to its
low point _ the ceiling to the sea _ and you're talking real
poetry. It's the result of tackling the 11{ mostly downhill but
strenuous miles from Circle X Ranch to Sycamore Canyon in Southern
Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   The route that travels over the Backbone, Old Boney, Serrano
Canyon and Big Sycamore Canyon trails is a study in extremes of
elevation and environment tied together by a common ruggedness and
stellar vantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's undeveloped and it's supposed to be kept as such,'' Point
Mugu State Park ranger Tom Evans said of the segment that passes
through Boney Mountain State Wilderness. ``The protection of it has
gotten to the point whereas I can't even patrol it on a routine
basis, so that would make it more lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   At its most remote sections, don't expect to see any other
trekkers; Evans therefore recommends logging a detailed trail plan
with friends or family beforehand and traveling with a hiking
buddy.
</P>
<P>
   And don't depend on an entirely well-groomed pathway, so only
the hardy need consider the journey. The Old Boney Trail is
overgrown and infested with ticks and poison oak, while the portion
of the Backbone Trail that exits the Santa Monica Mountains
National Recreation Area has been in disrepair most of the decade
following fierce fires and floods.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are primitive trails, meaning they haven't been built up
to standard,'' said Mike Zenan, the recreation area's maintenance
work leader for roads and trails.
</P>
<P>
   But inspiring vistas are regular occurrences. ``You can't get
many places with as many views from the Western Santa Monica
Mountains as there, which includes pretty much ocean views,'' Evans
said.
</P>
<P>
   The course commences in Circle X Ranch, the masterpiece of the
Santa Monica Mountains National Recreation Area with Boney Mountain
and the vast, parched chaparral and craggy outcrops that define it.
It concludes by meandering under a lush, cool creekside canopy of
sycamore and oak in Serrano Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at the Backbone Trailhead (elevation 2,100 feet), a
wide fire road climbs steadily, passing a connector to the stunning
Mishe Mokwa Trail (2,350 feet) in three-tenths of a mile before
cresting out at a saddle (2,800 feet) a half-mile later.
</P>
<P>
   Here view renowned Balanced Rock teetering to the north, above
Echo Cliffs and striking Carlisle Canyon. ``I can't understand how
that rock stays there with earthquakes going on,'' said English
outdoorsman Peter Smith, who makes the ascent during an annual
holiday vacation to the Southland.
</P>
<P>
   A milder grade takes hikers in another three-tenths of a mile to
the first significant plateau (2,950 feet), identified by a major
jog to the right and a poorly flagged signpost on the left pointing
the way up a series of stairs to Sandstone Peak, a worthwhile
diversion of a few hundred feet.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the popular destination ``combines the highest point
and good views with... a lot of wildlife and flowers. A couple of
years ago, I was sitting here on a rock that had fallen down, and I
spotted two hummingbirds in the branches. So I sat still and one
came within inches of my face and hovered around it, sort of
viewing me wondering what I was. It was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring is wildflower season, and as the Backbone Trail descends
gently over the next 1.1 miles to a junction (2,660 feet) one can
spot the blue flowers of the hairy ceanothus, pink prickly phlox
and rose-purple owl's clover. Turn left at the sign that directs
visitors to the Backbone Trail and Tri Peaks, and left again in 30
feet at the post pointing toward the Backbone Trail and Sycamore
Canyon. A half-mile farther on, veer left again at the next T in
the trail (2,700 feet), following the sign to Sycamore Canyon as
you enter the state park.
</P>
<P>
   Overcast days can bring low-flying clouds that funnel over the
precipitous ridges to the south like, dare I say, Mount Everest;
must be the mountains' poetry catching up to me.
</P>
<P>
   The next 3.1 miles loses the most altitude of the trip, more
than 1,500 feet, as the track slides down the west shoulder of
Boney Mountain. A curious monolith split in two with a plaque
dedicating it to ranch owner and wealthy Los Angeles industrialist
Henry Chamberlain (1889-1954) _ ``Who loved these mountains'' _ is
passed along the way over several zigzags to Old Boney Trail (1,150
feet).
</P>
<P>
   Turn left, departing the Backbone Trail that is identified by a
skinny plastic sign, for nine-tenths of a mile, passing oaks,
Indian paint brush, California poppy, overgrowth and those pesky
ticks. (Beware: Ticks collected in the mountains in February tested
positive for Lyme disease for the first time; wear long pants and
long-sleeve shirts, and check often.)
</P>
<P>
   At the next junction, veer left on Serrano Canyon Trail (1,010
feet), which in 3{ miles connects with Big Sycamore Trail (115
feet). Serrano Canyon offers gentle grasslands and awesome shots of
Boney Mountain before crossing its namesake creek a dozen or so
times to the croaking of tiny beige frogs with booming voices.
</P>
<P>
   The final 1\ miles of the ugly fire road that is Big Sycamore
Canyon Trail brings visitors back to reality that this verdant
oasis is surrounded by concrete metropolis. But the diversion
brings out the verse and ballad in all of us, if only for a day. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SIDEBAR: &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Climb to the zenith of the Santa Monica Mountains and you face a
choice. No, it's nothing as monumental as whether to return to your
car and the workaday world.
</P>
<P>
   You can call the rock that rises to 3,111 feet Sandstone Peak,
as officially identified on topographic maps, or Mount Allen, as
the lonely bronze plaque stationed atop it proclaims.
</P>
<P>
   It may be confusing, but, take your pick, the panoramic view of
Circle X Ranch and its surroundings are just as stellar.
</P>
<P>
   The plaque notes the mountain was named in honor of W. Herbert
Allen; it was presented in 1965 by the Exchange Club of Los Angeles
to commemorate ``his gift of the mountains to the Boy Scouts of
America.'' Allen's bespectacled image appears with a Boy Scouts
emblem on the lapel.
</P>
<P>
   Further research reveals that Allen was a title insurance
executive who began acquiring land in the mountains in 1949 with
other members of the Exchange Club, a service organization for
downtown businessmen, to create a camping area for various youth
groups. Allen's wealth and vision were instrumental in preserving
the area as the scout's Circle X Ranch, named for the Exchange
Club's icon _ an encircled C and X.
</P>
<P>
   The property was leased to the Boy Scouts in 1951 for 99 years
at an annual rate of $1. In turn it was purchased by a conservation
group in 1987 and sold to the National Park Service two years
later.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU'RE GOING . ..
</P>
<P>
   This is a shuttle trip, requiring two vehicles. Meet at Sycamore
Canyon in Point Mugu State Park and leave one rig in the $6 day-use
parking lot. With everyone in the second ride, drive east of
Pacific Coast Highway (1), turn left on Yerba Buena Road and drive
to the Backbone Trailhead (free parking), passing Circle X Ranger
Station en route.
</P>
<P>
   Allow at least seven to eight hours to complete the 11{-mile
route.
</P>
<P>
   Maps: Triunfo Pass, Newbury Park and Point Mugu 7.5-minute
series topographic maps, and Tom Harrison Cartography's ``Trail Map
of the Santa Monica Mountains West.''
</P>
<P>
   Information and camping opportunities: California State Parks,
Angeles District, (818) 880-0350, Point Mugu State Park, (805)
488-1827 or 488-5223, Santa Monica Mountains National Recreation
Area, (805) 370-2301. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DINKINS-PROFILE-NYT &LR;      04-14 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINKINS-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STILL-DIGNIFIED BUT ANGRIER EX-MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Note language in 4th graf.) 
(DW) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He still dresses as if he is going to dinner with
Brooke Astor, who by the way sent him ``the nicest note'' the other
day. He is still courtly, elegant, fussy, decent and remote. But
Wednesday, when David N. Dinkins, the former mayor, takes his place
as expected in the front lines of a large rally for police reform
alongside his combustible former antagonist, the Rev. Al Sharpton,
New Yorkers will be seeing an angrier man.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, I had little to say, but there comes a time,
either speak up or leave,'' Dinkins said in his office at Columbia
University the other day. ``So I've chosen to speak up.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is Dinkins on Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and the city he runs:
``As during World War II, the trains ran on time; there was no
crime in Nazi Germany. I'm not comparing him to Hitler and
Mussolini, but saying that efficiency in certain areas is not
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   On the attitude of New York City police toward Deputy Mayor Rudy
Washington, who recently said he was harassed for racial reasons by
officers who didn't recognize him: ``If you don't know who he is,
he's just another nigger. But I'm not surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   On the mayor personally: ``I don't like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who knows Dinkins will tell you that he has been angry at
the mayor since he lost to Giuliani in 1993 and that he has been
speaking out against police brutality since at least 1995. ``It's
just asinine to think that the police can police themselves,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But a turning point came on March 15, when Dinkins got himself
arrested for criminal trespassing with 13 others at Police
Headquarters in a protest over the death of Amadou Diallo, the
unarmed African immigrant killed in February in a barrage of 41
bullets fired by four white officers.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle of the former mayor being led away in handcuffs _
the civil disobedience brought sneers from Giuliani _ gave new life
to the daily protests. When it was all over, 1,166 people had been
arrested in the three-week campaign organized by Sharpton, who has
helped build the multiracial coalition that is staging the protest
march from Brooklyn to lower Manhattan Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers have said there could be as many as 25,000 people;
Dinkins simply called it ``a monster,'' predicting ``thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, he is full of praise for Sharpton, the
sometimes hotheaded street preacher who in the old days lobbed
political grenades at Dinkins but has now offered him his best
platform since City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   I will be very pleased to walk next to him,'' Dinkins said of
Sharpton. ``Unquestionably, he has matured.'' Dinkins referred to
Sharpton's civil disobedience campaign as ``genius,'' insisted he
couldn't remember what he and Sharpton had fought over, then
praised him because ``I've never, ever known him to counsel
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton, 44, more than returned the favor about the man he now
describes as an elder statesman: ``There were times when I said
things that were absolutely nasty _ that he acquiesces too much.
And he would never shoot back. It was almost like he was a father
thinking I would grow out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dinkins, Sharpton said, ``always said to me that he felt I could
broaden my base, that he thought I should be more measured and
thoughtful.'' If Dinkins has a fault, Sharpton said, ``it's that
David Dinkins is an eternal optimist, and he really thinks that
people are innately good, and it drives me crazy sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sharpton said, ``if I can grow up to be David Dinkins, I
would be very proud.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, one should not forget this story: When Sharpton was
recuperating in the hospital in 1991 after being stabbed in the
chest during a protest march against racism in Bensonhurst,
Dinkins, then mayor, went to his bedside. ``I'm always teasing
Mayor Dinkins that I looked up and I thought I had died and gone to
hell,'' Sharpton said in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Dinkins, 71, grew up in Trenton, N.J., where his father was a
real-estate broker, but moved to Harlem with his mother after his
parents separated when he was about 6. His mother cooked and
cleaned in houses in New Rochelle, Bronxville and Great Neck, then
became a manicurist at the Carlyle Hotel. ``I run into people all
the time who knew her and speak fondly of her,'' Dinkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Dinkins said the most painful racial experience of his life was
when he was turned down when he tried to enlist in 1945 in the
Marine Corps, which was then segregated. ``And this is a time when
people you know are dying,'' he said. ``This is very real. And you
don't give a thought to not going.'' But he persisted and got to
boot camp just as World War II was ending. The experience, he said,
was ``humiliating.''
</P>
<P>
   Dinkins graduated from Howard University and Brooklyn Law
School, then worked his way up through the Harlem political
establishment with Basil A. Paterson, Percy E. Sutton and Rep.
Charles B. Rangel. He is married with two children, is a professor
at Columbia's School of International and Public Affairs, and says
he has a ``29-year-old forehand'' in tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he's not competitive,'' said one of his tennis
partners, Betsy Gotbaum, the president of the New-York Historical
Society. ``He's so competitive it's unbelievable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
