<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-GRETZKY-ART-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRETZKY STRADDLES BLUE LINE OF RETIREMENT AS ICE GETS MUSHY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RYE, N.Y. _ As he contemplates retirement after 20 seasons in
the NHL and 21 as a professional athlete, Wayne Gretzky of the New
York Rangers hears many opinions, from old and young, both inside
and outside his profession and family. He recently spoke with
Gordie Howe, who called to congratulate Gretzky on goal No. 1,072,
which surpassed Howe's career total.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `How ya doing?''' Gretzky said Wednesday after practice
in Playland Ice Casino. ``He said, `Oh, I just played in a hockey
game the other night.' I said `Gordie, you're 70 years old!' He
said `I love it.' I think I'm going to have the same feeling 30
years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, 38, also spoke with his 6-year-old son, asking him if
he planned to attend Sunday's season finale at Madison Square
Garden against Pittsburgh, possibly the last professional
appearance of Gretzky's magnificent career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `No, I've got a baseball game,''' Gretzky said. ``I
said, `Well, I don't know about next year.' And he said, `Well, I
don't care. I've got a ballgame.' He seems to have everything in
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky smiled occasionally, turned serious often and rubbed his
hands on his bare forearms as he spoke during a news conference.
Then Gretzky and his teammates traveled to Ottawa for Thursday
night's game, which might be his last in his native Canada.
</P>
<P>
   With his production waning from age and his body hurting from a
seasonlong injury to a disk in his neck, Gretzky is debating
whether to accept or turn down a $5 million contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Although gratified that people are urging him to play one more
season, Gretzky hinted broadly that retirement is his strongest
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd probably be lying if I didn't say I was leaning somewhat
one way more than the other,'' Gretzky said after practice. ``No
question about that. What I'm going through is just totally about
myself, what I need to do, what's best for myself. It's my
decision. I'm seriously at a crossroads.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky has spent recent days in talking with his wife, Janet;
his agent, Mike Barnett; his coach, John Muckler, and NHL
commissioner Gary Bettman, among others. He spoke in Ottawa later
Wednesday with Rangers general manager Neil Smith and was to meet
his father, Walter. Gretzky said Muckler was encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about a lot of things, mostly my importance to the
organization as far as my presence, what I bring to the hockey
club,'' Gretzky said. ``He said it will be a lot better team if I'm
back. So that was obviously very flattering and very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky has scored only nine goals this season, his minus-23
rating in the plus/minus ratio is the worst on the team and his
diminished mobility has led to several hard and painful hits from
opposing checkers. But Gretzky remains one of hockey's best passers
on the power play, creating scoring chances for others. Muckler was
asked whether he had suggested to Gretzky a reduced role in
1999-2000 as a power-play specialist, limiting him to what he does
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we didn't get that far,'' Muckler said. ``That's a good
point, though. I wish I would have thought of it when I was talking
to him. He'd be very valuable in that area. Our power play has been
one of the better power plays in the NHL this year and he is the
main reason why.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an adjustment in Gretzky's role would limit his playing
time, reduce his exposure to injury and give the fans and clubs the
chance to give him a seasonlong farewell. ``I know I could play,''
Gretzky said. ``I'm not going to play at the level I did 10 years
ago. As John said today, I can contribute to the hockey team. I
don't want to let him down. On the other side of it, I don't want
to let myself down and I don't want to let the Rangers down.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The retirement rumors began with the broadcaster John Davidson,
who sits with Gretzky on the team's charter flights. Davidson began
suggesting the Great One's imminent retirement on last Friday's
Ranger telecast on the MSG Network, then elaborated on Saturday
night's telecast of ``Hockey Night in Canada'' and on Sunday
afternoon's Fox network telecast in the United States. Gretzky
denied Wednesday that he is unhappy with how Smith has failed to
structure the team around his perceived wants and needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not my business, nor did I ever want it to be,''
Gretzky said, referring to player personnel. ``Madison Square
Garden has treated me tremendous. Neil has always been fair to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gretzky has strongly urged the Rangers to sign free
agents this summer, he has often said that he dislikes the
widespread perception around hockey that he influences roster
decisions. His retirement option, rather than a use of leverage, is
merely a personal dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to be an idiot about this,'' Gretzky said.
``It's a lifetime decision. Once it's done, it's done. It's 100
percent. There's going to be no wavering. Everyone wants to go out
like Michael Jordan did. It's not going to happen that way, this
year. It is nice to be able to say: you know what? People do want
me to play next year. Whether it be my teammates, coaches or from
what you people are saying, I'm listening to everybody. I know,
eventually, I'll make the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what one factor is most important, Gretzky said: ``Time.
That's the only word I can come up with. Twenty-one years is a lot
of time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
