u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-CONGRESS-IOC-NYT &LR;      04-14 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CONGRESS-IOC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL SEES IOC DALLYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While members of a Senate committee harshly
reprimanded two U.S. members of the International Olympic Committee
on Wednesday for a ``culture of corruption,'' and suggested varying
timetables for reform, Sen. Ernest Hollings lent an air of blunt
impatience to the proceedings with a call for immediate action.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are y'all waiting for?'' asked Hollings, D-S.C., asked
during a Commerce Committee hearing on the IOC ``Why not get rid of
Samaranch?''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Antonio Samaranch, the IOC president since 1980, has been
under fire during the Olympic crisis, but has resolutely resisted
calls for him to step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not say, `Get rid of the guy?''' Hollings said, adding:
``Let them all resign. Get a clean group. That's the only way to
get structural change.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at George Mitchell, the former senator who headed a
special inquiry into the Salt Lake City bribery scandal on behalf
of the United States Olympic Committee, Hollings said: ``Give us
some marching orders. Tell us what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mitchell commission offered a road map for IOC and USOC
reform in March in its report examining the ``culture of improper
gift-giving'' that characterized Salt Lake City's successful bid to
host the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC quickly adopted the commission's recommendations, but
the IOC has moved at a slower pace, creating ethics and reform
panels that have yet to meet. A 30-member task force created by
Samaranch has so far named only six members.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated praise for the USOC's swift move to adopt some
reforms, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the Commerce Committee's
chairman, chastised USOC president William Hybl for not turning
over the organization's internal report of its investigation into
the Salt Lake scandal.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also repeatedly expressed annoyance with the two U.S.
States representatives on the IOC, Anita DeFrantz and James Easton,
for the vagueness of their answers during testimony, and for their
failure to fully support the Mitchell panel's recommendations for
reform.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, McCain said he would have preferred to question
Samaranch, who declined to testify. ``I think he has the
information they clearly didn't have,'' he said, referring to
DeFrantz and Easton. DeFrantz, named to testify in place of
Samaranch, said of Samaranch's absence, ``English is his fourth
language.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mitchell commission's recommendations for the IOC include
term limits and periodic re-election for its members; prohibiting
any country that does not sign an international treaty against
bribery from being the host of an Olympics; opening IOC meetings
and financial statements to the public, and requiring all IOC
members' visits to Olympic bid cities to be paid for by the
committee or by the members.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Mitchell commission recommendations are not adopted,
there should be strong and valid reasons for not doing so,'' McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's sincerity will determine the severity of possible
congressional legislation. Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, suggested
measures to limit the IOC's tax-exempt status in the United States,
to reduce the tax deductibility of payments and sponsorship fees to
the IOC by United States television networks and other companies,
and to shift control of all domestic TV payments from the IOC to
the USOC.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Reps. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., and Rick Lazio, R-N.Y.,
introduced a bill that would prohibit U.S. corporations and
individuals from providing financial support to the IOC until it
adopts the Mitchell commission's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Stevens cautioned against rushing into harsh
legislative action, in order to gauge how quickly the IOC acts and
to forestall any cuts in money from anxious global sponsors, which
would hurt athletes. Nonetheless, McCain said he would move
immediately to introduce legislation to place the IOC under the
federal Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, which bars bribery of
foreign officials.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was irked that DeFrantz, a former Olympic rower, could
not say what the IOC's revenues are or how much of the money flows
to athletes.
</P>
<P>
   DeFrantz could only guarantee McCain that the commission's
suggestions would be placed on the IOC's June meeting agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by McCain why the minutes of IOC general sessions have
been kept secret for 10 years and executive board minutes have been
embargoed for 20 years, DeFrantz said the policy protected members
from seeing their candor displayed publicly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
