<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MARBURY TOUCHES OFF A FUROR AT POINT GUARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an odd way, Stephon Marbury, the Nets' impetuous
point guard, has thrown down the gauntlet, issued a challenge to
the Knicks that may provide the impetus to push the team _ and its
backcourt _ into championship form. Following Sunday's blowout loss
to the Knicks, Marbury blasted Chris Childs and Charlie Ward,
declaring that the Knicks would never win a championship with them.
Never. Ever.
</P>
<P>
   Time heals most wounds, but the venom of Marbury's words, their
harshness before the news media, will have long, lasting
reverberations.
</P>
<P>
   Childs refers to himself and Ward as the Knicks' ``two-headed
monster.'' They have shut down two of the league's best point
guards recently. Childs, who has been the rock of the Knicks'
backcourt all season, rendered Marbury ineffective (8 points) on
Sunday for the second consecutive time this season.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, while Marbury and the Nets were losing to the
Los Angeles Clippers, Ward and Childs hounded Philadelphia's Allen
Iverson into an atrocious game (4-of-16 shooting, 11 points, 6
turnovers).
</P>
<P>
   The next challenge facing Childs and Ward was the Washington
Wizards' Rod Strickland, one of the premier players at his
position.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday night's game, Stickland acknowledged that the
Knicks' two-player approach to manning one position worked for
them, but he wasn't sure if it could work for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really evaluate what they're doing because that's
their situation; they're there every day,'' he said. ``It probably
would be tough for me to be in a position where I play half and the
other guy plays half _ coming up in this league. That's why I
didn't want to be in New York at the time when Mark Jackson was
there.''
</P>
<P>
   For Strickland, the issue is not Ward and Childs but Marbury;
not whether Ward and Childs can carry the Knicks to a championship,
or even whether they are championship players. The issue for
Stickland is Marbury's intemperance and apparent disrespect for
fellow players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young guys speak their mind, but we're men first,'' said
Strickland, who will be 33 in July. I respect everybody in this
league. I respect that fact that they got in this league, you have
to be good to be here. But for me it's an issue of how we relate to
each other, man to man.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments were interesting, given Strickland's background and
sometimes turbulent tenure in the league. Strickland was raised in
the Bronx and played at Truman High. Unlike Marbury, he did not
grow up with a passion to play for the Knicks. When they drafted
him in 1988 in the first round he was annoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go there because they had Mark,'' he said,
referring to Jackson, who was the NBA rookie of the year. ``Back
then, playing in New York wasn't that important to me. Now I'd love
to go back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing behind Jackson led to a deteriorating relationship with
Coach Stu Jackson, which set in motion a series of image-related
blunders, Strickland feels, that still haunt him. The attitude
problem. The troublemaker. The malcontent.
</P>
<P>
   While Marbury is being treated with kid gloves now, Strickland
warned that there's a thin line between indulgence and
image-staining ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get the stain it's almost impossible to get it off,''
he said. ``It's like a tattoo. It'll always be there. You've got to
do a lot to get it fixed _ you just can't rub it off.''
</P>
<P>
   After being traded to San Antonio in 1990, Strickland flourished
and built a reputation as an outstanding penetrator and assist
guard. He signed as a free agent with Portland in 1992 and stayed
until 1996 after a flurry of highly publicized run-ins with P.J.
Carlesimo, then the Trail Blazers' coach.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland came to the Wizards in 1996. There was a DWI charge
before the 1997 season and a fight with a teammate, Tracy Murray.
Since those episodes, Strickland has been quiet off the court. He
is known as an independent thinker who speaks his mind and is an
exquisite, prototypical point guard.
</P>
<P>
   His message for Marbury is that there is a price to be paid for
speaking one's mind; there's a point when talent is not enough.
Strickland has never made an All-Star Game, even last year when he
was considered the best point guard in the league. The run-ins with
Carlesimo have apparently worked against him.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury's outspoken comments' about fellow players may come back
to haunt him. ``The thing with Stephon, as long he understands that
there are ramifications and consequences for things he says, then
he can do what he wants to do,'' Strickland said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
