<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SAMARANCH WISE TO DUCK THE SENATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It all goes back to ``good old Jim McKay.'' That's
how Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., explains his personal interest in
the nasty little Olympic corruption scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The way the senator remembers it, McKay was the intelligent and
humane voice of the Olympics, the man behind the great moments.
</P>
<P>
   McCain talks about Cassius Clay's gold medal in 1960, Kerri
Strug's last golden leap on a damaged ankle in 1996, the 1980 gold
medal in ice hockey, Bob Beamon's leap into space in 1968, and even
though McKay wasn't the voice on all of them, his is the voice
McCain hears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly it is a bit of nostalgia,'' McCain said Wednesday.
``But these are our transcendent experiences in sport. They
represent the kids from the farm, the kids from the inner city, the
kid from Minnesota who competed in the luge. They made our bosoms
swell with pride.''
</P>
<P>
   A man who spent time as a prisoner of war in the Hanoi Hilton
can get away with using a phrase like that. The senator is not
naive. He understands the Olympic movement is not amateur sports
any more _ never was all that amateur, probably _ but the new
Olympic events of delegates taking presents, taking tuition, taking
medical care, taking flat-out cash bribes, well, maybe he can do a
little something about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have oversight over sports,'' said McCain, the chairman of
the Senate Committee on Commerce, Science and Transportation, in a
private interview after a hearing into the Olympic mess Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Antonio Samaranch, the president of the International
Olympic Committee, did not see fit to attend the hearing, and the
senator could understand that. McCain is a busy man himself. He has
been one of the more vocal senators on the current conflict in
Kosovo and he is also running for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch travels all over the world at the drop of an
invitation, but he knew better than to meander into the hurly-burly
of elected American public officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't as upset as it might have seemed,'' said McCain, who
mentioned Samaranch's absence, oh, more than a few times.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch left the dubious pleasure of being grilled to a vice
president of the IOC, Anita DeFrantz, who started off by taking the
position that she was speaking for herself, as one of two American
delegates. Instead, she was rather pointedly informed by McCain
that she was representing the entire IOC _ in His Excellency's
absence, you understand.
</P>
<P>
   The senator asked her a lot of questions and seemed a trifle
crabby when she did not spew out figures. He said later, ``I was a
little disappointed in her lack of specifications.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFrantz, a lawyer and foundation president and former Olympic
medalist, explained later that she is just not that great with
numbers. She insisted that the IOC is dealing with the scandal
which has seen 22 of its 107 delegates either resign or be
implicated.
</P>
<P>
   DeFrantz explain that Samaranch was not present because
``English is his fourth language.'' Samaranch often conducts
business in English, but more to the point is that he needs his
cadre of assistants to clarify his responses in whatever language
is being used. He gives the impression of being fixated on
finishing his term, through the year 2000, and not giving in to the
growing chorus that he resign. McCain said he did not think it was
his business to discuss Samaranch's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   William Hybl, the president of United States Olympic Committee,
came to the hearing Wednesday, apologized, and pointed to reforms
already in place, and that pleased McCain. ``Bill Hybl said they
had been wrong,'' McCain said later. ``What else is there to
investigate?''
</P>
<P>
   What can McCain hope to accomplish with these hearings? He
downplayed talk of legislation to end tax-exempt status, and said
in private that the worst-case scenario would be ``they don't get
the sponsors, because the sponsors think it's a dirty business.''
</P>
<P>
   In the hearing, McCain claimed that ``between 60 and 70
percent'' of the IOC's income comes from American sponsors, some of
whom are currently leery about committing funds until the scandal
runs its course.
</P>
<P>
   James Easton, the other American delegate, pointed out in the
hearing that the corporate sponsors are doing it as a business
investment rather than from the goodness of their hearts. The
senator seemed to agree with that. He wasn't rushing with threats.
``The biggest mistakes I've made came when I was in a hurry,'' he
said in his office. ``I say we should let the tea sit in the saucer
for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   A nice phrase. ``Good old Jim McKay'' could not have said it
better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
