<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-ART-7     04-14 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-ART-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVILIAN DEATHS HAVE SERIOUS CONSEQUENCES FOR NATO PLANNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As NATO ratchets up its air campaign over
Yugoslavia, relentlessly bombing Yugoslav armored forces in the
field, the inevitable is happening: Civilians are dying, some at
the hands of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   This unintended but inescapable consequence of modern warfare
has an inevitable effect on the military planners who pick the
targets and worry about holding together a 19-nation alliance. They
understand that public opinion, which has supported the air
campaign thus far, can shift as quickly as pictures of children's
dismembered corpses flash across the world's televisions.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1991 Gulf War, a single mistake _ the bombing of a bunker
that sheltered hundreds of family members of Iraqi intelligence
officers _ prompted Gen. Colin Powell, as the chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, to rein in the air campaign over Baghdad. All
future targets in the city had to win Powell's approval.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Gulf war, American commanders have placed a premium on
minimizing civilian casualties, the price they must pay to keep
multinational coalitions united. ``I trace the problem we're having
back to our inability to embrace the idea of war,'' said Maj. Gen.
Chuck Link, a retired Air Force commander.
</P>
<P>
   American military officers say it is unrealistic to expect the
officers picking targets and the pilots flying at hundreds of miles
an hour to perform flawlessly day after day.
</P>
<P>
   Faulty intelligence reports, for example, indicated that the
bunker in Baghdad was being used solely by military personnel. The
passenger train hit twice by NATO missiles on Monday was crossing a
bridge that was being used by the Yugoslav army, NATO officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The single-mindedness of that strike, pursued even after the
pilot knew he had mistakenly hit the train with his first missile,
reflects a ruthlessness that seems inconsistent with antiseptic
notions of an air war.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, NATO said its planners and fighter-bombers take
extreme caution to avoid what the military calls collateral damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there's 100 percent assurance that what you're hitting
is a military target, you don't drop,'' Maj. Gen. Charles Wald, a
top officer on the military's Joint Staff who has flown bombing
runs over Iraq and Bosnia, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The incident involving a column of refugees in Kosovo on
Wednesday illustrates the political and propaganda stakes. Pictures
taken at the scene undeniably establish that people were killed,
and Yugoslavia immediately blamed NATO. The alliance, in turn,
initially accused the Yugoslavs of fabricating the incident, and
then said it did not know what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Wednesday, Belgrade's state-run television had been
quick to air gruesome pictures of bodies from cratered
neighborhoods in Pristina and of the blasted train caught on the
bridge in Grdelica, pictures that were rebroadcast around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   There have been two fundamental surprises so far in this war.
Few expected Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to defy the West
and defy an extended round of bombing, which has now reached cities
across his country.
</P>
<P>
   And the alliance has shown an unusual unanimity in continuing a
three-week bombardment that has retained widespread public support.
</P>
<P>
   That support stems largely from the strong reaction to the
expulsion of hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo
in scenes that evoked the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Now it appears that Belgrade is moving to drive a wedge among
the allies by offsetting the pictures of terrified refugees
streaming into Albania and Macedonia with images of civilian
casualties it attributes to NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   American officials suspect that this is one reason Yugoslav
commanders park their tanks next to residential buildings and
travel in convoys near refugees.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO moves down its list of targets, fixed buildings standing
alone, far away from populated areas, have given way to equally
important targets set in urban areas, or, in the case of mobile
forces, mingled among or near civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Strikes on these targets carry a much larger risk of hurting or
killing civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Pentagon and NATO officials have even mused that the
complete expulsion of Albanians from Kosovo would give the alliance
a big military advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be Serb troops primarily left, and we would be
able to attack them with more precision and more concentration,''
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said recently.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The comment underscores the frustration military planners and
commanders are feeling, and shows how difficult it is to wage a
controlled air war in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   In the Gulf War, there were civilian casualties in Basra and
Baghdad. But the war against forces in the field was waged mainly
in the desert, far from urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav campaign is trickier, not only because of the foggy
weather and hilly terrain that thwart NATO's armada of radar-guided
bomb droppers, but also because the enemy is mixed in among the
very civilians NATO is trying to protect.
</P>
<P>
   Wald told reporters Wednesday that in Yugoslavia, NATO's rules
of engagement _ which govern when pilots can drop bombs and fire
weapons _ are ``as strict as I have seen in my 27 years'' of
service.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials here and in Europe said the attack on the
train and Wednesday's civilian deaths were unlikely to force NATO
to ease up on its accelerated air war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The train incident is a good illustration of the limitations
of this so-called surgical-strike myth,'' said Brig. Gen. Robert
Osterthaler, a retired Air Force general and former Pentagon
official who dealt with Bosnia. ``As precise as our weapons are,
they have limitations.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet political leaders know that under the right conditions,
the searing images of civilian dead can clash violently with
Americans' expectations of near flawless military campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the images have sufficient political influence on people
who make the decisions, it could change things,'' said Osterthaler.
``I don't think so, but it could.'' l
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
