<HEADER>
A8570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-TAXES-NYT &LR;      04-14 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: COLLECTING TAXES, EFFECTIVELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, April 15:
</P>
<P>
   As Americans file their tax returns this year, they are dealing
with a tax collection agency that has been significantly hobbled in
its ability to enforce the laws. Congressional budget cutters have
constrained the funding for the IRS in recent years while
simultaneously expanding its responsibilities into new areas, with
the result that fewer agents are available to conduct tax audits
and investigations. Unless Congress reverses this trend, compliance
with tax laws may begin to plummet.
</P>
<P>
   A report by a panel headed by former FBI Director William
Webster found that there are fewer criminal investigation agents
and that their effectiveness is compromised because many are
diverted into investigating drug dealers rather than enforcing the
tax laws. The good news in the report was the conclusion that there
are few abuses of taxpayers by those agents, and that improved
disciplinary procedures have dealt with the isolated abuses that
have occurred.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a report from Syracuse University this week showed
that big corporations are half as likely to face audits as they
were a decade ago. Such companies often file very complicated tax
returns, and the possibility that no one will be checking on them
makes it tempting to use corporate tax shelters of questionable
legitimacy. The explosion of such shelters has led the Clinton
administration to seek legislation to combat them.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS needs to continue its efforts to become more
taxpayer-friendly and efficient, and it is to be hoped that the
agency's reorganization into functional groups, dealing with
different areas of tax law, will improve the agency's performance.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to receive a call from the IRS, but taxpayers who
abide by the law have an interest in an effective agency that can
assure that others also pay their fair share. Legislators who have
sought headlines by investigating IRS abuses should now make sure
that the agency has the resources it needs to do an effective job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
