<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-SAFIR-NYT &LR;      04-14 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SAFIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 CIVIC GROUPS SEEK REVIEW OF POLICE COMMISSIONER'S TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three civic groups announced Wednesday that they had
filed a complaint against Police Commissioner Howard Safir with the
city Conflicts of Interest Board because of concerns that Safir
violated ethics rules by accepting a trip to the Academy Awards in
March from a corporate executive.
</P>
<P>
   Safir's trip to the Los Angeles gala with his wife as the guests
of a Revlon executive is already being reviewed, at the
commissioner's request, by the city's corporation counsel.
</P>
<P>
   But the groups _ the Citizens Union, Common Cause and the New
York Public Interest Research Group _ asked for a second, more
formal inquiry by the conflicts board, which is responsible for
disciplining officials who violate the ethics code.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the groups said the review by Corporation
Counsel Michael Hess was insufficient because there was ``an
intrinsic conflict in asking a mayor's top lawyer to judge the
ethics of a mayor's appointees.''
</P>
<P>
   The city ethics code bars officials from accepting free trips or
gifts if there is an appearance that the benefit is being awarded
because of an official's position. Safir has said he was given the
Oscars trip because of his friendship with his host, Revlon
president George Fellows, not because of his police post.
</P>
<P>
   Hess, whose review is expected to take several weeks, rejected
any notion that his inquiry was not impartial. ``I am an
independent agent,'' he said, ``and I would not be doing this job
if I didn't have that independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir's reaction was muted. ``The Conflicts of Interest Board
will make their determination and whatever determination they make,
I will certainly abide by it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Oscars trip, in which the commissioner traveled in a
corporate jet and enjoyed the amenities of a $700-a-night suite in
a Beverly Hills hotel, raised the first in a series of questions
that have surfaced about his ethics in recent weeks. He has also
faced scrutiny for using detectives to investigate an auto accident
involving his wife, Carol, and to guard his daughter's wedding.
Safir has said those decisions were founded on bona fide security
concerns because of threats made against him. Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani has repeatedly backed the commissioner's conduct.
</P>
<P>
   But the possible ethical lapses were cited by the Patrolmen's
Benevolent Association on Tuesday when it issued a ``no
confidence'' vote on the commissioner and Wednesday, another group,
100 Blacks in Law Enforcement Who Care, issued a second ``no
confidence'' vote as they faulted Safir's response to a number of
incidents, including the February police shooting of Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   As he met reporters Wednesday at Police Headquarters and faced a
new barrage of questions about the mounting criticism and
suggestions that he resign, Safir spoke as if he felt the circling
news media had already decided he is chum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the papers today,'' he said. ``My picture is on the
front of three papers. If you look at what the allegations are,
there's a lot of misinformation. There's a lot of things that are
not true. There's a lot of prejudgment before any facts are known
and a lot of misstatements.''
</P>
<P>
   Again Wednesday, Safir found himself facing questions about his
judgment as he defended a five-day trip he took to Florida last
November with his wife. The trip was partly paid for by the Palm
Beach County Law Enforcement Foundation, whose expenses are largely
underwritten by New York City business executives.
</P>
<P>
   Safir's itinerary for the November trip, in which he made a
breakfast speech before the foundation, indicated that all his
meals, first-class air fare and four nights in the Breakers, a
resort hotel, were being paid for by the foundation at a cost of
$1,672.
</P>
<P>
   But the commissioner's spokeswoman, Marilyn Mode, said that the
itinerary was mistaken and that the foundation had only paid for
two nights in the hotel. Ms. Mode said the commissioner had paid
for the third night of his stay and had stayed with a friend, whom
she would not identify, on his final night in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The length of the reimbursed stay is important because, while
city regulations allow officials to make trips of this type, they
state that the length of the stay should be in keeping with the
business purpose involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe there was any conflict of interest at all,''
Safir told reporters. ``This was a law enforcement trip for law
enforcement purposes to spread the word about programs we are
involved with in New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the executives on the Palm Beach foundation's board is
directly involved in doing business with the Police Department,
although several are prominent New Yorkers who also have homes in
the Palm Beach area. Among the directors are James Robinson III,
the former head of American Express; Michael Tarnopol, a vice
chairman at Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co.; Larry Fisher, a real estate
developer, and Jeffrey Silverman, president of Ply Gem Industries,
who hosted a dinner party in Safir's honor at his Palm Beach home
after the commissioner's speech to the group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
