<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   APPLE POSTS STRONG RESULTS WHILE RIVALS ARE STRUGGLING
</P>
<P>
   Reporting its second-quarter earnings, a resurgent Apple
Computer again beat analysts' earnings estimates based on strong
demand for its iMac and G3 machines.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's renewed fortunes are all the more striking at a time
when the rest of the personal computer industry is mired in price
wars and slowing growth. Compaq Computer, the world's largest
personal computer maker, has warned that earnings for the current
quarter would fall far short of estimates, and Intel reported
slower than expected first-quarter sales.
</P>
<P>
   Alta Vista, one of the leading services that search for
information on the World Wide Web, is inviting advertisers to pay
for the right to be listed atop its search results.
</P>
<P>
   HEDGE FUNDS LAG BEHIND MARKETS
</P>
<P>
   Several hedge funds, the private partnerships that control more
than $200 billion for pension funds, endowments and very wealthy
individuals, have gotten off to a poor start this year. For
example, Jeff Vinik, the former manager of Fidelity's Magellan fund
who now oversees about $2.5 billion at Vinik Asset Management,
gained just 1 percent in the first quarter after strong returns of
45 percent last year and 77 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT RISES 64 PERCENT AT JP MORGAN
</P>
<P>
   JP Morgan, regularly cited as vulnerable to a takeover after
successive quarters of weak profits, posted a stellar 64 percent
increase in first-quarter earnings, kicking off a year in which
management says the bank will finally prove its mettle.
</P>
<P>
   DOW RISES AS INVESTORS SHIFT FOCUS
</P>
<P>
   Stock traders took profits in some recently high-flying sectors
and moved into some neglected basic industries. The Dow Jones
industrial average edged up 16.65 points, to 10,411.66, its third
straight record, but the Nasdaq plunged 76.22 points, or nearly 3
percent, to 2,507.28, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index
fell 21.38 points, to 1,328.44.
</P>
<P>
   Prices of Treasury securities drifted lower as weakness in the
dollar, stock gains and a big supply of higher-yielding corporate
debt securities weighed on the market.
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUNDS OF MICROSOFT
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft generated excitement when it announced its entry into
the businesses of downloading and streaming music from the Internet
with its Windows Media Technologies 4.0 at the House of Blues in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   HARTFORD DAILY BUYS WEEKLY PAPERS
</P>
<P>
   The Hartford Courant has purchased five weekly publications in
Westchester County, N.Y., Fairfield County, Conn., New Haven,
Conn., and western Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   TIME WARNER REPORTS SOLID PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner said that it posted a solid profit in the first
quarter based on strong growth at its cable television networks and
the Warner Brothers film studio. Each of the company's business
segments performed well, and some benefited from turnarounds.
Still, shares of Time Warner fell $3.50, to $73.50.
</P>
<P>
   A STRUGGLE FOR A TRADE LEADER
</P>
<P>
   The World Trade Organization's 134 countries are struggling to
agree on who will succeed Renato Ruggiero of Italy as director
general. No consensus has emerged for either Suphachai Panichpakdi
of Thailand or Michael Moore of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST CALL TO EXPAND WEB ESTIMATES
</P>
<P>
   First Call, which tracks Wall Street earnings estimates, said
that it had decided to expand the calculations used for 20 Internet
companies, giving investors an earnings measure that excludes
merger-related charges.
</P>
<P>
   MCI IN NO HURRY FOR NEXTEL DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Nextel directors met to consider whether to sell the company to
MCI Worldcom _ even as an MCI Worldcom executive said his company
was in no hurry for a wireless business.
</P>
</TEXT>
