<HEADLINE>
ROBERT COX, WHO WON PULITZER PRIZE FOR REPORTING IN 1967, DIES AT
72  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.H.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert V. Cox, a small-town Pennsylvania newspaper reporter who
won a Pulitzer Prize in 1967 for writing about the manhunt for a
sniper, died on Monday at at a health care center in Chambersburg,
Pa. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from heart bypass surgery, said Jim
Hook, a reporter at The Public Opinion, the 22,000-circulation
Chambersburg newspaper where Cox worked from after graduating from
the local high school until 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, who lived in Fayetteville, Pa., won the Pulitzer for
general spot news reporting. He later wrote two books, ``Deadly
Pursuit'' (Stockpole Books, 1977) and ``Missing Person'' (Stockpole
Books, 1979).
</P>
<P>
   After winning the Pulitzer, Cox made an unsuccessful run for the
state House of Representatives. In 1969, he joined another small
newspaper, The Record Herald of Waynesboro, Pa., from which he
retired in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Martha Rife; five daughters, Michele
Reed, Linda Jones and Kathleen Statler, all of Chambersburg,
Christine Miller of Philadelphia, and Julia R. Plank, of Orrtanna,
Pa.; a son, Robert M., of Waynesboro, Pa.; four sisters, Helen
Weaver and Delores Hawk, both of Chambersburg, Miriam Sollenberger
of Nashua, N.H., and Sandra Burkhart of Robesonia, Pa.; 13
grandchildren, and 2 great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWPORT-NEWS-NYT &LR;      04-14 0914
