<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWPORT-NEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. BLOCKS HOSTILE BID FOR SHIPBUILDER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La. )   By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saying that the potential savings did not justify the deal, the
Defense Department Wednesday rejected an unsolicited $1.4 billion
offer by the General Dynamics Corp. for Newport News Shipbuilding
Inc. Within minutes of the Pentagon's announcement, General
Dynamics withdrew its offer.
</P>
<P>
   These twin announcements, not unexpected, end General Dynamic's
effort to create a shipbuilding giant that would have controlled
all of the nation's nuclear warship construction and four of the
nation's six military shipyards. Had General Dynamics' hostile bid
succeeded, it would have also brought an end to a friendly $519
million takeover by Newport News of Avondale Industries of New
Orleans, a smaller Navy ship supplier. The Pentagon has already
approved that deal.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Defense Department said that ``the savings
projected by General Dynamics did not now outweigh potential
competitive disadvantages from the proposed merger.'' The Pentagon
specifically said that with only one supplier of nuclear
submarines, ``there would be a reduction in the likelihood of
future competition.'' Similarly, the proposed merger would have put
more than 75 percent of all military shipyard engineering talent
and more than 95 percent of Navy research and development
investments in one company, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that a General Dynamics-Newport News
combination would have brought some savings, the secretary of
defense, William S. Cohen, said the savings were ``not now so great
as to override the management and competitive challenge we could
face from the merger.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the withdrawal of his company's bid, Nicholas D.
Chabraja, General Dynamic's chief executive, called the Pentagon's
decision ``disappointing.'' Still, Chabraja said, ``We respect it
and have withdrawn our offer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``General Dynamics believes that its proposed acquisition of
Newport News Shipbuilding would have meant significant savings for
the U.S. Navy, enhanced value for the shareholders of both
companies, and still preserved jobs,'' he added. ``We will pursue
other acquisition opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Newport News, William P. Fricks, said
that with the collapse of the General Dynamics-Newport News deal,
his company would proceed with the Avondale takeover, a deal that
``we continue to believe makes sound strategic and financial
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   General Dynamics shares rose $2.50 each, to $69.5625, while
Newport News fell 25 cents, to $27.75; Avondale Industries rose
68.75 cents, to $31.9375.
</P>
<P>
   When General Dynamics announced its hostile bid last February,
it was seen as a bold stroke by both Wall Street and the military
industry. But it was given little chance of success because it flew
in the face of evolving Pentagon policy against larger mergers and
because it complicated the existing friendly deal between Newport
News and Avondale. It was seen as a last-ditch effort by General
Dynamics to thwart a friendly merger that threatened to challenge
its Naval shipbuilding dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Dynamics gave it a good college try,'' said Howard
Rubel, military industry analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.. ``It was
an innovative deal. General Dynamics is well positioned to continue
its expansion strategy. There will be other opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, some analysts began speculating that General Dynamics
might consider buying an electronics company. It recently lost in a
bid to acquire United Defense Limited Partnership, which makes
tanks. Among General Dynamic's existing product lines are nuclear
submarines, destroyers and auxiliary ships for the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Peter J. Arment, an analyst with JSA Research in Newport, R.I.,
added that General Dynamics knew from the outset that it ``had a
50-50 shot at best.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hostile attempt,'' he added, ``and even if they won,
they would be in command and control of six major shipyards and
they obviously knew that the Pentagon might not allow that going
into it.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed deal ran into considerable political opposition,
with the Virginia congressional delegation opposing the Newport
News takeover. Sen. John W. Warner, a Republican and chairman of
the Senate Armed Services Committee, which helps determine Pentagon
spending, was opposed to the deal at a time when the Pentagon needs
the Senate committee's support for more military spending because
of the warfare in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Warner said that ``the greatest concern to me was,
and is, the concentration, in a single corporation, of well over
one-half of the Navy's shipbuilding account. This would not be in
the long-term national security interests of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Loren Thompson, an analyst at the Lexington Institute, a
research group in Arlington, Va., said: ``What this outcome says is
that General Dynamics will be looking outside of its existing areas
for future defense business acquisitions. It appears that
shipbuilding acquisitions are now foreclosed to it, which would
drive it into other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Ginsberg, an analyst with Fourteen Research in New York,
said: ``You want to make sure, with the Yugoslavia conflict, that
the head of the Senate Armed Services Committee is on your side.
And, if the merger went through, there would be one key shipyard,
and the government would not tolerate that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
