<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 04/14/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) RYE, N.Y. -- April 14, 1999 -- HKN-RANGERS-GRETZKY, 4-14
-- Wayne Gretzky at a news conference Wednesday after Rangers
practice. He says he has still not decided if he will retire after
this season. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio -- April 14, 1999 -- PRIVATE-PRISON-2,
4-14 -- ``When I first walked into the prison there were over 250
inmates who had separation orders who were in the same facility,''
says Jimmy L. Turner, the warden who was brought in to run things
last March at the Northeast Ohio Correctional Center after 20
inmates were stabbed and six others escaped. ``Most prisons don't
operate with known enemies in the same facility.'' (Phil Long/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio -- April 14, 1999 -- PRIVATE-PRISON-1,
4-14 -- A therapeutic community meeting at the Northeast Ohio
Correctional Center in Youngstown. The private prison has come
under scrutiny after 20 inmates were stabbed, and six others,
including four murderers, escaped. (Phil Long/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) FORT CARSON, Colo. -- April 14, 1999 --
KOSOVO-TRAINING-VILLAGE, 4-14 -- The owner of a contracting company
in Colorado Springs, Christine Headrick, helping build a
Bosnia-style training village at Ft. Carson. Starting this week,
the Army is converting 150 square miles of Rocky Mountain foothills
into a Balkan stage set, complete with four villages and a copy of
the American military base in Tuzla, Bosnia. (Kevin Moloney/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- April 14, 1999 -- COUNSEL-LAW, 4-14 --
Rebuked by Democrats at a Senate hearing Wednesday, Kenneth W.
Starr defends his prosecutorial tactics in the investigation of
President Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky. ``How
frequently does the judge supervising the grand jury say, 'The
prosecutor is out of control?' `` he declares indignantly. ``To us,
none. Not once have we been found to have conducted ourselves
inappropriately.'' (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) BRADLEY, Fla. -- April 14, 1999 -- FLA-WILDFIRES, 4-14
-- Firefighters monitor flames in a fire near Bradley on Monday. It
has been fine weather for the tourists here in Florida, with day
after day of blue skies, but firefighters across the state have
learned to despise these perfect days. (Pierre DuCharme/Lakeland
ledger Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- April 14, 1999 -- IRS-PUBLIC, 4-14 -- Tax
Commissioner Charles O. Rossotti of the Internal Revenue Service
outside his Washington office. Rossotti disciplined 12 officials
last year for using dollar quotas in collections. He says such
quotas have not only been banned, but also that he has issued
regulations that will result in new ways of measuring employee
performance, such as how well officials serve customers, as the IRS
now calls taxpayers. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) BLACE, Macedonia -- April 14, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-2,
4-14 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Urosevac, Kosovo, on board a
bus after crossing into Albania on foot Wednesday. Yugoslav forces
in southeastern Kosovo are accelerating and broadening a campaign
of expelling Albanians from across southeastern Kosovo, according
to accounts from refugees pouring across the border. (Alan Chin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) BLACE, Macedonia -- April 14, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1,
4-14 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Urosevac, Kosovo, on board a
bus after crossing into Albania on foot Wednesday. A new wave of
attacks, growing food shortages and a new Serb policy of allowing
Albanians to freely cross the border here has prompted a resurgent
flood of refugees. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) KRUME, Albania -- April 14, 1999 -- KOSOVO-CHILDREN,
4-14 -- Young ethnic Albanians at a refugee camp in Krume on
Wednesday. A U.N. envoy says that Kosovo refugees in northern
Albania are living in dreadful conditions and that the situation is
especially difficult for children, who make up two-thirds of the
refugees. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) HOLLYWOOD -- April 14, 1999 -- JOANOU-FILMS, 4-14 --
Phil Joanou in the editing room at his Hollywood Hills home.
``Entropy'' is the opening movie at the Los Angeles Independent
Film Festival, which begins Thursday night, and it is Joanou's
introduction to what many critics regard as the hottest realm in
the world of movies, independent films. (Steve Goldstein/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NORTHAMPTON, Mass. -- April 14, 1999 --
NORTHAMPTON-KIDDER-FORD, 4-14 -- Northampton Mayor Mary Ford likes
to say she was elected mayor of every resident, including those who
won't vote for her no matter what she does. They're natives and new
arrivals, friends and foes, civic-minded or uncommitted, but
they're not strangers. The subjects of Tracy Kidder's new book,
``Home Town,'' make Northampton work by living together in it.
(Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NORTHAMPTON, Mass. -- April 14, 1999 --
NORTHAMPTON-KIDDER-RYAN, 4-14 -- Judge Michael Ryan of Northampton
stops being a judge when he leaves court. If a stranger on a nearby
bar stool asks him what he did for a living, Ryan will say: ``Oh, I
have a government job, cleaning up small messes at the
courthouse.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NORTHAMPTON, Mass. -- April 14, 1999 --
NORTHAMPTON-KIDDER-SCHEINMAN, 4-14 -- Alan Scheinman suffers ``from
an illness which makes my behavior seem bizarre. I can't stand in
line, and I can't touch papers that anyone else has handled.''
Northampton residents do their best to make sure his eccentric
needs are met. The subjects of Tracy Kidder's new book, ``Home
Town,'' make Northampton work by living together in it. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NORTHAMPTON, Mass. -- April 14, 1999 --
NORTHAMPTON-KIDDER-TROTMAN, 4-14 -- Every year for the past eight,
Michael Trotman had tried to leave. He'd taken scouting trips to
New York City, Phoenix, Los Angeles. But he would always miss
Northampton. He can't fully account for the pull the town has on
him, but he has a short answer for friends who ask: ``No one's
called me a nigger in eight years.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- April 14, 1999 --
ETHIOPIAN-CHURCH-BOS, 4-14 -- Mesert Geresu adjusts her shawl
during singing rehearsal at St. Michael's Ethiopian Orthodox Church
in Cambridge. Reluctant refugees who never thought they would leave
their homeland, many Ethiopians say their American community is at
a crossroads. (Jonathan Wiggs/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NORTHAMPTON, Mass. -- April 14, 1999 --
NORTHAMPTON-KIDDER-2, 4-14 -- At the turn of the century, Main
Street in Northampton had trolleys. Now, the crosswalks beep
electronically for the blind. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NORTHAMPTON, Mass. -- April 14, 1999 --
NORTHAMPTON-KIDDER-1, 4-14 -- Tracy Kidder has chronicled a
late-20th-century version of hometown America, Northampton, Mass.,
in his book ``Home Town.'' ``There are some magical things about
this that couldn't have been planned,' says Kidder, 53, who lives
in nearby Williamsburg with his wife, Frances, a painter, but
