<SLUG> BC-CUSACK-FORGERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGED PAPERS OF KENNEDY AND NIXON CITED IN TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A man accused of forging papers in the handwriting of
John F. Kennedy and selling them for millions of dollars to
unsuspecting investors also suggested to a business partner that he
wanted to sell a trove of secret papers of Richard M. Nixon, the
government charged Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The assertion by a federal prosecutor came in the opening
statements of the trial of Lawrence X. Cusack 3rd in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan. Cusack, a former paralegal, has been charged
with 13 counts of wire and mail fraud. He is accused of selling the
forged Kennedy papers to more than 100 investors for $7 million,
keeping about $5 million for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The papers were entirely phony,'' the prosecutor, Paul A.
Engelmayer, told the jury. ``They had been phonied up, forged,
manufactured by Lawrence Cusack himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Engelmayer offered no elaboration on Cusack's contention that he
had Nixon papers and even some tapes, except to suggest they were
fraudulent. But he said that the prospect of helping Cusack sell
them someday had two of Cusack's partners, who did not know the
documents were fraudulent, ``salivating.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial has been widely anticipated because of the publicity
surrounding the documents when they first surfaced two years ago
and were to be the subject of a television documentary and a book.
Some of the papers appeared to confirm a long-rumored affair by
Kennedy with Marilyn Monroe, and the payment of hush money for her
silence about their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Cusack appeared relaxed in court as he sat by his
lawyer at the defense table, even smiling as Engelmayer pointed at
him for the jury, naming him as the defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack has maintained that he found the papers in the files of
his late father, a prominent lawyer in New York, that they were
genuine and that he sold them in good faith.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Robert F. Katzberg, signaled to the jury that his
defense strategy would not be to try to prove that the papers were
genuine _ indeed, he conceded there may be problems with their
authenticity _ but to show that Cusack and his two partners had
every reason to believe that the documents they were selling were
real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I expect that the government is going to be able to show in
various ways that there are problems with these documents?''
Katzberg told the jury. ``You bet I do. Can they raise questions
about these documents? Yes. But as you will learn during the course
of this trial, even if every single one of those documents is
bogus, that does not automatically mean that a crime was committed
by the people who sold them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2250EDT &QL; 
