<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SCHOOL-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW N.J. EDUCATION CHIEF PROPOSES HIGHER BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ The new state education commissioner Wednesday
proposed a budget of $5.4 billion for the 1999-2000 school year,
$380 million more than the current year, in the state that already
has the highest per pupil spending rate in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner, David Hespe, who started his duties last week,
told the Assembly Appropriations Committee that the proposed
education budget would be almost a third of the state's total
budget. ``It's a staggering sum,'' he said, ``but it is an
investment in our children and in our future.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey spends 11 percent more than Connecticut, the state
with the second-highest rate, Hespe said, and 20 percent more than
New York, Pennsylvania and Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   But as he was addressing the committee inside the Statehouse,
officials from the state's 28 poorest districts, which were the
subject of a lawsuit challenging the state's school finance laws,
held a rally outside the building to protest that the state is not
spending enough on them despite a court order last year.
</P>
<P>
   At the rally, Assemblyman Craig Stanley of Irvington said the 28
districts have been ``victims of an administration that has shown
either the lack of compassion or the lack of capacity to implement
the Abbott decision,'' a reference to the decision last year in the
case, Abbott vs. Burke.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the State Supreme Court ordered the state to
spend millions of dollars on the 28 districts, which range from
cities like Newark to rural communities like Phillipsburg, to
equalize spending with wealthier districts. This is the first year
the state has drawn up an education budget that includes the
additional funds for the Abbott districts, as they are called, and
many officials said the districts have been slighted by the
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is asking for a blank check,'' Stanley, a rally
organizer, said. ``Don't get me wrong. What we are asking for is
education funding fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the 28 districts complained that in many cases,
the Department of Education has turned down their requests for
additional funds for programs they believed were mandated by the
court ruling, like preschool for 3- and 4-year-olds and
whole-school programs designed to revamp the whole school, from
curriculum to parent involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of those proposals to this day have been subjected to an
arbitrary rejection by the Department of Education solely on the
basis, we would contend, that they asked for more funding,'' said
David Sciarra, executive director of the Education Law Center,
which undertook the lawsuit on behalf of the 28 districts.
</P>
<P>
   Sciarra said that in its ruling, the court held that it was up
to the schools and the districts to create programs to improve
education and then present specific proposals to the Education
Department for those programs. Further, he said, the court ruled
that if the districts demonstrated a need for additional funds for
those programs, the education commissioner was to provide it.
Sciarra said the commissioner had violated the court order by
rejecting districts' plans.
</P>
<P>
   But at the committee hearing, Hespe said that it was the
department's job to review those requests, and that it had rejected
proposals that did not include enough justification for extra
funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we are in compliance,'' he said. ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   The state has already approved plans for preschool programs in
21 of the 28 districts, he said, and whole-school programs have
already been started in 72 schools this year, and 100 more are
expected to be added in the next school year.
</P>
<P>
   The Abbott districts have requested funds in the tens of
millions of dollars above what they were already provided, he said,
and the department expects to make a decision on those requests
within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hespe's first appearance before the committee, and
committee members peppered him with questions.
</P>
<P>
   They asked him how schools were doing in adopting the state's
core curriculum requirements, the blueprint of minimum educational
standards for students at all levels. They wanted to know about the
process for deciding what will be built with the
multibillion-dollar school construction program proposed by Gov.
Christie Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Hespe said he was considering ways to reduce the number of
categories of state aid, and he pledged to communicate with
legislators and local school officials before making any policy
decisions. Critics of Klagholz, his predecessor, had said he failed
to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
