<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAKE BACK, O'DONNELL OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Kings' sin bin had a revolving door
Wednesday, with defenseman Rob Blake escaping exile and defenseman
Sean O'Donnell preparing to serve his sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Blake was preparing to return to the lineup tonight at home
against the Mighty Ducks after serving two games for cross checking
San Jose's Alexander Korolyuk. But the NHL announced that O'Donnell
will miss the next two games for cross checking Nashville's Cliff
Ronning in the head and spearing Sergei Krivokrasov in the lower
body late in Monday night's victory over the Predators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand where (NHL discipline czar Colin Campbell) is
coming from,'' said O'Donnell, who will lose $10,416.66 of his
$1,000,000 salary. ``They're trying to crack down on anything above
the shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell will be eligible to return to the lineup Sunday
afternoon when the Kings (30-44-5) conclude their disappointing
season against the St. Louis Blues in what almost certainly will be
the final regular-season game at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I get to play one more game,'' O'Donnell said.
``We're going to have a long enough vacation as it is. I didn't
need an extra week off.''
</P>
<P>
   LEACH SELECTED (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   Kings assistant coach Jay Leach will be an assistant for the
U.S. team at next month's World Championships in Oslo, Norway.
Leach was an assistant two years ago when the U.S. team reached the
medal round, and he also was an assistant for the U.S. when it won
a silver medal at the 1991 Canada Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about it,'' Leach said. ``I'd much rather have our
team in the playoffs. But this is a chance to go over and represent
your country. It's a coaching challenge. You have to get 23 guys
and bring them together quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's Terry Murray will be the head coach of the U.S. team
and Nashville's David Poile is the general manager. Asked if his
uncertain job status with the Kings might pose a distraction while
he's overseas, Leach said, ``I can't control that. I've been in
this business 15 years. I've never been without a coaching job.
I'll be somewhere next year. I'd like to remain with (the Kings),
but whatever happens, I can't control it.''
</P>
<P>
   RETURN OF WAYNE? (SUBHED)
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was a possibility the New York Rangers' Wayne
Gretzky would take a job in the Kings' organization if he retires
after this season, General Manager Dave Taylor said, ``It's a
little premature to even talk about it. If Wayne announces his
retirement, we'd certainly be open to discussing something with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky reportedly is considering retiring after the Rangers
complete their season Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   LOOSE PUCKS (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are expected to send goalie Manny Legace to the Long
Beach Ice Dogs today and recall Ryan Bach. Coach Larry Robinson
said he didn't know if he would play Bach in one of the final
games. Jamie Storr will miss the remaining games with an ankle
injury. ... Blake was ill while serving his suspension, an
infection covering his body with a rash. He said he expects to play
tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
