<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0475 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8600 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NGUYEN-HNS &LR;      04-14 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NGUYEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
No stopwatch can record what Nguyen brings to a team
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
On the surface, it seems nothing about Dat Nguyen is ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   He rode in his mother's womb on the boat ride that began a
journey from war-torn Vietnam to the United States, and 23{ years
later he is a college football All-American.
</P>
<P>
   And those are merely the bookends to his life thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Include his transformation from a somewhat rowdy preteen to a
model citizen and his rise from an unknown to an icon at Texas A&AMP;M,
and you recognize his is far from a typical tale.
</P>
<P>
   But as he prepares to add the next chapter to his story, Nguyen
finds himself placed in an unusual category _ ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   How ordinary?
</P>
<P>
   A dime a dozen, some say.
</P>
<P>
   Despite strikes, free agency and inflation, that remains the
going rate in the NFL for linebacker wannabes who stand less than
6-foot tall, weigh less than 240 pounds and cannot finish a 40-yard
sprint in under 4.6 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But if you listen to those who know him, if you latch on to Dat
Nguyen, you have yourself a bona fide football player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to explain, but you don't have to know much about
football to know Dat is a very good football player,'' Texas A&AMP;M
coach R.C. Slocum said. ``He has instincts that you can't teach. He
may not be as big or as fast on paper as you would like in a search
for the perfect linebacker, but he has never been too small or too
slow to get the job done. In fact, he gets the job done better than
most bigger and faster people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one guy you don't have to worry about when you put
together your game plan. You know he will take care of his
responsibilities; size and speed don't matter to him.''
</P>
<P>
   But it matters to others, including the non-licensed scientists
who help teams formulate NFL draft plans. When the NFL draft gets
under way Saturday, the bigger and faster linebackers are sure to
go ahead of Nguyen.
</P>
<P>
   It is a numbers game, and many of Nguyen's numbers are not
impressive numbers like 5-11, 234 pounds and a best of 4.58 seconds
in the 40.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers mean little to Nguyen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game of football is more of what happens while you're out
there playing,'' he said. ``I've seen throughout my career, guys
who run 4.4 (seconds in the 40-yard dash) but on the field runs
5-flat, and guys that run 5-flat go on the field and play 4.4. A
lot of people have football speed. You can have natural speed, but
no football speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a lot to do with instincts and just desire and effort.
I think that's the category I fit in. I am fortunate to have the
instincts that I have. Also, it's because the coaching staff gave
me great tendencies (to look for) during the week. My preparation
during the week gave me a good understanding of what the opponents
wanted to do, so when I went out there it was all reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   It goes that for every action there is an equal and opposite
reaction. Not with Nguyen. His reaction may have been opposite to
an offense's action, but it was not equal. He usually got the
better of the deal because he got there first.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M's all-time leading tackler believes there is one way
for a player of his speed to get to a spot before those who are
faster _ preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's best to be over-prepared than under-prepared,'' Nguyen
said. ``If you are willing to put the extra time in to prepare
yourself and see what the opponent likes to do in different
situations, you'll end up being successful because you're a step
ahead of them.''
</P>
<P>
   When NFL scouts evaluate this year's linebacker pool, Nguyen is
not a step ahead of the class. He may even be a step behind. He is
rated by many, including former Dallas Cowboys player personnel
director Gil Brandt, to be about the 12th-best linebacker
available. Brandt rates A&AMP;M's Warrick Holdman as the sixth-best
linebacker eligible for the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Nguyen, tape measures, stopwatches and the
numbers they show are not the only criteria that go into measuring
football ability.
</P>
<P>
   It is the other components that make Nguyen something other than
ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M defensive coordinator Mike Hankwitz, who has coached
successful NFL linebackers like Keena Turner, Chad Brown and Ted
Johnson, said what Nguyen brings to the table probably means more
than the numbers he posts in workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a great competitor with great heart and the biggest
thing is he made plays,'' Hankwitz said. ``He was always so
productive. He was always around the football and to me that's the
key to being a football player _ making plays. Not only did he make
plays, he made big plays. What made him so unique is he did it so
consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen was the first Aggie to lead the team in tackles four
consecutive seasons, broke the Texas A&AMP;M career tackles mark by
more than 50 stops and averaged 10.7 tackles a game, bumping that
up by two extra stops a contest against Top 25 opponents.
</P>
<P>
   He claimed the Lombardi Trophy, Chuck Bednarik Award and a long
list of Defensive Player of the Year honors this past season.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he can duplicate what he did in college on the next
level is now the question.
</P>
<P>
   If Nguyen were an NFL general manager, he would have no
reservations about taking the guy Slocum once described as ``the
little linebacker with the heart of a giant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would give myself a shot,'' Nguyen said. ``I would take me
because you know you're getting a guy who's going to come out and
give you 110 percent every play. You know he's not going to give
you any trouble off the field. He's going to be one of those
players that helps you, helps the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have an opportunity to understand the system, I can play
it. I know it's going to be different, I know it's another level
and I know all the players there are great players. If not, they
wouldn't be there. So, it's going to be a challenge for me to go up
there and see where I stand. But I love the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you want is an opportunity to measure yourself. If you go
out there and don't do well you won't play, you don't deserve to
play. But you need the opportunity first.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a request that does not seem out of the ordinary.
Especially from a guy who has proven to be rather extraordinary to
this point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
