<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-WINNER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVE-IN BABY SITTER, 54, WINS $197 MILLION LOTTERY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to attach five grafs at end about the Boston cabdriver who
was rumored to be the lottery winner. No other changes.) (mk) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was last Wednesday that Chris Gabrieli, a venture
capitalist, discovered that his live-in baby sitter was a
multimillionaire like him.
</P>
<P>
   The baby sitter, a 54-year-old Chilean immigrant named Maria
Grasso, told Gabrieli's wife, Hilary, who then told him, that she
had won the $197 million Big Game jackpot, the largest lottery
prize ever won by one person in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Gabrielis were among the few people who knew her secret
until Wednesday when, after a week of rumor and speculation about
who had bought the winning ticket at the Star supermarket in the
Fenway neighborhood last week, Mrs. Grasso, a modest, soft-spoken
mother of two, claimed her winnings at Massachusetts Lottery
headquarters in Braintree, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very down-to-earth person,'' Mrs. Grasso said at a news
conference, with the Gabrielis standing nearby, beaming. ``I work
hard in my entire life. I'm one of six children, and so I always
try to be low, down-key, and I'm going to continue that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Grasso, who said she was an occasional lottery player,
chose an immediate lump sum payment of $104 million, instead of 26
annual payments that would have totaled $197 million, and collected
a check Wednesday for $70,244,814.02 after taxes. It was the
nation's second-largest jackpot. The largest, a $295 million
Powerball jackpot last July, was won by a group of 13 machinists in
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Grasso did not give details about her plans, other than to
say she would like to keep helping children, and she declined to
give any interviews beyond the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman, Raymond Howell, said Mrs. Grasso came to the United
States in 1971 and found work as a live-in baby sitter in New York
City. She earned a high school equivalency degree, attended
LaGuardia Community College and the College of Staten Island, both
in New York, and eventually got a job as a teaching assistant in
special education classes in the city's public schools. She also
worked part time for United Cerebral Palsy.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Grasso, who is divorced, has two children, both in college.
She moved to Boston in 1996 and went to work for the Gabrielis.
</P>
<P>
   Gabrieli had only praise for the woman who became his former
employee last Thursday with what was apparently some reluctance on
her part. ``She's a very warm and caring person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's extremely family-oriented,'' Gabrieli said. ``She has
two children she's very proud of. She's got a large family in
Chile. When I talked to her, she said, `How can I make this a
blessing for them?'''
</P>
<P>
   Gabrieli said Mrs. Grasso was in her apartment in his home in
the Beacon Hill neighborhood watching the 11 p.m. news last Tuesday
when she saw the winning number flash across her television screen.
``It matched,'' Gabrieli said. ``She couldn't believe it could be
true. She confirmed it on the second go-round at 11:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a sleepless night, and the first thing in the morning,
she called up to our room on the intercom.''
</P>
<P>
   With Gabrieli already on his way to a meeting, Mrs. Grasso spoke
to Mrs. Gabrieli, a tax lawyer who is at home, raising the couple's
four children, ages 1 through 5. ``My wife's first thought was:
`Are you sure?'''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gabrieli congratulated Mrs. Grasso, put her in touch with a
lawyer and then telephoned her husband in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the same reaction as my wife: `Are you sure, darling?'''
Gabrieli said.
</P>
<P>
   The new multimillionaire, meanwhile, insisted on putting in a
full workday. ``She actually worked Thursday as well,'' Gabrieli
said. ``Her first reaction was, `I'll work until you get a
replacement.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her, `I think this is going to be something that will
take all your psychic time. We'll muddle through.''' And so on
Thursday night, Mrs. Grasso moved out.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement put to rest persistent reports that the
lottery winner was a Boston cabdriver, Patrick Okusanya.
</P>
<P>
   A distraught Okusanya insisted he was not the winner, but even
his friends and family did not believe him, said John Ricci, a
lawyer Okusanya retained last Friday to help him deal with the
attention.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor seems to have begun with a group of cabdrivers, who
said Okusanya was the winner. Ricci said he was working free for
Okusanya, who drives his cab 60 to 70 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   Okusanya was working Wednesday, and could not be reached for
comment. Ricci said Okusanya had stopped by his office to say he
was happy for Mrs. Grasso, and glad to be out of the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   All Okusanya wanted was a coat hanger, his lawyer said. The
nonwinner had locked his keys in the cab.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
