<SLUG> BC-EXECUTE-OF-RETARDED15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bill tries to ban execution of retarded criminals
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The emotional debate over Texas' frequent use of
the death penalty rekindled Wednesday before a Senate Committee, as
opponents and supporters squared off over a bill to ban executions
of mentally retarded criminals.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, said his bill was designed
to spare convicts who ``don't have the mental capacity, the
cognitive ability, to understand what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not execute children in Texas, and I don't think we
ought to execute people who have the mental capacity of a child,''
Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   During a three-hour hearing, numerous witnesses supported the
measure _ from mental health advocates to attorneys who have
represented mentally retarded criminals.
</P>
<P>
   William Allison, a court-appointed attorney, testified how his
client on death row _ a man who he said has the mental age of 7 _
seems unaware that he was found guilty of strangling an 8-year-old
San Marcos girl, Bertha Martinez, in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never, ever even talked to me about his trial,'' Allison
said of Doil Edward Lane. ``His trial does not register with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison showed lawmakers several Crayola drawings Lane had sent
him, child-like drawings of houses and such.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have the capacity to be remorseful.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Whittington, a former member of the Texas prison system's
governing board, was among those urging passage of the bill. ``This
state should set a higher moral course for justice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors were just as adamant in opposing the bill. They
argued that passage of the bill could undermine Texas' death
penalty statute.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, they said, juries can review the specifics of
each case and determine whether a criminal should be executed.
Courts can also review whether they are competent for trial and
whether they are criminally insane.
</P>
<P>
   But under Ellis' proposal, they said, anyone who was mentally
retarded would be spared automatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should go case by case. If you don't look at individuals,
you don't do justice,'' said Walker County Criminal District
Attorney David Weeks of Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   Brazos County District Attorney Bill Turner said he opposed the
bill because it ``would lump a group of human beings together and
says that because they are morally irresponsible they should not be
held liable for their actions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It says if you can't spell murder, if you don't know where the
state of Louisiana is, then you get a break on a capital murder
case,'' he said. ``Murder is not an intelligence exercise. Just
because you are intellectually challenged doesn't mean you can't
know the difference between right and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
