<HEADLINE>
JAZZ, CLIPPERS IN REMATCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This time, it's personal.
</P>
<P>
   The last time, it was technical.
</P>
<P>
   That would be two technical fouls, and you're a goner. It's a
TKO, NBA-style.
</P>
<P>
   The date was March 27. The place was The Pond of Anaheim,
Pond-for-Pond the toughest arena in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   In the coffin corner was Utah Jazz power forward Karl Malone, at
6-foot-9 and 260 dangerous-looking pounds, with a reach that
usually extends to a referee's soul.
</P>
<P>
   In the hot corner, we had Clipper Maurice Taylor, also 6-9 and
260, with a reach he attempted to put around Malone's neck.
</P>
<P>
   To book this showdown, the last of several unsavory Malone elbow
maneuvers turned the typically riled-mannered Taylor into a
revved-up stalker.
</P>
<P>
   Order had to be restored.
</P>
<P>
   Malone was issued his second (and disqualifying) technical foul
of the evening, while Taylor painted the canvas with colorful
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   After Malone was banished, the mighty Jazz were unable to alter
their dire predicament and finished the night with a 103-77 loss to
the Clippers. It was the Clips' third victory in 27 games.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, a rematch is scheduled for the Sports Arena. Utah is
29-8, having conquered the Kings while working OT on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, whose team whacked New Jersey that night in achieving
its first back-to-back this season, was asked if the return of
Malone will inspire a heightened sense of purpose.
</P>
<P>
   As is his custom of slick verbal counter-punching Taylor said,
``Naw.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, then. No added motivation. Well, does he expect Malone to
arrive in a nasty, revenge-seeking mood?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' Taylor said following Wednesday's workout at the
Sports Arena. ``It wouldn't be any fun if he didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun? With a respectful nod to Ralph Lawler, voice of the
Clippers, fight and basketball fans may wish to shout ``Bingo!''
</P>
<P>
   sub UF5 Footloose forward
</P>
<P>
   cp,8,8.2 In case you haven't noticed, Taylor has averaged eight
rebounds per game in the Clippers last four engagements. His season
average is five.
</P>
<P>
   The improvement is easy to trace: Foot work.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely, Taylor - whose Achilles-tendon problems discouraged
animated board work - visited his friendly chiropractor. The
chiropractor fixed him right up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my feet aligned,'' Taylor said. ``I got my toes cracked,
my ankles. I'm moving a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   sub UF5 `Pike' peaking
</P>
<P>
   Guard Eric Piatkowski's 7-of-12 shooting performance in
Tuesday's victory over New Jersey was worth a few huzzahs, but his
teammates were more impressed with his two-handed dunk on a
first-quarter baseline drive.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Chris Ford has been urging `Pike' to attack the basket
with more frequency, so the fifth-year Clipper obliged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time I get a play called for me, I do my best to take
advantage of it,'' Piatkowski said. ``I was happy out there. With
all the losing we'd gone through, it starts to get embarrassing
after a while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
