<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PHILLIES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves pound Byrd, Phillies
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Phillies were looking a lot more like, well, the
Phillies on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves needed four games to win two from the Phillies in the
season-opening series in Atlanta. But on this trip to Veterans
Stadium, the Braves have needed only two games to win two. For the
second game in a row, the Braves picked on Phillies pitchers. First
it was Carlton Loewer on Monday, this time it was Paul Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   Getting home runs off Byrd by Chipper Jones and Javy Lopez, an
insurance two-run shot by Gerald Williams and another eight hits in
between, the Braves blew away the Phillies 10-4.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's trouble started with its starter. After shutting
down the Braves offense down last week, Byrd was run off by his
former team this time out. He left with one out into the third
inning and his team down 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd helped shake Chipper Jones out of his first-week funk, as
he had an RBI double and a home run in his two at-bats against
Byrd, who wasted no time finding trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning he did a little bit of everything, allowing
a walk, two doubles, a single, a wild pitch and a hit batsman and
balked in a run. By the time it was over, all nine Brave batters
had taken turns at bat, four of whom scored for a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves got only two hits off Byrd in 7 1/3 innings on April
8. It took them three batters to get two on Wednesday. Otis Nixon
lead off the game with a walk, which was followed by a Bret Boone
single and a Chipper Jones double.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was facing an 0-2 count from Byrd when he worked it back
to 2-2 and sent the pitch off the right- field wall. On his next
at-bat and pitch, which came in the second inning, Jones fired his
second home run of the year to right center field.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had been 0 for his last 7 going back to Sunday's game
against the Diamondbacks. He opened the season hitting .241 in the
Braves' homestand.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies charged back to make it 6-4 with four runs off
Kevin Millwood in the fourth and fifth innings. They reached him
over that stretch for six hits _ three on the infield _ and drew
two walks to make it a game again.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble started when Millwood loaded the bases on an infield hit
and two walks in the fourth inning. He struck out Ron Gant with a
high fastball for the second out but couldn't fool Bobby Abreu, who
singled to right to score two runs making it 6-2 Braves.
</P>
<P>
   BRAVES TONIGHT
</P>
<P>
   -- Opponent: at Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   -- When; where: 7:05; Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   -- Probable starters: Braves LHP Tom Glavine (0-2, 7.11 ERA) vs.
RHP Curt Schilling (2-0, 3.86 ERA).
</P>
<P>
   -- TV; radio: Ch. 69; WSB-AM (750).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
