<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TITLE-MATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIMINAL INQUIRY INTO JUDGING OF HOLYFIELD-LEWIS MOVES FORWARD
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ State Sen. Roy Goodman said Wednesday that he has
turned over evidence of a potentially criminal nature involving the
judging in the heavyweight championship fight between Evander
Holyfield and Lennox Lewis last month at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman gave the evidence to Robert Morgenthau, the Manhattan
district attorney, Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The senator turned up the evidence during his Senate
Investigation Committee inquiry into the fight, and Morgenthau is
conducting a criminal investigation into the bout's possible
corruption. The fight ended in a controversial draw.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is the WBC champion and Holyfield holds the WBA and the
IBF titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned it over because the Manhattan district attorney has
the interstate power of subpoena,'' Goodman said by telephone from
his office in Albany Wednesday. ``Our powers would not apply to New
Jersey and we had certain witnesses there that refused to appear
before our committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman pointed out that the information he discovered was
potentially criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Thompson, a spokesperson with the Manhattan district
attorney's office, confirmed that they had received Goodman's
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks very interesting,'' Thompson said of the information.
``We don't want to characterize it. But it's obviously something we
will look at as part of our investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan district attorney has convened a grand jury to
look into possible wrongdoing in the Holyfield-Lewis bout, which
created a public outcry. The fight was declared a draw, even though
it appeared Lewis controlled most of the 12 rounds of the bout.
</P>
<P>
   Eugenia Williams was the only judge to score the bout for
Holyfield. She was selected by the IBF and confirmed by the New
York State Athletic Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Williams admitted during hearings before Goodman's committee
last month that she had filed for bankruptcy shortly before the
fight. There was also testimony that indicated Larry O'Connell, a
judge from England, had fallen behind on his mortgage payments.
O'Connell scored the fight a draw. Williams said she did not take
any bribes to score the fight for Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said he was dismayed that people with financial problems
who could be open to temptation from corrupting influences were
allowed to judge fights. He was also surprised at how much power
the sanctioning organizations had in regard to selecting judges.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
