r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     04-14 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFECTION WELL WITHIN REACH FOR GRAND PRAIRIE'S GRAND PALACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ They got it right the first time. And
again the second time. Not bad for an initial track record. So
what's next?
</P>
<P>
   Tune an ear to the mid-cities Thursday night and you will hear
the rolling thunder of the thoroughbreds as Lone Star Park opens
its third season.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Sunday, it will be Real Quiet on Belt Line Road. The
Baffert Gang from California turns loose its stable stud at Grand
Prairie's grand palace.
</P>
<P>
   A Bob Baffert and a Real Quiet bring Lone Star continued
national recognition. Even more important is the local perception.
Real Quiet translates to big time. Big time sells around here.
</P>
<P>
   But the amazing Mr. Baffert, a staunch supporter of Lone Star
from Day One, wouldn't be coming back, particularly with Real
Quiet, if success hadn't been achieved here the first two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the third step.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, Lone Star needs to get it \Rexactly\S right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you ever reach perfection in this business, but
you never stop trying,'' said general manager Corey Johnsen.
</P>
<P>
   The doubters who once harpooned the Lone Star project are long
gone, and that includes financial institutions that five years ago
wouldn't touch the building of this track with a ten-dollar bill,
much less fifty-or-so million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same banks who once wouldn't allow us in their front door
now ask if they can fly us to New York for bond meetings,'' said a
laughing Charles England, the Grand Prairie mayor, and the No. 1
reason there is a Lone Star Park.
</P>
<P>
   Purses are bigger than ever. Attendance surges. Surveys of the
North Texas marketplace concerning Lone Star bounce higher than a
golf ball on concrete _ positive, positive, positive.
</P>
<P>
   But the quest for perfection goes on for Johnsen and his staff.
Negatives are there, and ironically, most of those come from within
the ranks of people who benefit the most from a strong Lone Star.
</P>
<P>
   A certain segment of trainers have bad-mouthed the racing
surfaces _ both the dirt track and the grass course. If this sounds
familiar, yes, it's similar to what Texas Motor Speedway went
through with NASCAR drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Trainers are like coaches, but trainers can work with one to 20
owners. When a horse doesn't perform well, owners ask why. Horse
trainers, by reputation, are the most notorious excuse makers in
the sports world. Give them a chance to blame anyone (jockeys), or
anything (the track surface), and they will.
</P>
<P>
   But Lone Star, to its credit, has had only two knocks against it
_ the heat and the track being too hard, making horses more
injury-prone. One noted trainer, Bobby Barnett, pulled his stable
out of Lone Star two years ago, blaming the track surface. Barnett
was also 2-for-38 in wins at the time. You be the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Heat is out of Johnsen's control. This, however, is the third
year of operation, and any and all kinks in the track should be
worked out. Accomplish that, and Lone Star removes the only nagging
negative, and shoves in front of a mirror those trainers looking
for an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Johnsen, however, is blunt in addressing this subject. ``The
surfaces are the foundation of what we are all about,'' he said.
``Our job is to listen to the horsemen and then make progress on
the surfaces, based on what they tell us. Whatever it takes _
money, man hours, whatever _ we will get this right.''
</P>
<P>
   Major changes costing more than $100,000 were made on the dirt
and grass courses for this season. At the moment, the trainers are
pleased. Then again, no trainer has lost a race yet.
</P>
<P>
   But from the most basic elements of thoroughbred racing _ dirt
and grass _ Lone Star has attracted ample and positive attention
for its philosophical approach to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   It is trying to mix the lifeblood of racing, as in wagering,
with a good-time concept based on entertainment. How much money
goes through the betting windows ultimately determines if a track
is successful, but...
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of people will come this weekend who maybe will not
bet more than 20 bucks for the whole day,'' said Johnsen. ``We
don't care. We welcome them. Did they have a fun time? Will they
come back? We hope so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people who return, the more they will start to
understand the sport, and somewhere down the road, the more they
will wager. That is our philosophy. It goes against the so-called
tradition of horse racing. Tradition is great, but tradition has
also damaged our sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnsen points to Baffert and his main owner, the colorful Mike
Pegram. ``They became successful by bucking the tradition of horse
racing,'' he said. ``It's a balancing act for us. We want our
veteran fans to be happy, and to continue to support us with their
wagering. And we want the newcomers to get to know what we're all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. And starting tonight, Lone Star is off and
running in search of perfection.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
