<SLUG> BC-CT-WITNESS-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO BROTHERS CHARGED WITH KILLING OF EIGHT-YEAR-OLD WITNESS AND HIS
MOTHER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two brothers were charged Wednesday in a Connecticut criminal
court with killing an 8-year-old boy and his mother, apparently to
prevent the boy from testifying against one of the brothers in a
murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   The murder charges against Russell Peeler, 27, and Adrian
Peeler, 22, capped a three-month investigation into one of the most
shocking crimes in the state in years.
</P>
<P>
   The killing of the boy, Leroy Brown Jr., in his home in
Bridgeport provoked nationwide horror and outrage, prompting a
debate about the wisdom of having someone so young testify in a
criminal trial. And it led to measures, now before the state
legislature, to provide better protection for witnesses to violent
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers were arraigned Wednesday in state Superior Court in
Bridgeport, each on two counts of capital felony, one count of
murder and one count of conspiracy to commit murder, said the
state's attorney, Jonathan Benedict.
</P>
<P>
   The charges of capital felony allow prosecutors to seek the
death penalty if the Peelers are convicted. In addition, the
brothers were also indicted Wednesday on several federal narcotics
charges. Both had been in police custody on charges unrelated to
the killings of the boy and his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Leroy Clarke, who was called B.J., and his mother, Karen Clarke,
29, were found shot to death in their duplex apartment on Jan. 8,
five months after prosecutors had reluctantly given the boy's name
and address to Russell Peeler's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. had been scheduled to testify against Peeler, who had been
charged with the shooting death of Ms. Clarke's fiance, Rudolph
Snead Jr., last May. The boy was a passenger in Snead's car in
September 1997, when prosecutors say Russell Peeler pulled up in
another car and fired shots at Snead. Though Snead survived that
shooting, he was gunned down last May in a Bridgeport barbershop.
</P>
<P>
   Based in part on B.J.'s identification of a photograph of
Russell Peeler, the police charged Peeler with attempted murder. He
later posted bond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
