<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-BLACK-QBS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL TEAMS CHANGES ITS MIND-SET ON BLACK QUARTERBACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, many blacks who played quarterback in college were
switched to another position in the pros. Blame it on circumstance
or plain old ignorance. But the bottom line is this: In the history
of the NFL, there have been more kickers (four) selected in the
first round of the draft than black quarterbacks (three).
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday night, that statistic will likely fade into history.
</P>
<P>
   The best quarterback class since 1983 features three black
athletes who are expected to go in the first round _ Oregon's Akili
Smith, Syracuse's Donovan McNabb and Central Florida's Daunte
Culpepper. Each has combined superior athletic ability with a
strong arm and the college experience to give them a chance in the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Williams, who was the first black quarterback selected in
the first round of the NFL draft, has answered numerous calls from
the media about his history-making brethren. As the first-year head
coach at Grambling State last year, Williams did not watch many
college football games on television and admits to having little
knowledge about the talented trio.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he said, it does not take a degree in human performance to
understand why Smith, McNabb and Culpepper are about to join
Williams, Andre Ware and Steve McNair as black quarterbacks taken
in the first round of the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were given a chance,'' Williams said. ``And now, these
kids have an opportunity that 20 years ago might not have been
there for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Tampa Bay Buccaneers made history by taking Williams
with their first pick in the 1978 NFL draft, Pittsburgh's Joe
Gilliam and Chicago's Vince Evans were the only black quarterbacks
drafted in any round who'd made much of a splash in the NFL at the
position they played in college. (The Rams' James Harris was an
undrafted free agent).
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, blacks who wanted to play quarterback in the pros had
been undone by their own college system, or by pro general managers
who doubted whether a black player had the intelligence to play the
position.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma's Jamelle Holloway and J.C. Watts, who excelled at
running a wishbone offense, had little training as a drop-back
passer. Even black quarterbacks who succeeded in a pro-style
passing offense, like the University of Washington's Warren Moon,
were asked to switch positions. Moon had to prove himself as a
quarterback in the Canadian Football League before the NFL was
convinced he could play the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I had played was quarterback,'' Williams said. ``I
couldn't backpedal like a defensive back. Maybe they could have put
me at tight end. But that wasn't a position I'd played before, and
I wasn't looking to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Given a chance to play the only position he knew, Williams led
the Buccaneers to their only NFC Championship Game appearance in
1979. In the 1987 season, he became the only black quarterback to
start in the Super Bowl, leading the Washington Redskins over the
Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Williams retired after the 1989 season, several
others were making old-guard league owners rethink their positions
on the black quarterback. Moon was re-writing most of the Oilers'
passing records. And Randall Cunningham, with his ability to pass
and run with equal aplomb, was twice a runner-up to Joe Montana for
the league's most valuable player award.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, with biases against black quarterbacks easing and
with blitzing defenses wrecking havoc, black quarterbacks are
growing in number. But progress hasn't come fast enough for
Williams. Of the league's 31 starters, only four _ Kordell Stewart
in Pittsburgh, Charlie Batch in Detroit, Cunningham in Minnesota,
and McNair in Tennessee _ are black.
</P>
<P>
   But with Smith, McNabb, and Culpepper on the horizon, that
number figures to change. Former Cowboys scouting director Gil
Brandt is sure of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One, I think that more and more young African-American players
are realizing that they want to emulate quarterbacks rather than
running backs and wide receivers,'' Brandt said, ``and when you see
these kids in Pop Warner, you see more playing quarterback. Two,
college teams are getting away from the option offenses. Had a guy
like \Rformer Nebraska star\S Tommie Frazier grown up as a
drop-back passer, maybe we'd be talking about him in the National
Football League because he had a lot going for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Times are changing, indeed.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
