<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DONNIE-NELSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH-IN-WAITING IMMERSED IN MAVS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ After every Mavericks loss, there seems to be one
constant: Nobody takes those losses harder than assistant coach
Donnie Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson is so engrossed in his work that he looks dazed and
depressed after losses, and acts as though he just lost his best
friend. Can he maintain that high-strung frame of mind when he
replaces his father as the Mavericks' head coach in the 2000-01
season?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to die of a heart attack, because I'm young,''
Nelson, 36, said yesterday. ``But I can't tell you that I'm not
getting gray hairs and the losses don't wear on me, because they
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I beat myself up after every loss,'' Nelson said. ``I think
that's a sign of somebody that cares and somebody that wants to be
successful. Yes, it doesn't make for a great family life during the
season. Yes, I can be a pain to be around because I throw myself
into those situations, but that's who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   For 14 years, Nelson has worked as an assistant coach to or with
Danny Ainge, Cotton Fitzsimmons, Gregg Popovich, Paul Westphal,
Garry St. Jean and his father, Don Nelson, who is the Mavericks
coach and general manager. He believes those six men helped prepare
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are extremely bright minds who are in the game today,
and guys that I respect a ton,'' the younger Nelson said. ``I've
picked up different stuff from all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of feel like I've gotten a Harvard basketball
education, and now it's time to go out there and let 'er rip and
see what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Nelson has been a head coach in NBA summer leagues,
and has taken over NBA games at various times when the head coach
has been ejected. But 2000-01 will be a season like no other for
the younger Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like going to battle for the first time,'' he said.
``You jump out of that helicopter and you hit the ground, and it's
a sink-or-swim deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks players A.C. Green, Steve Nash, Michael Finley, John
``Hot Rod'' Williams and Cedric Ceballos were with the Suns during
parts of Nelson's tenure there, and believe he will be a solid NBA
head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always difficult for a rookie head coach who has no
experience, because they go through growing pains just like rookie
players,'' Nash said. ``But his work diligence and perseverance has
always been great.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously learned a lot of wisdom from his father and
other coaches he coached with.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson believes in paying attention to detail, a philosophy that
he tries to get across to the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a hard-working, well-prepared guy, and certainly he's in
a good situation right now,'' said Westphal, who coaches the
Seattle SuperSonics. ``He's a good basketball guy who knows the
game and can do a fine job as a head coach. He established himself
enough in Phoenix through three different head coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams recalls, during his days with the Suns, when he and
Nelson would hop in a taxi and go to the arena 90 minutes before
the rest of the team so he could prepare for a game that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we did in Phoenix the last three years, Donnie's
the one who prepared us for the game, defensively and
offensively,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the reasons I came here is because I knew he was
going to be a good coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has heard the cries of nepotism, but said he doesn't put
much stock into it. He just files it in his memory bank and moves
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the package that you do in accepting a job like this
is taking criticism. I don't mind taking criticism, as long as it's
warranted. But there isn't any critic out there that can be harsher
on me than I am on myself.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
