<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-LONE-STAR-OPENS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONE STAR'S TOP TWO TRAINERS RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Thoroughbreds begin racing again tonight
at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie, whose 72-racing-day season gets
under way with a festive touch.
</P>
<P>
   Gates open at 4:30 p.m., and post time is 5:30 for the bands,
acrobats, sky divers, balloons and stilt-walkers. Four-legged
entertainment begins at 6:35 with the first of nine races.
</P>
<P>
   The training contest will start anew as well. The battle between
Dallas Keen and Jim Gaston for king of the Texas hill has been
raging for two years and sometimes gets more attention than the
horses. Keen won't have a starter tonight, and Gaston saddles only
one. But if recent history holds up, they will be frequent visitors
to the Lone Star winners circle over the next three months.
</P>
<P>
   Keen was the track's top trainer in 1997, edging Gaston 41 wins
to 36. Last year, the friendly rivals tied with 36 winners each.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston won a race on the last day of the 1998 season to tie Keen
and nearly won another to take the title outright.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tie was better than second,'' Gaston said. ``But it was a
little bit stressful for us, coming down to the last day like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaston was born in Dallas. Keen hails from Cameron. To both
native sons, recognition as Lone Star's leading trainer is the
local version of knighthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor because this is a very classy track,'' Keen
said. ``It's a track like the old days. Fans come out to the track
instead of watching races on TV at a pavilion somewhere. That makes
it fun for us. Because they're actually here, it makes horse racing
exciting, besides the gambling part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes us kind of like the racehorses. We get competitive.
Everybody wants to win, and winning races keeps you in the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, Keen won the Arkansas Derby with Valhol, a 30-1
long shot that had not previously won a race. Keen also trains
Allen's Oop, who finished a neck behind Real Quiet in the New
Orleans Handicap last month and tries 1998's 3-year-old champion
again Sunday in the $250,000 Texas Mile.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Sunday is the $300,000 Lone Star Derby, which will be
televised live on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   And if two major stakes races, national television and the
presence of Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner Real Quiet aren't
enough to get the adrenaline pumping, Julie Krone is also scheduled
to make the last riding appearance of her legendary career Sunday
at Lone Star. She has mounts on Allen's Oop and Lone Star Derby
starter Desert Demon, after which she has said she will retire.
</P>
<P>
   It gets started tonight with the $75,000 Premiere Stakes for
older Texas-breds, the first race of the meeting. Desert Air, a
full brother to Desert Demon, will be the heavy favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston's only starter tonight will be Meanest Rene, a longshot
3-year-old maiden who runs in the nightcap. Gaston has Meanest Rene
in one of his 18 stalls at his Lone Star barn, but he has access to
dozens more horses at his Benton, La., training center. He shuttles
horses back and forth from the farm, a four-hour van drive from the
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got quite a few horses just now starting to come
around,'' Gaston said. ``We ought to have a good meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Keen, who keeps all 36 of his horses at Lone Star, isn't
optimistic about repeating as leading trainer. However, it should
be noted he gave a gloomy forecast before last season, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as strong as last year and sure not as good as the
year before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Keen will spend much of the next few weeks at Churchill Downs in
Louisville, Ky., preparing Valhol for the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year it's going to be like I've got a split stable,'' he
said. ``I won't be able to devote 100 percent of my attention here
because I'll be in Kentucky so much, and I don't like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to weigh it in my mind,'' Keen added with a
laugh. ``Do I want to be leading trainer again, or do I want to win
the Kentucky Derby?'' Real Quiet arrives At Lone Star Park, it's a
reversal of the norm: In with the old, out with the new.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet, who came within an eyelash of sweeping the Triple
Crown last year, arrived at the track yesterday after a flight from
Louisville, Ky. The 4-year-old, owned by Mike Pegram and trained by
Bob Baffert, was bedded down in trainer Louie Roussel's Barn 14,
and is scheduled to run Sunday in the Texas Mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the trip in great shape,'' said assistant trainer Eoin
Harty, who accompanied Real Quiet. ``He's flown enough that he
knows something's up.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on the plane was Black Mercury, another Baffert trainee
running in Sunday's co-featured Lone Star Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet is a proven superstar, but today, 3-year-old Valhol
heads in the opposite direction to try to stake his claim in racing
history. Fresh off his shocking upset in Saturday's Arkansas Derby,
Valhol is being flown from Lone Star to Churchill Downs for the May
1 Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Valhol belongs to James Jackson of Rockdale, who turned down two
$2.5 million offers for his horse earlier in the week. Jackson also
owns Allen's Oop, who will run in Sunday's Texas Mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it's not about the money,'' explained Jackson,
saying if the offers get much higher, the money might become more
important. Briefly Vivace, the 6-year-old millionaire mare owned by
Jerry and Linda Minter of Pilot Point, is scheduled to make her
second Lone Star appearance Saturday in the $50,000 Irving Distaff
at 7 1/2 furlongs on grass. She won an allowance on May 2, 1997, in
Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't met the summer-heat test yet, but Lone Star's retooled
dirt surface is getting early approval from most horsemen. Workout
times have been fast, but observers standing on the outside rail
can barely hear the horses run past, a sign the track has ample
cushion. Another problem has been the hardness of the grass course
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   For those keeping score at home, Lone Star will be going up
against 1998 opening-night figures of 15,711 in attendance, and
betting on local races of $1.3 million on-track and $3.2 million
counting all sources.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
