u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-ORANGE-POLICE-NYT &LR;      04-14 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-ORANGE-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE THINK THEY HAVE WRONG MAN, LAWYERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Lawyers for the man charged with killing a
policewoman in Orange said Wednesday that actions by law
enforcement officials, including the disclosure that a recent
polygraph indicated that the suspect was innocent, were signs of a
growing belief among investigators that the man's arrest was a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Hamlin and Ronald Hunt, lawyers for the suspect,
Terrance Everett, 24, of East Orange, said the disclosure was just
the latest development since Everett's arrest Saturday to suggest
that investigators are having second thoughts. Results of the
polygraph test were first reported in Wednesday's issue of The
Star-Ledger of Newark, which attributed the information to
unidentified law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin said he and Hunt had yet to see the results of the
polygraph test, which was administered after Everett was arrested.
The lawyers have subpoenaed the office of Essex County Prosecutor
Patricia Hurt to obtain the results.
</P>
<P>
   Polygraph tests, while inadmissible as evidence in court, are
generally used as investigative tools by law enforcement agencies
to bolster their rationale for an arrest, not undermine it.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also noted that investigators had continued to
search for the killer of the officer, Joyce Anne Carnegie, even
after Everett had been arrested and charged. During that search,
investigators used a composite sketch of a robbery suspect who they
believed was involved in the shooting of Officer Carnegie.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials close to the investigation said
investigators had witnesses only to two street robberies, not to
the shooting, which they believe occurred when Officer Carnegie
arrived to investigate one of the robberies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is interesting and significant that they did
this,'' said Hunt, referring to investigators' use of the sketch
more than 24 hours after Everett had been picked up.
</P>
<P>
   As for the release of Everett's polygraph results, Hunt said:
``There may be some damage control by them now rather than later.
If their investigation ultimately leads to his release, they may
want to show now that they had some misgivings.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt's office would not comment Wednesday on developments in
the investigation of the shooting of Officer Carnegie, 38, who
lived in North Plainfield. She was shot in the abdomen and head
Thursday on an Orange street.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Ms. Hurt's office also continued to investigate the
death of Earl Faison, 27, while in police custody Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt's office has not responded to questions about why
Faison was stopped by Orange police officers Sunday night. But
according to police, he struggled with the officers and later
collapsed and died at Police Headquarters. Published reports have
suggested that Faison was stopped because he had matched the
description of the robbery suspect being sought in connection with
Officer Carnegie's death and because he had an illegal gun. The
police have not confirmed those reports, however.
</P>
<P>
   While preliminary autopsy findings ruled out blunt force as the
cause of death, Faison's father, Earl Williams, said the family had
retained a lawyer and was seeking an independent autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, James Coker, 29, of Newark, who was arrested in
Orange late Sunday as part of the investigation of Officer
Carnegie's death, remained in custody Wednesday, charged with
possession of crack and attempting to destroy evidence. He has not
been charged in connection with the killing or the robberies.
</P>
<P>
   FBI forensic experts have been made available to the local
agencies investigating Officer Carnegie's death. Monica Patton, a
spokeswoman for the FBI office in Newark, said the agency's
Evidence Response Team, which includes chemical, engineering and
DNA experts, was supporting the investigation, but she would not
say how.
</P>
<P>
   Everett is being held on $1 million bail. Hamlin said he
expected that Judge Betty Lester of state Superior Court in Newark,
who is presiding over the case, would schedule a bail-reduction
hearing within three days. He said he might present witnesses and
evidence at that time to show that his client could not have killed
Officer Carnegie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
