<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KEVORKIAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JAIL TIME FOR DR. KEVORKIAN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, April 15:
</P>
<P>
   That was a harsh sentence a Michigan judge imposed on Dr. Jack
Kevorkian this week for his murder conviction in the ``mercy
killing'' of a seriously ill patient. Some may think that a
sentence of 10 to 25 years in prison _ with the possibility of
parole after 6 years and 8 months _ is even too harsh, given that
Kevorkian is 70 years old and performing what, from his skewed
perspective, was an act of conscience. But quibbling over whether
the sentence should have been a few years lighter pales against the
important message sent by Judge Jessica Cooper's tough sentence and
blistering statement to Kevorkian. No one can openly flout the law
on murder and expect to get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Kevorkian moved from giving patients the means to
kill themselves to personally administering the lethal injection.
As part of his increasingly reckless campaign to promote assisted
suicide and euthanasia to end the suffering of desperately ill
patients, he provided CBS-TV's ``60 Minutes'' with a videotape in
which he ended the life of Thomas Youk, a victim of Lou Gehrig's
disease. Kevorkian virtually dared the legal system to try to stop
him _ and that is what has now happened.
</P>
<P>
   True, Youk and his family had sought Kevorkian's assistance as a
way to end the patient's suffering. That such patients feel they
must turn to Kevorkian is a glaring indictment of our society's
failure to allow assisted suicide in rigorously controlled medical
settings.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian has helped bring the need for right-to-die reforms to
public attention. But his idiosyncratic crusade has actually begun
to hurt the cause he supports. He veered toward flamboyant
self-promotion by dealing death to patients when he had no
long-term knowledge of their cases and no corroboration of his
medical judgments. The virtue of the harsh sentence _ in a case
that Kevorkian intends to appeal _ is that it may put him out of
action and let leadership of the assisted-suicide movement pass to
people with sounder judgment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
