<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0490 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8753 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-EUROPE-1STLD-W     04-14 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-EUROPE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN LEADERS OFFER KOSOVO PEACE PLAN; U.S. SEES LITTLE CHANCE
OF SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs for additiional details beginning with 4th graf and
continuing mostly throughout)   (ac)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Joining in the search for a diplomatic
solution to the crisis in Kosovo, leaders of 15 European Union
countries presented a plan Wednesday under which the province would
be placed under temporary international European administration if
President Slobodan Milosevic agreed to withdraw his forces and
allowed hundreds of thousands of Albanian refugees to return.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials gave the European initiative, and a more detailed
one made public separately by Germany on Wednesday, little chance
of being accepted by Belgrade. NATO reiterated that it would
continue bombing in Yugoslavia until Milosevic withdrew all police
and military units from Kosovo and let the ethnic Albanian
population go back home.
</P>
<P>
   But the European proposal could break new ground by signaling to
Yugoslavia's leaders and to Russia that the United States and the
North Atlantic military alliance it dominates do not have to be the
only players if Milosevic is interested in any outcome in Kosovo
other than his own fiery end.
</P>
<P>
   The European leaders insisted that the United Nations, Russia
and the European Union _ a primarily economic grouping of West
European countries that does not deal with defense issues _ should
all play a role in diplomatic moves to resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who attended the European
Union discussions Wednesday, welcomed support for his own efforts
from the Europeans and said that other members of the United
Nations Security Council would be consulted about their proposals.
``I have no plans for a trip to Belgrade,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also discussed some of the
ideas in the European plan in Oslo on Tuesday with Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov, according to allied officials. There was no
indication that a broad agreement emerged from the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   NATO continued attacking Serbian military targets Wednesday,
bombarding Belgrade with its heavy strikes, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
   Summarizing the discussions of the European leaders, German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said Wednesday night that the goal of
both diplomacy and of NATO military action was to create a change
in Yugoslavia that would stop Serbian attacks on Albanian
population centers and insure safety for all two million people in
Kosovo. About 90 percent of them are ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heads of state and government reiterate their
determination not to tolerate the killings and deportations in
Kosovo and believe that the use of the most severe measures,
including military measures, was both necessary and justified,''
Schroeder said, meaning NATO bombing to stop the Serbian attacks.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the Europeans now considered that ``establishment
of an international interim administration which the European Union
could take over'' was an essential part of an eventual peace
settlement in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Other parts of a settlement package that the leaders had
discussed, Schroeder said, included a police force that would
reflect the province's ethnic composition; elections, and
``deployment of international military forces that will guarantee
protection for the whole population of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of making Kosovo a ``protectorate'' under international
security guarantees has been previously mooted by NATO, but all
discussions so far have supposed that Milosevic's forces would be
either withdrawn or neutralized before any international force was
introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Germany also floated its own diplomatic proposal earlier
Wednesday to take Kosovo away from Serbia as part of a peace
settlement, but it suggested putting the province under United
Nations administration.
</P>
<P>
   French officials said the idea of taking Kosovo under the
European Union's wing instead came from President Jacques Chirac.
Schroeder said the other leaders agreed to that proposal in
Wednesday night's discussions.
</P>
<P>
   But unless Milosevic suddenly gives up and accepts these ideas,
the only way to impose them on him remains the bombing campaign,
now being carried out by about 1,000 U.S. British, French, Dutch
and German warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The original German proposal also suggested a 24-hour suspension
of the bombing if Milosevic actually began pulling forces out of
Kosovo by deadlines set by Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   But Britain is staunchly opposed to any letup of the bombing
until the Serbs end actions, their forces withdraw from Kosovo, an
international military force can go in and the refugees are allowed
to return to their homes in peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not going to be a halt to the NATO action until the
demands that we have set out, which are entirely reasonable,
humane, civilized demands, are met in full,'' Prime Minister Tony
Blair said Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to allow Milosevic to get away with the
policy of ethnic cleansing,'' Blair said. ``He will be defeated on
that policy and the military objectives that we have set at the
beginning of this campaign will be seen through in their entirety,
in their entirety.''
</P>
<P>
   These objectives, the European leaders agreed Wednesday night,
included ``deployment of international military forces that will
guarantee protection for the whole population of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO allies insist that any such force should be led and
commanded by the alliance, possibly under a mandate from the United
Nations, but Yugoslavia has so far refused to discuss any kind of
force.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, a permanent member of the United Nations Security
Council with veto power over its decisions, has said it would
approve such a force only if Milosevic was willing to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Under the original German plan, which Foreign Minister Joachim
Fischer discussed with the United States, Britain, France, Canada
and Italy at a NATO meeting in Brussels on Monday, the Security
Council would set firm deadlines for Milosevic to start and finish
a withdrawal of all Serbian and paramilitary forces from the
province.
</P>
<P>
   If he began withdrawing, according to the proposal, NATO forces
would break off air strikes for 24 hours. If the Serbian police and
army troops kept withdrawing, the 24-hour pause would be extended,
with peacekeepers moving in as the Serbian forces left.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and other allied officials reacted to the German plan
skeptically, but apparently agreed to see if the Russians would try
it out on Belgrade. ``Nobody thinks it will work,'' a U.S. official
said. ``First of all, Milosevic will never accept it. But at this
point, everybody is willing to try everything.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin said in Washington, ``The
main point in the German plan that's relevant here is that this
would be done ideally by resolution of the Security Council, which
would be fine with us.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bonn, Fischer said Russia ``almost fully agreed'' to his
plan. But he said Russia still had concerns about the peacekeeping
force.
</P>
<P>
   Acceptance of a plan to surrender Kosovo to international
administration would mean, for the fiercely nationalist Milosevic,
giving up sovereignty over territory that was historically Serbian,
something not even the plan he refused in negotiations at
Rambouillet Castle in France this winter would have asked him to
do.
</P>
<P>
   His refusal to accept that plan's proposals to leave the
province under Serbian sovereignty but give its 1.8 million
Albanians political and legal autonomy set off the NATO bombing
that began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union also reaffirmed plans announced last week for
it to provide $160 million for refugee relief and $107 million to
Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro to help them provide for the
hundreds of thousands of Kosovo Albanians who have fled to those
countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
