<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WENDELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WENDELL, ANNOUNCER ON DAVID LETTERMAN SHOW, DIES AT 75  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn.)   By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Wendell, a radio and television announcer whose crisp
authoritative voice provided an ironic foil to entertainers from
Ernie Kovacs to David Letterman, died Wednesday at a hospice in
Boca Raton, Fla. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was complications from cancer, said one of
his daughters, Francette Nunziata.
</P>
<P>
   Until his retirement in 1995, Wenzel was most recently known for
the off-stage introduction of guests at the beginning of
Letterman's show at NBC and later CBS. The introductions typically
began with a municipal characterization like, ``From New York,
mountain fortress of the ancient Incas, it's `Late Night With David
Letterman . . .'''
</P>
<P>
   But Wendell also worked with Bob Hope, Dave Garroway, Jack Paar,
Merv Griffin, Gary Moore, Alan King, Tom Snyder, Billy Crystal and
Jerry Seinfeld. But what brought him the earliest and widest
attention was his work in the 1950s as the on-air sidekick for
Ernie Kovacs, Mrs. Nunziata said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were always playing practical jokes on each other,'' his
daughter recalled. ``One time Ernie was supposed to gulp a big
martini, but it was supposed to be filled with water, only it was
really filled with vodka. He spit it out and started coughing like
crazy on live national television. Dad and his cronies were
laughing their heads off.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendell was born William Joseph Wenzel, Jr. on March 22, 1924,
in New York City to William J. Wenzel , a beverage distributor and
an owner of several Manhattan fruit stands, and Mildred S. Wenzel,
a housewife. After serving in the U.S. Army Air Corps in World War
II, he worked in radio and early television. He had taken the
professional name of Wendell ``because he wanted to give his family
some privacy and maybe a German name at that time wasn't that
popular,'' Mrs. Nunziata said.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell then went on to work as a staff radio and television
announcer for NBC, on call for network promotions, special news
bulletins and network identifications.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his daughter Mrs. Nunziata of Pelham Manor, N.Y.,
Wendell is survived by his wife, Anne Eustace Wenzel; two other
daughters, Anne Wenzel Markgraf of Burbank, California, and
Elizabeth Hansbury of White Plains; two sons, William J. Wenzel 3d
of Southport, Conn., and Richard Eustace Wenzel of Mount Vernon,
N.Y., and 14 grandchildren. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0494 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-14 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8761 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COAL-DERAIL-KAN &LR;      04-14 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COAL-DERAIL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI TOWN BRUSHES OFF COAL DUST, THANKFUL DERAILMENT WASN'T
WORSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHAWNA A. HAMEL and BILL GRAHAM  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARKVILLE, Mo. _ Parkville will continue cleaning up Thursday
from a spectacular train derailment that dumped 2,600 tons of coal
onto its Main Street late Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, what happened is a miracle,'' said Mike
Newburger of the Southern Platte Fire Protection District. ``Just
think if something like this would have happened at 11 p.m. on a
Saturday night. It could have been worse than the flood of 1993.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The derailment, which happened about 11:45 p.m. Tuesday, shook
the antebellum town of 2,700 that sits along the Missouri River
west of Kansas City. No one was injured. The derailment posed no
health hazards, but it paralyzed Parkville's downtown and most
likely will cost more than $2 million to clean up and repair the
damage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt if this happened at 5:30 in the evening it
would have killed people,'' said Parkville Mayor Bill Quitmeier,
``whether it was shop owners or families sitting at the crossing on
their way to soccer practice.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tracks rumble a few feet past century-old buildings on the
city's historic Main Street. On the other side of the tracks are
the city's park and a newer shopping district. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary review indicated that the derailment was caused by
a ball bearing that malfunctioned. Excess heat from that ball
bearing caused a wheel to lock, detach from its axle and slip from
the track, said Steve Forsberg, a spokesman for Burlington Northern
Santa Fe Railway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The locked wheel was about a third of the train's length from
the engine. Twenty-six cars of the 121-car train derailed and
crunched into the length of about two city blocks. It appeared that
part of the train dragged for up to three miles, Forsberg said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speed was not a factor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speed tapes show the train was traveling 31 mph, Forsberg said.
The maximum trains can travel through downtown Parkville is 45 mph,
he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, which could take several months, will include
a review of the train's speed tapes, and a look at the tracks and
cars for defects. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg said he did not know when the train was last inspected.
Federal laws require trains to be inspected every 1,000 miles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An investigation into the derailment by the National
Transportation Safety Board is not required because there were no
injuries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg called the derailment ``moderate.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Derailments like this don't happen too often,'' Forsberg said.
``There really are only a few incidents like this that occur every
million train miles. And if the derailment did result from a ball
bearing, well, it's like the tire on a car. Even when you make all
the normal and required checks, there are still instances where
something goes wrong.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two buildings, one of which was built in 1885, were severely
damaged but can be salvaged, fire officials said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At One Main Street, closest to the tracks, Ronda Sulltrap of
Parkville and her five partners frequently had been working until
midnight or beyond to stock a gift shop they opened April 1. On
Tuesday night, they contemplated going to the store, but worked at
her house on paperwork instead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rail cars smashed most of one wall and filled the store with
coal in seconds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really just a fluke that we weren't there,'' Sulltrap
said. ``We think someone was looking out for us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nearby trains, she said, have long rattled walls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about train derailment, that it hasn't happened in
150 years, that it could never happen,'' Sulltrap said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five apartments also had to be evacuated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``First, it was just a big rattle, then a bang, bang, bang,''
said Police Officer Steve Bagley, who lives in an apartment near
the tracks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He was watching television and jumped back from his wall near
the tracks during the 20 to 30 seconds the cars were derailing.
When he opened a screen door to a deck on his second-story
apartment, he saw building insulation falling like snow, four
inches of coal on his upper deck and a mountain of coal and wrecked
cars in the parking lot below. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bagley then heard another train whistle. Fearing another crash,
he rushed three other people from their apartments in the block,
away from the tracks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A power line was severed, but electricity in the downtown area
was restored by 2 p.m. Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A broken water main prompted an advisory to boil water through
Thursday for residents whose service was interrupted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Park College canceled classes Wednesday because of the lack of
water. Classes are expected to resume Thursday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the downtown businesses are expected to be closed
through Friday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burlington Northern will pay for the cleanup and the track
replacement, Forsberg said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He expects the company will pay for damage to buildings and
vehicles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do the responsible thing here...but I can't promise
that anyone who files any claims...will be reimbursed,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg said that other trains were rerouted and that other
operations were not affected. The derailed train was headed from
Lincoln, Neb., to Kansas City, Kan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The spilled coal is being taken to a landfill because companies
will not use coal contaminated with dirt, Forsberg said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg said two track side detectors near downtown Parkville
did not indicate any high temperatures radiating from the trains'
wheels. High temperatures generally are caused by ball-bearing
malfunctions, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trains using the railway winding through Parkville carry all
manner of materials; Newburger said a hazardous materials spill
there would have caused ``nothing less than a disaster.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have had a major evacuation situation,'' he said.
``Of all the hazardous materials that could have spilled, this is
really the best-case scenario for any of us. Coal is the least
life-threatening material, so there basically is no danger for the
public.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trains carrying coal generally run through Parkville twice a
day, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quitmeier said that although there were no injuries, the
``aftermath is more than enough for any of us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we were lucky because we dodged a bullet this time,'' he
said. ``But now, what do we do to make sure there aren't any more
risks in the future?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
