<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-BRAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE'S ELTON BRAND, PLAYER OF YEAR, ENTERS DRAFT TWO YEARS EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wave of underclassmen defections to the National Basketball
Association finally washed over Duke on Wednesday, when sophomore
center Elton Brand, the consensus player of the year, announced
that he would forego his final two years of eligibility to enter
this summer's draft.
</P>
<P>
   Brand, who is expected to be among the top three players
selected, is the first Duke star to leave the program early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been a dream of mine to take care of my family,''
said Brand, whose mother, Daisy, worked to raise two sons alone
while living in a Peekskill, N.Y., housing project. ``Now I have
the means.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 8 inches and 260 pounds, Brand was the dominating
interior player _ he averaged 17.8 points and 9.8 rebounds _ who
helped propel the Blue Devils to a 37-2 record and the National
Collegiate Athletic Association championship game, which it lost to
Connecticut. Brand, who is likely to be a power forward in the NBA,
said he would finish this semester and attend summer school before
beginning his pro career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will eventually finish, but just not in the four-year time
period,'' Brand said. ``I will always be a part of Duke, the
coaches and the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand's announcement was the latest in a series by the game's
premier underclassmen who are shaping this year's draft while they
also reshape the landscape of college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Brand's decision follows by only one day that of his friend and
his Amateur Athletic Union teammate Ron Artest of St. John's to
enter the draft. Artest, who gave up two years of college
eligibility, has been projected by some scouts as a lottery pick _
among the first 13 players selected _ but his standing largely
depends on who else enters the draft. Maryland's spectacular junior
shooting guard Steve Francis has already announced that he will
enter the draft after only one year with the Terrapins, and the
junior forward Albert White of Missouri is also coming out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're recruiting great players, you almost have to look
at it as if you're recruiting junior college players,'' St. John's
coach Mike Jarvis said after Artest's announcement. ``You're only
going to have them one or two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski, whose previous stars Grant Hill and
Christian Laettner stayed four years, said he backed Brand's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of how well he has done, the decision-making process
has been moved up,'' Krzyzewski, who is recovering at home from hip
surgery, said by telephone. ``Elton is making the right decision
for everyone involved. I am 100 percent in support of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski might not be so thrilled if several of Brand's
teammates follow him. Point guard William Avery is strongly
considering taking the leap, too. The Duke school newspaper
reported earlier this week that Avery, a sophomore, had decided to
leave. But after hearing the report, Avery's mother, Terry
Simonton, drove to Durham, N.C., from their family's home in
Augusta, Ga., to encourage him to say.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Avery's father, William Sr., told The Augusta Chronicle
that the family was still weighing the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Duke freshman forward Corey Maggette, an athletic sensation
with tremendous power and a sweet shot but only three collegiate
starts, also considered entering the draft _ he would likely have
been a top-five pick on potential alone _ but according to some
reports, has decided he should get one more year of experience. If
he remains healthy and averts a sophomore slump, Maggette would
almost certainly be the top pick in next year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 selection this year remains a good question. Rhode
Island's Lamar Odom, a 6-9, 215-pound guard-forward, could be the
first player taken, and would certainly be in the top three if he
decides to leave school. But Odom, who considered entering the
draft directly from high school, is sitting on the school's
selection committee for a new coach. If the job goes to assistant
coach Jerry DeGregorio, who is something of a father figure to Odom
after he coached him at a Connecticut high school and then ushered
him to Rhode Island (after which DeGregorio was hired by former
coach Jim Harrick), there is a slim chance Odom will stay.
</P>
<P>
   Among other premier players who are still undecided is the
Connecticut junior swingman Richard Hamilton. A first-team
all-American and two-time Big East player of the year, Hamilton is
expected to leave the Huskies after leading them to the national
championship this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was in the car when his teammate, point guard Khalid
El-Amin, was arrested Tuesday on a misdemeanor drug possession
charge in Hartford, Conn. El-Amin, a sophomore, had previously
announced that he would stay in school. Others left to decide by
the May 15 deadline: UCLA's Baron Davis, Michigan State's Mateen
Cleaves and Auburn's Chris Porter.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
