A8766 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIP-TUBE-KAN &LR;      04-14 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIP-TUBE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKERS OF DEFECTIVE WATER HEATERS TOLD TO FIX PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first government action against the makers of thousands _
perhaps millions _ of defective water heaters, Michigan's attorney
general on Wednesday said five companies must agree to fix the
problem or face a lawsuit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The problem, which involves a defective plastic pipe called a
dip tube, could affect virtually all 24 million water heaters
produced in North America from 1993 to 1996, said Jennifer M.
Granholm, the Michigan attorney general. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The manufacturers must stop burying their corporate heads in
the sand and own up to this problem,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Granholm's office on Wednesday filed a legal notice that gives
the companies 10 days to settle the matter before a lawsuit is
filed. Any settlement would include commitments to publicize the
problem and pay for repairs. Granholm said other state attorneys
general, including those in Missouri and Kansas, would be asked
next week to make it a multistate action. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   National publicity for the problem has increased since a January
story in /{The Kansas City Star/} told about the defect. But the
companies themselves have not notified customers, waiting instead
until people ask for help with repairs. That has made it harder to
gauge the extent of the failures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand of the dip tubes have failed, disintegrating
into plastic pellets that can clog faucets, showers and appliances.
In addition, a water heater becomes much less efficient because the
dip tube is needed to circulate cold water properly in the heater's
tank. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Perfection Corp., which made the dip tubes, was named as a
defendant in the Michigan action, as were four water heater
manufacturers: American, Rheem, A.O. Smith and Bradford White.
Together, the four make most U.S. water heaters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Repairs often cost $100 to $400, but can be more if plumbing or
appliances are damaged. Granholm said the bill to fix the problem
would reach into the millions, and consumers shouldn't be the ones
to pay the bill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The manufacturers must be held accountable,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the manufacturers say they have been working to
take care of their customers, and Perfection says it is committed
to fixing the water heaters and paying the repair bills. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a problem that Perfection has been running away
from, and it's not running away now,'' said William Mertens, an
attorney representing Perfection. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Star article in January reported that many consumers were
puzzled when their heaters failed or plastic chips clogged their
plumbing. Since then, other newspapers and TV stations across the
country have printed or aired stories about the defective tubes.
ABC's ``Good Morning America'' aired a story on the problem
Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Michigan attorney general's action, private
class-action lawsuits have been filed in Kansas, Missouri and
Michigan seeking damages for consumers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Phalen, a lawyer with Humphrey, Farrington &AMP; McClain in
Independence, one of the law firms involved in the private
lawsuits, said talks were being held with the water-heater
manufacturers and Perfection over ways the litigation could be
settled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perfection's manufacturing process could have been defective for
up to 24 million dip tubes from 1993 to 1996 _ a time when at least
some of the tubes were not properly infused with chemicals needed
to keep them from decaying. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At first, Perfection estimated that only 15,000 heaters would be
affected, a fraction of those made during the years in question.
That estimate was based on requests for repairs, and Mertens said
Perfection was re-evaluating how many might fail. He said about 16
million defective dip tubes might have been installed, but the
company still thought only a fraction of those would fail. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anecdotal evidence indicates that there are still plenty of
consumers just finding out about the defect. A Detroit TV station
aired a story on the problem Wednesday, causing hundreds of calls
to a Birmingham, Mich., law firm involved in one of the
class-action suits, said Tim Arnold, a lawyer for the firm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, Marvalea Shoemake of Merriam said she
had been noticing how much longer it took to fill her coffee maker
from a kitchen faucet. So this week, her husband took off the
faucet's aerator screen and found it packed with plastic chips. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like we've got it,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roger Peugeot, owner of Roger the Plumber in Johnson County,
said he had replaced or repaired 300 water heaters with
disintegrating dip tubes. In the last few days, he was called by a
customer whose home had weak water pressure. It turned out that the
water lines were clogged with plastic chips from a dip tube. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the craziest thing I've ever had to deal with,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990414.0498 </DOCNO>
