<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WAR AND PEACE IN KOSOVO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, April 15:
</P>
<P>
   Wars are easier to start than to stop, and the diplomatic
initiatives now in play on Kosovo are likely to mutate several
times before a political settlement draws within sight. But
Wednesday, for the first time since the combat began, the diplomats
were as active as the generals, with Germany leading the way. The
most difficult challenge for the United States and NATO is to blend
force and diplomacy to bring Slobodan Milosevic into negotiations
without sacrificing the alliance's objectives.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is maneuvering furiously to divide NATO and induce it
to end the war on his terms. His offer Wednesday to accept unarmed
international monitors in Kosovo as part of a peace deal may sound
reasonable, but it would leave ethnic Albanians vulnerable to
Serbian repression. Nor should anyone be impressed by his talk of
building an alliance of Slavic nations to oppose NATO. His meeting
in Belgrade with the dictatorial president of impoverished Belarus,
Aleksandr Lukashenko, looked like a parody of a Warsaw Pact summit.
</P>
<P>
   For now, NATO must sustain and intensify the bombing. But damage
to Serbian military and industrial installations is mounting, and
at some point Milosevic may start to look more seriously at peace
possibilities. Germany's proposal would move too quickly to a
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   But it broadly reflects NATO's goals and can serve as a useful
basis for diplomatic discussions. It calls for the withdrawal of
Serbian forces from Kosovo, the safe return of refugees and the
introduction of a robust international peacekeeping force to
prevent further ethnic conflict. The scheme would also require
ethnic Albanian guerrilla forces to cease hostilities and would
place Kosovo under U.N. administration while its status is
determined. The European Union offered a similar plan of its own
that would put Kosovo under European supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Cease-fire terms are critically important. The Germans suggest a
24-hour moratorium if Belgrade begins to pull out its troops, with
the bombing halt extended as long as the withdrawals continue to
meet a predetermined schedule. But more must be required of
Milosevic before the bombing stops, including his agreement in
principle to the core NATO conditions and an end to his assault on
Kosovo. Otherwise he could start withdrawals while using the
cease-fire to resupply his forces and continue the attacks against
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, in its own fashion, seems ready to help mediate.
Wednesday President Boris Yeltsin named his former prime minister,
Viktor Chernomyrdin, as a special envoy for the Balkan crisis.
Chernomyrdin is a pragmatic negotiator who appreciates the
importance of maintaining Russia's economic and political ties with
Europe and the United States. With Secretary General Kofi Annan of
the United Nations also prepared to serve as an intermediary,
Milosevic cannot complain about a shortage of potential
peacemakers.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-99 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
