<HEADLINE>
WNBA AND PLAYERS SETTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Women's National Basketball Association and its players
union reached an agreement in principle Wednesday on a new
four-year contract, managing to negotiate differences that had once
threatened to delay the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   If ratified, the collective bargaining agreement will be the
first for the women's pro league and, according to league
officials, the first of its kind for women's team sports. The
league's 122 players are expected to vote on the proposal by April
22 for a season that runs from June to August.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary contract, reached late Wednesday evening through
a series of telephone calls, averted the cancellation of the
league's tryout camp, which is scheduled for this Friday and
Saturday in Chicago. A number of top college prospects and former
players from the defunct American Basketball League are expected to
be invited to participate in the camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to report that the WNBA and the Women's National
Basketball Players Association have reached an agreement,'' said
WNBA president Valerie Ackerman. ``This is, in fact, a preliminary
agreement. The agreement has not been written or signed and we have
a bit of work to do to finalize it.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which expires in 2002, calls for an increase in
player salaries from last year's $15,000 minimum, to $25,000 for
rookies and $30,000 for veterans. Veterans' minimum salaries will
be raised $2,500 for each of the next two years, reaching $40,000
by 2002. Rookie minimum salaries will also increase, to $26,500
next year, $28,000 the following year and $30,000 in the fourth
year. Players will also be able to negotiate additional increases
based on merit.
</P>
<P>
   But money was only part of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The union was determined to secure the jobs of its members by
limiting each team to two ABL players. The league wanted free rein.
In the end, the two sides compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 12 WNBA teams will be allowed to add three ABL
players this year, except for the league's two expansion teams _
Orlando and Minnesota _ which will be allowed to add five.
</P>
<P>
   There will no limits on the number of ABL players in the 2000
season. The WNBA will expand by four teams that year, creating an
additional 44 jobs for women in the game. Ackerman said the league
hoped to name the sites of its expansion teams by June 10, the
start of the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long process, but it was well worth it,'' said Pam
Wheeler, director of operations for the Women's National Basketball
Players Association and one of the union's chief negotiators.
``This is a milestone, not only for women's sports, but women's
basketball. This agreement is a significant step forward for the
players.''
</P>
<P>
   A majority vote of the union members is needed to ratify the
contract. Wheeler said the executive committee, which included
player representatives like Coquese Washington, Rebecca Lobo and
Theresa Witherspoon, will recommend that the contract be approved.
Witherspoon plays for the Liberty, host team of the league's first
All-Star game, on July 14 at New York's Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   While both sides acknowledged that the negotiations, which began
nearly two months ago, had at times been emotionally charged, they
characterized the talks as ``cordial and productive.'' In doing so,
it appeared that the women of the NBA wanted to distinguish their
negotiations from the contentious NBA labor dispute. The WNBA
players are represented by the NBA players association.
</P>
<P>
   The women's contract has a no-strike, no-lockout provision in
its fourth year. The contract can be renegotiated in its third
year.
</P>
<P>
   These are among some of the other key provisions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Royalties to players for all player-identified merchandise,
with a guaranteed minimum payment of $100,000 going to the union
for each year of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   _ A 401(k) plan with mandatory employer contributions and
matching amounts in the event players make their own contributions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Guaranteed salaries for players who appear in at least half of
the 32-game season.
</P>
<P>
   _ A $100,000 life insurance policy for each player.
</P>
<P>
   _ Year-round health benefits, including maternity leave and a
dental plan.
</P>
<P>
   Washington said the players were ecstatic about the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always considered ourselves partners with the WNBA and
happy they have stepped forward and told us through this agreement
that they consider us partners as well,'' she said. ``We will have
labor peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington said there was never any animosity between WNBA
players and their rivals in the ABL.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them are personal friends, people we played with
overseas or in college,'' Washington said. ``We have a history and
a relationship with these players.
</P>
<P>
   ``With them in the league, it makes our games that much more
exciting and competitive.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
