<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVS STEP UP EXPULSIONS IN KOSOVO AREA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ Yugoslav forces in southeastern Kosovo are
stepping up a campaign of expelling ethnic Albanians from across
southeastern Kosovo, according to refugees crossing the border here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The new wave of Yugoslav attacks, growing food shortages and the
latest Yugoslav policy of allowing Albanians to freely cross the
border here has swollen the flood of refugees fleeing from Kosovo.
More than 3,000 disheveled and dispirited ethnic Albanians trudged
across the border here Wednesday clutching their life possessions
in tote bags and backpacks, triple the number who entered the
previous day.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. refugee officials, while cautioning that their information
about what is happening inside Kosovo is limited, said a new exodus
of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo could be dawning. ``It could very
well be that very large numbers of people are coming,'' said Paula
Ghedini, a spokeswoman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees,
adding that the situation in Kosovo was ``probably deteriorating
very rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees painted a stark picture of thousands of people trying
to flee southeastern Kosovo as the Yugoslav expulsion campaign
spreads outward from the town of Urosevac, the site of a Yugoslav
army barracks.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three days, refugees said, Serbian paramilitaries
and Yugoslav soldiers have attacked ethnic Albanian villages in a
20-by-5-mile valley of rich farm land that hooks through
southeastern Kosovo. Villages along the Macedonian border are also
being attacked, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Expulsions that began last week in villages around the town of
Urosevac have now been extended to Albanian villages in three
different directions: those around Ljipljane, about five miles to
the north; Kacanik, 10 miles to the south, and Gnjilane, about 15
miles to the West, refugees said. Those who refuse to leave their
homes are killed, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians remain trapped in small
pockets in the hills bordering the now nearly deserted valley, an
area that Western diplomats said was not a center of activity by
the Kosovo Liberation Army, the ethnic- Albanian guerrilla group
that has been fighting for Kosovo's independence from Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the villages from Gnjilane to the border here were
empty,'' said Hysen Hoti, a 57-year-old construction worker who
said Serb paramilitaries forced him out of the village of Kmetovic
on Wednesday. ``You could see no people, only domestic animals and
cows wandering.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians who fled from their villages to Urosevac are so
desperate to leave Kosovo that they are overwhelming the region's
transportation system. Over the last two days, word that the border
was open has spread in Kosovo, refugees said. They said that
thousands of ethnic Albanians jammed the Urosevac train station
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials brought in an additional train and three
buses to expedite the ethnic Albanians' flight, but their
generosity apparently has its limits. Refugees who were there on
Tuesday said that each departing ethnic Albanian was forced to pay
$20 for a ride into exile.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers on the train from Urosevac said there were about 200
people at the station in Kacanik, a town on the way south toward
Macedonia, U.N. officials said. But the train was too full to let
them on.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The refugees' problems do not end when they cross the border.
U.N. officials said that the Macedonian government, which was
initially criticized for callous treatment of the refugees, forced
1,000 Kosovo Albanians to wait in buses at the border for seven
hours before allowing them to go on to refugee camps. The officials
said another 1,000 to 1,500 people, presumably ethnic Albanians,
were waiting to cross from Yugoslavia into Macedonia near the town
of Kumanovo Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian police were holding the group in a no-man's land, Ms.
Ghedini said, because they do not consider the area an official
border crossing. Two weeks ago in a similar situation, the
Macedonians eventually allowed the refugees to enter.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia's prime minister, Ljupco Georgievski, said on Tuesday
that he was unaware of delays at the border. Georgievski said his
government had at first been overwhelmed by the ``catastrophe''
that unfolded on its doorstep and was simply trying to keep the
situation under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``No state can allow the opening of its frontier, and that
anyone can enter uncontrolled,'' he said. ``There had to be some
kind of order.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hardships they have suffered since the NATO bombings
began on March 24, ethnic Albanians arriving here Wednesday voiced
strong support for the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   They conceded that the Yugoslav units now rolling through
southeastern Kosovo appeared undaunted by the NATO assault. But
they insisted that the bombing was slowing the Yugoslavs and that
the expulsions would have occurred whether or not NATO struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did the same thing in the southwest of Kosovo even before
NATO bombed,'' said Skenderi Ifusi, who was forced from his village
near Urosevac six days before.
</P>
<P>
   Other refugees said they, too, supported the airstrikes but
added that it was a mistake for NATO not to have anticipated mass
expulsions. They called for NATO ground troops or the arming of the
Kosovo Liberation Army, and immediate air drops of food into
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Faruk Sinani, who was expelled from a village near Urosevac last
week, said he believed that many of the Albanians remaining in
Kosovo were trapped. But he insisted that others were intentionally
staying behind, believing that their liberators may soon appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them are waiting for NATO,'' he said. ``Nothing else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
