<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-McNOWN-LADN </SLUG>
 
McNOWN'S STOCK RISES QUICKLY 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the past three weeks, former UCLA quarterback
Cade McNown has been to Portland twice, Orlando, Miami, Chicago and
Kansas City. Before that, he spent six weeks at an elite training
center in Florida. He also took an FBI lie detector test, underwent
a battery of physical and psychological tests for NFL teams,
participated in the Senior Bowl and severed his controversial
relationship with a convicted mobster who got his start in the
concrete business.
</P>
<P>
   So, how was your winter?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hectic,'' McNown said. ``I've been racking up the
mileage, but at a cost. I haven't had a chance to get into a
workout regimen. But I'm excited about getting into some structure
as soon as I get drafted.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and mobster Dominic Montemarano aside, McNown spent the
winter preparing for this weekend's NFL draft _ with seemingly
positive results. With a slew of quarterbacks available, McNown has
raised his value dramatically. Considered a second- or third-round
pick after the Rose Bowl, he could go as high as 12th or 15th
overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question he's a first-round pick,'' said Larry
Kennan, executive director of the the NFL Coaches Association and a
former assistant coach who tutored McNown at the International
Performance Institute in Bradenton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last three or four months, he has solidified himself
as a first-round guy. He had a wonderful career at UCLA, but NFL
people were saying he was a little short and didn't have a real
strong arm. But as they've watched him work, they see he's tall
enough and has a strong enough arm. And everything else is there.''
</P>
<P>
   McNown, who led UCLA to 20 wins in his last two seasons, was the
anti-prospect. Whereas many first rounders have questionable
character and sensational talent, McNown oozed integrity but needed
to prove what NFL scouts call the ``measureables'' _ size, speed,
arm strength.
</P>
<P>
   He's not as fast, not as tall and can't throw as hard as
Syracuse's Donovan McNabb, Oregon's Akili Smith, Central Florida's
Daunte Culpepper and Kentucky's Tim Couch, which means he'll
probably be the fifth quarterback selected. His greatest attributes
_ his toughness, intelligence, knack for big plays and success _
simply aren't as important to NFL scouts as the measureables.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, McNown closely resembles another college
quarterback who was overlooked on draft day (second round, 42nd
selection) but has become one of the NFL's most exciting young
players, Arizona's Jake Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny . . . all of a sudden you're a better prospect if
you throw one mile-an-hour faster,'' McNown said. ``A guy can
become a great passer and leader with a differential of one
mile-an-hour. It seems like they're missing the forest for the
trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, McNown figured his game needed some landscaping.
After the Rose Bowl, he headed to the International Performance
Institute (IPI) to join a handful of prospects for six weeks of
training. He rose at 7:30 and spent half the day doing mobility
drills, strength exercises and speed workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cade's prescription was designed to address what people
thought were his limiting factors,'' said Mark Verstegen, IPI's
chief trainer. ``Every step he took, he got feedback.''
</P>
<P>
   After a mid-afternoon break, McNown executed a series of
position-specific drills. He worked on technique and accuracy and
emphasized the arm-strength throws NFL scouts wanted to see _ the
20-yard slants and 15-yard outs.
</P>
<P>
   At the NFL Scouting Combine in Indianapolis in mid-February,
McNown stunned scouts with a 4.7-second 40-yard dash _
approximately 0.2 seconds faster than expected _ and executed every
throw asked of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IPI really helped Cade,'' said Kennan, a former assistant
for the Raiders, Denver, Indianapolis, Seattle, New Orleans and New
England. ``It showed what kind of guy he is. A lot of guys wouldn't
have wanted to give up six or eight weeks to work eight hours each
day. They'd want to party. But Cade heard all the talk about not
having a strong enough arm or being fast enough, and he used that
as a motivator.''
</P>
<P>
   Although McNown's relationship with a former mob boss made
headlines and prompted a brief inquiry by the FBI, he says it did
not derail his pre-draft routine. He had already gotten the
training he needed in Bradenton and impressed the scouts in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was much to do about nothing,'' he said. ``I understood
what it could do if it continued in the NFL. But it's too bad for
the other guy. His name was smeared and nobody was doing anything
wrong. Everybody knows there was nothing to it. It was in and out
of the papers.''
</P>
<P>
   McNown recently held a workout for scouts at UCLA and has spent
much of April interviewing with various teams. He has no idea where
he'll get picked, and if his detached approach to the Heisman
Trophy race was any indication, he doesn't much care. McNown always
was _ and is _ about proving himself.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, as a high school senior, he was UCLA's No. 2
quarterback recruit behind Brock Huard, who eventually chose
Washington. Now, Huard is behind McNown as an NFL prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a pride thing for me, I don't care where I get
drafted,'' McNown said. ``Ultimately, if you play well for a few
years the money will come. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense I'm ideal for is a coach who's smart enough to
look at what he has. That's what UCLA did better than anything
else. They looked at what they had and figured the best way to
utilize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like McNown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
