<HEADLINE>
WIZARDS DEFLATE KNICKS BY WINNING 95-89 IN OVERTIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The New York Knicks cannot enjoy a good thing. They
came to the MCI Center floating on a three-game winning streak, and
left in disbelief after a dispirited Wizards team had more nerve
than the Knicks did in the end, taking a 95-89 victory in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards' Tracy Murray curled away from Allan Houston and
knocked down a 21-foot jumper with 1 minute 4 seconds left in
overtime to give the Wizards a 91-89 lead. After Latrell Sprewell
missed a leaner, and the tap-back escaped Marcus Camby and Larry
Johnson, the Wizards grabbed the rebound and Otis Thorpe scored on
an up-and-under move to give his team a 93-89 lead with 25 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   With 11 games left in the season, the Knicks (21-18) are hanging
onto seventh place in the Eastern Conference after suffering
Wednesday night's loss without the injured Patrick Ewing. But it
wasn't the big men like Camby and Johnson who failed coach Jeff Van
Gundy; it was the combined shooting effort of 9 for 33 by Houston
and Sprewell. Camby led the Knicks with 18 points off the bench,
while the Wizards (15-23) were led by Thorpe and Rod Strickland,
who both scored 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards broke an 81-81 tie in regulation when Murray was
left alone by Sprewell for a 3-pointer with 30 seconds left. Then,
after a miss from 3-point range by Sprewell, Charlie Ward grabbed
the rebound, stepped back on the wing, and hit a game-tying
3-pointer for New York with 18.1 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards had a chance to win the game in regulation when
Strickland drove and kicked the ball out to an open Jeff McInnis,
who missed a 19-foot jumper at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   To gain an edge in overtime, Johnson, using a nifty reverse
layup against the contact of Ben Wallace, created a 3-point play to
give the Knicks a 89-86 lead with 2:29 left.
</P>
<P>
   After a free throw by Strickland and a driving layup from
Thorpe, the game was tied again with 1:38 left.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the scene was set for the Knicks to throw sand
in the face of the skinny kids on the beach, the Wizards. Already
thin at center and undersized at forward, the Wizards were missing
the starters Juwan Howard (ankle) and Terry Davis (shin). This is a
team on the skids. Their coach, Bernie Bickerstaff, was fired last
week and they had lost five of the six games before Wednesday
night's.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, meanwhile, were on a fast break to recovery. They
had won three straight, including their last two in blowouts.
Simmering with optimism, they faced the Wizards with an eye on
moving from seventh place to sixth, and possibly to fifth if
Detroit lost. One week ago, after a miserable loss to Charlotte,
the Knicks were in 10th place and had no thoughts of grabbing a
top-four spot in the Eastern Conference. They were gasping.
</P>
<P>
   ``From outhouse to home-court advantage,'' Van Gundy said before
Wednesday night's game. ``That's a big swing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were thinking big. But first they had to get by the
Wizards, and they had to do it without Ewing. That proved to be a
problem as the game wore on. With Sprewell and Houston shooting
with a cold touch, the Knicks were left to lean on the offensively
challenged Chris Dudley to stay ahead through three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   After the game was tied, 47-47, with eight minutes left in the
third quarter, Dudley scored on three consecutive possessions,
keeping New York even with the Wizards. The Knicks opened some
space after Johnson scored on a 3-point play and followed with an
encore that left the crowd in awe. Showing surprising spring,
Johnson exploded to the rim for a baseline dunk past a lethargic
Thorpe to give the Knicks a 62-59 lead after three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   This was a little tighter than the Knicks had expected. Ewing
was missed. After leaving the Knicks victory against Philadelphia
on Tuesday with a sore Achilles' tendon, Ewing told Van Gundy this
morning that he was not going to be able to go Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't seem critical since Dudley and Camby had been
playing so well. But the Knicks didn't count on their two pivotal
scorers, Sprewell and Houston, shooting a combined 5 for 17 in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   After building a 10-point lead midway through the second
quarter, the Knicks went 1 for 10 and had three turnovers in the
final six minutes of the half. Strickland and Mitch Richmond took
advantage of the suddenly sluggish Knicks, and led the Wizards on a
11-2 run. Washington trailed by just 42-41 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   That was an uncomfortable position for the Knicks, who in
Ewing's absence could not take advantage of the small, piecemeal
front line the Wizards offered. Still, Ewing's absence has not been
their undoing in most cases this season.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's hard to imagine the Knicks slipping past Indiana,
Orlando or Miami without Ewing, their offense has been more fluid
in his absence this season against the mediocre teams in the
league.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
