<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORTON FACES CHALLENGE FROM WASHINGTON TRIBES  
PANEL WANTS MFUME TO RUN FOR BALTIMORE MAYOR IN FALL  
DAVIS FACES TOUGH CHOICE ON PROPOSITION 187 APPEAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATT: Calif., Md., Wash.)  (rk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., has been at odds with Native
Americans going all the way back to the 1970s when, as the state
attorney general, he tried to limit the amount of salmon tribes
could take from Washington waters.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, as chairman of the Interior Appropriations
subcommittee, he has further antagonized tribes, not just in the
state but elsewhere, by advocating tighter tribal budgets and
tougher tribal laws.
</P>
<P>
   The senator argues that government policies too often elevate
the rights of Native Americans above the rights of other Americans.
Indian leaders counter that he has it all backward.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, the ability of Native Americans to influence
Indian policy and those who make it, like Gorton, has always been
limited, not just because of the relatively small number of Native
Americans but because of a severe shortage of tribal money to pour
into political causes. But that is changing, and therein lies a new
threat to Gorton, who is up for re-election next year.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of casino gambling on reservations, along with
the flow of natural gas and oil money, has left some tribes flush.
Mostly they have been using their new-found wealth to lobby for
more casinos and other needs, but increasingly they also are
beginning to dump money into political races.
</P>
<P>
   Indian money played no significant role in Gorton's 1994
re-election campaign. Two years later, the nation's 550-plus tribes
collectively spent less than $1.5 million on federal contests,
including the presidential race. But in 1998, Indian spending
jumped sharply, with at least one tribe spending some $400,000 on
congressional contests.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, Indian leaders say, are the 2000 elections.
Native American tribes plan to spend even more to elect candidates
friendly to their causes, with special attention toward defeating
Gorton.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Allen, the president of the National Congress of American
Indians, predicted recently that there would be a ``scramble'' by
tribes to pour big money into that contest if it appeared there was
a good chance to defeat ``the dean of the anti-Indian movement.''
But that is a big ``if,'' Allen concedes.
</P>
<P>
   Political pros say that the senator could be vulnerable, given
that he has displeased not only Native Americans but many of the
state's trial lawyers, labor bosses and environmentalists. Still,
they note, the Democrat with the best shot at defeating him, Gov.
Gary Locke, has said he will not run.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton is taking no chances. He says he needs to raise $7
million for his run and warns supporters in his latest fund-raising
letter that ``Indian tribes flush with gambling dollars'' are
willing to spend ``whatever it takes'' to beat him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Panel Wants Mfume to Run For Baltimore Mayor in Fall
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Mayor Kurt L. Schmoke of Baltimore announced last
December that he would not seek a fourth term, many top business
and political figures in the city and elsewhere in Maryland have
been casting about for a strong candidate to replace him in this
fall's election. Without the right candidate, they fear, the
impressive urban rebirth that Baltimore has enjoyed over the past
quarter of a century might falter.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the city's register of wills and three little-known
community activists, at least one member of the City Council is
talking about running, and a former member already is in the race.
But neither of the latter two strikes the search party of top
business and political leaders as having the right stuff.
</P>
<P>
   So a draft _ one with enticing come-ons _ is under way by the
search group, whose members include state Comptroller William
Donald Schaefer, a former mayor and governor; Peter G. Angelos, the
owner of the Baltimore Orioles; Otis Warren and William Adams, both
developers; Glenard S. Middleton, president of the Baltimore
Chapter of the American Federation of State, County and Municipal
Employees, and members of the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   For the right candidate, the group says, it has the clout to
change the rules of the game, to make election all but a sure
thing.
</P>
<P>
   The object of the draft effort is Kweisi Mfume, a native
Baltimorean who is president of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, based in Baltimore, and who before
that served 10 years in the U.S. House of Representatives and seven
years on the Baltimore City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume says he is committed to getting the NAACP solidly back on
its feet after years of drift and has no time to run for mayor. But
the draft leaders note that he has yet to say ``no'' with
Shermanesque finality.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were they deterred when someone pointed out recently that
Mfume lives in the suburbs, not the city proper, and thus could not
meet the requirement that a mayoral candidate be a city resident
for a least a year.
</P>
<P>
   They persuaded the state Legislature to rewrite the law. Under a
bill signed on Tuesday by Gov. Parris N. Glendening, only a
six-month residency is required _ meaning that Mfume still has time
to move in, and jump in, before the fall election.
</P>
<P>
   What about the cut in salary Mfume would have to take if
elected, given that he makes $220,000 annually, more than twice the
$95,000 paid to Baltimore mayors? No problem, the draft group says,
promising to persuade the City Council to raise the mayoral pay to
$150,000 annually. Beyond that, group members say, there are
speeches to be made for fat fees and boards to serve on for still
more fees, provided there are no conflicts interest.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume still insists he has no time to run for office, but he
recently bought a $300,000 condominium just a few blocks from City
Hall. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Davis Faces Tough Choice On Proposition 187 Appeal
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis of California is in a political quandary.
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat elected last fall with heavy Hispanic support, he
must decide within the next few days whether to appeal a federal
court decision that declared Proposition 187 unconstitutional. That
proposition, passed by voters in 1994 at the strong urging of Gov.
Pete Wilson, Davis' Republican predecessor, shut off benefits to
illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   In California, most illegal immigrants are Hispanic. They saw
the measure as unusually harsh _ as did most other Hispanics in the
state, not the least being those able to vote.
</P>
<P>
   For years, many Hispanics faithfully voted Republican. But in
last fall's election, they went heavily Democratic, contributing
significantly to the defeat of Dan Lungren, Davis' Republican
opponent. That vengeful switch has not been lost on Davis, who
knows as well as anyone that Hispanics make up more than a third of
California's population, with the percentage growing daily.
</P>
<P>
   But his quandary is even more complex. The other important
figure that he must keep in mind is that Proposition 187 did not
pass with just Republican backing. It also had heavy Democratic
support.
</P>
<P>
   Gray also must consider whether pressing an appeal might
seriously damage California's economic ties with Mexico. In recent
years, trade with Mexico has become a major factor in the state's
economic well being.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the question of whether Davis, as California's
top official, is duty-bound to follow through with an appeal of a
court ruling that struck down a state law. If legal experts
conclude that he must, he just might find political refuge in that
conclusion. But thus far the experts can't agree on anything.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
