<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLAUS STARTS FAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND -- Troy Glaus is off to a hot start, so hot that he was
the Angels' cleanup hitter Wednesday. Upon seeing his name in the
No. 4 spot after his arrival to the visiting clubhouse at the
Oakland Coliseum, Glaus said he took it in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking the same thing I always think every day -- I'm
excited to be in the lineup, he said. ``It doesn't matter where you
hit. If you've got guys in scoring position, whether you're hitting
first, fourth or ninth, you're expected to drive them in.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus, who took a .452 (14 for 31) average into Wednesday's
game, replaced Tim Salmon as the cleanup hitter. Salmon hit third.
Glaus said he hit cleanup in one game last season at Chicago, but
never hit fourth at UCLA -- he always hit third.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins was asked before Wednesday's game
if there was a danger of putting too much pressure on a young
player like the 22-year-old Glaus by hitting him fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only if they think they've got to do more than when they were
hitting sixth, he said. ``He's going up there feeling good,
swinging good. Now might be the time to run him up there.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Edmonds was examined by Dr. Lewis Yocum Wednesday and
reported the center fielder's right shoulder is improving. However,
the shoulder -- which has a cyst in the muscle and wear and tear to
the labrum -- does not feel good enough for Edmonds to swing a bat
without pain.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds, whose medication and physical therapy program have been
altered, won't be ready by the weekend for the Angels three-game
series against the Mariners at Edison Field. Instead, Edmonds will
be re-evaluated this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth inning of Tuesday's game against the A's, Orlando
Palmeiro mistakenly thought the hit-and-run sign had been put on
when it was actually the bunt sign. So Palmeiro broke from first
and was thrown out at second after the A's pitched out.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was upset about it after the game, and Wednesday he did
something about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to confuse guys with signs, so they'll be changed
today, Collins said. ``(The signs) are not real hard, but because
we've missed some, we're going to change 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Terry Clark, who graduated from La Puente High and
attended Mt. San Antonio College, combined with two other pitchers
to throw a no-hitter for the A's triple-A team in Vancouver on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 38, started and went four innings, and was followed by
Bill King (four innings) and Anthony Chavez (one inning). Clark
began his professional career in 1979, and has included playing
parts of two seasons with the Angels (1988 and '89).
</P>
<P>
   According to an A's spokesman, the club will honor former
pitcher Catfish Hunter before their game against the Dodgers on
June 12 at the Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter has amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (Lou Gehrig's Disease).
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and A's finish their series today (1:05) at the
Oakland Coliseum. Omar Olivares (1-0, 0.00 ERA) will start for
Anaheim against Oakland's Gil Heredia (1-0, 3.55).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
