<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-UNION-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASS PROTEST AGAINST BUS TERMINAL'S USE OF NONUNION JANITORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For AFL-CIO president John Sweeney, it was a perfect
homecoming _ the New York janitors' union he long headed held one
of the city's most spirited labor demonstrations in years Wednesday
as 5,000 union members rallied at the Port Authority midtown bus
terminal to protest the use of nonunion janitors.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in Bryant Park, thousands of union members, often
shouting and blowing whistles, marched two blocks west to the bus
terminal, where they denounced Laro Service Systems, the contractor
responsible for cleaning the terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen members of Sweeney's old local, Local 32B-32J of
the Service Employees International Union, have been on strike
since 1996, when Laro won the contract to clean the terminal,
resisted having a union and refused to keep all the janitors who
were working there.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Balanoff, the trustee overseeing Local 32B-32J, said,
``We're demonstrating against the below-standard wages and benefits
that Laro is paying.''
</P>
<P>
   For the two decades that Local 32B-32J was headed by Gus Bevona,
whom the parent union forced out two months ago because of his high
salary and his penthouse at the local's headquarters, the local
never held large demonstrations. The 55,000-member local earned a
reputation as a slothful giant.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Local 32B-32J is back,'' said Sweeney, who headed the local in
the 1970s. ``It should be obvious to the Port Authority and to Laro
Service Systems that we're back to stay. We're here today to
deliver a message to the Port Authority and every office building
and every residential building that we are first-class workers and
we will not allow you to treat us like second-class citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   In a show of solidarity, there were hundreds of protests from
the hotel workers, laborers, operating engineers and needle trades
unions. Dozens of demonstrators held printed signs that said,
``Shame on Port Authority, Shame on Laro.''
</P>
<P>
   Laro chairman Robert Bertuglia said in an interview that all of
the union's sound and fury was unwarranted. He said he was ready to
sign a contract with Local 32B-32J and that Laro paid its workers
well and provided health insurance and other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how some of these things get said,'' Bertuglia
said. ``These people are being paid everything their union brothers
and sisters are getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Many protest signs called on Laro to pay a ``living wage,'' but
Bertuglia noted that the Port Authority required his company to pay
the prevailing janitor's wage of $15.09 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Bertuglia said it was wrong for the union leaders to accuse Laro
of being antiunion because his company, which employees nearly 200
workers at the bus terminal, had contracts with numerous unions at
other sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is it possible that they think we're antiunion,''
Bertuglia said. ``I'll be more than happy to make peace. I don't
need all the publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ira Sturm, a lawyer for Local 32B-32J, said Laro has fought for
years against having a union represent the bus terminal's janitors.
</P>
<P>
   Balanoff, the local's trustee, said that before Laro signed a
union contract, the local wanted Laro to restore seniority to the
bus terminal janitors who worked there before Laro arrived. The
janitors Laro kept on lost their seniority when Laro hired them.
</P>
<P>
   Annie Gilmore, who has cleaned toilets at the bus terminal for
10 years, said she lost her seniority when Laro became the cleaning
company. As a result, she said, her vacation time dropped to one
week a year from three weeks. She also complained that Laro heaped
on far more work than its predecessor and that Laro's health plan
was not as good as 32B-32J's because it did not pay for her
diabetes medication.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gilmore said she felt glorious that thousands of workers
were marching in support of her cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not fighting for welfare, you're fighting for fair
share,'' said the Rev. Jesse Jackson, one of the speakers at the
rally. ``If you can fight for human rights and dignity in Kosovo,
then you can fight for it in New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Morrison, a Port Authority spokesman, said the dispute was
between the union local and Laro and not between the union local
and the authority. He said Laro won the contract three years ago
when it submitted the lowest bid.
</P>
<P>
   With many building managers contracting out to nonunion cleaning
companies in recent years, the demonstration yesterday was intended
to pressure buildings not to contract out to nonunion companies by
signaling that they might face demonstrations next.
</P>
</TEXT>
